<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15 BODIES REMOVED FROM SCHOOL IN COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Fla.) 
(Eds: subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ After a long day of agony for victims'
parents and anxiety for police officers searching for explosives,
the authorities on Wednesday evening removed the bodies of 15
people killed in a massacre at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead were the two members of the senior class who are
believed to have unleashed the carnage on Tuesday before turning
their guns on themselves. They were found shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve of the dead, including both suspects, were found in the
school's library, said the Jefferson County sheriff, John Stone,
who added that there were so many weapons and explosive devices _
including 30 bombs, a semi-automatic rifle and pistol and two
shotguns _ that investigators were still unsure how they got it all
inside the school. They may have hidden it during several trips or
they may have had help, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   David J. Thomas, the district attorney, at a press conference at
the school Wednesday afternoon, said that investigators are looking
at eight to 10 people who might have knowledge of the case through
familiarity with a Web site connected to the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is evidence to suggest that other people were at
least aware of what was going on. There were a lot of devices. They
took a long time to construct and a lot of people were familiar
with the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said a computer had been seized at a suspect's house, and
they were tracing the e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   An unfathomable set of questions surrounded the motivations of
the two suspects, 18-year-old Eric David Harris and Dylan Bennett
Klebold, 17. They were described by many students Wednesday as
members of a self-styled group of loners and outcasts who called
themselves the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' after the long black coats they
wore and shared a fascination with violent video games and a
antipathy toward the more popular students who they referred to as
``jocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Harris and Klebold were arrested last year for breaking
into a car, and parents of another student at the school said that
they had complained to authorities last year about death threats
made by Harris against their son. Nonetheless, school authorities
and many students insisted Wednesday that they never seriously
considered either young man to be inclined toward the horrific
violence let loose here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident set off a national bout of soul-searching and
debates over whether the killings were spurred by easy access to
guns or by the violent images on television and in video games to
which America's children are routinely exposed.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said in Washington that ``all of us are
struggling to understand exactly what happened and why.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings also had immediate political reverberations as
well: In at least three states, including Colorado, sponsors of
legislation expanding the rights to carry guns withdrew those
measures Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were still so concerned about the possibility of
more danger that most of the bodies were removed from the school
only Wednesday evening. They were taken to the county coroner's
office. Some were so unrecognizable that parents were asked to
bring dental records of their missing children to the school.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll, which represents the largest school massacre in
the country's history, was a downward revision from the possible 25
deaths that the authorities had said on Tuesday. But it was unclear
whether it would rise again as the search inside the school
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the dead are male, including at least one teacher and
one black student whom the killers had shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen people are still hospitalized, 11 of them in serious or
critical condition, according to a spokesman for the sheriff's
office.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, under sunny skies that turned slate grey with an
approaching storm Wednesday afternoon, students gathered near the
high school for any news about friends still officially listed as
missing. Many were crying or clutching flowers that they brought to
a makeshift memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even imagine walking into that school right now,''
said 17-year-old Dara Ferguson, a junior, who had three friends
whom she feared were dead. ``I don't think I ever want to set foot
in there again.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Jefferson County School District said that
the building, with hundreds of bullet holes and several inches of
water that came from sprinklers that went off after the bombs did,
would remain closed for the rest of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama and Florida, the school shooting prompted lawmakers
to postpone consideration of bills that would prohibit cities and
counties from suing gun makers for the cost of gun violence. The
bills, similar to others passed around the country, were introduced
at the behest of the National Rifle Association to protect the
firearms industry from liability suits.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, officials of the NRA said they had decided to
scale back their national membership meeting, scheduled for May 1
in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter, the NRA president, actor Charlton Heston, said the
group was canceling a gun show along with all other ``festive
ceremonies normally associated with our annual gathering.'' The
group was nevertheless going to hold its annual members meeting at
the city's convention center.
</P>
<P>
   But he and some other politicians said that the violence might
have been averted if someone else had been armed at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had there been someone who was armed, in this particular
situation, in my opinion, it may have stabilized,'' said Gov. Jesse
Ventura of Minnesota, who supports loosening restrictions on
concealed handguns. ``I believe it supports conceal and carry
because of the fact that what happens when a group of unarmed
individuals are confronted with people with weapons like this, you
have no defense.''
</P>
<P>
   And Heston said the incident showed that there should be armed
guards in the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been even one armed guard in the school, he could
have saved a lot of lives and perhaps ended the whole thing
instantly,'' he said in Los Angeles on Wednesday. There was, in
fact, an armed guard at the school and he exchanged fire with one
of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   A police officer assigned to the school, Neil Gardner of the
Jefferson County Sheriff's Department, apparently exchanged gunfire
with one of the teenagers shortly after the melee began at 11:30
a.m., and two other patrol officers fired some shots about a half
hour later, according to Steve Davis, a sheriff's spokesman.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
