<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ Boom, boom, boom.
</P>
<P>
   They were like cannon blasts ringing in a new Astros home-run
king, echoing off the Wrigley Field outfield walls and bouncing off
the bricks that line Waveland Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The first one was a towering no-doubt shot over the left-field
grandstand and into the street. The second one sailed like a rocket
into the right-center-field bleachers, pushing this Astros star
with the gun-barrel forearms past the Toy Cannon, Jimmy Wynn, as
the club's all-time home-run leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one to right field,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker would
say later, ``wow. It was a bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   The third one was high, huge and straight into a wind that
earlier in the day knocked back would-be shots hit by two other
players.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Bagwell, on the way to 225 career home runs, has done
little like other players. He stands all wrong. He hitches his
hands all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Just standing there in the batter's box, like he has one foot on
the dock and one on a boat that's drifting away, he looks all
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't teach my swing to anyone,'' Bagwell says.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, it always ends up right. Always, it seems he is
getting better.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the most impressive and revealing thing about
Bagwell's slamming three home runs in Wednesday's 10-3 Astros
victory over the Chicago Cubs is not how many he hit, but how he
hit them.
</P>
<P>
   Two came on two-strike pitches. Two were on breaking balls. None
wound up dribbling their way meekly to the third baseman or
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   These were home runs that proved to be the most significant
endorsement yet of Bagwell's offseason tinkering with his swing,
even if the statistics said it needed no tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   These were home runs that reflected the drive in a man who is
like few others. Always, Bagwell scrutinizes every detail,
criticizes every failure and allows himself only small doses of joy
for the great moments.
</P>
<P>
   Always, he is searching for perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Even Wednesday, amid the glorious record-setting afterglow,
Bagwell talked about the three home runs being only three-fifths of
the story. In his other two at-bats, Bagwell struck out and
grounded to third.
</P>
<P>
   Of the groundout, Bags shook his head and said, ``I swung at a
bad pitch. I was disappointed I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the strikeout, he said: ``That was a horrible at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Always, there is a search for more. It is something that might
sometimes keep Bagwell from fully appreciating performances such as
Wednesday's. But it also is something that virtually guarantees
there will be more days like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a constant battle for me,'' Bagwell said. ``If I'm
terrible, I'm going to tell you I'm terrible. I'm the first one to
admit it. It's just a constant battle to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why Bagwell is Bagwell _ a great hitter always seemingly
getting better.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Bagwell might not have come close to hitting three
home runs given the pitches he saw Wednesday afternoon at
wind-whipped Wrigley. A year ago, the deep hitch in his swing might
have had Bagwell ending similar at-bats with groundouts to the left
side of the infield, particularly on the two-strike breaking balls.
</P>
<P>
   It almost seems comical that Bagwell's 34-homer, 111-RBI season
of a year ago was considered a down year by some. It was his third
straight season of at least 30 home runs and 100 RBIs. But Bagwell
himself considered 1998 a down year.
</P>
<P>
   He hated the frequent two-strike dribblers down the third-base
line. He hated how he dropped his hands nearly to his waist as he
loaded for a swing. He called Astros hitting coach Tom McCraw and
asked for help. He worked on starting his hands higher, which would
give him a better chance to extend his arms, protect the plate with
two strikes and drive the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, `I'm beating the ball around, and I should be
crushing those pitches,''' McCraw said. ``He was committed to
making it better.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, he obviously did. Bagwell was the Astros' best
hitter start-to-finish. But once the Cubs arrived in Houston to
begin the regular season, Bagwell got off to a slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned he might say the heck with it and go back to
what he was doing before,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bagwell stayed with the new starting point for his swing and
began hitting for average. Finally, on Wednesday, he tore apart the
fences and the Astros' record book and now is hitting .396 with
four homers, 12 RBIs and a .688 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really watched my swing on tape,'' Bagwell said.
``But on the first (home run) today, I was out in front of it, and
the way I used to hit, I wasn't usually out in front. Something's
definitely different.''
</P>
<P>
   He still looks all wrong standing there in the batter's box. But
it's definitely right. And getting better all the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
