<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-CHIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHIEFS ARE CHOSEN FOR ARMY AND MARINES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton nominated new chiefs for the Army
and Marine Corps on Wednesday, turning to the highest ranking
Japanese-American officer in the Army's history and a close aide of
Secretary of Defense William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   If ratified by the Senate, as expected, Gen. Eric K. Shinseki
will become the Army's 34th chief of staff in June, replacing Gen.
Dennis J. Reimer, who is retiring from the position he has held for
the last four years. Shinseki took over as vice chief in November
after serving two years as the top Army general in Europe and
commander of the NATO peacekeeping force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The nominee to be the 33rd commandant of the Marine Corps is Lt.
Gen. James L. Jones, a three-star officer who was chosen over a
number of prominent four-star candidates within the service. Jones,
who was also nominated to receive his fourth star, has served as
military assistant to the secretary of defense since Cohen took
over in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Both officers are decorated veterans of Vietnam who have
significant experience navigating Pentagon politics in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For the Army, more so than the Marines, the appointment comes at
what many inside and outside the service consider a time of
wrenching change.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the major services, the Army has had the most difficult
transition from a Cold War force ready to defeat the Soviet Union
to the sort of nimble force needed to fight wars like the one under
way in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki, 56, was born in Hawaii of Japanese ancestry. He is a
graduate of West Point who went on to earn a master's degree in
English at Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   He served two tours in Vietnam as a young officer and was
seriously wounded twice. An armored officer, he rose through the
ranks in a variety of commands and staff assignments, much of the
time in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki is respected and well regarded within the Army, but his
appointment is disappointing to critics who have said the Army
needs to move more quickly to restructure itself.
</P>
<P>
   He was selected over other candidates who were thought to be
more open to change, including Gen. John N. Abrams, commander of
the Army's Training and Doctrine Command, and Gen. Barry R.
McCaffrey, the nation's drug czar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `steady as she goes' choice,'' said John Hillen, a
former Army captain and now a senior fellow at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington. ``He is a superb
warrior, heroic, smart, but his choice shows the Army would rather
not go through the tumult of innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 55, will replace Gen. Charles C. Krulak, an outspoken
commandant who has left a significant mark on the Marine Corps
during his four years in the post. It was Krulak who initiated
changes in Marine basic training _ including the creation of a
grueling 54-hour endurance test called the crucible, which the
other services are emulating.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was born in Missouri, but spent much of his formative
years in France. He returned to study at Georgetown University,
where he studied at the School of Foreign Service and played
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   After a tour in Vietnam, he held commands at Camp Pendleton and
Okinawa. In the early 1980s he served as the Corps' liaison officer
to the Senate, where he befriended Cohen, then a senator from
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   As commander of the 24th Marine Expeditionary Unit, he led the
effort to provide aid to thousands of Kurdish refugees driven into
the hills in northern Iraq in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
