<SLUG> BC-Q&AMP;A-BALKANS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRIEF BALKANS Q&AMP;A  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This helpful 300-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 And RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: WHY IS NATO NOT ARMING THE KLA?:
</P>
<P>
   A: Any formal decision to arm the KLA would have to be
authorized by the United States, which has specifically ruled that
out.
</P>
<P>
   Until it successfully persuaded the KLA to sign the Rambouillet
agreement, Washington regarded the KLA as little more than a
terrorist grouping, too weak and undisciplined to be effective as a
fighting force. Those suspicions persist.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also fears that victory for the KLA would strengthen
Kosovan claims for independence from Serbia, a change of border
that the U.S. fears would lead to a free-for-all in the Balkans and
strongly opposes.
</P>
<P>
   The precedents are not encouraging either. Arming Nicaraguan
guerrillas without Congressional approval got Ronald Reagan into
the biggest trouble of his presidency; the arms supplied to the
Afghan mujahidin following the Soviet invasion have subsequently
been used by the Islamic fundamentalist Taleban and may have
assisted anti-U.S. terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Official denials, however, do not mean that the KLA will get no
U.S.-funded weapons: Washington repeatedly denied that it had
helped arm the Bosnian Muslims, but was forced eventually to admit
that it had.
</P>
<P>
   Q: NATO ESTIMATED MONDAY THAT SOME 3,000 ETHNIC ALBANIANS HAVE
BEEN MURDERED BY THE SERBS SINCE NATO BEGAN BOMBING ON MARCH 24. IS
THIS SORT OF SLAUGHTER UNPRECEDENTED THIS CENTURY?
</P>
<P>
   A: Alas no. In early 1919, as Belgrade reimposed its rule on the
province after the First World War, events were gruesomely similar
to those of today. Villages which resisted were bombarded.
</P>
<P>
   The enemy consisted of rebel bands of ethnic Albanians known as
kacaks (cedilla under `c'), equivalent of the modern Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   In January and February 1919 alone, 6,000 Kosovan Albanians were
killed and 3,850 houses destroyed, according to detailed figures
published later in Italy. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this helpful 300-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to
reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
