<SLUG> BC-STARWOOD-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARWOOD HOTELS PRESIDENT RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Nanula, president and chief operating officer of
Starwood Hotels and Resorts Inc., resigned Wednesday, just over a
year after he was chosen by his friend, Barry Sternlicht,
Starwood's chairman and chief executive, to help run the world's
largest hotel company.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after the close of financial markets,
Sternlicht said Starwood's evolution since Nanula arrived at the
company _ principally, the decision to sell its gaming operations,
which Nanula has been running _ led the executives to conclude
``our interests were best served by pursuing our careers
separately.''
</P>
<P>
   However, rumors of a rift between the two men, who first met
when they were classmates at the Harvard Business School, have been
circulating for months.
</P>
<P>
   According to most accounts, the backbiting began last August,
following the publication of a profile in The New York Times that
described Nanula (pronounced na-NOO-lah) as the man who would make
Sternlicht's operations work well.
</P>
<P>
   The article appeared only weeks after Nanula had arrived at
Starwood from Walt Disney Co., where he had been a highly regarded
senior executive vice president and its chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   When Nanula was hired by Starwood last April, Sternlicht
admitted that ``for his own sanity'' his knowledge of and
friendship with Nanula ``was a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   But The Times article did not sit at all well with Sternlicht,
who is as mercurial as Nanula is unflappable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Times piece created internal problems,'' Jim Gallagher, a
Starwood spokesman, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry and Richard realized that friendship and business has
its own set of complexities,'' Gallagher said. ``They continue to
be friends, have parted amicably and Richard did make contributions
to the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties, which most described as a clash of egos
between the two, were severe _ and surfaced fast.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to help resolve the problems, last fall Sternlicht
brought in Michael Feiner, an organizational consultant, to work
with the two men. According to an article in the May 10 issue of
Fortune magazine that details the problems, Starwood employees
nicknamed Feiner ``the marriage counselor.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Sternlicht nor Nanula, who are both 38, were available
for comment Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the Starwood statement, Nanula called Starwood ``a truly
great company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the confidence in the world that it will continue
to thrive under Barry's leadership with the support of his talented
management team,'' Nanula added.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Nanula, who asked not to be identified, said he
decided to resign about a week or 10 days ago. That is about the
same time that Starwood said it intended to put its Caesars casino
unit up for sale. It was not clear Wednesday if the Fortune article
also played a role in the timing of the resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard thinks Barry is a brilliant guy, but it became
apparent they were both strong-willed individuals, and that it was
impossible to have two captains running one ship,'' said one person
close to Nanula, who asked not to be identified. ``It was a noble
experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts said Nanula's resignation was not likely to
have a material effect on Starwood's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hire was extremely unique,'' said Jonathan Litt, an
analyst at Paine Webber. ``I am not saying that Sternlicht is easy
to work with, but the saving grace here is that Starwood has a very
deep bench. I don't think this is going to be a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Starwood said it had no immediate plans to seek a replacement
for Nanula. Juergen Bartels and Peter Boynton, chief executives of
Starwood's Hotel Group and Gaming Group, respectively, will now
report directly to Sternlicht. Previously, they had reported to
Nanula.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher declined to discuss the terms of Nanula's severance
package. But when Nanula signed up, his compensation agreement
included 3 million Starwood options. At least some of those options
recently vested at $24 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Like many hotel companies, for much of the last year Starwood's
stock has fared poorly. When Nanula's appointment was announced on
April 15, 1998, Starwood's stock traded at an intraday high of $53.
The stock closed at $32 Wednesday, down $2 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Nanula, who last month moved into a $6 million house he bought
in Greenwich, Conn., last September but spent months renovating, is
not likely to be out of work for long.
</P>
<P>
   But while he was highly regarded at Disney and reportedly
reluctantly left his native California, people close to him said it
was unlikely he would return to the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he is going to close any doors, but I think he
views that as something that is in the past,'' the source close to
Nanula said.
</P>
<P>
   Since neither Sternlicht nor Nanula were available to discuss
the resignation, it is not known how their final, corporate
conversation went.
</P>
<P>
   But the topic has come up in the past, albeit in a different
context.
</P>
<P>
   For years Nanula has offered advice to Sternlicht on a wide
variety of issues, including the dismissal of executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not good at firing people,'' Sternlicht told The Times
last August. ``When I had to let somebody go, Richard and I would
rehearse what I was going to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
