u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     04-22 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS SILENCES BOOS AS HE EXTENDS HIS WIN STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens heard the boos in the first inning and
again in the fourth Wednesday night. They were scattered and lasted
only a few seconds, but the fans berated Clemens because he was not
throwing strikes consistently and because he allowed a home run to
Todd Zeile. Clemens expects a lot from himself, and New York fans
obviously expect a lot from him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clemens was repeatedly serenaded by the fans as well.
Especially after the right-hander helped the New York Yankees quiet
the Texas Rangers, 4-2, and inflate his two-season streak to 17
straight victories, matching the American League record shared by
Baltimore's Dave McNally (1968-69) and Cleveland's Johnny Allen
(1936-37).
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been fortunate to win that many games and
have that type of record,'' Clemens said. ``I don't bask in it.
I'll look back on it over the winter when I see all the hard work
is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was more bullish than dominant Wednesday night, but it
was enough because he limited the Rangers to no hits in 14 at-bats
with runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, Clemens gave the fickle fans and the revived
Yankees exactly what they wanted: another businesslike victory.
Clemens stretched himself into the eighth inning, permitting just
one earned run and four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter's two-run homer, which sneaked inside the
right-field pole, keyed a pivotal three-run fifth inning off Rick
Helling that framed the Yankees' seventh victory in eight home
games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Clemens has given up as many homers in his last two
starts as he allowed in the last three months of last season, he
has kept his record unblemished and is seven consecutive victories
from Carl Hubbell's major league mark of 24, set with the New York
Giants in 1936-37. Clemens' streak seemed difficult to fathom even
for the Yankees' interim manager, Don Zimmer, who has been in
baseball for 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say,'' Zimmer said slowly, ``it's one heck of a
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has not lost since Cleveland beat him by 7-3 last May
29, and while he has endured nine no-decisions since then, he has
allowed more than four earned runs in a game only once, in his last
start against Baltimore (seven runs and 11 hits).
</P>
<P>
   He actually has a 4.47 earned run average in his no-decisions,
which is rather high for the five-time Cy Young award winner, but
it is not brutal.
</P>
<P>
   With Clemens and the Yankees trailing, 2-1, in the fifth, Chuck
Knoblauch looped a one-out single to center off Helling and scooted
to second on a wild pitch. Helling tried to place a 2-1 fastball on
the outside corner, and Jeter smacked the ball into the right-field
corner for his fifth homer of the season. It drifted toward the
foul pole, but was fair by about 10 feet to put the Yanks in front,
3-2. A walk, a single and Tino Martinez's forceout fetched the
fourth run.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had base runners in seven of the eight innings that
Clemens pitched, but he stifled them on no hits with men on base.
He struck out Mark McLemore with a runner on second to finish the
seventh and whiffed Juan Gonzalez with a man on first in the eighth
to complete his night in style.
</P>
<P>
   A weary Clemens, who had his hands on his knees, was replaced by
Mike Stanton and was treated like a rock star by the fans as he
ambled to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   When Zeile blasted Clemens' 1-1 fastball over the right-field
fence to give the Rangers a 2-1 lead in the fourth, the fans booed
as Clemens asked for a new baseball. It was the fourth homer
Clemens had allowed in his last seven innings; he gave up just four
homers in his final 123 innings of 1998, spanning three months.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Clemens had difficulty during a 25-pitch first
inning in which he walked three of the first five batters. The
leadoff man, Tom Goodwin, walked, stole second and then third as
Joe Girardi's hurried throw went about six feet to the right of the
bag at third. Luis Sojo dived for it, but it bounced past him for a
throwing error and Goodwin glided home with Texas' first run in 23
innings against the Yankees, including the playoffs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis slapped Helling's first pitch into the right-field
bleachers in the second to tie the score, 1-1, to give him four
homers and 11 runs batted in. That is more than the three homers
and the nine RBI he mustered in 35 games during an injury-scarred
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a new year, even if it appears to be old hat for
Clemens, who refuses to lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
