<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS TIES AL RECORD, DEFEATS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Texas Rangers owner Tom Hicks suggested fear as the
Yankees' motivation for acquiring five-time Cy Young Award
recipient Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Yankees made a sideways move,'' Hicks said in
February, ``because they're scared of the Texas Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would the defending World Series champions fear the Rangers?
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' 4-2 defeat Wednesday night marked their fourth
consecutive loss and seventh during their past eight games against
the Yankees since Aug. 16. That includes the Yankees' three-game
sweep during the 1998 American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a broken record,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said. ``Our ballclub plays well, but it seems like we're always one
pitch or one hit away from winning a lot of these ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   The clutch hit eluded the Rangers Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, whom the Yankees acquired two months ago from Toronto
for left-handers David Wells and Graeme Lloyd and second baseman
Homer Bush, stranded three runners in scoring position during the
first three innings and went on to match an American League record.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (2-0) surrendered only two runs (one earned) on four
hits and four walks and recorded six strikeouts in 7 1/3 innings.
That gave Clemens his 17th consecutive victory, which matched the
record shared by Baltimore's Dave McNally and Cleveland's Johnny
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will attempt to break the record next week against the
Rangers in his next scheduled start. Carl Hubbell of the New York
Giants set the major-league record of 24 in 1936-37.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers attacked Clemens' only apparent weakness _ his
inability to hold base runners well _ from the start. Opponents
stole 28 bases during 37 attempts against Clemens during 1998, and
the Rangers gambled with success on four occasions with center
fielder Tom Goodwin and second baseman Mark McLemore aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin drew a first-inning, leadoff walk _ one of three Clemens
issued during the first inning _ and stole second and third base
with left fielder Rusty Greer at the plate. Yankees catcher Joe
Girardi unleashed an errant throw on the steal of third, which
allowed Goodwin to score with the game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger struggled with his command early, and we ran ourselves
into a run there,'' Oates said, ``but we couldn't get that one hit
to get us started.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile produced the Rangers' other run with a
fourth-inning home run that gave the Rangers a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling, though, could not protect it.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who allowed only one run on two hits through 4 1/3
innings, surrendered a one-out single to second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch. The Rangers trailed for the first time after shortstop
Derek Jeter's two-run, opposite-field home run during the next
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Helling (0-3) did not retire another batter. Right fielder Paul
O'Neill walked and advanced to third on the ensuing single by
center fielder Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up first baseman Tino Martinez, who entered the
game 3-for-9 with two walks and two home runs during his career
against Helling.
</P>
<P>
   Oates summoned left-hander Mike Munoz from the bullpen for
Martinez, a left-handed hitter who entered the at-bat 0-for-5
during his career against the Rangers' left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the move to make there,'' Oates said. ``You've got a
left-hander to face the left-hander. (Rick) had four consecutive
hitters reach, and he's thrown 100 pitches. It's time to make the
move, and our bullpen did a super job again tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz induced the desired ground ball, but Martinez did not hit
the ball hard enough for the Rangers to turn an inning-ending,
4-6-3 double play. Williams' slide into second base also prevented
shortstop Royce Clayton from making a strong throw to first base,
and O'Neill scored from third with the game's final run on a
fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, though, did not appear pleased by being removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy with what happened, but Johnny makes those
decisions,'' Helling said. ``I don't ever question those decisions.
That's his job. I don't know what to say, but I don't think I
pitched that poorly tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Helling surprised to see Oates emerge from the dugout?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing surprises me anymore,'' Helling said. ``We haven't
pitched well as a rotation, and I'm sure he's losing his patience
with some of us.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
