u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLPOX-REPRIEVE-NYT     04-22 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLPOX-REPRIEVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO KEEP SMALLPOX SAMPLE, CLINTON AIDES SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER and WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defying international pleas, President Clinton has decided to
retain America's sample of smallpox virus, administration officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which is to be announced Thursday, is certain to
be fiercely debated within the scientific community and criticized
by the scores of nations that recommended in 1996 at a World Health
Organization meeting that the world's remaining smallpox stocks be
destroyed now that the disease has been eradicated around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The issue deeply divided the administration, which debated it
for months, seeking outside scientific guidance from numerous
sources. Initially, arms control advocates and some senior health
officials within the administration argued that the virus should be
destroyed this year as planned. But Defense and State Department
officials argued for retaining the stocks on grounds that there may
already be clandestine supplies of the virus around the world, in
North Korea, for instance, that could be used against America in
war or terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, the only other nation known to retain smallpox stocks,
has opposed their destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The president acted after an independent scientific panel
created by the Institute of Medicine, a branch of the National
Academy of Sciences, concluded in March that preserving the last
known samples in Russia and the United States could provide
important scientific and medical opportunities that would be lost
if the virus were destroyed. While the panel's 100-page report did
not express an opinion on whether the stocks should be destroyed,
its conclusion that retention had important scientific and medical
potential affected Clinton's thinking about the issue,
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Informed of the decision, some leading experts promptly
condemned it as dangerously short-sighted. ``I find it very
regrettable,'' said Donald Henderson, a former White House science
adviser who led the campaign to destroy the virus sample. ``Of all
the potential organisms that might be used in bioterrorism, this is
probably the most formidable, and I think we should do everything
we possibly can to mitigate against the risk of that virus being
released at any time in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who is dean emeritus of the Johns Hopkins School of
Public Health, warned that the United States would become a
``pariah'' when the World Health Assembly, the governing body of
the World Health Organization, meets in May to take up the issue of
the virus' destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll within the organization, he added, 74 of 79 countries
said the virus should be destroyed. Four, including the United
States, were uncertain, and at the time only Russia favored its
preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in January that this was an exceptionally difficult
issue, laden with foreign policy and scientific implications. ``We
said in 1996 that we would destroy it,'' the president said of the
virus stocks. But, he added, he wanted to be sure that destroying
the virus would not make it more difficult for the United States to
develop antidotes and new vaccines that would protect Americans and
``frankly the rest of the world,'' if there were a recurrence of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would rely heavily on guidance provided by the
Institute of Medicine in formulating his administration's position.
He said his major concern was that the United States should have
``whatever it takes to buy us a response'' to fight a potential
outbreak of smallpox, which was responsible for the deaths of
millions of people over centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the sole known collections of live virus are kept by
the Federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta
and the State Research of Virology and Biotechnology, known as
VECTOR, a leading Russian research institute in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   But many American experts fear that rogue states or terrorist
groups may have secured samples. There have been intelligence
reports, for example, that North Korea may have a stockpile of the
virus, possibly for use in biological warfare. Some experts have
speculated that a North Korean long-range missile fired in war
would more likely carry germs than nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Germs such as smallpox can be far more deadly than a nuclear
weapon, these experts say, because most people are no longer
vaccinated and hence have lost their immunity to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Smallpox is highly contagious and there is very little vaccine
stockpiled either in the United States or globally.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said that the president had
decided to retain the virus stocks ``in order to allow time to look
at antiviral agents and vaccines.'' Asked whether the White House
was concerned about objections to the decision, the official said:
``We need to prepare for weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of retaining the stocks also pointed out that the
vaccine available today could not be administered to people with
HIV and others with immune deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of all this, he made the right decision,'' said
another administration official who spoke on condition of anonymity
about the president's choice. ``To do anything else would have been
irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview late last year in Moscow, the VECTOR director,
Lev Sandakhchiev, denied that Russia had given samples to nations
like North Korea, as some conservatives have charged.
</P>
<P>
   But he passionately argued against destroying the virus,
stating, as he has in scientific papers, that infectious diseases
like smallpox cannot ever be considered completely eradicated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
