A8495 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CARBONNEAU-TEX     04-22 0294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CARBONNEAU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARBONNEAU HITS NET WHEN IT'S NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dallas Stars center Guy Carbonneau always expects he
could be the man in a tight playoff game. That's what keeps his
39-year-old bones energized at this time of season.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, he was the game breaker _ as he has been in six
previous playoff games _ when he scored the game-winner as the
Stars defeated Edmonton, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   With his goal, a forehand wrister off a drop pass from winger
Dave Reid, Carbonneau stands atop the Stars' list of playoff
difference makers, with seven game-winning goals.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the fan with the ``What a Guy'' sign said it best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got guys like (Mike) Modano and (Joe) Nieuwendyk, and
they've got guys like (Doug) Weight and (Ryan) Smyth, and they're
expected to score,'' Carbonneau said. ``But those guys get checked
so tightly that someone else has to do the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, it was me. Next game, hopefully it will be someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars needed Carbonneau's veteran leadership Wednesday
night. The Stars outshot the Oilers, 31-13. Nieuwendyk and Brett
Hull had four shots each on Edmonton goalie Tommy Salo, but the
puck wouldn't cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Modano even skated behind Salo through the crease with the puck
and was unable to bury it.
</P>
<P>
   It was the old-timer who solved Salo when it meant the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's proven that he's a winner,'' Edmonton captain Kelly
Buchberger said of Carbonneau. ``I don't know exactly how many
rings he has, but he's proven he can deliver in pressure
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau has two Stanley Cup rings, and if he continues to
make the opposition look bad this year, he might make it three.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT &LR;      04-22 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOSHII BLOWS 4-0 LEAD AS METS LOSE TO REDS, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The New York Mets were so convinced that Masato
Yoshii was the weak link in their pitching staff during spring
training that they were desperately trying to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii's performance Wednesday night might persuade the Mets to
resume their efforts. Staked to an early 4-0 lead the day after his
34th birthday, Yoshii did not survive the fourth inning, allowing
six runs on six hits in three-and-two-thirds innings in a 7-4 loss
to the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Through his first three starts this season, Yoshii (1-2) has
allowed 13 runs and 19 hits in 15 2/3 innings. Wednesday night, the
Japanese right-hander seemed unnerved by a two-run home run by Greg
Vaughn. Yoshii walked the next three batters, and all three runners
came around to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three walks were fatal,'' Yoshii said after the game
through his interpreter. So was Mike Cameron's two-run, two-out
ground-rule double to right. Bobby Bonilla, hobbled by the brace on
his right knee, could not run it down, and it gave the Reds a 5-4
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii's earned run average is now a jumbo 7.47 and the Mets
(9-6) have now dropped four of their last six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a few good innings,'' manager Bobby Valentine said of
his starter, adding that Yoshii will take his next scheduled turn.
``He just lost the strike zone there for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   And it cost the Mets a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla _ who felt a twinge in his knee making a tumbling catch
in the ninth _ had drilled his second home run in two days, a
two-run shot in the first, and Todd Pratt belted a solo shot in the
second. Roger Cedeno doubled to lead off the third before scoring
on a groundout, as Denny Neagle lasted just four innings in his
first Cincinnati start.
</P>
<P>
   But those were the only three hits the Mets could muster, and
Yoshii could not hold down the struggling Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was batting just .186 before the game, which might have
been one reason he was talking to a pair of bats in front of his
locker Wednesday afternoon as he attempted to decide which one to
use against Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just an adjustment period anytime you go somewhere
new,'' said Vaughn, who struggled when he was traded from Milwaukee
to San Diego in 1996. ``But I'm not going to have that type of year
this year, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hit just .216 for the Padres with 18 homers in 1997, his
first full season with the team. Then last season, Vaughn hit .272
and belted 50 home runs. Through his first 12 games with the Reds
this season, however, Vaughn had just two homers.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn _ who has been hampered since spring training by a
strawberry-size blister on the palm of his left hand _ was also
aware that Yoshii has a penchant for allowing home runs. Yoshii
surrendered 22 in 29 starts last season, and two in his first two
starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   And Vaughn said he had hit his share of homers here when he was
with the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have some this year, too,'' Vaughn said before
the game. ``I might even have some tonight if he gets the ball
up.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Yoshii did with Sean Casey standing on first
base in the fourth inning after Casey's second single of the game.
Vaughn made contact with an inside sinker that did not sink.
</P>
<P>
   And when the ball soared over the left-field fence for Vaughn's
third homer of the year, the four-run lead was 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   But afterward Vaughn was still upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be happy,'' said Vaughn, who had keyed the winning
rally. ``But I'm still battling on every at-bat. It shouldn't be
that tough.''
</P>
<P>
   At least, it was pointed out, he had picked out the right bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think I used Dmitri Young's bat,'' Vaughn said.
``My bats weren't listening too good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
