<HEADLINE>
BONE SPUR'S RETURN PUTS OSUNA BACK ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In two days, Los Angeles Dodgers right-hander
Antonio Osuna went from having a blister to needing surgery to
remove a bone spur from his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers put Osuna back on the 15-day disabled list,
retroactive to Sunday, and recalled left-hander Jeff Kubenka from
Triple-A Albuquerque on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI revealed Osuna has a bone spur in the same location as
the one removed in September. Dodgers team physician Dr. Frank Jobe
was scheduled to perform surgery today at 8 a.m., but Wednesday
afternoon Osuna decided to put it off for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who played long toss afterward, said he would like to
throw on the side Friday before he elects to have surgery. If he
feels even a slight twinge in the elbow, Osuna said he'll opt for
the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, manager Davey Johnson said the 26-year-old
could miss 6-8 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am worried because I already had an operation and it's
almost the same thing I had last year,'' Osuna said. ``I'm also
worried because even though I pitched in San Bernardino and San
Diego, I never felt 100 percent. It was not like any other year
when I threw all of my pitches and didn't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna began the season on the disabled list with soreness in his
right elbow. He was activated Friday and pitched a scoreless inning
Saturday in San Diego, but was unavailable the next few days
because of a blister.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna's disability puts the Dodgers' bullpen in a precarious
situation with a sore-armed Alan Mills (he's expected to be
available Friday), closer Jeff Shaw, lefties Pedro Borbon,
21-year-old Onan Masaoka and Kubenka and right-handers Robinson
Checo and Jamie Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, Checo, Kubenka and Masaoka entered Wednesday's game
against Atlanta with a combined 22 major-league appearances on
their resume.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers' decision makers said Arnold's two innings of
scoreless relief Tuesday eased their minds. Kubenka was 1-0 with a
0.96 ERA in six appearances with Los Angeles last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kubenka pitched well here last year and Arnold took away a lot
of concerns last night,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``In comparison to what other clubs are going through, I feel
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Kubenka, who was 0-1 with a 4.50 ERA with
Albuquerque, gives the Dodgers 2{ lefties in the bullpen. Though
he's a left-hander, the movement on his pitches resembles that of a
right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the stuff we did in spring training is here right
now,'' Dodgers pitching coach Charlie Hough said. ``Davey had a
good plan. You don't go with five or six men in the bullpen, you go
with 10 or 11 so you see what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubenka and Arnold accompanied the Dodgers to Los Angeles for
the exhibition games prior to the season.
</P>
<P>
   Skippin' Perez: As expected, Hough said right-hander Darren
Dreifort would start Sunday against the St. Louis Cardinals while
the Dodgers skip left-hander Carlos Perez's spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Hough said the Dodgers, who are off today and Monday, would
think of using Perez in relief between starts. But he wants Perez
to use the time to work on his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just throw his fastball, locating his fastball,'' Hough said.
``All eight of the Braves' hits came on offspeed pitches. He just
throws too many offspeed pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra bases: Jose Vizcaino made his second straight start at
shortstop for the Dodgers.... The Dodgers entered the finale of the
three-game series with Atlanta leading the league with 26 stolen
bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
