r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPUS-AZR &LR;      04-22 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY STUDENTS EXPRESS SORROW OVER KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apollo High School senior Julie Tadano wept softly Wednesday as
she penned a sympathy note to a stranger in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   She had no ties to Columbine High School, where 15 died Tuesday
in one of the worst shooting rampages in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was some kinship: In another act of random
violence, two classmates at Apollo had been shot to death last year
while walking to a pizza parlor. Suddenly, a shooting hundreds of
miles away seemed all too close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really over it,'' Tadano said, ``and I don't think I
will ever be.''
</P>
<P>
   She was joined Wednesday by 1,200 other Apollo students who
wanted to send words of encouragement to the grieving students and
families at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in the situation and thought of how we might
help, such as doing a blood drive or raising money,'' said Fred
Weaver, Apollo student body president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that writing notes that we care about them would be
best,'' he said. ``We realize how a tragedy can affect kids on
campus, and we want them to know how we came together as a
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the Valley on Wednesday, students had vastly different
reactions to the deadly attack in Littleton. Some sought to show
support by giving blood, donating money or sending cards.
</P>
<P>
   Some came to school confident they were safe; others expressed
fear that their campuses could be next.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scary thing about teenage life today is you don't know,''
said D.J. Mahoney, 17, a senior at Brophy College Preparatory in
Phoenix. ``It's not about a fistfight anymore. It's about a kid who
has a gun and it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others empathized with the shooters, saying they too had
been taunted.
</P>
<P>
   Said Saguaro High School sophomore Mary Dalsin, ``I think
everyone has been tormented at school, but the fact they went
through with it was pretty wild.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting spree had other effects as well: ``I told my mom I
wasn't going to pick on anyone anymore,'' said Danielle Honeybone,
a 17-year-old Mesa High School junior.
</P>
<P>
   School officials and counselors, meanwhile, worked throughout
the day to address safety concerns and help students and parents
make sense of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Peoria Unified School District, for instance, elementary
school students were given brochures on gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   There were also simpler gestures: The staff at Tempe High School
lowered its flag to half-staff to honor the shooting victims.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide effort to promote safe schools also began to take
shape Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Hemphill, spokeswoman for the Arizona School Boards
Association, said a coalition of educators, employees of Tosco
Corp. and others are taking the first step with a sticker campaign
that promotes safety.
</P>
<P>
   They want to distribute stickers shaped like red school houses
that read ``I support safe schools and safe communities'' to the
800,000 schoolkids around the state. They hope to have them
available early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull may also call for a statewide moment of silence,
or some other show of support, in the next few days, her
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   For some students, Wednesday began with a moment of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise Valley High School Principal Gary Damore also made a
plea to students to report anything suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although incidents like this are extremely rare, we want you
to feel safe in reporting anything that may interfere with the
safety and well-being of anyone on campus,'' Damore told the
students in an early-morning announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo students, led by Weaver, quickly organized their
note-writing campaign to Columbine students. Some said the deaths
of their own classmates, honor students Renelyn Simmons and Andre
Bradley, were still fresh in their minds even after 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   Tadano offered students in Colorado a religious message. ``I
told them to watch for the answers and to pray; God promises that
he will heal the brokenhearted.''
</P>
<P>
   Student Jill Dumbauld, who also took part in the effort, said,
``It's so heartbreaking for students when someone you know is the
victim of violence. We understand what the students in Colorado are
going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Peoria school officials hustled to get letters out to
parents explaining officials' efforts to cut down on violent
behavior in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the safest places children can be in today's day and
age is in a school. . . . What happened was a random act of
violence,'' said Peoria district spokeswoman Sandi Hicks. ``It's a
one in a million chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Sandoval, 16, a sophomore at South Mountain High School,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe what happened (in Littleton) could happen anywhere, but
this is a pretty safe campus,'' she said of the south Phoenix
school.
</P>
<P>
   Schoolmate Danielle Gill, 16, said the campus is a world apart
from Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have stuff going on at our school, but it's nothing here
compared to what's going on at that Littleton school,'' she said.
``It just doesn't compare to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Peoria High School junior Jason Allis was sure nothing like the
incident in Colorado would happen at his school. How do he and his
friends get beyond the tragedy that took the lives of kids their
age?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't here,'' Allis said and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   But some students and parents weren't so secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible tragedy,'' said Michael Schwimmer, as he was
dropping his son at Saguaro High School. ``As a parent, I have
fears it could happen anywhere. But part of me wants to naively
believe it won't happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   At Mesa High School, Brittaney Malone walked to campus as she
does every day. She waved to friends in passing cars and exchanged
quips with friend Melissa Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   But all the while, she was thinking about Colorado and a friend
who lives there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend may have been shot,'' said Malone, a 16-year-old
junior. ``I called her house and couldn't get through. I'm just
hoping nothing happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to come to school today.''
</P>
<P>
   Student after student at Mesa High repeated the mantra of the
day: ``If it could happen there, it could happen anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a ripple effect,'' said Jermaine Henson, a 16-year-old
junior. ``It could happen to anyone anywhere any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooters in Columbine have been called members of a ``Trench
Coat Mafia'' clique _ a group many students in the Valley said they
had never heard of. But groups of students on their campuses do
favor a ``Gothic'' look, dressing in all black, with dyed black
hair and painted black nails.
</P>
<P>
   Honeybone, the junior at Mesa High, said some athletes and other
students at her school often pick on the Goth crowd, a small clique
that mostly keeps to itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call them `freaks,' '' Honeybone said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney, the Brophy senior, said a similar Goth group also is
ridiculed at his campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though you don't know, based on their dress, I think it's
a typical high school's reaction to have some negativity toward
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few kids at Marcos de Niza High School in Tempe, who say they
are part of the Goth crowd, say they've been unfairly taunted and
stereotyped.
</P>
<P>
   Said Sara Nelson, 16, ``Just because you are Gothic doesn't mean
you don't know right from wrong, it doesn't mean you don't have
morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Eric Gray, 18, ``I wear black and I'm probably the biggest
pacifist.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the shootings prompted some students to make a mental
list of whom they've crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of scary because you don't know if someone is going
to bring a gun,'' said Tom Thurmond, a freshman at Saguaro High
School. ``I don't know how many people I made mad.'' &QL; 
Contributing to this report were Lori Baker, Connie Cone Sexton,
Jim Gintonio, Melissa Jones, Ryan Konig, Rachel Ochoa, Kelly
Pearce, Betty Reid, Susie Steckner, Herb Whitney and Sherrie
Buzby. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
