<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALO, OILERS SERVE STARS A SWEATY TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sweaty, yet perfect. But very sweaty, not to mention
physical and bloody, at least for Guy Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that, however, just what the Dallas Stars needed Wednesday
night _ blood, sweat and a good scare?
</P>
<P>
   The answer would seem to be yes, as long, of course, as the
evening was finally topped off with a Game 1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton did not want to go easy. Then again, when has Edmonton
done a timid fade when hooked up against the heavily favored Stars
in a playoff series?
</P>
<P>
   Any chance of ho-hum overconfidence creeping in for the Stars,
and that was certainly a possibility, was washed away in the stream
of blood that flowed down Carbonneau's face in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It was no way to treat the night's hero, but Carbonneau's
game-winning goal with just less than seven minutes to play secured
a 2-1 victory. But it took a while to secure anything.
</P>
<P>
   Down 1-0 going into the final 20 minutes, the Stars were shoved
into survival mode by the give-me-your-best-shot goaltending of one
Tommy Salo.
</P>
<P>
   Who does this Salo think he is _ Cujo?
</P>
<P>
   With Curtis Joseph finally a distant memory, or nightmare, when
it came to playing the Oilers in the postseason, here comes Salo,
making the first playoff start of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, I was thinking flashback,'' said Carbonneau, and
no one around here had to ask flashback to what?
</P>
<P>
   Salo? Cujo? There wasn't any difference in the first two
periods, or really for the game. With the Stars putting 31 shots on
the Swede, it was a fluke Jere Lehtinen goal that tied it seconds
into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau finally cracked Salo, beating him on a wrister that
found five-hole. To perform so well all night, then give up the
game winner on a puck between his legs, put only a small dent in
Salo's Grade A effort.
</P>
<P>
   But the small dent was enough for the scared Stars to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, this was a game where we would have become
frustrated,'' Hitchcock said, recalling that still hard to swallow
playoff ousting by Cujo and the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Salo was causing frustration of his own. To a certain
degree so did the referee duo of Don Koharski and Mick McGeough,
who called a loose game, allowing the muscle to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't necessarily make Koharski and McGeough bad people,
but it played right into Edmonton's body slams. With top scorers
Bill Guerin and Josef Beranek missing with injuries, the Oilers'
best chance to steal a victory was with muscle and Salo. It almost
worked, too.
</P>
<P>
   In a brutal game overall, the lads became overhyper in the final
minutes, and as the rough stuff prevailed, Doug Weight boarded
Carbonneau, opening up a nasty gash under his left eye. That led to
more roughness, and although the final buzzer ended it, it may have
only given us the theme for Game 2 on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was fitting that the opener be decided by the play
of the Stars' checking line. Old-timers Carbonneau and Dave Reid,
along with the youngster, Blake Sloan, were excellent on every
shift.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the third period, with the score tied, that
threesome took the puck off the end boards and passed it around
like the Showtime Lakers of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Carbo creeping in, and slid it to him,'' Reid said. ``We
finally had a guy who was open in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on everything else Salo had stopped all night, it was
stunning when Carbonneau's hammer sailed through the legs.
</P>
<P>
   But Reid made a key point. The Oilers were effective in keeping
traffic clear in front of Salo. And when there was an Edmonton
breakdown, Salo either had the answer or the Stars couldn't bury
the puck. The Stars not finishing off good chances became a nagging
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, nothing came easy for the Stars, which was an
instant reminder that the Presidents' Trophy is now stored away in
Tom Hicks' closet. In other words, no one cares.
</P>
<P>
   And the history lesson attached to this Game 1 is also
significant. In the past two years, the Stars have lost Game 2's in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday night will define our team in this series,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   But so maybe did Game 1. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
