<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' CARBONNEAU SCORES WINNER IN TIGHT OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Guy Carbonneau stood with blood covering his face and a
mix of French-English expletives spewing from his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and freeze that picture of the 39-year-old center; it's
a symbol of what the Stars might have to become to capture their
first-round playoff series with the Edmonton Oilers, and eventually
what they might have to become to win the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau pumped in the game-winning goal with 6:53 remaining
in Game 1 to complete a third-period comeback in a 2-1 Stars
victory over the Oilers Wednesday night before a frenetic crowd of
17,001 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to getting a key victory in their best-of-seven
Western Conference quarterfinals with the Oilers, the Stars also
established themselves as a team that won't back down from a
physical challenge. In a game that contained an astounding 110 hits
and ended with five players receiving misconduct penalties, the
Stars showed they can flex plenty of muscle even with suspended
captain Derian Hatcher out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where people got this idea that we're not a tough
team or that they can push us around,'' defenseman Craig Ludwig
said. ``We've played tough against (the Oilers) before; we played
tough against Phoenix. We'll play whatever game they want to put
out on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars did just that, getting a team-leading seven hits from
Carbonneau and spreading their venom throughout the lineup. When a
decidedly larger Oilers team came out hitting in the first period,
the Stars didn't back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rough,'' defenseman Richard Matvichuk said. ``When you
see (Stars center) Mike Modano and (Oilers center) Doug Weight
throwing it around, you know it's a physical game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers almost used that physical strategy to perfection,
surviving a tight-checking game and taking a 1-0 lead into the
third period, thanks to an acrobatic game by goalie Tommy Salo, who
faced 31 shots while his teammates took 13.
</P>
<P>
   But just when Salo seemed impenetrable, the Stars came up with
two third-period goals and avoided what could have been a huge
upset. The Stars entered the series with the best record in the NHL
during the regular season and were 34 points better than the
Oilers, who came in as the eighth seed in the West.
</P>
<P>
   But with Salo looking the part of former Oilers goalie and Stars
killer Curtis Joseph, the Stars turned to their most unlikely
scoring line. With the score tied 1-1, the line of Carbonneau, Dave
Reid and Blake Sloan _ which had accounted for a total of 10 goals
during the regular season _ worked the shift of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan and Reid continuously pounded against the physical Oilers
to win possession of the puck behind the net, then Sloan circled
into the slot on his backhand. Sloan flicked the puck forward to
Reid, who dropped a pass across the slot to the right circle. From
there, Carbonneau snapped in a 25-footer for the game winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if we kept working, we could get a chance, and we just
happened to find someone open,'' Reid said. ``And Carbo buried
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams meet again Friday night at Reunion Arena in Game
2, and it promises to be a physical affair. Weight received a
five-minute major penalty and a game misconduct for boarding
Carbonneau with 4.6 seconds remaining _ the hit that bloodied his
face. A scrum ensued, and four more misconduct penalties were
handed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more physical the better,'' Oilers coach Ron Low said.
``If you think this series is going to go more than four games, and
some people don't, then physical is the way we have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers came out flailing and established that the game would
be a physical affair, and referees Don Koharski and Mick McGeough
went along with that plan. With each Oilers hit, though, the Stars
decided to hit back until the first period became a shoving match
in which neither team was able to establish much in the department
of offensive chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers scored on their eighth shot of the game with 1:06
remaining in the second period. Rem Murray chipped a puck past Ed
Belfour after a strong forecheck by Oilers linemate Alex Selivanov,
and the Oilers were looking like Spoilers once again.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton upset the second seed in the first round the past two
years _ including over the Stars two seasons ago _ and appeared
ready to go for the hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars gathered themselves after the second intermission,
and Jere Lehtinen scored 13 seconds into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars then kept hammering Salo until Carbonneau finally came
through with a statement goal in a statement game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to play physical, we can play physical,'' Ludwig
said. ``We're going to miss Derian, but we're through talking about
that right now. We're just playing games right now, and we'll do
whatever we need to do to win games.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
