<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-SPRINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR IMPLICATIONS SEEN IN GERMAN-ITALIAN COMMUNICATIONS MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TELECOM and EUROPE-CHANGES) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some details of the deal between Deutsche Telekom and Telecom
Italia may remain uncertain, but many executives close to the
Global One partnership of Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and
Sprint agree that at least three things with important implications
for the future structure of the global communications industry have
become clear.
</P>
<P>
   First, a merger between the German and Italian companies would
spell the end of Deutsche Telekom's seven-year partnership with
France Telecom. Even if a Deutsche Telekom-Telecom Italia merger
never happens, the relationship between the German and French
companies may have already been shattered by the German carrier's
ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a dissolution of the France Telecom-Deutsche Telekom
partnership spells the end for Global One, at least in its current
form. It became clear last month that long-troubled Global One was
on the verge of collapse; a merger between Deutsche Telekom and
Telecom Italia would turn Global One's likely demise into a virtual
certainty. It is almost inconceivable that Sprint, France Telecom,
Deutsche Telekom and the former Telecom Italia could remain in a
four-way partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Sprint, the No. 3 U.S. long-distance carrier, may soon be
faced with the opportunity to redefine its international strategy.
For Sprint, that redefinition will probably mean deciding whether
to link with France Telecom, a merged German-Italian behemoth, or
with another international carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The other major U.S. long-distance companies, AT&AMP;T and MCI
Worldcom, are also trying to build their international businesses,
AT&AMP;T in partnership with British Telecom and MCI Worldcom in tandem
with Telefonica de Espana. But the impact of a Deutsche
Telekom-Telecom Italia merger would be smaller on them than on
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom each agreed to
acquire 10 percent of Sprint and in 1996 the three companies formed
Global One, a venture aimed at serving the communications needs of
multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   But the German and French companies already had their own
partnership, formed in 1992 and code-named Atlas.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas is in trouble. France Telecom is extremely upset at
Deutsche Telekom not only for pursuing Telecom Italia in the first
place but for reportedly denying such aspirations up until the very
day news of the negotiations broke last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project is contrary to the agreements between France
Telecom and Deutsche Telekom,'' Michel Bon, the chairman and chief
executive of France Telecom, said Wednesday in reaction to the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some executives close to Global One are convinced that
the European antitrust regulators will oppose an alliance among the
dominant phone companies in France, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The split between France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom is
important for Sprint because Global One is technically a joint
venture between Sprint and Atlas, and if Atlas collapses, the basic
structure of Global One is thrown into doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Global One said that from France Telecom's
perspective, Deutsche Telekom had moved to withdraw itself from
Global One, leaving France Telecom together with Sprint for now.
But it may not be that simple.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the discord among the European carriers, France
Telecom and Deutsche Telekom each have told Sprint they want to
continue working with Sprint in order to keep a foothold in the
lucrative U.S. market, according to executives close to Global One.
</P>
<P>
   That could leave Sprint in something of the catbird seat, with
the ability to choose its partner for the future. Global One
foundered largely because of differences among its three partners.
For Sprint, the chance to link with one overseas carrier with whom
it shares a common vision might compensate for the loss of the
third partner.
</P>
<P>
   One rumor is that Deutsche Telekom would actually like to
acquire Sprint. But that could prove difficult because under its
agreement with Sprint, France Telecom has the right to match any
additional equity investment made in Sprint by Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
</TEXT>
