r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-OILERS-SALO-TEX     04-22 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-OILERS-SALO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALO FALLS SHORT OF FILLING BIG SHOES LEFT BY `CUJO'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ His first NHL playoff game, and all Edmonton goalie
Tommy Salo had to do was play the team with the best record in the
league and replace former Oilers goalie Curtis Joseph, who always
had his best game going in time for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So, any sign of nerves from Mr. Salo?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when he started puking before he got on the ice,'' Oilers
forward Doug Weight deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Salo blamed his upset tummy on Tuesday's dinner. He said he took
some of ``that pink stuff,'' and felt well.
</P>
<P>
   He played well, too, and was a bright spot in the Oilers' 2-1
loss against the Stars in Game 1 of a Western Conference
first-round series last night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Salo said when asked if he felt confident coming
in. ``With a performance like this, and if we continue to play like
this, we can continue to cause them some trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   For 53 minutes and 7 seconds last night, Salo looked like the
guy he replaced. Joseph bolted last summer for a bigger contract
with Toronto. Salo came to Edmonton in a trade at the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   He made save after save after solid save last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, I was thinking flashback,'' said Guy Carbonneau,
a Star in 1997 when Joseph almost single-handedly upset Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Flashback looked to be an understatement until Carbonneau
slipped a puck, and eventual game-winning goal, between Salo's
seemingly impenetrable pads with 6:53 remaining to erase a 1-all
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   Chants of ``Salo, Salo'' began in earnst from Stars fans then.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us a chance to win the hockey game,'' Oilers coach Ron
Low said. ``I thought he was outstanding, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for him, his Oilers needed better than
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Shots were sporadic at best for Edmonton, 13 in all. Kelly
Buchberger registered Edmonton's first shot midway through
first-period action.
</P>
<P>
   Salo kept them in the game. He couldn't win it.
</P>
<P>
   He had been kind of an unknown coming in, so unknown that Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock called a couple of Eastern Conference coaches
for a scouting report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing they told us is if he sees it he'll stop it, and
that's what he did tonight,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's a world-class
goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Salo faced 31 shots, stopping all of them but two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe for the people in Dallas and people wondering about
Tommy's first playoff game, he answered it,'' Weight said. ``He
answered it for us a long time ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
