<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS BEAT UNIMPRESSIVE BULLS, 99-87 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Needless to say, these were not Michael
Jordan's Chicago Bulls who visited Continental Arena Wednesday
night. But to the dismay of the 15,874 fans, they were not even
Toni Kukoc's Bulls, or Ron Harper's, or Brent Barry's.
</P>
<P>
   While the presence of Chicago's talent-challenged,
injury-depleted club enabled the fans to witness a New Jersey Nets
victory, it also made for an uncompetitive game that was filled
with poor play and devoid of suspense. Without approaching their
``A game,'' the Nets never trailed, led by as many as 25 points and
won by 99-87.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Nets' first over Chicago since Jordan missed
a 13-footer at the buzzer in March 1997, giving New Jersey a 99-98
victory at the Meadowlands and ending the Bulls' seven-game winning
streak over the Nets. Wednesday night's outcome also served as
payback for the two embarrassing losses the Nets endured this
season in Chicago. But there was little celebration in the Nets'
locker room afterward. As hungry as they were for victories, they
realized that this was nothing to party about.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were without Kukoc and Harper and, to be honest, they're
not a very good team without those guys,'' said Kendall Gill, who
coasted through a lethargic 6-point, 4-rebound, 1-steal effort.
</P>
<P>
   As a Chicago native, Gill usually gets psyched for the Bulls
(12-31). But he admitted there was no adrenaline rush Wednesday
night. ``I wasn't so pumped up to play against them this time,''
Gill said, laughing. ``I was running down the court, thinking about
what I was going to do and where I was going to go eat after the
game. I'm serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc, the Bulls' leading scorer in this wretched season with an
18.7 point average, was out with a minor separation of the left
shoulder. Barry, their second-leading scorer (11.4), missed the
game with a sprained right ankle, and Harper, third in scoring
(10.6), was sidelined by a broken nose. Those were all of the
Bulls' double-figure scorers.
</P>
<P>
   That left guys like Kornel David, Cory Carr and Keith Booth in
Chicago's starting five, and enabled the Nets (13-29) to run to a
24-14 first-quarter lead that was never challenged. Keith Van Horn
led the Nets with 28 points and made all 14 of his foul shots as
the Nets set a franchise record by making 23 of 23 free throws. The
previous New Jersey mark for perfection was 17 of 17, set on Nov.
27, 1989, at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Feick continued his game-by-game improvement by grabbing a
career-high 17 rebounds to push the Nets to a 9-rebound advantage
on the backboards. Feick's 8 first-quarter rebounds were 1 more
than the Bulls' entire team managed.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Feick was no more excited than the rest of his
teammates. When asked if these were the real Bulls, he looked up
with a sheepish grin and said, ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
