<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FACES, 1 EXPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ They had started arriving by the time
daylight began to fil ter through the tree's naked limbs. They came
to Clement Park with hand-scripted posters, rosary beads and newly
bought bouquets in their arms, and with their eyes drizzling tears.
They came to that thin sapling within sight of Colum bine High
School all Wednesday long.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, to a woman, to a child, each arrival shared the same
face.
</P>
<P>
   It was an expression simulta neously intense and flat, numb and
full of hurt, a stare that bored into the tree like the bit of a
drill. The man fingering his rosary wore it. So did the football
player trying to hide his face behind scabbed fingers. So did the
teenage girl whose lips moved as she silently recited the sign on
the ground at her feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is our future? To all my peers who lost their lives and
inno cence.''
</P>
<P>
   She added her three white carna tions to the pile. Her footsteps
tracked through the wet grass. Her face never changed.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of like the day.
</P>
<P>
   They wore that same look all across Littleton on Wednesday, in
the aftermath of Columbine High School, as the 15 bodies left
behind began to come out one by one, and the story of Eric Harris
and Dylan Klebold, the killers, began to come out one mouthful at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Baumgart, a Columbine senior, stood not 10 yards from the
tree, staring past it. He went to grade school with Klebold, he
said, was friends with him in the Boy Scouts during middle school.
By Columbine, though, by the time Nick, Harris and Klebold shared a
video production class junior year, everyone could sense the
separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't the students se cluding them. It was kind of
mu tual,'' he said. ``They pushed themselves away, and in turn the
student body kind of pushed them away. But there was nothing to
clue you in that something like this could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until gunfire and explosions ripped holes in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   And five holes in 17-year-old Richard Castaldo.
</P>
<P>
   The junior's father, Rick, flew to Colorado from Virginia within
hours of flipping on CNN. As his son lay upstairs in critical
condition in the Swedish Medical Center's ICU _ spleen gone, two
ribs bro ken and a bullet left embedded in his back _ Rick stepped
outside wearing the Littleton look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard has a breathing tube, but he looks pretty good to
me,'' he said. ``What the nurses have done is, they put a pen in
his right hand. He has both arms bandaged, but they hold a
clipboard up and every time he writes, he writes, `When does the
breathing tube come out?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Out comes the father's wallet and a picture of his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fortunate,'' he explains. ``Even though my son still has a
bullet in him and he's in critical, I feel fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Dr. Phil Mallory, though his downcast eyes worked like a
sur gical mask.
</P>
<P>
   His patient, Anne Marie Hochal ter, 17, was among the first to
arrive Tuesday, in deep shock, shot through her chest and liver.
Mallory served in the Army Medical Corps during Desert Storm. The
condition of the teens and the doctoring re minded him of battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally went to the operat ing room with our fingers in
the dike as far as her liver injury was concerned,'' he said. ``My
thought . . . was `My God, if I don't do something quick, this
pretty little girl is going to die.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Marie did not, will not, though 15 others have. This kept
men, women and children coming to that bare tree a few hundred
yards from the school all day long. The flower pile grew until it
seemed feet deep, and a pinwheel fluttered lightly when the wind
picked up. Each new arrival wore that same face.
</P>
<P>
   From dawn to dusk, they prayed, wept, laid gifts and stared with
a vengeance at that sapling.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of eyes looked for hours, face after face, and no one
saw a thing. &QL; 
 &UR; David Leibowitz can be reached at (602)
 &UR; 444-8515 or at david.leibowitz &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
