<P>
   FROGDESIGN (Undated) _ Seeking to improve the image of its
flight attendants, Lufthansa went to frogdesign, a company founded
in Germany, with offices in New York, California and Texas, and
dedicated to what it calls ``integrated strategic design and
communications.'' Airlines have always resorted to designers; in
the '40s and '50s, Henry Dreyfuss and Raymond Loewy did full
redesigns, right down to the forks and sugar packages. By Phil
Patton.
</P>
<P>
   NC-FURNITURE (High Point, N.C.) _ If furniture follows fashion,
then the International Home Furnishings Market, which opened here
last Thursday and ends tomorrow, is a cashmere twin set: luxurious,
understated, pretty and comfortingly familiar. By Liz Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   PICKLE-BOTTLE (Undated) _ ``Did you hear about the guy who
bought an old pickle bottle for $30 at Brimfield and sold it on
eBay for $32,000?'' That was the buzz at a flea market in
Adamstown, Penn.,earlier this month. And it was almost the truth.
The pickle bottle wasn't bought at Brimfield, the popular flea
market in Massachusetts, but it was sold on eBay, the internet
auction site. The pickle bottle actually cost only $3 and it sold
for $44,100. By Kathleen Moloney.
</P>
<P>
   WILLOWS-GARDENR (Palm Springs, Calif.) _ A Mediterranean-style
mansion called the Willows, tucked into the flank of Mount San
Jacinto here, was best known in the 1950s as the home of Marion
Davies, an actress famous as the paramour of the newspaper magnate
William Randolph Hearst. Before that it was known as the place
where Clark Gable and Carole Lombard stayed on their honeymoon. But
perhaps the best reason to know the Willows is that it was bought
shortly after it was built in 1927 by Samuel Untermeyer, a New York
civil rights lawyer and passionate horticulturist. By Jim Robbins.
</P>
