<HEADLINE>
TRANSITION FROM OUTCAST TO MURDERER CAN BE QUICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For as long as there have been high schools, there have been
``outsiders'' _ students who don't quite fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Although several decades ago it was often considered romantic to
be a rebel, today it can mean bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   School counselors across the Valley, charged with everything
from guiding students down career paths to helping them cope,
watched in horror as the massacre in Littleton, Colo., unfolded
Tuesday. In an instant, they realized it could have been their
school, their students.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, worried students came to them a day later,
saddened for teenagers they had never met.
</P>
<P>
   Like never before, anticipating the actions of troubled
teenagers is as complicated as an intricate spider's web,
counselors said Wednesday. No longer is it just the rowdies and
aggressive kids who have the potential to turn their schools into a
war zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the silent menace,'' said Linda Somo, a Mountain
View High counselor who views her school population as a mirror
image of that at Columbine High School. ``Where do you draw the
line? Where do you go from being an outsider to being a murderer?''
</P>
<P>
   And, why is the school no longer a safe refuge from violence?
</P>
<P>
   According to some psychology experts, it's because our world is
increasingly fragmented, that it's too easy for children to get
their hands on weapons, that the young harbor too many prejudices
and that families continue to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Although school counselors are adept at spotting suicidal
students or those with drug problems, predicting who will become
violent is a shade of gray.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a student writes an essay about death. Maybe another wears
black clothing, black nail polish and black lipstick. Maybe a third
is a fan of Dungeons and Dragons or Marilyn Manson.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, teachers refer these students to school counselors
like Somo, who oversees about 450 students. Ninety-nine times out
of a 100 their actions are harmless.
</P>
<P>
   But one is too many.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to address this,'' said Somo, who has 28 years of
experience in the education field. ``Maybe there needs to be more
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Zello, Mesa Public Schools' lead psychologist, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is on the lookout for troubled students,'' he said.
``We want to help them get through adolescence, which is difficult
at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the school needs to be more observant, said Alan
Brown, director of planning and research at Arizona State
University's Arizona Prevention Center. He has isolated 15
programs, from early childhood intervention to anti-bullying
classes, that might deter youth from violent paths.
</P>
<P>
   Being observant means looking for warning signals, including
changes in friends, behavior, family situations, attire and grades,
said Donna Pisciotta, a social worker in the Tempe Union High
School District.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors call parents, sometimes asking them to pursue outside
therapy for their children. They also interview the student's
friends to get at the heart of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Fabes, a professor of child development at Arizona State
University, said intervention also should include compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you feel empathy, nurturing and caring toward others, it's
unlikely that you are going to engage in violent acts that harm
others,'' he said. ``Parents who take the time to point out the
consequences of the child's negative behavior on others promote
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with all this effort, however, tragedies still can strike.
</P>
<P>
   Pisciotta knows the students in Littleton will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be traumatized for years,'' she said. ``You don't
forget someone putting a gun to your head.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
