<HEADLINE>
PUGET SOUND REGION IN DANGER OF VIOLATING EPA POLLUTION LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Smog is threatening Seattle's reputation as one of the
nation's most livable metropolises.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of avoiding violations of federal clean air
standards, growing levels of ozone are likely to put the
Seattle-Tacoma-Everett area in violation of the EPA's new standards
this summer or next, according to the Puget Sound Air Pollution
Control Agency.
</P>
<P>
   At risk is the region's eligibility for federal highway funds
and the health of its residents, particularly children, whose rates
of asthma have been rising in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And the villain this time around is not factory smoke stacks
belching pollutants into the air. On Thursday, Earth Day 1999,
about 60 percent of the region's air pollution can be blamed on its
drivers, on the road and off.
</P>
<P>
   A soaring number of motor vehicles daily travel 63 million miles
in the Puget Sound area, emitting pollutants as they go, said
Dennis McLerran, the region's Air Pollution Control Officer. Power
boats, gas-powered lawn mowers and construction equipment also
contribute to pollution in King, Snohomish and Pierce counties.
</P>
<P>
   During the hottest days of summer, ozone is formed in the open
air when oxides of nitrogen mix with volatile organic chemicals
released from car exhausts and other sources. A prevailing
southeasterly breeze carries the smog to the foothills of the
Cascade Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   At a monitoring station two miles east of Enumclaw, Wash., ozone
levels have consistently climbed over new federal limits set in
1997 over the past few years, said the pollution control agency. In
July 1998 ozone levels also exceeded the standards at Lake
Sammamish State Park and in La Grande, near Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown the ozone is stunting needle growth on pine
and fir trees in what scientists have dubbed the region's
``photochemical belt,'' said Jane Koenig, a University of
Washington professor of environmental health. Koenig is designing a
study to examine whether towns in the Cascade foothills are also
seeing an increase in children's emergency room visits, as Atlanta
did when its smog exceed federal limits.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA won't determine whether the Puget Sound region is
officially in violation until it has three years of data showing
ozone levels have consistently exceeded standards, said Mahbubul
Islam, an EPA environmental scientists.
</P>
<P>
   But McLerran said ``after four more days of temperatures at or
above 90-degree levels this summer,'' the region could be in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Once in violation, the region must document steps it's taking to
reduce ozone levels to healthful levels within 18 months. If it
fails, it could lose federal highway funding, Islam said.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, for instance, more than 60 road building projects
have been put on hold since the city ran afoul of the Clean Air Act
last year.
</P>
<P>
   An even greater motivator for reducing ozone levels may be the
ill effects of air pollution. In King County, the rate of children
being hospitalized with asthma has increased 34 percent since the
late 1980s, jumping from 350 per 100,000 children to 470 per
100,000 children in 1996, according to the Seattle-King County
Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig, the UW environmental health professor, said air
pollution alone can't be blamed for the increase, but is
unquestionably a contributor. She said laboratory studies have
shown children have increased inflammation and fluid in their lungs
after being exposed to ozone.
</P>
<P>
   And a recent study of 130 freshman at the University of
California at Berkeley found those with higher lifetime exposures
to ozone had smaller lung capacities, suggesting air pollution
actually ``blunts lung growth,'' said Koenig.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with asthma, especially children, are being considered
the canaries in the coal mine,'' she said. ``They are telling us
that the air we breathe even at the present EPA standards can cause
adverse health effects.''
</P>
<P>
   At a forum next week sponsored by the Economic Development
Council of Seattle and King County, business and government leaders
will discuss what steps can be taken to tackle the ozone problem.
McLerran said possible solutions include:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Ramping up the campaign to encourage people not to drive,
mow laws, refuel gas tanks, or cruise in motorboats on hot summer
days. Gasoline and diesel-powered cars produce more than 500,000
pounds of smog-forming pollutants on the average summer day.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Better growth management. According to the Puget Sound
Regional Council, the growth in total vehicle miles traveled each
day has far outpaced the region's population growth over the last
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   From 1981 to 1997, the population of King, Pierce, Snohomish and
Kitsap counties increased from 2.3 million to 3.1 million, a 35
percent increase. But the number of vehicle miles traveled
increased 107 percent. Planners attribute the growth to women
joining the work force in increasing numbers, and people choosing
to live in suburban communities far from employment centers.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCumber, executive director of the regional council, said
urban villages that encourage people to live, work and shop in
relatively compact areas have been slow to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to stop driving our cars, but we can encourage
people to drive them a little less,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Toughening emission standards for pickup trucks and sport
utility vehicles, which tend to emit several times as much
pollution as cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
