<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROTHSCHILD-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATSHEVA DE ROTHSCHILD, 84, DANCE PATRON, DIES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baroness Batsheva de Rothschild, a patron of Martha Graham and
of modern dance in Israel, died on Tuesday at her home in Tel Aviv.
She was 84.
</P>
<P>
   The granddaughter of Baron James de Rothschild, the founder of
the French branch of the Rothschild banking family, de Rothschild
became a supporter of Graham after seeing performances by her and
her company in New York in the early 1940s. She bought the house on
East 63d Street in Manhattan that was the company's headquarters
for many years and supported the Graham school and its activities.
</P>
<P>
   De Rothschild began her professional life as a research
biologist at a laboratory in Paris. She came to the United States
at the start of World War II, studied chemistry and biology at
Columbia University and worked in an industrial laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   During the war she worked for the Free French movement in New
York and London. She enlisted in the French Army and landed in
Normandy after the Allied invasion. She was a liaison between the
French and U.S. forces in Paris, returning to New York at the end
of the war.
</P>
<P>
   In her quiet way, de Rothschild intrigued the Graham dancers,
who knew her as Bethsabee, the French version of her first name.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all I know, the tour being my first, wardrobe mistresses
are always baronesses,'' Paul Taylor wrote in his autobiography,
``Private Domain.'' ``Bethsabee supervises the laundering and
packing of our costumes with quiet efficiency, almost as if born to
it, and by looking at her own outfits, you can't tell she's an
heiress _ that is, if you don't know that expensive dresses are
sometimes the dumpiest.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides supervising the wardrobe, de Rothschild was involved in
a wide range of company activities, including taking a few dance
classes with Graham and buying the dancers jewelry one Christmas at
a lavish party she gave for the troupe.
</P>
<P>
   De Rothschild founded the Batsheva de Rothschild Foundation for
Arts and Sciences in the early 1950s in New York. The foundation's
first project, in 1953, was to sponsor a two-week festival of
American modern dance on Broadway. In addition to underwriting
Graham tours, the foundation also helped establish the Juilliard
Dance Theater, directed by Doris Humphrey, and sponsored a second
three-week festival of modern dance on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   One of the baroness' greatest contributions to modern dance was
the founding of the Graham-based Batsheva Dance Co. in 1964 in Tel
Aviv. De Rothschild, who had moved to Israel two years earlier,
believed the country needed a professional modern dance company
with full-scale sets and costumes and thorough training. She sent
several dancers to New York to work with Graham, who agreed to be
Batsheva's artistic adviser, and Graham sent dancers to Israel to
work with the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally known choreographers like Jerome Robbins and
Jose Limon went to work with Batsheva, and the troupe toured
extensively in the United States, Europe and Asia. De Rothschild
went on to form a second, more balletically based group, the
Bat-Dor Dance Co., in 1967. She withdrew her support from Batsheva
in 1974 after the company refused to hire as its director Jeannette
Ordman, her protegee and the head of Bat-Dor.
</P>
<P>
   Though she never became an Israeli citizen, she remained
immensely loyal to the nation, working as a driver after her car
was mobilized during the 1973 war. She supported many Israeli
causes through her foundation, giving money to hundreds of emigre
scientists and providing housing for new arrivals and loans to the
poor in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   She supported the establishment of the Center for Dance
Medicine, the Chamber Music Association, the Chamber Ensemble and
the Batsheva Crafts Corp. She also established the Batsheva
Foundation for the Advancement of Science in Israel, an endowed
fund of the Israel Academy for Science and Humanities. She was the
author of a French book on modern dance, ``La Danse Artistique aux
USA.''
</P>
<P>
   De Rothschild is survived by a brother, Guy, of Paris, and a
sister, Jacqueline Piatigorsky of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   She received the Israel Prize in 1989 and was honored in 1997 at
a celebration of the 30th anniversary of the Bat-Dor Dance Co. at
the new Tel Aviv House. Those paying tribute included Roni Milo,
the mayor of Tel Aviv, and choreographers Merce Cunningham and Paul
Taylor.
 &UR;  &LR; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Throughout her life the baroness fascinated people by her
innocent grandeur. Graham long remembered an exchange she had with
the baroness after they visited the august Rothschild Bank in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unlike any bank I had ever seen,'' Graham wrote in her
autobiography ``Blood Memory.'' ``No real tellers, no depositors
that I could see.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Bethsabee, where are the depositors?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Depositors?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Bethsabee had evidently never been asked that question before.
</P>
<P>
   `` `We don't really encourage depositors, but yes, we do have
one now ... the Pope.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
