<SLUG> BC-COPING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDERS IN ARIZONA, COLORADO STIR FEELINGS OF VULNERABILITY
</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of us didn't know the Chandler policeman who was buried
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't know the families of the teenagers murdered at the
Little ton, Colo., high school on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, we find ourselves numbed by the violence, and united in
grief.
</P>
<P>
   A human trait is the ability to empathize with other people's
expe riences, said Dr. James MacKenzie, a psychologist with Good
Samaritan Hospital. More intense events trig ger more intense
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's not close to us, there is a part of us stirred by
it,'' MacKenzie said. ``We think our kids could have been in that
school. If you are an intensely spiritual person, you might stop
and pray.''
</P>
<P>
   People are reminded how vulner able they really are. They want
to do something, he said. They need to understand.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Alan Nelson has been called upon to make sense of the
senseless before. In Oklahoma City at the time of the Federal
Building bombing, he was part of the team that broke the news to
those who had lost family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't pin it on God,'' said Nelson, an author and now
pastor of Scottsdale Family Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as people are alive on Earth because of our nature,
we're always going to have murders, crimes and hatred. It shouldn't
surprise us. God is as much hurt and angered by this as anybody,
probably more than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   God doesn't give neat solutions to tragedy, he said, but God
does offer hope.
</P>
<P>
   He said people react to grief in two ways: ``They will hate God
and they will hate life and they will become angry. There will also
be people who now more than ever will be so in love with their
families and so in tune with God, they will just be better people.
This is the lesson we can all learn, because we all go through
traumas in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Nelson stood with others at Bank One Ballpark
for a moment of silence for the Colorado victims. The Rev. Paul
Eppinger, executive director of the Arizona Ecumenical Council,
called his counterpart in Denver to tell him Arizonans were praying
for his community.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, members of the Valley's religious community
gathered in Phoenix for a prayer service for the high school
victims and their families, hastily called by the Interfaith Action
Coalition of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of things that will help Valley residents
cope with the tragedy and that will help Littleton survive its
grief, said Rabbi David Rebibo, spiritual leader of Beth Joseph
Congregation in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``You help people who have incurred a loss by genuinely sharing
and carrying that burden,'' Rebibo said. ``If somebody is carrying
100 pounds, two people share it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Talmud, Rebibo said, a person who visits
someone who is ill takes away 1/60th of his sickness. The person
feels better just because someone cared enough to come, he said.
Society can do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times people will say `Where is God?' I think God is
present through our presence, when we as friends, relatives and
society identify and share. That's the begin ning of healing,''
Rebibo said.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie, who describes him self as an unconventional Catholic,
calls spirituality an important part of the healing process for
people who are close to or far from tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a world where these things happen,'' he said. ``We
need to be as true to our own beliefs as we can and try to live in
a way in which we are kind, loving and respectful to other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Maher's belief that this life isn't the end comforts her
when the evil in the world seems over whelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly does not quell the trauma or the misery, but I
think it gives you hope for the future,'' said the American convert
to Islam and a Phoenix mother of two. ``Muslims, Christians, Jews,
I think we all share a common belief that God is there and God is
good. We need to try and stay close to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy already has encour aged people to look for solutions
and work together to prevent future tragedies, said the Rev. Dwight
W. Cumbee, pastor of Rio Verde Com munity Church and a pastoral psy
chotherapist at the Center for Pastoral Psychotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   This creates meaning and purpose out of something without
meaning and purpose, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragedy after tragedy after trag edy, it just goes on, whether
it's the Holocaust or Kosovo or a police officer getting killed or
15 children getting killed,'' Cumbee said. ``But we also know that
somehow, even in the darkest of the times, we get through, and we
move on. It takes time and it takes community and it takes the love
of God being acted out in the love of people.'' &QL; 
Kelly Ettenborough can be reached at (602) 444-4877 or at
kelly.ettenborough &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
