<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY CRISIS PUTS SUSPENSION INTO PERSPECTIVE FOR HATCHER
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA AND JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Maybe Derian Hatcher needs his days off _ he has been
through an emotional wringer for the past week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to feeling frustration about the seven-game
suspension he received for breaking Phoenix center Jeremy Roenick's
jaw, Hatcher has had to deal with the fear, relief and finally joy
after the complicated birth of his third child.
</P>
<P>
   Kelton Eric Hatcher was delivered by emergency C-section late
Monday night after his heart rate started dropping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary there for a while, but he's OK now,'' said
Hatcher, who added that the birth put the suspension in
perspective. ``I'll tell you what: I forgot about the playoffs for
a while there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, the Stars' captain, practiced with the team yesterday
morning and said he would be in and around the locker room during
the five playoff games he will miss. CAPTAIN JOE
</P>
<P>
   Center Joe Nieuwendyk will wear the Captain's ``C'' on his
uniform while Hatcher serves his suspension. The selection by coach
Ken Hitchcock was a nice touch because Nieuwendyk missed almost all
of the playoffs last season with an injured knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice honor, but I think we have a lot of leaders on
this team,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I'm just holding it for Derian.''
NEW SEATS
</P>
<P>
   The Stars added 73 seats on a shelf extending over the Zamboni
tunnel to bring the hockey capacity at Reunion Arena to 17,001. The
move made Wednesday night's 38th consecutive sellout a Reunion
Arena-record crowd. INJURY UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were without Pat Verbeek, who has a sprained left
knee. Verbeek is expected to skate this weekend but isn't expected
to play for another 10 to 17 days. Healthy scratches for the Stars
were forwards Brian Skrudland, Tony Hrkac and Brent Severyn and
defenseman Brad Lukowich. FULL OF CONFIDENCE
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Blake Sloan was inserted into the lineup, despite playing
most of the season in the International Hockey League and having
switched from defenseman to forward this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been an NHL player,'' Hitchcock said of the scrappy
forward. ``All I know is just about every time he's on the ice, the
other team is yelling at him about something or another.''
</P>
<P>
   So, did Hitchcock try to ease the pressure on his rookie?
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me I needed to bury my chances,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan started the play that led to Guy Carbonneau's game-winning
goal in the third period. MAYBE, MAYBE NOT
</P>
<P>
   Oilers injured wingers Josef Beranek and Bill Guerin skated
yesterday morning but were scratched from Wednesday night's game.
Both could return as early as Game 2 but might not return at all.
</P>
<P>
   Guerin sprained the medial collateral ligament in his left knee
at the end of the season, and the Oilers are afraid he could do
more damage if he comes back. Beranek underwent surgery on his left
knee. LET'S GET PHYSICAL
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Oilers said they felt they had to hit the
Stars, and hit them hard, to win.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, Edmonton had 21 hits with defenseman Jason
Smith leading the way with four.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, hitting begets hitting, and the Stars answered with
19 of their own. Carbonneau had a team-leading three. BEEN THERE,
DONE THAT
</P>
<P>
   This is the 16th season in which the Oilers have qualified for
the Stanley Cup playoffs. They have a 12-3 record in the previous
15 first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   The three first-round losses came against Philadelphia in 1980
and Los Angeles in 1982 and '85.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one of the Oilers' 12 first-round victories was in
1997 against the second-seeded Stars. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
