<HEADLINE>
SIMPLY MAV-NESS: ROCKETS LATEST TO FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Too bad the Mavericks only have eight games remaining
in the regular season. It appears the fun is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Beaten down and talked about at water coolers nationwide for
their inept performance this decade, the Mavericks are quietly
disrupting the Western Conference playoff race while suddenly
becoming the talk of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Last night before a sellout crowd of 16,285 at the Compaq
Center, the Mavericks whacked another NBA West powerhouse, as they
controlled the Houston Rockets throughout and won going away,
109-95.
</P>
<P>
   The game was so one-sided that Mavericks rookie Bruno Sundov,
who barely knows any of the team's plays, played in the final two
minutes. At 19 years, 2 months, Sundov became the youngest
Mavericks player ever.
</P>
<P>
   Within an eight-day span, the Mavericks have beaten San Antonio,
Minnesota, Phoenix and Houston. That's half of the field that will
likely represent the Western Conference in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Finley, who converted 11 of 20 shots, said it was the
most complete game the Mavericks have played all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played consistent for 48 minutes,'' said Finley, who poured
in 13 of his 27 points in the third quarter. ``Defensively, we were
doing things that we needed to do; offensively, our shots were
falling, and as a result we had fun out there tonight and we had a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks made a season-high 46 field goals, scored a
season-high 61 points in the first half, and shot a season-high
52.9 percent from the field. Had the Mavericks played this
efficient all season, they would be in the thick of the playoff
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just so happened that guys hit their shots early,'' said
Gary Trent, who returned from a one-game absence after a right
hamstring injury to score 24 points and grab 10 rebounds. ``I'm
just hoping we can get the eighth seed so I won't have to watch the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the Mavericks snapped an 11-game road losing
streak, broke an 11-game losing streak to the Rockets, and probably
made Charles Barkley have second thoughts about that nasty comment
he made last year about the Mavericks not being good enough to win
the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Big Three were no match for the Mavericks. Hakeem
Olajwuon (27 points, 11 rebounds), Barkley (16 points, 14 rebounds)
and Scottie Pippen (2-of-8, four points) could not stop the
onslaught from the Mavericks. Dallas built a 107-81 lead and
cruised to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Dirk Nowitzki, playing against Pippen _ his boyhood idol
_ used the basket for target practice. Nowitzki nailed 10 of 13
shots and finished with 22 points, including some incredible
long-range shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Break up the Mavericks,'' said Mavericks coach/general manager
Don Nelson in jest. ``I just think we were deserving of some wins
early that we didn't get, so maybe it's that time of the year now
where we're getting some.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were very hospitable. They played weak on defense
and were completely outhustled by the visitors. The Rockets'
nickname is ``Clutch City,'' but the Mavericks made all of the
clutch plays.
</P>
<P>
   Boos even cascaded from the crowd when John ``Hot Rod'' Williams
snaked behind the Rockets' defense for a stick-back basket and an
88-68 Mavericks lead early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Davis added 14 points and Shawn Bradley contributed six
points, 10 rebounds and four blocks.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second consecutive game the Mavericks shot better
than 50 percent from the field. After beating Phoenix (104-100)
Tuesday night, they seem to be kicking their offense in gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two really have surprised me the way we are
playing,'' Nelson said. ``They were both unexpected. I was hoping
to play well and to be around at the end and maybe win it there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to play with a lead the whole game says that the team is
maturing a little bit and that we're playing with patience. And
that's not easy against a veteran team.'' Nash out Point guard
Steve Nash is out indefinitely with a lower back strain.
</P>
<P>
   Nash got the news after he visited a back specialist yesterday.
Nelson said he wasn't sure when Nash would be able to play again,
but that he definitely wouldn't play tonight against San Antonio or
in Saturday's game in Sacramento. Numbers game
</P>
<P>
   2: First-half points scored by Dirk Nowitzki's childhood idol,
Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   6: Biggest lead by the Rockets in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   10: Points Michael Finley scored in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   12: First-half points scored by Nowitzki.
</P>
<P>
   14: Number of points Gary Trent scored in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   15: Biggest lead by the Mavericks in the first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
