<HEADLINE>
TCU SPRINTER RICARDO WILLIAMS' NICKNAME CAME IN A `FLASH'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ ``Flash,'' TCU coach Monte Stratton says, pausing a
second to smile.
</P>
<P>
   He's obviously tickled by that sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a perfect name for a sprinter or what?'' Stratton
says, finally finishing his thought.
</P>
<P>
   His nickname, like his running, came naturally for Ricardo
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   His running led to his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Williams remembers fragmented details from that day in 1992 when
he became ``Flash.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers being surrounded, his classmates gathering to watch
him race another classmate, Omar Bailey. Bailey had developed a
reputation in Jamaica as being St. Jago High School's fastest
sprinter.
</P>
<P>
   Williams simply had decided to try his luck against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat him in the 100, 200, everything,'' Williams said. ``So
they started calling me `Flash.' I like that. I've been hearing
that so long.''
</P>
<P>
   His running has taken him from schoolyards in Kingston, Jamaica,
six years ago to TCU this season to Philadelphia and the
prestigious Penn Relays this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He has remained ``Flash,'' his times now endorsing his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   He has traveled 100 meters in 10.5 seconds this season, going as
low as 10.21 seconds wind-aided. He has traveled 200 meters in
21.52 seconds, going as low as 21.18 with wind help.
</P>
<P>
   He has been instrumental in turning a Horned Frogs' 4x100 relay
team into a good bet to earn back-to-back national championships.
</P>
<P>
   TCU lost Syan Williams and Percy Spencer from 1998's national
championship-winning relay. Ricardo Williams, along with fellow
newcomer Lindel Frater, has stepped in seamlessly and meshed
perfectly with returnees Bryan Howard and Jarmiene Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Spencer, Syan Williams, Howard and Holloway etched
themselves in collegiate 4x100 relay record books with a time of
38.04. Just a couple of races into this season, Howard, Holloway,
Frater and ``Flash'' have already gone 38.64.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of potential to get better,'' Stratton said,
``and probably Flash most of all. He has had the least preparation
in terms of base and competition over the last two, two and a half
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams transferred from TCU from Southwestern Christian, a
tiny junior college in Terrell where training proved to be a little
less vigorous.
</P>
<P>
   He adapted, though.
</P>
<P>
   His times are dropping week after week after week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, each week I have improved my times,'' Williams
said. ``Coach was surprised that every week I cut down so rapidly.
I'm not real surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   He says this without any hint of ego. If he has any, he has hid
all traces rather well.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy nicknamed ``Flash,'' Williams talks rather slowly,
almost deliberate in manner. His hobbies, books and music, seem
very un-Flash-like.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quiet, very much a gentleman,'' Stratton said. ``And he's
very, very, very talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just keeps getting better with each passing day and with
each degree warmer. He was just ready to really blossom when the
cramp hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been battling hamstring troubles since he cramped
in an event in Tempe, Ariz., two weeks ago. He'll likely run in
Philadelphia, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He has been looking forward to the Penn Relays for too long to
miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ``the'' meet for the Jamaicans,'' Stratton said. ``All of
the Jamaican high school elite are at the Penn Relays running in
the high school division. So these guys were there as high
schoolers, and they want to show the high schoolers coming up
behind them what they've done and where they are and perform well
in front of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams raced at Penn twice while at St. Jago. He has a 4x100
trophy from 1995 and a 4x400 trophy from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a good meet,'' Williams said. ``There are
several high schools there that have kids who were there when I was
a senior.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams isn't sure if there is anyone around from the old days
who would remember the day he became ``Flash.''
</P>
<P>
   You didn't have to be there, though, to understand. The nickname
sticks not because of how he got it but because of how he runs.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the minority are the people who know him by anything
other than `Flash.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who don't know me call me Ricardo. Most people,''
Williams said, pausing, ``call me Flash.''
</P>
<P>
   What a perfect name for a sprinter.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
