<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO SECRET TO FORCE'S `UNFAIR ADVANTAGE'
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From rear spoiler to front air dam to the quarter-panels in
between, NASCAR's ``aerodynamic wars'' have taken on a life of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, teams in the respective Chevrolet, Ford and Pontiac
camps believe that the playing field NASCAR Winston Cup officials
are constantly trying to level is forever tilted in favor of the
other guys.
</P>
<P>
   It's a healthy paranoia, one that has been packing brand-loyal
fans into oval-track grandstands for 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, a nice aero war is simmering in the NHRA's
Funny Car ranks heading into Texas Motorplex this weekend. At the
epicenter of the debate is _ surprise! _ Team Castrol, better known
as reigning Funny Car champion John Force and teammate Tony
Pedregon.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with their $500,000, Roush-built, replica Ford
Mustang-bodied hot rods, ``Brute Force'' and Tony P. have combined
to win all four National Hot Rod Association national events run
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Force, the eight-time champion and current points leader, has
bagged the past three consecutive races. Force not only hammered
the field at the O'Reilly Nationals at Houston Raceway Park on
April 11, he also reset the national elapsed-time record _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   The magic number for Funny Car ET is 4.788 seconds, and
apparently it's falling heading into the third annual Castrol
Nationals in Ennis. Force also has the national Funny Car speed
record at 324.05 mph, set in March at Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the domination exhibited by Force and Pedregon
has begun grating on teams running replica Chevrolet Camaro Z/28
and Pontiac Firebird Funny Cars. The new ``swoopy'' Mustang mold
Force successfully lobbied past NHRA officials and onto the
quarter-mile has forced the GM teams to retool in hopes of catching
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same old stuff,'' Force said after bagging his 73rd career
victory at Baytown. ``Truth is, they're just two real good race
cars and they don't like us. And I'm getting to where I don't care
to argue anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Force speculated that the first 330 mph pass in a
Funny Car could be run down the all-concrete Motorplex at this
meet. If it happens at the right foot of Force and his Castrol GTX
Ford or Pedregon's Syntec Mustang, expect the whining from the pits
to drown out the nitro engines. That's loud.
</P>
<P>
   Should Force be criticized for having the money, manpower and
moxie to design and develop a better race car body, one he said
produces 17 percent more downforce than its predecessor?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all. This is the ``unfair advantage'' every racing team
dreams of squeezing out of the rulebook. Force, in fact, has spoken
openly about the ingredients that have given him the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with crew chiefs Austin Coil and Bernie Fedderly,
Force's arsenal also features oodles of money supplied by Castrol
and associate sponsors; quality time in the wind tunnel as Ford's
sole Funny Car team; and a recently realized 30 to 40 horsepower
wallop supplied by engine guru Alan Johnson's cylinder heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also don't take vacations. That's another thing,'' Force
said. ``I love all my competitors, and they're mad right now, a
number of 'em. It's not that we're smarter; we're focused and we
have the money to back me up. Go get more money. I don't know what
else to tell 'em.''
BOAT SEES RAY REMATCH IN RUN TO GAIN INDY POLE
</P>
<P>
   A hot lap at 227.072 mph during open testing has installed Greg
Ray of Plano as chalk favorite to win the pole position for the
83rd Indianapolis 500 next month.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean, however, that 1998 pole-winner Billy Boat is
conceding a tenth of a second to his rival when qualifying begins
May 22 at the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, two things you've got to remember about open testing,''
said Boat, who drives for four-time Indy 500 champion A.J. Foyt of
Houston. ``Nobody goes through inspection. And when there's
multiple cars on the racetrack, there are times when you can get
behind other cars and get a `tow.' That will give you a mile an
hour, two miles an hour worth of extra speed. So it's hard to say
about that (227) lap.''
</P>
<P>
   We can say that Ray owns the fastest unofficial speed recorded
in a new-formula Pep Boys Indy Racing League car at IMS. The
previous record was 223.797 mph, set by Tony Stewart in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Boat won the pole at Indy last May with a four-lap average of
223.503 mph. Ray, who has replaced Stewart at Team Menard,
qualified No. 2 at IMS at 221.125 mph last year for former team
owner/current team manager Thomas Knapp.
</P>
<P>
   Team Menard has ``shown they can be fast,'' said Boat, who wound
up third on the open test speed chart at 224.456 mph. ``When we go
back there, I think we're going to see a faster pole speed than
last year. I think it's going to take at least a 225 mph average to
win the pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat was among a group testing Goodyear tires at Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth this week.
</P>
<P>
   Boat and Ray are running Dallara chassis powered by Indy
Oldsmobile Aurora V-8s. But there are significant differences in
their programs.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt has Roush Racing assembling the Olds engines used by Boat
and teammate Kenny Brack, the reigning IRL champion. Last year,
when Boat won a series-leading six poles and Brack won three races,
their engines were built by Katech.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's engine program at Menard is in-house, and his team is
committed to Firestone Firehawk tires.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ray carries the traditional multicolored splash of
Glidden/Menards, Boat's formerly green Conseco car is devoid of
major sponsorship markings. Conseco and Harrah's are featured as
associates on Boat's otherwise unadorned chassis, which is painted
a very bright red.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Clydesdale Red, perhaps in anticipation of an impending
major sponsorship announcement?
TMS SALES WERE BRISK
</P>
<P>
   Here's another round of statistical ammunition that Eddie
Gossage, executive vice president and general manager of Texas
Motor Speedway, can trot out in his search for additional NASCAR
race dates in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR fans brought voracious appetites for driver collectibles
to race weekend last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold as much merchandise ($2 million) in four days at Texas
as we did in 11 days at the Daytona 500,'' said Fred Wagenhals,
chairman, president and CEO of Action Performance Companies Inc.
PETTY PANS `WALLBANGERS'
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty did the Hot Wheels Pontiac proud at Martinsville
(Va.) Speedway, where he qualified 10th and finished in the same
position after 500 rowdy, short-track laps.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, who led a lap for the first time since the 1997 season
finale, has three top 10s in eight races. But he has also failed to
qualify for two events.
</P>
<P>
   Along with seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt and three-time
champion Darrell Waltrip, Petty has been lumped into an expanding
group of veteran drivers who struggle to qualify in the top 25,
maybe because they have whacked one concrete wall too many?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's the fact we're shy because we've taken some
hard hits,'' said Petty, anticipating the DieHard 500 at the
Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway on Sunday. ``Our experience on
running fast and how we started to drive was in a different kind of
car with a different kind of tire and different kind of engine and
a different type of horsepower and different type of torque.
</P>
<P>
   ``You went through stages where you were Jack the Bear, where
you could qualify. Then you get to a stage where you're junk again.
I don't think it has anything to do with hitting walls.'' MEET TEAM
FRUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   If you have any of these drivers on your NASCAR Winston Cup
Fantasy League team, you know what it feels like to write the
checks at Sabco Racing. Consider that:
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt has posted one victory in the past 100 races
(1998 Daytona 500), and has not led a lap in 1999. He last led a
race at Rockingham, N.C., in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Craven has posted four DNFs in eight races this season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Benson, Jimmy Spencer and Bill Elliott are without a
top-10 finish this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd is seeking his first top-15 finish of 1999. LAST
WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``A Talladega crash never seems to end.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Andretti, on getting swept up in a restrictor-plate race
wreck at the 2.66-mile Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway nn
</P>
</TEXT>
