<HEADLINE>
LITTLETON COMES TOGETHER IN SORROW 
</HEADLINE>
 SHOOT-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ It remained in the high school parking lot, a
haunting reminder of an evil too enormous to comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Scott's car. Students said she was missing. The mourning
had begun.
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers sat in a prayer circle next to the dented red
Acura. They decorated it with flowers. They waited for their
friend's fate to be confirmed. And they cursed those responsible
for the hell that had visited Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who did this, they're going to get theirs. They're
going to rot in infernal damnation,'' said Antwan Rodriguez, a high
school graduate from Arvada, who brought flowers and a teddy bear
to Columbine to honor the victims of the attack. He said his
emotions ran the gamut _ anger, sympathy, love and hate.
</P>
<P>
   On a grassy hill just north of Columbine, other students and
parents stood and waited. There was nothing else to do. Inside the
school, their friends and teachers could be dead, killed in
Tuesday's murderous rampage of bullets and bombs. They didn't know
for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really don't know where to go or what to do,'' said Donna
Krier, whose daughter survived the rampage. ``They're looking for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some brought flowers to put on makeshift memorials, located
under several small trees in the city park. Others huddled in small
groups, hugging and crying and shooing away television cameramen
who got too close.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in this community seemed to be touched by death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a horrible day, as I watched the fear and terror on
the parents' faces who didn't know where their children were,''
Bill Oudemolen, senior pastor at Foothills Bible Church in
Littleton, told his congregation. ``Sadly I have to inform you that
one of our Foothills families is living with the hellish nightmare
of having a son unaccounted for.''
</P>
<P>
   Though few names had been released by late Wednesday afternoon,
many already knew. They had scoured the hospitals, quizzed their
friends, seen the cars still parked forlornly in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, people were missing. About thirteen of them. Already
confirmed dead were the two gunmen, who committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Kayley Boyle, 16, was convinced that one of her teachers, Dave
Sanders, was among the dead. Boyle lives across the street from
Sanders, and had talked to his wife. He never emerged from the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, authorities confirmed that Sanders, 42, was
among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle said Sanders died a hero, saving students from the gunmen.
Another witness, interviewed by an area TV station, reported that
Sanders had lain wounded for three hours, while students tried to
keep him alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard that he pushed a girl out of the door and got shot
twice in the back,'' said Boyle, choking back tears. ``He was so
nice. He didn't deserve to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders taught business and coached girls basketball. Breanna
Cook, 17, said she was angry with the gunmen, who apparently shot
themselves after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot of anger, a lot of hurt,'' she said.
``I don't think I'll be able to go back to that high school for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The names of several students _ rumored to be among the dead _
floated through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel helpless, that's the thing,'' said Joe Marino, 17. ``My
friends were in there and I couldn't do anything to help them. They
were just at the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino called the gunmen, Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold,
17, ``dorks'' and said they always looked angry.
</P>
<P>
   He said the name ``Trench Coat Mafia'' _ a moniker adopted by
the two teens and others who ran with them _ was originally given
to them by other students, as a way to ridicule them.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed the teens always planned to commit suicide,
as a final satisfaction over their victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just not fair . . . they went out the way they wanted
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Autumn Hettinger, 18, said she saw Harris right before he
entered the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to go to the library, but something told me not
to go in there,'' she said. ``So I went out to my car, and as I was
driving out, I saw Eric. He had on this black trench coat, and had
this huge bulge around his waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood in front of my car and stared at me with this
piercing glare,'' she said. ``I looked at him, like, `Move, Eric,'
and he just walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   Hettinger said Harris and Klebold were good students. She said
she knew Harris, and had even worked on a project for philosophy
class with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him in the hall he would wave at me and I would
wave back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Barnes, 15, could not stop crying as she recounted the
horrific events of the past day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this big bang, like somebody hit a locker,'' she
said. ``The teacher went out to see, and said all she could see was
people running everywhere . . . then someone said, you've got to
get out of here, somebody's got a gun. Then I heard the bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said everyone had to pull together to get through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to cry on me and I'm going to cry on you and
we'll cry together,'' he said. ``It can happen anywhere, and that's
what (Littleton) is _ anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Muller can be reached at (602) 444-8178 or at
bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
