<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWING WORKERS AS INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Perhaps in the past few weeks you've leafed
through one or more corporate annual reports. Perhaps you've run
across the phrase ``our people are our most important asset.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's the cliche of the decade. Some companies actually mean it
and treat their workers that way. Others put it in the annual
report because it's a ``best practices'' thing to say; they really
count their people as expenses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overuse and misuse bequeaths ``our people are our most important
asset'' a place in the social conscience right next to ``I'm from
the government and I'm here to help you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus, I'm grateful to Kevin McCarthy, a business professor at
Baker University in Baldwin City, Kan., who directed me to an essay
by Kevin Wheeler, president of Global Learning Resources and a
corporate education and recruiting consultant. Wheeler says he
winces twice every time he sees ``our people are our most important
asset.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wince the first time because I know that most executives
really believe that labor is a cost, just like steel or
semiconductors, and want to get it as cheaply as they can,''
Wheeler wrote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wince a second time because an asset is by definition a
possession or something we can own and control, and we can do
neither (legally) to people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, if employees aren't assets or expenses, what are they? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler's reasoning: Employees choose to invest their talents,
skills, time and energy _ instead of dollars _ in the organization,
and they expect a return on that investment, just as financial
investors do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the continued tight labor market, qualified workers are in
demand. Those who have the expertise sought by employers can, and
do, change jobs quickly and often if they don't think they're
rewarded for their contributions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investor/workers will pull their investments when they can get
higher returns elsewhere, just as individuals pull their accounts
from one bank and move them to another where the interest rate is
higher or fees are lower. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The notion of employees as investors is in sync with the trend
of performance-based pay, incentives and bonuses. Straight salaries
are long since dead for competitively sought executives; now
they're fading for some of the rank and file, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not that today's workers are coddled babies born in or to
the Me Generation. It's not that they need constant stroking. It's
that they want a fair return on their investment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've seen several employee surveys recently that sound similar
themes: About one-third of all full-time U.S. workers are changing
or seriously considering changing their jobs at any given time.
When they change, they usually jump for more money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pay isn't the only return on worker investment, but it's a huge
indicator of how a company rates employee contributions.
Financially and emotionally, money talks. So do opportunities for
professional development, job security and better benefits such as
health insurance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good places to work provide those. Plus, they care as much about
recruiting and retaining their investor/workers as they do their
financial investors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
