<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SECURITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO SCHOOL'S PAIN PROVIDES POWERFUL REMINDER FOR KANSAS CITY
AREA SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The question for local schools now is, ``Can
what happened in Littleton occur here?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The security chief for what is perhaps the area's most heavily
guarded district posed a concise answer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People have walked into some of the most heavily secured
businesses, like banks, and still do these type of things,'' said
John L. Coleman, director of safety and security for the Kansas
City, Mo., School District. ``I doubt seriously if it could have
been prevented.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say that Kansas City and other area districts
don't use a variety of measures to ensure the safety of students.
Many efforts involve reaching troubled youth before they act out
violently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But several area school officials said that if students are
heavily armed and determined _ as the Colorado shooters were _ even
metal detectors and armed police in schools might not be able to
stop such mass killings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try to achieve a balance between keeping an
atmosphere conducive to teaching and learning but also provide
enough protective measures to ensure the safety of the students and
staff,'' Coleman said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, students at Hickman Mills High School were
checked with hand-held metal detectors as they entered the
building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The detectors are used randomly at the schools and at school
events. But Wednesday's check came partly because of the shootings
in Colorado, said Gary Martasin, director of public relations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to reinforce the message that we are
serious and concerned about school safety,'' Martasin said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The district requires its faculty to wear photo identification
badges. Work crews and other visitors to the schools are also
required to wear badges. Martasin predicted some districts might
eventually require students to wear identification. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Thomas, manager of risk and safety for the Blue Valley
School District in Johnson County, Kan., said the district's most
recent safety measure _ a $66,942 surveillance camera system at
Blue Valley Northwest High School _ wouldn't have prevented a
tragedy like Littleton. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect the cameras would not have fazed them,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uniformed police officers are assigned full time to Shawnee
Mission district high schools in Johnson County, and the district's
campus police provide extra security, said Shelley Bartkoski,
communications director. Students are encouraged to call hot lines
at each school where they can anonymously report problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent David Smith said Excelsior Springs High School in
Excelsior Springs, Mo., will have an intruder-alert rehearsal today
Thursday, as part of its crisis plan. The high school added video
cameras this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Middle School in Libery, Mo., by coincidence, had its
first planned practice lockdown _ in which all school doors are
locked and students aren't allowed to leave _ on Tuesday morning as
part of its crisis plan, said Mary Pat Shelledy, the school's
principal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a crisis drill; they had a crisis,'' Shelledy said of
Columbine High School. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
