A8552 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCE-SOLUTIONS-KA     04-22 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-SOLUTIONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T EXPECT EASY ANSWERS TO VIOLENCE, EXPERTS ADVISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEAN BUCHANAN, OSCAR AVILA AND KATE BEEM  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isolated and resentful of popular classmates, the self-described
outcasts hatched a plot to gun down classmates and teachers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They developed elaborate plans to cut phone lines, lock down the
school and meticulously execute those on a hit list. Authorities
called it a suicide mission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the bloodbath never happened. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Burlington, Wis., learned of the plan days before
it was scheduled to take place last fall, when a student informed
police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After shootings in other states, Burlington officials were part
of a growing move to intervene aggressively to prevent violence.
Tuesday's massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.,
provided a stark reminder of the potential dangers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a situation that could have turned out the same way,''
Superintendent Ron Jandura said Wednesday.`` ... But we were
fortunate that someone was brave enough to step forward, that the
administration took the threat seriously and that police didn't
look the other way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Littleton slayings cannot be attributed to a single
cause, experts in education, sociology and law enforcement say
there is no single method for preventing such carnage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they see a larger societal challenge that must be
addressed with positive influences of parents and peer groups,
intervention with mediation and counseling programs like those used
in the Park Hill School District in Platte County, Mo., and
preparation by school officials and law enforcement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, experts said, students need to help ensure their own safety
by refusing to look the other way when classmates exhibit aberrant
behavior. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is a key, said Joanne McDaniel, research director at the
Center for the Prevention of School Violence in Raleigh, N.C. After
school shootings across the country last year, it became apparent
that students knew a lot more than the adults did about the
destructive behaviors of the shooters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Communities need to cultivate a climate where children's
opinions are valued, she said: ``Then when you do have kids who are
outcasts and potentially destructive, the other kids will let the
adults know about this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Geenens, a child psychiatrist in private practice in
Overland Park, Kan., who is on the staff of the Crittenton Center,
cited the need for society to intervene earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in my practice alone, there are dozens of kids who have
the potential to do something like this,'' Geenens said. ``What
this is for us is a cold slap in the face, because this can happen
here and it probably will ... because we are not giving these kids
what they need.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As children approach adolescence, parents must make sure they
have a positive peer group, whether it centers on athletics, music,
4-H, chess or church, Geenens said. That's because once they reach
adolescence, peer groups, not parents, become primary influences in
a child's life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who aren't accepted in these will find each other,
and bad things can happen,'' Geenens said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Failing in school, making few friends and having little in
common with peers are some of the signs of children at risk,
Geenens said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Society cannot ignore these problems, said Elaine Johannes, a
community mental-health specialist at Kansas State University in
Manhattan, because children have the means to arm themselves. So
adults must be tuned in to what's happening in a child's life, she
said, and the earlier the better. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much easier to work on this when they're 6 than when
they're 16, and they're big, and they have friends, and they don't
communicate the way they used to,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Troubled students get lots of help at Park Hill High School in
Parkville, Mo., said Assistant Principal Janet Nease. Preventive
efforts there are enormously time-consuming, Nease said, but she
believes the investment has paid off by creating an atmosphere
within the 1,500-student school where students feel supported
through their difficulties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Support groups that meet during the school day, for example.
Often, when students who feel isolated join those groups, they
realize they're not alone, Nease said. Since those groups formed,
Nease has noticed a drop in discipline referrals to her office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schools also need a climate of trust so students who notice
changes in their peers or hear rumors of violence will feel
comfortable telling someone about potential danger, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Park Hill uses two student groups to help defuse dangerous
situations. Peer mediators can arbitrate disputes between students,
and a group called ``Natural Helpers'' offers peer counseling for
students who request it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said even elementary-school students must be
encouraged to report talk of violence. Students might be willing if
they viewed it as protecting friends, rather than tattling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials and teachers in the Blue Valley School District in
Johnson County, Kan., are advised to take seriously every threat
students make about harming themselves or others, said Bruce
Passman, executive director for student services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, everyone loses when something like that happens in
one school,'' Passman said. ``It rocks us all. You can only ask,
`Can it happen here?' The answer is, `Yes, it can.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
