r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COPING-VIOLENCE-KAN &LR;      04-22 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPING-VIOLENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS DEAL WITH QUESTIONS ABOUT COLORADO SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Wednesday was a hectic day at Heart of
America Family Services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   School administrators called to see whether the agency's
counselors could talk to students about the massacre at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some callers talked about threats they had heard. Students
called to talk about school safety, and parents shared concerns
about their own children, who they feared might be capable of
violence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when you have a national crisis like this is that
it's not far away anymore,'' said Betsy VanderVelde, president of
the agency. ``It could happen to us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For students in the Hickman Mills High School in Jackson County,
Mo., winter drum line and winter guard, the tragedy hit close to
home. The 40 band members were at Columbine High a month ago for a
band competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hickman Mills band director Michael Wright said some of the
Kansas City, Mo., students made friends at Columbine. They plan to
send cards, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we were there ... it kind of spooked them quite a
bit,'' Wright said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VanderVelde stressed that everyone needs to talk about what
happened in Colorado. Discussion has prevented crises from
happening here, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recently, she said, counselors learned of a 16-student suicide
pact at an area high school. Agency counselors talked to the
students and defused the situation, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students at schools throughout the area devoted a lot of time
Wednesday to talking about the killings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Lindbergh Elementary School in Kansas City, Kan.,
fourth-grader Lenora Hyche critically examined the condolence card
she was making for parents of the students killed in the massacre. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Lenora decorated her card with stickers, green grass and
purple-red flowers, she discussed the tragedy with classmates
hunched over their own cards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty sad about it. Now the parents lost their kids,''
she said. ``For those kids to just burst in there and say, `I'm
going to kill you.' That's terrible.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh teacher Michelle Wilson thought the conversation and
card-making exercise would help her 15 fourth- and fifth-graders
cope with the news _ and possibly prevent similar tragedies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My main goal is to make the kids aware that death is
permanent. It is not something to joke about. It is real,'' Wilson
said. ``I thought by sending the cards to the family, they'd think
about that more. That these are real people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most schools told students that counselors were available to
talk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to comprehend the magnitude of it all, but I'm not
shocked something happened again,'' said Jim Andra, a counselor at
Shawnee Mission Northwest High School in Johnson County, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andra pointed out that school shootings have happened in Pearl,
Miss.; Paducah, Ky.; Jonesboro, Ark.; Edinboro, Pa.; Fayetteville,
Tenn.; and Springfield, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of students out there who are troubled,'' he
said. ``I think it's a reflection of our society. There's a lot of
problems with families these days.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No students came to speak to Andra on Wednesday, but an office
worker said at least 30 parents had called. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shawnee Mission Northwest's unofficial Web site contained
several student responses to the tragedy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching the news about the school shooting in Colorado
and this is the only school shooting that has made me stop and
think if SMNW is a safe place to be,'' one student wrote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Shawnee Mission West in Johnson County, Principal John Laurie
said some students appeared numb and teary-eyed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw kids hugging,'' Laurie said. ``There's a lot to talk
about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Blue Springs High School in Blue Springs, Mo., where teachers
and students have been evacuated five of the past six school days
because of bomb threats, no special arrangements were made to offer
counseling or organized discussions about the shootings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If a student needs us, we are here for them, but we feel like
if you tell students they need counseling, suddenly everyone
does,'' said Yvonne Evans, spokeswoman for Blue Springs schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students at Lee's Summit High School in Lee's Summit, Mo., were
called into a morning assembly where the entire school observed a
moment of silence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Raytown School District in Raytown, Mo., sent out a memo
outlining security measures at the schools and informing the media
and parents about the district's dress code, which prohibits
students from wearing long coats to school. The killers in Colorado
reportedly wore black trench coats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Southwick, superintendent of schools in Belton, Mo., said
the district held a staff meeting Wednesday morning to discuss the
killings as well as the bomb threats at Blue Springs and two arsons
this week at Ruskin High School. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Schempp, vice president of clinical and community services
for Heart of America Family Services, said people need to identify
troubled students so they can be helped right away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very fine line between being homicidal and suicidal
for some individuals,'' Schempp said. ``I sympathize with schools:
They're trying to run an institution of 800 or 900 kids, but find
themselves busy with kids who have problems because parents
sometimes won't deal with these stressed-out kids.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
