<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8554 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAVS-HNS &LR;      04-22 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAVS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Dallas Mavericks _ for whom success is landing a lucky pingpong
ball in the draft lottery _ did not stop with whipping the Rockets
on Wednesday night. They mocked them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They didn't just outwork them, care more, play harder, score
more easily. They didn't just go up by 26 points, inspiring the
fans at Compaq Center to either boo or just get up and leave as if
they had dropped garbage at the side of the curb.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks laughed in the Rockets' faces, knowing on this
night the Rockets had no legitimate retort in a 109-95 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was jaw-jacking them all night,'' Mavericks forward Gary
Trent said before laughing openly. ``I told Scottie Pippen there's
only one No. 33 that was going to show up tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   On defense, Pippen was toasted by 20-year-old German rookie Dirk
Nowitzki, who idolizes him, and Michael Finley. Pippen did less on
the other end, making two of eight shots for four points.
</P>
<P>
   But just about every Rockets player could fall into the no-show
category. Even Charles Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon, though putting
up respectable numbers, never seemed sharp or could jostle their
team from its obvious grogginess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (ticks) me off,'' Rockets center Antoine Carr said. ``We
didn't come out to play. I'll put it on all 12 of us. If we're
going to win a championship, we've got to come and play every
night. Either come to play, or sit your (butt) at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with no emotion, no intensity. Either come to play,
or go home and go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets did not have to get their winks at home.
Instead, they sleepwalked through most of Wednesday's game,
jump-starting Finley, Trent and Nowitzki to a combined 73 points.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second quarter, the Mavericks were pushing 70
percent shooting. Midway through the second half, they were clearly
on their way to their first road win since Feb. 20. And that was
against the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets began the night just a game ahead of the Lakers for
the fourth seed in the Western Conference playoffs. But with LA
losing at Portland, the Rockets couldn't capitalize and boost their
edge for home-court advantage in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't figure that out,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``There's no way, with everything so obvious _ the goals, the
situation we're in _ to get that kind of performance. I'm baffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got their confidence going. They made good shots. They
made easy shots. We never got it going, ever. I'm baffled. I can't
give you an explanation. We just showed up. Our guys have got to
understand it's a big deal (for teams) to play us. We're a
high-profile team. They came to play; we didn't. I can't understand
it with everything at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rockets guard/forward Sam Mack of the damage such losses
can cause: ``We had a talk about that. We can't throw away the
season like this. We came out and plain (stunk).''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley offered an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the Mavericks credit,'' he said again and again. ``They
just played terrific tonight. Give them credit. Give them credit.
Michael Finley was unbelievable. We had no answer for him. Trent
played well. Nowitzki played well.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets gave Finley and Nowitzki unobstructed target
practice outside and Trent a running start into the lane to get his
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the outset, when the Rockets rushed to a 16-8 lead
within five minutes, the teams were flying up and down the court to
easy baskets. And as much as that was a portent of things to come,
it also revisited Monday's second half, when injury-depleted
Seattle rolled to 68 points.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, talent- and injury-depleted Dallas (point guard
Steve Nash was out with back spasms) scored nearly as easily,
rolling up a 61-49 halftime lead, the most prolific first half
against the Rockets this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks answered the Rockets' quick start with a 15-2 run,
completed when Tomjanovich marched onto the court to protest an
illegal defense and drew a technical foul. That run took all of 3{
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Rockets closed within 31-30 early in the second
quarter, they never picked up their defense. This time when the
Mavs put together a 15-2 run, they needed just over two minutes,
pulling ahead 46-32 four minutes into the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the moment the ball was tossed, we never could establish
ourselves,'' Pippen said. ``We were on our heels all night. We
never stopped them. Even when we played well offensively, we didn't
stop them from scoring. It does bother us. No matter what your
offensive game is doing, you have to establish your defense. If
you're not going to play any defense, you're not going to beat
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Down to their last realistic chance of mounting an attack on the
Mavericks' lead _ the sort of comeback that has become routine for
Rockets opponents _ the Rockets began the fourth quarter down 18.
They immediately increased the deficit to 23.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich cleared his bench with 4:31 left, and the Mavericks
slapped around the subs for a few minutes, pushing the margin to 26
before Dallas coach Don Nelson had mercy on a beaten opponent.
</P>
<P>
   But even when the Mavericks stopped pushing them around, the
Rockets beat themselves up nearly as thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no justification for this,'' Olajuwon said. ``You
can't take any team lightly in this league. There is just no
excuse. Every game is just as important as the last. This was a big
setback, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Big enough for even the Mavericks to find it amusing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
