<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-3RDLD     04-22 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS PRESSED TO CONSIDER GROUND TROOPS FOR KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs first four grafs for updating and rewriting)  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON and CRAIG WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ On the eve of the NATO summit meeting in
Washington, Britain and France are pressing the United States to
start thinking seriously about sending ground forces into Kosovo
without a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   With the meeting, commemorating NATO's 50th anniversary, opening
on Friday, there is still no consensus about using a powerful
ground force to drive Serbian troops and paramilitary police units
out of Kosovo. The differences are so pronounced that the issue has
been left off the formal agenda.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Clinton administration has been wary of any
suggestions involving ground troops in a combat role, and American
officials have generally tried to avoid public discussion of the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday night, Washington signaled some flexibility,
agreeing to a broad review of the options that NATO developed last
summer on the use of ground troops in Kosovo. That review will now
proceed, Javier Solana, the NATO Secretary General, said on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes debate broke out into the open this week
in a coordinated series of statements by Britain's prime minister,
defense minister and foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   With four weeks of bombing attacks already behind them, they
argued that weeks, if not months, of sustained bombing might
sufficiently weaken the Serb military so that NATO ground forces
could move into Kosovo and establish order with limited casualties.
The scenario has been discussed so much in the corridors of NATO
headquarters here that it even has a name: ``a semi-permissive
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The British proposal would be a major shift from the NATO's
current plan, which is to send in a peacekeeping force of 28,000
troops, but only if President Slobodan Milosevic withdraws his
forces from Kosovo and accepts a peace settlement that allows the
hundreds of thousands of exiled ethnic Albanians to return to their
shattered homes.
</P>
<P>
   As Robin Cook, Britain's foreign minister put it Tuesday in an
address to Parliament, it is possible to ``conceive of
circumstances in which it may be feasible to commit ground
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The main condition would be the assurance that NATO's force were
not facing ``organized armed resistance.'' As British officials
tell it, Milosevic would not be given a ``veto'' over the
introduction of allied ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The British are not alone in pressing for the possible
introduction of ground forces. President Jacques Chirac of France
said in a televised speech Wednesday night that the alliance should
apply ``additional means'' besides escalating the air war to stop
``massacres, rapes, burned villages, families separated and thrown
onto the roads.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials said Chirac's statement was an allusion to
ground forces, and that France's plan was to seek a U.N. Security
Council resolution mandating such a force, though such a request
would almost certainly face a Russian veto. President Boris Yeltsin
has objected strenuously to any thought of the West sending in
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the entire question of ground forces going into
potential combat in Kosovo has been highly sensitive. American
officials have sought to avoid public discussion of the matter.
Defense Secretary William Cohen suggested on Wednesday that the
matter of ground troops did not need to be decided because Gen.
Wesley K. Clark, the NATO commander, had not officially requested
authority to plan a military operation using combat forces.
</P>
<P>
   Left unstated was the fact that NATO's military commander was
not about to propose a major escalation in the fighting unless the
United States, the leader of the alliance, was behind it and was
ready to use its political influence to build support for a
decision to send in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   But after saying for weeks that no such planning was necessary,
the White House said on Wednesday that it was time to study the
size and composition of the forces that would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. would certainly support as a prudent measure any
updating of the assessments of the use of ground troops in a
permissive and non-permissive environment,'' the White House
official said on Wednesday evening. ``It would be irresponsible for
us not to periodically update our plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies were not the only ones the Clinton administration
appeared to have in mind. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is seeking
the Republican presidential nomination, has lambasted the Clinton
administration for starting an air campaign against Yugoslavia
without a backup plan for combat troops.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, all the allies agree the bombing needs to go on for a
long time. Clark has repeatedly argued that the bombing campaign
has to have time to do its work and that it is too early to say if
it will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the 29th day of bombing, allied planes hit
the headquarters of Milosevic's party in Belgrade, a
glass-and-steel 23-story building that also housed three local
television and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister George Robertson of Britain described the
building as ``one of the nerve centers of the machine which plans
the killing in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Western diplomats say Clark has told allied leaders
that he cannot guarantee that bombing attacks alone will compel
Milosevic to withdraw Serbian troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, NATO nations have yet to ask him to draw up a new
plan to send in combat troops, nor has he asked for the authority
to begin planning.
</P>
<P>
   The review of military options, which the Clinton administration
says it now supports, stops considerably short of that.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there was a plan, lengthy preparations would be needed
to assemble the force. Even then, no ground attack could be carried
out without the approval of the entire 19-member alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of an agreement, diplomats here initially sought
to paper over their differences. But lately, the British have
insisted that ground troops might be needed to bring the war to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Prime Minister Tony Blair met with Clinton in
Washington Wednesday night in an apparent effort to persuade him to
do more to actively prepare in case land forces were needed.
</P>
<P>
   Blair made the case for this after meeting at NATO headquarters
with l Clark on Tuesday. He drew a distinction between sending in
ground troops against tough Serb resistance and sending them in
after punishing NATO bombing had taken the fight out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always made clear the difficulties of putting in
ground forces as a land force invasion against undegraded organized
Serb resistance,'' Blair said. ``We have also equally made it clear
that the international military force is there to allow people to
go back to their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Going in on the ground would mark a huge departure for NATO,
which has been as preoccupied with maintaining public support at
home for the military campaign as in taking the war to Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroder of Germany would probably be in
favor of sending ground troops to Kosovo, but one European official
speculated that Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer's Greens Party
might break apart over the issue, collapsing the government.
</P>
<P>
   Canada would not oppose an alliance consensus, Prime Minister
Jean Chretien said in Montreal on Tuesday. ``If everyone is in
agreement, I will not be the only one disagreeing,'' Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
   The French position is less bold than it seems. French officials
say that France would be prepared to send in troops but only with a
mandate for such a force from the U.N. Security Council, which
would require persuading Russia not to use its veto power there.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a tall order since Moscow is adamantly opposed to
any force that does not have Milosevic's approval.
</P>
<P>
   NATO members will have ample opportunity to debate the issue at
the summit. Their foreign ministers and defense ministers will also
have separate meetings of their own on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of ground troops is not on the agenda in Washington,
but the leaders are certainly going to be talking about it, in
bilateral meetings, over dinner, informally,'' a high European
official of the alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British, the French and the Turks might all be willing to
go in with ground troops,'' he added. ``Others are more reticent.
But what do the Americans want?''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been reluctant to take the lead
in thinking about a land operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an American-led organization,'' the senior European
official said. ``If the Americans said we can't let Milosevic get
away with this, we've got to go in with ground troops, then each
country would have to consider the issue and make a decision. And
we could agree that only the countries that wanted to would
contribute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS     04-22 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS BEAT RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ If he were a pitcher, John Valentin said, he'd take
one look at the Red Sox lineup and decide he wasn't going to let
Nomar Garciaparra beat him, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have other guys beat me than him,'' Valentin said
after the Red Sox lost, 9-2, Wednesday night to the Detroit Tigers.
``That's just the way ballgames are played. It's a chess match.
He's going to have to be more patient to get a good pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Red Sox these days, of course, is not
patience but production. While the Tigers unloaded a four-home run
barrage on Tim Wakefield and Mark Guthrie, with third baseman Dean
Palmer going deep twice and adding a two-run double on a five-RBI
night, the Sox offense remained more rumor than reality Wednesday
night, even as manager Jimy Williams shuffled the names on his
lineup card for the 12th time in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Of their eight hits, only Reggie Jefferson's double went for
extra bases. Both of the Sox' runs were the product of infield
hits, and for the sixth time in their last seven games, they
managed just two runs or fewer. Their record in that stretch, not
surprisingly, is 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   For some Sox players, like Mike Stanley, who is now 0 for his
last 16 _ a hitless funk exceeded only by the 0 for 21 of benched
rookie Trot Nixon _ bats have fallen silent. For Garciaparra, it's
more a matter of his bat being taken out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the five games since the Red Sox shortstop returned to the
lineup after straining his left hamstring, Garciaparra has five
hits, all but one a single. So far this season, he has as many
walks (seven) as he has hits _ remember, this is a guy who last
season walked just 33 times in 645 plate appearances _ and has as
many RBIs (one) as his buddy Lou Merloni.
</P>
<P>
   So while Garciaparra might wish to singlehandedly rejuvenate the
offense, the way his mere presence seemed to ignite the team upon
his return last Saturday at Fenway Park, it's not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm not going to go out there and force things,''
said Garciaparra, who beat out an infield hit in the fourth and
scored the Sox' first run, which came after Palmer already had
cuffed Wakefield for a two-run home run in the second and a
bases-loaded double in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go out there and be forced to swing at
pitches that the pitchers want me to swing at,'' said Garciaparra,
who these days sees a fastball about as often as Dan Duquette hears
a good word on talk radio. ``I have to stay within myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in everybody on my team. I can't change from
game to game. I don't care who's hitting behind me, if I walk, I
have confidence that they'll have the chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Garciaparra's confidence has gone unrewarded, though
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's cleanup hitter, Jefferson, had two hits,
including his two-out double in the eighth. By that time, however,
the Sox were in hopeless mode, as the Tigers scored four times in
the seventh on doubles by Brian Hunter and Bobby Higginson off
newcomer Tim Harikkala and back-to-back home runs by Tony Clark and
Palmer off Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie, who already had arrived at the mound, had to wait out a
13-minute rain delay before throwing a pitch to Clark. Asked if the
delay might have impacted his offerings, Guthrie scoffed. ``Not at
all,'' he said. For emphasis, he described himself with a
hair-curling expression.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, who now hasn't made it out of the fourth inning in
either of his last two starts, was similarly unsparing in assessing
his effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stink, basically,'' said the knuckleballer, whacked for
eight hits, four for extra bases, in just 3 2/3 innings. ``The
ball's not doing what it's supposed to be doing, and they're
hitting (the stuffing) out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield's night might not have turned as sour if Darren Lewis,
playing right field in place of Nixon, had been able to find
Higginson's liner with two on and one out in the third. Lewis lost
the ball in the lights and at the last moment turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights here are big, real big,'' Lewis said. ``The light
poles are real big, with a lot of lights. I lost it just as it got
to me. I was hoping I could catch it without seeing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball fell for a single, loading the bases, and after
Wakefield struck out Clark, Palmer drove a ball off the right-field
wall that just missed being a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Two runs scored, and it would have been three except for a
scorching relay by Garciaparra to catcher Jason Varitek, who
blocked Higginson's advance to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox can't score runs, with or without obstacles at home
plate. Five times Wednesday night, they went down in order against
Tigers starter Brian Moehler and two relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing we can do about it,'' Lewis said, ``but to
keep going out there scrapping, finding some way to get it done.
That's all you can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax, and things will get better. But right now, everybody's
struggling a little bit. Maybe we're not as relaxed as we should
be, which is what happens when things aren't going well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to try and keep a positive frame of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And hope one of these days, someone makes a mistake to Nomar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
