<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8564 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHY-SHOOTING-SPI &LR;      04-22 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHY-SHOOTING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS THEORIZE ABOUT WHAT FUELED KILLERS' ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DEBERA CARLTON HARRELL AND VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Why would two teenage boys plant bombs, open fire on
classmates, kill themselves and time a bomb to explode after they
had died?
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the killers likely were time bombs themselves who
blew after not being heard and who felt alienated from both peers
and their community.
</P>
<P>
   While nobody knows exactly what provoked Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold to carry out an apparently carefully planned massacre of
peers at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., experts say a
sense of alienation and not belonging may have played a major role.
</P>
<P>
   That same alienation also appears to have played a role in
previous school shootings across the nation, according to
Seattle-area psychologists, counselors and family therapists who
deal with angry and violent at-risk kids.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it's unlikely the two Columbine High School youths
liked being outcasts. Some speculate that the massacre might have
been the killers' odious way of communicating their own ``inner
woundedness'' and pain at feeling disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think there is a level of rage among young
people, especially young people who think they are disconnected
from mainstream society and mainstream opportunities,'' said Jim
Theofelis, a mental health therapist who specializes in at-risk
youth and works both in private practice and as a consultant to the
King County Department of Youth Services.
</P>
<P>
   He and others said the shooters in Littleton might have given
the impression they wanted to be different as a defense mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's playground psychology: You reject me, I reject you,''
Theofelis said. ``Making all kids feel included, and getting kids
the emotional support they need instead of leaving them to their
own devices _ where they hook up with other kids who feel
disassociated and support each other in their anger and rage _ is
something we as a society have to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Trupin, professor and vice chairman of the Department of
Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at the University of Washington
in Seattle, said ``alienation, a sense of not belonging, is
absolutely a running theme'' in numerous school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling like an outcast can be a powerful force for violence,
particularly if you're in a situation where you don't have any
reality testing from others who can challenge your viewpoint,''
Trupin said. ``The temperament a lot of these kids appear to have _
the sense of alienation and being on the outside _ is definitely a
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Trupin said kids who see themselves as outsiders often feel
deprived by ``not going out with the prettiest girl, having the
nicest clothes, getting the best grades or making the team.'' And
they often tend to blame others for their deprivation _ perceived
or real _ rather than taking responsibility and trying to improve
themselves, Trupin and others said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to open this up as a dialogue, and try to find more
ways to coach parents, teachers, students, counselors, ministers,
primary care health providers and others about helping kids feel
more included,'' Trupin said.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Williams, a program manager for counseling and
psychological services for Seattle Public Schools, said a core
issue of the Colorado shooting was how isolated the suspects
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``All students go through some of that. What moved these
students over the edge? It's hard to know what additional factors
contributed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Seattle district has many programs in place to
reach out to loner students, including peer counseling, an
elementary social skills program and intervention teams that
identify and help at-risk students.
</P>
<P>
   At Garfield High School in Seattle yesterday, students said the
descriptions of the Colorado suspects sound like loners and
outcasts they know.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got people who are exactly like that. When I heard about
them, I thought, we have a trench coat mafia here,'' said junior
Andrew Spieth, 17. ``But that's just their appearance. I've never
seen them do anything outright mean or cold-hearted.''
</P>
<P>
   Students knew kids who listened to Marilyn Manson and wore black
``Gothic'' clothing, but didn't fear them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think kids who do this stuff don't have any self-esteem.
They don't have anyone to talk to except each other,'' said David
Main, 18.
</P>
<P>
   Students said Garfield has its cliques but is generally an
accepting environment because of its large diversity. Still, they
all knew a few people who were often shunned, and they re-evaluated
their behavior in light of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun legislation only touches the surface. In high school,
there's always the issue of acceptance. I mean, we don't feel
accepted all the time,'' said Melissa Slaker, 17. ``Maybe all it
takes is taking the time to say `Hi' to someone, or smiling at
someone, or saying, `Why don't you have lunch with me?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that Michael Jackson song _ you have to look at the
man in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Willner, an assistant principal at Garfield, said the
``dynamics of kids getting picked on has always been around.... But
if you're dealing with deranged people, it's hard to predict how
they will react.''
</P>
<P>
   What should teachers look for? Signs of depression, aggression,
withdrawal and extreme behavioral changes, according to the Seattle
School District's Williams. She said counselors also try to
understand family dynamics and examine physical and mental health.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to alienation, experts say other factors behind
violence include availability of guns, prevalence of violence in
the media and social tolerance of it.
</P>
<P>
   William Singer, a family counselor in Redmond, Wash., who
specializes in high-risk and difficult kids and families, believes
there are always ``red flags'' signaling impending trouble and that
society needs to learn to recognize this ``early warning system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, kids headed for violence and anger are easy to
spot,'' Singer said. ``There will always be exceptions, but many
times there are flags that either have not been recognized, or
dismissed or ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer and others say those flags can range from argumentative
or defiant behavior early on to lack of empathy for other kids and
animals. Trouble signs include kids who have an obsession with
violent, graphic movies or video games as well as kids who are
angry and bullying, physically violent and who are destructive
toward others or property.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
