<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-SCENE-SFCHRO     04-22 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-SCENE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SHELL-SHOCKED LITTLETON SEARCHES FOR WORDS  &HT;     By C.W. NEVIUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Rachel Scott did not get a great parking
place Tuesday morning. The Columbine high school junior had to pull
her red Legend into a place far in the back of the parking lot,
hundreds of yards from school.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday afternoon, Scott's car still hadn't moved.
There was a schoolbook in the back window and an ``E'' parking
sticker on the window. On the hood, the roof, and in front of the
bumper were sprays of flowers, slips of paper, and candles.
</P>
<P>
   And sitting silently on the grass in front of the car were a
group of Rachel Scott's friends. One of them reached out and
touched the hood with her fingers, then broke into racking sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening?'' she wailed. ``What is going on?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a cruel delay of over 24 hours, but officials were
finally able to confirm for the parents of 12 Columbine High School
students that their children were dead, gunned down by two seniors
with a grudge. One of them was Rachel Scott.
</P>
<P>
   In all, as many as 35 students and faculty members were shot
during an explosive rampage by Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold,
leaving the students of this preppy, upscale school gasping in
disbelief. They wanted to talk about it Wednesday in this Denver
suburb, but no one could quite find the words.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was nothing officially planned, people began to
gather at Clement Park, the sprawling, lush swath of athletic
fields that surrounds Columbine High, and by midafternoon there
were hundreds of students, parents, friends and neighbors, all of
them wearing the same dazed look of hurt and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   They formed random circles for group hugs, they held hands and
prayed, and they created informal memorials, piling flowers under
trees. And eventually almost all of them broke down and wept.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last place in the world this should happen, said
Jarrad Tomicich, a Columbine senior. ``There has never been a drug
problem, never a gang problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the students are clean-cut and MTV-chic, the girls with
straight blond hair and the boys sporting baseball caps with
carefully curled brims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jocks,'' said Tomicich, ``dress with Abercrombie, and the
(in-line) skaters dress with JNCO (clothing).''
</P>
<P>
   And the Trenchcoat Mafia, which Harris and Klebold belonged to,
wore black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down here in the suburbs,'' said Eric Veik, who says he knew
Harris and Klebold well, ``it is a little quieter. There are not
many people who want to stand out. They did. They wanted to be
their own class, and they were continually being made fun of
because of the way they dressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Can that really be the reason for murder? Teasing because they
did not fit into the carefully structured high school culture?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to say, I would say that it is,'' says Ian Nelson, a
senior who played violent video games like ``Duke Nukem'' and
``Doom'' with Harris and Klebold. ``Kids are cruel nowadays. They
would come up and say, `Why do you dress like that, you freak?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he had seen and heard that kind of taunting, but he
could not imagine why the two seniors would snap now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time believing that they dealt with it for four
years,'' Nelson said, ``and they couldn't deal with it for 18 more
days.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the grief was giving over to anger. There was a
report of a sympathy card to ``Eric and Dylan'' in one of the
memorials, and a group of the jocks said one of their friends had
``yanked it out and burned it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know the shooters?'' 15-year-old Jason McLaughlin was
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, ``but I am glad they are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Veik, a slight 16-year-old wearing a T-shirt with a tattooed
alien, said he came to Clement Park because ``I wanted to tell
everybody about Eric and Dylan, and tell the truth about how they
were,'' but he couldn't figure out why this happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would joke about it,'' Veik said. ``They would say it is
time to plan the senior prank for 1999. They would say, Hitler's
birthday is coming up, maybe we should get in one last bang to let
people remember us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Veik says, ``I have no explanation for what they did. I am
shocked. It was not in the normal range for them. All I can think
is that they decided they weren't going to take any more crap. They
were going to give these guys some of their own medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Veik paused, then found himself unable to go on. He stood in a
cluster of reporters, shoulders shaking as he wept. Finally, he
excused himself and rushed away.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps the anger was best shown when 17-year-old Michael
Staver spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all said it,'' Staver said. ``When the Jonesboro (shooting)
happened, we all said, `If something like that happens, it will be
the Trenchcoat Mafia that will do it.' They would come down the
hall, almost marching, with these dark sunglasses on. They'd bump
you, and if you'd turn around they'd try to start something with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like that all day in Littleton. Everyone had an opinion
or an idea. Talk show hosts wanted to require uniforms for all
students, and religious leaders sang hymns and shouted out prayers.
</P>
<P>
   At a service at Christ the Light Church, just up the street from
Columbine High, a student got up to speak. She was running out of
the school Tuesday, she said, when explosions began to go off
behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said to myself, `Don't look back,''' she told nearly
2,000 people, a crowd that included some of the victims' families.
`` `Don't look back and give yourself all those bad memories.' And
that's what I advise all of you to do. Move ahead. Don't look
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a better sentiment came from a preschool class at the
church that made a giant sympathy card. On it, in a child's scrawl
were the words of someone named Grant Ordenheide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want you not to feel bad,'' it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
