<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-SIXERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIXERS BEAT CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't an ache, break, pull, strain, sprain, or spasm that
hurt the Celtics most Wednesday night. You know what really pained
them at the FleetCenter? Two airballs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's not to say the Celtics weren't affected by their
growing number of injured players. A few guys on their bench could
still be coverboys for the New England Journal of Medicine. But not
many of the 18,287 people at the FleetCenter left the building
talking about Antoine Walker's ankle, Ron Mercer's back, or Kenny
Anderson's leg. They were talking about four 3-pointers and two
airballs that were major factors in the 76ers' 80-78 win.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was Allen Iverson's airball with 11 seconds left.
It was the airball that led to the winning basket. That's because
the attempt was about a foot short, and Theo Ratliff just happened
to be alone under the hoop to make sure the shot went the
additional 12 inches. His layup went in with 7.4 seconds left, and
the game was no longer tied at 78.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't mean the Celtics' 26th loss of the season was
solidified. That's because Paul Pierce took many Kansas fans back
to those nights in the Big 12 when he easily flicked in 3-pointers.
Roy Williams, who attended the game, remembers those evenings. The
rest of the NBA is just getting used to them. Pierce made five
shots from Faraway Land Wednesday night, four of them in the game's
last five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling it tonight in the fourth quarter,'' the rookie
said. ``I told Dana (Barros) to kick it out to me whenever he had a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   So with the Sixers ahead by 2 and those 7.4 seconds left, there
was no doubt who was going to get the ball for the final shot.
Everyone knew the ball was going to Pierce. The man who had his
lower back vigorously massaged on the bench was being asked to win
or tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really hurting,'' Celtics coach Rick Pitino said. ``He
couldn't move, so that's the only thing he could do: stick a
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Or attempt a three. He dribbled the ball upcourt and tried to
pull up from the top of the key. It was an airball. Some fans and
players screamed for a foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't fouled,'' said Pierce, who finished with a team-high
20 points. ``I took too many dribbles and waited a second too late.
It's a tough call to make at that point in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one man thought the game still wasn't over. When
Pierce's shot fell short, it went into the hands of guard Damon
Jones. The free agent, angling for another 10-day contract, thought
he had tied the game when he put the miss in the hoop at the
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so loud out there that I didn't hear anything,'' he
said. ``I put my hands up in the air because I thought we were
going to overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   They weren't. The officials waved off the hoop, saying it was
well after the buzzer. Instead of going to overtime, the Celtics
headed to their locker room to talk about another strong effort.
And another loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers were pleased with the win. They are trying to make
the playoffs for the first time since the 1990-91 season. They are
trying to survive despite the major shooting slump of Iverson _ he
was 8 of 28 Wednesday night _ and an injury to starting forward
George Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game we would have lost last year,'' head coach
Larry Brown said of the win. His team trailed, 44-39, at the half
and was locked in a tie (59-all) after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   As Brown talked about last year, Pitino talked about the 1999-00
season. He said if his team plays with as much passion and heart as
it did Wednesday night, the playoffs will be a reality. But now
there are eight games left in a season in which every Celtic near
you is either aching, limping, or rehabbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the fans come out for the remainder of the home
basketball games and applaud this effort,'' Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   They applauded Wednesday night, even if the Celtics didn't make
their first field goal of the final quarter until 6:39 remained.
They applauded the rebounding of Tony Battie (12), the defense of
Iverson (an ugly 25 points), and the 3-point shooting of Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   But as Brown observed, the attention to Iverson may have cost
the Celtics. Ratliff was free because everyone leaned toward the
scorer. There were a few other near-misses and could-haves for the
Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game we could have won,'' Pitino said. Pierce added,
``We were one or two seconds away from winning this one.''
</P>
<P>
   They could have been in overtime if one more second had been
added at the end. Or if one of those airballs had gone a different
way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
