<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICSPIERCE-BOS     04-22 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICSPIERCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE GAVE IT COLLEGE TRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten rows above center court, a man wearing a white turtleneck,
gray sportscoat, and wire-rimmed glasses glanced anxiously from the
parquet floor to the overhead scoreboard and back to the floor. He
held a rolled game program in his hands. Shifting his weight from
right foot to left, he waited for the Celtics' final play.
</P>
<P>
   This is what he and 18,287 fans saw in the final seconds of
Wednesday night's contest between the Celtics and the 76ers:
</P>
<P>
   With the Celtics behind, 80-78, and 7.4 seconds left, Paul
Pierce took the ball downcourt as planned. The rookie with the
aching back pulled up behind the 3-point line. But he recognized
the double team too late. He couldn't kick the ball out to a
teammate on the wing. So Pierce desperately dribbled to his right
and his left, hoping for a semi-decent look at the basket. No luck.
He had no choice but to shoot, letting loose an airball as the
buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The man wearing the white turtleneck, gray sportscoat, and
wire-rimmed glasses did not flinch or grimace or shake his head.
Kansas coach Roy Williams understands the learning process. And
from his vantage point, he saw a terrific performance from a former
student, even if it did not have a storybook ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was sensational,'' said Williams of Pierce, his
protege. ``He made four 3-pointers in a row, but I'm sure he would
have liked to make that last one, too. His back was bothering him
quite a bit, but he's a warrior. He'll try to play when he's hurt.
I just told him I didn't want to look in the paper two days from
now and see `DNP-sore back.' He better be ready to go tomorrow
night, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce injured his back in the second quarter after falling hard
to the floor. The soreness limited his ability to get low on
defense and box out. Players from Philadelphia managed to aggravate
the injury with constant elbows to the forward's lower back. After
gingerly walking around the locker room and struggling to bend
over, Pierce acknowledged that the injury affected his play. He was
clearly hurting during the second and third quarters, managing just
2 points and committing four turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   He more than made amends in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With the game hanging in the balance, Pierce found his range
from behind the 3-point line. He drilled threes on four consecutive
Celtic possessions, keeping the game within reach for the home team
until the final seconds. His fourth 3-pointer brought the crowd to
its feet and the Celtics a brief 2-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling it tonight in the fourth quarter,'' Pierce said.
``I told Dana (Barros) to kick out whenever he had a chance, to me
. . . It always feels good to have the crowd into it. It picks up
everybody's play even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce scored 12 of his team-high 20 points in the fourth
quarter. And the Kansas product's performance in the fourth made it
clear the ball would be in his hands on the final possession. It
didn't end the way Pierce and his cohorts had hoped. But a young
player can always learn a new lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it can help me grow and develop as a player,'' said
Pierce. ``So much is asked of me now. It's time for me to grow up a
lot faster than expected. Coach (Pitino) is expecting a lot and I
feel like I'm ready to step up and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   The mentor couldn't agree more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LA     04-22 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FALL TO BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ For the Los Angeles Lakers, every day brings a
new learning experience, and this week they're back in drama class.
</P>
<P>
   They finally put the blockbuster trades and coaching changes and
other assorted wackiness behind them, but now the Lakers are
improvising their own form of drama _ the fourth-quarter comeback.
</P>
<P>
   It worked Tuesday in Oakland. It failed Wednesday against the
division-leading Portland Trail Blazers, and the Lakers lost their
second game in eight days at the Rose Garden, 88-82.
</P>
<P>
   A night after bouncing back from a 28-point deficit against
Golden State, the Lakers again took a double-digit deficit into the
final quarter of play, but climbed within two points with less than
four minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits crept back in, though, from ill-advised 3-pointers to
poor rebounding, and the Blazers held on for the win.
</P>
<P>
   For the Lakers, playing their third game in three nights, it was
at least an improvement over the 27-point blowout suffered here a
week ago. Small consolation though it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're improving,'' Shaquille O'Neal said after a 25-point,
13-rebound performance. ``We just gotta be smart down the stretch.
You know, a couple of bad shots there at the end. We've gotta work
it, move the ball until we get a good, high-percentage shot. We
can't be shooting with two guys in our face, shooting 3s and all
that stuff. That's what I mean by playing smart.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not much of an assumption to say O'Neal's ire was directed
at Kobe Bryant, who scored 22 points but made some questionable
decisions in the waning moments _ the worst a 27-foot airball when
the Lakers were trailing by four with more than a minute to go.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis also was frustrated by the lack of precision
in the offense down the stretch. In his own defense, Bryant pled
guilty, and said he'll learn from the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just comes with experience,'' he said of taking the
errant 3-point try. ``To tell you the truth, I feel very fortunate,
because I tend to learn in clumps. It's not one game or one thing
that I learn, it tends to come all at once. Just (have to) learn
how to use the clock. I should have gone to the (hoop), drawn a
foul or something like that, but you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing since the opening tip and by 13 early in the fourth,
the Lakers went on a 14-3 run, paced by a pair of 3-pointers from
Derek Fisher and a pair of buckets from Shaquille O'Neal, cutting
the lead to 78-76 with about three minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blazers held off the charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers arrived here late Tuesday night, still buzzing over
their amazing comeback victory over Golden State, and hoping the
emotional lift would provide a confidence boost and some momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of excitement with the guys, especially how we
won,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``It wasn't pretty. A lot of
turnover dug a big hole for us, Shaq going out (ejected), a lot of
guys had to step up and play, guys were tired, you could see they
were tired. Down at the half, down more in the third and an
absolute flukey play gets you back in the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   But the drama of victory masked what was mostly a flawed,
turnover-marred performance, one that saw the Lakers trail by 28
points to a sub-.500 team. Rambis said no one was deluded by the
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody realizes we won that game with our heart and
effort and will. We didn't win it because we performed pretty
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kobe Bryant said, ``it could'' help turn the team around
for the stretch run of the regular season, if not against the
Blazers as the Lakers played their third game in three nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off an emotional win, it's a big challenge for us, let
alone that it's three back to back-to-back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Blazers, turnovers again stunted the Lakers' start,
as they coughed up possession five times in the first quarter to
fall behind by double digits. The Blazers held a one-point lead
before mounting a turnover-assisted 16-2 run, with seven points
from Rasheed Wallace, to make it 27-12 late in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A Robert Horry 3-pointer capped a Laker run that pulled them
within five points midway through the second quarter, but the
Blazers responded immediately with a 9-0 run that made it 46-32
with 3:30 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers defense responded, holding Portland to just a
pair of Wallace free throws the rest of the way as O'Neal and Rice
scored seven straight to cut the deficit to 48-42 before
halftime. &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
