r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-L     04-22 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE ANOTHER ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Mo Vaughn is due back in the Anaheim Angels lineup
today, and if his teammates had any common sense they'd pay for his
limo ride to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   They should offer to polish his shoes, oil his mitt and even
tape his sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Vaughn couldn't afford to pay someone to do those
things himself, it's just that the Angels need Vaughn in the lineup
now more than ever. Especially after they lost their fourth in a
row Wednesday night to the Toronto Blue Jays 3-2 before 23,749 at
SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   For the second game in a row, the Angels had plenty of scoring
opportunities but failed to come up with clutch hits. Wednesday,
they were 0 for 10 with runners in scoring position and stranded 13
baserunners.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson drove in both Angels runs _ with a solo homer in
the fourth inning (No. 2) and a bases-loaded walk in the fifth. But
that was all the offense could muster against Blue Jays starter
Chris Carpenter (2-1) and three relievers. Robert Person pitched
the final 11/3 innings for his second save and the Blue Jays won
their seventh game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like every time we hit the ball hard it was right at
somebody,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``Sometimes
placement is more important than how hard you hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting the job done,'' said Darin Erstad, who went
0 for 3 with two walks, despite hitting the ball hard. ``No matter
how hard you hit the ball or where it goes, we're not getting the
job done. Bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is expected to serve as the designated hitter and bat
third in the lineup tonight. He won't be 100 percent, but a
fraction of Vaughn and his name on the lineup card might be what
the team needs right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't get any worse than it's going right now,'' Erstad
said. ``So I'm sure it's going to be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be a welcomed addition to a struggling offense, but the
Angels won't ask him to be their savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could help, certainly,'' catcher Matt Walbeck said. ``But
we can't expect him to carry the team on his shoulders. He's not
going to be 100 percent but that could motivate guys too, knowing
he's in there not 100 percent grinding it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense, off to such a good start, has come to a sudden halt
scoring just three runs total in the past two games. But if there
were any answers as to why it's happening, the Angels would make
the necessary adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a dull feeling right now,'' Walbeck said.
``Say what you want, but chemistry means a lot in this game.
There's no spark. There's no real explanation for it. I don't know
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure _ it wasn't the pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Omar Olivares (2-1) wasn't bad (six innings,
three runs, eight hits), but wasn't nearly as good as in his first
two starts, when he allowed only one run in 141/3 innings in two
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should win a lot of games when we only give up three
runs,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a respectable night by Olivares, it was a struggle for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have much tonight, he really had nothing,'' Walbeck
said. ``He basically got away with high pitches. To do as well as
he did shows a lot. He kept us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays scored on a fielder's choice in the third inning,
then got what turned out to be the game-winning hit by Willie
Greene in the fourth when Greene hit a two-run homer to right
field.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels, despite having baserunners in every inning and
runners in scoring position in six of the nine innings, couldn't
come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't one moment today when I didn't think we had a
chance to win the game,'' Collins said. ``Even late in the game I
said if we get some guys on we can get a base hit to win the
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
