<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENE FINED, SUSPENDED FOR PART IN BRAWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Todd Greene was suspended three games and fined $500
for charging the mound to fight Mariners pitcher Brett Hinchliffe
last Sunday after Hinchliffe hit him with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Make that $510.
</P>
<P>
   The American League imposed the three-game suspension and $500
fine. The extra $10 goes to Greene's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Little League my dad said if I ever get kicked
out of a game I owe him $10,'' said Greene, who is appealing the
suspension. ``I never had been ejected from a game until Sunday. I
never even argue. I decided years ago if I was ever blatantly hit
on purpose I was going to go. But when it happened I didn't think,
it was just instinct. I just went.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like doing it. I hope I never have to do it again, but
I will if I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels were hit by pitches five times in the
three-game series against the Mariners last weekend. Greene was
victim No.4, and it came one pitch after Troy Glaus homered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt all four guys were hit on purpose,'' Greene said.
``Charlie Hayes (of the Giants) got four days and said he was
trying to hurt the guy (Diamondbacks pitcher Todd Stottlemyre). I
wasn't trying to hurt the guy, I was defending myself. Hinchliffe
even said he'd do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe, a former Lancaster JetHawks pitcher, also received a
three-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking Mo-mentum: Mo Vaughn (sprained left ankle) is expected
to be removed from the disabled list today and serve as the club's
designated hitter, though manager Terry Collins said he'd wait
until game time today to make a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word is this guy can handle discomfort and he does heal
fast,'' Collins said. ``There's no question in my mind he's ready
to get out there if nothing happens today to hinder that. But he's
probably going to play with some pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Vaughn is playing at less than 100 percent, Angels
players are happy to have him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Vaughn's return) had better do something because right now we
(stink),'' said Darin Erstad, who will move back to left field from
first base when Vaughn is ready to play defense. ``We can't play
with any less intensity. Hopefully guys will feed off him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just that he's hurt and he wants to be in the lineup shows you
what kind of character he has,'' catcher Matt Walbeck said. ``And
that stuff rubs off of players.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's buying?: Ex-Angel Dave Hollins, who has a broken bone in
his left hand and is on the disabled list with the Blue Jays, had
dinner with Craig Grebeck (ex-Angel now with the Blue Jays), Gary
DiSarcina and Erstad on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins has no hard feelings for the trade that sent him away
and cleared the way for Glaus to play every day at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tearing it up, I knew he was going to have a good year,''
Hollins said. ``He's a good player, but I didn't know he'd get off
to that great a start. That's why the trade was good. It got me out
of there and you don't have me looking over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss a couple guys I played with over there.
That's the hard part. But it's a much better scenario for me. I got
tired of being 3,000 miles away from my kids (who live about an
hour away in the Buffalo area).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
