<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8603 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-TIMBERWOLV     04-22 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-TIMBERWOLVES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONIC ROMP SOOTHES SOME OF THE STING FROM BAKER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It began as another one of those paltry days.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing the stain of a three-game losing streak, the Sonics
learned of yet another affliction to this season.
</P>
<P>
   However, no one wondered what else could go wrong after the
Sonics throttled the Minnesota Timberwolves 119-105 Wednesday night
at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics could do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   They shook off the news that forward Vin Baker will be lost for
2 to 4 weeks with a deep bone bruise in his right knee. In the
process, the Sonics snapped a two-game losing streak at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory provided much-needed relief for the Sonics as they
remained in the thick of a race for the final Western Conference
playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (20-22) are tied with Sacramento, which beat Golden
State Wednesday, dropping the Warriors two games back from
postseason contention. But the Sonics also are just 1{ games back
from moving into the sixth or seventh seed after Phoenix beat Utah
Wednesday to pull even with Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Confused?
</P>
<P>
   This season has been a series of twists and turns for the
Sonics, who had appeared to reach their lowest point just two days
ago. Monday's loss at Houston dropped the Sonics into the tie with
Sacramento and left them three games under .500 for the first time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   However, if Wednesday night was any indication, the Sonics have
some fire left for the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight games left in the regular season _ four of which
are at KeyArena. The New Jersey Nets blew away the Sonics by 30
points the last time they played at home.
</P>
<P>
   However, Minnesota never threatened to inflict a record
third-straight home defeat on the Sonics since KeyArena opened.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics took a double-digit lead in the first four minutes.
Their biggest lead was 95-67 with 1:09 left to play in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was focused,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said.
``(Minnesota) missed a lot of shots early. But our defense was
good. We made them shoot jumpers instead of layups. Our thing was
to make them shoot over our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton led the rout with 27 points on 9-for-13 shooting. He
also dished out nine assists. The Sonics had four starters score in
double figures, including Hersey Hawkins' 24 points and Don
MacLean's 21.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean played in place of Baker and provided a spark in his
third consecutive start. He had seven points and six rebounds in an
explosive first quarter that ended with Sonics ahead 33-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots will fall,'' MacLean said. ``I've had some big
nights in this league. ... I'm going to come out and play hard and
do some things that the teams needs to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics buried the Timberwolves by playing fast and
aggressively attacking the basket. Their defense wasn't shabby,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota missed 13 of its first 14 shots. Meanwhile, the Sonics
were relentless. They ran up court on every opportunity and scored
mostly in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody seemed to be a step faster,'' Hawkins said. ``We got
to a lot of loose balls. Everything bounced our way. We're going to
miss (Baker) in the low post, but other players understood they
have to step it up and be more aggressive. If we play the way we
did tonight and play hard on every possession, we should be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle racked up 61 points in the first half _ the most allowed
in a half by the Timberwolves this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Vin Baker in the lineup they are much quicker,''
Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. ``They were quicker than us to
the ball. They point-blank had guys that were faster than us.''
</P>
<P>
   A 16-5 run to start the third quarter put the game away.
Payton's three-point play with 7:41 left in the period gave the
Sonics a 77-53 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle led 110-84 with 6:12 left in the fourth, which was
mostly garbage time.
</P>
<P>
   Good news to the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   TIP-INS: Hawkins was recently named the Pacific Division winner
for the 1998-99 NBA Sportsmanship Award. Hawkins is one of four
players in the running for the award, designed to honor a player
who best represents the ideals of sportsmanship on the court. Other
divisional winners were Minnesota's Kevin Garnett (Midwest),
Philadelphia's Eric Snow (Atlantic) and Toronto's Vince Carter
(Central). ... The Sonics announced that first-round single-game
playoff tickets will go on sale Saturday through Ticketmaster. ...
Payton, through the Gary Payton Foundation, recently dedicated a
covered play area to Zion Prep Academy, a private non-profit
Seattle school. The $100,000 project took two years to complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
