u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-22 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW SEED COULD SPROUT IN NBA POSTSEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The appearance of the Minnesota Timberwolves Wednesday
night at KeyArena evoked poignant hoop memories of last spring,
back when the Sonics were full of hope and turned out to be full of
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The young T-Wolves, historically the Sonics' most favored NBA
doormat, nearly destroyed then-coach George Karl in his personal
house of horror _ the first round.
</P>
<P>
   After 61 regular-season wins, the second-seeded Sonics needed
all five games to eke past the seventh-seeded Minnesotans in Lake
Wobegon's first appearance in the NBA postseason festival.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew it at the time, but the event signaled the beginning
of the end for Western civilization _ well, at least Western
Conference civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics in the next series collapsed under the weight of
Shaquille O'Neal's thunder rump, losing to the Lakers 4-1. Then the
NBA went into a self-imposed coma (from which it has yet to
recover), Minnesota elected T-Wolves mascot Jesse Ventura governor
and the world slipped its timing chain.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe it's hard to connect those dots. But having watched
Olden Polynice make 29 percent of his free throws this season, I am
fresh out of logical discourse and rational conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it help that the T-Wolves, who themselves are a fair
mess, took two of three from the Sonics in this infected blister of
a season. The Sonics routed them 119-105 Wednesday, but that
outcome was also absurd since the locals were playing their sixth
game in eight days while many prominent members of the team posed
in street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   No sense is to be made of a season wherein the Sonics can lose
at home by 30 to the New Jersey Nets shortly after beating
Portland, the Lakers and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, while reflecting upon Sonic playoff history,
it occurs that preposterousness has often been a Sonic postseason
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this refreshing history lesson: The last time the
Sonics were this bad, they went to the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Sonics finished with a losing record was
1986-87, a 39-43 mark under then-coach Bernie Bickerstaff.
</P>
<P>
   The finish did bring them a No. 7 seed in the playoffs, but that
drew the Sonics against No. 2 Dallas, which owned 55 wins,
including all five games against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In the series opener in Texas, the Sonics were obliterated
151-129 _ a single-game club playoff record for most points
surrendered. Rarely has a playoff team appeared more helpless
against an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the mystery meteor out of the athletic cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics astonished the Mavericks in Game 2 112-110, then
returned to Hec Ed, of all places (the Coliseum was booked), and
slashed up Dallas twice more, 117-107 and 124-98.
</P>
<P>
   The series remains one of the great upsets in NBA history and
among the first pieces of evidence cited by the gods of all matters
sporting:
</P>
<P>
   Never assume anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goes to show you: Anything can happen when a team comes
together,'' said Dale Ellis, primary architect of the upset. ``That
felt great.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years ago, Ellis was reaching his 26-year-old prime as
one of three bloodless scorers for that Sonic team. Along with Tom
Chambers and Xavier McDaniel, the Sonics had the highest scoring
trio in NBA history _ a nightly average of 71 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also had great role players,'' he said. ``Nate McMillan was
a great passer, Alton Lister was happy rebounding and blocking
shots, and Maurice Lucas would put people on their butts whenever
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   But they could do nothing with the loaded Mavericks, who with
Mark Aguirre, Rolando Blackman, Derek Harper and a couple of
versatile shooters named Sam Perkins and Detlef Schrempf, shredded
the Sonics at every meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first game, Nate couldn't get us into the offense
because Harper was so good at hand-checking in the backcourt, which
was legal back then,'' Ellis said. ``So before the second game in
Dallas, Bernie moved Xavier into the backcourt and sent Lucas to
set a pick on Harper to free up Nate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate made sure to run Harper so that Luke blindsided him. Luke
hit him hard once, and it was all over. The rest of the series,
Harper never came up to Nate without looking over his shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how little things can make for big results in the NBA,
particularly with the five-game format of the first round. All it
takes is for the underdog to win one in the first pair of road
games, and the series is in full chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics know the drill. Last spring against Minnesota, they
blew Game 2 at home, then lost Game 3 on the road when coach Flip
Saunders came out with a tiny lineup that included minutes at
center for 6-4 guard Terry Porter. Karl was completely flummoxed
and the Sonics lost 98-90.
</P>
<P>
   Only through sheer force of will by Gary Payton did the Sonics
pull out the fourth and fifth games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're the favored team and you lose one of those first two
games, it's like you're in a coma for two or three days,'' said
James Worthy, Sonic radio analyst and a member of the Lakers' 1987
team that finally ousted the Sonics in the Western finals and went
on to beat Boston for the NBA title. ``Despite the records in a
five-game series, a lot is expected of the favorite, and if you
overlook any opponent at all, you're very vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Sonics found out in 1994 against Denver, when
they became the first and only No. 1 seed in NBA history to lose to
a No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   In '87, Worthy remembers the Lakers nearly made a similar
mistake against the Sonics. Although L.A. won a four-game sweep,
the first three games were decided by margins of five, eight and
one before a Game 4 blowout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, ``was a very dangerous team.''
</P>
<P>
   So could this year's Sonics be playoff dangerous? Unlikely.
First, they have to make the playoffs, and then they may have to do
it without Vin Baker and Billy Owens, both likely done for the year
with bad knees.
</P>
<P>
   A big difference: The '87 Sonics were coming together after a
full season. The '99 Sonics have spent most of a broken season
trying to keep from falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wednesday night, they engage a Minnesota team that has owned
them, that was 22-20 entering the evening, and ran off a
wire-to-wire blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Remember two things:
</P>
<P>
   This is a senseless season.
</P>
<P>
   This is sports: Never assume anything.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
