<HEADLINE>
GALAXY FIRES ZAMBRANO, HIRES UCLA'S SCHMID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Galaxy will hold a press
conference at noon today at the Rose Bowl to announce it has fired
head coach Octavio Zambrano and replaced him with UCLA head coach
Sigi Schmid, this newspaper has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has struggled this season under Zambrano, posting a
2-3 record, with both wins coming in shootouts. However, the Galaxy
has lost three straight and scored only two goals this year.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, who was in his second full season since taking over
for Lothar Osiander on June 10, 1997, had warned of a slow start
because of the team's youth and inexperience. He had preached
patience, claiming that the team would start to click in a month or
so.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano and team president Tim Leiweke were unavailable for
comment. One Galaxy official who asked not to be identified said
Zambrano received the news with ``shock and disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, reached at his home Wednesday night, confirmed the
coaching change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have new employers so there's not much I can say at this
point,'' he said. ``Coaching in the professional ranks is something
I've always considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, who began coaching at UCLA in 1980, won three NCAA
titles with the Bruins (1985, 1990 and 1997) and his past and
current players have made more than 1,000 appearances for various
U.S. National teams. He said leaving UCLA was a tough decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, very hard,'' Schmid said. ``But beyond that, I
really can't say too much at this point. I will be at the press
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, a 1994 U.S. national-team World Cup assistant and
current coach of the U.S. U-20 national team, will become the
Galaxy's third head coach. Zambrano replaced Osiander in a similar
situation during the 1997 season after the Galaxy started 3-7. A
year earlier, in the team's inaugural season, Osiander led the
Galaxy to the MLS championship game, where it lost to D.C. United
in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, 41, was the winningest active coach in the MLS (39-18)
prior to his firing. Under Zambrano last season, Los Angeles
finished with Major League Soccer's best record (24-8), set an MLS
team scoring record (85 goals) and also finished tied with Chicago
for the least goals allowed (44).
</P>
<P>
   He first learned his job was in jeopardy last October after the
Galaxy was swept by the Chicago Fire in the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy was subsequently sold to Denver-based billionaire
Philip F. Anschutz, who also owns a stake in the Kings and Staples
Center. Anshutz turned over control of the team to Kings and
Staples Center president Leiweke, who advised Zambrano he would
have to re-interview for his job.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano was named the permanent coach a few weeks later,
although Schmid and a few others also interviewed for the position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
