</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX STEAL WIN FROM M'S ON CARUSO'S SCRAPPY PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Mariners couldn't have hoped for better. With one
out, a one-run lead, the bases loaded and a slow runner hitting
Wednesday night, the M's needed a double play ball to escape the
eighth inning. The Chicago White Sox's Frank Thomas obliged.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an infielder in that situation, you're thinking, please get
the double play and get out of the inning,'' said Mariners second
baseman David Bell. ``It was exactly what we were looking for. I
got to the base, and I felt for sure I was going to be able to get
the throw off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Caruso never gave him the chance. Thomas grounded to
shortstop Domingo Cedeno, who was nearly behind the bag when he
fielded the ball and shoveled it to Bell, who turned his back to
the runner and barehanded it for the force out. But Caruso had a
good jump off first and was on Bell instantly, upending the second
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   There was no relay, and the tying run scored. Bell knelt near
second, his hesitation more out of shock than anything, and Ray
Durham crossed the plate to give Chicago a 2-1 win, before 9,405 at
Comiskey Park. The decisive two-run inning came without benefit of
a hit; the bases had been loaded on walks.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches, players and manager Lou Piniella watched the play in
slow-motion afterward, replaying it over and over to see exactly
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hit up the middle, and it wasn't hit very hard,'' said
infield coach Steve Smith. ``If it's hit a little harder, you turn.
It was a clean play. He got there fast; he's a gamer. There's
nothing our guys could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss spoiled a strong outing by Jamie Moyer, who worked into
the eighth inning and was charged with one run. Jose Paniagua
(1-2), who walked two before Thomas' ground ball, was the losing
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said he felt responsible for not getting off the ground
quicker to make a strong throw to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many guys play the game like that,'' he said, referring to
Caruso. ``That was a great play on his part. It was just a
hard-nosed play, and it cost us the game. I was a little surprised,
but that's no excuse. I've got to be aware. I was aware of the
runner, but I've got to bounce right up. It was not a play you see
happen all the time, but you have to be ready for everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part of it that surprised me was how quickly he got there.
Never for a second did I think I would not have a chance to get a
throw off.''
</P>
<P>
   The play epitomized the type of team the White Sox have become
without sluggers Albert Belle and Robin Ventura. They are scrappy
and aggressive and come at you, said Moyer, who added the Sox
should have a ``very interesting year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to slide clean and stay low,'' said Caruso,
a shortstop in his second season. ``I was trying to make sure he
wouldn't be able to turn the double play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners threatened in the ninth when Jay Buhner reached on
a one-out throwing error by Caruso. But closer Bob Howry struck out
the side, getting John Mabry and Russ Davis after starting the
inning by fanning David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was called out by umpire Larry Barnett on a pitch that
looked well inside. It ended a rapidly played game that began after
a 24-minute rain delay and ended in drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 10 feet inside,'' Davis said of the last pitch.
``Brutal. That (guy) wanted to go home. It shows as plain as day on
the replay that that pitch was not even close. And then he has the
nerve to tell me he was calling that pitch all night. I never say
anything to those guys, and then to do me like that _ not even
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm up there busting my (butt) and they just do that (stuff).
Bear down a little bit. I'm up there doing my best, and he needs to
do his job. And he didn't right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis led off the eighth inning with a double, but was stranded
at third. The Mariners again missed several offensive
opportunities, going hitless in seven at-bats with runners in
scoring position. They went 1-for-7 in that category in Tuesday's
loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' lone run came in the second, when Mabry sacrificed
home Edgar Martinez, who had singled and reached third on a double
by Segui. Segui was tagged out at home by catcher Brook Fordyce,
who gloved a quibber by Davis. Tom Lampkin popped out to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer's night ended when he walked Jeff Abbott, who was batting
.069, to lead off the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running out of gas,'' Moyer said. ``Why, I don't know.
It was the kind of pace of a game that I like to pitch. ...
Ideally, if I could pitch every game like that _ put it on a cookie
sheet and let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, likewise, would take his chances with a ground ball like
Thomas'. But this was not a night that turned out the way the
Mariners hoped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 0256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
