 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2536 - April 22, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2536 -- April 22, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. A PLEA : LISTEN TO THE LESSONS OF VIETNAM Robert S. McNamara,
U.S. secretary of defence in the Kennedy and Johnson
administrations, compares the Kosovo and Vietnam tragedies and
expresses the hope that lessons learned in Vietnam about wasted
chances for peace will not be repeated in the Balkans. By Robert S.
McNamara. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words. 2. THE CONSEQUENCES OF
NATO'S AIR STRIKES : A NEW
</P>
<P>
   WORLD DISORDER, A NEW ARMS RACE Mikhail Gorbachev writes that
the Kosovo conflict has turned into a catastrophe. ``It could have
untold consequences for Yugoslavia and for all of Europe, unless
urgent steps are taken to stop this madness.'' 1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
PARADISE AND OIL In New Guinea's rain forest, environmentalists and
business executives are learning that what's good for this pristine
world is also good for the bottom line. Jared Diamond, a professor
of physiology and an avid bird-watcher, made his 17th visit to New
Guinea and discovered an elusive bird - a cassowary - living near
the oil fields. What makes it possible for this big, shy,
ostrich-like, flightless bird (rarely found anywhere near the
disturbances people create) to survive alongside the country's
largest operating oil and natural gas field? By Jared Diamond. From
Discover magazine. 1,000 words + 200-word sidebar + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
WHAT'S DOING IN HONG KONG It has been nearly two years since the
former British colony reverted to Chinese rule. But some residents
are still startled when they see the words ``Hong Kong, China'' on
a television report or travel brochure. Old habits die hard and
Hong Kong is still in the midst of an awkward transition from
colonial outpost to Chinese metropolis. Here are ideas on events,
sightseeing, where to stay and eat in Hong Kong from Mark Landler,
chief of the Hong Kong bureau of The New York Times. Way To Go!
1,500 words + photos + map.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
SCHIZOPHRENIA - AN UPDATE Just under one per cent of the global
population will develop schizophrenia (a severe mental disorder,)
at some point in their lives, posing enormous burdens on
health-care resources. By S. Hargreaves. Lancet News Service. 1,000
words. 6. From MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   A. BOTOX AIDS CHILDREN WITH CEREBRAL PALSY A deadly poison
turned medication may help children with cerebral palsy to walk,
report Czech researchers. 500 words. B. HYPERACTIVE CHILDREN MAY BE
MISSING BRAIN CELLS Hyperactive children may suffer from a small
deficit of crucial brain tissue, according to a new study. 500
words. C. TIPS FOR SELECTING 'SUNPROOF' SUNGLASSES Good sunglasses
protect the eyes from damage and also shield the surrounding skin.
400 words. D. GUM DISEASE LINKED TO STROKE RISK A new report links
gum disease to strokes. 500 words. E. MULTIVITAMIN WITH 'E ' FOUND
TO REDUCE STROKE RISK Vitamin E pills may reduce the stroke risk in
men. 500 words. F. DIFFERENT WIRING IN MALE AND FEMALE BRAINS
Different brain structure may explain behaviour differences between
men and women. 500 words. 7. WHY CHILDREN TELL TALES Founded on a
grain of truth, a child's tall tales take shape when reality and
make-believe collide. Through these artful stories, children
explore issues that range from fear to hope, from failure to
success. By Julia A. Savacool. From Child Magazine. 1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
DEPRESSED DOGS AND COMPULSIVE CATS A pharmaceutical company in the
U.S. has gained attention with a new tablet called Clomicalm,
intended to treat ``separation anxiety,'' a behaviour disorder in
dogs. Jokes soon spread about ``Puppy Prozac,'' but when pets'
misbehaviour can't be controlled, their owners often abandon them.
By Ben Steelman. NYT Regional Newspapers. 1,500 words + photo .
