<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN25-COX     04-22 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Information campaign should have preceded air
campaign
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The smartest idea so far in all the back-and-forth and busy
second-guessing over NATO's war against Serbia comes from former
U.S. Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not surprising. Even a couple of years distant from
office, the longtime Democratic chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee is still crackling smart about military policy
and the tricky places where that blends with foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn is making the point in interviews that in dicey situations
like the one in the Balkans, where civil war and ethnic hatred mix,
U.S. military and civilian planners first need to unleash, not
their bombs and missiles, but an aggressive information campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Our failure to make it clear to Serbian civilians just what
horrors Slobodan Milosevic was committing in their name in Kosovo
and the reasonable compromises NATO was pressing for has made the
NATO attack seem arbitrary and merely abusive to most Serbians. The
effect has been clear in interviews as even longtime anti-Milosevic
Serbs angrily take up with the man they were working just weeks ago
to be rid of.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's efforts to catch up now, with the bombs dropping, have
obvious credibility problems. The field has been ceded to the
manipulative, hyper-nationalist government-controlled media of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The democracies, Nunn says, need what he calls ``a new set of
tools'' _ in effect, information warfare _ as a potential first
resort.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea is hardly new. Allied planes dropped propaganda
leaflets in World War I. Something far more sophisticated is called
for now.
</P>
<P>
   Voice of America and other established means for getting the
word out should be targeted to specific policy purposes, Nunn says.
Even if that failed to deter an authoritarian regime like
Milosevic's, the civilian readiness to see a nasty conflict through
would be softened.
</P>
<P>
   The military, too, needs an upfront ability to press an
information campaign itself _ much of its current limited capacity
is in the reserves _ and, if hostilities start, should take out
opposition media, Nunn says. The nation's information war
``capacities are not well inserted into doctrine.'' The need is
``to get them into the minds of policy makers'' as part of any war
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn sees NATO's failure first to make its case compellingly as
having a potentially disastrous side effect in U.S.-Russian
relations. Russian anti-American sentiment is running stronger now,
he says, than during the Cold War. Then, the Soviet government was
pushing the people to be anti-American; now the Russian people are
pushing their government to be anti-American.
</P>
<P>
   Unless that can be fixed _ perhaps by involving Russia in a
solution, though Nunn says that could be a ``migraine headache'' _
populist anti-Americanism could bring Communists and nationalists
to power in Russia's December elections.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the United States, Nunn says, have ``good motives, the
instincts are humanitarian.'' Those instincts and motives will have
a harder time prevailing when they are lost on the very people for
whom they are intended.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
