<TEXT>
<P>
   What are the most important ideas, inventions, creations and
happenings of the last thousand years?
</P>
<P>
   Find out in the following articles from ``The Best of the
Millennium,'' the first of six special issues, to be published by
The New York Times Magazine. Available from The New York Times
Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   These articles, which are for release April 18 or thereafter,
will move on the wire starting Tues., April 20. Many feature LOCAL
ANGLE boxes. For rates on one-shots, ``partnerships'' and packages
of three or six articles per issue, please contact your New York
Times Syndicate sales representative, listed at the end of this
advisory.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   THE FOLLOWING SPECIAL PACKAGE of three articles will move on
April 16 FREE to Centerpiece clients. To become a subscriber,
please contact your sales-rep for details.
</P>
<P>
   ---
 &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-IDEA &LR;  -- It is romantic love, which in the
ancient world was virtually unknown. ``Eros'' referred to chaos,
even disaster. But to the modern sensibility, love is the very
engine of life. 1,100 words. By the prolific American author Joyce
Carol Oates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-INVENTION &LR;  -- No doubt, the printing press is
one of the greatest inventions in history, but Gutenberg does not
deserve sole credit for inventing it. 1,500 words. By Jared
Diamond, Pulitzer Prize-winning author and physicist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SERMON &LR;  -- The concept, the `Shining City on a
Hill,' came to life in the 1630 sermon by the Massachusetts Bay
Colony's Gov. Robert Winthrop. His plea for civic virtue inspired
JFK and Reagan and perhaps even Martin Luther's King Jr.'s ``I Have
a Dream'' speech. 1,200 words. By Peter J. Gomes, minister of The
Memorial Church at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE 3 FEATURES ABOVE, in addition to the following piece of
ARTWORK and 3 ARTICLES BELOW may be published by special Millennium
Series package clients. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----
 &UR; MAPPING the MILLENNIUM: ``The Best View of the World'' &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; ''The Agnese Map'' -- Created by Battista Agnese, a Venetian
cartographer, in Venice, in the mid-16th century &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; CREDIT: Courtesy of the John Carter Brown Library at Brown
University &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Artwork availability: 35mm color slides or electronic transmission
(via E-MAIL, NEWSCOM or WIECK photo database) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This flat map of the world traced the route of Magellan's
voyages and the Spanish silver fleet. Decorated with cherubs' faces
in a cosmos of billowing clouds and turquoise skies, it is a high
mark of the Renaissance fascination with science and humanism.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-DEMOCRACY -- Every dictator's nightmare is the
idea that humans have rights. The universal principle of the
fundamental rights of man is any tyrant's ``province of terror.''
1,900 words. By Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright and Nigerian
pro-democracy leader Wole Soyinka.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-TIME &LR;  -- In this panel discussion moderated by
veteran New York Times columnist Russell Baker, the talk is of the
best time to be alive. The Ming dynasty? Puritan New England?
Yale's Jonathan Spence, Harvard's Orlando Patterson and others tell
where they'd have lived, given the choice. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-PRODUCT &LR;  -- Forget electricity, the microchip
and the car. Without beans we wouldn't have made it out of the Dark
Ages. If human beings are still here, descendants of the Pilgrim
Fathers or the Spanish conquistadores, it is thanks to beans. 2,400
words. By Umberto Eco, the author of ``The Name of the Rose'' and
``Foucault's Pendulum.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The following articles are available for purchase as ONE-SHOT
features. They are FREE to subscribers to the Millennium Plus
partnership package. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---
 &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-BATTLE &LR;  -- The millennium would see other great
battles, like Gettysburg and D-Day, but for 1,000 years, only the
defeat of the Turks by Jan Sobieski near Vienna in 1683 has rivaled
the Battle of Saratoga. 1,200 words. R.J. Apple Jr., chief
correspondent for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-UTOPIA &LR;  -- As utopians go, the Shakers were a
kindly, harmless bunch. They never took up with Big Brother; they
were pacifists; they didn't kill anyone; they didn't try to impose
their ideas by force. Plus they made a lasting contribution to
furniture design and music. 700 words. By Margaret Atwood, author
of ``A Handmaid's Tail'' and ``Alias Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-GAME &LR;  -- Soccer is a perfect substitute for war,
by assuaging national rivalries. Case in point: Last summer more
than 1 million people gathered on the Champs-Elysees to celebrate
France's victory in the World Cup. Just a sports coup? 800 words.
By Paul Auster, the author, most recently, of ``Timbuktu.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-INSTRUMENT &LR;  -- The human voice is a blessed
gift, whether alone, as part of a chorus, chanting in prayer or in
wild outbursts of percussive sound. 300 words. By Leon Botstein,
music director of the American Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-REVOLUTION &LR;  -- Thanks to Gandhi, the peacemaker,
India won its freedom without firing a shot. ``Of the many
revolutions ... the human-rights revolution seems to be the most
morally appealing to the world of our time.'' 700 words. By Alan
Brinkley, a Columbia history professor and author of ``Liberalism
and Its Discontents.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-STORY &LR;  -- ``Scheherazade'' has everything a tale
should have: sex, death, treachery, vengeance, magic, humor, wit,
surprise, a gorgeous heroine and a happy ending. 2,000 words. By
the noted storyteller A.S. Byatt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-DEAL &LR;  -- The purchase of the Suez Canal Co. gave
bankers more power than they had yet known or would ever know
again. 600 words. By Ron Chernow, the author of ``Titan,'' a
biography of John D. Rockefeller Sr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-LEADER &LR;  -- ``Just look how well she governs,''
the once-reluctant subjects of Elizabeth I, the Virgin Queen, later
would remark. For the ravishing ruler exceeded all expectations,
and by now she is namesake to an era. 500 words. By New York Times
editorial board member Gail Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-FIRST &LR;  -- Among first millennium notables, the
Chinese dared to dream _ and outlasted the Romans, Persians, Maya
and Ethiopians. 1,500 words. By Felipe Fernandez-Armesto, author of
``Millennium,'' being made into a TV series for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-NUISANCE &LR;  -- Octavia Hill, queen of open spaces,
loved the English countryside, its green fields and fresh air. And
the tiny, stout, badly dressed Hill was obstinate, a downright
bully, about preserving the land she loved. 350 words. By Penelope
Fitzgerald, author of ``The Blue Flower.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-ESCAPE &LR;  -- Just as the lords of evil were about
to make the world part slave colony and part death camp ... the
democracies seized their chance, and mankind made its narrow escape
from global darkness. In short, the Axis self-destructed. 400
words. By David Fromkin, author of ``The Way of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-MEDICINE &LR;  -- In 1796 Edward Jenner tried the
first smallpox vaccine. Its success signaled the first step in
medicine's control over the microbial world _ one that led to the
discovery of safe, inexpensive and effective vaccines. 400 words.
By Harvard medical school physician and professor Jerome Groopman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SCANDAL &LR;  -- When it comes to failed romance,
nothing beats the British royals. Case in point: Henry VIII and
Anne Boleyn. 450 words. By Josephine Hart, author of ``Damage,''
``Sin'' and ``Oblivion.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-ART &LR;  -- Florentine architect Brunelleschi's
invention of perspective, a system for representing three
dimensions in two, made it so that, in a painting or drawing, a
beautiful lady's string of pearls would look closer than the map on
the wall. 500 words. By New York Times chief art critic Michael
Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-BREED &LR;  -- Keep your AKC pedigree and ``give me a
genetic hodgepodge.'' With a mix, one gets the best of everything
developed in dogs for the past 1,000 years. 500 words. By Caroline
Knapp, author of ``Drinking, A Love Story'' and ``The Intricate
Bond Between People and Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-COMEDY &LR;  -- There was Shakespeare, there was
Moliere _ and then there was Oscar Wilde, most notably, his `The
Importance of Being Ernest.' 500 words. By David Lodge, author of
``Therapy: A Novel'' and ``The Practice of Writing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-FASHION &LR;  -- The zipper is probably the only
clothes fastener to have been the star of a Broadway song. And yes,
there's nothing sexier than a zipper, a ``perfect set of teeth.''
500 words. By Alison Lurie, author (appropriately), of ``The
Language of Clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-PUNCTUATION &LR;  -- Natch, it's the period.
``Diminutive as a mote of dust, a mere peck of the pen, a crumb on
the keyboard, the full stop _ the period _ is the unsung legislator
of our writing systems ... the irreplaceable ``dot that death
devours.'' 500 words. A gem by Alberto Manguel, author of ``A
History of Reading.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SHOT &LR;  -- A nameless bowman in the forests of
Normandy took a random shot and from 100 yards pierced the right
eye of King Harold of England. It was an arrow in the eye that
changed the English language. 500 words. By New York Times Book
Review editor Charles McGrath.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-LOVESONG &LR;  -- Not ``You're a Hard Dog to Keep
Under the Porch.'' Not even Dolly Parton's sublime ``I Will Always
Love You.'' The prize for finest love song goes to Richard Strauss,
who knew that love triangles make the best music, and proved it in
the ravishing final trio of ``Die Rosenkavalier.'' 600 words. By
Lorrie Moore, author of ``Birds of America.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-PORT &LR;  -- ``Talk has been of Venice sinking below
the flood. But it has not been so. So rich is the port, so
incomparably hemmed around by beauty, that it will remain a prodigy
among the havens, a true bride of the sea, a port of a thousand
years.'' 750 poetic words. By Jan Morris, author of ``The World of
Venice.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-BUILDING &LR;  -- The Seagram Building, a 38-story
Manhattan office tower designed in 1958 by Mies van der Rohe, is
not only supremely elegant; it also welds the classical and the
Gothic. 500 words. By New York Times chief architecture critic
Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-DECEPTION &LR;  -- In the entire history of
Christendom, the darkest chapter is that of the Crusades, the
journey of wayward Christian soldiers. 600 words. By Lord John
Julius Norwich, the author, most recently, of a three-volume
history of the Byzantine Empire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-VICTORY &LR;  -- It was a come-from-behind triumph:
Oct 2, 1978, the Red Sox were ahead 2-0, with the tying runs on
base, and harmless Yankees shortstop Bucky Dent stepped up to the
bat and miraculously sent a homer into the netting over the
left-field fence. 300 words. By Keith Olbermann, senior
correspondent and anchor for Fox Sports News.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-QUESTION &LR;  -- ``What interests me,'' Albert
Einstein once remarked, ``is whether God had any choice in the
creation of the world.'' That is, might the universe be any other
way than it appears to be _ and if not, how much room remains for
chance and miracles? 1,000 words. By Dennis Overbye, the author of
``Einstein in Love'' and ``Lonely Hearts of the Cosmos.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-CONCEPT &LR;  -- Abu Ali al-Hasan Ibn al-Haytham,
born c. 965 in Basra, which is now Iraq, resolved a scientific
dispute that had been deadlocked more than 800 years: the mystery
of vision. 2,000 words. By Richard Powers, the author of ``Gain''
and eight other novels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-MEAL &LR;  -- What was consumed at the first meal
eaten by Columbus after he set foot on this continent?
Unfortunately, nobody's sure. 500 words. By Ruth Reichl, the former
chief restaurant critic for The New York Times, who is now the
editor of Gourmet magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-WHY &LR;  -- We live in a time when we know so much
about the universe that our major millennial anxiety is the
desperate wish to sort it out. So we hunger to rank almost
everything as The Best. 1,500 words. By op-ed columnist and senior
writer for The New York Times Magazine, Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-PIANO &LR;  -- The keyboard music of Johann Sebastian
Bach cannot be called piano music, but there is one magnificent
exception: the six-voice ``ricercare'' from ``The Musical
Offering.'' 400 words. By Charles Rosen, concert pianist and author
of ``The Classical Style.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-TOOL &LR;  -- ``It is not an exaggeration to say that
accurately threaded screws changed the world.'' Without screws,
entire fields of science would have languished, and there'd be no
Industrial Revolution. 650 words. By Witold Rybczynski, the author
of ``A Clearing in the Distance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SPEECH &LR;  -- Forget ``Give me liberty or give me
death!'' Or ``Four score and seven years ago ...'' Who needs ``Let
no man write my epitaph!'' A tip of the hat to a Missouri
congressman's tear-jerking tribute to Fido. 800 words. By New York
Times columnist William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SQUARE &LR;  -- The Piazza del Campidoglio in Rome,
laid out by Michelangelo on the height of Rome's Capitoline Hill,
tells us about a great human achievement, the shaping of the city
over the past 1,000 years. 700 words. By Vincent Scully, the
distinguished Yale art and architecture historian.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-LAWYER &LR;  -- Born in Prague in 1881, Hans Kelsen,
who drafted Austria's 1920 Constitution and designed its
constitutional court, was a great lawyer because he delved into the
very nature of law. 400 words. By Bernhard Schlink, a law professor
and author of ``The Reader,'' a novel about post-war Germany.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-MAGIC &LR;  -- A tale of witchcraft as statecraft or,
a trick and entreaty. 400 words. By Teller, the smaller, quieter
half of Penn &AMP; Teller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-TRIAL &LR;  -- The jurors in this notorious trial of
William Penn in 1670 were starved, jailed _ and victorious. 500
words. By Scott Turow, the author of ``Presumed Innocent and
``Personal Injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-POEM &LR;  -- In ``Hamlet,'' a work as lyric as it is
dramatic, death became the fated prince; Hamlet's preoccupation
with mortality is the philosophical turning point of the century.
700 words. By Helen Vendler, professor of English at Harvard and
author, most recently, of ``Seamus Heaney.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-FABLE &LR;  -- The spirit of Virgil saved Europe,
time and again. Virgil could penetrate the mysteries of the
afterlife and emerge unscathed. 550 words. By Marina Warner, the
author, most recently, of ``We Go the Bogeyman.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-CLOWN &LR;  -- Whether stuffing factory-line candy in
her cheeks or stomping grapes in a wooden vat, Lucy Ricardo (aka
Lucille Ball) was lovable _ but not darling and sweet. 500 words.
By playwright Wendy Wasserstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-POPE &LR;  -- Celestine, the only pope in history to
have resigned, is the millennium's best pontiff. 500 words. By A.N.
Wilson, author of ``Jesus: A Life'' and the forthcoming ``God's
Funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SPECIES &LR;  -- Face it: We're no match for E. coli.
Humans may be the most intelligent species, but ants, along with
termites and honeybees, are the ultimate social animals. 700 words.
By Edward O. Wilson, a Harvard biology professor and author of
``Consilience.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-TREATY &LR;  -- The Treaty of Westphalia, which
brought an end to the bloody Thirty Years War meant, in effect,
that ``the empire strikes out.'' 700 words. By Fareed Zakaria, the
Newsweek commentator and managing editor of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ......................................................
</P>
