<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-PROFILING-BLAC     04-22 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-PROFILING-BLACKS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK MOTORISTS SAY PREJUDICE RULES THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On highways and in neighborhood streets, many
minority citizens say they are stopped for no apparent reason by
law enforcement officials, a practice they find humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned by what some lawmakers describe as racial profiling,
some House members and senators are pressing the Justice Department
to begin collecting police and highway data to determine whether
there is any disparity among the races and ethnic groups when it
comes to traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman conceded Tuesday that some New
Jersey state troopers singled out black and Hispanic drivers on the
highway. On Monday, New Jersey officials had announced the
indictment of two state troopers on charges of trying to hide the
fact that they were pulling over black motorists. Those two
troopers were already suspended from the force and are under
investigation in a racially charged shooting on the New Jersey
Turnpike last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All citizens regardless of their race should be free to travel
America's highways without undue harassment,'' said Rep. John
Conyers, D-Mich., who introduced a bill calling for a study of
traffic stops. A similar bill passed the House last year, but
stalled in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno endorsed the idea of collecting
data, saying there is at least a problem in how minorities feel
they are treated by law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have only anecdotes and allegations,'' Reno said
Thursday in a speech before the National Press Club. ``We need
more.''
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, Reno talked at length about tensions between
minority communities and law enforcement agencies, an issue that
seems to be gathering some steam among Democrats on Capitol Hill,
fueled in part by a high-profile police shooting of an unarmed
immigrant in New York and the collective frustration of many
African-American lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Justice Department has no statistics on traffic
stops and race, although some independent studies have pointed to a
disproportionate number of black motorists being stopped.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 1996 court-ordered study found that black
motorists accounted for 71 percent of stops and searches on
Interstate 95 in Maryland by state troopers who were part of a
drug-interdiction team. African Americans, meanwhile, made up just
10 percent of the driving population in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said that if no reason is given to explain the stop, the
motorist is often left to feel that race was the primary factor.
</P>
<P>
   That was the impression left with Rep. Jim Clyburn, D-S.C.,
chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus. Clyburn, 58, said he
has experienced several unexplained traffic stops over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The latest, he said, was three years ago when a young black
staff member was driving Clyburn through the state in the
congressman's new Lincoln Continental. A police officer, Clyburn
said, pulled them over.
</P>
<P>
   No reason, Clyburn said, was ever given for the stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were stopped and the driver of the car was asked whose car
is this,'' Clyburn recalled. ``My staffer told him it's the
congressman's car. And then the officer asked, `Who's the
congressman?'''
</P>
<P>
   Recounting the incident, Clyburn exclaimed, ``I'm sitting right
there! But I don't fit the profile of a congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   Several police advocates were skeptical of the proposal to
collect racial data on traffic stops, saying that numbers alone
would be too easy to misinterpret and could be used for political
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To assume that stops are made on a racial basis is
misleading,'' said Jim Pasco, executive director of the National
Fraternal Order of Police. Pasco said that in looking for drug
traffickers, police consider many factors, including the type of
car, the driver's age, the neighborhood, the time of day and how
the driver is handling the car.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reno, Pasco rejected the idea of racial profiling, saying
that police should focus on behavior, not race. An exception, he
said, would be if officers were looking for a specific suspect and
race was part of the description.
</P>
<P>
   But another law enforcement expert suggested that since
minorities are disproportionately represented in the criminal
justice system, it stands to reason that more would be pulled over
if law enforcement officials were looking for suspected criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll obviously find that some people violate the laws more
than others,'' said Donald Baldwin, executive director of the
National Law Enforcement Council in Washington. ``That's a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin declined to elaborate, but according to Justice
Department statistics, black suspects accounted for 30 percent of
all arrests in 1996. Blacks make up 13 percent of the general
population. The black inmate population is far higher, accounting
for roughly 39 percent of the federal prison population in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clyburn said that those numbers don't mean that blacks are more
prone to crime. Instead, he said, they point to biases throughout
the criminal justice system, where minorities are arrested at
greater rates and treated more harshly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other ways of looking at those numbers,'' Clyburn
said. ``I do not think the Justice Department has developed a sense
of urgency yet about many of these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is a Washington correspondent for the New York
Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
