<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8804 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONCEPTUAL-ART-3TAKES     04-22 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCEPTUAL-ART-3TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCEPTUAL ART: OVER AND YET EVERYWHERE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is it going too far to say that Conceptual Art has
been to the second half of the 20th century what Cubism was to the
first half _ that is, a great divide, a demarcation after which
nothing was quite the same? Maybe, but not by much.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptual Art produced far fewer masterpieces than Cubism,
having disavowed the very term, and overall it probably did not
turn out as many art objects, dematerialization of art being one of
its goals. But in some weird, insidious way, it may have had a
greater impact on art, our view of art and its relationship to
life. Conceptual Art announced a recess from conventional
art-making; when class resumed, it was conducted according to a
different set of rules.
</P>
<P>
   It is now about 30 years since the phrase Conceptual Art gained
wide usage. (Coined by Edward Keinholz in the 1950s, it was put
into active play by Joseph Kosuth and Sol LeWitt in the late 60s.)
Its adherents dispensed with or radically redefined art objects,
material and technique and began questioning the very being and
usage of art.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, charts, graphs, maps and especially texts and
photographs _ and most especially the image-text combination _
emerged as the movement's stylistic traits. The era of reading
while standing up in art galleries was under way. So was a period
of unusual purity and idealism; the Conceptualists made few
concessions to the practicalities of galleries, collectors or
sales. They had almost ``no stuff,'' in the words of an artist I
know; that is, stuff to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barry projected words onto walls; Kosuth exhibited photo
enlargements of dictionary definitions of common objects beside the
objects themselves as well as photographs of them; Vito Acconci had
himself photographed furtively following strangers in the street,
and he famously masturbated under a slanting floor at Sonnabend
Gallery in SoHo; Gilbert and George sent out cards announcing that
they were ``Living Sculpture''; and a California art student named
Chris Burden began a run of notorious acts and events by spending
five days in a locker at art school.
</P>
<P>
   It is now more than 20 years since the movement was seen as
petering out. Its ``classic period,'' in fact, seems to have been
barely a decade long. In the main essay to ``Reconsidering the
Object of Art: 1965-1975,'' an exhibition at the Los Angeles Museum
of Contemporary Art in 1995, Lucy R. Lippard, the movement's
presiding critic, wrote about it in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   But Conceptualism never really faded away, and it certainly
didn't die; it simply rose, fell and rose again by infiltrating
other art forms. By now it seems virtually radioactive in its
staying power and ubiquity; it is the shifting terra infirma on
which nearly all contemporary art is built _ and a crucial factor
in the increasingly globalized art world.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, several exhibitions in the New York area are
deliberately or inadvertently noting the anniversary. ``Museum as
Muse: Artists Reflect,'' organized by Kynaston McShine at the
Museum of Modern Art, contains a skeletal outline of Conceptualism,
tracing its effects through the work of younger artists of the 80s
and 90s.
</P>
<P>
   It includes Hans Haacke's documentation of the progress of
Seurat's ``Poseuses'' through 14 collections between 1888-1975;
Fred Wilson's commentary on the Modern's elitism, a telling
arrangement of photographs drawn entirely from the museum's
archive, and Andrea Fraser's video tour of the Wadsworth Atheneum
in Hartford, which concentrates exclusively on the businesses,
marriages and collecting tastes of the museum's patrons and never
gets inside the front door.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Thread Waxing Space on lower Broadway, ``Conceptual
Art as Neurobiological Praxis'' mixes contemporary work with
Conceptual Art documentation and publications from the late 1960s
and 70s. (The latter, arranged by the artist Warren Neidich, the
show's organizer, itself presumably qualifies as a work of
Conceptual Art.) There have been unexpected retrievals, like the
little-known word paintings from the 60s by Gene Berry, recently
shown at Mitchell Algus in SoHo. Berry once lived in the same Lower
East Side loft building as LeWitt.
</P>
<P>
   But the real departure should be ``Global Conceptualism: Points
of Origin, 1950s-1980s,'' which opens at the Queens Museum of Art
this week. Overseen by Jane Farver, the exhibition is to include
more than 240 works by 135 artists from more than two dozen
countries, much of it being shown in this country for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The works will range from the tiny ``Postcard Paintings'' by the
Japanese artist Yutaka Matsuzawa, made in 1967, to an untitled work
from 1993-94 by the South African artist Kendell Geers, which
documents his joining all his country's political parties at once.
That the actual selections have been made by 11 curators from
different parts of the world suggests that Conceptualism and its
aftereffects are too big and diffuse for a single mind to
encompass.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptual Art was forged in the cauldron of political unrest
(civil rights, anti-war, feminist) of the late 1960s and early 70s
and in the mathematical tendencies of Minimalism and the
philosophizing ironies of Jasper Johns and various European
forefathers (Piero Manzoni, Yves Klein). It brought into focus, and
into the artistic mainstream, subversive ideas that had been
hovering on modernism's edges for much of the 20th &UR;  &LR; century, in
Dada, Fluxus, Happenings, Concrete Poetry and Situationism.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Duchamp's readymades, which had established as early as
1913 that anything (and by extension any activity) could be art,
were the movement's ground zero, its ``Demoiselles d'Avignon.'' The
movement's crucial non-Western influence _ as African art was to
Cubism _ was Eastern thought, which entered the postwar art world
by way of John Cage and reinforced the Conceptual interest in the
quotidian, the modest, the random and the immaterial.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Conceptual Art seems to have been populous from the start. It
either spread like wildfire, or, as Ms. Farver's exhibition seems
likely to confirm, it combusted spontaneously at several points
around the world in reaction to local strands of modernism and
specific political and social crises.
</P>
<P>
   By 1970, when McShine organized ``Information'' at the Museum of
Modern Art _ the first large survey of Conceptual Art in this
country _ he was able to bring together nearly 100 artists from
more than a dozen countries.
</P>
<P>
   What made it so universal? It certainly didn't hurt that it was
virtually formless, devoid of style and without national identity;
that it could be manifest in any material or no material; that the
written text and the photograph, its staples, were familiar and
available worldwide, and that it required very little traditional
art training.
</P>
<P>
   Its rise happened to coincide with the widespread availability
of video, which opened the way for other marginal activities _
film, for example _ to become more central, and it allowed artists
to make performance and moving images integral to their work.
</P>
<P>
   The Conceptualists were like little Davids approaching Goliath
art subjects. The paucity of their means enabled them to tackle
grandiose themes that artists working in traditional materials
could not touch. Their projects did not necessarily have to be
completed, or even possible, for them to put the viewer in touch
with the pulse of the universe, or to see the artist as
quixotically dedicated to a calling higher than producing
traditional, and saleable, art objects.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Huebler announced that he intended to photograph
everyone in the world. The career of the artist On Kawara has been
an extended exercise in marking and making visible the passage of
time, whether in his date paintings (recently seen in an exhibition
at the David Zwirner Gallery in SoHo) or his daily telegrams
announcing his waking time each day (``I got up'').
</P>
<P>
   When Conceptual Art seemed to wane, in the late 1970s, there was
a sigh of relief about the return of the art object. Some of the
Conceptualists themselves came in from the cold and started making
paintings and sculpture _ much as Picasso took up Neo-Classicism
after the rigors of Cubism. Burden and Acconci, exemplars of
endurance art, turned to sculpture; Mel Bochner and Dorothea
Rockburne gradually worked their way to paint on canvas. Perhaps
Conceptualism was a young artist's work, best pursued when the body
was strong and the mind fresher.
</P>
<P>
   But Conceptualism remained a force. By nullifying the art
object, it created a clean slate, reintroduing possibilities that
Minimalism and Pop, worldly as they were, had held at bay. Mainly,
it resurrected subjects largely expunged by abstraction _ the body,
psychology, society, for example. It declared not only that subject
matter was permissible in mainstream art, but that (italics)any(end
italics) subject matter was permissible.
</P>
<P>
   In this manner, Conceptualism encouraged two contradictory
tendencies: a new self-consciousness and critical attitude on the
one hand, and a new sense of anything goes on the other. Both
tendencies were visible in the resurgence of art objects _ whether
they were by the photo-based Pictures artists, the
Neo-Expressionists, the commodity-oriented Neo-Geoists or the
political-is-personal artists of the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Neo-Expressionists in particular were widely denounced as
regressive, but to some extent they were simply taking advantage of
the range and liberties exemplified by Conceptual Art. In fact,
several painters of the 1980s, including David Salle, Eric Fischl
and Sigmar Polke, passed through Conceptual Art on their way to
painting.
</P>
<P>
   Hewing more closely to the original style, the Pictures artists
breathed new life into its image-text combination. Barbara Kruger,
for example, made her exhortative captions part of the image, while
Cindy Sherman's early ``Film Stills'' plugged into each viewer's
memory bank of movies.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, having mastered reading while standing up, the art world
now learned to read images for their cultural meanings, their
suggestions of multiple, fragmented narratives and ambiguous
meanings. And throughout the paint-laden 80s, certain members of
the original generation _ Lawrence Weiner, John Baldessari and
Kosuth _ achieved eminence gris status, remaining fixtures in big
international shows.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's hard to think of a supposedly past art movement that
feels more present. Conceptual Art's influence and that of its
conceptually oriented siblings _ Performance, Process and
Installation Art _ is visible wherever contemporary art is on view,
in surveys around the world, in galleries around the corner. Stroll
around SoHo and Chelsea in Manhattan and Williamsburg in Brooklyn
and you will repeatedly be confronted with echoes, homages and
reprises, both intentional and not.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, its influence is apparent in the multimedia
fluidity that today's younger artists take for granted, moving
effortlessly from painting to video to photography to drawing at
will. It is visible in conventions that we all accept without
question _ the wall drawings and wall paintings whose point of
origin was primarily Sol LeWitt, but also Ms. Rockburne and
Bochner.
</P>
<P>
   A recent manifestation is the brightly colored wall painting
that LeWitt just completed for Christie's new American headquarters
at Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptualism's influence is apparent in the corrosive presence
of photography, in the relentless emphasis on narrative, in the
implication of performance in work in all media and in the constant
use in art writing of words like ``post,'' ``neo'' and ``late''
Conceptual to refer to work by artists who were still in diapers in
the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptual Art's most visible effect is the widespread use of
language, the written word in art or as art. The written word has
progressed from Acconci's semilegible scrawls to the aphorisms of
Jenny Holzer, first printed on paper, then carved into granite
benches and translated into vibrant LED signs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the English artist Fiona Banner made a large
black-on-white painting that simply reiterated the entire dialogue
and action of ``Lawrence of Arabia.'' But some recent
manifestations have returned to the rudimentary approaches of the
early 70s: In ``Signs That Say What You Want Them to Say, and Not
Signs That Say What Someone Else Wants You to Say'' of 1992-93, the
English artist Gillian Wearing asked passersby to write anything
they wanted on a piece of posterboard and then pose for her camera.
</P>
<P>
   A new wrinkle is the latest work of Sean Landers, known since
the early 1990s for large canvases covered with embarrassingly
confessional monologues. In his new paintings, on view at the
Andrea Rosen Gallery in Chelsea, Landers's writing is as
self-obsessed as ever, but it now fills the space _ like enormous,
borderless thought balloons _ around clownish portraits. The
teeming words form a wavering, cosseting net while permanently
capturing on canvas some of the anxiety once cultivated, in
performance, by artists like Acconci, Adrian Piper, or the
monologuist Spalding Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Certain tactics circulate and recirculate. Kawara's accumulation
of daily data has a strong echo in the work of Danica Phelps, whose
drawings and charts keep meticulous track of her expenses and the
money earned from her art.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptualism's questioning of the art object has not affected
only contemporary work and the growth of new media. Conceptualism
was among the first of many breakdowns and transgressed borders
that have continued to occur across the entire field of art,
greatly expanding its scope.
</P>
<P>
   These days art history is a bigger, more complicated subject
than ever before; it has been opened up to include previously
neglected areas of craft and design, folk art and outsider art and
to art from other cultures.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, this stealthy, multifarious art movement has had
effects beyond the art world. The catchier side of Conceptual Art _
the legacy of William Wegman's Weimaraners, of Ms. Kruger's
red-on-black-and-white graphic signature _ is apparent every day in
television commercials and print advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Many aspects of the displays in the Holocaust Museum in
Washington are also indebted to Conceptual and Installation Art.
There, glass walls etched with names are reminiscent of Jenny
Holzer; a gallery lined with photographs of victims brings to mind
the work of Christian Boltanski, and its pile of shoes from
concentration camps is a descendant of countless works of
installation art that impress by presenting a familiar object or
material in quantity.
</P>
<P>
   More profoundly, and at times negatively, the way art is
experienced has changed. Conceptual Art has encouraged the
assumption that every object, every picture, even every abstract
painting tells a story _ that it carries within it some kind of
narrative, meaning or ``subtext.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally ingrained is the more limiting expectation that all this
meaning is primarily intellectual and easily reduced to language,
that art as an entity is completely explainable. We owe to
Conceptualism years of one-liner artworks in all media _ the ``I
get it'' school of esthetic experience. This condition has caused a
permanent confusion of content with subject matter, to the
continuing detriment of both content and form. Too often, art that
lacks an explicit subject is thought to be without content and
dismissed (this happens especially to abstract art).
</P>
<P>
   By diminishing the role of form, Conceptual Art made all art
easier to grasp, less threatening and less mysterious. This may be
a strange fate for a movement that has often seemed so arcane and
opaque, and that was initially viewed as a reductivist dead end for
artists. But it's not so surprising. By expanding the definition of
what art can be, Conceptual Art released art into the culture at
large. It has become the paradigm, but also the caricature of
radical art.
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave us? Partly in recovery from Conceptual
Art, and partly in its debt. It could be argued that the
rematerialization of the art object has been a preoccupation of
artists of the last 20 years. The challenge is to embed concepts,
ideas and critique in material and form. This, along with the rise
in numerous realist styles, has contributed to a return of
traditional skills, techniques and to some extent standards.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Conceptual Art has played a major role in the
dramatic opening out of the art world _ to women, minorities and
artists from different cultures _ that has also transpired during
the same 20 years. It is no longer possible for art to be dominated
by one country, one style or one medium. For a dematerialized art
movement, this is a tangible accomplishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
