<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-MUSEUM-PHILLIPS-2     04-22 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-MUSEUM-PHILLIPS-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING A CENTURY OUT VENTURING INTO THE NEXT ONE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 William Harris writes frequently on art, dance and theater in
Manhattan.  
 By WILLIAM HARRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any big art opening is crammed with fabulous people
gossiping about everyone and carping about what's on view. Last
Tuesday, when the first half of the Whitney Museum of American
Art's ``American Century,'' a behemoth exhibition featuring 1,200
works of art, was to be unveiled, the opening proved bittersweet
for Lisa Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips had been organizing exhibitions at the Whitney
since 1977 and was one of four people who pulled together this
show. But that evening she was to be a guest rather than a host,
for earlier that day she was scheduled to begin her new job as
director at the New Museum of Contemporary Art in SoHo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips is only the second director at the 22-year-old New
Museum, a not-for-profit institution devoted to art by living
artists. She follows Marcia Tucker (also a former Whitney curator),
who created the place in 1977, in part as an alternative to what
she perceived as a stale, male-dominated museum world.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker's goal was not to build a permanent collection _ the
New Museum does not have one _ but to provide a showcase for
challenging conceptual and political art that other museums were
ignoring. Ms. Tucker resigned as director last March to pursue
other interests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips, 45, a slender woman with an elongated face that
Modigliani might have painted, is not nearly as flamboyant as her
predecessor. Understatement is her M.O. But she is known within the
art world for her intelligence, her passion for contemporary art in
all its manifestations _ she curated more than 25 shows at the
Whitney _ and her keen eye for spotting emerging talent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She is also incredibly discreet. During a recent interview, she
declined to discuss her resignation from the Whitney last December,
after 22 years. Ms. Phillips was more forthcoming about her plans
for the New Museum, where her curatorial touch will first be felt
in mid-2000 (museums plan far ahead).
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants the next chapter in the museum's life to be
different,'' she said. ``That is actually built into its mandate.
Part of what the New Museum is about is change. I would like to see
it do more with film, architecture, design and other media that
haven't been a prominent part of the programming. I also hope to
collaborate on projects with other institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As an example of such collaboration, the New Museum, in the
spring of 2001, will house a Tom Friedman exhibition, put together
by the Southeast Center for Contemporary Art in Winston-Salem, N.C.
Friedman is a whimsical Conceptualist who has made delicate
sculptures out of Play-Doh or boxes of spaghetti. That same year,
Ms. Phillips will collaborate with the Museum of Contemporary Art
in Chicago on a show of works by William Kentridge, a white South
African who explores issues of racial bias through drawings and
video.
</P>
<P>
   Before these, in the fall of 2000, the New Museum will mount a
show by Paul McCarthy, the Los Angeles-based sculptor and
performance artist, who has inspired a whole new generation of
artists but has never had a major show in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips does not lack ambition. ``One of my first
priorities is to make sure everyone knows of the museum's
existence, its location and its programming,'' she said. ``I've
frequently been asked, `What is the New Museum?' People in the art
world know it, but I want to broaden its base of support, not just
to New Yorkers but around the country and the world. I want to make
sure the New Museum is a must-see stop on anyone's itinerary when
in New York.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New Museum, with an annual operating budget of $2.7 million,
occupies 33,000 square feet on three floors in a residential loft
condominium at 583 Broadway. There are three distinct exhibition
spaces, plus a bookstore. Under Ms. Tucker, the museum made its
mark by mounting group shows, often overstuffed with socially
engaged art.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, with the hiring in 1995 of Dan Cameron, a critic
and independent curator, as senior curator, the museum has been
staging more one-person exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The New Museum remains committed to work that is edgy and often
unfashionable, as well as to non-United States-based artists. In
November, for example, there will be a show by Cildo Meireles, a
Brazilian Conceptual sculptor. Through June 20, there is a
retrospective honoring David Wojnarowicz, a
writer-photographer-painter-performance artist who died of
AIDS-related illnesses in 1992. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As director, Ms. Phillips will spend much of her time with
administrative chores, including raising money. But she will also
continue to organize exhibitions with the help of Cameron, a
longtime friend and colleague. Ms. Phillips has often relied on his
advice, particularly when working on the Whitney Biennial, that
museum's signature and always controversial survey of new trends in
art.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips was curator of the 1997 Biennial and served on the
curatorial team for every Biennial between 1985 and 1993. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will it be awkward being Cameron's boss? ``It's a team,'' Ms.
Phillips says. ``Dan is one of the New Museum's strengths. He
consistently gets out and sees work around the world, more than
practically anyone else I know.'' For his part, Cameron isn't
worried about titles. ``The New Museum is nonhierarchical,'' he
said. ``Besides, I like having a peer as a boss and a sense of
direction in place.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker said of her successor: ``I couldn't be happier. Lisa
has contacts, she has ideas and she's really respected and loved by
artists. That makes an enormous difference.'' Ms. Tucker was not
consulted in the selection of her replacement. That was handled by
the board of directors' search committee, led by the board
president, Saul Dennison, with the help of a head-hunting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips was initially interviewed last May, then didn't
hear a peep until November, when she was interviewed a second time
and subsequently offered the position. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Dennison, the New Museum considered four candidates
seriously. What tipped the scale in Ms. Phillips's favor, Dennison
said, was that ``she's extremely focused and has great credibility
in the art world.'' He continued: ``She had been working for a
mainstream museum and was willing to leave. Plus, our senior
curator highly endorsed her.'' Still, it took months for the search
committee to make a decision. Perhaps Ms. Phillips low-key manner
had been disarming. ``The first interview didn't go as well as the
second,'' Dennison said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips grew up in Brooklyn. Today, she lives in lower
Manhattan with her husband, Leon Falk, an independent film
producer. (She was previously married to the Venezuelan artist
Meyer Vaisman.) Her father, Warren H. Phillips, worked for The Wall
Street Journal and eventually became the chief executive at Dow
Jones, the parent company. But journalism was never a career
option.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everything you write as a child is edited,'' Ms. Phillips
said, ``that dissuades you.'' Ms. Phillips discovered a love of art
while at Middlebury College in Vermont, and during her junior year
abroad in Vienna, she started thinking seriously about a museum
career. It was also there that she discovered the uncomfortable
truth about a painting in the living room of her parents' home: It
was just a reproduction of the Velazquez original. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips did graduate work in art history at City University
Graduate Center and was selected for the Whitney Independent Study
program, a course for curators, critics and artists. Immediately
after, she joined the Whitney curatorial staff as manager of the
now defunct downtown branch in Manhattan. Last November, after
Maxwell L. Anderson succeeded David A. Ross as director of the
museum, she was given the title curator of painting and sculpture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, she is about to embark on only her second job in her adult
life. ``A lot of thought and a lot of agony went into `The American
Century,' said Ms. Phillips of her Whitney swan song. ``There are
many deserving artists who are not included. But you try to tell a
story that will reach a lot of people. It's only one story; there
are hundreds of others to tell. That's what I hope to be doing at
the New Museum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Separating from the Whitney is a little difficult. But I was
really ready to move into a director's job. The New Museum was the
perfect fit because of its size and because of its mandate, which
coincides with my own interests so closely. Plus, I can walk to
work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
