<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALAU-PREACH-BOS &LR;      04-22 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALAU-PREACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REV. LUIS PALAU SEEKS SOULS, GRAHAM'S MANTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Luis Palau doesn't give up easily.
</P>
<P>
   His 40-minute sermon about the transcendent power of Jesus's
resurrection draws four-dozen people out of their seats and up to
the stage of the Dartmouth arena, where they proclaim Jesus their
savior.
</P>
<P>
   Palau wants more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid to say yes to eternal life,'' Palau exhorts
the crowd of 1,300. ``Don't close your hearts to Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   A few more people, some crying, haltingly make their way up
front. On stage, Palau beams.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he prays, thanking God for using him, once again, to
bring more people to Jesus in a rugged, cold corner of the country
dominated by Catholics and mainline Protestants. It's rough terrain
for Gospel evangelists, more often associated with tent revivals in
the rural South.
</P>
<P>
   But Palau _ an Argentine-born evangelist so revered in
Spanish-speaking countries that he is referred to as the Billy
Graham of Latin America _ welcomes the challenge of unexplored
territory.
</P>
<P>
   He has spoken before 13 million people in 67 nations from Chile
to Romania, an audience second in size only to Graham's. Some
believe that if anyone can succeed Graham as unofficial pastor to
America, it is Palau.
</P>
<P>
   And while he may not be a household name in New England, the
preacher has come to the region on his Mission Maine tour to change
that.
</P>
<P>
   Palau, who decided he wanted to be an evangelist when he was 18
and heard Graham's fiery preaching on a shortwave radio, is
spending a month in Maine and a couple of days here and in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   His mission is simple: Convince as many people as possible to
accept Jesus as their personal lord and savior. So far, the crusade
has exceeded Palau's expectations. In the first week, 15,000 people
have come to hear him in Maine and New Hampshire. One thousand of
them have made public commitments to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Palau's colleagues were skeptical when they heard about
the crusade.
</P>
<P>
   After all, New England is not exactly a hotbed of evangelical
fervor. Only about 6 to 8 percent of the region is evangelical,
according to Vision New England, a Christian organization based in
Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   And the perception among evangelicals is that New Englanders, by
and large, are indifferent and even somewhat cynical when it comes
to the kind of passionate, emotional preaching Palau brings to mass
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Many evangelicals believe New Englanders also are less likely to
accept evangelical Christianity's core message, that the Bible is
the word of God and eternal life is only possible for Christians
who embrace Jesus as their savior.
</P>
<P>
   Palau is one of a number of evangelicals trying to plant their
charismatic, soul-saving, and uncompromising brand of evangelical
Christianity in the tough New England soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told me that New England was too hard and people were
so unholy,'' Palau said in an interview inside a locker room at
Leede Arena in Hanover, where he preached on consecutive nights
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, New England does have deep evangelical roots.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Awakening of the mid-1700s was born in New England,
and the region was the home territory of some of America's greatest
evangelists, including George Whitefield and Dwight Moody.
</P>
<P>
   So Palau, accompanied by a small army of assistants, younger
preachers, and nationally acclaimed Christian musicians, was
hopeful when he arrived in Maine earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Palau added: ``I love a challenge. When people say,
`You can't break through here,' I say, `Oh, yeah. Maybe I can't,
but God can.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been decades since citizens of this region have been
confronted by the claims of Christ, and we thought it's about time
it happened,'' he said. ``All of Maine is going to have to hear the
voice of God. They may reject his message, but they are going to
hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, Christian pastors and activists are calling Palau's
holy crusade a religious milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proclamation of the Gospel on such a large scale is
something this state has not seen in a very long time,'' said the
Rev. David McBride, chairman of Mission Maine.
</P>
<P>
   McBride, senior associate pastor of First Baptist Church in
Portland, Maine, noted that more than 10,000 people have
volunteered for Palau's crusade, an extraordinary number, given
Maine's relatively small evangelical population.
</P>
<P>
   Palau's ability to mobilize evangelicals is nothing new. Since
1966, when he first began staging revivals in stadiums and arenas,
Palau has drawn huge crowds: 106,000 in Mexico City in 1970,
518,000 in London in 1984, and 127,000 in Hong Kong two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars and evangelical activists say Palau's appeal lies in
his sincerity, integrity, and enthusiasm. He's not a
fire-and-brimstone preacher. He's more of a storyteller, weaving
together personal anecdotes with quotes from Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   At Dartmouth, Palau's message was simple, straightforward, and
sometimes humorous, gradually building the case for why his
listeners should ``open their hearts to Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God's plan for the human race is that we know happiness,''
Palau told an audience that began arriving two hours before the
evangelist took the stage. ``He doesn't want us to walk around with
long faces. God has a plan, but his plan is that you trust him and
let him come into your life. I'm here to tell you tonight that a
loving God wants you.''
</P>
<P>
   Palau said Graham taught him the finer points of staging a
massive crusade. Graham also gave Palau $100,000 to help the Luis
Palau Evangelistic Association in Portland, Ore., 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   About a decade ago, Palau decided he needed to ask Graham's
blessing before holding his first crusades in the United States.
America, Palau says, was Billy Graham's territory, and he did not
want to look like he was stepping on his toes.
</P>
<P>
   According to Palau, Graham told him: ``You don't need (my
blessing), but if you want it, you've got it. We've got to get on
with evangelism.''
</P>
<P>
   As Graham, now 80, becomes increasingly frail, many Christians
wonder who, if anyone, will replace him as the de facto spokesman
for evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout American history, almost every era has had one
preacher who came to be regarded as the nation's own, from
Whitefield to Charles Finney, Dwight Moody, Billy Sunday, and
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Palau is cited frequently as Graham's potential heir. But there
are other contenders, including Franklin Graham, Billy's son;
Bishop T. D. Jakes Sr., a Pentecostal African-American and senior
pastor of Potter's House in Dallas; Bill Hybels, senior pastor of
Willow Creek Community Church outside Chicago; and Anne Graham
Lotz, one of Billy Graham's daughters and founder of Angel
Ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Billy Graham is going to be off the scene fairly soon, I
think Palau would likely rise to a similar stature in the public
mind,'' said Keith J. Hardman, professor of philosophy and religion
at Ursinus College in Collegeville, Penn., and author of ``The
History of Evangelical Christianity in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't so sure anyone can come close to having as large
an influence as Graham did in his heyday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evangelical Chrsitianity has moved beyond stadium crusades and
television as its major thrust,'' said William Martin, professor of
sociology at Rice University in Houston and the author of a
biography of Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of parachurch organizations, megachurches,
and many other competitors for public attention that these other
evangelists in American history really didn't have,'' Martin said.
``It would be difficult for one person to stand above the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Lon Allison, director of the Billy Graham Center, a training and
research center for evangelism housed at Wheaton College in Wheaton
Ill., agreed: ``Can anyone replace Billy Graham? No, unless God
wants to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Palau said it's flattering simply to be mentioned in the same
breath as Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also gives me credibility,'' he added. ``People might say,
`Well I don't know who that guy Palau is, but if he's compared to
Graham he must be OK.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
