w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-JON-VOIGHT-IN-NO     04-22 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JON-VOIGHT-IN-NOAHS-ARK-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JON VOIGHT STEERS A NOT-SO-SERIOUS ARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Jon Voight in
``Noah's Ark.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In the beginning there was the Bible and there was Cecil B.
DeMille. And DeMille saw the Bible, and it was good screenplay
material.
 &HT;    Hollywood may not be the most religious town on earth, but it
does seem to have an affinity for the Bible. No need to option the
book, and the leading characters are all so long dead that no one
can sue if you get anything wrong.
 &HT;    DeMille scored big with his silent version of ``The Ten
Commandments'' (1923), and repeated the exercise _ this time with
sound _ in 1956, with Charlton Heston parting the Red Sea and
ensuring himself a long career in righteousness. DeMille's ``Samson
and Delilah'' (1950) was another Bible story that had everything,
including sex, violence and a really bad hair day.
 &HT;    More biblical or quasi-biblical epics followed, including ``Quo
Vadis'' (1951), ``The Robe'' (1953), Heston again in ``Ben Hur''
(l959) and ``The Greatest Story Ever Told'' (l965). By 1966
Hollywood was ready to tackle the entire book with ``The Bible,''
most notable for casting John Huston as the voice of God _
naturally, a director got the part.
 &HT;    In our more secular age, however, the Bible has fared less well
on screen. There was ``King David'' (l985), but Richard Gere was
nobody's idea of the King of Israel, and the movie bombed. Martin
Scorsese's controversial ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' (l988)
spurred hostile demonstrations outside Universal Studios' gates,
and the good book pretty much forsook the big screen until last
year's animated epic, ``The Prince of Egypt.''
 &HT;    Recently. however, the Bible has been resurrected on the home
screen by cable evangelist Ted Turner, whose network has so far
given us ``Joseph,'' ``Moses,'' ``Samson and Delilah'' and ``King
David'' in miniseries form.
 &HT;    The latest Biblical saga comes to us from a major network,
however, as NBC launches ``Noah's Ark,'' a special-effects-laden,
four-hour miniseries airing May 2 and 3, and starring Jon Voight.
Bearded and sporting an elaborate, 1960s-style silver ponytail,
this God-fearing arkbuilder has Mary Steenburgen as his peppy,
no-hausfrau-she wife, Naamah.
 &HT;    But something strange has happened to Noah, Naamah and their
sons Ham, Shem and Japheth. They've become comedians _ all of them,
that is, except for Noah, whom Voight plays straight down the
waterway.
 &HT;    But for the rest, this is the Bible gone bananas. Even God comes
off like a cross between Henny Youngman and George Burns.
 &HT;    He instructs Noah to make the ark 500 feet long, 83 feet wide
and 50 feet high.
 &HT;    ``Why so big?'' Noah asks.
 &HT;    ``I think big,'' He says. ``I made the world in six days.''
 &HT;    Later, disgusted with mankind, God considers wiping out the
whole human race, Noah and family included.
 &HT;    ``It's an option,'' the Deity says. ``Don't call me, I'll call
you.''
 &HT;    By the time Lot (F. Murray Abraham) refers to his wife (Carol
Kane) as ``the salt of the earth,'' you've gotten the picture.
 &HT;    There's lots of sex talk, too, particularly on the ark, where
Noah has forbidden his sons and their three girlfriends to
procreate until they're off the boat. Not to mention the fine old
orgy going on in Sodom and Gomorrah.
 &HT;    And, yes, you're right _ Sodom and Gomorrah came after the
flood. But this is television.
 &HT;    ``I think if God created the world, He must have had a sense of
humor,'' director John Irvin says. ``It's an irreverent story _ not
blasphemous or disrespectful. It's respectful without being overly
pious, too solemn or heavy. It's ebullient, it's light, it's full
of life.''
 &HT;    There's a subplot of sorts involving the archvillain of the
piece _ Lot, who in this version leads a convoy of pirates on a
flotilla of rafts and attempts to board the ark. Think Dennis
Hopper's character in ``Waterworld.''
 &HT;    In the midst of this floating funny farm, only Voight as Noah
retains his dignity.
 &HT;    ``Our approach has a lot of humor in it,'' the actor admits
during an interview at the Ritz Carlton Hotel in Pasadena, Calif.
``That's the style of the piece.
 &HT;    ``But the story itself is quite disturbing,'' he adds. ``There's
been so much destruction on the planet perpetrated by the human
race. The good news is that more and more people are becoming aware
of that destruction, and of the urgent need to reverse the
process.''
 &HT;    One of the nicest, most unassuming actors in Hollywood, even
after almost 40 years acting, Voight still loves what he does and
takes the work, though not himself, very seriously indeed.
 &HT;    ``I think all the Bible stories are packed with meaning,'' he
says earnestly. ``No question about it. I take these stories quite
literally _ I don't treat them as metaphors. It seems to me there
are no deeper stories than these. They're powerful.''
 &HT;    It's vintage Voight _ serious, philosophical and downright
upright, with the kind of sincerity that has made him believable
even when wrestling with a giant, animatronic snake in the 1997
epic ``Anaconda.''
 &HT;    His career has been a fascinating one ever since he first caught
our attention as Joe Buck, the dumb but likeable street hustler in
``Midnight Cowboy'' (l969). In the years since he's built a
formidable resume in films such as ``Catch 22'' (l970),
``Deliverance'' (l972), ``The Odessa File'' (l974) and ``Coming
Home'' (l978), for which he won an Oscar as a paraplegic Vietnam
vet.
 &HT;    Not all of his roles have been equally meaty, however, and of
late the 60-year-old has metamorphosed from leading man to
character actor, often playing villains such as the go-between
crook in ``Heat'' (l986), the oily corporate lawyer in ``The
Rainmaker,'' (l987) the corrupt national-security chief in ``Enemy
of The State'' (l998) and the fanatically driven police inspector
in ``The General,'' John Boorman's upcoming Irish gangster film.
 &HT;    And now, Noah. Voight says that he enjoyed the romp, and adds
that he sees a message in the film, comic or not, for
turn-of-the-century America.
 &HT;    ``If you want to be simply entertained for a few hours over a
few nights, you can approach `Noah' at that level,'' the actor
says. ``After all, it's stunning visually, filmed in beautiful
places, full of special effects and epic scenes. But this film
invites the audience to use its brain, to reflect on where as a
species we've been _ and where we're going.
 &HT;    ``Here we are just a few months away from a new millennium _
this just may be the right picture in the right country at the
right time.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Noah's Ark,'' consult the NBC
Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
