<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8817 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLISTS-STARS-$ADV25     04-22 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLISTS-STARS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLISTS ARE THE TWIN STARS OF AN ORCHESTRAL GALAXY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Comparisons are especially odious in the arts. To try
to prove that the New York Philharmonic has, in Cynthia Phelps, the
``best'' principal violist of any orchestra would be futile and
unsatisfying in the extreme. Still, it is tempting simply to
declare that the Philharmonic has the best (italics)pair(end
italics) of violists of any orchestra in the United States, if not
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phelps, at 38, has amply displayed her sterling qualities,
not only in her excellent leadership of what has in recent years
become, perhaps, the Philharmonic's plum section, but also in solo
appearances with the orchestra and in chamber performances around
the city.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she arrived here from the Minnesota Orchestra to
become principal violist, in 1992, Rebecca Young had been elevated
to associate principal violist: a close No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young, who entered the Philharmonic as its youngest player
in 1986, at 20, would by now, at 33, be the principal violist in
almost any other orchestra. In fact, she took that position with
the Boston Symphony Orchestra in 1993, but she returned to New York
the next year to be close to her husband and young son.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Masur, the Philharmonic's music director, has repeatedly
voiced his admiration for the two violists. And now Masur's wife,
Tomoko, has shown hers in tangible fashion: by commissioning from
Sofia Gubaidulina a concerto for two violas, ``Two Paths,'' to be
given its premiere in a series of concerts conducted by Masur
beginning on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Also in that series, without Masur's guiding hand, Ms. Phelps
and Ms. Young will anchor performances of Bach's Sixth
``Brandenburg'' Concerto, in which violas carry the upper lines.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra's original plan to commission a solo concerto for
Ms. Phelps stalled several years ago. ``But Tomoko didn't want to
let it go,'' Ms. Phelps said recently of Ms. Masur, who was herself
a violist before she turned to singing professionally. ``She sits
up there in her box at concerts and watches us play together and
knows we are really good friends. And she came up with the idea for
a concerto for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The players learned of the commission at the intermission of a
concert, when they were summoned to Masur's dressing room. They
were doubly gratified to hear the reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were in for it,'' Ms. Phelps said. ``It was the
end of a week, and things had gotten a little out of hand in the
first half of the concert. We play off each other a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In repartee as well as in performance, to judge from their
conversation during a break between rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   MS. PHELPS: I'm a complete nerd. I'm totally single-minded about
making as much music as I can.
</P>
<P>
   MS. YOUNG: I don't know how you do it. I would rather be home in
my back yard digging up weeds. I'm not as ambitious. Whatever has
come to me has come to me, and I'm having a lot of fun now. Maybe
if I had been trained differently__
</P>
<P>
   MS. PHELPS: I came up through a very competitive environment. I
just did it. I've always wanted to play with people who are better
than me.
</P>
<P>
   MS. YOUNG: That's why I like sitting next to you.
</P>
<P>
   This last might have have been utterly sincere or mildly
facetious. It is sometimes hard to tell with the freewheeling Ms.
Young, who, when asked whether her husband was also a musician,
replied in perfect deadpan, ``No, he's a bass trombonist.'' And
this to a reporter who was determined, in such exalted company, not
even to mention viola jokes, let alone trombone jokes. (Ms. Young's
husband is Jack Schatz, a bass trombonist and a musician. Ms.
Phelps's second husband is the cellist Ronald Thomas; no joke.)
</P>
<P>
   But what was obvious beneath the banter was a warm friendship
founded on mutual respect. ``We were friends before we were even
colleagues,'' Ms. Phelps said, recounting how, when she moved east,
Ms. Young immediately initiated contact. They met and brought their
children together before they began performing together.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are embarked on their most unusual collaboration. Ms.
Phelps, with her mania for performing, has at least played
concertos with some frequency, though she has never given the
premiere of one. Ms. Young has played few concertos at all.
</P>
<P>
   They got the parts for this one in mid-February and found them
of limited use in judging the piece as a whole. ``I didn't really
know what to expect from my part,'' Ms. Phelps said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young showed admirable initiative, recording Ms. Phelps's
part and playing her own against it. ``The parts are abstract, and
they sometimes extend way up into nosebleed territory,'' she said,
``but if you put them together, they make a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-March, they gave a command performance of the work with
piano for Masur. ``Gubaidulina gets definite ideas of color and
emotion, and she doesn't care whether it's difficult to play,'' Ms.
Phelps said. Masur helped the players work through certain
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Both violists reciprocate Masur's expressions of admiration and
seem uneasy at the prospect of a successor on the podium, as yet
unknown. ``We don't have a lot to choose from, and we will have to
choose very carefully,'' Ms. Phelps said. ``The orchestra is really
at its strongest now. It won't settle for a pretty-boy conductor
now that we have had Masur's raw integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Paths,'' meanwhile, may well escape the typical fate of
new works, which tend to drop out of sight after their premieres.
For one thing, the Philharmonic plans to keep it alive, playing it
in June in Washington and next year in Carnegie Hall and on tour in
Europe. What's more, the work stands as a challenge to any
orchestra that thinks it has a pair of violists as good and well
balanced as these two. One can only wish that orchestra well.
</P>
</TEXT>
