</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Creating separate Balkan states is a surrender
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, April 25, 1999.)
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOMOGENEOUS: I've seen the word too much in recent months. It
means, in its strictest dictionary interpretation: ``1. the same in
structure, quality, etc.; similar or identical. 2. composed of
similar or identical elements or parts; uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, however, it is a political term that has as its
goal the separation of peoples who are not alike. It also could be
called apartheid or segregation, except in the way ``homogeneous''
is used today, it is not so much of a segregation within the
borders of a nation but redefining borders so as to segregate
people; people who do not get along, who hate each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethnic cleansing'' and ``homogeneous'' are cousins, perhaps
more closely related than that. What Slobodan Milosevic has been
trying to do within the political entity of Yugoslavia is to
homogenize Kosovo of people whose heritage and daily practices are
Albanian and not Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   This was the thinking of Adolf Hitler and the Nazis: It was
Germany (and Austria) for Aryans and no one else.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about the Balkans is about homogeny, and always has
been.
</P>
<P>
   It recently was proposed by two political scientists in an
article written for The New York Times that all the fighting would
go away if only that which was and is Yugoslavia was redefined and
space apportioned ethnically, with the Kosovars getting that part
of Kosovar which was ethnic Albanian while the northeast quadrant,
being ethnically Serbian, being another place _ a Serbian place.
They proposed other divisions of the land so as to isolate alike
peoples and ostracize those who are not.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the Croats, the Serbs, Kosovars and whomever else apart by
adhering to a homogeneous formula is what their solution appears to
be. It sounds to me more like surrendering to ethnic provincialism.
</P>
<P>
   It might appear inviting until you recognize the precedent it is
setting. While the world at one time must have been ethnically
divided by natural means, it is not now.
</P>
<P>
   We are mixed together, for better or for worse. Even the Asiatic
nations of China, Japan and South Korea, once bastions of
homogeneous existence, have lowered their ethnic barriers in the
face of the modernization of their previously ancient
civilizations; foreigners now fit in, however precariously.
</P>
<P>
   When the Soviet Union broke into essentially separate ethnic
states, the hatred that was within them all those years under
communism emerged.
</P>
<P>
   There is something in the human spirit that says we want to be
with alike peoples, but the world cannot work that way anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A capitulation to ethnically driven borders within the Balkan
states would be a message to the world that agrees with the same
kind of horror that is manifest in Africa, in Northern Ireland, in
the Middle East and even in less precipitous situations such as
prevails between Scotland and England, between Quebec and the
remainder of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Divide up Yugoslavia with harsh ethnically drawn lines and the
precedence will have been established in these most modern of times
for a retreat to medieval days, when walls were constructed to
separate people and cities. Our history books show us that did not
create a peace at all. Someone always seemed to want the other
group's place as well.
</P>
<P>
   We, as a civilization, are faced with the arduous task of
demanding of people that they learn to live together and as equals.
No longer can we return to apartheid, or to segregation. And
recreating homogeneous nations devoid of other people will do
little to ease the world's tensions.
</P>
<P>
   It will just put us back into an ancient city-state mentality.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
