<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, April 22, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for the Friday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIDEO (Undated) _ More than 15 million copies of a
shoot-'em-up 3-D computer game called Doom are floating around the
world, used by players who wield virtual guns and chain saws to
blast away monsters. One such user apparently was one of the young
gunmen in Colorado, who knew the game well enough to design his own
map. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PREVENTION (Undated) _ Parents who wonder whether the
high school shootings in Colorado have troubled their children
should face the issue head on _ by inviting their kids to talk. By
opening up the topic themselves, parents reassure their kids that
it's OK to express their thoughts and feelings about the tragedy,
said Sharon Williams, director of child and adolescent psychiatry
at Stanford University's Medical School. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-MOOD (Denver) _ The large illuminated sign in front of
the Denver Center for the Performing Arts read: A time to reflect.
Coors Field, home of Major League Baseball's Colorado Rockies, was
empty. A scheduled game had been postponed for a second straight
day. This city is in numb shock. By ROSS McKEON.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SCENE (Littleton, Colo.) _ Desultory skies over Columbine
High School mirrored the anguished mood of the throngs convened
below. Sometimes the tears and the rain could come, sometimes they
couldn't. Only the occasional sprinkle mingled with the tears of
the weeping masses, many of them students of the school where death
came calling one day before. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-WARNINGS (Littleton, Colo.) _ Had anyone one been been
looking a little harder, they would have seen red flags hinting
that Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, were in serious
trouble. The two Colorado seniors believed to have killed 12
classmates, a teacher, and, finally, themselves in the worst school
shooting in U.S. history were behaving in ways that experts say
indicate a kid is headed toward violence. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FUN-EMPLOYERS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ In a new book, ``Work Like
Your Dog,'' Matt Weinstein and Luke Barber describe the benefits
that large and small companies derive from making work more
enjoyable. ``It makes so much sense,'' Weinstein says, ``yet it's
one of those disconnects in people's brains.'' By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   GE-SHAREHOLDERS (Cleveland) _ Led by a 79-year-old woman,
retirees of the General Electric Co. urged stockholders to tap some
of the mammoth company's pension fund surpluses to provide higher
retirement benefits. The rally, one of several issues shareholders
faced at their annual meeting, failed. By JAY MILLER.
</P>
<P>
   PC-NETWORKS (San Francisco) _ As people buy more computers, they
consider buying additional peripherals, installing separate phone
lines for Internet connections and subscribing to an additional
Internet service provider. To bypass these costly additions, many
have considered networking their home PCs to share resources and
peripherals. By MARIE J. BALBA.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TILBERIS-APPRECIATION (San Francisco) _ Harper's BAZAAR
editor-in-chief Liz Tilberis, 51, lost her five-year battle with
cancer Wednesday. But she left an indelible mark on the magazine
she resurrected in 1992 and on the lives of the people with whom
she worked. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALADS (Undated) _ There's no law that says salads have to
contain leafy greens. And in addition to tuna, chicken and
potatoes, there's a whole host of foods you can use as the basis
for a good salad. Not the least of which is grains. By RUTH
FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   MARINADE (Undated) _ Occasionally you find a recipe that's so
easy, so flexible and so universally devoured by everyone who
tastes it that it becomes THE recipe for all entertaining. In my
house it's a teriyaki marinade my mother and I discovered during a
trip to Hawaii. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-LABEL (Undated) _ Q: What does the American Heart
Association logo mean on food? A: A food packaging that carries the
logo - a red heart with a white check mark - means the food has no
more than 3 grams of fat per serving, 20 milligrams of cholesterol
and 480 milligrams of sodium. By LISA STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-A'S-BIDDING (Oakland, Calif.) _ The bidding game for the
Oakland A's baseball team has gone into extra innings. Rather than
choose between two bids, an investment banking firm hired to find a
buyer for the team by Wednesday's deadline opted instead to leave
the decision to the Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum Authority. By
SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The real world didn't become
defined by TV until my junior year in high school when a lone
gunman (or so I believe) killed our president. Then the real world,
as filtered through TV, began being defined by a series of lone
gunmen. TV and lone gunmen sort of grew up together. This week TV
and reality were redefined by an organized, uniformed club of lone
gunmen at a high school. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ At an Air Force base about an
hour south of Kansas City, Mo., daughters and sons of some 45
American daddies got shut out of ``Take Your Daughter (or Son) to
Work Day.'' That's because there wasn't room in daddy's B-2 to take
the kid along during the 30-hour trip bomb Yugoslavia and return
home. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
