<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plumbing and mowers are my downfall
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Some days it doesn't pay to get out of bed.
At least it would be cheaper if I just stayed buried under the
covers. A recent Saturday was such a day.
</P>
<P>
   First the riding lawn mower died in the midst of mowing. Just
died, with no warning. I stopped to get a glass of water, came back
out and it wouldn't turn over. I figured out that it likely was a
malfunctioning safety switch under the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn mowers are as regulated as automobiles these days. They
have safety switches so that the mower dies if you get off it,
presumably to keep you from doing something dumb like sticking your
hand under the deck while it's running. That's all well and good,
but the switches inevitably are made of plastic. I call this the
Lawn Mower Service Association Profit Assurance Switch. It is bound
to break, sooner or later, and you have little choice but to call a
repair person or take it somewhere _ at least if you have my
limited mechanical ability.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to hot wire around these switches, but it takes
someone who knows more about electricity to do that, so I left well
enough alone and finished mowing by hand with the push mower. It
too has a safety feature _ a bar that must be pulled toward you to
start and run the mower. The bar has a spring so if you let loose,
the mower dies.
</P>
<P>
   I have gotten around this safety feature with duct tape because
my hands get tired of holding the bar. Duct tape, not a dog, is
man's best friend. I wrap a few revolutions around the real handle
and leave a few extra inches. When I get ready to start the mower,
I pull the safety handle back and wrap the tape around it. It's
easy to unwrap and kill the engine, and generally my duct tape
anti-safety device lasts about three months before the sticky stuff
wears out.
</P>
<P>
   When I bought this mower a few months back, I ended up calling
the folks who sold it to me. It had no throttle switch. Looked like
it had a place for one, and I figured they just forgot to put it
on. I called the store, a bit peeved. The mower would run, but it
wasn't at a high enough rpm to suit me.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out new push mowers don't have throttles anymore. The EPA,
worried about air emissions, has banned them, and mowers just have
a set speed. You can adjust the carburetor to rev it up, but that
requires fiddling with screws, which makes me nervous, given my
past history with mechanical devices.
</P>
<P>
   I was cutting some high, wet grass, and the mower died
constantly. Eventually I hit a spot of mud and the blade dug into
the ground and bent. I had to buy a new blade and install it. Time
I was finished, a two-hour mowing chore had stretched out nearly
all day.
</P>
<P>
   I took a shower and remembered the faucet in the kitchen was
leaking. It's been leaking for about a month, not from the spout
but from the base. For reasons that still escape me, I decided to
see if I could tighten this down and save a plumber's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time readers know that I am the Darth Vader of plumbing. I
have a long history of plumbing disasters. Now it's a tad longer. I
took the spout off and started fiddling with some screws, hoping to
tighten it down.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing I know, a geyser of water is bouncing off the
ceiling. Luckily, there was a cutoff under the sink, so the water
only ran about 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   An exploding faucet puts out a lot of water in 20 seconds.
Luckily, nobody was home. I calculated I had about 15 minutes to
clean up the mess without anybody being the wiser. It took about a
dozen towels. I cleaned knick-knacks, emptied glasses on the shelf
half-filled with water, sopped water off the kitchen floors and the
cabinets, wiped water off the wooden blind on the window behind the
sink. I got it all cleaned up with about three minutes to spare.
</P>
<P>
   I probably could have gotten away with it except that the faucet
really didn't work now, and I had a dozen wet towels. I told my
wife I had decided to clean the cabinets, but she didn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tried to fix the faucet yourself, didn't you,?'' she said
with a semi-accusing stare. I 'fessed up.
</P>
<P>
   We had no water in the kitchen for two days, this being on a
Saturday. I paid penance by buying a lot of meals out for those two
days. The faucet is fixed now, and the service person came out and
fixed the lawn mower. Sure enough, it was the safety switch.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I borrowed a chain saw to cut down a small dead
tree. Rather than witness another potential disaster, my wife left
and went shopping. Some things are just too painful to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
