<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Answering an age-old question
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Adulthood is a funny thing. It's not like you
roll out of bed one day and announce, ``Today I am an adult.'' It
creeps up on you and before you know it, you're saying things like,
``Back in my day, we didn't have MTV and personal computers and
VCRs, and we liked it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming an adult doesn't necessarily happen when you graduate
from school, or when you start a job, or start a family. And it
sure doesn't have anything to do with age. Some people become
adults when they're 16, some (like 73-year-old Hugh Hefner) never
get there.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who wonder, here's a list sent to be by a friend
of ways to know if you may be an adult:
</P>
<P>
   You start drinking V8.
</P>
<P>
   You make ``oof'' sounds when you sit down.
</P>
<P>
   Going out at night starts feeling like something you ``should''
do.
</P>
<P>
   You don't know who those new bands are, and you don't
particularly care.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a full night's sleep makes you so much more productive.
</P>
<P>
   Your potted plants stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping in a twin-sized bed seems absurd.
</P>
<P>
   You keep more food than beer in the 'fridge.
</P>
<P>
   You have to pay your own credit card bill.
</P>
<P>
   Mac &AMP; Cheese no longer counts as a well-balanced meal.
</P>
<P>
   8 a.m. is not early.
</P>
<P>
   You hear your favorite song on an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   You're not carded anymore.
</P>
<P>
   You carry an umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   You learn that ``bachelor'' is a nicer term for a jerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-something'' means overqualified, underpaid and not
married.
</P>
<P>
   You start watching the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Jeans and baseball caps aren't staples in your wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   You can no longer drink shots, and smoking gives you a sinus
attack.
</P>
<P>
   You go from 130 days of vacation time to seven.
</P>
<P>
   You go to parties that the police don't raid.
</P>
<P>
   You don't know what time the fast food chains close anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Your car insurance goes down.
</P>
<P>
   You refer to college students as kids.
</P>
<P>
   You feed your dog Science Diet instead of Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   One not mentioned, but certainly an indicator is: You find your
favorite recording artist in the easy listening section of the
music store.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
