<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buchanan glides easily through revolving door
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ This is a nutty business. Civilians shake their
heads whenever one of us is driven to hand-wringing angst over an
invitation to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   People in this business are likely to cluck their tongues loudly
if they see one of their number socializing with ``them'' _ a
politician or (gasp!) a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   We adhere to a constantly evolving code of ethics that is
rigidly elastic depending on your status, standing and profile in
the business.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, if you will, that professional blowhard Pat Buchanan,
who was in Texas last week campaigning yet again for president.
</P>
<P>
   While some kid reporter working for a small-town daily or a
mid-market television station might get yelled at for accepting a
39-cent ballpoint pen or taking a part-time job that might
constitute ``a conflict of interest,'' Buchanan is a television
commentator one day and presidential candidate the next. No
conflict of interest there, boss.
</P>
<P>
   All this against a backdrop of endless industry seminars on
ethics with the obligatory colon in the middle (as in Ethics:
Keystone of Journalistic Credibility).
</P>
<P>
   Some may argue that Buchanan and his brethren are not
``journalists.'' My definition of journalist, however, is pretty
simple: one who presents or comments on the news.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, I don't think that viewers, readers or listeners
pay attention to the artificial distinctions the way we do.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is certainly not the first politician/journalist to use
the revolving door. Jack Kennedy tried his hand at reporting before
launching his political career. Then, there's George
Stephanopoulos, the White House aide turned Newsweek columnist and
television personality. There are many others who wandered through
the revolving door between politics and journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, we have a couple of former reporters, Daryl Slusher,
the council member, and Karen Sonleitner, the county commissioner,
holding elected office.
</P>
<P>
   So Buchanan isn't the only one to go through the revolving door,
he just makes it spin louder and faster than most.
</P>
<P>
   What really cracks me up is that very few people in the business
even want to discuss the glaring double standard: There's one set
of rules for the stars and another for working stiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Once Buchanan loses his quest for the Republican presidential
nomination, he will undoubtedly be welcomed back to the commentator
fold where he will have another four years to chop on potential
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   No conflict of interest there, boss.
</P>
<P>
   Ethics, schmethics. People apparently love to watch people
yelling and Buchanan is good at that, so he gets hired. And the
rest of us get to grin and bear it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, readers and viewers are becoming increasingly cynical
about ``the news product'' and people who deliver it. In turn, we
hold seminars to try to figure out why. Somebody at one of those
seminars may even remember to turn the volume down on the show
featuring a bunch of former speech writers and political operatives
yelling at each other during our interminable soul searches.
</P>
<P>
   What a racket. All this brings to mind the line delivered by Lee
Strasberg in ``Godfather II'': ``I didn't ask any questions ...
this is the business we've chosen ...'' It's like no business I
know.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
