<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8849 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-OP-VOINOVICH23     04-22 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-OP-VOINOVICH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voinovich view has been tried
 &HT;    WITH an editorial offering opposing views by Ohio Sen. George
Voinovich slugged KOSOVO-VOINOVICH.
 &HT;    By Martin Gottlieb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Sometimes it seems as though what a person thinks
about the bombing of Yugoslavia depends upon where that person came
in.
</P>
<P>
   For many people who have been following events in the Balkans
through this decade, the bombing seems a natural progression, a
necessity brought by process of elimination. Here, after all, we
had this war-mongering, war criminal of a dictator whose
society-destroying instincts and intentions were beyond dispute.
Negotiations and economic sanctions had been tried ad nauseam, and
land troops were politically out of the question. That leaves a
bombing assault.
</P>
<P>
   Some people now paint that assault as the work of a hapless and
directionless Clinton administration. That's absurdly wrong.
Foreign-policy experts in droves have been looking toward military
action against Slobodan
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic for a long time. And NATO is not exactly an arm of
President Clinton. Across Europe a near consensus had developed
that the time for bombing had come.
</P>
<P>
   When Washington and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization first
considered making the threat to bomb Yugoslavia if Milosevic didn't
come to terms over Kosovo, few voices were raised in opposition.
That was the time for the people in Congress and the media who are
now second-guessing to speak up; that was the point of no return.
</P>
<P>
   What about people who have not been focused on the Balkans
through this decade _ who have not gone through the phases of
dealing with Milosevic? Some are understandably mystified and
skeptical. One caller to a talk show said he gets worried any time
Washington and the media start ``demonizing'' somebody (Milosevic).
</P>
<P>
   There is a third group: People who were focused on the Balkans
even before the 1990s. Ohio Sen. George Voinovich is one of those.
His Serbo-Slovenian ethnicity _ similar to that of many people
around Cleveland _ is the reason.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that Washington underestimates the power of Serb
nationalism, which he says the NATO bombing has now unleashed, to
the detriment of any hopes for surrender by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich's voice comes off as an antidote _ an instruction _ to
the prevailing notions of the NATO policymakers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, however, people like Voinovich dominated the foreign
policy of the West through the early 1990s, when the various Balkan
wars broke out. They said the Balkans are a cauldron, not of good
guys and bad guys, but of competing nationalisms, of ancient feuds
waiting to burst into flames at the strike of a match. They said
the West's approach should be neutrality. As evidence of Serb
atrocities in Bosnia mounted, the United Nations remained
even-handed, partly because it did not want to fan the flames of
Serb nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Only slowly and reluctantly _ as war raged on and on and reports
of atrocities became common _ did the West come to side with the
Muslims against their better-armed foes; eventually NATO bombed
Serb sites.
</P>
<P>
   The successful Dayton peace talks followed shortly thereafter.
Then the old detachment _ the old fears of awakening Serb
nationalism _ became unfashionable. After all, acting against the
Serb side had worked.
</P>
<P>
   Now NATO has gone back to that well. And, for all anybody knows,
this may be once too often.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, with Voinovich's general antipathy to
NATO's posture is that it leaves the West with nothing to do about
Milosevic as he planned the expected ``ethnic cleansing'' of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich's response to that charge would be that, although
negotiations were tried, they were tried badly. He says NATO
shouldn't have given Milosevic the ultimatum to accept autonomy for
Kosovo (enforced by NATO
</P>
<P>
   troops) or face bombing. In fact, however, that ultimatum was a
last-ditch effort to save the whole idea of negotiations; nothing
else had worked. And Milosevic had not rejected the idea of
autonomy, only the enforcement mechanism (NATO troops). So the NATO
position can't be called extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Given Voinovich's emphasis upon the importance of Kosovo to
Serbia, it should be explicitly noted that NATO was not asking
Milosevic to give up Kosovo. NATO never even wanted independence
for Kosovo. It wanted the kind of autonomy within Yugoslavia that
Kosovo had had for years before Milosevic removed it in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO hadn't insisted upon that, it's hard to see what its
position could have been, short of reversion to its former
passivity.
</P>
<P>
   How many times must that approach be discredited?
</P>
<P>
   Martin Gottlieb writes for the editorial page of the Dayton
Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
