<HEADER>
A8852 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN23-COX     04-22 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Left to ponder how such terrible things can happen in a place as
idyllic as this
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Immersed in the anguished looks, the bloodied children, the
armored police chop-stepping into position, we were at another
horror scene Tuesday. We are on-call emergency gawkers, never to
miss. And the satellite always delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Our children went to bed so immersed. We owe them a walk in the
park, and a dose of reality. No, not ``RealTV.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the odd things about such on-screen terror is the
striking realization, upon wrenching one's self away from the
screen, that the world is more peaceful than one's converter box
will relay. People coexist. They say ``excuse me'' and ``after
you.'' Except maybe in their automobiles, most are decent and
deferential. They play by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for Columbine High School, scene of the most gruesome
school incident ever. It is beautiful, inside and out. Its students
have all the attributes we value, the vitality, the camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Columbine seems idyllic by any standards, a getaway
school in a getaway district at the feet of Colorado's Front Range.
The dateline ``Littleton'' is a subtle misnomer. This is Greater
Denver, with suburban neighborhoods defined as much by outstanding
schools as any other thing.
</P>
<P>
   A place like Columbine, a place like Littleton, is where parents
of means can take their children so as not to be in among all the
problems associated with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, asked on TV Tuesday night if the
school had metal detectors at the doors, wasn't sure but assumed
not, and safely so. After all, he said, it's ``not an urban
school.'' It's away from all that urban danger, just like the kids
in rural Paducah, Ky., and Jonesboro, Ark., and those at
Springfield, Ore., or any place now labeled, ``Couldn't Happen
Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Guns in their hands
</P>
<P>
   Metal detectors would have saved no lives at Columbine High. The
gunmen _ gunboys _ decided it was a good day to die and to take
classmates with them.
</P>
<P>
   A Colorado National Rifle Association official asked for equal
time amid all the concerns about the armaments of these
executioners. The equal-time response: Guns aren't the problem.
Sure they aren't. Teens on boil are the problem. But teens on boil
with ready access to firearms are a problem that will send shock
waves around the world.
</P>
<P>
   From petty to calamitous
</P>
<P>
   What we must acknowledge about what happened at Columbine,
however, was the excruciating universality of it. Disenfranchised
teens, outcasts, the brunts of jokes, hating those who are exalted
as special.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the boys' racism and the search for a shocking cultural
hook _ Hitler in this case, Teutonic techno-rock. Outcasts of every
era have found ways to distance themselves even further from the
pack. These boys found a doozy.
</P>
<P>
   What a fever the teen years can be _ the focus on what happens
any day as the end of the world, the amplification of a petty
dispute into life-or-death fodder. It's common enough to see young
people take their own lives without fully explaining. In this case
we see two who did it and invited company.
</P>
<P>
   They were the bad guys, and they killed good guys. But one
wishes that in their frantic quest to be different, to offend, they
wouldn't have been given any more fuel for their explosion, that no
one had made fun of them and accentuated their differences.
</P>
<P>
   We hurt each other in so many ways. Even good people do. We
cause divisions. Indeed, we crave them. Generally, away from the
TV, these divisions never cause physical harm, only drift. But on
every street corner, in every classroom, the conditions are there.
One day at another crime scene we'll be left gawking.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. . E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
