<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8856 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN23-COX     04-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School voucher bill likely to fade
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Rep. Barry Telford (D-DeKalb) says using money
from public schools for vouchers to private schools ``hurts them
both.'' The private schools have to submit to state controls and
testing, and the public schools lose badly needed cash.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, Telford told an anti-voucher rally in front of the
Capitol last week that he strongly opposes them.
</P>
<P>
   Telford's comments have added weight because he is chairman of
the House Calendars Committee, which sets bills for House floor
debate.
</P>
<P>
   There is a saying in lawmaking circles about ``an idea whose
time has come.'' But in Texas, school vouchers may be an idea whose
time never quite came, and now may be receding.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher proponents, led by the likes of San Antonio
multimillionaire James Leininger, have tried to change the minds of
legislators _ or beat those who oppose vouchers. Leininger and Co.
pumped millions of dollars into state representative and other
races _ including an attempt to beat House Speaker Pete Laney and
legislators who support him for speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Laney won anyway. He hasn't forgotten that voucher supporters
provided much of the opposition to his re-election. This year, the
usually noncommittal Laney has been outspoken against vouchers,
including a recent speech before the Texas Daily Newspaper
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The money that Leininger and others laid down included a
guarantee on a $1.1 million bank loan to Republican Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry in the final days of the campaign to help cement his victory.
Perry repaid the loan before taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Perry recently has made it clear to some members of the Senate,
over which he presides, that he has a strong interest in seeing a
voucher bill reaching the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to teachers and public-school administrators,
voucher opponents include some private schools, which don't want
the state controls and testing proposed to go with them.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Sen. David Bernsen (D-Beaumont) said he's against
vouchers despite legislation that would limit eligibility to
low-performing students in low-performing schools in major urban
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's explained to me how you take money from public
education and make it better,'' Bernsen said.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, the voucher project's Senate sponsor, Education
Committee Chairman Sen. Teel Bivins (R-Amarillo) acknowledged he
still was short of the two-thirds vote of the Senate necessary to
bring up the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 15 Democrats in the 31-member Senate, voucher opponents
have claimed 12 firm votes against bringing the measure up _ though
Sen. Mike Moncrief (D-Fort Worth) backed off the list late last
week. Even so, 11 senators can block the two-thirds present and
voting that's necessary to get a matter to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor could wait until one or more of those
votes are absent and bring the bill up then. And one voucher
opponent, Sen. Greg Luna (D-San Antonio), has missed several Senate
sessions because of health problems. But even then, at least one
Republican senator, John Carona of Dallas, is openly against
vouchers
</P>
<P>
   Perry said vouchers will come up _ one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have a debate on it in the Senate _ and a
vote,'' Perry said. If he can't bring up the Senate bill, the
debate will happen ``in some more unique fashion,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   That means by approving an amendment to another bill from the
House _ which would require only a Senate majority, rather than
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   House voucher proponent Rep. Ron Wilson (D-Houston) tried to
amend a bill two years ago to add vouchers. It narrowly failed. Is
he looking for another bill to amend this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' Wilson responded, smiling. ``Going to find one,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators don't want a vote because however they vote is
bound to anger some of their constituents. And an anti-voucher vote
puts a target on their backs for Leininger and friends to spend
money against their re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But Louis Bacarisse, a lobbyist who added the anti-voucher
effort to his client list this year, says he'd welcome a vote, in
both the House and Senate, because he thinks vouchers would be
voted down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Bacarisse said. ``The sooner the better. I've
got other stuff to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com or 445-3644.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
