<P>
   N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKTAB-HEMINGWAY _ Larger than life when alive, Hemingway
became a giant when dead. On the 100th anniversary of his birth
this summer _ June 21 _ Hemingway fans can enjoy a feeding frenzy
on new books about the man whose goal in life was to write one true
sentence. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 25
</P>
<P>
   BOOKTAB-ELLISON _ Writing a first novel that becomes a classic
can be a blessing and a curse. There's instant acclaim, but intense
pressure to write an even better second book. Margaret Mitchell and
Harper Lee didn't even attempt to top their spectacular debuts.
Ralph Ellison died trying. Forty-two years after ``Invisible Man''
was published, Ellison was still reshaping and rewriting his
sprawling manuscript when he died in 1994. Sidebar at bottom of
file. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 25
</P>
<P>
   BOOKTAB-PROULX _ Annie Proulx isn't easy. Little she writes
about smacks of the familiar. Where so many authors create worlds
that are instantly recognizable, Proulx goes where few others
would. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 25
</P>
<P>
   BOOKTAB-MASON _ Q&AMP;A with Bobbie Ann Mason, author of ``Clear
Springs: A Memoir.'' (Weaver, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 25
</P>
<P>
   BOOKTAB-NABOKOV _ On the centenary of his birth, Vladimir
Nabokov has never thrown off the criticism that his novels and
stories were those of a dilettante _ intricate, interesting in the
way chess puzzles are interesting. Critics expected an emigre from
the Soviet Union to write tracts about tyranny in the form of
fiction. Nabokov was utterly resistant. ``I write for the sake of
the pleasure, for the sake of the difficulty,'' he told an
interviewer. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 25
</P>
