<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   YELLING-EXCERPTS _ The ability of children to manage anger and
handle conflict is a topic of conversation in the wake of the
school shootings in Colorado. Cox News Service is excerpting a new
Longstreet Press book that addresses the conflict issue, ``Tired of
Yelling.'' Preschoolers learn reading readiness. Elementary
schoolchildren spend hours every week on math and English. Teens go
to soccer, Scouts, or piano lessons. Yet, in many cases, no one
teaches our kids one of the most valuable lessons of life _ how to
get along with other people. ``Tired of Yelling'' is the textbook
for that lesson. Dr. Lyndon D. Waugh offers the 15-step model he
developed during years of practical application that can give
parents, educators and children the ability to manage anger and
handle conflict. Dr. Waugh is co-founder and co-director of the
Atlanta Area Family Psychiatry Clinic, where he has had a
prestigious practice in child, adolescent, and family psychiatry
since 1977. The book is written with Letitia Sweitzer. Cox News
Service is excerpting this book in five parts, all of which are
moving today. (An image of the book jacket is available. The
excerpts also will be featured on the CoxNet weekly Science &AMP;
Health page for the next five weeks.)
</P>
<P>
   Part 1: The Defensive Child
</P>
<P>
   Part 2: The Right Words
</P>
<P>
   Part 3: Content and Process
</P>
<P>
   Part 4: The Perspective Check
</P>
<P>
   Part 5: Think, Talk/Listen, Solve
</P>
<P>
   SPA-ATHOME _ Feeling tired, stressed out, overworked from trying
to do too much? Then stop. At least for one hour, to pamper
yourself. Relax and rejuvenate your body with a spa treatment in
the comfort of your own bathroom. We have advice from some of the
top spas in metro Atlanta about what to do and what products to
use, when you want to re-create the spa experience at home. (Hill,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EARTHDAY _ Study from Use Less Stuff/Michigan State/National
Consumers League shows one easy way people can save money and help
the Earth: Buy 10 common things, like soft drinks, cereal and
pasta, in the least massive containers (i.e. cereal in bags instead
of boxes). Waste reduction promises to hit home even harder, as
cities go to various pay-as-you-throw schemes, which charge
homeowners based on the amount of garbage they produce. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH CHART. MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ICELAND _ REYKJAVIK, Iceland _ ``Why Iceland?'' people
said when they heard I was headed to this unlikely destination. So
I'll tell you. At two in the morning, as the Northern Lights
performed the world's most fantastic light show in the Icelandic
heavens, I forgot the lateness of the hour and the Arctic cold. The
night before, I had watched the world's most fantastically
beautiful people madly dancing with delicious abandon in one of
Reykjavik's hottest nightclubs. In three nights I got a total of 11
hours of sleep, and you know something? I didn't care, because it
was wonderful, glorious, entrancing, and I'd go back _ I will go
back _ to this island of savage, unearthly beauty with savagely
beautiful inhabitants who can at will shed their exquisite civility
for the bacchanal. Kim, w/Ivansco pix.(Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) .
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ICELAND-NIGHTCLUBS _ REYKJAVIK, Iceland _I hate to
interrupt couples while they're doing mouth to mouth and exchanging
some major saliva. But I really wanted to talk to this particular
Icelandic couple, and they hadn't come up for air in about five
minutes, so I figured they could use an oxygen break. ``What are
your names?'' I asked, and the girl looked at the guy and shrugged,
and said, ``What's your name?'' That was pretty much par for the
course on a Saturday night in Reykjavik. In truth, Reykjavik's
clubs vary little from those of Miami or New York _ or Atlanta. But
clubbing in Iceland does have a certain exotic aura. Maybe it's the
unusually steep proportion of beautiful people, maybe it's that
they dress and dance better than Americans. Or maybe it's that
these people are descended from Vikings, not Puritans. (Kim,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 25.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ICELAND-TOPOGRAPHY _ Twenty minutes, we had been told,
but in less than ten my eyes had adjusted sufficiently to the
darkness to register wisps of green luminescence gently wafting
across the night sky. It was the aurora borealis, known as the
Northern Lights when seen from the globe's northern latitudes, and
it was the grand finale to a marvelous day of sightseeing in the
Icelandic countryside around Reykjavik. Iceland has an uncanny
ability to mesmerize. Called the land of fire and ice, Iceland
possesses awesome, almost surreal landscapes of soul-penetrating
desolation and stirring beauty. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 25.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ICELAND-IFYOUGO _ You cannot travel on the cheap to
Iceland. You can only travel less expensively. The best way to do
that is via one of Icelandair's special packages, which include
hotel and round trip airfare from a number of U.S. cities. We took
the ``Spring Break in Reykjavik,'' which cost about $500 per
person, and provided just enough time for us to develop a taste for
Reykjavik and the lovely surrounding countryside. (Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
