Nabokov has never thrown off the criticism that his novels and
stories were those of a dilettante _ intricate, interesting in the
way chess puzzles are interesting. Critics expected an emigre from
the Soviet Union to write tracts about tyranny in the form of
fiction. Nabokov was utterly resistant. ``I write for the sake of
the pleasure, for the sake of the difficulty,'' he told an
interviewer. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
