14th graf
 &HT;    PORK BARREL POLITICS IN ISRAEL: SOVIET IMMIGRANTS PIVOTAL IN
ELECTIONS
 &HT;    700&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHKELON, Israel _ As a middle-aged deli worker who's skeptical
of politics, Tatiana Vilansky seems like an unlikely king maker.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in a land of Hebrew speakers, but talks politics in
her native Russian. On the job, she serves up pork salami in a
country where pork is shunned by religious customs and, in some
cases, official law.
</P>
<P>
   But the 45-year-old immigrant from Belarus is in demand because
she has not decided who she prefers in Israel's upcoming elections.
Political activists have called on her about five times, as hungry
for her vote as her customers are for her sliced ham.
</P>
<P>
   That is because, as their numbers swell, Vilansky and other
immigrants from the former Soviet Union might decide the future of
Israel's leadership. Most favor Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
but candidates see a large slice of the immigrant vote is still up
for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the candidates are shaping their messages to the immigrants'
tastes on everything from the peace process to the question of just
how Jewish Israel should be.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, for parliament and prime minister, is May 17. A June 1
runoff is likely in the prime minister's race. The so-called
Russian voters (they come from Russia and other former Soviet
republics) are key.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all means, the Russians are important for the elections,''
said Vilansky's boss, Riva Kalichman, 50, an immigrant from
Moldavia. ``There are many of us and we have power.''
</P>
<P>
   After just eight years of heavy immigration, people from the
former Soviet Union now number more than 1 million of Israel's 6
million population. They are still arriving at a rate of more than
4,000 a month and they make up more than 15 percent of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   They have already changed Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Former Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky, now Minister of Trade
and leader of a political party for immigrants, says that the
influx doubled the number of engineers, teachers and scientists in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Many delight in Russian treats like pork chops and vodka. They
read more than 15 local Russian newspapers and watch television
beamed directly from Russia. They have formed four of their own
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   They backed Yitzhak Rabin when he won in 1992 and Netanyahu when
he won in 1996. Polls show over 50 percent of them still favoring
Netanyahu, known by his nickname ``Bibi.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ashkelon and Ashdod, neighboring coastal cities with more
than 80,000 immigrants from the former Soviet Union, voters
announce their choice in Russian -- ``Dah (yes) Bibi'' -- and wear
ball caps with Russian letters stating, ``Vote for Benjamin
Netanyahu.'' Most like him for his reluctance to hand land over to
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But polls also show 20 percent of the immigrants undecided,
double the rate among other sectors of Israel. The more than
100,000 votes at stake is triple Netanyahu's victory in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last elections we knew how to vote, but this year we
are in a dilemma,'' said Marina Solodkin, one of six Soviet
immigrants in the Israeli parliament.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the immigrant community is changing. Of the more
than 820,000 arrived since 1990, more than 150,000 are new since
the last elections in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In general, both groups have had trouble finding jobs to match
their skills and have been disappointed with Israel's schools.
</P>
<P>
   They are also angry at government policies that require rigorous
documentation of their Judaism in order to qualify for legal
marriages and burials in Israel. They complain of discrimination by
police.
</P>
<P>
   But, their political desires are still enigmatic. Solodkin says
her party polls weekly to find out what its voters want.
</P>
<P>
   They seem to be savvy and open-minded, but still view Israel's
mainstream Labor Party, headed by candidate Ehud Barak, as
reminiscent of the detested socialists from their homelands. They
don't like Israel's religious hardliners, but support a Netanyahu
government that gives the ultra-Orthodox great influence.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator seems to be land. Tiny Israel is barely
as large as the Moscow region alone and immigrants don't want it to
get smaller, as it likely will under the Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are real hawks. They are against the peace process,''
said Mina Tsemach, an Israeli pollster. ``For the first time in
their lives the have their own territory. It belongs to them and
they don't want to return it.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky said the Russians will vote for their own immigrant
parties for parliament, hoping to address their domestic concerns.
Then, they will vote for security and the right-wing for prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   But, Sharansky's own party has stayed neutral on the prime
minister's race, refusing to endorse his boss, Netanyahu. He says
there is opportunity for Barak or Center Party candidate Yitzhak
Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to seize on that, Barak earlier this week hinted that
he would appoint a Soviet immigrant to run the country's interior
ministry, the ministry that carries out the controversial policies
on immigration and religious identification.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments, Barak noted that he recently shared Passover
dinner with a Jewish immigrant soldier from Russia whose mother was
expelled from the country apparently because she was not Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Netanyahu has courted Russian voters via their
homeland, Russia. Though he has long urged the United States to
sanction Russia on suspicion that it aids weapons programs in Iran
and Iraq, Netanyahu recently traveled to Moscow seeking to mend
fences.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face irked American officials, but not as much as
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon's comments questioning the wisdom of
the U.S.-led NATO bombing of Yugoslavia, a position apparently
aimed at Russians in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In a home for immigrant senior citizens in Ashdod, the move did
not impress Eliana Kurnina, a 66-year-old from Moscow. She called
Sharon's statements a ``pre-election trick,'' adding, ``He needs
the Russian voters.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said she will still vote for Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
