<HEADLINE>
HOUSEHOLD HINTS FROM THE FIRST LADY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Hillary Rodham Clinton &LR; 's ``An Invitation to the White House,''
a detailed account of the rollicking good times in the first
family's home, will be published by Simon &AMP; Schuster this fall. A
contract for the book was signed way before Clinton was mentioned
as a possible senatorial candidate and before the recent White
House scandal broke, at the same time that she agreed to do last
fall's ``Dear Socks, Dear Buddy: Kids' Letters to the First Pets.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, which will be cookbook-sized, will include anecdotes
about visits by heads of state, details of private parties and
accounts of holiday celebrations at the White House. Its
illustrations will include photographs, menus and invitations;
recipes for at least 30 dishes are to be included.
</P>
<P>
   In the footsteps of recent non-cooking cookbook authors  &UR; Jane &LR; 
 &UR; Fonda &LR;  and the  &UR; Duchess of York &LR; , the first lady, who once angrily
told the press that she was not the sort to stay home and bake
cookies, ``is not pretending that she cooks this food or sets the
table,'' said  &UR; Carolyn Reidy  &LR; of Simon &AMP; Schuster. Nonetheless,
readers will learn what to serve the prime minister of China should
he drop by their homes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Egg magazine asked  &UR; Chris Isaak &LR;  to free-associate on the
devil. ``All dressed in a latex suit with a tiny erection, he wants
to be evil,'' said Isaak, ``but he's not really up to it. I laugh
at the devil _ there's nothing to fear because God outweighs him.
People fear him because of that latex suit. And it's not so much a
bad fear; you just don't want him to touch you, like somebody with
bad breath and sticky fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In ``Awakening to the Sacred: Creating a Spiritual Life From
Scratch'' (Broadway Books; $26),  &UR; Lama Surya Das  &LR; provides
``ancient Eastern wisdom (to) help improve your Secretary's Week
workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you inspiration. You want to do a couple of hit
movies, so that maybe, someday, you can have something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Movie director Richard Donner on the source of his
inspiration, a stroll through Rupert Murdoch's Beverly Hills
mansion, for sale for $19.5 million. Donner was quoted in the New
Yorker.
</P>
</TEXT>
