<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8968 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-MOOD-TEX     04-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-MOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEMINGLY SECURE COMMUNITY STRUGGLES WITH SHOCK OF KILLINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Mike Collins was shuttling his son between
the orthodontist and middle school, a routine errand for parents in
this affluent community, when a tide of fleeing students abruptly
swept away such suburban sureties as straight teeth and safe
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stopped in the middle of the street and asked a kid what
was going on,'' said Collins' wife, Kristie. ``He said, `Somebody's
shooting everybody at the school.' And then it got worse from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   More terrible than the sight of terrified Columbine High School
students was the final result of the rampage that set them running:
more than a dozen dead, including the two gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   The worst school shooting in U.S. history, the attack would have
been shocking anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But residents here say they cannot fathom how such a tragedy
unfolded in their quiet community on the Front Range of the Rocky
Mountains, an area with strong schools and such family-oriented
public policies as extensive open-space initiatives and
hike-and-bike trails.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five percent of Columbine High School graduates attend
college, and their mean SAT scores break 1,000, according to the
school's Web site. Located outside the city of Littleton, in view
of snow-capped Rocky Mountain peaks, the school serves students
from a rapidly growing, unincorporated area of southern Jefferson
County, on the southwestern fringe of metropolitan Denver.
</P>
<P>
   About 90,000 people live in the area known as ``South JeffCo,''
where the population has nearly doubled since 1980. Houses worth
$200,000 and $300,000 are the norm, and median household income is
$70,000 to $75,000, said Nick Morgan, a long-range planner with the
county.
</P>
<P>
   ``People move here because of the open-space programs and
schools,'' Morgan said. ``It's the last place people would think a
tragedy like this would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As a classroom volunteer in area elementary schools, Mary
Mattison said, she knows firsthand that even children from affluent
homes can be neglected or troubled. ``It doesn't matter what the
demographics are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she thought the rampage was particularly shocking
because it tore through such a seemingly secure community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here,'' she said, ``it's stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   South Jeffco residents are struggling with their grief and shock
in ways as predictable as lowered flags, as poignant as a
seventh-grade girl clinging to her mother's hand on a shopping
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 17-year-old son has let me hug him, even this morning, and
it wasn't like, `Get away from me,''' said Karen Baird, whose son,
Tavis, hid in a science room for two hours before escaping.
</P>
<P>
   At a grocery store a few miles from the high school, a woman
sobbed as she loaded sacks into her car. Two normally garrulous
rock radio disc jockeys spent the morning urging parents to talk to
their children and vice versa. A local TV reporter broke down on
the air.
</P>
<P>
   A 13-year-old athlete vowed that he will never again wear a
baseball cap, one of the criteria police say the assailants may
have used to choose victims. A 16-year-old junior said she will
never return to the high school, which a few of her friends had
fortuitously ``ditched'' Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd throw up,'' said Amanda Lamontagne, 16.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Gibbs, a retiree from nearby Englewood, felt compelled to
call his son after hearing about the attack, even though he could
not have been in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 29 years old and lives in San Francisco,'' Gibbs said.
``It was just that feeling of security. My wife teaches first grade
and she was just bawling all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the tragedy itself, people here are unsettled to find
their community suddenly swarming with international media. They
are used to Denver, their big-city neighbor about 20 miles to the
northeast, making headlines, but that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting at Applebee's eating dinner watching President
Clinton talk about Littleton,'' marveled the Rev. Brad Berglund, a
Baptist pastor from Englewood. ``All of a sudden the whole world is
focused on Littleton, this sort of snoozy, upscale part of town.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people were able to carry on with their activities without
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   At a store a few blocks from the school, Mattison, the classroom
volunteer, struggled to pick out a birthday card for a son who
turns 18 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a zombie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She broke into tears talking about the slain students whose
bodies could not be immediately recovered because of homemade bombs
littering the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's babies are lying like rag dolls and no one can get
there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattison also expressed concern for a friend whose two sons
attend Columbine. No one had been answering the phone at their
house, and she feared the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said she intended to carry on with plans to make her
son's birthday special, cashing in frequent flier miles to take him
on a quick surprise trip to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I need to celebrate his life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
