<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are stories the Kansas City Star is offering for April 22,
1999:
COLORADO SHOOTING COVERAGE: GOTHS: The first reports of the
Littleton suspects were that they were part of the ``goth'' crowd,
but later accounts showed they leaned more toward right-wing
extremism. Nonethless, local goths lament that once again, they
have been portrayed as dangerous and unstable. They fear that
others will continue to treat them poorly - just as classmates said
others mocked the Denver suspects. A look at the realities and
misperceptions behind the goth subculture. Oscar Avila. 18ish
w/photo.
NRA: More about the growing problems of the NRA which wanted to
hold a national convention in Denver. Scott Canon.
DEATH: Youth disconnect regarding death. What leads people like
these young shooters to become completely disconnected from the
concept and reality of death? To have no regard for their own lives
or the lives of anyone else? To be unable to empathize with others
about death, dying or suffering? We talk to theologians,
psychologists and others about this phenomenon. Ed Eveld. With
CHECKLST. List of danger signs indicating a teen may threaten
serious trouble.
EXCEL: Excelsior Springs, Mo., High School today holds a mock
intruder drill because of the Littleton, Colo., tragedy. The school
puts a sign on someone that says intruder. School officials see how
long it takes for someone to report the intruder to the office. The
school has done this in the past as a security precaution, but the
recent event prompted officials to hold it again. Jerry Berrios.
10. Photos.
GUNS: For years, people thought nothing could be done about drunken
driving, but then a bunch of mothers got mad and changed society's
perceptions. Some people wonder when Americans will get fed up with
gun violence and say `We're mad as hell, and we're not going to
take it any more?' 25. Richard Espinoza.
CON: Violence experts say schools must adopt and encourage conflict
resolution programs to stop incidents like Littleton. A number of
area schools have such program. To show how the programs work,
we're trying to set up an interview with a counselor and two
students who've used the program. TBA.
VICTIM: We'll try to round out a story about the teens who were
shot in Littleton, Colo., now that some of the names are coming
out. Rick Montgomery. 30.
OTHER OFFERS: QUAKE: Researcher at University of Missouri-Columbia
reports his findings in Science magazine that the New Madrid
earthquake fault in Missouri's bootheel probably won't witness an
8.0 earthquake for another couple thousand years. Turns out the
hype about the possibility of a huge earthquake in Missouri was
just that -- hype. But there still could be a 6.0 quake in
Missouri's future _ and such a quake could cause serious damage and
cost lives. Lynn Franey. 25 inches. w/ photo from the Web, locator
map, and fact box of highlights from New Madrid Fault history.
DRIVE: A year ago, three Blue Valley High softball players died in
a wreck on their way to practice. It was one of three fatal wrecks
involving BVH students last year. In response, several students
created a presentation on safe driving. We watch it Thursday
morning at a middle school. Christine Malamanig. 18 inches. .MDNM/
MERGE: The Missouri Public Service Commission and the Missouri
Office of Public Counsel file their testimony on the proposed
merger of Western and KCP&AMP;L. The testimony is expected to be
critical of the union. Steve Everly
BLOCK: H&AMP;R Block acquires a sixth accounting firm. Gene Meyer
UMB: UMB releases first quarter earnings; annual meeting and proxy
report. Charles R.T. Crumpley
TENTATIVE OFFERS: NATO: Washington, D.C. braces for NATO's 50th
anniversary celebration, which begins Friday and will virtually
shut down the entire city for the weekend. It will be the largest
gathering ever of world leaders in Washington. David Goldstein. 30
inches.
NHIST: NATO's 50th anniversary celebration will be overshadowed by
the failing war in Kosovo, but the organization's birth was not
without controversy, either. Promoters of NATO had to overcome 150
years of isolationism dating to George Washington's warning about
entangling alliances with Europe. But the aggressive Soviet Union
was the concept's best salesman. With map showing evolution of NATO
membership. Brian Burnes. 25 inches.
</P>
