<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GE-SHAREHOLDERS-HNS &LR;      04-22 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GE-SHAREHOLDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE CHIEF WOOS STOCKHOLDERS, BUT RETIREES SEEK SLICE OF PIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY MILLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The theme at the annual meeting of General Electric
Co. shareholders could have been ``taking big swings.''
</P>
<P>
   Some were taken by chief executive John F. Welch. Others were
taken by dissident shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Welch used the phrase to describe the strength of his diverse
company, whose 1998 revenues topped $100 billion for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one decisive advantage a big, global company has (is) the
ability to take big swings in the pursuit of growth,'' Welch said
Wednesday in his closing remarks to about 2,000 shareholders,
retirees and securities analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said the company used its size in 1998 to spend $21
billion on 108 acquisitions. The big swings in those buys, he said,
were the $15 billion in acquisitions in economically troubled
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Welch drew applause from the audience as he recounted the
financial results of the year _ a 13 percent growth in earnings to
$9.3 billion and record results for operating margins and total
return on capital.
</P>
<P>
   The company's ``Six Sigma'' quality improvement margin came in
for considerable praise from Welch. He credited the 3 1/2-year
program with saving the company $750 million and extolled its
potential to increase company sales and market share.
</P>
<P>
   After Welch spoke, shareholders who had put their own issues
before shareholders trooped up to two microphones to expound on
their proposals. Helen Quirini and Hank Antonelli from Schenectady,
N.Y., spoke in favor of a shareholder proposal that raised the
issue of pension payments.
</P>
<P>
   Quirini, who is president of International Union of Electrical
Workers Local 301 retiree group, asked that the company use
pension-fund surpluses to grant annual cost-of-living increases to
long-time retirees. Retirees estimate the surplus at $16 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Quirini and Antonelli were among about 50 retirees, mostly from
Erie, Pa., who picketed quietly outside the entrance of the
International Exposition Center in suburban Brook Park before
entering the meeting. Most wore yellow T-shirts with the message,
``GE _ Bring Good Things to Retirees _ Please!'' on the front.
</P>
<P>
   Quirini, 79, said that when she retired in 1980, after 39 years
with the company, she began receiving pension payments of $444 per
month. The pensions of more recent retirees are higher, because of
a higher earnings at retirement and the way base retirement pay is
computed.
</P>
<P>
   Quirini had no increase in her retirement for 11 years, until
1991, when the company boosted it to $480 a month. Now, after
several more increases, it is $576 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pension fund has a huge surplus, and it's a shame that
such pitiful pensions are still being paid to earlier retirees,''
she said. ``Make us whole again, Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonelli, who worked for GE in Schenectady for 44 years, added
that while he and other retirees appreciated the past pension
increases, ``Our fund certainly can support substantial payouts
without jeopardizing its solvency.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch responded by describing the issue as ``a no-win
discussion.'' He said the company is living up to all its
responsibilities to its retirees, who number 190,000, but that it
also had to consider the future needs of its 276,000 employees.
Then, referring to his own impending retirement in two years, Welch
added, ``I'll be out there with you in three or four years.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Quirini called the response ``disgusting.''
The measure was defeated, but it received more than 29 percent of
shares voted, a significantly higher affirmative vote than any
other shareholder proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Other shareholder issues focused on environmental issues. Three
proposals questioned the company's commitment to environmental
concerns, particularly in the Hudson River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nuns from several Catholic orders questioned a recent study that
found no connection between exposure to polychlorinated biphenyls
(PCBs) and cancer deaths. Others urged the company to cooperate
with the Environmental Protection Agency's review of the PCB issue.
</P>
<P>
   Welch defended the company's environmental record in his
prepared remarks, saying the company spent $2 billion in the last
decade to comply with environmental regulations ``and going beyond
them to voluntarily improve the air, water and soil in the
communities in which we operate.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a recent study of workers in upstate New York _ the
fifth undertaken _ reached the same conclusion as others: ``There
is no evidence that PCBs cause cancer in people.'' None of three
environmental proposals received more than 8.4 percent of the
shares voted.
</P>
<P>
   GE used PCBs for about three decades as an insulator in electric
capacitors. The company legally discharged more than one million
pounds of the chemicals into the Hudson River before the chemicals
were banned in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The company _ and Welch in particular _ have been highly
regarded by shareholders and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a half hour before the start of the meeting, Welch
stood outside the meeting hall surrounded by reporters and largely
admiring shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Some asked for autographs and others, including several
retirees, thanked him for improving their financial circumstances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
