<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUN-EMPLOYERS-HNS &LR;      04-22 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUN-EMPLOYERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNMEISTER URGES EMPLOYERS TO LOOSEN UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ It's Matt Weinstein's job to have fun at
work.
</P>
<P>
   As the founder of Playfair in Berkeley _ his job title is
``emperor'' _ Weinstein has been telling companies for decades that
making the workplace fun will make the company stronger.
</P>
<P>
   In a new book, ``Work Like Your Dog,'' Weinstein and Luke Barber
describe the benefits that large and small companies derive from
making work more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes so much sense,'' Weinstein said in an interview,
``yet it's one of those disconnects in people's brains.''
</P>
<P>
   He said more companies are realizing that making work fun is one
way to retain good employees, which is crucial because of the low
unemployment rate, but many are reluctant to change age-old company
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes a story about Jim McGory, who worked in
corporate sales for a major airline. His boss told him that
although his numbers were excellent, he wasn't acting in a
professional manner: He was always the first one to take off his
jacket at meetings, and the boss would hear him laughing when he
was talking on the phone with customers.
</P>
<P>
   McGory explained that the reason he did so well was because he
treated customers like friends, but the boss wasn't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ```Jim, you have to remember that in business, perception is
reality,' responded his boss. ``If people hear you laughing, then
they won't believe you're doing a good job.'''
</P>
<P>
   McGory started his own business, and told Weinstein what he
recalled about his old boss: ``I remember that he didn't understand
me at all. But the main thing that I remember is that he forced me
out the door and forced me to become a millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its title, the book does not carry the ``Work Like Your
Dog'' idea to extremes. One short chapter does, however, describe
how guide dogs and other working canines can teach human workers a
lot of lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They approach their work not only with dedication, loyalty,
discipline, sensitivity and love, but also with joy, enthusiasm and
happiness,'' Weinstein writes. ``If you want to increase your
abilities in this area of study, spend a few hours this week in the
company of a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein writes that managers often don't understand that
people will work harder if they know that doing well will allow
them to have some fun. He describes how Kirt Womack, who works at a
plant that makes booster rockets, persuaded his supervisor to let
workers have a paper airplane contest if they reached 150 percent
of their quota by 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By 2:30, they had reached 210 percent of their quota.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all celebrated by going outside and jubilantly flying
their paper airplanes,'' Weinstein writes, ``and when Kirt asked
his manager what he thought of their accomplishment, his manager
churlishly replied, `If you can produce this well with an hour off,
imagine how much more you could get done if you actually worked
that hard for the whole shift.'''
</P>
<P>
   But when Womack proposed the same sort of reward the following
week, the manager had a change of heart. ``After the team handily
trounced its quota once again that day, it began to dawn on Kirt's
supervisor that the days with the highest productivity were the
days when Kirt's team was having some organized fun together.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Weinstein said that having organized fun is
far easier in companies with enlightened management, but even
rank-and-file employees can make work better by spending their
breaks having fun. Here are some of the favorite activities he has
come across:
</P>
<P>
   _ Having secret pals.
</P>
<P>
   For a period of two weeks, give each participating employee a
secret pal, a co-worker who tries to do something nice for the
person each day, like putting chocolates in her desk or sending
flowers to his wife. If the company doesn't provide any money for
the program, agree on how much each person should spend during the
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Creating a ``stress-free day.''
</P>
<P>
   Have a masseuse walk through the office giving free neck and
shoulder rubs all day. Have a bootblack give free shoeshines and
have someone in the parking lot to give free carwashes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establishing a swearing room.
</P>
<P>
   A company did this, putting the swearing room next to a
trainer's office. Prizes were awarded to employees who came up with
particularly creative curses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dressing as a favorite holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said that Women Inc. in Sacramento, Calif., had just
such an event, with people dressing as the Easter Bunny or Cupid.
</P>
<P>
   One woman showed up with pillows stuffed under her dress.
</P>
<P>
   She was Labor Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
