<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROMOTION-$ADV25-COX     04-22 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROMOTION-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHICAGO'S BAN ON SOCIAL PROMOTIONS MAY BECOME NATIONAL MODEL
 &HT;    700&AMP;add. With PROMOTION-DATA for release Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Last June, Monica Turner failed eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of more than 25,000 grade-school students in Chicago
who were held back, and like most of them, she had failed to score
high enough on Iowa Tests of Basic Skills in reading and math.
</P>
<P>
   Monica became a beneficiary _ or a victim, some would say _ of
the city's ban on social promotions, the widespread practice of
keeping all but the worst students with their own age group.
</P>
<P>
   And if President Clinton can persuade Congress to make a similar
ban a condition of receiving federal education aid, there could be
millions of Monicas from coast to coast within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, one-fourth of the city's third-, sixth- and
eighth-graders were ordered to go to summer school last year for
courses in arts, sports, reading and math.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them did go. In August, more than half of them passed
both Iowa tests and were promoted.
</P>
<P>
   But Monica, who passed only the math test, was among the 12,152
who were held back once again.
</P>
<P>
   In January, she flunked the reading test for the third time. As
of April, according to the Chicago Public Schools, 7,568 of the
children still hadn't been promoted.
</P>
<P>
   School officials are coy about how many have dropped out, were
pushed out, or transferred to other school systems. Most, like
Monica, are still plugging away.
</P>
<P>
   On a cold, rainy Thursday in late April, parents and guardians
collected their children's latest report cards at Sengstacke
Transition Center, one of nine special schools for eighth-graders
15 or older who haven't qualified for high school.
</P>
<P>
   Monica's card showed passing grades in high school-level courses
and in her double-period course in reading, which takes 100 minutes
a day. She was feeling a lot more confident than she did a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   When she takes the reading test for the fourth time in May,
``I'm going to hit this test,'' Monica said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley is proud of the students who
persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't say the kids are dumb,'' Daley said. The mayor, who
needed three tries to pass the exam that allowed him to practice
law, said, ``I flunked the bar twice and I'm not dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before 1995, they socially promoted children. It was the easy
way out for adults,'' Daley said. ``The children got into eighth
grade and they just moved them into high school, and then it was,
'What are we going to do? Let's just give them this diploma.' ``
</P>
<P>
   He said social promotions had horrifying effects: eighth graders
promoted to high school while reading at the third-grade level, and
high school juniors reading at the fourth-grade level.
</P>
<P>
   Half who began high school dropped out before graduation. Of the
graduates who were admitted to Chicago's colleges and universities,
96 percent had to take remedial reading courses.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino of Boston, a friend of Daley's who also
appoints his city's school board, doesn't have as much faith in
standardized tests. He says some well-educated students, like some
candidates for teaching posts, just happen to freeze up on tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much emphasis on testing,'' Menino said. ``You
know what it is? It's a good mechanism for politicians to beat up
teachers and students.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Chicago, children who are held back get lots of expensive
extra help. The city offers summer school, extra teachers, remedial
specialists, smaller classes, test-taking courses, after-school
programs and tutors drawn from from colleges, businesses and the
ranks of retired teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago voters also approved a $2 billion bond issue that Daley
is using for replacement or renovation of the city's tattered old
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, all of Chicago's 431,000 school children will be
covered by a private or public health plan. Free eyeglasses will be
provided for the thousands who can't focus on the blackboard when
they are at their desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call it retention with intervention,'' said Cozette
Buckney, chief educational officer of the Chicago Public Schools.
``Our attendance is up, our dropout rate is down. Teachers are
working diligently to make sure the students are achieving their
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   However, new school policies might not deserve the credit for
those improvements or for a slight upward tilt in average test
scores, said Tony Bryk, co-director of the Consortium for Chicago
School Research. For example, teenagers in Chicago can't get
welfare assistance if they leave school; that may be why the
dropout rate among the city's 1,100 pregnant teens fell to less
than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents are upset about the city's tough promotion policy,
and others are indifferent, even though those held back include 42
eighth-graders who first failed the Iowa tests in May 1997. School
officials are considering admitting that group into special high
school classes if they fail one more time.
</P>
<P>
   But surveys and election results indicate that most parents
support Chicago's use of high-stakes tests to hold back students
who perform poorly and dump teachers whose students don't pass the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were coming up in life, they were just pushing you
through school,'' said Camilla Dickens, whose daughter also goes to
the Sengstacke center. ``My daughter is reading better than she was
before. Now she just has to pass the test.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was antsy,'' said another parent, Brenda Baker.
``But they have shown here that what kids thought they couldn't do,
they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 216 older eighth-graders who have been bused to the
Sengstacke center on the fringe of downtown Chicago since last
August, 72 passed the January tests and were promoted immediately,
57 transferred or dropped out, and 87 are preparing to retake the
tests in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reform changed the culture among students in (the worst) high
schools,'' said Fred Hess, director of Northwestern University's
Center on Urban Policy. ``More students are serious about their
work and not embarrassed by doing good work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, the attitude among the professionals toward reform
was, 'This too shall pass,' `` said Betty Dispenza-Green, principal
of Chicago Vocational Career Academy. ``Now everybody understands
there are repercussions, that there is accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   However, positive reports on Chicago's retention policy will
fade within a few years, predicted Ernest House, a professor of
education at the University of Colorado at Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they identify at-risk kids and that special
treatment early on, so they can avoid flunking them?'' asked House,
who charted the collapse of a similar experiment in New York City
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have all these lesson plans based on the Iowa tests, but
the kids will do worse when they give them other tests,'' House
said. ``Even worse, flunking a kid increases the kid's chances of
dropping out.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vallas, chief executive officer of the Chicago Public
Schools, said the city had to rely on the well-known Iowa tests
because nobody trusted the system's ``phony grades and phony
diplomas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think three or four years down the road, grades from classes
will carry much greater weight than they carry now,'' Vallas said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Monica Turner yearns desperately to pass the
reading test that is her only passport to promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice here, but it ain't where you want to be,'' she said.
``You want to get into a regular high school.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
