u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-SMUGGLE-BOS &LR;      04-22 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-SMUGGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERIL SEEN IN UNLAWFUL EXPORT OF REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ The name is whispered like an illicit drug.
``Skaf?'' the local men ask, using the Albanian for boat, as they
approach Kosovars in refugee camps to peddle a midnight ride across
the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Only some 1,000 of the 340,000 refugees throughout Albania have
accepted the illegal offer in recent weeks, paying approximately
$350 each for the rough sea journey to Italy, according to law
enforcement officials and smugglers themselves. Nearly half of the
Kosovars transported since March 24 have been caught on the other
side, only to be placed in Italian refugee camps like the ones they
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   But as warmer weather sets in and as the time since their flight
from Kosovo begins to lengthen, many more refugees are expected to
seep into the network of smuggling. That has long plagued the
Albanian coast, which has sparked massive political turmoil over
the last year, officials said. In a worst case scenario, thousand
of refugees _ already preyed upon in Yugoslavia _ are in danger of
falling victim to the violence of the local smugglers, who last
fall murdered at least one foreign refugee, or to the rough seas,
which claimed six lives in a single night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great concern for the situation,'' said Ylli
Vejsiu, a member of the Albanian Parliament. ``Fortunately, the
situation is under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it appears to be. According to one refugee smuggler
in the southern port of Vlore, from which the vast majority of
illegal immigrants depart, the main impediments to the trading in
Kosovar refugees have been bad weather and price. Most Kosovars
fled their homes without money or were robbed by Serb troops along
the way, leaving them unable to pay the fee _ even though many boat
operators have dropped their prices to accommodate the newcomers,
according to the smuggler, who agreed to be identified only by his
first name, Bashkim.
</P>
<P>
   And even for those Kosovars with enough cash, available boats
have been few, and freezing rains have made the Adriatic too rough
to cross, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is cold on the water,'' he said. Then he joked: ``But with
all the money we take, we should be hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bashkim, 25, a native of Vlore, says he runs what amounts to a
ferry service between Albania and Italy, with three partners. He
said he shipped several thousand people across the water each year,
departing from Vlore at 1 a.m. almost every night and arriving in
Italy an hour-and-a-half later. The showpiece of the operation is
his skaf, a rubber Yamaha boat with two 250-horsepower engines that
is big enough to seat up to 30 adults. And the product comes with a
guarantee: Refugees caught and returned to Albania within five days
are given their money back, their identities checked against
Polaroid photos Bashkim snaps before every trip.
</P>
<P>
   No Kosovar refugees have returned as yet, he said. And the
numbers have remained relatively low; Bashkim said he has
personally driven just one boatload of Kosovars in recent weeks,
transporting 28 adults and 8 children on April 8. Local officials
also believe traffic has remained steady, with no more than six
boats running each night.
</P>
<P>
   But few have forgotten the Albanian smuggling explosions of the
past. In the early 1990s, more than 100,000 fled the country's
Communist regime, causing chaos as they tumbled from the shores of
Durras into boats run by the Albanian and Italian Mafias. In 1998,
another wave of refugees fled the country's financial crisis at a
rate of 800 passengers a night, prompting an outcry nationwide when
several were killed. Last Oct. 22, smugglers robbed and beat an
Iraqi passenger traveling from Vlore, tossing his body overboard.
Three nights later, two speedboats collided, killing a half-dozen
refugees, including an 18-month-old baby and a 19-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Police immediately cracked down, and the Albanian government
earlier this year tried to remove the skafs from the water
altogether, passing a law against running boats that travel faster
than 20 miles per hour. But the effort has been nearly meaningless.
The Vlore police chief, Sokol Kociu, was held hostage by local
smugglers when he tried to confiscate the boats and was forced to
give them back. Earlier this week, Kociu was dismissed, reportedly
as a result of the political controversy surrounding the smuggling
rings.
</P>
<P>
   Italian officials have tried to pick up the slack, installing an
operations center on a small island off the coast of Vlore. And yet
there seems to be little anyone can do in and around the refugee
camps where Kosovars tell stories of having been solicited. In
Durras, refugees at an Italian camp were told they could flee to
Italy at a price of $350 each, according to Veli Raduni, 23, a
waiter from Djakovica, who said he declined. In Tirana, Valdet
Nila, 35, of Pec, told a similar story, saying a man found him near
a refugee camp two weeks ago and said, ``You need a skaf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm here. Here's my number,' '' Nila said. ``But I
said, I don't need the number because I don't need to go. I need to
go back to my home in Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
