<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING SOLACE, CLASSMATES GATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ If there was a sadder sound than the mournful
wail of a lone bagpiper in the Light of the World church Wednesday,
surely it was the quiet sobs of traumatized children mingling with
the notes of ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   They came by the hundreds to this Roman Catholic church a
half-mile west of the carnage at Columbine High School. They came
as much to purge themselves as to pray.
</P>
<P>
   In their baggy blue jeans and khaki cargo pants, they filled the
pews with pain as tangible as their tears.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver archbishop offered words of faith. The Colorado
governor offered words of comfort. But it was not until the priest
invited the students themselves to speak that they found solace in
one another. One by one they walked tentatively to the lectern to
bear witness to the terror they had seen and heard in the corridors
and classrooms of their suburban high school.
</P>
<P>
   Their voices thick with grief and exhaustion, teenagers who on
another April afternoon might have been discussing prom dresses and
graduation parties, stood up to speak of death and blood, gratitude
and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got up for school Wednesday, I wondered what I would
wear, whether I'd be hip to the ladies,'' said one young man who
later that day spent three hours cowering with 50 classmates in a
locked classroom. ``When you are listening to your friends being
shot, you find out quick what's important _ God, family, your
friends. I called my parents from my cell phone and I didn't know
if I would ever see them again. I wanted to tell them `I love you.'
''
</P>
<P>
   A student whose best friend died in the hail of gunfire told the
congregation that, in her mind's eye, she can see her lost
classmate smiling down from heaven. ``I know she would tell you
that heaven is beautiful, that our life here is just a little time
compared with eternity. Yes, it does hurt. I know that life seems
unbearable know. But I see her in heaven, saying, `Don't give up.'
She knows it's hard for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how hard was evident on the tear-streaked face of Eddie
Olsen, a senior and star athlete at Columbine. He told his
classmates he may never get over the guilt he feels, simply for
surviving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember running out of school to the sound of blasts going
off in the halls and screams coming from the library. Innocent
people died because they were trying to kill people like me,'' he
said, referring to Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, who are
said to have targeted their rage at popular athletes and the few
minorities among the 1,800-member student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry. I'm sorry I ran out of the building when I was
being targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling with a different sort of guilt were two high school
girls who counted themselves informal members of the Trench Coat
Mafia, the collection of misfits from which the gunmen sprang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, please, don't blame us,'' one girl named Nicole begged
her classmates. ``We didn't see any signs of this. We are so sorry
our friends did this to all of us. We had no clue this was going to
happen. To us, they were cotton-fuzzy, the sweetest guys in the
world. I would never have thought they could have done this.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither could 16-year-old Eric Veik. He met Harris and Klebold
last semester in a video production class. They wrote a screenplay
and acted in what Veik described as an ``action video,'' which Veik
turned over to police Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you looked at the video carefully, maybe there were some
subtle hints,'' he said. ``But the video can't explain anything.
Can't give us a motive. These guys weren't violent, but there was
always this physical tension toward other people. This spring one
of them said to me, it's time to plan a senior prank. I didn't
consider it to be any kind of threat,'' he said, choking back sobs.
``I thought they were just two normal people in school who wanted
to dress their own way and be individualists. They often walked
around as if they were macho guys. Everyone in the halls always got
out of their way.''
</P>
<P>
   Not always.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, 12 students and one teacher at Columbine High School
did not have that chance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
