<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FEAR OF ROAD RAGE ON THIS LONG COMMUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Somewhere, about an hour south of Kansas City,
Mo., daughters and sons of some 45 American daddies got shut out of
``Take Your Daughter (or Son) to Work Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other prohibitions, the dads have just too long of a
commute: 15 hours one-way to the skies above the Republic of
Yugoslavia; 15 hours straight back.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the expense. Each time one of the dads goes to
work, it costs the taxpayers of the United States about $441,000.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the seating problem.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the dads commute in a $2.2 billion jet plane, the
B-2 stealth bomber, there are only two seats: one each for two
pilots. If a daughter or son would be willing to ride in the cargo
hold (and if Mom would allow it), there still would be no room:
Every B-2 is stuffed to the gills with a dozen 2,000-ton bombs,
nicknamed ``bunker busters.''
</P>
<P>
   One nice thing though: The long-commuting dads are away from
home only one night. Because they never land their B-2s during a
mission (jet gasoline tankers fill 'em up in mid-air), they can
leave on a Monday morning, drop their bunker busters on Yugoslavia
and be back home by Tuesday to take in a daughter's ball game or a
son's school play.
</P>
<P>
   The above scenario may sound like a sequel to Stanley Kubrick's
1964 tour de force, ``Dr. Strangelove, or How I Learned To Stop
Worrying and Love the Bomb,'' but it is merely a slice of modern
American life.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, not in the late Mr. Kubrick's fantasies, almost four
dozen U.S. Air Force pilots _ most married with children _ commute
via B-2 from Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri to the ether above
the Balkans. In a chilling story by Thomas E. Ricks in the Wall
Street Journal, several unnamed pilots and their wives talked about
how ``weird'' and ``surreal'' it is to operate under such
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   One wife, whose pilot husband's birthday coincided with his
first combat commute to Yugoslavia, put a piece of celebratory cake
in the lunch she packed for him. Without a hitch, he made it home
the next day in time to see their son score his first-ever goal in
a soccer game. The wife allowed as how the experience was ``very
strange _ to drop bombs and then come home and watch my son's
soccer game.''
</P>
<P>
   A pilot who returned from his first mission to a kiss and the
command to ``mow the lawn,'' described his home-gathered K-rations.
</P>
<P>
   On the 30-hour mission, he ``went through two gallons of water,
a liter of Mountain Dew, half a bag of nachos, some chocolate.''
</P>
<P>
   Other pilots protein-load for their missions on the
``traditional `bomber dogs' _ hot dogs and chili _ warmed with the
heater just behind the second pilot's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all that long ago (the Persian Gulf War), U.S. bomber pilots
did not commute to combat. They were stationed for months on end in
the Indian Ocean. But that was before the B-2 saw bona fide action.
So advanced is the plane, the Air Force prefers to keep all of them
based at Whiteman; it's easier, and the security is better.
</P>
<P>
   So now, instead of fleeting phone calls, the wives of the B-2
pilots are telephoned in Missouri by Air Force personnel as soon as
their husbands have completed their bombing runs, are out of harm's
way and are headed for home.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots interviewed by Ricks said they did not take their
missions lightly. Just because they are allowed to live at home,
they said, did not make the combat runs ``antiseptic flyovers.''
</P>
<P>
   With technology this clean and efficient, however, who can rule
out a future in which even B-2 stealth bomber pilots participate in
Take Your Daughter (or Son) to Work Day? The kids would just love
those chili dogs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
