<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADCLIFFE-HARVARD-BOS     04-22 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADCLIFFE-HARVARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLIFFIES' LOOK BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They wore their hair in deliberate curls, high buns, and severe
parts. Black collars hid their pale necks, and stiff pleats flowed
like tents around their ankles.
</P>
<P>
   As 21 women from the Harvard Annex class of 1882 posed modestly,
the faint grains of a black-and-white portrait trapped them in
photographic amber. But the folded hands and lowered eyes disguised
the movement these women were spurring.
</P>
<P>
   It was an experiment that unleashed revolution inside the
nation's premier university: an independent women's college with
Harvard professors as its faculty. In a few years, Radcliffe
reached a level of excellence other women's colleges struggled to
match.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Adam's rib of its more powerful brother, Radcliffe
found itself in a constant push-pull bind with Harvard _ banned
from its campus, dependent on its faculty, obscured by its global
footprint.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle ended Tuesday, when Harvard announced it would
absorb Radcliffe and dissolve it as a separate college. The
Radcliffe name will remain as an ``institute,'' but it will give up
what few remaining holds it has on undergraduate life for women at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Radcliffe students are in a great state of shock,'' Maya
Sen, a junior and treasurer of the Radcliffe Union of Students,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tension over fund raising and real estate forced the change, in
part. But by making good on its century-old mission _ access to
Harvard for women _ Radcliffe also helped bring about its undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Graduates from decades past say something important will be lost
now that Radcliffe exists only as an institute. Future students,
they say, will never know the all-female bonds that grew out of
exclusion, or have the independent pulpit that once meant as much
to Radcliffe students as the privileges Harvard denied them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my day, we gathered at Agassiz theater for all kinds of
plays and songs, and we never thought about Harvard,'' said Alice
Johnson Brown of Chesterfield, Mo., who graduated in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``Because Harvard just wasn't that important to us. Sure,
we'd go over to Harvard Yard to meet boys for dates. But in those
days, we did not lean on Harvard as undergraduates.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, only alumnae of a fading era will remember Radcliffe as it
was at its moment of greatest independence. It was a segregated
world of curfews and gloved hands, but also one where student
government presidents, drama directors, newspaper editors, and band
leaders were women.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Radcliffe girl carries feminism and feminity in almost
equal balance. It's enough to upset anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   _a Harvard professor to an interviewer, 1951
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the benign sentiments of Radcliffe's founding ladies _
who never wanted coeducation, only the chance to mold pupils into
enlightened wives and mothers _ turmoil has rocked Radcliffe
throughout its history.
</P>
<P>
   Once the ``annex maidens'' proved they could match the men grade
for grade, Radcliffe found itself in an awkward position: forced to
choose between protesting inequality and quietly pushing forward
the goal of higher education for women.
</P>
<P>
   In that balancing act, it carried a burden no other womens'
college shared: a never-ending obligation to please the country's
most prestigious university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radcliffe was always careful to keep Harvard happy with them,
so that as an institution, it ended up being very conservative,''
said Dorothy Howells, 1960 graduate and author of ``A Century to
Celebrate: Radcliffe College, 1879-1979.'' ``There were political
issues the college just shouldn't get into. It was seen as
unlady-like.''
</P>
<P>
   That caution extended to the outside world, making for an odd
contradiction. Reluctant to offend its powerful older brother and
rock their delicate arrangement, Radcliffe's managers towed a
conservative line against some of the very social movements being
pushed by its more radical alumnae.
</P>
<P>
   Like almost every other womens' college at the turn of the
century, Radcliffe opposed women's suffrage. But it nurtured
genteel defiance in women such as Maud Wood Park, the first
president of the League of Women Voters. Dressed in white linen and
a wide-brimmed hat, the 1898 alumna stood over a leather chair
inside the House of Representatives as congressmen signed a woman's
right to vote into law in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   By 1930, Radcliffe had produced a pioneering suffragist and a
founding member of the NAACP. In the next 40 years, it would
graduate a Pulitzer Prize-winning poet, a member of Congress, and a
prime minister of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But whether its students tapped softly against closed doors or
barreled headlong into them, they always found their way back to
Radcliffe Yard, a campus that began as an appendage but emerged as
a full-fledged community, where women were the best athletes and
the brightest thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a company of women, and starting after World War I, it
really came into its own identity,'' Howells said. ``The doors to
Harvard were shut, and what do you do when the door is shut? You
develop your own community. And as that community developed, women
developed a strong allegiance to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth ``Bucky'' Helman, class of 1943, said the Radcliffe she
remembered handed down strict rules on chaperones (no lenient older
brothers) and forbade pants (they broke the rule once, allowing ski
pants during a brutal storm).
</P>
<P>
   But it was also a place where women took on the male roles in
Greek plays, operated their own radio station, and led their own
choral society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radcliffe Yard was jumping,'' Helman said. ``I mean, it's a
serene place now, but back then, there were students spilling out
all over the lawns . . . We felt we had the capability of doing
whatever we wanted to do. We were encouraged in this, and we would
attack things.''
</P>
<P>
   When Helman was a student, war had pushed women to hold on to
the jobs men had left in order to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring that struggle, Harvard was flirting with coeducation.
By 1943, Harvard opened all courses to women and moved toward more
merging of the two schools. But Helman was already making daily
treks to Harvard Yard, having negotiated her way into a previously
all-male, graduate biology class.
</P>
<P>
   Though she and other women excelled in those courses, Harvard
still did not grant them equal status on many fronts. While men
freely roamed the stacks of Widener Library, Helman and her
classmates were confined to a single room. To retrieve a book, they
had to hand a slip to a male ``runner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows what they thought we were going to do to those men
on our way to the card catalog,'' said Helman, former president and
trustee of the Radcliffe Alumnae Association. ``The bottom line
was, we had to wait longer for books.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Howells was a senior, in 1960, the contradictions
were more flagrant. Classes were fully coed, and women were allowed
to enter Widener. But they were not allowed to use the newer Lamont
Library. Suddenly, the movement to fully infiltrate Harvard was on.
</P>
<P>
   But with every push, the bonds Radcliffe graduates had forged
with each other over generations loosened.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Phyllis Lugger entered Harvard College in 1972, one of the
first orientation meetings she attended was sponsored by Radcliffe
College. Nervous as they began their freshman year, Lugger said,
the gathering of women without men seemed even more awkward, almost
unnatural.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us a Radcliffe mug and talked about maintaining our
Radcliffe identity,'' said Lugger, now an astronomy professor at
the University of Indiana. ``But for the women that I knew, I don't
think there ever was a bond to Radcliffe as an institution. We
didn't want there to be any difference between us and the men. We
wanted to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the student protests in the 1960s and '70s, men
and women at Harvard were much more the same than they had ever
been. From sit-ins at Harvard Yard to invasions of Radcliffe
offices, the war between men and women gave way to wars between
students and administrations. And most of the women who arrived on
Harvard's campus had not sought out a Radcliffe identity, yet found
themselves bound by the rules of an archaic charter _ the
transcripts they sent to graduate schools still said ``Radcliffe,''
not ``Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   Female students seemed ready to shed their Radcliffe ties and
fight their battles at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the gender battles that continue to rage at
Harvard are subtler than those of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Conflicts over diversity and the lack of tenured female faculty
still plague the school; some say the conflicts have discouraged
women from pursuing certain fields. But almost all agree the merger
that Radcliffe in part brought about has closed the door on an era
of male domination at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Now, alumnae say, Radcliffe faces a challenge as tough as its
pioneering mission of education for women excluded from Harvard: to
stay relevant as a resource for Harvard women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radcliffe hasn't been a college in a really, really long
time,'' said Lugger. ``The most important thing it can do right now
is to keep building on its incredible network of women, and help
the young women who continue to seek it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
