<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEEDY SIDE OF GARDENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dee Dee, our all-purpose advice columnist, is shocked by the
results of a survey conducted by a British gardening magazine. It
revealed that one in four women prefers gardening to sex.
</P>
<P>
   Only one in four? Is it possible? Dee Dee would have guessed it
was more like three out of four. Because everywhere she turns all
anybody talks about is gardening, gardening, gardening.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only Wednesday that all anybody talked about was
sex, sex, sex. Maybe it was only Wednesday because, as the contents
of Dee Dee's mailbag indicate, sex and gardening raise similar
issues. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   My husband has given me an ultimatum. I must choose between him
and my compost heap. He says I lavish all my attention on my
compost at the expense of his needs. I have tried to cut back on
composting, but compost requires constant attention. Like
lovemaking, it cannot be rushed.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any way to save my compost and my marriage?
</P>
<P>
   SuperHot, Sharp Sand, R.I. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself: Do I really want to spend my life with a man who
doesn't understand my compost? Dee Dee thinks the answer is
obvious. However, if you feel you must try to salvage the marriage,
Dee Dee advises you to read ``The Joy of Compost'' together. This
may help him see that his needs, and yours, too, must come second
to your compost's. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   My boyfriend wants me to share my garden fantasies. I feel it is
far too soon. We have known each other only two years. Last night,
in bed, he asked me to describe my preferences in ornamental
shrubbery in more detail than I thought appropriate. I told him I
wasn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   He says that unless I am willing to share my most intimate
horticultural thoughts, our relationship is doomed. What should I
do?
</P>
<P>
   Shrinking Violet, Dormant, Vt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tell your boyfriend in no uncertain terms that you are saving
your garden fantasies for marriage. If he refuses to accept that,
it's best to end the relationship now before you do something you
may regret. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   Believe me when I tell you that I never meant to stray. But I
wasn't getting the satisfaction I needed at home, so I foolishly
became involved in a neighbor's garden. I began spending more and
more time in her prize-winning perennial beds, at the expense of my
own modest plot.
</P>
<P>
   That's all behind me now. But my wife says she can't trust me
and has forbidden me to set foot in our garden. The grounds are
looking seedy and the children are beginning to ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   Faithless, East Ragwort, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee thinks you're being too hard on yourself. Your wife
needs to see a therapist who specializes in horticultural issues to
help her work through her unreasonable jealousy. As for the
children, it's never too early to learn the facts of gardening
life. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   My wife feels uncomfortable experimenting with anything even
slightly out of the ordinary, so I have had to put my plans for a
water garden on hold. She says she feels ``uncomfortable'' with the
idea of turning our back yard into a half-acre pond complete with
waterlilies, ducks, frogs, islands, ornamental fountains, schools
of koi, canoes, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Is she narrow-minded? Or am I asking too much?
</P>
<P>
   Submerged, Poxweed, N.H. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee thinks it's no wonder almost one in two marriages ends
in divorce. Remind her that she pledged herself to you for better
or for worse, and that Dee Dee says ``worse'' includes a water
garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
