<HEADLINE>
DECIPHERING THE HEART SYMBOL ON FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA STEVENS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What does the American Heart Association logo mean on food?
</P>
<P>
   A: A food packaging that carries the logo _ a red heart with a
white check mark _ means the food has no more than 3 grams of fat
per serving, 20 milligrams of cholesterol and 480 milligrams of
sodium. The food must also contain at least 10 percent of the daily
value for one or more of the following nutrients: protein, vitamin
A, vitamin C, calcium, iron, or dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Products that carry the logo aren't necessarily better than
products without it, according to Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many cups of cooked barley does one cup of uncooked make?
</P>
<P>
   A: One cup of uncooked barley yields three cups of cooked
barley. Can't eat that much all at once? Store the unused cooked
barley in an airtight container and refrigerate. It will keep for a
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
