<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PUTTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTS USUALLY THE DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes memorable putts sidebar)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many of us have stood over a simple 3-foot putt, a $5 Nassau
on the line? All that has to be done is to roll the ball in, but
you stare at the ball and dart your eyes to the cup, which seems to
be shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   You back away, look at it from one side, then the other. You
walk behind the hole and check it out for a second time. You grit
your teeth. You begin to kick yourself for not getting the first
putt closer to the hole, in gimme range.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can feel the dagger-like stare of your partner piercing
your back. You won't look him in the eye. You won't look at your
opponents, either. You just know they are smiling, believing there
is no way you are going to sink this putt.
</P>
<P>
   If you make it, all those weak irons, pop-up drives, and stubbed
chips are forgiven. If you miss it, you figure you wasted four
hours on a beautiful Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you stand over the putt. You pick your line, take a
deep breath, pull back the putter, and strike the ball. It rolls,
and . . .
</P>
<P>
   Do you sink the putt? Sometimes you do and sometimes you don't.
</P>
<P>
   There are a thousand reasons why you may have missed it. Average
weekend hackers make a little more than half of the 3-footers they
face. PGA Tour pros sink 95 percent of their 3-footers.
</P>
<P>
   But that means PGA Tour pros, the best players in the world,
miss 5 percent of their 3-footers, a statistic that almost seems
inconceivable given their talent.
</P>
<P>
   Putts are either the bane or the salvation of every golfer
because, as Billy Casper once said, ``There are two kinds of
putters, those who find a way to miss it and those who find a way
to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's like style. Either you have it or you don't. Although there
are no born putters, there are plenty of golfers who seem to have a
knack for knocking in putts when it matters. Putting theories are
similar to one of those philosophical debates, such as how many
angels can fit on the top of a pin. There is no right answer or
wrong answer. Putting is an abstract. Some will argue that it is an
art _ a black art. Others believe it is a science that can be
quantified and analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, putting is also the most important part of the
game. There are several ways to move the ball down the fairway to
the green. Just look at all the different swings that work, from
Jim Furyk's to Tiger Woods's.
</P>
<P>
   But once you get to the green, it is an entirely different game.
</P>
<P>
   Perfectionist Ben Hogan was blunt about it. He said putting
simply was not golf. Sam Snead said as much when he attempted to
use a croquet-type stroke that the US Golf Association quickly
outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   More putters are broken in anger than any other club in the bag.
However, those who putted well, like the late Bobby Jones, and Ben
Crenshaw in his prime, humanized the flat stick by giving it a name
like Calamity Jane or Little Ben. But many abuse the putter. Ky
Laffon, a colorful Depression-era professional, often punished his
putter by dragging it along the highway while driving from one tour
stop to another.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer has gone through more putters than Imelda Marcos
has had shoes. He has a garage full at his Florida home. If Palmer
ran through putters, Johnny Miller has taken another route. He has
tried countless putting stances and strokes over his career. During
the 1973 Hawaiian Open, he was paired with Jack Nicklaus and
noticed the Golden Bear's stroke. Nicklaus had his right elbow way
out. Miller tried it ``and the floodgates opened.'' In 1973 Miller
won the US Open, shooting a record-breaking 63 at Oakmont. The
following year he adopted another putting routine and won eight
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest putting tip can turn around your game, and such
enlightenment can come from anywhere. Kenny Knox set a PGA Tour
record by taking just 93 putts during the 72-hole Heritage Classic
on Hilton Head Island, S.C., in 1989. He credited his amateur
partners from the Wednesday pro-am, telling the media: ``In trying
to ascertain why these high handicappers pushed and pulled their
putts, I noticed that they lifted their heads just before impact.
That head movement led to body movement, which in turn caused the
putter head to stray.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus picked up a putting tip while watching television in
the clubhouse after his final round at the 1966 Masters when he
tied Gay Brewer and Tommy Jacobs after 72 holes. ``My putting
ranged from average to awful all week and I'm just about to leave
the clubhouse and work on it,'' Nicklaus told the press. ``CBS was
replaying the 17th hole, where I missed the cup entirely from 3 1/2
feet, and I saw that I was moving my head at impact.'' Nicklaus
literally ran out to the practice green and resolved his putting
problems. The following day he won the 18-hole playoff.
</P>
<P>
   As important as putting is, one rarely sees amateurs work on
their strokes.
</P>
<P>
   They will invest time and money on the driving range, hitting
countless buckets of balls and taking lessons from professionals so
that they might hit it 10 yards farther off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   But they spend just a few minutes on the putting green as they
wait for the foursome ahead to vacate the first tee.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that 43 percent of all the shots on the PGA and LPGA
tours are putts. If a professional shoots 70, he takes about 30
putts a round. As for amateurs, if they shoot 85, they average
around 35 putts, and if they shoot 95, they take about 38. If you
can putt like a professional, that would knock more strokes off
your score than 10 extra yards off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``Putt Like The Pros,'' Dave Pelz quantified how
well the players on the LPGA and PGA Tours putt. For example, pros
make 95 percent of 3-footers, but the numbers quickly drop off.
They make only 50 percent of 6-footers; 30 percent of 10-footers;
20 percent of 15-footers; 12 percent of 20-footers; 10 percent of
25-footers; and 7 percent of 30-footers.
</P>
<P>
   Putting simply wins tournaments. When Woods won the Masters by
12 strokes in 1997, he was the only competitor to survive all 72
holes without a three-putt. This year he was nowhere to be found.
He took 126 putts, second most (to Vijay Singh's 127).
</P>
<P>
   There is no right way or wrong way to putt. But practice is a
key.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus and local favorite Brad Faxon are among pros who have
had artificial putting greens installed in their backyards. Both of
their practice putting areas were built by Form Technology/Symmetry
Products of Lincoln, R.I., which is one of the world's largest
artificial putting green companies. Besides providing backyard
systems for avid putters, they have built million-dollar miniature
golf putting surfaces on luxury ocean liners, such as the Royal
Caribbean and the Princess Cruise Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Good swing thoughts are vital. The late Harvey Penick in his
``Little Red Book,'' suggested that one concentrate on the line on
short putts, but on long putts, one should concentrate on distance.
Penick suggested that the putter be carried in your left hand (if
you are a righthander) for feel, because the arm is an extension of
the putter shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Penick said to never allow yourself to think about what is
riding on the putt, whether it is a major championship or a $2
Nassau. Fuzzy Zoeller agrees, saying the biggest obstacle keeping
amateurs from being good putters is fear, especially when there is
something on the line. Timid putts usually are missed.
</P>
<P>
   When Tom Kite left for the PGA Tour, Penick gave him a final
word of advice. ``Go to dinner with good putters.'' The reason?
Good putters talk about what putts they are going to make, or great
putts they have made. Bad putters complain about the tough
conditions and say there are some putts that are impossible to
sink. It is a matter of attitude.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RECORD PUTTS . . . THE LONG AND SHORT OF IT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some putts have been defining moments in the history of golf.
Jack Nicklaus's birdie putt on No. 17 at Augusta National set up
his Masters victory in 1986. Crenshaw drained a 60-footer on the
10th hole at the Masters that sparked his ride to victory in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   There are putts that lose championships as well. Scott Hoch
never will live down the 18-inch putt he missed on the first
playoff hole that cost him the Masters in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Shorter putts have been missed. Bruce Lietzke tried to backhand
a 2-inch putt at Colonial and semi-whiffed. This gaffe cost him a
playoff berth. Hale Irwin tried to backhand a 1-inch putt in the
third round of the 1983 British Open and missed. He finished one
stroke behind eventual champion Tom Watson at Royal Birkdale. Andy
Bean could have won the 1983 Canadian Open, but he tapped in a
2-inch putt with the grip end of his putter and was assessed a
two-stroke penalty. He missed getting into a playoff by two
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The longest putt ever sunk in competition, according to Golf
Digest, is 140 feet. It was drained on the 18th green of the Old
Course at Saint Andrews, Scotland, during the International
Four-Ball Pro-Am in 1976. Nick Faldo holed out the longest putt in
the history of the Masters, when he won the tournament in 1989.
Faldo sunk a 100-footer for a birdie-4 on the second hole during
the third round. This feat bettered Cary Middlecoff's record eagle
putt at the 13th hole of Augusta National in 1955. He also won the
tournament that year.
</P>
<P>
   The longest putt in PGA Tour history was a 110-footer made by
Nicklaus in the 1964 Tournament of Champions at the final hole at
the Desert Inn CC in Las Vegas. It gave him a two-shot victory over
Doug Sanders and Al Geiberger, who were standing by hoping Nicklaus
would three-putt and extend the tournament to a playoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
