<HEADLINE>
GOOD SALADS DON'T HAVE TO BE GREEN AND LEAFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no law that says salads have to contain leafy greens.
And in addition to tuna, chicken and potatoes, there's a whole host
of foods you can use as the basis for a good salad. Not the least
of which is grains.
</P>
<P>
   Start with a package of long grain and wild rice pilaf, toss in
a few colorful and flavorful additions such as nuts, raw vegetables
and cheeses, then bind the dish with dressing for a salad good
enough to be a lunch entree or dinner side dish.
</P>
<P>
   But don't limit yourself to rice. Wheat berries, quinoa, barley
and amaranth are also perfectly good salad starters. If you want,
you can even combine grains. A supermarket down south sells a salad
made of long-grain and wild rice mixed with wheat berries. It's
flavored with almonds, dried cranberries and orange peel for a
crunchy, nutty, zesty mixture.
</P>
<P>
   The keys to a successful grain salad are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pre-mixed grains, such as rice pilaf mixes, usually cook
faster and more consistently than if you buy the different grains
individually.
</P>
<P>
   _ If using a rice pilaf or other grain mix, try to find one
where the seasonings are package separately from the grain. This
way, you can control what kind and how much seasoning is in the
salad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vary the texture of the ingredients. Since most grains cook up
relatively soft, mix in some crisp ingredients such as raw bell
peppers, grated carrots, minced celery or nuts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make it colorful. The more colors in your salad, the more
nutrients you'll be including. For orange or red; add bell peppers,
chile peppers, carrots, dried cranberries, dried apricots, orange
sections, melons, mangoes or tomatoes. For yellow, add corn kernels
or bell pepper. For green; add scallions, green beans, snow peas,
parsley, bell peppers or jalapenos.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toast nuts to bring out their flavor. Simply place a nonstick
skillet on the burner over medium heat. When pan is hot, add nuts
and toast, shaking occasionally for a few minutes until the nuts
begin to give up their aroma and turn darker.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add heavily flavored cheeses such as crumbled blue or feta.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use oil and vinegar based dressings _ either bottled or
homemade _ instead of creamy dressings. Experiment with flavored
vinegars such as berry or tarragon vinegars to complement the
ingredients or substitute fruit juice for half the vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   _ Combine the ingredients while the grain is still warm but only
mix in half the dressing. Just cooked grains will absorb more
dressing than cold grains. Reserve part of the dressing to add
fresh flavor just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chill for several hours to allow the flavors to marry but let
sit at room temperature for 30 minutes before serving for best
flavor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
