<HEADLINE>
PLUGGING INTO THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As birthdays go, the 29th lacks the glamor that goes with a
number ending in zero. But for Denis Hayes, who has been nurturing
Earth Day since its inception in 1970, this year's anniversary has
been commandeered as the launching pad for a really big event next
year, one replete with zeros. Hayes wants Earth Day 1999 dedicated
to a national goal of deriving a quarter of the nation's energy
needs from the sun. It is a worthy ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, president of Earth Day Network, wants to make the country
_ and the world _ more aware of the burdens rich industrialized
nations place on a fragile and changing environment.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the problem is the ominous certainty of global
warming, for which there is, in Hayes's words, ``overwhelming
evidence.'' That makes it imperative to stop the steady release of
carbon dioxide into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes's pragmatic approach deserves careful attention. His
specific objective is a reduction of the cost of photovoltaic
energy _ produced when sunlight is converted to electric current _
by two-thirds of its present level of $5 a watt. That can be
achieved, he contends, by a subsidy program that would increase
demand and add to productive capacity. Economies of scale, he says,
would lower costs to levels no longer requiring subsidies, making
it possible to reach the target of replacing a quarter of
carbon-based fuels by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sensible approach that would not lower anyone's
standard of living or even rule out continuing use of fossil fuels.
America is the appropriate leader to undo some of the collateral
damage from its consumption practices. The United States, with
about 4.5 percent of world population, consumes 25 percent of the
world's oil and is a similar glutton with other resources. Earth
Day is the time to focus on changing that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0165 </DOCNO>
