<HEADLINE>
ALOHA! A MARINADE FOR ALL SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Occasionally you find a recipe that's so easy, so flexible and
so universally devoured by everyone who tastes it that it becomes
THE recipe for all entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   In my house it's a teriyaki marinade my mother and I discovered
during a trip to Hawaii. And it's perfect for grilling, even when
it's still too chilly to dine outside.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple.
</P>
<P>
   Combine 1/2 cup soy sauce, 1/4 cup bourbon (I'm not kidding), 2
cloves crushed garlic, 1 tablespoon grated gingerroot, 2
tablespoons brown sugar and a dash of dry mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve 1/4 cup of the marinade and use the rest of the mixture
to marinate chicken, pork or a London broil for at least two but
not more than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Grill the meat as you normally would, basting occasionally with
the reserved marinade. The chicken will be nicely browned, not
charred, if you cook it slowly for 45 minutes to an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the cooking time, throw some pineapple slices
on the grill and brush them with the marinade, too. Add a rice
pilaf and pretend you're in the islands for dinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
