<HEADLINE>
HASBRO BELIEVES THE FORCE IS WITH IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can the Force propel a stock already near its all-time high?
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Inc., the Pawtucket, R.I., toy company riding the wild
success of Furby, will find out. A barrage of Hasbro toys and other
products tied to ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' go
on sale May 3, more than two weeks before the opening of the movie
itself.
</P>
<P>
   People are already camping out near California theaters waiting
to buy movie tickets. Anticipation about the merchandising power of
the most eagerly anticipated movie in recent memory has the toy
industry buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be the biggest toy story of the year,''
said Chris Byrne an independent consultant and author of The Toy
Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Force has to pay the Tab. Hasbro has agreed to cough up
at least $590 million in four advance payments in toy royalties
over the next decade for rights connected to the three films in the
``Star Wars'' prequel era about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro, the nation's number two toymaker, paid the first
installment of $100 million last year. When The Phantom Meance
premieres on May 19, Hasbro chief Alan Hassenfeld will write a
check for another $250 million. Other advances are due upon the
release of the two remaining film trilogy ``episodes.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all: Hasbro has issued warrants for 5.7 million
shares to Lucas Licensing Ltd., excercisable at $28 each. Warrants
are securities that allow the holder to buy stock at a specified
price. Hasbro stock, riding the announcement of strong first
quarter earnings, hit an all-time high of 32 15/16 this week. It
finished Wednesday 31 7/16 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To put that in perspective, consider that the new ``Star Wars''
film itself only cost producer George Lucas $115 million to make.
Hasbro thinks it is still getting a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant property,'' said John T. O'Neill, Hasbro's
chief financial officer. ``Obviously we expect an awful lot of good
things to happen from the licensing arrangement and, yes, good
things are expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how significant the toy rights will become is open to
widely differing estimates. On the high end of the range, some
people think ``Star Wars'' toy products can sell nearly $1 billion
this year as as much as $5 billion over the 10-year life of the
prequel era. All Hasbro sales totaled $3.3 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro officials declined to provide details about their new
``Star Wars'' line, but agree that it is their largest product
rollout ever. Games, toys, even interactive candy are in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   There will be more. One reason the ``Star Wars'' license is so
valuable is the large number of film characters, vehicles and other
figures that can be turned into toys. That means Hasbro can
continue to roll out new toys in the years between films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Hasbro is going to make a concentrated effort to pace
itself by holding some new product for next year and the following
year,'' said analyst John Taylor of Arcadia Investment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro has been selling ``Star Wars'' toys, based on the
original three films, for years under an old license. It was
awarded the license for larger toys tied to the new series and
Lewis Galoob Toys Inc. won a license for miniature products in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro bought Galoob last year and wound up with all the ``Star
Wars'' toy business, except for a small piece awarded to Lego Group
AG of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' success would represent another big score for
Hasbro, which has been on a roll. Its portfolio of hot lines, from
Furbies to Teletubbies and a fast-growing interactive games unit,
boosted first quarter earnings by 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The performance, achieved while top toymaker Mattel Inc. was
peparing to lay off 3,000 employees, added more fuel to a stock run
that has boosted the price of Hasbro shares by 60 percent since
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more going on than `Star Wars,' although it's
the single most visible thing,'' said Taylor. ``The whole operation
is running well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
