<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION GETS KICK BACK IN SAVARESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Giovanni Savarese's career with the Revolution could
not have started much more dramatically. The second time Savarese
touched the ball, he converted a goal, leading to speculation that
he would continue the rate which made him the MLS's second-leading
scorer in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Savarese has not produced a goal since the game against the
Miami Fusion on March 28, opening day. In fact, he has played only
13 minutes since then, after suffering an ankle injury in a
training match against the New Hampshire Phantoms March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Now Savarese is on the verge of returning. Though Savarese will
not likely be at full speed, the Revolution could use his
inspiration and offensive instincts for their visit to D.C. United
Saturday night. Since Savarese's goal, a rebound of a Joe-Max Moore
shot off the post, the Revolution have just three goals, and only
twice in the run of play, in 359 minutes 38 seconds of official
play.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive output has been better than opposition, as the
Revolution have established themselves as a potentially solid
defensive team. And their defensive play has been an especially
important point of reference during a stretch of two games against
D.C. United and one against Columbus, the top teams in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be going there to win the game,'' said Savarese, who
returned from a visit to his ailing grandmother in Caracas for
training at Babson College in Wellesley Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go in there and just play crazy. We have to have the
right mentality. But whether we are playing at home or away, we are
playing to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese was seeking a sort of second chance with the Revolution
after having been relegated to a reserve role with the MetroStars,
despite his dependability and dynamic scoring figures. In 85 games,
he scored 41 goals for the MetroStars, a strike rate of .488, one
of the best in the league. His quick start seemed a portent of a
positive future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a good sign,'' Savarese said. ``To be away
from home and score the first goal was great. Even though they
scored to tie the game, it was a good start to the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I got hurt, and I haven't been able to go full speed.
It's been frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution is not a direct part of the Carlos Valderrama
stakes. But they could be involved in a three-way deal, since Miami
has committed itself to dealing Valderrama, and Tampa Bay is the
logical taker. The Fusion refused a deal of Valderrama for Swedish
defender Jan Eriksson and Costa Rican forward Alejandro Sequeira,
demanding Bolivian midfielder Mauricio Ramos . . . Giuseppe
Galderisi was named assistant coach after acting in that role for
the Revolution's first two home games. Galderisi, 36, played in the
1986 World Cup finals in Mexico, and scored 38 goals in 156 games
in Italy's Serie A and another 50 goals in Serie B games. In the
MLS, Galderisi scored 12 goals in 48 games for the Revolution and
Tampa Bay . . . Tickets for the Revolution's July 21 exhibition
against Ajax of Amsterdam became available Thursday (April 22).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
