<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_ZINC FOUND TO REDUCE INFANT MORTALITY RISK  
 _SOBRIETY, COUNSELING TRIM DOMESTIC ABUSE  
 _MEDICATION BACKED FOR HEART AILMENTS  
 _WEEK WITHOUT TV? SOME MOVING ADVICE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Zinc found to reduce infant mortality risk &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving zinc supplements to children _ including low birth weight
babies _ can substantially reduce infant mortality, one study
shows, and can also dramatically lower the risk of developing
diarrhea and pneumonia, according to another.
</P>
<P>
   The studies were presented this week at a meeting of the
Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology.
</P>
<P>
   The first study, led by Dr. Sunil Sazawal, a pediatrician and
researcher at Johns Hopkins School of Public Health in Baltimore,
involved 1,250 babies in India weighing between 2 and 5 pounds.
They were divided into four groups. One group got a daily syrup
containing 5 milligrams of zinc; another got zinc plus vitamins and
other minerals; a third got vitamins and minerals but no zinc; the
fourth got a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure that the babies were given the proper medicine, a
public health worker visited every family every day, Sazawal said
in a telephone interview. The results were impressive: the two
groups that got zinc showed a reduction in infant mortality of
about one-third, perhaps because of zinc's ability to boost immune
function.
</P>
<P>
   In the second study, researchers pooled data on about 4,000
children from 17 studies and found zinc reduced the prevalence of
diarrhea by 25 percent and pneumonia by 41 percent. ``We need to
ensure that children get enough zinc,'' said Sazawal. For children
less than one year old, that is 5 milligrams a day; for older
youngsters, it is 10. Many get all they need from fortified
cereals, whole grains, meat, and beans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Sobriety, counseling trim domestic abuse
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence is often linked to alcoholism, and a study
shows that when a couple gets counseling and an abusive husband
stops drinking, the violence often abates. The study was led by
psychologist Timothy O'Farrell, director of the Counseling for
Alcoholics' Marriages (CALM) Project at the Brockton VA Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The team studied 75 couples in which the man was an alcoholic
and the wife was not. Before treatment, 60 percent of the men were
violent toward their wives, said O'Farrell, whose study is
published  &UR; today &LR;  in the Journal of Studies on Alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after treatment _ which involved 20 sessions of
couples counseling, plus a medication called Antabuse and/or
Alcoholic Anonymous meetings _ the prevalence of violence dropped
to 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For couples in which the man maintained sobriety _ which was
nearly half the sample _ only 3 percent reported violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Medication backed for heart ailments
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A study of 10,333 volunteers provides evidence for what doctors
have long assumed to be true: Blood-pressure medicine reduces the
prevalence of high blood pressure and of a heart problem called
left ventricular hypertrophy and may in part explain the 50 percent
decline in heart disease deaths since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   The research, from the Framingham Heart Study, tracked data from
1950 to 1989 and is published in the current New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Week without TV? Some moving advice
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ok, kids, you may not want to hear this, but listen up.
</P>
<P>
   Top health officials, including Surgeon General David Satcher,
have a plan. It's called TV-Free America and the idea is _ gasp _
to turn off the TV for a whole week starting Thursday (April 22).
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because obesity is at epidemic proportions. About 55
percent of adults are overweight or obese, government figures show.
More than 13 percent of children 6 to 17 are overweight and are
getter fatter each year. Moreover, research shows that the average
American watches three hours and 43 minutes of TV a day.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and the answer is: Get off the couch, turn
off the TV, and do something like ride a bike, play soccer, jump
rope, fly a kite or _ double gasp _ clean your room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
