<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-ADVICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PARENTS, A TIME TO TALK _ AND LISTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and l coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the biggest mistakes we can make as parents in dealing
with the Littleton, Colo., murders is to think or hope that our
children haven't heard about the tragedy and thus to say nothing.
This would send a message that it's unimportant or that we don't
care. It also leaves room for children to imagine awful
possibilities, including the scariest thought of all: ``This could
happen in my school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the fear children of all ages have and they all need a
chance to get it out,'' says Cornell University psychologist James
Garbarino, an authority on the impact of violence on children.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is not to say too much to preschoolers or too little
to adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   Preschoolers. Find out what he already knows, says psychologist
Diane Levin, a professor at Wheelock College. A good opener:
``There was something on the news about teenagers. Did you hear
about it?'' If your child says no, you could say, ``Some teenagers
got hurt, but everyone is taken care of now.'' If she says yes,
here are some points to make:
</P>
<P>
   --It happened in a place far from here. Children ages 3 to 5
don't have a good grasp of time and distance, so they personalize
details, says psychologist Susan Linn of the Judge Baker Children's
Center in Boston. Reassure them about their safety: ``Your school
is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   --It makes you sad. Sadness may be the only thing that
differentiates this event from violence they may see on TV. If we
don't talk about our feelings, it increases the likelihood that
children become accepting of violence.
</P>
<P>
   --You don't know why it happened. Levin suggests saying,
``People are working to make sure this never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   School-age. Even if you discussed it Wednesday, start a
conversation today: ``I`m wondering what you've heard.'' The 6- to
12-year-old's response can be confusing. She may grill you for
details, then run out to play. ``It's too threatening for them to
stay with the thoughts for long,'' says psychologist Sandra
Graham-Bermann of the University of Michigan. Don't push her to
talk, but don't be surprised if in a day she's fearful (``Will bad
kids come to my school?'') or angry (``Why couldn't adults stop
it?'')
</P>
<P>
   --Validate her feelings and share your own: ``I don't blame you
for being angry/upset/sad. I am too.'' Letting her vent can be a
source of comfort. Let her experience your compassion: ``My heart
goes out to those parents.''
</P>
<P>
   --Keep communication open. Answer honestly what you can but feel
comfortable saying, ``I don't know. If I hear more, I'll tell
you.'' If he's not talking, the third-person may be less
threatening: ``I know some kids worry about their school.''
</P>
<P>
   --Find truthful ways to reassure about safety. School vacation
this week could cause children to worry either more or less. Some
children may not be troubled today, but come Monday, they won't
want to go to school. Assume the refusal is related, says Linn of
the Judge Baker center. Say, ``I wonder if you're worried about
safety. Let's talk to the principal.''
</P>
<P>
   --Distinguish between behavior and dress. Because school-age
children think concretely, they may assume that anyone who wears a
black raincoat is a bad person. ``They need to hear you say that
(wearing unusual clothes) doesn't mean a person is bad,'' Levin
says.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers. Because of his age group's melodramatic impulse, a
17-year-old may say, ``I'm going to carry a weapon from now on'' or
``I'm dropping lacrosse because athletes were targeted.'' Don't get
caught up in it, says Garbarino of Cornell University; it's
probably masking worry and fear. The more you can tolerate what
they say with simple responses (``I know how you feel, this is very
scary''), the sooner you can get to the feeling itself. Also:
</P>
<P>
   --If your teen isn't talking, let him know you're always
available or that you hope there's another adult he'll talk to.
</P>
<P>
   --Watch TV with her, read the articles she reads, visit the same
Web sites. It can be a starting point for a conversation.
</P>
<P>
   --Share your feelings even if he isn't sharing his, including
worries about the spread of violence in our society.
</P>
<P>
   --Talk about peers who may be troubled and how to help them.
</P>
<P>
   Garbarino says that teens who are contending with other issues _
parents divorcing, a recent breakup with a girlfriend or boyfriend,
a death in the family _ need particular attention.
</P>
<P>
   With any child, he advises, have a family dinner tonight and a
moment of silence or a prayer. ``After the initial hunger for
information, kids need the chance to be reflective with you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara Meltz writes the Child Caring column for the The Boston
Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-WEB-CHAT-BO     04-22 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-WEB-CHAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES BUSY AS MANY SEEK OUTLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A family in Orem, Utah, sent out kind words and electronic
prayers. A free-lance Web designer in California set up an on-line
condolence board. Teen-agers in chat rooms alternated between
anger, despair, and tough-guy posturing. Harvard professor and
child psychiatrist Alvin Poussaint counseled parents and teens in a
live chat on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Wednesday, Web sites with the words ``trench coat'' in
their addresses were bombarded with hits Wednesday, despite the
fact that these sites had nothing to do with suspected killers in
Tuesday's Littleton, Colorado school rampage or with their group,
the Trench Coat Mafia. Rumors blanketed bulletin boards and dubious
news sites before being quickly swatted down by vigilant Web users.
And in Golden, Colorado, at the offices of the Jefferson County
Schools, an official worked to dispel such rumors and set up a
on-line resource center in the aftermath of the tragic shootings at
Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   As it has in other crises, the Internet was both a labyrinth of
misinformation about the shootings as well as a comfort zone for
concerned citizens. ``Please be careful about taking any
information about this event from unreliable Internet sources,''
warned John Adsit, who set up the site for the the county school
system. (The site is at
http://204.98.1.2/communications/crisis/crisis.html.) Adsit was
responding to a series of on-line hoaxes and rumors that emerged
instantaneously on-line, even as police and rescue workers were
still clearing the school building of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   On America Online, for instance, more than a hundred users
altered their member profiles to include references to the killings
and the Trench Coat group _ seeking to draw attention to
themselves. In addition, several news reports broke late Tuesday
about an AOL page alleged to have been posted by deceased gunman
Eric Harris, one of the two students who went on a wild shooting
rampage at the Colordo high school. The address for the AOL site,
which is posted on many electronic discussion groups, has been
removed from the server, but it is said to have featured pictures
of the kind of pipe bombs used in the Tuesday's attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working with the FBI since (Tuesday) night, and
our folks here pulled content to preserve some information they
thought was relevant to the case,'' said AOL spokesperson Kim
McCleery.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other site was pulled from the Internet Wednesday,
and others posted disclaimers. An adult entertainment site with an
address that seemed affiliated with the fringe group received so
many hits Wednesday it temporarily suspended its business and
posted this message: ``This site has nothing to do with the Trench
Coat Mafia...I'm just as disturbed and saddened as the rest of you
about the events that transpired in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Internet users aimed to inflame the tragedy even as it
was still unfolding. In the discussion group
alt.motorcycles.harley, a user who used the handle Queen Jeff
alleged that the attack had been unleashed by ``gay bikers''
seeking revenge. The user posted the message via the popular
on-line service Dejanews.com. ``We are a very democratic site, and
we don't alter content,'' a spokesperson for the New York-based
Deja News, Inc said ``It's unbiased _ that's the beauty of it. The
company does not control content. That is too Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   But while hoaxers used the Internet to posture, other users
sought solace and comfort in discussion groups and live chat
forums. Marian McKenna Olivas, a California Web designer, set up a
condolence site on her business pages (see
http://www.wecanhelp.net/columbine.html). ``I lost my second child
(to meningitis, not violence) and was just moved by the sight of
parents waiting to hear from their children,'' she said. ``I
decided to set up a place where people could send sympathy.'' The
site was receiving 10 condolence letters an hour Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, various on-line sites offered cyber
counseling: At family.com, for instance, therapist Sylvia Rimm
posted a piece called ``What to Tell Your Kids.'' Poussaint fielded
questions on AOL; friends supported each other in such forums as
alt.teens.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere on-line was a mix of heartfelt emotion and false
bravado. ``I could make a bomb,'' boasted an AOL member in a chat
room. Recipes for explosives are, in fact, readily available
on-line.
</P>
<P>
   But for every braggart on-line Wednesday, there was a somber
counterpoint. This message appeared on Olivas' bulletin board
Thursday night: ``All I can say is I'm sorry. I live in Jonesboro
(Arkansas), and I went to the high school at Westside when last
year there was the shooting. I know how hard it is and I know how
hard it will end up being.'' The posting was signed, ``Sincerely,
Erin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
