<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING YOUR VCR ON STEROIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One reason I dread leaving the office for a week is all the mail
that piles up in my absence. It's 90 percent trash, of course, even
the boxes filled with software and gadgets that arrive unbidden
from publicity-hungry entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   The big black box from Replay Networks Inc. of Mountain View,
Calif., fell into that category. I thought one of our arts and
entertainment reporters might want to take it home and play with
their new ReplayTV device. But he didn't. So I ended up lugging it
home, hooking it up to my television, and chuckling with admiration
and delight. You've heard of VCR Plus? ReplayTV is VCR Squared.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a computer that thinks it's a VCR. Hook it up to
a TV antenna or cable, and ReplayTV will let you copy 10 to 28
hours of video. Unlike a VCR, which records on a long spool of
analog videotape, ReplayTV uses a data protocol known as MPEG-2 to
create compressed digital copies of TV shows and store them on a
built-in hard drive. In addition, ReplayTV connects by telephone
modem to a free on-line service that automatically updates your
local TV listings every day, storing the information in an
electronic channel guide. And, of course, the thing sets its own
internal clock; no blinking 12:00 here.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a device that makes TV time-shifting a trivial
exercise. Want to tape tonight's evening news? Just open the
channel guide with ReplayTV's remote control. Flip to the network
of your choice, and press the record button. You can even tell it
to record the same news show every night.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a computer in charge of the process allows even more
sophisticated controls. Say you want to watch the Flintstones but
don't know when it's on. Punch in the word ``Flintstones,'' and
ReplayTV will scan its database, find the program, and record it.
</P>
<P>
   Some genius at ReplayTV came up with the idea of a data buffer
that records a portion of any live show you might be watching. What
good is that? Two words: instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   I tried it during an Atlanta Braves baseball game. The batter
hit a pop fly to right field. I wanted to see it again. I pressed
the replay button, and instantly the TV image leapt backward in
time by a few seconds, rerunning the play. Meanwhile, the unit kept
recording the live TV feed. I could keep watching in replay mode,
seeing the rest of the game delayed by several seconds. Or I could
push a live-feed button and go back to watching the game in real
time.
</P>
<P>
   The video recording looked at least as good as videotape on my
ancient RCA set, and the sound quality, pumped through my home
stereo system, was excellent.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, ReplayTV isn't a complete substitute for a VCR.
It won't play rented movies. Equally important, its hard drive
eventually fills up, forcing you to record over shows. It's easy to
plug a VCR into the back and offload the stuff you want to keep
permanently. As for extra hard drive space, the designers had the
wit to include a couple of data ports that use Apple Computer
Inc.'s red-hot FireWire system. Replay Networks plans to sell
plug-and-play FireWire hard drives that would let a user boost
video storage capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the price, $700 for the basic 10-hour unit, up to
$1,500 for a model that can store 28 hours of video. This is much
too high. Then again, it's bound to get cheaper. After all,
ReplayTV is a computer, and we all know what's been happening to
computer prices lately. In a year or so, one of the basic units
could well be in the $350-$400 range.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing I'd like to see is a hookup with Microsoft Corp.,
whose superb WebTV device still hasn't achieved the success it
deserves. WebTV has full Internet access, and a slick
picture-in-picture feature that would look great on a ReplayTV
unit. Merge the two technologies in a cheap consumer device and
you'd have the hottest home electronics product since the Sony
Playstation. I'd love to find a box like that waiting after my next
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
