<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMCHAIR QUARTERBACKING THE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Day twenty-seven and no end in sight,'' declared CNN
``Crossfire'' host Bill Press, kicking off another television food
fight over who lost Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Over on MSNBC, talk host John Gibson sifted through the Balkan
rubble for psychological clues to its origin. ``What was (Bill
Clinton's) real motive here?'' he asked his guests. Is the
president ``doing the right thing'' or ``fighting for his legacy''?
</P>
<P>
   Most journalists may have been driven from the war zone in
Yugoslavia, but commentators have overrun the TV studios. And the
first major war conducted in the glare of the 24-hour-media
universe has produced a torrent of punditry that observers say
creates unrealistic public expectations _ and potentially
signficant policy implications _ for a conflict that may involve
serious time and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of what former ABC diplomatic correspondent Barrie
Dunsmore called ``the armchair quarterback syndrome'' is apparent
in a recent CNN/USA Today survey. While the main sentiment was that
NATO was losing the war, the most revealing finding was that only 9
percent thought it was ``too soon'' to render a verdict on the
success of the mission after a few short weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one thinks about the various major conflicts that have
taken place, the notion that this thing should be settled in the
first two or three weeks is bizarre,'' added Dunsmore, an associate
fellow at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. ``I think the
time frame has been reduced . . . because of television and the
all-news channels.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable news networks _ with their ravenous appetite for
talking heads and instant opinion _ have become ``a media
technology issue that ultimately affects the culture and people's
expectations about war and life,'' said Marvin Kalb, director of
Harvard's Shorenstein Center.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on television coverage early on in the Kosovo
conflict, New York Times columnist Thomas Friedman warned that
``this is war, not infotainment.'' But that can be hard to
remember, watching such unlikely military experts as Bianca Jagger
and Michael Isikoff weigh in on the use of ground troops and Bill
Clinton's resolve as commander in chief. Or when, in the apparent
interest of fairness, Fox News Channel airs a debate between a
political science professor calling for a full-fledged ground war
and a peace activist offering college scholarships to Serb
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   According to several analysts, the demand for instant answers to
intractable problems represents an evolution in both the media and
political environments. Conventional wisdom holds that the public
did not decide America was in trouble in Vietnam until Walter
Cronkite said so in his famous 1968 Tet offensive broadcast. Three
decades later, TV pundits rush to declare the United States a loser
in 20 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are different now because there's not the kind of
consensus about foreign policy that there was in the Cold War
era,'' said Daniel Hallin, author of ``The Uncensored War: The
Media and Vietnam.'' ``When there is no consensus, journalists step
into the void and try to sort things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalb contrasts today's rampaging punditry with what CBS used to
call ``instant analysis.'' In moments of grave crisis,
correspondents covering the story would cautiously discuss the
situation on air. ``We generally filled out the half-hour of time
and that was that,'' Kalb said. Even that modest level of
pontificating, he added, was deemed ``controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, you have a lot of time,'' he added. ``Everything is a
crisis. And retired admirals and generals need work.''
</P>
<P>
   This often comes across as a cacophony of confusion as the
voices of competing interests battle for the precious media
megaphone. In one hectic sequence on Fox News Channel this past
weekend, viewers were bombarded with the pleadings of a Bulgarian
senator arguing for a negotiated settlement, an Albanian
representative urging a ground war, and a US congressman advocating
both an intensified military and diplomatic campaign at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   This past Sunday's television talk-show circuit offered a
smorgasbord of doomsday scenarios and second-guessing. Republican
presidential candidate Pat Buchanan and Senator Judd Gregg,
Republican of New Hampshire, argued for a quick diplomatic solution
to cut US losses. ABC commentator William Kristol and former NATO
supreme commander General George Joulwan advocated a major ground
campaign before all was lost.
</P>
<P>
   When Senator Christopher Dodd Democrat of Connecticut, speaking
on CBS's ``Face the Nation,'' wondered how such crucial judgments
could have solidified so soon and warned that ``we have a tendency
to lose patience quickly,'' journalist Gloria Borger seemed
stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``But how much patience do you think the American people have?''
she responded.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics say the problem with this punditry is its potential
to prematurely galvanize opinion, and thus to influence the elected
officials who must conduct the war with some sort of public
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shultz, director of the Security Studies Program at
Tufts's Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy, believes a good deal
of this armchair quarterbacking is not particularly ``serious,''
but that the implications can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is it fuels the crisis mentality,'' Shultz
declared. ``I think it does put (policy makers) in a bind. We
expect results fast. Yet, we have an air campaign designed not to
have fast results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference now is the intensity of the negative
drumbeat,'' said Dunsmore. ``In terms of how this affects policy, I
have to believe it has some impact simply because the drumbeat
ultimately does get through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A TABLOID'S RESTRAINT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Chicago Sun-Times editor Nigel Wade kept the Columbine High
School carnage off the front page of his tabloid, it marked the
second time in two years that he made news by bucking journalistic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the Sun-Times covered a deadly Oregon high school
attack inside the paper and published a note voicing Wade's concern
that front-page treatment would traumatize children and inspire
copycat crimes. Many news industry observers suspected a publicity
stunt and Wade made the media rounds, discussing his unorthodox
decision on the ``Today'' show and in an New York Times op-ed
column.
</P>
<P>
   Wade acknowledges that the level of bloodshed in Colorado made
it ``a tougher call'' to run the news on inside pages. But, ``If we
were right to do it last time, we're right to do it again,'' he
said. ``This is certainly not censorship. This is presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case last May, Wade said his decision was proving
very popular with grateful parents. ``My phone's going nuts,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
