<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-THINGS-BOS &LR;      04-22 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-THINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIRL'S-EYE VIEW OF QUIRKINESS GOING CRAZY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LAST THINGS 
By Jenny Offill 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 272 pp., $23, 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most children, Grace Davitt has an active imagination. She
plays detective, pretends to fly, and her favorite book is ``The
Encyclopedia of the Unexplained,'' full of weird ``true'' tales,
such as the man in California struck dead when a hunk of meat fell
from the sky, or the baby in Oregon born half-chicken, half-boy,
who pecked his mother to death.
</P>
<P>
   The book was a gift from Grace's mother, Anna, who leads an even
richer fantasy life than her 8-year-old daughter. An ornithologist
who works at a center for raptors in a small Vermont community,
Anna imparts fables, myths, and imaginings to her impressionable
daughter. Her quirkiness brings to mind Aunt Sylvie in Marilynne
Robinson's dark coming-of-age classic, ``Housekeeping.'' Sylvie's
young niece, Ruth, watched helplessly as her aunt's eccentricity
veered toward insanity; Grace is in a similar situation.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's father, Jonathan, a chemistry teacher, is the opposite
of his wife; he's a stubborn realist who sees everything in black
and white, and then only when there's proof.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Jenny Offill, in this strong debut novel, has created a
fantastical family, at times loving and sweet, sorrowful and
dangerous. The prose, told through the eyes of Grace, is sparse,
elegant, and inviting. What starts off innocently often ends up
chilling, with no warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat on the edge of the bathtub and watched my mother put on
her face. Outside, the trees were breaking themselves into pieces.
Ice tapped against the glass. My mother went to the window and
rubbed away the steam. `Listen, Grace,' she said, `I think
someone's speaking to us in code.' I looked out the window. There
was nothing but the dark trees to see. My mother tapped twice on
the glass, then cupped a hand to her ear. . . . I wanted to ask her
if she had really been a spy, but I was too afraid. If I told you
that, I'd have to kill you, she said once.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of their family traditions are charming if not bizarre.
Because Anna doesn't believe in cutting down trees for Christmas,
they choose one in the forest. ``On Christmas morning, we got
dressed in our warmest clothes and went to see our tree. My father
pulled a sled behind him with all our presents on it and we had a
picnic breakfast in the snow. Pine needles fell on the coffee cake
my mother had made. We opened our presents all at once because it
was too cold to take turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace's baby sitter is Edgar, a tall, 16-year-old genius who
studies mold, including a luminous variety he hopes will someday be
used to light entire cities. The only normal thing about him is the
unrelenting crush he has on Anna.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan's twin brother, Uncle Pete, represents yet another side
of science, the popular version that he dispenses daily on his
``Mr. Science'' national television show, which Grace's parents
enjoy mocking with a nasty, jealous fervor. His children, who visit
occasionally, are the closest thing Grace has to traditional
playmates.
</P>
<P>
   Anna is the kind of mother many girls wish from afar they had _
alluring, playful, young, and beautiful. But up close, when the
mystery turns to madness, it's no longer fun. One moment Anna is
joyous, innocent, wise; the next, Offill has painted her as a
disturbed, pitiable creature whose behavior equates neglect or even
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the many nighttime trips to the local lake, where
Anna is convinced a monster lives, Grace falls asleep while riding
her mother's back in the water and nearly drowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we reached the shallow part, my mother set me down. `If
you ever try a stunt like that again, I'll kill you,' she said. I
tried to take her hand, but she pulled away.''
</P>
<P>
   After Grace mildly acts out at school, Anna decides to
home-school her, using the sewing room, which she'd painted black
to represent the galaxy, as her classroom. They trace the cosmic
calendar, beginning with the Big Bang and ending with the first
humans. Sometimes lessons are given in Annic, the secret language
Anna's father developed for her that Grace, like her grandmother,
could never catch the hang of.
</P>
<P>
   As for her father, the only real show of strength he makes is a
move to New York City for a job; his weakness is in asking his
8-year-old child to take care of his wife. Mother and daughter go
on a schizophrenic road trip that includes New Orleans, Joshua Tree
National Park in California, and the Burning Man festival in
Nevada. Here, Offill could have done a better job of pulling
together earlier events with current ones, perhaps using Grace's
detective kit.
</P>
<P>
   What is made painfully, poignantly clear is that when the two
return home, it's time for the Davitt family to deal with their
monsters, at home and in the lake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
