<HEADLINE>
MOLD IN THE TOILET TANK? TRY BLEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My toilet tank is just chock full of black mold: Sides and
bottom are covered. How can I get rid of it, and is there a way to
keep it away?
</P>
<P>
   PAULINE, Westborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. As far as toilets are concerned, that's an easy one. Mold
will grow virtually anywhere it is damp and preferably warm. But as
you discovered, it can grow in water, and in cold water. The
handyman had it a little while ago, and this is what he did: Pour a
cup of liquid chlorine bleach into the tank, leave it for a while,
and scrub the sides and bottom with a brush to loosen the stuff.
Then flush the toilet; you will have to do this several times to
flush away the mold. If you have a low-flow toilet, keep the
flushing handle down to empty the tank, then wait for the tank to
fill before flushing again. Completely emptying the tank will get
rid of more mold.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the mold away, add a cup of bleach to the tank once a
week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The handyman has received many calls and letters on how to
reduce sound transmission from one apartment or condo unit to
another, or between rooms in a house. Goodness knows, there is too
much sound pollution in our modern lives, and anything one can do
to reduce it or block it will be a big help.
</P>
<P>
   And the handyman has given out the proper answers to those calls
and letters. Those answers describe sound as vibration, which makes
its way through the solid part of a wall: studs and other wood and
metal members. To stop this transmission, the wall finish
(plasterboard, paneling, etc.) must be separate from the wall
itself. Thus, those vibrations still will go through the solid
parts, but they will dissipate in the air space between wall finish
and solid parts.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish this separation, apply acoustic resilient strips,
which are steel strips shaped like an ``L.'' Screw one leg of this
``L'' to the wall, then screw sound-absorbing board to the other
leg of the ``L.'' This will allow the sound-absorbing board to
stand out from the original wall by a half to three-quarters of an
inch, enough dead air to dissipate the vibrations. Then apply
plasterboard as a final finish.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy the strips at Waltham Sand &AMP; Cement Co. and possibly
building supply centers. Sound-absorbing board is sold in building
supply centers and lumber stores.
</P>
<P>
   What's the point of all this?
</P>
<P>
   The point came from Janet Donovan of South Boston, who called to
say that she did this with her ceiling, as per the handyman's
suggestion, and it ``worked perfectly. The sound transmission is 80
percent reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to do the walls,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Janet Donovan, for taking the time to reply, all of
which proves that the handyman's theory really does work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to put ceramic tile on my kitchen floor. There are
vinyl tiles there now. I was told to put down quarter-inch plywood
and install the ceramic tile with thin-set mortar. Is this a good
way?
</P>
<P>
   JACK DOHERTY, Natick, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That is one way, and it is a good one, especially if you do
it yourself. If you put down the plywood, make it as even as
possible; that is, with no ridges or sudden changes in grade. An
even surface will allow tiles to be set flat and full against the
plywood and not rock over an uneven surface. If the tiles do rock,
they will break. That is a promise. As an extra precaution, the
smaller the tile, the less it will rock. So put in tiles that are 6
or 8 inches square.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to do it: Instead of plywood, use cement board,
which is one-half-inch thick and made of concrete. The tiles will
stick better on cement board with thin-set mortar than on plywood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am putting in a hardwood floor in my kitchen. The boards
will be sanded, and then three coats of polyurethane varnish will
be applied. I read that hardwood floors should be put down in the
winter, when the boards are at their driest, to prevent the boards
from opening up when they dry. The floor will be installed in
mid-April; is that too late?
</P>
<P>
   MARY LYNN RITCHEY, Auburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Not at all. The advice to have the boards installed in winter
was a general one, to ensure the boards are at their driest (and
smallest) when installed. The months to avoid laying the boards are
June, July, August, and September.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to fight those joints' opening up is to store the
boards in the house for two weeks before installation; this is to
allow the boards to become acclimated to the moisture in the house.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to get around all this is to install prefinished
boards, ones that have four or more coats of polyurethane on them.
Laid tightly, such prefinished boards will resist opening of the
joints.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
