<HEADLINE>
BMW'S M COUPE _ A MITE ODD-LOOIKING, BUT OH SO FRISKY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been a remarkable ebb and flow in America's
relationship with the sports car _ foreign or domestic, roadster or
coupe _ for nearly 50 years now.
</P>
<P>
   Some old standards _ Porsches and Corvettes _ have been
enduring; others have come and gone, or come and gone and come
again, or are new: the MG, the Nissan Z models, Jaguars, Volvos, a
funky Saab, the Mazda Miata.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are in the midst of a dual-track revival. Mazda gave us
the Miata at the dawn of the 1990s and the roadster was reborn as
other manufacturers followed. Now comes at least a minirevival of
the coupe. BMW has produced the M coupe, descendant of its
roadster, Audi will have its TT coupe in showrooms in weeks, and
Nissan is bringing back the Z, 20 years after it was first
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   And if the M coupe is any example of what the meld of modern
technology and the old Italiante style of Gran Turismo sports car
can produce, enthusiasts are in for a choice of wild rides.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the 1999 M coupe is like taking a frisky puppy for a
walk on a leash; all that energy if you can harness it. But puppies
do not cost $41,800, as does this 3.2-liter rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: This is a driver's car. No one will buy it for
sheer utility and no one should. You do not need an inline
six-cylinder aluminum engine, with dual overhead cams and four
valves per cylinder stuffed (literally) into a 3,131-pound auto to
get to the store for milk. You do not need to accelerate from 0-60
in just over 5 seconds to be first away from a stoplight on your
morning commute, or take a sweeping highway entrance ramp at 80
m.p.h. or click into fifth as you hit the highway and feel the
puppy ready to leap because there is plenty more energy there.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in some ways, an odd-looking car: fenders bulging like
muscles, long hood jutting like a bully's chin, short cab abruptly
chopped at the rear. Some have said it looks like a roller-skate.
Others are reminded of the Volvo 1800. I prefer to think of it as
an MGB-GT on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   When a muscle car accelerates, it pushes you straight back in
your seat as if you were riding a rocket sled. High performance
cars are different: They seem to suck you down into the seat as
they crouch ever lower on the road, and that is what the M coupe
does as you accelerate through the tight clicks of its 5-speed
manual transmission.
</P>
<P>
   In the windshield, the world comes at you like some video game,
darting ahead with a domain at your fingertips. Indeed, with many
of its controls _ lights, cruise control, directionals, wipers _
hidden on short stems behind the air-bag- filled center of the
steering wheel, this is a futuristic step toward the day when
driving will be much like operating a computer.
</P>
<P>
   With any high-performance sports car, corners are the crucible.
That is why we do not prefer to race them straight-ahead or
round-and-round. The M coupe is remarkable on the corners. Set the
inside front wheel to any line you wish to take through a corner,
power the turn with the gas pedal, and the coupe sticks to the arc
as if it's on a rail.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is a hardtop, this is a stiffer car than its
stablemate, the M3 roadster. It's got stiff springs, an anitroll
system, and an ABS keyed to vented disc brakes nearly a
foot-and-a-half in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   It is equipped with an automatic stability and traction control
system. In generic terms, that means that if it senses one of the
rear drive wheels spinning faster than the other _ as in losing it
on a corner, snow, ice, water, sand _ it cuts motor torque or
gently applies the brakes. A light flashes on the dash when you
reach this point. It is a simple circular arrow but means: Without
me, you'd be sideways right now. The daring can turn off this
system.
</P>
<P>
   With a wonderful guttural rumble from its exhausts, the M coupe
cruises the interstate on a commute to work with an effortless
ease, moving in and out of traffic, changing lanes nimbly. On
rougher roads _ frost-heaved pavement in New Hampshire and a
handful of dirt and gravel roads _ it is remarkably smooth. There
is none of the jarring you might expect from a small, stiff sports
car.
</P>
<P>
   Dirt roads and the lingering sand left on pavement from a winter
just past indicated, however, that this would not be a car you'd
want to rely on in the snow and ice. Tap the gas on these surfaces
and the ``you'd be sideways'' light comes on.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said of fine sports cars that you don't sit in them,
you wear them. That is the case with the M coupe. The leather seats
sit low to the floor and wrap thighs and shoulders. There are two
long pockets of leg room, though the roof is so low it is hard not
to wonder if someone with legs to fill those pockets would bang
their head on the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   And as futuristic as parts of the car seem, there are
wonderfully retro aspects to some of its interior design. Most of
the gauges are analog (wonderful to not confuse the time with the
call letters of the radio station you have on). They are each
circled in chrome and are reminiscent of older sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Because it seats two and has airbags front and side, this is not
a car in which to transport children. Its rear compartment will
hold ample suitcases for a trip. On a trip to the recycling center,
it held four plastic bags of garbage, a week's worth of newspapers,
one grocery bag full of bottles, and another full of cans.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers beware: You cannot fit your clubs safely into this rear
compartment. But if you can afford this toy, you can afford to
belong to a club where you just leave your clubs in your locker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
NICE TOUCHES:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The 10- and-2-o'clock grips on the leather-wrapped wheel.
</P>
<P>
   --Windows on each door that open slightly each time the door is
opened and close only after the door is shut. No more surge of
eardrum pressure that comes when a door to a small compartment is
slammed.
</P>
<P>
   --The search-free, single, rectangular knob on each seat that
controls height and distance from the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   --The separation net that shields the driving compartment from
the rear storage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The cheap plastic box of a tiny console jammed between the
seats almost as if an afterthought. At $40,000 plus, I'd expect
wood or leather.
</P>
<P>
   --The way whatever aerodynamics are going on outside coat the
rear window with road dirt.
</P>
<P>
   --The sound of whistling wind at the tops of the doors at 60
m.p.h. and above.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
