<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING AN 1896 PORCH AS GOOD AS NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD PENNINGTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed a straightforward job.
</P>
<P>
   The front porch of our Queen Anne-style house, nicely designed
and built as these houses always are, needed new decking, stairs,
and railings. The lattice skirt under the deck had to be removed
and redesigned. The whole porch could use a bit of scraping and a
new coat of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the wood dated from 1896 and it was as strong as ever.
The services of an architect were not required; a major rebuilding
was not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   My plan was to replace the decking with teak or mahogany, but
while searching for these materials, I came upon a similar
reddish-brown wood in the yard of Moynihan Lumber in Beverly, Mass.
It is called Cambara.
</P>
<P>
   My only surprise came when I ripped up the old fir deck. It had
rotted where rain had been collecting and water had seeped into the
six-inch-square beam that supported the deck. Carpenter ants had
tunneled into it until it was as light and frail as a feather.
</P>
<P>
   I decided not to replace it with a new six- by six-inch beam but
made up a beam from three 2 x 6 pressure-treated joists. I bolted
them together after filling the joints with roofing tar.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture is the enemy of wood, so I applied Thompson's Water
Seal to the now exposed joists and beams. Later I would use
caulking liberally wherever pieces of exposed wood were joined.
</P>
<P>
   A screw jack, a column with a big screw on the top, allowed me
to lift the corner post and the entryway off the decking, and made
it possible to slip the new Cambara boards underneath. I
blind-nailed galvanized nails into the tongue and groove decking. I
prefered not to have the end grains of the boards exposed, so I
finished off the ends with several tapered strips of Cambara,
cutting a drip groove along the bottom of the board so that the
water would fall away from the porch. I applied an oil-based primer
and stain to the deck. I don't trust water-based stains on flat
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   I applied a new coat of mortar around the outside of the brick
pier that supports the deck porch beams, and I gave extra support
to the long beam by adding two posts.
</P>
<P>
   When designing the skirt below the deck I decided against the
usual lattice panels in favor of a row of vertical beveled strips
cut from cedar boards. I painted these strips gray to match the
color of the brick foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The original railings and balusters had been replaced years
earlier with 2 x 4s and 2 x 2s. I replaced these with wood more in
keeping with the original style of the house: slope-topped beaded
fir rails and turned hemlock balusters. The spacing of the
balusters posed a tricky problem in arithmetic. I ended up spacing
them 4 1/2 inches apart. I cut a channel in the underside of the
handrail to accept a subrail wood strip, to which I attached the
balusters.
</P>
<P>
   The cedar newel post is attached to the decking with two hidden
dowels.
</P>
<P>
   The large space under the porch provides a convenient place to
store an extension ladder and a kayak, if I ever get one. The
stairs detach from the porch to permit access to the space under
it.
</P>
<P>
   A Mission-style lamp purchased at Restoration Hardware in Boston
replaced the bare light bulb over the porch. I added another light
inside the foyer for security.
</P>
<P>
   The project did seem simple enough when I began, but in the end
I had spent well over 50 hours putting it together. Out of
curiosity I counted the pieces of wood: 233 had to be put in place,
many cut several ways for an exact fit.
</P>
<P>
   The materials cost about $1,300. The decking for the 12- by
7-foot porch came to $350; the Mission lamp was $100; and the 35
hemlock balusters cost $4.25 each, or $150. The cedar is costly,
$3.36 a board foot, but is worth it, considering the fact that the
skirt is close to the ground. Even clear pine costs $3.08 a board
foot.
</P>
<P>
   A good table saw is indispensible for a project like this. It
might not have been necessary, but I sanded all materials before I
finished them. One extremely useful tool proved to be a handheld
grinder, which I used to cut stubborn nails and screws.
</P>
<P>
   A handy guide is ``The Book of Ideas for Porch Design'' by J.
Gregory Tatsch (Vintage Wood Works, Quinlan, Texas; telephone
903-356-2158).
</P>
</TEXT>
