<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, April 23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTING &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the aftermath of the high school shooting in a Denver
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ The ledeall, focusing
on developments in investigation and whether others were involved
in the attack. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-VICTIMS (Undated) _ Snapshots of the victims. By
James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SENIORS (Littleton) _ What will happen to seniors
and others at a now-closed Columbine High School. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-MEDIA (Littleton) _ A look at the media invasion in
Colorado. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-WEB (Littleton) _ The role of the World Wide Web as
a home for lonely outcasts. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS (Littleton) _ Guns and politics in Colorado. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHOOLS (Alexandria, Va.) _ President Clinton meets with
high school kids to discuss youth gun violence. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on the group known as
the Trenchcoat Mafia and a visit to a suburban New York high
school.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning three pages of stories, photos
and graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo and the NATO summit
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ Daily developments: One of
Milosevic's homes was destroyed in NATO bombing overnight, but the
Pentagon says they weren't trying to kill him. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS-ASSESS (Brussels) _ A military analysis: From the
military's point of view, planning for ground troops won't
accomplish much. What's needed to have a force ready by July or
August is putting the force together now: calling people up,
signing basing agreements, starting to move equipment. And if NATO
waits much longer it could miss goal of having force able to go in
before winter. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ On the ground in the
Yugoslav capital: The scene after Milosevic's home is attacked with
Serbs saying it was an assassination attempt. The Yugoslav
information minister says 517 civilians have been killed and more
than 4,000 seriously hurt since campaign began. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Viktor Cherynomyrdin, the Russian
special envoy, meets with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslavia
president; is expected to return to Russia tonight. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VETS (Washington) _ What Vietnam veterans serving in
Congress say about the campaign against Yugoslavia. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   More NATO summit stories as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ Developments in Albania with the
arrival of the Apache attack helicopters and other U.S. forces. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline to kum, Macedonia) _ Developments on
Kosovar refugees in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-CLINTON (Washington) _ Developments with President Clinton
and Tony Blair, the British prime minister, and the NATO summit. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, a story on the plight of
refugee children separated from their families.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Washington) _ The federal government brings
its first case against one of the proliferating number of
information brokers who advertise on websites that they can get
consumers' bank accounts and other financial information for a fee.
By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-KOSOVO (Washington) _ The real domino effect will be what
happens to the overall budget, the surplus and the plan for walling
off Social Security now that the bills for the Balkan battle are
mounting. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-TEACHERS (Seattle) _ Five thousand teachers walk out in
Seattle, protesting that their pay is to low for a city that is
increasingly expensive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU (Jerusalem) _ Three weeks before the Israeli
election, it is as if Benjamin Netanyahu's world view has collided
with his self-image: like Israel, he too is surrounded by the
``circle of hatred'' he often describes. And it is not without
reason; on the right, in the center and on the left, there are many
Israelis hoping he becomes a fluke of history. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM-CRASH (Paris) _ The Dutch Parliament releases a report
on the El Al crash in which mysterious cargo _ probably nerve gas
components _ sickened hundreds of people. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washingtton) _ The Los Alamos lab director meets the
press, facing questions on Chinese espionage and security issues.
By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GAYS-GENE (Undated) _ Researchers report they are unable to
replicate earlier findings that variations in a region of the
X-chromosome are linked to male homosexuality. The report does not
necessarily invalidate the earlier work but scientists say it shows
how difficult it will be to link complex behavioral traits to a
particular gene or genes. By Erica Goode. (800 words).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-FOSSIL (Undated) _ In another filling-out of the human
family tree, scientists report they have found fossils of a
previously unknown creature that may represent a midway point in
the evolution from the hominid australopithecus afarensis, a.k.a.
Lucy, to the precursors of modern humans. The discovery of
butchered bones nearby suggests that australopithecus ghari, as it
has been dubbed, may have been the first hominid to use stone tools
to butcher meat. By John Noble Wilford. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NYC-BUDGET (New York) _ Mayor Giuliani releases his budget for
the city. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ Mrs. Clinton visits Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM (London) _ Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom must
overcome a number of obstacles before they complete their deal.
Executives spoke about the $82 billion merger at a news conference
in London. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BIAS-SUIT (Washington) _ Senior black executives of
Coca-Cola are suing the company, accusing Coke of racial
discrimination. The executives say their career options are limited
by racists supervisors. Suit is being filed today in U.S. District
Court in Atlanta. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON-CRAZE (Langhorne, Pa.) _ Pokemon, a video game that
features 150 monsters, or Pokemons, is the new craze among
schoolchildren across the country. Introduced in Japan by Nintendo
just three years ago, Pokemon has already grown into a $5 billion
international industry that includes comic books, plastic
figurines, virtual pets, bean-bag toys, lunch boxes, T-shirts, a
television cartoon show and compact disks. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ Three months after the largest economy
in Latin America appeared headed for an Asian-style meltdown,
provoking panic in markets around the world, Brazil is bouncing
back. While the country remains in recession, the average Brazilian
seems willing to tolerate that so long as there is no renewal of
the hyperinflation of the 1980s and early 1990s. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-NOTES (New York) _ Brazil prices $1 billion in five-year
notes in late afternoon. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   LAZARD-SETTLE (New York) _ U.S. Attorney in Manhattan announces
$11 million settlement with Lazard Freres over its role in
municipal refinancing, or yield burning. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:15, the Dow Jones industrial average
was up 111 points, the Nasdaq up 53. Stocks in Europe are up by as
much as 1.5 percent. The Nikkei in Tokyo closed up 1 percent, and
the Hang Seng in Hong Kong rose 3 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-DOLLAR (Washington) _ Fed Chairman Greenspan speaks to
Congress on the proposal that Mexico and others adopt the dollar as
their national currency. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Lucent reports sharply higher
earnings for its second-quarter. It also announces the sale of its
U.S. sales group to an investor group led by Susan Mandl _ wife of
Alex Mandl, the former AT&AMP;T president and chief of Teligent. Bell
Atlantic and GTE post gains in lines with expectations, while
Airtouch's results are better than expected. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Pepsico reports quarterly earnings.
By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   NABISCO-EARNINGS (Undated) _ RJR Nabisco reports quarterly
earnings. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BANKRUPTCY (Hong Kong) _ A Chinese court said it expected
to salvage only $783 million in assets from Gitic, the bankrupt
investment trust. Banks now face the likelihood of recovering less
than one-fifth of their original loans. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-TRADE (Geneva) _ The rate of growth in world exports
slipped to 3.5 percent last year, a third of its 1997 level, the
World Trade Organization said. The continuing bite of the Asian
crisis was the main reason for the slowdown, but the trend was
evident in all major trading regions. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
