<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-22 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TO WEAN? WHEN IT FEELS NATURAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the reasons a mother may give for wanting to wean her
baby, lactation specialist Lisa McSherry says only two really mean
a mother is done nursing: ``I'm tired of having a baby draped over
me'' or ``I want my body back.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything else, she says, is ambivalence, and for these women,
her advice is to continue to nurse. ``Sooner or later, the
ambivalence disappears and weaning is easy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In our Western culture, where autonomy is highly valued even in
young children, it's not surprising that women feel torn about
weaning. To many fathers as well as some pediatricians and
grandparents, a 2-year-old who's still nursing is a child who isn't
being allowed to grow up. To the nursing mother, however,
breast-feeding describes a relationship, not just a source of
nutrition. The societal norm to give it up can feel like pressure,
and even a loving husband can become an antagonist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a habit that needs to be quit,'' says Gale Pryor,
author of ``Nursing Mother, Working Mother: The Essential Guide for
Breastfeeding'' (Harvard Common Press).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, pediatrician and parenting author T. Berry Brazelton
says weaning is a developmental process, like walking or talking:
It happens when it happens, on a timetable that has little to do
with our wishes or needs.
</P>
<P>
   He agrees with the recommendation of the American Academy of
Pediatrics that nursing last through the first year for the medical
benefits and emotional closeness it continues to accrue.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many mothers stop earlier because they think
their child is telling them to. ``At five months, a baby may turn
away, and parents take it as a signal he doesn't want to nurse
anymore. That's mistaken,'' says Brazelton. The turning away is not
a loss of interest, it's a burst of cognitive development as the
baby becomes more curious about the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to plow through that period and nurse in a dark,
quiet spot to minimize distractions,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Your baby will tell you when she's ready to stop nursing, but
it's far more likely to be during the second year.
</P>
<P>
   Linnea Warburton was 12 1/2 months old when she let her mother
know. ``She was walking more and becoming more active, and she was
so busy, she'd forget to come to me to nurse,'' says her mother,
Betty Gau. As her meals became more substantial, Linnea also
stopped asking to nurse in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, without any effort on Gau's part, they were nursing
only once a day, first thing in the morning. Then one morning, when
Linnea slept late, there was no time for the feeding in Mama's bed.
``We just took her right downstairs for breakfast, and she didn't
ask to nurse that day,'' says Gau. ``It was pretty clear she was
done. That began to become our routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks have passed since then. At first, Gau anxiously
awaited Linnea's tug on her shirt, her baby's signal that she
wanted to nurse. It hasn't happened even once.
</P>
<P>
   This is close to Pryor's ideal: a child initiates weaning
because she's expanded her ability to comfort herself and is ready
to have a different kind of relationship with Mom.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't necessarily what Gau had in mind, though.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, she had a difficult time nursing; her goal was to
keep at it for only six months. As things improved, she decided to
stay with it for another six. When she evaluated at a year, she
says simply, ``I wasn't ready to give it up.'' Two weeks later,
when it was Linnea who initiated weaning, Gau was not only
surprised but emotionally unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was incredibly sad, and I still am sometimes,'' she says,
fighting back tears. ``But I can see how excited she is at all the
new things in her life, so I have to move on, too. I wish there was
a ritual to mark this, though. It's such a moment in time, such a
significant life passage.''
</P>
<P>
   This sense of loss is normal, says Diane Bengson, a leader and
spokeswoman for La Leche League International and author of a
forthcoming League book, ``How Weaning Happens.'' She says mothers
who are saddest are those who are nursing a last baby; who
struggled with breast-feeding to begin with; who nurse to provide
comfort as well as nutrition; who wean quickly and have hormones
that haven't adjusted; or who feel pressured to stop. The last
group worries her most.
</P>
<P>
   Bengson says a woman's sense of loss is less intense when
weaning is on her timetable. When pressure comes from a husband,
especially one who was supportive of breast-feeding, there is
confusion and anger. She cites four reasons a dad may push to end
breast-feeding:
</P>
<P>
   --He's tired of sharing his wife with the baby and hopes for a
resumption of the pre-baby sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   --He feels insecure or unsure of his role as a father.
</P>
<P>
   --He thinks nursing is encouraging too much dependency in the
baby.
</P>
<P>
   --He's uncomfortable with public nursing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Bengson urges couples to be honest and talk
it through, lest resentment build. ``Look for ways to compromise,''
she says. ``If he's uncomfortable when you nurse in public, can you
keep it private? If he feels lost, can you carve out a specialty
for him, like bathing the baby?''
</P>
<P>
   An emotionally healthier path to weaning is mother-initiated,
although if you begin when a baby is under 12 months, it can be
difficult. ``The breasts are more likely to get engorged,'' says
McSherry, who works at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in
Boston. If a woman wants to wean in the first year as a
prerequisite for returning to work, McSherry recommends taking a
minimum of a month to accomplish it, with at least three days
between each dropped feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor argues that working moms should be last to wean. ``Nursing
provides a connection despite the daily separation. It builds
confidence for a working mother,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Weinstein, a lawyer, went back to work when daughter
Katrina was 5 months old but she continued to nurse full time,
pumping twice a day. When Katrina turned a year, Weinstein weaned
gradually, over three months. Like Gau, she feels sad, even six
months later. ``Nursing guaranteed snuggle time. I miss the bond it
provided,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps with that in mind, she wasn't rigid about weaning. For
instance, when they were down to only one feeding a day and Katrina
took sick and wanted to nurse on demand, Weinstein complied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much milk I had, but the nursing gave her
comfort. I didn't see a reason not to,'' she says. Once Katrina was
well, she adds, they easily resumed weaning.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor says this kind of approach feeds into a child's
developmental need. ``If he falls and wants to nurse for comfort,
that's appropriate,'' she says. Relaxed weaning _ for three days
you drop a feeding, the fourth you don't, and then you do again _
comes easier if nursing wasn't on a time schedule, either.
</P>
<P>
   When you wean gradually, a toddler may not even miss it, says
Pryor. For the times when he does, you can:
</P>
<P>
   --Nurse, but keep it short: ``We can nurse for as long as it
takes to sing the `ABC' song.''
</P>
<P>
   --Offer choices: ``You can nurse or have chocolate milk/read a
book/play a game.''
</P>
<P>
   --Defer it: ``We're not going to nurse now, but we can do it
before your nap.'' Avoid saying simply, ``Not now'' or ``No.'' That
can confuse a child: ``Why is Mommy acting differently?'' Even
``Mommy doesn't want to nurse now,'' said kindly, is OK.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor, who is in the process of weaning her 22-month-old son,
sometimes tell him, `` `My breasts are empty now; let's get a glass
of milk.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He accepts that just fine,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
