<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING DETOXIFYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget spring cleaning. The dirt can stay where it is.
</P>
<P>
   This year I'm performing an exorcism instead, ridding my home of
threats to my family's health. I don't know why it's taken me so
long to act on my knowledge that the American home is filled with
products containing toxic chemicals. A recent five-year EPA study
found peak concentrations of 20 toxic compounds _ some linked with
cancer and birth defects _ 100 to 200 times higher indoors than
outdoors. It's no wonder women who stay at home have a higher
cancer-death rate than women who go to work.
</P>
<P>
   I'm finally ready to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   I'll start under the sink with my all-purpose cleaners,
including one that proclaims itself ``environmentally safe,
non-toxic, biodegradable, and phosphate free.'' I've been blithely
spraying this on my shower walls without using rubber gloves or
worrying about the fumes, even though our bathroom window doesn't
open. The label, however, reveals that this product contains butyl
cellosolve, which according to David Steinman and Samuel Epstein,
authors of ``The Safe Shopper's Bible: A Consumer's Guide to
Nontoxic Household Products, Cosmetics and Food,'' is a neurotoxin
that rapidly penetrates the skin. I don't want it in my house.
</P>
<P>
   Out goes every spot remover and glass, tile, carpet, and oven
cleaner whose labels disguise hazardous ingredients by calling them
``cleaning agents'' and ``grease cutters.'' I'm also ditching my
antibacterial liquid soaps and ``improved'' pot scrubbers imbued
with the fungicide triclosan, a derivative of Agent Orange. Since
the law doesn't require companies to list the cancer-causing
chemicals commonly found in household products, why expose myself
unnecessarily? They're headed for the trash.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also getting rid of my aerosol products. I don't need to
have what's in them delivered to my lungs in an easily inhaled
mist. Out goes every product with the following words: ``harmful
fumes,'' ``eye irritation,'' ``use rubber gloves,'' and my
favorite, ``contact a physician.'' With cases of multiple chemical
sensitivity on the rise, I'm removing all products that can
irritate my eyes, skin, or respiratory tract.
</P>
<P>
   In the bathroom I'm tossing out all my old nail polish. Those
characteristic fumes you can't help but inhale as you paint your
fingernails are laced with toluene, a poison with serious
reproductive effects, including spontaneous abortion and birth
defects. California has banned its use so now you can actually find
nail polish labeled, ``Toluene free.'' How come they'll tell us
it's gone, but not that it was there in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that cosmetics are the least regulated products in
the federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act. Who knew that even the
most expensive of them contain dangerous wetting agents,
preservatives, colorings, pesticides, talc, silica, and
formaldehyde, which can cause contact dermatitis, allergies, tissue
irritation, or cancer?
</P>
<P>
   I've always considered my reluctance to wear make-up a fault. I
may have done myself a favor.
</P>
<P>
   I know why I've held back from doing this sooner. I couldn't
believe that companies would promote products that harmed their
customers. A childlike part of me wanted to think that some
all-knowing parent was watching out for my interests. It's taken
years for me to face that I, and others like me, are the only
people I can trust to look out for my interests. Everyone's
reaching the same conclusion. Even a middle-of-the-road magazine
like Time recently stated that ``industry develops products for
their physical characteristics and doesn't always test for human
toxicity.'' It concludes that current tests for dangerous
substances are ``being conducted on involuntary human
populations.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, I stop being a guinea pig.
</P>
<P>
   It's not going to make my life more difficult. With the ``Safe
Shopper's Bible'' in hand, I'm going to a supermarket like Bread
and Circus or Wild Harvest and, checking the labels carefully,
stocking up on brand names given a seal of approval. One careful
shop and I'm done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Safe Shopper's Bible'' is full of do-it-yourself recipes.
I plan to whip up my own all-purpose cleaner from borax, vinegar,
soap and water, to deodorize my house with strategically placed
boxes of baking soda, and to polish my furniture with vinegar and
olive oil. If this seems like a step back to the good old days, so
be it.
</P>
<P>
   Let people call me names. How about pioneer?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
