<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-SPRING-BOS &LR;      04-22 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SPRING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE SPRINGS ETERNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
(poetry style 
 
Here's to the mud, the dried leaves and crud, 
here's to the detritus of last season. 
Here's to our dreams, drawn out in schemes, 
here's to complete loss of reason. 
 
(end poetry style) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring comes in fits and starts. The gardener, at least this
gardener, rushes out on a lovely warm day in March (40 degrees,
gusty, intermittent sun) to survy the domain.
</P>
<P>
   GardenPathways
</P>
<P>
   This leads to catalog orders (not to mention illness), stoking
the gardening ambition that has smoldered all winter. Later forays,
in better weather, reveal the true, tattered condition of the
garden, necessitating another round of purchases.
</P>
<P>
   While more is clearly needed of this and that, we must have
replacements for the English roses that evidently were not planted
deeply enough to survive the winter (lack of snow cover left
vulnerable bud unions between understock and desirable cultivars
exposed).
</P>
<P>
   Bergenias bit the dust, too, and where did those geraniums go? I
see just two, no, three, of the six I planted last year. Those on
order, intended to extend the presence of geraniums, will simply
mark time until I can obtain even more. On the other hand, the
lamb's ears are just ducky.
</P>
<P>
   From April on, it rains every weekend, of course _ is there some
way we can blame the Red Sox for this? _ and when it isn't raining,
the ground is too soggy to be worked. Digging destroys the soil's
tilth, and just walking on grassy paths and lawn causes destructive
soil compaction.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually I sally forth, pruners hanging from my belt, gripping
a rake in one hand and in the other toting large heavy-duty plastic
bags designed to hold and transport debris.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow garden needs raking. Oak leaves are specially formed
to burrow their way deep into santolina and cactus (and cotoneaster
is a nightmare). Out they must come and into the bags. The only way
is to start at one end and work to the other, then on to the next
bed, and the next.
</P>
<P>
   While I work in the front beds, I have loosed the hounds on the
backyard. Tessie noses clean through the screen in the back door
and returns to bed. (Is she a bad dog or smarter than me?) Lucy
goes the other way, wiggling under the back fence and making for
either the husky next door (Lucy's intentions are unclear) or the
woods and swamp on the other side. I know when she chooses the
latter because the yappy beast two houses down goes bazoo. Lucy is
a 120-pound Newfoundland and to the yapmeister must look for all
the world to be a large bear emerging from the woods, probably
hungry.
</P>
<P>
   After a successful bear hunt, I return to gardening.
Distractions are a gardener's lot, and the next is an inquisitive
neighbor asking what kind of tree that is. She is pointing to a
large hunk of ornamental grass. I need to whack it down to the
ground to make way for new growth, and it is overdue for dividing.
Slyly I suggest that she could have some for free if she'd like to
help in the division. We shall see.
</P>
<P>
   The ornamental plum that is bedeviled with black knot, a fungal
disease, is almost gone now. I hack off all the diseased parts, and
perhaps it will spring back to life from the sparse sprouts that
remain. Otherwise, I will be acquiring that lacecap hydrangea I
have wanted for several years.
</P>
<P>
   The apple tree undergoes its regular butchery, this year another
large, high branch removed to let in light, while smaller branches
that drag the ground also are removed, along with watersprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Peonies are spring, but first the old foliage must go and wire
rings installed above them to keep the heavy stems of the new
plants from flopping. I take care to not disturb the swelling buds
rising from the crowns. Each stake of each ring strikes a rock, but
eventually I shove them firmly in place.
</P>
<P>
   Roses require pruning (they also require a measure of blood),
sweetpeas demand a dollop of composted manure where I plant them,
and squirrels just insist on replanting certain bulbs (I am
positive I did not stick crocuses in the herb garden).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, like dogs, gardening is demanding. But there is enjoyment,
too, as we face our spring tasks. Even as we toil, we see. The
bulbs that went in last fall are up and glorious. Many, many
daffodils, delicate snowdrops under a dwarf blue spruce, cheery
yellow winter aconite here and there. The furry catkins on the
pussy willow bring smiles, and the spread of violets throughout the
lawn makes us beam.
</P>
<P>
   As old friends emerge, we forget winter's losses and glory in
the season aborning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
