<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9066 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      04-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TOUR COULD TURN CREE SUMMER INTO HOT STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In December, singer and sometime actress Cree Summer
opened for Lenny Kravitz on his European tour. In many ways, she
considers it one of the most terrifying experiences in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights would go black,'' Summer recalls, on the phone from
her home in the Hollywood Hills. ``Like 15,000 people in the
audience think Lenny is coming out. Then here I come, and everybody
is like, `Who the (expletive) is that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   History probably won't repeat itself next week in Phoenix, when
Summer does the honors again for the recent Grammy winner. She's
familiar to sitcom viewers from her run as the idealistic Freddie
on ``ADifferent World'' as well as her voice-over work on the
animated ``Rugrats'' and ``Tiny Toons.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get nightmarish visions of another Tatyana Ali assaulting
the radio waves. Summer's enchanting ``Street Faerie'' disc is a
cool, refreshing taste of retro-minded soul and sensual rock.
Production chores are handled by her pal Kravitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your friends push you,'' Summer enthuses. ``When I'm working
with strangers, I can get a little timid or scared. With friends,
I'm willing to try anything, because there's a lot of trust
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Summer, a self-proclaimed daughter of a couple
of hippies, grew up on a Canadian Indian reservation. She has a
trippy, bohemian way of talking that is engaging. Same thing goes
for her music, which is delicately spiritual in nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just inspired by music,'' she says. ``I just talked to
this chick the other day, and she told me she draws every day. I
felt like putting a pencil in my eye! On the one hand, it's really
mystical. On the other hand, it's really frustrating because I'm
completely at the mercy of the muse.''
</P>
<P>
   Her songs spring to life as poems, then music is added later.
Inspiration comes from the strangest places; for example, imagine
the birth process of the swirling ``Soul Sister.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenny and I picked the songs according to how we felt each
day,'' she recalls. ``One day I showed up with this T-shirt that
said `Soul Sister.' There was no rhyme or reason for anything _
that's why I liked the process so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer and Kravitz go back a long way. She's also friends with
Lisa Bonet, star of ``A Different World'' (a ``Cosby Show''
spinoff) and Kravitz's ex. Apparently it was an amicable split,
because Bonet directed Summer's first video and was involved in the
album's recording in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was laugh, talk, (expletive) and write,'' Summer
says. ``It was just a gas. I feel so safe that way. When you sit
around and share your dreams with your friends, just talking smack
about the stuff you're going to do . . . when it happens, it just
blows your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The disc hit streets last week, the realization of her dream.
But it's not her first time in the studio. She cut an album for
Capitol Records in the early '90s and toured behind the disc.
Ultimately, the album never was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that happened,'' she says. ``At the time, it was
horrible. But now, for this record, I'm not going in green. I know
my way around the studio. I knew what I was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think back about making a record in my early 20s, when
you're young and righteous and your writing is just (expletive). I
think I lucked out that it never got released.''
</P>
<P>
   She focuses exclusively on ``Street Faerie'' material in her
shows. After surviving the European dates, she's looking forward to
seeing how American crowds will react.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nerve-racking enough singing in front of 150 people, let
alone 15,000,'' she says. ``I mean, even my eyebrows were
sweating.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, while audiences responded positively to her music, there
was a different reaction when she simply walked around the streets
of the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I went, the people thought I was Scary Spice,''
says the big-haired Summer, spitting out the words. ``People get
locked on to something and they don't care, but they all thought I
was Scary Spice.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, other than the awe-inspiring hair, she doesn't
resemble the Brit hitmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for that, honey!'' she says with a laugh. ``And
thank you, Lord! That is one woman I don't want to look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1417EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
