<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9075 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-22 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS FROM COLORADO: BOMB THE TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The real world didn't become defined by
television until my junior year in high school when a lone gunman
(or so I believe) killed our president.
</P>
<P>
   Then the real world, as filtered through TV, began being defined
by a series of lone gunmen. TV and lone gunmen sort of grew up
together.
</P>
<P>
   This week TV and reality were redefined by an organized,
uniformed club of lone gunmen at a high school.
</P>
<P>
   The high prince of all lone gunmen, celebrated in movies, books
and continued conversation, was Charles Whitman, who climbed the
tower at the University of Texas and shot 15 people to death.
</P>
<P>
   That was on Aug. 1, 1966, and I even remember where I was at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   I was a patient in the Bethesda Naval Hospital in Maryland, then
filled with wounded, embittered teen-age Marines. A few crazy ones
talked about what weapons they would have taken to the tower.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman had some hunting rifles and a shotgun. One Marine I knew
said he could have done better with an M-60 machine gun and a
grenade launcher.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that these guys at Bethesda were evil, or that they
would have done anything. That's just the way the inflamed and
bored male teen-age mind sometimes works.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, teen-agers don't commit a fraction of the homicides
that adults think they do. Unless the adults send them to war.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the occasional evil teen-age mind or two.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, only nine people were killed this school year
in American schools, down from 55 in 1992. School is a safer place
to be than home. School buses kill more children than guns. School
lunches may be more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly 13 more people have been killed in one school by two
young gunmen who then took their lives. But 200 million people were
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Visceral horror outweighs statistics. We don't like to believe
statistics. We slurp up horror. The scale of this horror outweighs
even a growing and vicious war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   All over America, people will tell you TV coverage of the
massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., was
sensationalistic, and it was.
</P>
<P>
   But the people still watch, and TV still serves it up. The
coverage may increase black trench coat sales and put strange ideas
in disturbed teen-age minds. Maybe a few will talk about what
weapons they would have brought into school.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of stuff definitely will appear on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Things were different before Lee Harvey Oswald, Charles Whitman
and the Vietnam War, the failure of which gave us Rambo, Soldier of
Fortune magazine and paramilitary culture, or ``Warrior Dreams,''
as James William Gibson titled his great book on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, my friends and I hated the popular kids and they
hated us. We owned guns. But we didn't shoot anyone. Our .22s were
for shooting rats at the town dump. Our parents made us work and
kept us in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   When we wanted revenge on the popular kids, we ambushed them
with snowballs. We drove the football players crazy by starting a
soccer club. No American played soccer in the early 1960s. It was
the sport of outcasts, and we wore funny shorts and knee socks.
</P>
<P>
   We knew high school was stupid and the only acceptable stance
was to be different.
</P>
<P>
   There were no video games. The most violent movie was
``Psycho,'' and my mom wouldn't let me see it. We had heard about
Charlie Starkweather and his girlfriend, Caril Ann Fugate, driving
around the country killing people in 1958. They were later
celebrated by the 1973 movie, ``Badlands.''
</P>
<P>
   We have immortalized our psychopaths since the days of Billy the
Kid. If CNN had been around in Wild West times, it would have had a
bureau in Dodge City.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a pair of teen-age lone gunmen blew a
multibillion-dollar war off the front pages. They got what they
wanted, going out in a blaze of gunfire with vengeance for God
knows what slights.
</P>
<P>
   This week, many Americans sounded like Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, when he commented on the massacre in Colorado,
saying, ``Violence is obviously the only principle and value which
the American society knows, unfortunately for its youth and future
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to admit, the timing was atrocious. President Clinton
was saying that our children need to be taught to ``resolve their
conflicts with words, not weapons,'' just as his cruise missiles
hit a high-rise building in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   We've been getting our heads whipped back and forth between
aerial video of falling bombs and aerial pictures of children
fleeing a high school in terror.
</P>
<P>
   But we know Milosevic is wrong when he says violence is our only
value. So why are so many Americans bemoaning our supposedly
murderous culture?
</P>
<P>
   I'm critical of our air war in the Balkans, but I would never
say it is being waged for the sake of violence. Neither would I say
that our culture is corrupt or our children hopelessly vicious.
</P>
<P>
   The homicide rate is falling nationwide, but rising
precipitously on television. One study shows murders increased 721
percent on network news between 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If you own a gun, keep it locked away from children. But first
shoot your TV.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-MURPHY-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     04-22 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-MURPHY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (s and a coding)  
 BELMONT, Mass.: ... 19-year-old prospect.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riding on a godforsaken old school bus _ ``built for
sixth-graders,'' recalls Bonnell _ through sweltering Carolina
nights from one obscure outpost to another, Bonnell would read the
Book of Mormon, and curious teammates would approach him, asking
questions. Bonnell noticed that Murphy was a listener, though, not
a questioner. So one night he got on the bus after Murphy, sat next
to him, and began reading, illuminated by a fishing flashlight. He
and Murphy quickly struck up a dialogue, and the next morning at
the team's roach motel, Bonnell asked Murphy if e would like to
pursue the discussion with a couple of Mormon missionaries. The
answer was yes. The day after the season, Bonnell baptized Murphy
into the church.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons don't drink or smoke or curse, and Murphy acknowledges,
``I had to make some changes in my lifestyle,'' though he won't
elaborate. At any rate, it doesn't seem that a dramatic overhaul
was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd drink a beer every now and then before,'' says Bonnell,
``but Dale was never a runaround guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnell recalls that Murphy's conversion occurred during a time
of Christian reawakening, athletes included, and that
``nondenominational Christianity became so big that it got to be
like a denomination. On Sundays, we'd hold services before the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Murphy is emphatic in dismissing the widespread
notion that religion and competition don't mix, that being devout
is at odds with being a winner. ``Competitiveness is not an
un-Christian thing,'' he says. ``You can be competitive and a good
sport. Maybe I wasn't outwardly emotional about the game _ I was
never one to show emotion just for the sake of showing emotion _
but believe me, if we lost, I'd kick the water cooler. If I had to
take a guy out at second, I'd take him out. If I'd been a pitcher,
I'd have knocked you down if I felt it was necessary. I tried to
have a level of intensity. You can't play without a fire burning
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof was in the 1982 and '83 MVP Awards, the two NL home
run and RBI titles, the five 30-homer and 100-RBI seasons Murphy
accumulated while earning a reputation as one of the game's
courtliest gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he retired in 1993 after a couple of months with the
Rockies _ ``I figured that if I couldn't hit home runs in Denver, I
couldn't hit home runs, period'' _ Murphy was adrift. Despite
standing offers of an organizational job from the Braves, Phillies,
and Rockies, ``I kind of by design wanted to get away from
baseball,'' he says. He did some public speaking and endorsements,
spent a year in Atlanta, then moved with his wife, Nancy _ a native
of Utah and lifelong Mormon whom he'd met during a semester at
Brigham Young University in 1978 _ to the town of Alpine, between
Salt Lake City and Provo. While helping to raise seven sons and a
daughter who now range in age from 5 to 18, he was still casting
about for something he could immerse himself in when, as Murphy
recounts it, something almost mystical occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the mission presidents have three-year terms, about 100
become vacant every year,'' he says. ``Someone _ I have no idea who
_ nominated me. I went through the interview process, and one of
the 12 church leaders called and asked to see us. Nancy and I had
no idea what it was about.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his recruitment lacked the intrigue Murphy suspects.
Boyd K. Packer, a former Boston Mission president who now is
president of the 12 apostles (leaders), was the man who contacted
Murphy. ``We keep track of men as we travel around who have the
spirit and capacity to relate to young men in particular, who know
the gospel, and are stable in their professional and family
circumstances,'' explains Packer. ``Everybody knew Dale Murphy. It
was well known that he had served in callings for the church.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Murphys met with Packer and he told them Dale was under
consideration for a mission presidency, ``it was the most surprised
and honored Nancy and I had ever been,'' says Dale.
</P>
<P>
   His lack of a business background was not considered a
deterrent. ``We have mission presidents from all walks of life,''
says Packer.
</P>
<P>
   His fame could have been. ``Some celebrities are celebrities,''
says Packer. ``When Dale looks in the mirror, he doesn't see a
celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Until July 2000, when Murphy looks in the mirror, he will see
the president of the Boston Mission. After that, he's not sure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His only connection with baseball now is as an assistant coach
on his 11-year-old son Travis's Little League team, the Red Sox.
``I'm in charge of hitting,'' he says. ``We'd better hit this year.
I've never felt such pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Murphy is a magnet on the diamond. The kids listen
raptly as he delivers the same message countless other coaches have
passed along to deaf ears. And when he provides individual
attention for a would-be slugger, the fathers gawk and elbow one
another: ``That's Dale Murphy.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't know whether he'll resume a professional affiliation
with the game; despite those standing offers, ``I don't know about
the fit.'' One thing he's sure about: His dream destination is
Cooperstown. This year, his first for Hall of Fame eligibility, he
received 96 of the 373 votes required for induction. ``I thought
about it a lot this year and I'll think about it a lot next year,''
he says. ``I think I have a chance. I have some borderline
statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnell can envision a future in the church for Murphy as one of
the general authorities, ``although if you ask Dale, he'll deny it
because he's so humble. That's why he'd be perfect for the job.
What you see is exactly what he is _ a gentlemanly, wonderful
man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
