<HEADER>
A9087 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-MURPHY-2TAKES     04-22 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-MURPHY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW CALLING DRAWS EX-BRAVES SLUGGER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (s and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, Mass. _ A large scythe leans against the wall in the
far corner of his office, just as a bat once rested against the
back of his locker.
</P>
<P>
   The former has replaced the latter in his arsenal, but his
current teammates needn't fear for their safety. Dale Murphy does
not wield this implement as he once did a Louisville Slugger while
winning two consecutive National League Most Valuable Player awards
and clubbing 398 home runs during a 14-year career from which he
emerged as a borderline Hall of Fame candidate. The scythe is
purely symbolic. ``It's the analogy of harvesting souls,'' says
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   He is responsible for an extensive crop in his latest line of
work _ volunteer work, that is. Like all but a handful of others
who serve the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints,
popularly known as Mormons, Murphy receives no compensation in his
role as president of the Boston Mission. During his three-year
tour, which began in July 1997, he gets a house, a car, a food
allowance, and a dizzying array of duties. ``This is the most
challenging thing I've ever done,'' says Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   So pardon the mess. Sifting through the clutter on his desk in
the corner office of an eight-room downtown suite that houses the
Boston Mission's administration, Murphy laughs and says, ``It looks
like my locker. My teammates would be quite familiar with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they probably wouldn't. The few vestiges of baseball _
a Norman Rockwell illustration of some kids engaged in a sandlot
dialogue; a couple of plastic figurines from a birthday cake; a bat
from Cooperstown sent by a friend _ are overwhelmed by the
trappings of his calling. Behind his chair is a large portrait of
Christ. A Bible sits atop his slide drawer. His desk is piled with
reports and Mormon literature and little colored pieces of sticky
paper that facilitate his major undertaking: overseeing 209
missionaries throughout Massachusetts and parts of New Hampshire,
Rhode Island, Vermont, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like the supervisor,'' says Murphy, 43. ``I help, I train,
I educate, I see how they're doing. We help find them apartments
and provide them cars.''
</P>
<P>
   He readily acknowledges that he is far afield from his career as
an All-Star, Gold Glove outfielder spent primarily with the Atlanta
Braves before brief end-of-the-line stops in Philadelphia and
Colorado. He likens it to facing Nolan Ryan every day, and a look
at the wall across from his desk bears this out. It resembles a
strategic map in a war room, except that this one is dotted with
small pictures of each missionary in Murphy's jurisdiction. They
are placed under headings that identify their territories; each
photo is accompanied by an index card listing hometown, age, and
other pertinent background information, along with a slip of
stick-'em paper indicating months of service.
</P>
<P>
   These missionaries _ mostly young men and women, with a
sprinkling of couples whose children have grown or who have no
children _ are charged with spreading the word of God as revealed
to church founder Joseph Smith in the 1820s and contained in the
Book of Mormon, subtitled, ``Another Testament of Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible is part of our canonized Scripture,'' says Murphy,
``and we believe in something more. We believe that God the Father
came to Joseph Smith and said the true church of Christ was not on
Earth at the time, that it had been gone roughly since the deaths
of the apostles.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the strongly committed need apply. The typical missionary's
day begins at 6:30 a.m. and includes two hours of religious study
followed by 12 hours of proselytizing in pairs _ until 9:30 each
night _ with lights out at 10:30. During their terms, missionaries
cannot watch television, read newspapers and magazines, listen to
popular music, or date. They receive no compensation; in fact, they
are required to provide $375 monthly toward expenses.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the missionary term is two years for men, 1 1/2 for
women, and no one is allowed a second tour of duty. ``It's so
rigorous,'' says Murphy. ``It's very challenging. The challenge is
to find people receptive to the message of who we are: Christian,
family-oriented, service-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no shortage of applicants, culled from a church
membership numbering some 10 million worldwide. The popular
perception is that the Mormon stronghold is Salt Lake City, and the
church indeed is headquartered there. But Murphy points out that
less than half the Utah capital's population is now Mormon (perhaps
they've been displaced by International Olympic Committee members),
and more than 50 percent of the church's constituency is outside
the United States. That's one reason the Book of Mormon can be
found in 42 languages, from Albanian to Zulu, in one of the Boston
Mission's offices.
</P>
<P>
   There are some 300 missions, some 60,000 missionaries, and
Murphy has noticed a transformation among those in his purview.
``When they start, they're out of their comfort zone,'' he says.
``But from a reluctance to being here, they go through a change,
and eventually, they're reluctant to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   That easily could describe Murphy's Mormon journey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Portland, Ore., and raised in the Presbyterian
faith. He considered his parents extremely spiritual; as for
himself, ``growing up, I had a few (religious) thoughts. When I was
18 or 19, I started having a few more.''
</P>
<P>
   He found a receptive audience in Barry Bonnell, a future major
league journeyman outfielder who was his teammate with the Braves'
Single A affiliate at Greenwood, S.C., in 1975. Bonnell was married
and a Mormon, but he struck up a lasting friendship with the
19-year-old prospect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
