<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLSON SEEMS TO HAVE FOUND TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A huge development took place at Bank One Ballpark
Wednesday night, and it had nothing to do with the Diamondbacks'
victory or their first sweep or climbing two games over .500.
</P>
<P>
   The club's closing situation may finally have been resolved and,
lo and behold, the guy to take care of their worries may be the
same one who put them in a temporary mess.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter called on Gregg Olson to record the final
three outs of Wednesday's 4-2 victory over the Phillies. Yes, the
same Gregg Olson who badly botched all three of his save
opportunities during the first week.
</P>
<P>
   Olson fired three straight strikes to Bobby Abreu moments after
he replaced Todd Stottlemyre one batter into the ninth inning. He
then got catcher Mike Leiberthal on a called third strike before
giving up a double and getting the final out on a sharp grounder to
third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably the last step I needed,'' Olson said shortly
after recording his first save. ``There were definitely some nerves
going on there. After I got the first two outs, I started sniffing
the end and probably got a little jumpy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once that final out was done, I felt like all those monkeys
that were on my back jumped off.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter had told Olson before the start of Tuesday's game that
he was returning to the full-time closer's role. This was important
not only for Olson, who was in need of serious psychological help a
little over a week ago, but to the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of specialized relievers, it is almost vital for a
club's bullpen to know its role. It is the single biggest reason so
few clubs use a bullpen by committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start piece-mealing things together, it messes up
Darren Holmes, Greg Swindell, John Frascatore, Brian Anderson and
Vladimir Nunez,'' Showalter said. ``Oly knows this was just the
first taste. He knows this was just the start. You don't want to
think too much with your heart, but it's tough with him because
he's a guy who gives with all his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson remains heartbroken over blowing three ninth-inning leads
during the first six games of the season, when so many questions
surrounding the bullpen arose.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wednesday's save was simply step No. 1. By no means should
it be taken as a clear indication that all is right with Olson, who
was successful in 30 of 33 closing situations last season.
</P>
<P>
   Olson is not in the clear just yet, but the Diamondbacks are one
step closer to having normalcy return to their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Olson was equally wounded during the club's home opener when he
was loudly booed during player introductions. The boos did not come
as any big surprise to the 10-year veteran, but that doesn't mean
they didn't sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else, they stick,'' Olson said. ``No doubt
about it. I'll admit that I use them as motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia closer Jeff Brantley, who knows a thing or two
about being booed, can sympathize with Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for him (Wednesday) was when he came in and
the fans were behind him,'' Brantley said. ``When you hear boos as
you come in from the pen, it's an immediate downer. But he's not a
young kid. He knows what he needs to do.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, the Diamondbacks appear to be hitting on all
cylinders as they prepare to leave on their longest trip, one that
will take them to four cities.
</P>
<P>
   They can rest a little more assured knowing they have one person
to close games again, not several. Showalter used a bullpen by
committee to close out Monday's victory over Philadelphia, bringing
in Holmes to get the second out of the ninth and Swindell for the
final out.
</P>
<P>
   It worked that night but doing so over time could only turn a
bullpen into one big, confused mess.
</P>
<P>
   Olson has been around long enough to realize this job is not his
for the duration simply because he has it right now. This is a job
he must continue to perform at.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the Diamondbacks, there is no one else on the
roster they would rather see in the closing role. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
