<SLUG> BC-PC-NETWORKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL PRODUCT MAY EASE COST OF HOME NETWORKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIE J. BALBA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the prices of personal computers moving
toward affordable levels, more and more families are buying them,
creating a new breed of computer-dependent households in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The number of households with at least one or two computers has
soared. According to a 1998 Dataquest survey, 28 million households
will have at least two computers by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   As people buy more computers, they consider buying additional
peripherals, installing separate phone lines for Internet
connections and subscribing to an additional Internet service
provider. To bypass these costly additions, many have considered
networking their home computers to share resources and peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   Networking can be a costly endeavor, however. A traditional home
network involves such expenses as adapters, wires and cables
including installation, hubs (if necessary) and the time spent in
learning and implementing the features of the operating system.
There may be additional costs for adding network cards.
</P>
<P>
   To justify home networking, its costs must not exceed the cost
of buying duplicate resources, such as printers. If each home
computer user needs a printer, would it be more expensive to buy a
second printer or to install a network to share the printer with
another home computer? What technical know-how is needed to install
another printer vs. installing a network?
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. of Santa Clara, the world's top chip maker, says it
has a solution to the cost and hassle of traditional networking:
the Intel AnyPoint Home Network, a home networking system.
</P>
<P>
   The AnyPoint Home Network kit includes all the hardware and
software needed to connect two home computers and enable them to
share Internet access, share resources and communicate with each
other using any existing phone line.
</P>
<P>
   Intel says that any home computer user who can set up a new
printer or install a new piece of software can also install and use
the AnyPoint Home Network.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Intel network uses regular phone lines, it's not
supposed to compromise telephone service. In my case, though, I
could hear some background noise on the phone lines after I'd
connected the network.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it affected the telephone connection. After using the
AnyPoint Home Network, we tried to call our home number from a
cellular phone and found that our line was busy even after we had
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Transferring files across the newly formed network was rather
quick, but it could be interrupted by such things as lifting the
telephone receiver. Printing to a remote printer was just as quick
as transferring a file across the network.
</P>
<P>
   When downloading files from the Internet, AnyPoint users can
choose to use either the server or the client. The server was
definitely faster.
</P>
<P>
   Although our modem speed is 56K bps, data transfer tops out at
32.3K bps in my neighborhood and sometimes fluctuates.
</P>
<P>
   I was happy to note that two people in our household can access
the Internet at the same time, thus overcoming a common problem
when one person needs the Net for business and another needs it for
school work.
</P>
<P>
   This product is not a bad buy for $189, which includes two
external units, cables to connect two computers and one or more
printers and Intel's networking software. It beats paying hundreds
for a traditional networking environment installed in a home
setting.
</P>
<P>
   I would advise you to be sure that your equipment can handle any
additional gadgets before you start any installation.
</P>
<P>
   Because this product is new on the market, I would also give it
a chance to grow and develop into something else. I am sure that
Intel is already looking into upgrading it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
