<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9112 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TILBERIS-APPRECIATION     04-22 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TILBERIS-APPRECIATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIZ TILBERIS: ICON OF PRINT AND LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In her 1998 autobiography, ``No Time to Die:
Living With Ovarian Cancer,'' Harper's BAZAAR editor-in-chief Liz
Tilberis wrote: ``It's hard to keep your spirits up when you're
looking and feeling drained, but you cannot allow yourself to dwell
on the side effects of chemo or regard it as a poison. It's a life
force, an ally, a weapon, a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis, 51, lost her five-year battle with cancer early
Wednesday morning in New York City. But she left an indelible mark
on the magazine she resurrected in 1992 and on the lives of the
people with whom she worked. Tilberis was to have been honored June
2 with the Council of Fashion Designers of America annual
Humanitarian Award; actress Meg Ryan plans a TV movie of the
memoir.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannette Chang, publisher of Harper's BAZAAR, said Wednesday,
``Two hundred and fifty people have called since 5:30 this morning.
You're talking about one who was so loved, who so inspired us. She
was influential in everything she said. Her leaving has left a huge
gap in this world. She touched so many people. I have spoken to
Donatella Versace. She is devastated. So is Laura Ungaro, Emanuel's
wife, and Calvin Klein, and Donna, Ralph ... all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   With her shiny, cropped helmet of silver hair (she never let it
grow back after chemotherapy), and her elegant Michael Kors skirts,
platinum Celine turtlenecks and deliciously sexy Manolo Blahnik
ankle boots, Liz Tilberis was the picture of English reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, said Simon Doonan, author of ``Confessions of a Window
Dresser,'' a fellow Briton (whose windows for Maxfield's in Los
Angeles and Barney's in New York are legendary), ``She had this
cheeky, Monty Pythonesque sense of humor along with this English
stiff upper lip thing. She dealt with her serious illness with
incredible integrity and bravery. No whining. She was a tour de
force of optimism, humor and kindness. She was lovely.''
</P>
<P>
   Doonan said he would create a Tilberis tribute window at
Barney's on Madison Avenue in a few weeks to coincide with the
memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Kelly was born Sept. 7, 1947, in Bath, England.
</P>
<P>
   When she enrolled in art school in Leeds as a teen-ager, she met
her future husband, Andrew Tilberis, who was one of her tutors.
</P>
<P>
   While the school forbade any romantic entanglements between
faculty and student, Liz and Andrew fell in love and married in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Two years earlier, however, she had entered a writing and design
contest sponsored by British Vogue. She won a summer internship and
signed on as a fashion assistant. Four years later, she became
fashion editor and in 1984 she was named executive fashion editor.
She worked for Anna Wintour, British Vogue's editor-in-chief, and
when Wintour left to take over House and Garden, she suggested that
Liz Tilberis move into her slot.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gross, author of ``Model,'' and former fashion editor of
New York Magazine, chronicled Tilberis' rocky ride as British
Vogue's slightly overweight editor with the pageboy bob and
straight-across bangs. He commented that the British press ``put
her through the wringer.'' After she slugged a security guard who
was rude to one of her staff during a Parisian fashion show, she
became a kind of heroine.
</P>
<P>
   When Tilberis came to the States with husband Andrew and their
two adopted children in 1992 to take the reins at Harper's BAZAAR,
the magazine had lost subscribers and was in a state of disrepair.
Hearst Magazines gave her both the imprimatur and the money to
bring back the luster of the 130-year-old publication.
</P>
<P>
   She hired the best art director she could find _ Fabien Baron,
who stripped the magazine down to create a spare, elegant look with
stacked type and pictures that bled off the pages. She hired
photographers Patrick Demarchelier and Peter Lindburgh and, said
Jeannette Chang, ``told them to get the best goddamn pictures they
could. They told her to make BAZAAR the most beautiful magazine in
the world. That was her mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of Tilberis' editions hit the stands in September
1992. The cover was supermodel Linda Evangelista's face and hand on
a stark white background with one cover line: ``Enter the era of
elegance ...''
</P>
<P>
   She beefed up the arts coverage, instituting sections on
literature, decor and fine arts, for which she had as good an eye
as she did for fashion. Eventually, Tilberis replaced supermodels
with celebrities, populating her covers with everyone from her
friend, Diana, the princess of Wales, to Calista Flockhart of
``Ally McBeal,'' Elizabeth Hurley and Hugh Grant and Sharon Stone.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first of the high fashion editors to discard the
ghostly ``heroin chic'' look, Chang recounted that Tilberis told
her photographers, ``Tell those girls to think of sex and put a
smile on their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She couldn't stand that drabby little look anymore,'' Chang
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis was devoted to Andrew, her husband of 28 years, and her
two boys. She tried to give them as normal a life as possible,
trundling out to the family's house in the Hamptons on weekends.
Brave and down-to-earth are two terms that come up the most to
describe Tilberis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always loved to read the foreword she wrote in the front of
the magazine,'' said Gladys Palmer, director of fashion at the
Academy of Art College and former fashion editor of the San
Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wrote to people in a very intimate, immediate way. You
really could identify with her. She spoke for a lot of women
instead of talking down to them. Anyone who read that page felt
assured rather than intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In writing ``No Time to Die,'' Tilberis could have dropped every
name she ever met (and the list of celebrities, writers, artists,
designers and photographers who considered her a friend is legion),
but she devotes a great part of the book to educating her
readership about ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She was diagnosed shortly after she came to the states with a
Stage III cancer which she blames upon the series of fertility
drugs she took in failed efforts to get pregnant. She underwent a
(then) experimental bone marrow transplant and managed to bounce
back each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a heroic fighter,'' said Cathleen Black, president of
Hearst Magazines. ``In many ways, it was the magazine that kept her
alive, knowing that she was choosing a cover or had a photo shoot
to assign. She kept going. We'd meet in the Ritz Bar in Paris and
have a drink and gossip and laugh. Here was a woman with great joie
de vivre, who was going to put all of her really painful days aside
and kept trucking on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
