<P>
   COMIC-BOOK-ART (Undated) _ ``You don't want your characters to
be perfect,'' said Mark Bode, looking spiky, disheveled and
agreeably imperfect himself in his Felix the Cat T-shirt, black
sneakers, earrings and slouchy, conspiratorial demeanor. ``You want
them to have problems, quirks, personality. Just as long as they're
not normal. Normal isn't very interesting, is it? You want your
characters to have something wrong with them.'' We are at the Words
and Pictures Museum in Northampton, Mass., one of three museums in
the United States (and the only one in the Northeast) devoted
solely to what the museum calls ``fine graphic narrative and
fantasy illustration,'' i.e., cartoon and comic-book art in all its
caricatured, heavy-metal humor and superhero permutations. By Peter
Applebome.
</P>
