<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASEKELA-2NDTAKE-HNS &LR;      04-22 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASEKELA-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
including the Supremes and Stevie Wonder.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He became part of rock-culture history when he joined Jimi
Hendrix, Otis Redding and dozens of hippie bands at the Monterey
Pop Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never knew where to place me,'' Masekela said. ``But the
fact that I was an activist got me with the flower children, so I
was a flower child, as well. I played the Fillmore in San Francisco
quite a few times. I had the pleasure of hanging out with Sly Stone
and Hendrix and the Grateful Dead and Big Brother &AMP; the Holding
Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Masekela has moved around. He's lived in Ghana, where he led a
group called Hedzollah Sounds. In Botswana, across the border from
South Africa, he put together a band called Kalahari, with which he
recorded the international hit album ``Techno Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   He was planning to build an international music school in
Botswana when a dozen South African activists were killed by South
African death squads. He left Botswana shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Masekela toured with Paul Simon on the Graceland tour,
which reintroduced South African music to the Western pop audience.
He then joined the touring cast of the hit South African musical
``Sarafina!''
</P>
<P>
   His experience in ``Sarafina!'' reminded him that home is not
only where the music is, but it's also where the heart is. And his
heart was in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Since he's returned to his homeland, Masekela has become
something of a national institution. His latest album, ``Black to
the Future,'' has sold more than 100,000 copies _ the equivalent of
double-platinum in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Africans don't have the groupie mentality, with all the
screaming and fainting,'' he said. ``But it can be kind of a drag
to hang out with me in South Africa, because everybody knows me.
And everybody sings along with the songs when we play them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish that everybody was as advantaged and comfortable as I
am. But it's wonderful to be home.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASEKELA-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      04-22 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASEKELA-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASEKELA'S MUSIC IS HOME FREE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, Hugh Masekela figured home was wherever
the music was.
</P>
<P>
   The South African trumpeter left his country in 1960 to attend
the Manhattan School of Music. With his ex-wife, Miriam Makeba, he
helped introduce South African rhythms and melodies to American
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But when Masekela spoke out against the apartheid policies of
the white South African government, he found himself banished from
his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, Masekela lived in the United States. In the '70s
and '80s, he spent time in Liberia, Nigeria, Ghana and Botswana. He
titled one of his best albums Home Is Where the Music Is.
</P>
<P>
   When his mother died, he was denied permission to return to
South Africa, even for the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we'd ever come back,'' said Masekela by phone
from his home outside Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela
was released from prison as a result of international pressure,
Masekela was allowed to move back to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see so many wars,'' said Masekela. ``It's a miracle that
this leadership taught us to forgive the past. Not to forget, but
to forgive, so we didn't burn the country down. We are still
economically oppressed, but it's wonderful to be living in this
country in peace after 350 years of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Masekela, 59, grew up in the township of Witbank. As a child, he
sang with an Anglican school choir. He fell in love with the
trumpet after seeing the movie Young Man with a Horn, starring Kirk
Douglas, based on the life of American jazz trumpeter Bix
Beiderbecke.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of a local priest, Masekela formed a band
with other township youth. His first musical hero was Louis
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was everybody's hero,'' said Masekela. ``In my
township, everybody knew ''Blueberry Hill,'' everybody knew ``When
It's Sleepy Time Down South,'' everybody knew ``Rockin' Chair.'' It
was not just musicians who liked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about Louis Armstrong is that he brought music
down to everybody's level. He made it universally accessible. Of
course, he blew a great horn, but it was always simple. You could
sing along with his trumpet lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also taught Masekela about maintaining a positive
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style of music made it enjoyable to be alive. ''What a
Wonderful World'' came way down the line, but he had been singing
it in his soul all the time. He taught everybody to say `Yeah!' and
to walk with a little dip in their hip instead of looking dignified
with powdered wigs.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Masekela arrived in the United States, he had fallen
under the spell of bebop trumpeter Clifford Brown, as well as jazz
modernists such as John Coltrane. Miles Davis and Dizzy Gillespie
suggested that he experiment with a hybrid of African rhythms and
jazz improvisation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, `There are thousands of us. There is only one of
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'60s, Masekela scored a pop hit with ``Grazin' in the
Grass,'' based on a traditional South African folk melody. He
toured with folk artists such as Harry Belafonte, as well as with
pop-soul stars, including the Supremes and Stevie Wonder.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
