A9151 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-EXISTENZ-TEX     04-22 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EXISTENZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU SHOULD BE GAME FOR THIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spell-checker-challenging title of David Cronenberg's
``eXistenZ'' refers to a game, and a game is what the movie plays
with viewers' minds. Cronenberg is out to deconstruct notions of
reality, as if he were making a more intellectual answer to ``The
Matrix,'' and by the time ``eXistenZ'' ends, you may find yourself
wanting to see it again just to unravel its knots.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that this is a sort of Cronenberg-lite, a movie with
more humor and less sense of confrontation than recent Cronenberg
efforts such as ``Crash'' and ``Naked Lunch'' (it also helps that
the movie is a mere 90 minutes long). Jennifer Jason Leigh _ in a
sly, flirtatious performance that belies her more introverted
nature _ plays Allegra Geller, whose design of the virtual-reality
game eXistenZ has given her a rock-star celebrity status. It's also
affected some folks so strongly that they want to kill her, and an
assassin nearly succeeds at a demonstration of the game. Allegra
goes on the lam, taking along baffled security guard Ted Pikul
(who's merely a moonlighting publicist, played by ``Gattaca's''
Jude Law). To get more insight into what's going on, Allegra and a
reluctant Pikul play the game.
</P>
<P>
   You can see why Pikul is reluctant; playing involves having a
large hole drilled into your back so that what looks like a giant
umbilical cord can be plugged directly into the spinal cord. The
``umby cord'' connects to a kidney-shaped port that has breastlike
qualities, which the user manipulates to play the game. The
lifelike port is virtually a supporting actor; it's said that Leigh
developed such a maternal attachment to it that she took it home
during filming.
</P>
<P>
   While on the run, Allegra and Pikul run into a series of
eccentrics played by Willem Dafoe, Ian Holm and Don McKellar; the
actors employ odd accents (the dependable Holm appears to be doing
a Boris Badenov impersonation) as a way of furthering the movie's
reality-twisting themes. Cronenberg, who was inspired to write a
story of an artist on the run after meeting Salman Rushdie, says he
couldn't resist ``playing'' the game himself, and the screenplay
began to take on a life of its own, adding to the feeling that the
movie is making things up as it goes along.
</P>
<P>
   Although on the surface ``eXistenZ'' appears slight, especially
for Cronenberg, it keeps coming back after you see it. It evokes
faint echoes of 1997's ``The Game,'' but without the glossy veneer
and underlying sense of smugness. ``The Game'' was essentially one
long practical joke that didn't hold up under scrutiny;
``eXistenZ,'' with its underpinnings of existential philosophy and
man-as-technology, is one of the most thought-provoking escapist
entertainments to come along in a while. It's receiving limited
distribution, but it's well worth seeking out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``eXistenZ''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: David Cronenberg
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jennifer Jason Leigh, Jude Law
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, violence and some minorly gross
visuals
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
