<SLUG> BC-STATES-TAX-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PENNSYLVANIANS HAVE BETTER THAN AVERAGE CHANCE OF AVOIDING
IRS AUDITS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 21 -- Fear of being audited by the IRS is
common to taxpayers everywhere, but Pennsylvanians have less to
worry about than residents of many other states.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania ranked 25 out of the 33 IRS districts for the
likelihood of being audited last year, according to the
Transactional Records Access Clearinghouse at Syracuse University,
which collects and analyzes IRS data.
</P>
<P>
   William Kressman, a spokesman for the Pennsylvania IRS district,
said the state's rank was remarkable because it is the fifth
largest district in population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has one of the highest numbers of returns for an individual
district,'' Kressman said. ``But I have no reason to think there's
a difference in quality or accuracy of returns from Pennsylvania,
than from somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the IRS audited 17,046 of the 5.5 million individual
tax returns filed in Pennsylvania, giving residents about a 0.31
percent chance of being examined. The national audit rate was 0.46
percent in fiscal year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the rate of audits in the country has gone down in
recent years from 66 percent in 1992. Still, since that year,
Pennsylvania has been among the bottom 10 IRS districts when ranked
for the chances of being audited.
</P>
<P>
   Tax experts attribute the nationwide drop in audits to the
downsizing of the IRS. They say Pennsylvania's luck may be because
the state has fewer than average IRS agents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the national average of IRS agents per million people
was 54.4, Pennsylvania had only 44.8.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't a lot to it,'' said Bernie Phillips, tax
manager, at the National Society of Accountants. ``There are fewer
IRS agents, and the ones who leave often take with them the old
line harsher technique. There's some slackening in the old attitude
... a 'kinder gentler' IRS, which we've all heard about.''
</P>
<P>
   As IRS agents leave Pennsylvania, the number of audits goes
down. Last year in Pennsylvania, there were more than 6,000 fewer
audits than in 1994. There were 615 IRS agents in Pennsylvania in
1994 and 538 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said audit rates differ in the 33 districts, because
some IRS district offices are tougher than others.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Northern California taxpayers had the highest audit
rate of 1.08 percent, while Ohio taxpayers were least likely to be
audited, with a rate of 0.22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers in neighboring New Jersey were only slightly worse off
than Pennsylvania, being the 24th most likely to be audited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happens because of the particular personnel in a
district,'' Phillips said. ``It depends on how aggressive the
personnel are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
