<SLUG> BC-NO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO': A FARCICAL `NO' (MEANING NO, AND, YES, A PUN ON NOH) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The notion that history will sooner or later repeat itself as
farce is given an intriguing twist in the Canadian director Robert
Lepage's amusingly knotty film ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just repeated history that can be ludicrous, the film
asserts. It can be pretty silly the first time around, especially
when recalled a decade later by the people who lived through it.
</P>
<P>
   The particular bit of Canadian history ``No'' cleverly
deconstructs is the October crisis of 1970. That fall the Quebec
Liberation Front, a militant group advocating the secession of
Quebec province from the rest of the country, initiated a series of
uprisings that led to a declaration of martial law throughout
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem facing ``No,'' which opens Friday in
Manhattan, has to do with historical recognition. While many
Americans may have heard something about the October crisis, it was
eclipsed at the time by political turmoil in the United States. For
an American audience, the events the movie remembers will have
little or no resonance.
</P>
<P>
   In recalling those turbulent days, ``No,'' adapted from a
fragment of Lepage's seven-hour theatrical epic ``The Seven Streams
of the River Ota,'' explores questions of national identity through
the interrelationships of a group of Canadian and Japanese artists,
theater performers, diplomats and a Japanese translator who was
blinded in the bombing of Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film is set in Osaka, Japan, at Expo '70, an event
that also marked the 25th anniversary of the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian contribution to Expo '70 is an admittedly shoddy
production (done in French) of a Feydeau farce starring Sophie
(Anne-Marie Cadieux), a headstrong, wildly self-dramatizing actress
who while in Japan discovers that she is pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has a boyfriend, Michel (Alexis Martin), back home,
Sophie is not sure who the father is, and the couple are on the
verge of separating over the issue of raising a family. Michel, an
aspiring left-wing playwright dabbling in revolutionary politics,
has assembled a crude homemade bomb with two of his cronies.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' whose title is a pun on Japanese Noh drama, underscores
its bicultural view by switching back and forth between color (for
its Japanese scenes) and grainy black and white (for its Canadian
scenes). The ineptly performed Feydeau play in which Sophie
performs becomes a metaphor for the behavior of all the major
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Sophie allows herself to be taken out for dinner by Walter
(Richard Frechette), a philandering diplomat, and his mean, bossy
wife, Patricia (Marie Gignac). In the movie's wittiest scene, life
imitates art as the relationship among the three evolves into a
real-life bedroom farce unfolding in a hotel room that resembles
the tacky set of the Feydeau play.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in Quebec City, Michel and his revolutionary
cohorts embark on a bumbling, farcical exercise in terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   If ``No'' is an ingeniously structured play of ideas and has
impressively accurate period detail and several tart comic
performances (Ms. Gignac is particularly effective as the imperious
Patricia), it isn't a very compelling movie.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its location settings, the film feels less like an
unfolding story than a filmed theatrical collage whose vivid
characters become abrasive when blown up on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `NO'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Lepage; written (in French and English, with
English subtitles by Lepage and Andre Morency, inspired by Lepage's
play ``Seven Streams of the River Ota''; director of photography,
Pierre Mignot; edited by Aube Foglia; produced by Bruno Jobin;
released by New Yorker Films. Running time: 83 minutes. This film
is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Anne-Marie Cadieux (Sophie), Marie Brassard (Hanako),
Alexis Martin (Michel), Marie Gignac (Patricia) and Richard
Frechette (Walter).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
