<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-MOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CITY SHAKEN BY SCHOOL SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROSS McKEON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The large illuminated sign in front of the Denver
Center for the Performing Arts read: ``A time to reflect.''
</P>
<P>
   On news racks at every street corner, Wednesday's Denver Post
carried the double-deck banner headline ``High School Massacre.''
Its competitor, the Rocky Mountain News, displayed ``Heartbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   Coors Field, home of Major League Baseball's Colorado Rockies,
was empty. A scheduled game had been postponed for a second
straight day.
</P>
<P>
   Gray skies high above Denver's usually bustling lower downtown
area _ affectionately known here as ``Lodo'' _ matched the mood of
the people on the streets. The high school shooting that took place
about 25 miles southwest of Denver on Tuesday was on the mind of
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Offenbaker works at a small convenience and souvenir store,
Out of Time?, on Blake Street. Located along a stretch of popular
eateries and bars, it is usually buzzing with patrons.
</P>
<P>
   During a 10-minute interview, no one entered the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are melancholy,'' Offenbaker said. ``They push to go on
with their lives, but in the back of their minds they are thinking
it could have been someone they knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Offenbaker has lived in Denver for 13 years. He has overcome
polio, and because of that he professes a strong faith. He was
shaken by the shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here are two young boys,'' Offenbaker said of the gunmen who
died in the carnage. ``You can't call them young men because they
weren't yet. They're still children. What was going on in their
heads?''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, Karen is a bartender at Dick's Last Resort,
just a Mark McGwire clout away from Coors Field. No matter what
time of the day or night, people are eating there. And they were
Wednesday, too. But instead of television sets tuned to sports
programming, channels were fixed to news stations.
</P>
<P>
   A co-worker reached up to change the channel and Karen
interrupted, ``No, they're going to tell us the names of the
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Colehour staffs the concierge desk at the downtown Westin
Hotel. Since the shooting, she has found out-of-towners to be
respectful and understanding, all except one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one guy I wanted to hit,'' she said. ``He didn't
understand why the baseball game was canceled. No heart.
Unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Coors Field, a homeless man noticed that there wasn't
much traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``No baseball game, huh?'' he said. ``Those guys really made a
name for themselves. That's awful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
