<HEADLINE>
THE STATS ON RUSH LIMBAUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My sister says Rush Limbaugh is a has-been. I say his radio
show is rated No. 1. Am I correct?
</P>
<P>
   _J.B., Whitney, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Rush Limbaugh leads all nationally syndicated radio talk-show
hosts, with an audience of 14.75 million, according to the industry
journal Talkers Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh is followed by Dr. Laura Schlessinger at 14.5 million,
Howard Stern at 9.25 million, Art Bell at 6.25 million and Dr. Joy
Browne at 6.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The twice-annual Talkers survey was led by Limbaugh from 1990
until spring 1998, when he placed third, 750,000 behind
Schlessinger and 500,000 behind Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh, who claims a current audience of 18 million to 19
million after a high of 21 million in 1994, disputed the Talkers
third-place findings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have quite a few black iron skillets, pots and lids my
mother-in-law left me. They are badly rusted. How can I clean them
up?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.D., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Either scour the rust away with cleanser and a scrubbing pad,
or put the cookware in the oven during a self-cleaning cycle for 60
to 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This tip comes from Wagnerware Corp., which has sold cast iron
cookware since the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Use the self-cleaning oven method only if the pan is made
exclusively of cast iron, a Wagnerware customer support
representative said. Also, don't exceed 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the rust is removed, wash out the cookware and wipe each
piece with a paper towel dipped in vegetable oil to ``reseason''
it, taking care not to overuse the oil. Place the clean, oiled
pieces in a 300-degree oven for one hour, and the cookware should
be ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call Wagnerware at (888) 457-2665.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to William Styron, the author of ``Sophie's
Choice''? My maiden name is Styron, and I have a family tree I'd
like to send him.
</P>
<P>
   _ L.S.G., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Styron in care of Vintage Publicity, 201 E. 50th
St., New York, NY 10022.
</P>
<P>
   Styron, whose most recent book is ``A Tidewater Morning'' from
1993, won a Pulitzer Prize in 1968 for ``The Confessions of Nat
Turner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadrach,'' a film released last year, was based on a short
story Styron wrote in the '70s. The film was directed by his
daughter, Susanna, who wrote the script with Bridget Terry.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
