<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUFFAUT-FILM-2TAKES-     04-22 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUFFAUT-FILM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOUT TRUFFAUT': AUDACIOUS CHARMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Boston, Los Angeles, San Francisco)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Francois Truffaut was sent to a juvenile
detention center at the request of his parents in 1948, his first
letter home requested the essentials: jam, and his files on Charlie
Chaplin and Orson Welles. In retrospect, it's clear why that would
sustain him.
</P>
<P>
   By the time his stay at the Observation Center for Minors was
immortalized on film, fictionalized 11 years later at the end of
``The 400 Blows,'' he had acquired an encyclopedic film education
(after making three earlier short films) and weathered enough
turmoil and amour to tell stories laced with precocious wisdom. He
began his feature filmmaking career with enough experience and
subtle finesse to last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   That career is being celebrated with ``Tout Truffaut,'' a
comprehensive nine-week series that begins Friday at the Film Forum
in New York City. (It will be followed by similar series in cities
including San Franciso, Los Angeles and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is also chronicled in a newly translated French biography
(``Truffaut,'' by Antoine de Baecque and Serge Toubiana) that makes
a first-rate companion piece for the program. Dry but extremely
informative, the book (from Knopf) provides much background
material on Truffaut's evolution.
</P>
<P>
   From unwanted child to take-no-prisoners critic (once branded
``that young thug of journalism'') to dean of the Nouvelle Vague
(he wrote the brief story synopsis that evolved into Jean-Luc
Godard's ``Breathless''), he grew into the role of brand-name
filmmaker specializing in blithe romance. Yet as this series makes
clear, it is for his deeper, darker adult films that Truffaut is
best remembered.
</P>
<P>
   It's astonishing to realize, while re-experiencing the obsessive
passions of ``The Story of Adele H.'' and ``The Woman Next Door,''
the delicate balance of ``Two English Girls'' or the literally
haunting power of ``The Green Room,'' that these were not among his
widely acknowledged successes. (The incomparably devastating
``Story of Adele H.'' was a critical failure in France, and ``Two
English Girls'' an outright disaster.)
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, this series spans the full range from early
classics (``Jules and Jim,'' ``Shoot the Piano Player'') to a late
masterpiece (the 1981 ``Woman Next Door'' was his penultimate
feature, made three years before his death from a brain tumor at
52), with audacious experiments (``The Wild Child''), curious
anomalies (``Such a Gorgeous Kid Like Me'') and tales of the
adorably obstinate Antoine Doinel along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The great performances, like Isabelle Adjani's (in ``Adele
H.''), Jeanne Moreau's (``Jules and Jim,'') and of course
Jean-Pierre Leaud's as the Truffaut alter ego who came of age so
unforgettably on camera, remain sublime. And thanks to the series'
thoroughness, the misfires are here too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love on the Run'' (1979), Doinel's last gasp, was partly
cobbled together from nostalgic film clips. Though it's welcome in
a series where the complete Doinel cycle can be seen (beginning
with the 1962 short ``Antoine and Colette,'' and including ``Stolen
Kisses'' and ``Bed and Board''), ``Love on the Run'' joined
``Fahrenheit 451'' (from Ray Bradbury's book-burning book) and
``The Bride Wore Black'' (his closest Hitchcock approximation,
starring Jeanne Moreau) as the Truffaut films the director himself
liked least.
</P>
<P>
   Films about childhood, courtship and sexual betrayal gave
Truffaut's work its most obvious thematic hallmarks. They also gave
him the reputation of a filmmaker of narrowly bourgeois concerns.
And they made him an easy target for former New Wave friends like
Godard, who called him ``a businessman in the morning and a poet in
the afternoon'' and claimed that ``Shoot the Piano Player'' was the
only Truffaut film he could bear.
</P>
<P>
   On the occasion of one of Truffaut's most lovable and popular
films, Godard asked him for financial backing. He wrote: ``After
`Day for Night' you ought to help me, so that audiences don't think
that the only kind of movies being made are your kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's true that while France exploded into the
revolutionary turmoil of 1968, Truffaut was delivering ``Stolen
Kisses,'' the most delightful film in the Doinel cycle. (It holds
up charmingly well, as does the next installment, ``Bed and
Board.'')
</P>
<P>
   But in retrospect, he was also maturing in ways that would lead
him to revisit and reconsider early work in a more reflective,
sometimes newly passionate light. At opposite ends of his career
came ``The Soft Skin'' (1964) and ``The Woman Next Door,'' two
films about extramarital love affairs that have life-or-death
consequences, yet their attitudes could not be more different.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The Soft Skin'' is the film in this series most likely to
prompt tomato-throwing at the screen. Having the temerity to shoot
this black-and-white film in the apartment he still shared with his
wife, Madeleine Morgenstern, Truffaut watches how a celebrity
Balzac scholar (only in France!) becomes infatuated with an
admiring stewardess.
</P>
<P>
   She is played by Francoise Dorleac, part of the parade of demure
yet smoldering women whose high heels, silken lingerie and
especially beautiful eyes helped to define Truffaut's feminine
ideal. (It seemed to date back to the mother whose flirtatiousness
and neglect during Truffaut's boyhood exerted a formidable
influence on his art.)
</P>
<P>
   She enraptures the scholar, who remains guilty but insufferably
smug even while in the throes of erotic obsession. ``The Soft
Skin'' still plays like a marital mea culpa, effective chiefly for
its Hitchcockian homages (especially in a nighttime hotel sequence)
and candor about the husband's desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Woman Next Door'' explores these same ideas in a very
different atmosphere, a far more complex and passionate one. A
blandly contented suburban husband and father, played by Gerard
Depardieu in one of his most stirring performances, is startled to
find that a former lover is his new neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, now married and played ravishingly by the spirited
Fanny Ardant, does not share his eagerness to escape the past.
</P>
<P>
   So the film watches, with immense acuity, as the affair is
secretly rekindled and the lovers recapitulate their old struggles
while plunging headlong into new ones. As Ms. Ardant mentions in
the chatty biographical documentary, ``Stolen Portraits,'' that is
also part of the series, the film's eloquent visual restraint
contributes greatly to its power.
</P>
<P>
   She notes that an encounter lending itself to melodrama, a
lovers' quarrel at the end of which the woman faints, is
deliberately staged in a dull cement parking garage with grocery
bags as props. The emotions in the film are so pure that Truffaut's
simple, quotidian style only emphasized them further.
</P>
<P>
   His directorial shifts are also apparent in the similarly themed
``Jules and Jim'' (1962) and ``Two English Girls'' (1971). These
two menage-a-trois stories are derived from the work of the same
author, Henri-Pierre Roche, who was 76 and completely obscure when
Truffaut found ``Jules and Jim'' in a secondhand bookseller's
stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two English Girls'' is also the somewhat autobiographical
story that Roche transposed into his book ``Jules and Jim,''
adapted by Truffaut into a classic that now looks as fascinating
for its hidden cruelty as for its sense of freedom. ``This is the
third time it's happened to me,'' Truffaut wrote of ``Jules and
Jim,'' expressing the constant undercurrent that so deepens his
work. ``Starting a film with the thought that it's going to be
amusing and realizing along the way that it will be saved only by
its sadness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
