<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOST&AMP;FOUND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS DOG STORY HAS BEEN SPADE _ AND THAT'S A GOOD THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this year's ShoWest in Las Vegas, even David Spade seemed
dumbfounded that he was starring in the lightweight, canine-centric
romantic comedy Lost &AMP; Found.'' But don't worry, the former
``Saturday Night Live'' snarkster hasn't gone to the dogs just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Though you'd never know it from the trailers, ``Lost &AMP; Found''
actually has a number of funny moments that don't involve
animal-based sight gags.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan (Spade) is a struggling restaurateur whose lousy love life
seems largely due to his unrepentant smugness. But when Lila
(Sophie Marceau), a beautiful French cellist with a proclivity for
losing her precious pooch, moves into the building, Dylan believes
he's found true love. He also figures out how to get a four-legged
foot in the door by dognapping the pup in order to spend quality
time looking with Lila. What could go wrong, right?
</P>
<P>
   It works like a charm until the little hairball ends up
swallowing an expensive ring Dylan's been holding for his best
friend, so now he's stuck with the pooch until the problem ...
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing his idiot delivery boy Wally (''MAD TV's'' Artie
Lang) is on hand to help with the dirty work, but the stakes are
raised when Lila's ex-lover Rene (Patrick Bruel) shows up to refuel
an old flame. Dylan and Rene immediately size each other up as
competitors, and the race is on to win Lila's love.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, all this sounds like agonizingly awful romantic fluff,
and in many ways it is. But Spade's amusing asides and snide banter
keep the mood so light and silly, you have a hard time noticing how
cheesy the whole thing is. But, like almost every
former-SNL-cast-member-turned-movie-star venture, the film relies
too heavily on your personal like of Spade, and not enough on a
well-told story. If you hate his arrogant, caustic sense of humor _
something he honed on SNL and as a successful stand-up _ well,
there's not much sense in shelling out the 6 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it's an entertaining romp reminiscent of ``There's
Something About Mary,'' with wittier dialogue and sans hair-gel
jokes. Watch for cameos from Jon Lovitz and Martin Sheen, and stick
around for the amusing music video for Deee-Lite's ``Groove is in
the Heart'' over the closing credits.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Lost &AMP; Found''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jeff Pollack
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: David Spade, Sophie Marceau
</P>
<P>
   Length: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult subject matter, profanity, brief nudity and
crude humor
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
