</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING TO HIGH SCHOOL, WITH DIFFERENT RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVER BEEN KISSED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore, David Arquette, Michael Vartan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Raja Gosnell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you thought about Dartmouth?'' Sam (Vartan), a high
school English teacher, asks the student Josie Geller (Ms.
Barrymore). Josie says she hasn't. That's because she has already
graduated from Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   Sam doesn't realize it, but Josie is really 25 and a reporter
who has gone undercover at her old school to whip up a report on
today's youth. If she's nervous at the prospect, it's because eight
years earlier on the same campus she virtually defined the term
hapless dork.
</P>
<P>
   Josie was the overly sweet and vulnerable one who did
everybody's homework and got splattered with egg for her trouble.
As an adult, Josie does needlepoint, talks to her turtle and
rhapsodizes about what will happen when she gets her first real
kiss. (It will get all hazy.)
</P>
<P>
   At school she passes for 17, even after bandying about higher
literary concepts in Sam's class. (Poor Shakespeare is trotted out
yet again in a high school movie.) Everything else goes badly.
School now entails a weapons check each morning, and the students
are just as crude and nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Josie remains as gushily obsequious as she was at 17.
But after eating too much ganja cake and otherwise making a fool of
herself, she inadvertently reinvents her image by coming up with a
theme for the prom, which at this school is a little like Moses
returning from the mountain top.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly cool, she gets to hang out with the in-group. Later she
shows her true colors and issues a ringing defense of the dorks.
And now for that kiss.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY One or two naughty words are blurted and some of the
humor is off-color. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 Older viewers in this category, especially girls,
will enjoy themselves. The little ones will take to Ms. Barrymore,
an engaging presence, but as simple-minded as the film is (and it
gets goofy), it is probably too complicated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 If they don't succumb to sugar shock, girls will love
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP Many older teen-agers acknowledge the silliness
but report a warm and cuddly sensation brought on by Ms. Barrymore
and a general identification with a loser who finally rises up.
</P>
<P>
   THE MATRIX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne, Carrie-Anne Moss, Hugo
Weaving, Joe Pantoliano &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Andy Wachowski and Larry Wachowski &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 115 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A sleek, pallid computer hacker named Neo (Reeves) is recruited
to serve as a time-traveling Ping-Pong ball being swatted back and
forth between the pervasive artificial intelligence that rules the
world and a band of ragtag survivors fighting to save the new
millennium for good old humankind.
</P>
<P>
   Scooped up in a limo by an acrobatic operative named Trinity
(Ms. Moss), Neo gets briefed by Morpheus ( Fishburne), leader of
the embattled outcasts. It seems that all life on earth is really a
computer construct called the matrix, in which everybody goes about
business as usual unware that they are slaves to the artificial
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem? Morpheus points out that without free
determination humans will be forever chained to our not wholly
exemplary way of conducting ourselves. Inside the matrix, however,
is a man, referred to as ``the One,'' who has the power to break
the bond and change everything. Morpheus believes that the One is
Neo.
</P>
<P>
   On a computer screen, the matrix resembles beads of water
running down a shower curtain. Neo gets trained physically by a set
of floppy disks, which instantly impart fighting skills. But the
challenge is mental. To assume his full powers, he must let go any
notion of doubt or limitation.
</P>
<P>
   When Morpheus deems him ready, Neo will be taken to the Oracle,
who has the final say on who is the One. Down in the matrix there
are preliminary skirmishes with the artificial intelligence,
represented by Agent Smith ( Weaving) and several clones who
resemble the Blues Brothers. The Oracle, it turns out, is an
elderly woman who holds forth in her kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Is Neo the One? ``Sorry, kid,'' she says. ``You've got the
gifts, but you're waiting for something.'' The next life maybe.
Morpheus and friends fight on, as does Neo. But what is he waiting
for?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Gore flies, but while the movie is a grabber visually
and technologically, nothing, including the violence, seems in the
least way real. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Minimal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 The film is very violent (however surreal) and
parents should judge accordingly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP If the violence isn't a problem, neither is the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   TWIN DRAGONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Chan, Maggie Cheung, Teddy Robin, Nina Li Chi &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tsui Hark and Ringo Lam &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Chan always has fun with himself in his movies, and here
two Jackie Chans have a wonderful time with each other as they dart
around Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Separated shortly after birth, the Ma twins, John and Boomer
(both Chan), develop along separate career paths as, respectively,
a renowned conductor and an auto mechanic with a talent for
antagonizing the mob.
</P>
<P>
   To cut to the chase (there not being too much else to dwell on
in this movie), the sedate John arrives for a performance and finds
himself in the middle of a very active altercation between Boomer
and a horde of gangsters he has offended and kicked and punched all
over town.
</P>
<P>
   Though they've never met, the twins react instinctively to each
other, with Boomer's fingers working uncontrollably while John is
at the piano and the sedate John gyrating wildly every time Boomer
takes on his tormentors. (At one point, John nearly wrecks a hotel
lobby just sitting there.)
</P>
<P>
   Later the boys involuntarily swap girlfriends (an impresario's
daughter and a bar girl), as well as cell phones, which gets them
dashing off into each other's total confusion. But at last they
meet and join forces to trash a department store and take part in a
citywide donnybrook. ``You fight like a girl,'' Boomer tells John.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Much damage is inflicted with fists, feet, bullets,
vehicles and whatever, but it's all in a spirit of fun (sort of)
and at times approaches slapstick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Boomer and the impresario's daughter (Ms. Li Chi) are shown
in bed and there are other sexual situations and references. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Some. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 This isn't a film for the very young. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10 AND UP Parents beware, but this is an amusing and
entertaining movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
