<SLUG> BC-OLD97s-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD 97'S TAKE A MAINSTREAM TURN WITH LATEST CD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The grumbles, Murry Hammond says, have already started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard about 100 responses, and I'd say 90 percent are
positive,'' says the bassist for Dallas country quartet the Old
97's. ``The other 10 percent are like, `Well, I just like your old
stuff.'''
</P>
<P>
   The old stuff: records like their 1994 debut, ``Hitchhike to
Rhome,'' and their 1995 follow-up, ``Wreck Your Life,'' melodic but
raw efforts that earned the group a hard-core following, a
next-big-thing buzz and, as a result, a major-label deal.
</P>
<P>
   The new stuff: the group's latest effort, ``Fight Songs,'' its
second for major label Elektra and fourth overall. The disc, which
comes out Tuesday, marks a drastic change in the band's signature,
bare-bones sound: Most of ``Fight Songs'' consists of radio-ready
pop songs shimmering with chiming guitars, lush melodies and glossy
finishes. In other words, it could easily fit onto the play lists
of mainstream radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   As out of character as it may sound, the disc could finally lead
the guys to mainstream success. It could also be their last chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last record that's guaranteed on our contract, so
I don't know what will happen if it doesn't sell,'' says Rhett
Miller, the band's singer and primary songwriter. ``The (label) has
assured us up and down that they believe in us, and they've worked
with a lot of bands that haven't courted radio or tried to have a
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't feel like we're selling out or writing songs that
we hate,'' Miller says. ``We've put out a record that radio could
potentially pick up. People have said, `You've made a great record
and if the label can't make a hit out of it, it's their fault.' And
that's from people at the label.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime fans will notice another change: Miller's not wearing
glasses anymore. It was rumored that the label ``recommended'' he
switch to contacts to play up a more handsome image. Not so, Miller
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole thing's so funny,'' he says. ``I just decided to
stop wearing them because every time I play live, they fog up.
What's weird is that people at the label did, awhile back, say
stuff like, `When are you gonna stop wearing those dorky glasses?'
But that's not why I stopped wearing 'em. I stopped because I
couldn't see our set list.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this story is a familiar one: The Old 97's' Elektra
debut, 1997's ``Too Far to Care,'' was also, the label hoped,
destined to be a commercial breakthrough for the group, which
formed in 1993 and is rounded out by guitarist Ken Bethea and
drummer Philip Peeples.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a few of the disc's tracks were featured in movies,
including ``Hope Floats'' and ``Clay Pigeons, Too Far's'' slight
taste of success was too little. It sold 40,000 copies, far too few
in the eyes of a major.
</P>
<P>
   ```With Too Far to Care,' Elektra scratched their heads. They
liked it, but they didn't know how to get it to mainstream
America,'' Hammond says. ``I think the difference is now they feel
they have something they can work with.''
</P>
<P>
   True. At least half of ``Fight Songs''' are anything but:
Oppenheimer, 19 and the first single, ``Murder (Or a Heart
Attack),'' echo the easily digestible, choral melodies of '60s-era
pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, we explored our fascination with Buddy Holly and
Everly Brothers more than Hank Williams,'' Hammond says. ``We still
love Hank. We still love everything we love. We're just emphasizing
some things over others, which is the way we've always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller says that although the music has changed, his approach to
writing song lyrics has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the songs I write are invariably sad,'' he says.
``Sometimes it's obvious, but here I have more of a
sounds-happy-but-is-really-sad sort of thing going on. Put sad
lyrics behind upbeat, British Invasion-type music, you get this
weird hybrid. It's been done before but not by us.''
</P>
<P>
   A new sound, a new image _ maybe it'll help; maybe not.
Regardless, Miller says, the group will continue, success or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this record to do well, but even if doesn't, the Old
97's will make another one,'' Miller says. ``We've made enough
friends and contacts in the industry to where if we did get dropped
or whatever, we could put our music out elsewhere. Main thing is, I
wanna do this as long as I can. I don't want to have to go back to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew reviews pop music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
