<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUSHING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROL TOWER LANDS A CLUNKER 
</HEADLINE>
 TIN-MOVIE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The best thing about ``Pushing Tin,'' the air-traffic
controller movie, is that if you successfully duck it in the
theaters, you won't be surprised by having to watch it on your next
long-distance plane trip.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are not going to show an in-flight movie about
air-traffic controllers pushing themselves to the point of nervous
breakdowns. In the case of ``Pushing Tin,'' however, the ban may be
a matter of good critical judgment rather than concern for
passenger squeamishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin'' is based on a magazine article, and it plays
like a magazine article: some interesting facts, no drama. Not many
laughs either, in case director Mike Newell thought he was making a
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is set in New York's control center, where a group of
frenetic, kibitzing controllers directs planes from three metro
airports, slicing the available air into ever-diminishing shreds
while the controllers try to land planes on time and, incidentally,
keep them from crashing into each other.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes inside the control room play like a math nightmare:
lines of nervous people staring at blips on radar screens while
mumbling such pithy dialogue as, ``Delta two-four-seven-eight, you
have traffic at 10 o'clock. Turn right, heading zero-six-zero.
Continental, descend to 3,000, heading four-niner-three.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie tracks the rivalry between two controllers, Nick (John
Cusack), the veteran hotshot, and Russell (Billy Bob Thornton), the
enigmatic outsider who can really land them.
</P>
<P>
   The two men compete in pushing tin around the sky, shooting free
throws and bedding women.
</P>
<P>
   The women involved in the men's ego contest are Nick's wife
(Cate Blanchett) and Russell's (Angelina Jolie).
</P>
<P>
   Because director Newell (``Donnie Brasco'') can pump little
drama into the takeoffs and arrivals of airplanes, he diverts the
movie into an investigation of infidelity and other acts of marital
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The movie makes a serious point: that the air-traffic control
system is out of control because the control freaks running it are
too apt to crack under the stress. However, it doesn't make that
point in cinematic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Newell has to employ the interjection of facts (for example,
that each flight controller is responsible for more lives during a
single shift than a surgeon during an entire career) so we don't
think we're watching guys playing video games and talking math.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin'' is rated R for profanity and a peek of nudity. 2
stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Fenster can be reached at bob.fenster(at)pni.com  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
