<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PREVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNSELORS ADVISE PARENTS TO TALK ABOUT SCHOOL VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents who wonder whether the high school shootings in Colorado
have troubled their children should face the issue head on by
inviting their children to talk.
</P>
<P>
   By discussing the topic, parents reassure their children that it
is all right to express their thoughts and feelings about the
shootings, said Sharon Williams, director of child and adolescent
psychiatry at the Stanford University Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all over the newspapers and on television,'' she said.
``Even if they didn't hear about it at home, they're going to hear
about it from their friends. They're going to know it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Find out what children know, Williams advised, and then ask
open-ended questions as they tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to find out what's going on in your kid's head, to
see how they're making sense of what happened,'' she said. ``If
they're worried, be sure and ask them what they're worried about.
Let them tell you what their fears are.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents should also keep an eye out for behavioral changes that
show children may need help coping.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmares, loss of appetite, aggressive play, irritability,
isolation, clinging to parents _ all could be signs that a child or
teen-ager needs professional help, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know about trauma symptoms is that the earlier people
come for treatment, the better off they are,'' said Williams, who
works with children who have experienced traumatic events.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging how scary and heartbreaking the Colorado
incident is, parents should also emphasize that it is extremely
rare for children to be hurt at school by this kind of violence,
said Lois Salisbury, president of Children Now, a national
organization based in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not realistic for a child to walk around with their heart
in their throat worrying it's going to happen to them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Salisbury also suggested reminding children that there were many
adults who were looking out for their safety: teachers, neighbors,
the police.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the mayhem in Colorado with an adult can be
reassuring, said Sue Crivello, a counselor at Washington High
School in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents can say: We may never know why it happened,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened in a relatively affluent community, so the kids
had material things, but maybe something else was lacking in their
lives _ like Mom, or Dad, or love. You can discuss what might have
been missing in their lives. Kids are very perceptive about those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Mock, director of family, youth and children's services
at Berkeley Mental Health, a city agency, said parents should
monitor how much information children received on the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should not let their kids, particularly if they're
younger, watch such TV accounts without parental discussion or
involvement to see what their reactions are, to see how the kids
are responding,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
