r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     04-22 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'RE NOT USING AVAILABLE TECHNOLOGY FULLY, BILL GATES WRITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Information Age is about 30 years old, so why are we still
covered in a sea of paperwork?
</P>
<P>
   Because we're not using the tools in front of our faces, says
Bill Gates, creator and chief executive of the dominant leader in
computer toolmaking, Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical company has made 80 percent of the investment in
the technology that can give it a healthy flow of information yet
is typically getting only 20 percent of the benefits that are now
possible,'' Gates writes. ``The gap between what companies are
spending and what they're getting stems from the combination of not
understanding what is possible and not seeing the potential when
you use technology to move the right information quickly to
everyone in your company.''
</P>
<P>
   Filling that gap with ideas and examples is the basis of Gates'
latest book, ``Business (at) The Speed of Thought: Using a Digital
Nervous System'' (Warner Books, 470 pages).
</P>
<P>
   This book is a vast improvement over Gates' last tome, a
semi-autobiographical, industry observation that rambled more than
informed.
</P>
<P>
   Gates has honed his skills, becoming a writer of organized
thoughts and useful ideas. And he probably will sell some of his
products along the way.
</P>
<P>
   But that's OK, as long as he can give readers some insight into
what current information trends are and how to apply them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gates writes that only recently, new tools have
become available for analyzing and disseminating rich information
that could launch your company deep into the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here on the edge of the twenty-first century, the tools and
connectivity of the digital age now give us a way to easily obtain,
share and act on information in new and remarkable ways,'' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Those tools can be used to create what he has termed a digital
nervous system, which like a human nervous system reaches all parts
of the company, linking them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A digital nervous system consists of the digital processes
that enable a company to perceive and react to its environment, to
sense competitor challenges and customer needs, and to organize
timely responses,'' he writes. ``... It's distinguished from a mere
network of computers by the accuracy, immediacy, and richness of
the information it brings to knowledge workers and the insight and
collaboration made possible by the information.''
</P>
<P>
   That rich information, for example, may come in the form of
digitally tracking what your customers are buying. Grocery stores
have been doing it for years, with scanners that were originally
designed to speed checkouts.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be too expensive and technically complex to track
customers' buying habits, Gates said, ``but the PC and the Internet
give us an infrastructure that makes exchanging all kinds of
digital information very inexpensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates has developed 12 steps for getting your company up to
speed with technology. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use e-mail as an in-house communication system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use digital transactions with all suppliers and partners.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use digital systems to route customer complaints immediately
to the people who can improve the product or service.
</P>
<P>
   The book is also full of vignettes on how companies are using
the new tools.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, for example, has developed an ``extranet''
from which its 12 operating units work. An extranet is a private
Internet site that lets several companies share information and
conduct business.
</P>
<P>
   ``GE expects to do more than $5 billion in capital procurements
over the extranet by 2001, compared with less than 1 percent in
electronic purchases today,'' Gates writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fully deployed, the extranet could involve as many as 40,000
trading partners.''
</P>
<P>
   With nontechnical language, Gates provides a clear picture of
what's happening in a highly complex and vital area of business
from which many could profit.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TOO BIG TO BITE
</P>
<P>
   ``Infinite Loop: How Apple, the World's Most Insanely Great
Computer Company, Went Insane''
</P>
<P>
   By Michael S. Malone
</P>
<P>
   Currency Doubleday, $27.50
</P>
<P>
   I'm afraid that Tom Wolfe has started a bad trend: books that
never seem to end. At 597 pages, you would think seasoned
journalist Michael Malone was getting paid by the page. This
corporate history promises yet again all of the ``truth'' about the
topsy-turvy world of Steve Jobs, the Woz and the world of Apple
computing. I'm sure it's in there, but who wants to wade through
such a tome to find it? Especially when it has been written about
so many times before.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Work Like Your Dog: Fifty Ways to Work Less, Play More, and
Earn More''
</P>
<P>
   By Matt Weinstein and Luke Barber
</P>
<P>
   Villard, $22.95
</P>
<P>
   Work should be play, according to the latest book by Matt
Weinstein, a management consultant who also wrote the great
``Managing to Have Fun.'' Unfortunately, he says, Americans have a
fundamental idea that work and play should be as separate as church
and state. In a breezy, short-chapter style, his book explains how
to combine work and play for a happier and more productive work
force. The co-author is Luke Barber, a philosophy professor at
Richland College in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Free, Perfect and Now: Connecting to the Three Insatiable
Customer Demands: A CEO's True Story''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Rodin
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25
</P>
<P>
   This is an engaging look at how a 52-year-old electronics
distributor, Marshall Industries, reinvented itself using a Web
presence, an inverted organizational pyramid and a new pay plan.
``While you can't predict the future, you can prepare for it,''
writes Marshall's CEO, Robert Rodin. ``And that, as we're learning
at Marshall, can become a way to invent it.'' An interesting look
at one company's treatment of the new world of business.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
