<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     04-22 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A PRIVATE LIFE:' CASTING HENRY JAMES AS AN ARTISTIC CAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry James once described himself, half jokingly, as ``that
queer monster, the artist.'' It's a description that proves all too
fitting in Lyndall Gordon's new book about James, a book that
paints a chilling portrait of the novelist as a predatory genius
who did ``nothing that did not feed his art'' and who willfully
possessed ``the souls of certain people he had marked for `use.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent among those ``certain people'' were James' cousin
Minny Temple and the writer Constance Fenimore Woolson, the women,
Ms. Gordon argues, who inspired the two high waves of creativity of
the novelist's career, the first culminating in ``The Portrait of a
Lady'' in 1881, the other in ``The Ambassadors'' in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that James' fiction was heavily indebted to
autobiographical sources; nor is it a secret that Minny, and to a
lesser degree ``Fenimore'' (as Woolson was known), played major
roles in shaping his conception of the Jamesian woman. What's
different about Ms. Gordon's account is the vehemence with which
she accuses James of appropriating these women's sensibilities
while withdrawing from them in real life, when they most needed his
friendship. James, in her telling, emerges as the ultimate esthetic
cad, using women not for sexual favors but for literary material
and then cavalierly dumping them when they were no longer of any
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Private Life of Henry James'' is less a conventional
biography than a long, impassioned and often hectoring essay filled
with illuminating insights and highly speculative accusations. It
represents a significant departure from Ms. Gordon's previous work,
highly nuanced studies of Charlotte Bronte, Virginia Woolf and T.S.
Eliot, and from Leon Edel's monumental five-volume biography of
James, which took a psychological approach to the novelist's life
and art, but refrained from passing judgments.
</P>
<P>
   As we know from James' writings, Minny was a direct, eager girl,
blessed with a searching, restless spirit and a ``moral
spontaneity.'' The young James came to know Minny during their late
teens, and she made such an impression on him, his brother William
and their friends that James later hailed her as ``the heroine of
our scene.''
</P>
<P>
   For James, whose failure to serve in the Army during the Civil
War had cast his manhood into question, Ms. Gordon argues, Minny
was a kind of soul mate in defiance. She represented an alternative
to the prim and passive image of the traditional woman, ``a
parallel to the shadowed man'' (like himself) who defied
traditional conceptions of gender.
</P>
<P>
   Minny, who was suffering from consumption, dreamed of going to
Rome to visit its fabled museums and ruins and to seek a respite
from her illness in its temperate winter climate. Ms. Gordon
suggests that as a young single woman, Minny would have needed a
companion (preferably a family member) for her travels, and that
James, who was already in Europe, exhibited ``a willful blindness
in the way he would not grasp the gravity of her illness and the
urgency of her pleas to him to take her on.'' She would end up
dying in Pelham, N.Y., in 1870 at age 24.
</P>
<P>
   Minny's death, Ms. Gordon argues (and here she echoes Edel),
enabled James to take imaginative possession of her in a way he
never could have, or would have dared, in real life. She became an
idea, an ideal who could be ``locked away, incorruptibly, within
the crystal walls of the past,'' and she would also become an
avatar of the new ``American girl,'' featured in ``The Portrait of
the Lady'' and ``Daisy Miller.'' Many years later, James would
resurrect Minny in ``The Wings of the Dove,'' casting her as the
doomed Milly Theale, whose death transfigures her mercenary suitor
Merton Densher.
</P>
<P>
   Like the radiant Milly, the spinsterish Constance Fenimore
Woolson _ the great-niece of Fenimore Cooper and the author of such
works as ``Miss Grief'' and ``The Street of the Hyacinth'' _
possessed an independent spirit, and during James' middle years,
Ms. Gordon writes, she ``opened up a woman's mind'' to him, much
``as Minny Temple had done at the outset of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolson had sought James out in Europe as a kind of mentor, and
the two soon became close friends. By the end of 1886, James and
Woolson were sharing a house overlooking Florence. James had come
``closer than he had ever been to a voluntary domestic tie,'' Ms
Gordon writes, ``and Fenimore had the kind of intimacy she
craved.'' Ms. Gordon does not suggest, as Edel does, that Woolson
had sexual designs on James, but argues that James failed to be
supportive when she fell into a deep depression in 1893, thereby
repeating the same pattern of involvement and withdrawal that he
had exhibited with Minny. Near midnight on Jan. 24, 1894, after a
bout with the flu, Woolson fell or jumped to her death from her
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Gordon tells it, James, in typically self-absorbed
fashion, took her death personally: ``He, the knower, the deep
student of the female heart,'' was ``forced to acknowledge that he
had not known a woman'' who was one of his closest friends. She
also suggests that he began to spin Fenimore's death to friends and
colleagues, falsely describing her as being in the grip of an
uncontrollable dementia: ``The coded message is plain: no one, not
the best of friends, could have prevented this death.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Ms. Gordon's contention that James would continue to spin
his life, playing down the role Minny and Fenimore played in the
making of his art. Why, she asks, did ``he make a pact with
Fenimore to destroy their correspondence?''
</P>
<P>
   Why, as an old man, 44 years after Minny Temple's death, did he
destroy a batch of her letters, having used what he wanted from
them for his memoirs? The answer, she argues, is that James wanted
to promote ``the legend of a solitary artist'' and erase, or at
least diminish, ``the ghostly companions of his art.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of setting out this argument, Ms. Gordon makes
some interesting observations concerning the ``spectatorial''
impulse behind James' art and the real-life antecedents behind his
frequent portrayal of innocents destroyed by opportunists and
schemers.
</P>
<P>
   It is no great revelation, however, that artists can be ruthless
in using family and friends as material. Faulkner famously observed
that ``if a writer has to rob his mother, he will not hesitate; the
`Ode on a Grecian Urn' is worth any number of old ladies.'' In
addition, James has long been renowned for his voyeuristic
detachment and inability to form or sustain lasting emotional
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Ms. Gordon undermines the valid points she wants to make
by overstating her thesis, arguing that Minny Temple and Constance
Fenimore Woolson formed a ``collaboration'' with James, that they
were ``posthumous partners'' in the creation of his art. She
suggests that James' actions (or failures to act) contributed to
their untimely deaths, and she reviles him as ``an amorous predator
of the soul.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, such bald statements (often based on speculative
readings of the available evidence) and Ms. Gordon's relentlessly
censorious tone make for an angry, polemical book, a book that
lacks the judicious scholarship of her earlier biographical works.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A PRIVATE LIFE OF HENRY JAMES'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two Women and His Art
</P>
<P>
   By Lyndall Gordon
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 500 pages. W.W. NortonW.. $32.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
