<HEADLINE>
`PUSHING TIN:' BUCKLE UP FOR ROMANTIC TURBULENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.)  (DW) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Pushing Tin'' betrays its origins as a magazine
article (in The New York Times Magazine) with more atmosphere and
data than built-in story. As it describes the stressful lives of
air traffic controllers in the New York area, it makes no automatic
point beyond noting that the work is demanding and crazy. But as
directed by Mike Newell, it gets past its initial ``M-A-S-H''-style
comic chaos and becomes a four-character story with four characters
worth watching. Newell's ensemble timing and breezily sardonic
style make it work better than might be expected.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that the principals are played by John Cusack, Billy
Bob Thornton, Cate Blanchett and Angelina Jolie. They make a cast
that would be worth watching in just about anything and, in fact,
``Pushing Tin'' gives each one a colorfully offbeat role. The
closest thing to a familiar character here is Cusack's Nick, a
fast-talking wise guy who turns brilliantly professional whenever
planes need controlling. Cusack, as a man clearly wrestling with
himself while guiding traffic, goes a long way toward making the
character real.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever possessed Ms. Blanchett to play Nick's spouse, a jaunty
Long Island housewife with a strong local accent, has stood her in
good stead. She fits in so well here that it may be a while before
you wonder why Elizabeth I is talking about tuna casseroles. She
and all the story's other wives get a shock when Ms. Jolie slithers
into the movie as the biker-chick bride of a new traffic
controller, a daredevil named Russell. Thornton, carefully laconic
in ways that make a powerful impression, plays the newcomer who
becomes Nick's chief rival on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell is she doin' with Russell?'' one member of the
group asks about Ms. Jolie's knockout. ``He got her parents tied up
in the basement,'' somebody answers, in a film with a lot of
casually funny repartee along those lines. There are times when the
snap and rhythm of the film's best scenes bring to mind Newell's
``Four Weddings and a Funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   In surprisingly credible fashion, ``Pushing Tin'' shows what
happens after Nick falls for Russell's wife one boozy evening.
</P>
<P>
   And it watches the men's tense rivalry get understandably worse.
The story of the two couples is involvingly told and appealingly
acted, but it eventually gives way to the obligatory air traffic
control emergency crisis that has to be shoehorned in here. From
the moment those banks of computer screens first come into view,
it's clear that there eventually will be a controllers' emergency,
a show of courage and a crisis of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing there's a cast worth following anywhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity, partial nudity
and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PUSHING TIN'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mike Newell; written by Glen Charles and Les
Charles, based on an article in The New York Times Magazine,
``Something's Got to Give,'' by Darcy Frey; director of
photography, Gale Tattersall; edited by Jon Gregory; music by Anne
Dudley; production designer, Bruno Rubeo; produced by Art Linson;
released by Fox 2000 Pictures. Running time: 115 minutes. This film
is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: John Cusack (Nick Falzone), Billy Bob Thornton (Russell
Bell), Cate Blanchett (Connie Falzone), Angelina Jolie (Mary Bell),
Jake Weber (Barry Plotkin) and Jerry Grayson (Leo Morton). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
