<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-METROLAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOSTALGIA FOGS UP MOVIE OF HEDONISTIC LONGINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new animated television series ``Family Guy'' is an object
lesson in trying too hard. A recent episode featured three
flashbacks in the first five minutes. Something similar happens in
the movie ``Metroland,'' which stars Christian Bale in a '70s-style
shag haircut that looks so heavy you wonder how he keeps his head
up.
</P>
<P>
   It probably helps that the picture is set in the 1970s, in which
time Bale plays a young married father whose life is thrown into
doubt when his freewheeling, free-spirited best friend shows up.
Bale, who has given up his dreams of art for art's sake _ in other
words, he's sold out _ is reminded of the dreams he had as a boy.
Slivers of his dreams, and his past life, flash throughout the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a tolerant wife (Emily Watson) who manages to keep
their household in order, as well as iron his underwear, although
we're never quite sure whether the ironing is a part of some
fantasy. (It's where she also tells him she understands if he needs
other sexual partners.) The glimmers of flashbacks crystallize into
one extended scene in which a younger Bale is living a happy, but
impoverished, existence in Paris. He struggles with his
photography, and finds a young Parisian (the doe-eyed charmer Elsa
Zylberstein) who instructs him in the ways of amour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metroland'' _ which refers to the suburb where Bale, his wife
and baby live what he thinks may be a circumscribed life _ is the
kind of movie that used to be made all the time in the early '70s,
often starring Richard Benjamin as a middle-class bohemian. (These
were de facto versions of Philip Roth stories; in fact, Benjamin
starred in a few actual film versions of Roth stories.)
</P>
<P>
   These movies stopped being made because their time had passed.
They were about having your Sara Lee and eating it, too. The young
suburbanite would pass through his wild-oats phase and realize that
the real world was, in all places, the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   That is the same realization that Bale arrives at by movie's
end. Julian Barnes used his novel, from which the movie is derived,
as a way to get at the itch that never quite goes away, and the
perverse yearning for the return of a time that has just passed in
a man's life, the comedy of a guy in his early 30s pining for his
20s. (He also deals with the longing for the innocent hedonism of
the 1960s as compared to the tawdry hedonism of 1970s.)
</P>
<P>
   The exploration of such adult themes should add up to a better
movie. Director Philip Saville gets good performances out of his
cast. And the attempt to wrestle with sexual longing, and reconcile
oneself with monogamy, is an adult subject that pictures don't
tackle enough. But ``Metroland'' gazes at this grown-up dilemma
through the soft-focus purple haze of nostalgia. The emotional
content isn't nearly as up-to-date as it needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Metroland''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Philip Saville
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Christian Bale, Emily Watson
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity, sexuality, adult content, adult language and
drug use
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
