   &UR; CELL CROSSOVER MAY TRIGGER AUTOIMMUNE DISEASES ... &LR;  _
Autoimmune diseases, in which the body attacks its own tissues, may
in some cases be triggered by cells from your mother that have been
lurking within you since you were in the womb. Researchers in
Seattle found maternal cells in a man suffering from an autoimmune
disease. By Nell Boyce. 700 words. (slugged:
BC-AUTOIMMUNE-DISEASES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELECTRODES CONVINCE ASTRONAUTS SLEEP IS IMPORTANT &LR;  _ Astronauts
seem to sleep best when covered in electrodes, according to the
latest research into orbital insomnia. A researcher in Boston found
that covering astronauts in monitoring equipment made them sleep
better than when taking NASA's usual remedy for insomnia, the
hormone melatonin. By Nell Boyce. 400 words. (slugged:
BC-ASTRONAUTS'-SLEEP-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAT ID TAGS WARNING THEIR PREY &LR;  _ The jangling of ID tags used
to study bats could be forcing them to go hungry, warn researchers
in Britain. The metal rings worn by bats as identify tags make
strange ultrasonic noises when clashed together, scaring away
insects the bats feed on. By Matt Walker. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-BAT-ID-TAGS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
