reform the nation's educational system. (450 words.) By Kelly Hearn
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-NUKE-BILL. The House Commerce Committee rejected a
provision Wednesday that would have barred the Goshute Indian Tribe
from storing high-level radioactive waste on their reservation in
Utah, a ban U.S. Rep. Barbara Cubin, R-Wyo., supported. The panel
also left language out of a nuclear energy bill that would have
made it illegal for some companies to store on private land the
used fuel rods from nuclear power plants. This is good news for
Wyoming-based Newcorp, the only corporation other than the Goshutes
to consider building a spent fuel storage facility. (200 words.) By
Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-WELFARE-THOMPSON. For the second time in less than two
weeks, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson came to Washington to discuss
his state's success in welfare reform. While Thompson touted before
a House committee the strides Wisconsin has made in getting people
off welfare, at least one critic suggested the verdict on welfare
reform isn't in yet. (400 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
