<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMAICA-PROTESTS-0423     04-22 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-PROTESTS-0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JAMAICA PLAGUED BY MORE UNREST, TOURISM COULD SUFFER
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international category
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI -- Jamaica is a popular tourist destination known for many
things -- nice beaches, Red Stripe beer and all-inclusive resorts.
And, sometimes, it's been known for violence.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the island lived up to the worst of its reputation.
Jamaicans erupted in fury after the government proposed $100
million in new taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Looting, shootings and the setting of fiery barricades of tires
and furniture forced schools, businesses, and even the U.S. Embassy
to close Wednesday. Several airlines cancelled flights to the
island.
</P>
<P>
   At least six people were killed and 23 people were seriously
injured. One 25-year-old pregnant woman was shot by a private
security guard as he tried to fend off looters.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister P.J. Patterson now says he's ready to back down
on taxes, which appeared to bring calm on Thursday. The U.S.
Embassy reopended as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the violence, which sparked fears of a decline in Jamaica's
tourism industry, was nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country has a long history of violence, partly driven by
politics, partly driven by a gun culture, and partly driven by
economic troubles,'' said Larry Birns, director of the Council on
Hemispheric Affairs, a Washington-based research group.
</P>
<P>
   Although there's been a slight dip in the nation's astonishing
murder rate, street crime -- everything from carjackings to armed
robberies --persists.
</P>
<P>
   In a country of 2.5 million, 953 people were murdered in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, two busloads of German tourists were held up by
robbers armed with guns and daggers. No one was injured, but it was
one of the high-profile crimes against tourists that made the
Jamaican government decide in January to deploy troops to resort
areas to safeguard tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Then in March, a German tour operator was killed by a hammer
blow to the head during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen here as they do in any country, but that
shouldn't impact a tourist's decision to visit Jamaica, which has
so much to offer,'' said Noel Mignott, deputy director of the
Jamaica Tourist Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police in Jamaica do an excellent job,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say crimes against visitors have dropped
dramatically in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   But experts who know Jamaica say crime levels in general are
still high, fueled by drug trafficking and the large number of
firearms routinely smuggled into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Violent streaks also occur whenever the population grows
frustrated with a deteriorating economy, as it did this week.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1985, at least seven people were killed in two days
of violence as Jamaicans paralyzed traffic to protest higher gas
prices in the midst of a foundering economy. Deadly gas price riots
also occurred in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials emphasize that the country's murder rate is
down from an all-time high of 1,038 in 1997, and that the vast
majority of killings take place in Kingston, Jamaica's capital, far
from the tourist resorts in Ocho Rios and Montego Bay.
</P>
<P>
   And most of this week's unrest occurred in Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that this was an internal thing and that
protesters made an attempt to leave hotels and tourists out of it
because they recognize the value of that industry,'' said Karen
Hackshaw, a spokeswoman for the Caribbean Tourism Organization in
Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said tourism officials are concerned there could be
some fallout from the unrest.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines canceled flights to Kingston on Wednesday,
although service was to resume Friday. Air Jamaica _ which resumed
service Thursday _ and British Airways, also had canceled trips, as
did three cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   On an island that has an unemployment rate of nearly 17 percent,
at least 25 percent of the country's residents depend on tourism
for their livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean's largest English-speaking nation hosts 2 million
visitors a year, including 700,000 cruise ship passengers, most
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although some hotels reported cancellations, many in the tourist
industry reported business as usual on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a normal amount of business in Montego Bay and
the hotel has been full of tourists, so we're not being affected,''
said Suzette Scott of the Coyaba Beach Resort in Montego Bay.
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis Gayle, a professor of international business at
Florida International University who was born in Jamaica, said this
week's unrest had cost the country at least $30 million in trip
cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an economy that will not be revived any time soon,''
he said, adding that it has been plagued by mounting government
budget deficits for decades.
</P>
<P>
   This week's protests began last Friday after Finance Minister
Omar Davies unveiled a 30 percent tax increase on gasoline and
diesel and other fuels. The hike would take the price of leaded
gasoline from $1.55 to $2.01 per U.S. gallon, and the price of
diesel fuel from $1.33 to $1.74 per U.S. gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imposing taxes is never pleasant, but what we've done is the
best for Jamaica,'' said Prime Minister Patterson early in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   But Patterson softened his stance Wednesday in the face of
widespread protests and calls for his resignation. He named a panel
to make recommendations for at least a partial reduction on the
proposed tax by Sunday so that his Cabinet might consider it on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson's announcement may provide only a temporary reprieve
since, in the midst of a faltering economy, the government still
must find a way out of its financial quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   Both the country's agriculture and manufacturing sectors have
experienced declines, and even tourism's growth has been minimal.
As a result, the economy contracted by 0.8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the government admitted it couldn't afford its $3.6
billion budget and that it would have to slash public expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed taxes were to help restore lost money to about 2
million depositors at failed banks, 500,000 policyholders in
collapsed insurance companies, and 55,000 pensioners.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, opposition Labor Party leader Edward Seaga warned
that protests would begin anew if Patterson's proposal failed to
lead to a ditching of the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were already concerned about jobs and the high cost of
living,'' said Cliff Cameron, former president of the Private
Sector Organization of Jamaica. ``That gas tax increase was just
the straw that broke the camel's back.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
