<HEADER>
A9336 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-22 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF DEMONS ... BUT WE CAN'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is unfortunate that modern, civilized men and women have
become too sophisticated to speak seriously of demon possession or
to describe acts of unspeakable horror as manifestations of evil
incarnated.
</P>
<P>
   If that were not so, it would be so much easier to explain the
ethnic cleansing in Kosovo, the Rwandan genocidal rampage, the
hideousness of the killing and mutilating in Sierra Leone, Saddam
Hussein and the massacre of the innocents at Columbine High School
in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   To suggest that the devil makes them do it is to risk being
branded as naive, although no one else has a better explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The devil aside, the usual suspects must be hauled in again
after the Littleton atrocity to try to make some sense of the
incomprehensible. The objective of that exercise is to try to
prevent more repetitions of a form of tragedy that has been
repeated with terrifying frequency in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Suspect No. 1 in the view of many Americans will once again be a
decline in the quality of parenting. It is logical to conclude that
adolescent sociopaths capable of slaughtering fellow students and
taking great relish in doing so were in some major respects failed
by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to be missing in their rearing _ love, discipline,
moral instruction, quality time.
</P>
<P>
   Suspect No. 2, some will suggest, is a combination of lax campus
security and the inattentiveness of teachers, counselors and
administrators to anti-social behavior on the part of some
students.
</P>
<P>
   There was, after all, something decidedly peculiar about a group
of students who wore black trench coats year-round, exhibited
hostility toward other students and showed a fascination with guns.
</P>
<P>
   But that's crystal-clear hindsight. The Littleton school
authorities and everyone in that community were perfectly justified
in assuming that such a bloodbath would never happen there _ not in
their largely homogeneous, affluent, suburban school district.
</P>
<P>
   There will now be a rush to take steps to prevent a recurrence,
and in the process the school could become more like a prison.
Other schools around the nation will react similarly. But the
simple fact is that a determined sociopath, particularly one
disposed to suicide, can defeat any protective system.
</P>
<P>
   The third suspect is the ready availability of guns in this
society. In the wake of this tragedy, there will be intensified
calls for tighter restrictions on gun ownership. But the truth is
that the culprits in this case would have found a way to get the
weapons they used, including grenades and homemade bombs, under any
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth suspect is entertainment. Every time something like
this happens, the movie industry, the video game industry, the
music industry and television take a public beating for promoting a
culture of violence. And they deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the usual suspects, the media are the most culpable.
Amusement industries' apologists try to brush off the criticism by
glibly asserting, like gunmakers, that their products don't make
people hurt people. But they do.
</P>
<P>
   The constant inundation of violent images with which children's
minds are bombarded from toddlerhood to adulthood predisposes them
to accepting violent action, including multiple murders, as
ordinary fare. In the process, human life is devalued for them.
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder, then, that one of the suicidal members of the
Littleton slaughter team reportedly quoted a line from a movie
(''It's a good day to die'') as he went about his egregious
business.
</P>
<P>
   The killers appeared to be divorced from reality, caught up in a
virtual world gone mad _ a world in which they were free to play
God; to decide who should live and who should die; to take
vengeance upon anyone who had ever offended them; to eliminate
those they envied (the athletes) and those they hated instinctively
(the minorities).
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, they were similar to Slobodan Milosevic, Saddam
Hussein and Adolf Hitler, that personification of evil whose
birthday anniversary fell, certainly not coincidentally, on the day
they vented their pent-up rage.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that the makers of films, records and video games
contribute to the development of that kind of mind-set, they are
complicit in the increasing amount of violence being perpetrated by
America's children.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the devaluation of human life that is occurring in
this country and around the world certainly cannot be blamed
entirely on films, television or the virtual-reality-enhancing
powers of increasingly sophisticated computer games and networks.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be something more pervasive and frightening
going on. But it is not sophisticated to speak of evil or demon
possession these days, even if no one has a better explanation.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
