<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SCENE-HNS &LR;      04-22 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING LEAVES A CLOUD OF DARKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The skies over Columbine High School mirrored
the anguished, inconsistent mood of the throngs convened below.
Sometimes the tears and the rain could come, sometimes they
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of people circulated through an adjacent park
Wednesday in a hushed state of ambulatory bereavement, the clouds
above dropped lower by the hour, finally forming charcoal cumulus
formations that dipped like molten wax over the assemblage.
</P>
<P>
   Only the occasional sprinkle mingled with the tears of the
weeping masses, many of them students of the school where death
came calling one day before.
</P>
<P>
   Clinging to one another in couples and in groups, the students
sobbed silently, or wailed. They hoisted signs, created shrines
and, like the teen-agers they are, mingled madly.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen dead. Gunned down by two of their own, who apparently
killed themselves. There was the one thing the students couldn't
wrap their arms around. The circumstance remained stubbornly
incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   The children were not alone. They were matched in numbers by
adult members of this mind-boggled community, including many of
their parents. Clergy strolled through the crowd, offering
consolation to those who asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm struck by the sense of caring that these people are
showing each other,'' said the Rev. Peter Sawtell of the Columbine
United Church. ``It's amazing how people find a place to gather and
show their sense of caring.''
</P>
<P>
   One shrine, at the base of a leafless tree, was festooned by
balloons _ some in the shapes of butterflies, others bearing the
proud name of Columbine High School _ as well as hundreds of
flowers and several teddy bears.
</P>
<P>
   Another featured a huge canvas sign where students could write
messages to the living and the dead. One read: ``We'll miss all of
you. I don't understand why this had to happen to us. WHY? Jami.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why'' and ``love'' are frequently used here.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there was no anger. Above the tree shrine, on
a giant poster board, was this declaration: ``These flowers and
prayers are for the innocent victims and their families, not for
the two monsters that committed these selfish and violent acts.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Dylan Klebold, 17, and Eric Harris, 18, the two
gunmen who rampaged through the school Tuesday, killing students
and a teacher, before turning their guns on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One female friend told a Denver TV station the two young men
were ``good people who made bad choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Swanson, a 17-year-old senior, knew them both, though not
well. He said Harris played on the recreational soccer league
before joining the so-called ``Trench Coat Mafia,'' a small group
of outcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson said most of the Trench Coat Mafia ``are very smart
kids. They made good grades.''
</P>
<P>
   But they had been rejected, and teased, by many of the students.
Why? ``They didn't have very good hygiene,'' Swanson said. ``They
had greasy hair and smelled a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Klebold, he added, ``got teased a little more'' than the rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
