<HEADLINE>
TEENS SHOWED SIGNS OF TROUBLE, SPECIALISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Had anyone been looking a little harder, they
would have seen red flags hinting that Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan
Klebold, 17, were in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The two Colorado seniors who killed 12 classmates, a teacher
and, finally, themselves in the worst school shooting in American
history were behaving in ways that analysts say indicate a child is
headed toward violence.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, many teen-agers behave similarly, yet they don't
burst into schools and kill people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are patterns of behavior you can recognize, but the
behavior is not so different from other kids who go through radical
behaviors and emerge just fine,'' said Michael Kelleher, who has
analyzed school killings in his book, ``When Good Kids Kill.''
``There are very subtle differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Although much is still unknown about Harris and Klebold, the few
facts tumbling out about them suggest that, like other young
killers in other school shootings in the past two years, there were
plenty of warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   They were isolated from other students who taunted them for not
fitting in with one of Columbine High School's cliques, and created
their own group: the black-clad ``Trench Coat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   They immersed themselves in so-called fringe activities such as
role-playing computer games heavy on violence and fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   They held Web site conversations that discussed death, killing
and fury.
</P>
<P>
   They openly expressed hatred of certain groups: ethnic
minorities, athletes and the in-crowd.
</P>
<P>
   They boasted to classmates of having guns and the knowledge to
make bombs.
</P>
<P>
   They had recent run-ins with the law, arrested last year for
breaking into a car.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher and other specialists say any adult should pay
attention to these warning signs, even while realizing that most
disenfranchised teens turn out fine. And they should intervene by
talking extensively with children in their lives and by getting
them involved in social activities, be it work, or clubs or
volunteer efforts. If they don't, Kelleher said, society must
always be prepared to pay the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just pack yourself away and say you don't care,
because society won't work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Educators, psychologists and others say there are many things
that schools, parents and society at large can do to stem what
seems to be an increasing culture of violence in America.
</P>
<P>
   Most say the first line of defense remains the family.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a 1997 study published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association found that teen-agers' connections with their
parents and schools were the most powerful predictors of their
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers surveyed 90,000 seventh- through 12th-graders
nationwide. They found that children who spent more time with their
parents before or after school, and who discussed values and
expectations with their parents, were far less likely to drink,
smoke, have thoughts of suicide or get involved in violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``How often do we sit down and really communicate about issues
with our kids?'' Kelleher said. ``Information flows in great
quantity and with great rapidity, but it lacks the moral imperative
that goes with the communication of old-fashioned talking.''
</P>
<P>
   The schools, the next line of defense, can also do a better job
of knowing the student they are preparing for the world, added
Michael Rosenberg, chairman of the special education department at
Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many activities for the sports-minded and
academic-minded,'' Rosenberg said. ``But what happens is that kids
who are not in either group feel further and further away.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been stunned when he saw Columbine High students
saying on television news that the suspects were at the bottom of
the ``food chain'' at the 1,965-student school.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's it like for these kids to be at the bottom of the food
chain?'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullying, teasing and name-calling have been going on since
childhood was born, he acknowledged, but not every kid takes it in
the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some listen to taunts and suck it up and become brain
surgeons,'' he said. ``Others go to a bell tower and shoot
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
