<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DURANGO': AH, HOME ON THE RANGE, AND ESPECIALLY GREEN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it's comforting to watch a film that lets you know in
its first minutes just where it's headed. ``Durango'' telegraphs
its trajectory immediately. It gives you a decent young man with a
Big Idea who asks his neighbors to believe in him. Will they do so?
Will their faith be rewarded? Will the young man's success help him
win the hand of his beloved?
</P>
<P>
   Are the hills of Ireland green?
</P>
<P>
   So with no need to worry about the proceedings turning tragic,
you can sit back and relax while this sweetly improbable story
meanders through the dazzling Irish countryside. The trip may not
be exciting, but it's a delight nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its title, ``Durango,'' which CBS is offering on Sunday
night, is not a western. It is about a cattle drive, but through
County Kerry in 1939. The drive ends at a cowboy-theme pub called
Durango. That might seem like an anachronistic touch.
</P>
<P>
   But this being a made-for-television movie, it was based (all
together now!) (italics)on a true story.(end italics) In this case
the true story inspired a book by John B. Keane, the
publican-novelist of Listowel, who was one of the real Irish
drovers.
</P>
<P>
   The decent young man is Mark Doran (Matt Keeslar), who raises
cows with his widowed mum. The other farmers in Mark's village sell
their cattle at a crummy price to a sleazy local businessman who
then sells the stock at a whopping profit. The farmers know they
could get a better price at the market town 40 miles away. But how
to move the animals? There's no rail connection, and the farmers
can't afford a truck.
</P>
<P>
   Mark's inspiration is to organize that cattle drive. ``There's
many a good reason why it can't be done,'' says one of the
village's leading citizens, Fergus Mullaney (Patrick Bergin). For
starters, the route to market passes through a treacherous bog and
over a haunted hill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mark gets Fergus' blessing and his dear old bull to sell.
What Mark really wants from Fergus is permission to marry his
daughter Annie, his youngest child and the apple of his possessive
eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never let that darlin' girl go,'' says Fergus. ``If any
man ever comes near her, I'll pull off his head like the cork out
of an ink bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   The twinkle-eyed Annie (Nancy St. Alban) worries, but just for a
moment, that his neighbors' hopes and dreams may be too heavy a
burden for Mark. ``It doesn't weigh you down a bit?'' she asks.
``It lifts me up,'' he declares.
</P>
<P>
   Even a viewer too sophisticated for this kind of fluff may feel
a bit lifted up, too, as Mark and his ragtag crew move toward their
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The script, by the veteran screenwriter Walter Bernstein, never
strays across the border from sweet into maudlin. The film is full
of broadly drawn Irish characters, but there's no caricature in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most memorable supporting players are Brenda Fricker
as Mark's tough-talking Aunt Maeve, George Hearn, as a
motorcycle-riding Protestant rector, and Mark Lambert as a deserter
from the Irish Army who wants to join the British one so he can
fight Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Shields, who has been a producer for several ``Hallmark
Hall of Fame'' productions, makes his directing debut with this
one. He keeps his winning cast moving in the right direction, well
served by man and beast.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, beast. These cattle are not the monolithic longhorns of
``Rawhide.'' They are a mismatched pride of proud animals that seem
as wise as judges. Each one looks as if it could tell you a story
worth hearing. But none looks as if it would yield much of a
brisket.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DURANGO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Sunday night at 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written by Walter Bernstein and based on the novel by John B.
Keane. Music by Mark McKenzie. Brent Shields, director and
producer; Shelly Johnson, director of photography; Mark Geraghty,
production designer. Produced by Hallmark Hall of Fame Productions.
Richard Welsh, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Matt Keeslar (Mark Doran), Patrick Bergin (Fergus
Mullaney), George Hearn (Rector), Nancy St. Alban (Annie Mullaney),
Dermot Martin (Jay Mullaney), Paul Ronan (Tom Mullaney), Brenda
Fricker (Aunt Maeve) and Mark Lambert (Algie). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
