<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURVIVAL TALE IN THE ICE FLOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An engrossing if partial account of an incredible feat of
survival, Frank Hurley's film ``South: Ernest Shackleton and the
Endurance Expedition'' (1919) also must rank as one of the better
dog movies.
</P>
<P>
   On the 1914 voyage from Buenos Aires to the Antarctic continent,
which Shackleton planned to cross on foot, the decks of his ship,
the Endurance, were lined with kennels of the dogs who were to pull
his sleds. A more attractive, winning group of animals would be
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, everything aboard the Endurance has a natural grace in
Hurley's film, which has been restored and is available on cassette
from Milestone Film and Video. As photographer of the expedition _
his still pictures and clips from the film are on view at the
American Museum of Natural History (review in the Art Guide, page
X) _ he reveals a group of 27 men who seem particularly at ease
with themselves and their situation, even when it begins to
deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton never went on his trek, of course. The Endurance
became stuck in the ice before reaching land and was eventually
crushed. Having abandoned ship (the dogs sliding down a canvas
chute), the party drifted for months on the floes before sailing
their lifeboats to a tiny speck called Elephant Island.
</P>
<P>
   From there Shackleton and five crewmen got aboard the 22-foot
boat called the James Caird and in an astounding display of
seamanship kept it upright across 800 miles of the wildest water on
earth. Upon reaching South Georgia Island, he dispatched a rescue
party that, after three failed attempts, plucked his fellows off
Elephant Island. Every one of them lived.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley wasn't with Shackleton in the James Caird, so the latter
part of the saga is depicted only in drawings and referred to in
caption panels. But ``South'' offers wonderful views of the voyage.
Gradually the adventurers, who are mostly scientists, begin to see
their breath. A group of crab-eater seals is spotted headed in the
opposite direction, a sign of a bad winter. As the pack ice closes
in, Shackleton climbs to the crow's nest and directs the ship into
the floes.
</P>
<P>
   In one fine stretch of film, the Endurance acts as a battering
ram, with the great shadow of its bowsprit fleeting across the snow
as the prow opens seams through the ice beneath. At last the ship
is brought to a stop. The crew, a capable-looking pipe-smoking lot
dressed in woolens (no down parkas in those days) calmly gets off
and begins an earnest but by no means desperate-looking effort to
clear a path with picks and ice saws.
</P>
<P>
   The ship backs off and tries one more run at the pack. No luck.
Days later the Endurance sits pitched over to port with its stern
thrust high in the air. The men have set up camp close by and walk
about conversing, clapping one another on the back and choosing
items from the last of the clothing stores.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, a caption says, ``the real troubles and
hardships commenced.'' Hurley's account ends here, but the film
resumes on South Georgia Island. The syndicate sponsoring the film,
which runs 88 minutes, sent him back to fill it out with scenes of
seals and penguins, which were a novelty in movies of that era. The
dogs, alas, had perished.
</P>
<P>
   The tape is $29.95. Information: (800) 603-1104.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth
</P>
<P>
   With a passing nod to historical accuracy, Shekhar Kapur's
lavish costume drama sets out for racier cinematic precincts. As
Elizabeth I, Cate Blanchett (left) carries her responsibilities
with the air of a glamorously stressed-out modern woman with a
super-intense case of having it all. At first intimidated by her
adversaries, she survives to see heads roll. Lovers come and go, no
match for her destiny or needs. That Kapur knew nothing about the
real queen, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``only helps
to make his Elizabeth that much sassier a sovereign, slouching on
her throne.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $99.99. 121 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: April 27. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stepmom
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Kelly (Julia Roberts) couldn't be nicer or try harder
with her boyfriend's children (Jena Malone and Liam Aiken), but
everything she does either falls flat with them or is rated
dangerous to their well-being by their mother, Jackie (Susan
Sarandon). Isabel, a fashion photographer, has moved in with Luke
(Ed Harris), the children's father. Since her divorce from Luke,
Jackie has held forth from their old house in the suburbs. But
Jackie is ill and suddenly it's time to drop the rivalry. Despite
all the platitudes five screenwriters could muster, Ms. Roberts and
Ms. Sarandon ``go through their motions with unexpected conviction
and make the film a lot more watchable than it has any right to
be'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37. 124 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13. Release date: April 27. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Happiness
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not the customary suburban scene, what with Dad (Dylan
Baker) being a pederast and drugging the family's dessert so he can
have some time to seduce the friend of his young son (Rufus Read).
Todd Solondz's film portrays the three Jordan sisters (Cynthia
Stevenson, Jane Adams and Lara Flynn Boyle) and the problems in
their lives, not the least of them being the child molester, who is
married to one of them and who is a psychiatrist to boot. With this
follow-up to his acclaimed ``Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' Solondz
establishes his as ``one of the most lacerating, funny and
distinctive voices in American film'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Trimark. 139 minutes. Closed captioned. No rating. Release
date: April 27. &QL; 
 &QL; 
At First Sight
</P>
<P>
   Virgil Adamson (Val Kilmer) is a blind masseur who jokes with
his guide dog and lives peacefully in a little Hudson River town
until he starts kneading Amy Benic (Mira Sorvino), a tense
professional type up from New York City. Under his touch empathy
sets in between the two and then a major crush. Along the way
Virgil even begins to regain his eyesight, but one ends up wishing
they would just get on with it in ``an indulgently meandering film
that could have been pruned at many junctures'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. MGM. $105.77. 126 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: April 27.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   CONSPIRATORS OF PLEASURE. The surrealist visionary Jan
Svankmajer, one of the world's most renowned animators, uses clay
marionettes, dolls and eerily infused everyday objects to create
fiendishly witty nightmares from the fantasies of a group of
ordinary Prague residents. Six actors also contribute, Stephen
Holden wrote in The New York Times, to a mostly silent film about
``the erotic impulse of everyday life as a wild, chaotic,
antisocial force that lends people their sense of individuality.''
(The tape also includes ``Food,'' a 14-minute short by Svankmajer.)
1993. Kino. $79.95. 83 minutes. No rating. Information: (800)
562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   BEHIND THE SCENES. The magicians Penn and Teller are hosts of
two episodes of the PBS children's series that delves into the
creative processes of noted artists. On the first tape, David
Hockney draws ``a walk around a chair'' to illustrate tricks of
perspective and illusion. In the second show, the director and
designer Julie Taymor applies her concepts of visual theater to a
production of ``The Tempest.'' 1992. First Run Features. $14.95
each. 30 minutes each. Information: (800) 488-6652.
</P>
<P>
   MONDO. Wandering the streets of Nice, a young boy (Ovidiu Balan)
asks strangers if they want to adopt him in, Holden wrote in The
Times, ``a gorgeously photographed tear-jerker that hovers on the
line between the icky and the profound.'' 1997. New Yorker. 80
minutes. French with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
