<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-22 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 A JUG OF WINE, BOOK OF VERSE AND THOU   (For use by New York Times
News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An industry knows it has arrived when it graduates
from being looked on as a boutique ``special interest'' to being
both a political force and a political target.
</P>
<P>
   It's the American way.
</P>
<P>
   That's what has happened to the wine industry over the past
decade, as grapes grew to become the eighth largest crop in the
country and wine sales soared both at home and abroad. It is now an
agricultural giant to be reckoned with. And it has powerful allies
in the tourist and restaurant industries, which profit handsomely
from their wine-sipping customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wine has become so universally popular that a glass in most
restaurants and hotels sells for three to four times the retail
price, reaching as high as $15 a glass in the fanciest places. As
for the price of bottles _ wow! Chicken and beef may pose as the
main attraction but those items do not bring in nearly as much
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Money talks. And so the Wine Institute _ which represents the
vintners who are now the leading industry in California, in
addition to wineries in New York, Washington, Texas, Oregon and
Virginia _ was flexing its political muscle this week in
Washington. Led by Institute president John DeLuca, a horde of
folks representing big-name family labels descended on Capitol Hill
to lobby for their cause and fight off recent legislative attacks
upon their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   This thing about drinking is politically tricky. As a national
issue, only abortion is as emotionally susceptible to public
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to drinking, we too often say one thing and do
another. Some of the heaviest drinkers in Congress over the years
have raised the loudest voices against alcohol, pandering to sober
folks back home who have religious or teetotalist objections to its
consumption. But this issue is not really about morality, or about
some liquor versus no liquor. It's about votes.
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry tries to rise above the din by separating
itself from the beer guzzlers and the martini drinkers. It
advertises wine as merely a natural and healthy complement to meals
when taken in moderation. And, actually, so it is.
</P>
<P>
   Independent scientific studies suggest but do not finally
confirm that moderate consumption can lower the risk of heart
disease. This led the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
(BATF) to allow wine bottles to use a label suggesting buyers learn
the ``health effects'' of wine consumption by sending for the
federal government's dietary guidelines for Americans. The
guidelines include a glass of wine or two at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   (Wine, beer and spirits must still carry a mandated government
warning about the risks of drinking alcoholic beverages during
pregnancy or before driving a car or operating machinery.)
</P>
<P>
   But the winemakers are under serious assault on two fronts these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, held
hearings this month about legislation he has introduced that would
allow states to file suit against companies that ship beer, wine
and spirits directly to consumers who order them over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is described as necessary to prevent minors from buying
prohibited alcohol from out-of-state suppliers. And who could be
opposed to keeping kids from getting booze they shouldn't have?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but that's not the whole story. This little bill is really a
wholesaler protection measure, designed to protect the traditional
distribution system from being bypassed by direct sales. It's the
wholesalers versus the small retailers and the Internet world.
</P>
<P>
   The kiddie issue, however, has legs. So California Sen. Dianne
Feinstein is working with Hatch to develop legislation that would
require the delivery service to certify the age of the package's
recipient to establish that the alcohol is put into the hands of a
hopefully responsible adult. Hatch isn't jumping sides yet, but he
may accept a compromise. There isn't a big wine industry in Utah
yet, but who knows?
</P>
<P>
   A more stubborn and emotional opponent, however, is Senate
President Pro Tem Strom Thurmond, whose daughter was killed by a
drunken driver. Thurmond is out to get the wine industry, plain and
simple. He is furious that the vintners have, in his words, been
``using health claims as a marketing scheme,'' no matter how
accurate those claims.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond has proposed new taxes on wine _ but not on beer or
distilled spirits _ because ``wine is consumed by more prosperous
taxpayers'' than those who drink beer. He would transfer authority
over alcoholic beverage labeling from the BATF to the Department of
Health and Human Services, thus punishing the bureau for its recent
decision to permit the new nonthreatening wine label. And he would
rescind the new label itself.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Thurmond has found no cosponsors to join him in picking
on the wine industry this way. He has underestimated its clout.
This bunch got the French _ the French! _ to drink $1 million worth
of American wine last year. Truly a sign of formidable power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
