<HEADER>
A9379 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-BLACKCOATS-COX     04-22 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BLACKCOATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three Colorado school districts ban black dusters
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Three Denver-area school districts on
Thursday decided to ban students from wearing long, black dusters
to school, but school officials in Grand Junction said such a rule
is not necessary here.
</P>
<P>
   School District 51 administrators say they haven't noticed many
students wearing the long, black cowboy dusters that have been
associated with the two boys, Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris, who
shot and killed 12 classmates and a teacher Tuesday in Littleton,
before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who do wear them, said Fruita Monument Principal Mark
Zipse, do so only when it's cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date it hasn't been a problem,'' he said. ``But if we did
see evidence of that, we'll absolutely take a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver Public Schools, along with districts in Douglas County
and parts of Adams County, adopted new rules banning dusters,
saying in light of what happened at Columbine High School, seeing
people wearing such coats could be disruptive to students.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Junction High School Principal Joan Edmonds said she
believed there were two students who wore similar coats to class
before, but since Tuesday they have not been wearing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It presents a problem right now because of the nature of
what's happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policy already restricts students from wearing any attire that
is offensive or attire that inhibits student learning,'' said
Denise Henning, vice president of the District 51 school board.
``We have not had any discussion regarding banning any such apparel
nor do I think we need to put such a ban in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Clothing wasn't the most important issue, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to send a clear message that any hate symbols or
verbal expressions of hate toward any one individual or group is
not tolerated on school grounds,'' Henning said. Superintendent
George Straface was unavailable for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Marcia Neal said banning black coats would work for
a while, just like a similar clothing ban did several years ago
when the district began prohibiting students from wearing red and
blue bandannas to school, which have been linked to gang activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a temporary thing to make people feel better, but
if they're doing it because they think it will stop some future
event, I think they are wrong,'' Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be another group. They'll change to
something else or they will object.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
