<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ The stories of those that NATO seeks to
protect. Humanitarian aid officials try to figure out how to
protect the refugees from the increased shelling and fighting along
the Kosovo border. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ Now that the first
wave of Apache helicopters have landed, all the pieces seem to be
in place for a U.S.-led NATO ground troops strikeforce in Kosovo.
We talk to former military types and ask, ``Just what are we
waiting for, anyway?'' (Albright/Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TROOPS-BOX _ WASHINGTON _ A breakdown of just what we have on
the Montenegro, Albania and Macedonia borders with the Yugoslav
province. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SENATE _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.), one of
five Vietnam veterans now serving in the Senate, has emerged as one
of the most strident critics of introducing ground troops in Kosovo
while another vet, John McCain, has been a leading proponent. We
look at where veterans in the Senate line up on the Balkan crisis.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   NATO-WALESA-Q&AMP;A _ WASHINGTON _ Lech Walesa, a former president
of Poland and a Nobel Peace Prize winner, told Cox Washington
Bureau reporters Thursday that NATO should use massive military
force to dislodge Yugoslavian forces from Kosovo. A Q&AMP;A on
international issues. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-PROTESTS _ MIAMI _ Jamaica is a popular tourist
destination known for many things -- reggae music, pristine beaches
and, oftentimes, violence. This week the island has lived up to its
reputation. At least four people have been killed in a week of
protests over hikes in Jamaica's gas tax. The U.S. Embassy has been
closed and tourists have been ordered to stay in their hotels. And
airlines have canceled flights to Jamaica. Tourism officials are
afraid the protests will affect tourism, which generates income for
more than one-fourth of the population. Jamaica has a long history
of violence, and this isn't the first time protests have shut down
the island's capital, Kingston. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-LEDE _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ Main news developments of the
day. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BLACKCOATS _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Three Denver-area
school districts on Thursday decided to ban students from wearing
long, black dusters to school, but school officials in Grand
Junction said such a rule is not necessary here. School District 51
administrators say they haven't noticed many students wearing the
long, black cowboy dusters that have been associated with the two
boys, Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris, who shot and killed 12
classmates and a teacher Tuesday in Littleton, before killing
themselves. (Taylor, Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-RENO _ Attorney General holds press conference in
Jefferson County. (Daily Sentinel)
</P>
<P>
   COX-SCHOOL-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, speaking
Thursday to a high school class in suburban Virginia about the
Colorado massacre, assured them that America remained a decent
place and that schools were safe for students. Clinton was vague
about solutions for school violence, lightly touching on both the
availablity of guns and cultural influences. (Malone, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SIDE _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ Sidebar to main news of the
day. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SLAYINGS - WEST PALM BEACH _ Is my kid a sociopathic
loser? Kids experiment with their looks and personas. They go
through phases, jumping from grunge to black fingernail polish goth
looks to hip hop. They listen to techno music, then heavy metal,
then rap. They play war garmes, experiment wtih spirituality and
their sexual identity. And there is - and always will be, even in
an age of political correctness - tension between cliques. But how
can you tell, in an age where anything goes, if your kid has
crossed the line from creative self-expression to psycho loser
killer? (Evans, Palm Beach Post). 40.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SCHOOLVIOLENCE _ ATLANTA _ Barnes to sign law today that
requires public schools to work with emergency management agencies
in developing a safety plan for acts of violence or terrorism,
natural disasters and hazardous material accidents. Private schools
are excluded from the state requirements. (Mantius, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POLL _Two new polls indicate Gov. George W. Bush's
popularity is more name and image than accomplishment or position
on the issues. In the latest Texas Poll, Bush's approval ratings
remain high (7 in 10 Texans love the gov), but nearly half can't
name any accomplishments. A blind poll in New Hampshire indicates
Bush's popularity there is only name-deep. The poll gives Bush a
massive lead over runner-up Elizabeth Dole. But the lead melts away
when candidate bios _ instead of names _ are offered to voters.
(Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
