<HEADER>
A9382 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-A's-BIDDING-HNS &LR;      04-22 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A's-BIDDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STADIUM AUTHORITY CONSIDERS BIDS FOR OAKLAND CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The bidding game for the Oakland Athletics
baseball team has gone into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than choose between two bids, an investment banking
company hired to find a buyer for the team by Wednesday's deadline
opted instead to leave the decision to the Oakland-Alameda County
Coliseum Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The $122.4 million bids from two groups of investors were
presented to the authority, said Randy Vataha, executive of Game
Plan LLC, the Boston sports investment banking company hired to
handle the bids.
</P>
<P>
   The authority has 20 days _ until May 11 _ to look over the
financing and terms of each bid before making a decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The authority's top choice must be approved by officials of
Major League Baseball. In addition, three-quarters of the American
League club owners and a majority of the National League owners
must give their approval. All decisions must be reached by
mid-September, Vataha said.
</P>
<P>
   Game Plan announced Tuesday that two prospective buyers had met
the authority's requirement that they put $12 million deposits in
escrow.
</P>
<P>
   One group consists of San Mateo lawyer and former bank executive
Michael Lazarus, Arizona banker Lyle Campbell and former Baltimore
Orioles star pitcher Steve Stone.
</P>
<P>
   The other group is led by former A's executive Andy Dolich. The
other investors include George Zimmer, owner of the Fremont-based
Men's Wearhouse clothing chain, Modesto grocery mogul Robert
Piccinin, the Oakland Tribune, and San Francisco advertising
executive Jeff Goodby.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors may join either group in the weeks ahead, Vataha
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the non-negotiable terms of the proposed sale, the buyer
must pay $122.4 million (including $2.4 million in commissions) to
the club's owners, Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann, and agree to keep
the A's in Oakland at least through 2004. Dolich has said it would
be his group's intention to keep the A's in Oakland indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Without a buyer, Schott and Hofmann have the contractual right
to leave Oakland after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Leading candidates among alternative sites for the club are San
Jose and Santa Clara, where South Bay A's boosters say the club
would be able to make enough money to field a top-flight team.
</P>
<P>
   As the Coliseum Authority considers the offers, the buyers, too,
will have a chance to weigh their options. The A's confidential
financial statements have not yet been examined by a prospective
buyer, and the possibility remains that some spreadsheet revelation
could prompt a change in plans _ and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich said recently that, although he had been a club official
through 1994, he has not seen the A's ``audited financials.''
</P>
<P>
   Other prospective buyers who came forward at various points in
the bidding process, but dropped out along the way or chose to
withhold a commitment until after Wednesday's deadline, included
Hollywood producers Peter Guber and Paul Schaeffer of Mandalay
Entertainment, and Northern California real estate man John
Kehriotis.
</P>
<P>
   Kehriotis said he would consider bidding only after the deadline
and would offer less than the $122.4 million demanded. He also has
expressed interest in moving the club to Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to present both bids to the Coliseum Authority
rather than Game Plan's pick as the front-runner was made early
Wednesday, said Vataha, after all of the interested parties agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The talks with prospective buyers had been intensive and more
complex than anticipated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're down to the last minute, and we're trying to do what
our company feels is best for baseball, the city and the county,''
Vataha said. ``You're not sure how it will come out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
