<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOON ART IN SUBWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Art is continually being produced for New York's
subway stations, but little finds its way into the subway cars.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Public Art Fund, a nonprofit organization that produces
art projects around New York, has begun a citywide exhibition of
cartoonlike images by Simon Grennan and Christopher Sperandio in
subway cars.
</P>
<P>
   The artist team has been creating Conceptual Art since 1988,
even though Greennan lives in Manchester, England, and Sperandio in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest project, ``The Invisible City,'' is a series of
comic strips that tell real-life stories of night-shift workers in
New York. The comics, in the form of 1,140 advertising placards,
are being installed in about 1,000 subway cars.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Eccles, director of the Public Art Fund, said he expected
them to be on display for at least a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artists put ads in the paper seeking stories from
night-shift workers and got all kinds of responses,'' Eccles said.
They met with many of the respondents and chose several for the
project, including a cleaner, a waiter at a gay bar, a security
guard, a television network technician and, appropriately enough, a
worker in a subway train yard.
</P>
<P>
   The artists photographed the participants at work and with the
help of a computer program transformed these photographs into
comic-book-like scenes using the participant's own words to
illustrate the images. Each one tells of a different work
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were specifically looking for a media-based project,
something that would naturally follow Barbara Kruger's bus
project,'' Eccles said. (Two years ago Ms. Kruger decorated a New
York City bus in shrink-wrap plastic covered with her signature
pithy sayings.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Invisible City,'' sponsored by the Lannan Foundation, is
also available as a traditional comic book. Two thousand are
available free from the Public Art Fund, 1 East 53d Street, New
York, N.Y. 10022, or through its Web site at www.publicartfund.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Growing Hammer
</P>
<P>
   It's been just three months since Ann Philbin became director of
the Armand Hammer Museum of Art and Cultural Center, and already
she is making things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the museum's board gave Ms. Philbin approval to begin
a major renovation and expansion of the nine-year-old museum's
building in the Westwood section of Los Angeles. It hired Michael
Maltzan, a Los Angeles architect, for the project.
</P>
<P>
   When Armand Hammer, chairman of the Occidental Petroleum Corp.,
who founded the museum, died in 1990, much of the museum's $60
million building had not been finished. ``We plan to complete the
portions of the building that have never been properly finished and
renovate the building to make it more hospitable,'' Ms. Philbin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the proposed improvements are two flexible gallery spaces,
one for contemporary art and the other for works on paper. Another
addition would be a 300-seat auditorium, part of Hammer's original
design. Plans call for moving the bookstore from the second floor
to the Wilshire Boulevard entrance and adding a restaurant in the
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the building's entrances are architecturally awkward and
uninviting,'' Ms. Philbin said. ``This is one of the few spots in
Los Angeles that actually gets pedestrian traffic, and we want to
figure out a way to take advantage of that and create a more
welcoming public space inside the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   The renovation is expected to cost about $10 million. The museum
has also hired Bruce Mau Design, the Toronto-based graphic
designer, to work with Maltzan in redesigning the museum's signs.
</P>
<P>
   An All-Weekend Party
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Museum of Art is pulling a double
all-nighter _ more precisely, a 63-hour run _ staying open
continuously from 9 a.m. Friday, May 14, through midnight on
Sunday, May 16. The occasion is the closing of its hugely popular
show ``Van Gogh's van Goghs: Masterpieces From the Van Gogh Museum,
Amsterdam,'' which was organized by the museum and the National
Gallery of Art in Washington (where it was on view last fall).
</P>
<P>
   Since the show opened in Los Angeles on Jan. 17, it has drawn
600,000 visitors, making it the most successful show the museum has
had in 20 years. The record holder is believed to be ``The
Treasures of Tutankhamen'' 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured, why not give it a final blast,'' said Andrea L.
Rich, the museum's president and chief executive officer. ``The
demand here for tickets has been huge. We started out being open
seven days a week for 12 hours a day and were sold out every
weekend.'' With the end of the show near, there is a feeding frenzy
for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets cost $17.50 for adults on weekdays and $20 on weekends.
For those interested in seeing the show between midnight and 7
a.m., the museum will take $10. All tickets are available through
Ticketmaster as well as the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Late-night visitors may make a party of their visit. The museum
is transforming its fifth floor penthouse and outdoor terrace into
what it is calling the ``Club van Gogh,'' featuring hors d'oeuvres
inspired by the artist's paintings and a cash bar. (The drinks
include a van Gogh martini, a combination of Dutch gin and Pernod.)
</P>
<P>
   The museum can't claim to be the first to stay open all night.
The Royal Academy of London did it recently, for its crowd-pleasing
show ``Monet in the 20th Century,'' which closed last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Angeles, more than London, is a city that stays alive at
night. Evening attendance was so high that two years ago, after
surveying its visitors, the museum changed its hours from the
traditional 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and now opens at noon every day,
closing at 8 p.m. or, on Fridays, at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a whole new crowd,'' Ms. Rich said. ``Los Angeles has
people who work all over the city, and they find that it's most
convenient to visit museums after work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
