<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0423-     04-22 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A NEW 'TRICKLE' TIRED, CONFUSED REFUGEES CROSS ALBANIA,
MACEDONIA BORDERS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA BORDER POINT, Albania _ A small surge of about 800
refugees escaped here from Kosovo Thursday, giving clues but no
real answers to the fate of hundreds of thousands of others
believed still trapped in the vise of Serbian ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   At least 2,000 refugees walked through Macedonia's main border
crossing, Blace, on Thursday. It was unclear if these were the
vanguard of a new phalanx of ethnic Albanians who would be
permitted to leave, or merely one group set free by some
authority's whim.
</P>
<P>
   Some bore bullet wounds and others the glazed look of
exhaustion. The great majority had walked about 20 miles that
morning, after taking refuge for four nights in a greenhouse at a
village northwest of the border crossing.
</P>
<P>
   They confirmed speculation that the Serb army and police had
halted their flight from Kosovo last Sunday, the day the flow of
refugees here virtually dried up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers stopped us and told us to go back, to go home,''
said Ganimete Berisha, 43, who was traveling with her husband and
seven children, including a six-week old baby.
</P>
<P>
   Her family and others confronted with the same demand were too
frightened to try to return to their villages, which they said
local Serbian police and army had forced them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The townspeople of a village called Zrze took in the bewildered
wanderers, letting them stay in a large greenhouse and giving them
food and milk for the babies.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the refugees said, Serb soldiers came to
them and said they must leave Zrze in the morning. They said they
were told to chose their ravaged homes or this Albanian border as a
destination.
</P>
<P>
   None of the refugees questioned had any explanation for the
erratic policy of Yugoslavia's Serb authorities.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to this group still does not explain the
whereabouts of tens of thousands of others who had been reported on
the road in Kosovo and even standing in a line that refugees
arriving last Saturday and Sunday said extended more than 10 miles
to the border.
</P>
<P>
   Those others may have run into similar roadblocks to departure,
but have not yet been told they can cross into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   If these refugees are any example, the Kosovar Albanians are on
the run. Most of the refugees who arrived Thursday had been away
from their homes for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Berisha family told of being chased from their village and
staying in the mountains for three weeks before Serb forces found
them and demanded they get out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They walked for three days, being sent first in one direction,
then another. Then they ran into the soldiers who told them to turn
around and go home. After that, they ended up in Zrze.
</P>
<P>
   Others described similar odysseys, punctuated by beatings and
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tekepat Ceshmes Military Post along the Macedonian border
of Kosovo province, humanitarian aid workers were finally allowed
Thursday to get food, water and blankets to refugees sheltering in
``medieval'' conditions in a snowy mountain village on the
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey Davies of the U.N. World Food Programme, who was with
the convoy that entered the hamlet, said they had been rebuffed by
Macedonian authorities for three days before four aid trucks were
allowed to continue along the twisting, muddy road and deliver
their supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonians had for days forbidden access, citing what they said
was Serb military activity in the area. A short section of the road
passes through Serb territory.
</P>
<P>
   Even after aid workers were allowed through, journalists were
halted at the military post, which looks over a pair of steep
ridges into southern Kosovo. Throughout the day, warplanes roared
overhead, sonic booms sounding, and at one point a plume of smoke
could be seen rising in the distance on the Kosovo side of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers expressed relief at the Macedonian decision to
finally let supply convoys through and said they hoped it heralded
improved cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The episode marked the latest instance of tension between
Macedonia and international relief agencies. The government of the
former Yugoslav republic has expressed growing alarm about the
refugee influx, saying the huge numbers of new arrivals could lead
to political instability and an upsetting of the ethnic balance.
</P>
<P>
   If a big new wave of refugees is released, the relief agencies
here will be hard-pressed to accommodate them in Kukes, the largest
city in the district about 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday they started a new information campaign to urge
families to take the buses and trucks that were available to
relocate them to other cities or towns further south in Albania,
away from the increasingly dangerous Serb cross-border attacks up
here in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Teams went tent-to-tent in the camps, telling people the area is
risky and that the space they occupy well might be needed soon for
new refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Endres, coordinator here for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), said the Albanian government had
provided 30 trucks to move out refugees on Wednesday. But those
willing to depart filled up only eight of the trucks. He said 5,325
people left on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   This northern border region now holds about 125,000 refugees.
More than 130,000 are now in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
