<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(af) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tony Show is a Mystery, Too
</P>
<P>
   Want to know who's the host of this year's Tonys? You're not
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks before the awards, the show's host, format and
presenters have yet to be announced. Tony officials say the event's
planning is on schedule, but the lack of information is making some
Broadway professionals anxious. It's also complicating the job of
promoting the show.
</P>
<P>
   What several of those involved in the planning will say, on
condition of anonymity, is that the show will not have a single
host but multiple presenters, that there may be fewer musical
production numbers and that there will be no seats available for
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we have information we're withholding,'' said
one planner. ``Decisions just haven't yet been made.''
</P>
<P>
   The delays can be traced in part to a feud earlier this year
between the two groups that administer the awards: the League of
American Theaters and Producers and the American Theater Wing. The
spat was settled, but by that point, Rosie O'Donnell, who had been
the host for the last two years, had passed on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to lock up a similarly popular host, the organizers say
they are now aiming for an array of presenter-cum-hosts. This
strategy, however, has pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's Paul Newman and Gwyneth Paltrow, great,'' said one
Tony administrator. ``If it's not big names, though, we have a
problem.'' No presenter has yet been verified.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will also be tight, since this year's program has moved
from the 5,882-seat Radio City Music Hall to the 1,933-seat
Gershwin Theater. (Radio City is under renovation.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the knottiest problem is promotion. With no hosts or
presenters yet, it's impossible for press agents to set up
interviews. Deadlines for magazine covers are also already passing,
the planners say.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Sherman, the press agent whose job it is to generate
excitement about the Tonys, said he could not say exactly when any
announcement on the show would be made. ``We'll let you know as
soon as we do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Union Split
</P>
<P>
   After decades of tension and a recent confrontation, the local
union chapter that represents professional theater designers and
scenic artists is close to breaking with its parent union and
joining the stagehands union.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Miller, the president of United Scenic Artists, said
this week that the local's 2,600 members would likely approve a
referendum to dissolve its 81-year affiliation with the
International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades, which
primarily represents painters on construction sites and other
nontheater jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the referendum will not be announced until
Tuesday, but Ms. Miller said informal polls of the local's
membership showed that a vast majority approve of the split.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller said her membership, which pays dues to the
international brotherhood, was deeply dissatisfied with its
representation within the larger group, which, she said, had little
understanding of the theater world and its players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the millions we've added to their coffers, we
really haven't got much back,'' Ms. Miller added.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated calls to the international brotherhood were not
returned, but a letter sent to chapter members by Michael E.
Monroe, the brotherhood's president, said that the vote was
``inadequate and undemocratic.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a happy divorce. Last Wednesday, Ms. Miller said
officials of the brotherhood arrived at the local's offices on West
61st Street and threatened to take over the union. Eventually the
police were called to defuse the situation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the local received a temporary restraining order
from a federal judge barring the attempted takeover. Both sides are
due to appear before Judge Richard Owen Friday to re-examine the
order.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasy relationship dates to 1918, when Broadway's designers
joined the brotherhood. The scenic artists tried to dissolve the
relationship several times but were never able to muster the money
or support to do so. This time, if the split is approved, the local
will likely have to turn more than $400,000 in current assets over
to the brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller said her membership will then align itself with the
International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees, which
represents production technicians, stagehands and other stage and
film personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really where we belong,'' she said. ``They're our
home.''
</P>
<P>
   `Thwak,' a Hit
</P>
<P>
   Talking to the Umbilical Brothers involves, well, a lot of
listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a human cartoon,'' said David Collins, the
younger Umbilical, describing their show ``Thwak,'' at the Westbeth
Theater Center. ``It's like Jackie Chan meets Bugs Bunny with a bit
of my mother thrown in.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane Dundas, the older Umbilical, chimed in: ``It's kind of
doing an aerobics class in hell. Or on speed.''
</P>
<P>
   What their show is is a hit, a steady sell-out that transfers to
the Minetta Lane Theater on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Stated loosely _ very loosely _ ``Thwak'' involves the Brothers'
battle for a microphone, an 80-minute skit that involves imaginary
pets, imaginary guns and headfuls of tiny imaginary men.
</P>
<P>
   Like many young talents, the Umbilical Brothers credit their
success to schooling. (Sort of.) They first met in 1988, while
enrolled at Theater Nepean, an acting school in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole idea springs from boredom with acting
classes,'' Dundas said. ``We intended to have serious acting
careers.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning a television talent contest in their native
Australia in 1991, they began working professionally, starting with
a bar mitzvah in Sydney. Even then, things turned surreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd built a model of the Wailing Wall to perform in front
of,'' Collins said. ``I think when they booked us they thought we
were a band.'' Since then, they've hit many of the world's major
comedy festivals, as well as healthy runs on the West End in London
and at the Sydney Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they're here, the Brothers say they're excited about
staying in one place for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a bit more than an overnight,'' Dundas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
