<HEADLINE>
CHEVY, NASCAR AT ODDS OVER THE NEW MONTE CARLO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chevrolet has officially called it off. In a statement issued by
Kurt Ritter, Chevrolet's marketing general manager, the
manufacturer confirmed that it won't put a new version of the Monte
Carlo on the track until next year.
</P>
<P>
   That was pretty much a foregone conclusion as spokesmen for key
Chevy teams like Hendrick Motorsports have been saying since
February that there wasn't enough time to get the car approved,
built and tested prior to the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter ripped NASCAR, blaming stock car racing's sanctioning
body for the delay in introducing the new model Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consistently used NASCAR's input to develop the car before
formally submitting it in January for approval,'' Ritter's
statement read.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the vehicle was in line with their expectations.
Unfortunately, they did not agree and approval was not granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it stands today,'' Ritter's statement continued, ``NASCAR
is asking us to make changes that, when compared to the current '99
Monte Carlo and to other brands, would make the car
uncompetitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, NASCAR's take on all this is that Chevy kept making
changes on the car which NASCAR then had to check out, particularly
in regard to aerodynamic improvements. That, NASCAR says, prevented
officials from coming up with a set of specifications for the new
Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Before this is finally settled, it could get nasty because it
presents a problem for both Chevrolet and NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Chevy has had essentially one
competitive car, Jeff Gordon's.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt's Chevy has run well at Daytona and a couple
other places, but Earnhardt has dropped out of sight, and no new
Chevy teams have risen to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Although John Andretti won last Sunday in Martinsville, Va.,
with a terrific finish in his Pontiac, the race was dominated by
four cars _ Gordon and the three Fords of Jeff Burton, Mark Martin
and Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   And that is pretty much how the season has gone and will
continue to go. In Burton, Martin, Wallace and Dale Jarrett, Ford
has four cars that consistently run up front. Chevy has only
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   To remedy that, Chevy wants an improved Monte Carlo that will
help the performance of Earnhardt, Terry Labonte and some others.
</P>
<P>
   It is speculated, however, that NASCAR does not want the new
Monte Carlo to be any better than the current model because it's
afraid Gordon will simply crush everybody if he gets a superior
car.
</P>
<P>
   So this is a real dilemma because Chevy teams don't want to keep
getting embarrassed, and it could boil over before anyone comes up
with a solution.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
