<P>
   INTEL-BUSINESS _ Intel Corp. is the biggest and the richest
company in the semiconductor business, and its firm hold over the
personal computer industry shows no signs of weakening.
Nevertheless, Wall Street is worried about the health of the PC
industry. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GAPACIFIC-EARNINGS _ Georgia-Pacific reported profit for the
first quarter rose almost six-fold, as prices and shipments rose
for most building products. Georgia-Pacific Group, which excludes
the company's timber business, said net income rose to $99 million,
or $1.13 a share. (Bond, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NETBANK-EARNINGS _ Net.Bank, the Atlanta-based Internet banking
company, turned around a year-ago loss and reported a first quarter
profit today. The company partly credited a new marketing campaign
designed to lure away customers at more tradition banks. (Clothier,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PORTMAN-DEBT _ AMC Inc. the firm created in John C. Portman
Jr.'s huge debt restructuring in 1995, has paid off $8 million in
debt through the sale of its stake in Embarcadero Center in San
Francisco and is seeking an extension of a $93.1 million mortgage
due this summer. (Salter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;P _ ATLANTA _ Following lead that A&AMP;P is pulling out of
Atlanta market entirely. Company won't comment, but it has said
that its strategy is to be No. 1 or No. 2 in markets. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) &QR;
</P>
