<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-DREAMLIFE23-CO     04-22 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DREAMLIFE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intertwined lives of two women brilliantly observed
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Like a well-written novel, the French
film ``The Dreamlife of Angels'' slowly studies the lives of two
young women, adrift in a harsh world, in search of connections.
They strike up a bond of convenience and perceived similarities,
but have such different needs and outlooks that they soon begin
growing apart.
</P>
<P>
   That's about it in this character-driven tale, co-written by
first-time director Erick Zonca (with Roger Bohbot). But the result
has considerable cumulative power and an unshakable tug of sadness
as we get to know Isa and Marie and begin to perceive their fates.
They are two 20-something women who live for the moment, drifting
in and out of jobs, each heading toward her own particular dead
end.
</P>
<P>
   The film is engrossing enough, but its real attraction is the
pair of performances Zonca gets from Elodie Bouchez and Natacha
Regnier. They are performers so well-matched, in roles so
interwoven, that they shared the best actress award at last year's
Cannes Film Festival. They have their heightened emotional moments
occasionally, but what impresses is the understated inner lives
they build from tiny tics, longing looks and other observant
details.
</P>
<P>
   Isa (Bouchez), a close-coiffed waif who carries her worldly
possessions in a humble backpack, arrives in the dreary gray
blue-collar town of Lille and proceeds to hawk religious cards to
strangers on the street. You might call her cards homemade, if only
she had a home. When a customer offers her a real job in a garment
factory, Isa tries to fake sewing skill, but is soon found out and
fired.
</P>
<P>
   She gravitates towards co-worker Marie (Regnier), a statuesque
former waitress, who allows Isa to stay in her flat. Actually, it
isn't hers, but belonged to a woman who died in a car accident that
left her daughter in a coma. Isa and Marie seem to be kindred
spirits, roaming the streets, flirting with the bouncers outside a
dance club, coquettishly talking their way inside.
</P>
<P>
   Marie even sleeps with bouncer Charly, a fat teddy bear biker
type, but she trades him in for Chriss, the self-satisfied club
owner who rescues her from a shoplifting arrest and initiates an
abusive affair. Meanwhile, Isa has discovered the diary of the
comatose Sandrine and is drawn to visit her in the hospital,
identifying with her predicament and mortality. Isa sees Chriss for
the cad he is, but her attempts to persuade Marie merely drives the
women further apart.
</P>
<P>
   Marie grows increasingly irrational over Chriss and the hurt on
Isa's face as she watches her former friend self-destruct is
devastating. When they are abruptly told that they must move out by
the deceased woman's brother, they choose contrasting routes for
their next chapters.
</P>
<P>
   At times glacially slow, the subtitled ``Dreamlife of Angels''
is the antithesis of a Hollywood production. And that's the good
news. Those willing to give themselves over to the aimless lives of
these two women will find a simple, often undramatic tale, as
touching as it is inexplicably memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
