A9406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-TIN23-COX     04-22 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Pushing Tin' flies above just-for-laughs formula
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Was this flick produced by Amtrak? You
may never fly again after ``Pushing Tin.'' The airline pilots are
sober. It's those boggle-eyed, wisecracking, coffee-slurping,
hormonally juiced air traffic controllers who give you the shakes.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of laughs. Even though director Mike Newell can't land
this vehicle _ how many Hollywood movies end satisfactorily these
days? _ the flight of fancy is entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   We should mention what the movie rises above _ an
``Airplane''-type spoof or satire. These are real characters and
situations, although not too real, one hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin'' _ slang for landing airplanes one after another
_ is part quirky comedy, part mature romance and part documentary
of a sort. At its core is a boys-will-be-boys,
mine's-bigger-than-yours rivalry between two different hotshots.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fun unfolds against a sympathetic recreation of the
pressures facing air traffic controllers who deal with as many as
7,000 flights a day in the skies around New York City.
</P>
<P>
   John Cusack is cool Nick Falzone, a liquid-tongued terror of the
tower. He owns the sky as the best controller in the business.
Until Billy Bob Thornton shows up. He is Russell Bell, a stoic
wack-job with a style more Zen-like than zesty. To clear his head,
he once stood on a runway beneath a departing 707. He wanted to
feel the turbulence, and wound up tumbling through the air like a
decompressing balloon. He felt better for it.
</P>
<P>
   Falzone sizes up his rival and doesn't like what he sees.
Feeling increasingly insecure, he enjoys ringing Russell's bell.
One misguided evening, however, the married Falzone rings Bell's
equally bizarro wife (Angelina Jolie). Suddenly, the rivalry turns
subtle and amusing, even if it involves adultery, a faltering
marriage and near-miss, mid-air collisions.
</P>
<P>
   This is funny? You bet. Glen and Les Charles (co-creators of
TV's sitcom ``Cheers'') deliver smart, rapid-fire dialogue. The
jokes often emerge from situations that don't usually end in punch
lines. You pay attention. Tense confrontations produce unexpected
chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Until near the film's end, director Newell (``Four Weddings And
A Funeral'') keeps the weirdness within believable bounds. He's
also good with ensembles, making the most out of the control tower
repartee. The ``locker room'' camaraderie is predictable but
engaging, thanks to an eclectic supporting cast, each one a wit of
sorts. Their jests also speak seriously about the stress they face.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the versatile stars mix well, an attraction of
opposites beyond their physical appearance. There's fun simply in
the way the flip Cusack and the steely Thornton eyeball each other.
(There are a lot of close-ups.) And Cusack is human and humorous
even when his control freak loses control of his life.
</P>
<P>
   As Cusack's wife, Cate Blanchett (``Elizabeth'') is no longer
queenly, but a vulnerable American spouse who can throw a punch
line in the midst of tears.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a bit long. There are plot contrivances. And it
doesn't take radar to see how things will end. But for wit and even
wisdom, ``Pushing Tin'' is a rough diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
