<HEADER>
A9408 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENERAL-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      04-22 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT STORY CAN'T SAVE `THE GENERAL'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Inside every bloated two-hour and eight-minute movie
is a gripping 90-minute story.
</P>
<P>
   And inside the glossy Hollywood film ``The General'' is a
gritty, proletarian British film about class struggle.
</P>
<P>
   It's uncanny how director John Boorman has brought the amazing
and dinosaurian technical savvy of Hollywood to a subject that
would work all the more powerfully in grainy 16mm.
</P>
<P>
   The General is a clever Irish criminal, working in the space
left between the police and the Irish Republican Army. It is based
on a true story: In the 1980s, Martin Cahill and his gang of
thieves pulled off some of the most daring burglaries in history,
culminating with the theft of a rare and expensive Vermeer
painting.
</P>
<P>
   In each robbery, Cahill acted like a field marshal, planning and
executing some of the best-thought-out crimes of the century. Hence
his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   And he is clever. In one case, he even used the police as his
alibi. The cops sit there helplessly, knowing Cahill has just
pulled one over on them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the police don't like being played for suckers, and
the Dublin police eventually had a 90-man task force assigned to
catch the slippery Cahill, played by Brendan Gleeson.
</P>
<P>
   In the end it isn't the police who get him but the IRA. I'm not
giving anything away when I say this: Cahill is shot and killed in
the first scene of the movie. The rest is flashback.
</P>
<P>
   In the hands of a Tony Richardson (``Look Back in Anger'') or,
more recently, a Kenneth Loach (``My Name Is Joe''), this story
would have an almost-documentary sense of the street. There is a
long history of English-language films set in urban slums, with
people on the dole, looking for a way to make their lives
meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   But Boorman has overlaid the basic social realism of ``The
General'' with a Hollywood crime caper movie, like ``Topkapi,''
with a little of the police procedural thrown in. And in the end
the fine acting of everyone in his cast is rendered powerless by
the incessant constant intrusion of its director.
</P>
<P>
   The film is shot in gorgeous black and white, but instead of
giving the movie an edge, it gives it the look of a Calvin Klein TV
ad. It is a beautiful film, but its beauty is grotesquely out of
place. It is sort of like watching Sharon Stone smudge her face to
play a welfare mother, but all the time you can't help notice every
hair is in place and the smudges are oh so aesthetically applied.
</P>
<P>
   It would help if the story had some tension to it, but except
for the two set pieces of Cahill's two major thefts, the movie
wanders aimlessly. It is just one episode after another, rather
than one episode making the next inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's genuine pleasures is watching Jon Voight as a
police inspector out to bring Cahill down. Voight has aged into an
actor of some surprising depth: The lines have grown heavy on his
face in just such a way that, even before he has uttered a word,
you can see the complexity of his character in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some day soon Voight will get a role equal to his
immense screen presence. But it is not ``The General.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The General'' is violent and profane as you might expect from
a gangster film, but there is no sex or nudity. 3 stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Richard Nilsen can be reached at richard.nilsen(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
