<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRANTS-TOMB-ART-NYT &LR;      04-22 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANTS-TOMB-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S BURIED IN GRANT'S TOMB? A GOOD QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JONATHAN ROSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first time somebody asked me the inevitable
question _ who's buried in Grant's Tomb? _ I had no idea what the
answer might be. I must have been about 12 and had eyed the great
granite monument every time my family drove along the West Side
Highway into Manhattan from Westchester, where we lived. I had a
vague sense of Ulysses S. Grant, I certainly knew what a tomb was,
but the thought that he might actually be in there was somehow
shocking.
</P>
<P>
   If you had told me that Calvin Coolidge was lying under the
counter of Zabar's, I couldn't have been more disconcerted. It
wasn't so much that the famous man was buried there as that there
was actually a dead body on Riverside Drive and 122nd Street. I
think it hadn't occurred to me that anyone was buried in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But that is precisely where the power of the monument comes
from. It is in essence a mausoleum, preserving the mortal remains
of the general who, at a terrible cost, led the North to victory in
the Civil War. The capacity to stomach horrendous losses and keep
on going was part of Grant's disturbing greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw an open field,'' he wrote, describing the calamitous
consequences of the battle at Shiloh, ``so covered with dead that
it would have been possible to walk across the clearing, in any
direction, stepping on dead bodies, without a foot touching the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Grant turned out to be a splendid writer (his ``Personal
Memoirs'' recently have been reissued by Penguin), his tomb, unlike
the voluble memorials to Lincoln and Jefferson in Washington, makes
a mute appeal. Despite a couple of brief time lines that sketch his
life from his early years through his post-presidential career, it
is tokens of death and war that dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Two circular antechambers display the flags under which Grant
served, along with maps marking key battles. A single quotation,
``Let us have peace,'' is chiseled into the pediment above the
entranceway. The rest is stony silence. But if there is nothing
Grant said to match the grandeur of Lincoln's Second Inaugural, his
tomb is a stark reminder that there might have been no second
inaugural if Grant had not slogged his way to victory at Vicksburg
and at the battle of the Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln and Jefferson memorials live on the other side of
immortality; there is something enormously comforting about the
luminous marble statues of the men those monuments honor, as if
they were still there, dispensing the wisdom carved so memorably on
the white marble walls. But Grant's Tomb has an undeniable
sepulchral gloom.
</P>
<P>
   There is no statue of Grant, only a hollow at the center of the
main room through which one can gaze down onto his red-brown
granite sarcophagus, and the matching sarcophagus of his wife,
Julia Dent Grant. In the 1930s, a change in the tomb allowed
visitors to descend directly into the crypt where the bronze busts
of Grant's five favorite generals _ McPherson, Ord, Sheridan,
Sherman and Thomas _ ringed the general and his wife, keeping guard
with fierce expressions.
</P>
<P>
   It is the contradictions of Grant and of his tomb that make him
so compelling. When he died in 1885, he was one of the most famous
men in the world. One million people turned out to see his funeral,
60,000 marched in the procession. Though at the time the spot was
miles from the inhabited areas of Manhattan, it was a popular
destination for picnickers and strollers and a place for rallies
and Memorial Day gatherings. Today, though a bustling city exists
around it, with its sweeping view of the Hudson River, the tomb of
her 18th president has got to be one of the least visited places in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   This may be one of the reasons I love going there. Walking
across the vast, empty plaza, I always feel I am approaching an
undiscovered place.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the tomb, inside a little fenced-in area, are a ginkgo
tree and a Chinese cork planted when the monument was completed in
1897 by two Chinese dignitaries, Li Hung Chang, grand secretary of
state, and Yang Yu, envoy extraordinary and minister
plenipotentiary. The quaint effect of these trees, and the
descriptive plaque in English and Chinese, clashes with the garish
mosaic benches that surround Grant's Tomb on three sides. The
result of a misguided attempt in the 1970s to give the site
contemporary appeal, the benches are the most dated thing about the
structure.
</P>
<P>
   I began visiting Grant's Tomb about seven years ago when I moved
to Riverside Drive. I had abandoned a doctorate in English
literature, had just gotten married and within months had taken a
leave from my job to write fiction. My future seemed entirely
insecure and I would often break up a directionless day of writing
with walks through Riverside Park that would end at Grant's Tomb. I
found the idea of Grant comforting.
</P>
<P>
   Grant was always a figure of great tenacity. He spent years
failing at business ventures, working in his father's leather-goods
store in Galena, Ill., until the Civil War found him, at age 39,
and elevated him to greatness. For me, he seemed the patron saint
of late bloomers. That he came into his own just as, and in some
sense because, the country was falling apart, was a perverse but
appealing paradox.
</P>
<P>
   As a general, he was famously patient, biding his time while the
casualties mounted before beginning a counterattack. He waited
until the end of his life to produce a single, and enduring, book,
which he wrote after he had lost his fortune on Wall Street and
been diagnosed with cancer, finishing the work mere days before his
death. He even waited after death, lying in a temporary brick vault
for 12 years while his grand mausoleum was finished. He still
appears to be waiting for historical if not personal resurrection.
He suffers the fate of a man whose greatness in war seems remote to
a society that has been at peace for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his day, it seemed clear he was much better as a general
than as a president. The memoirist Henry Adams refers to him as a
``cave man'' in ``The Education of Henry Adams'' and sees his
presidential campaign slogan, ``Let us have peace,'' as a plea to
be left alone. Even as a general, Grant made stupid mistakes, as
when, in 1862, he attempted to expel Jews from parts of Kentucky,
Tennessee and Mississippi, fearing speculators and war profiteers.
It was an egregious, though momentary, lapse in judgment, and the
order was quickly reversed, though the fact that he must spend
eternity down the block from the Jewish Theological Seminary, where
I went to Hebrew school, seems an appropriate penance.
</P>
<P>
   Far more disturbing was his failure to make the reforms of
Reconstruction stick. His biographer, William S. McFeely, posits
that it was Grant's experience as a man of war that made him
reluctant to send the troops necessary to defeat the Ku Klux Klan
and secure the rights of black Americans, in which he seems
genuinely to have believed.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is a paradox. He was a figure of obscurity who became one
of the most celebrated men in the world. He was central to our
history and yet seems strangely marginal. As a general he was all
action, as president he was a model of passivity. He was a man of
few words who wrote an enormous and lasting book. He was a
Midwesterner who wound up in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Who's buried in Grant's Tomb? It still seems to me a good
question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1812EDT &QL; 
