<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICA-WHITNEY-2TAKE     04-22 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA-WHITNEY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE AMERICAN CENTURY': A NATION'S LEGACY, ICON BY ICON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The American Century: Art and Culture, 1900-1950,''
which opens Friday at the Whitney Museum of American Art, is the
first half of a two-part, marathon, end-of-an-era survey and a show
of substantial if limited pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Its 600 or so works are angled and packed into all four floors
of the museum's exhibition space, with roughly a decade's worth of
art on each floor. Paintings and photographs predominate, along
with a smattering of sculpture. A selection of ceramics, furniture,
books, appliances and architectural drawings makes up the
``culture'' half of the equation. Vintage film clips and music
generate atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The result _ organized by Barbara Haskell, curator of prewar art
at the Whitney, and Susan Cooke, an associate curator _ is not,
despite its somewhat proprietorial title, about American aesthetic
imperialism abroad. Just the opposite, in fact. It is designed as a
long trek through the turbulent history of American art at home.
And by the time you've worked your way from Edith Wharton-era
society portraits at the top of the museum to Jackson Pollock
below, you have had a genuine time-travel experience: exhausting,
sometimes diverting, occasionally moving, even pride inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also an experience dictated by the definition of
20th-century American art that the Whitney, the country's
pre-eminent museum devoted to the subject, has been shaping for
nearly 70 years, and it feels constrictive here.
</P>
<P>
   It's a definition with roots firmly planted in European
Modernism. By its lights, an avant-garde, generically and
monolithically conceived, is the arbiter of value. Provincialism,
whatever that means, is anathema. Art is something produced in a
New York studio, not in an Iowa church hall or a sharecropper's
kitchen in Georgia or a tenement bedroom in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Artists and historians have been chipping away at this blinkered
view for 20 years and more. And its uncritical reiteration here _
laid out chronologically chapter by chapter, illustrated by a
no-surprises string of canonical artists and their iconic works _
gives the show and its catalog a staid, intro-level textbook feel,
a bit like material that turns up on educational Web sites. (An
online extension of ``The American Century'' has, in fact, been
heavily promoted by the museum and was developed in collaboration
with the show's chief sponsor, Intel Corp.)
</P>
<P>
   But American art in the first half of the century was an unruly,
multifaceted, undefinable phenomenon, alternately hyped up and
strung out, streetwise and above it all, emerging from a patchwork
of disparate constituencies for whom no national style, modernist
or otherwise, would ever do. And even when tamed and homogenized,
as it is in this show, the vitality of that phenomenon somehow
shines through.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins at the Whitney in the turn-of-the-century
Gilded Age, when a prosperous nation turned its face toward Europe.
The American domestic interiors and society portraits gathered here
have a Continental polish; Robert Henri's 1916 likeness of Gertrude
Vanderbilt Whitney, the museum's founder, is executed with
cosmopolitan flair.
</P>
<P>
   But within genres that often served as pretexts for luxuriating
in pure style, curious things happen. The subject of Thomas Eakins'
painting ``The Thinker: Portrait of Louis N. Kenton'' (1900), with
his pale, pinched face and creased shoes, is resolutely
unglamourized. And the restless young woman in Thomas Anchutz's
``Rose'' (1907) looks like Calamity Jane dressed for a ball; her
passion-pink frock and the frown of vexation on her face don't
match up.
</P>
<P>
   Filmy Impressionist light fills the paintings of John Twachtman,
one of many American artists who absorbed contemporary styles while
in Europe. But the New York cityscapes of George Bellows are gilded
with a plangent, still-warm 19th-century sunset glow. (The Hudson
River School painter Frederic Edwin Church died only in 1900, and
Winslow Homer and Albert Pinkham Ryder were still active at the
time Bellows was doing some of his best work.)
</P>
<P>
   The modern city determined the direction of much American art in
this century. But early on, metropolitan life was self-consciously
new; small-town communal values were still part of the urban mix,
and artists had only recently begun to take the city as their
primary subject.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's towering architecture turns soft, almost pastoral in
Edward Steichen's early pictures. George Luks painted his Lower
East Side subjects as mugging Frans Hals peasants. And the great
Lewis Hine photographed real peasants arriving _ voyage-stunned,
expectant _ at Ellis Island, as if he understood they were the true
cultural harvest that Europe was sending abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's old rural self-image lingered on in the decorative
arts (Tiffany windows, Rookwood pottery vases), and was distilled
in the early abstract work of artists like Arthur Dove, who worked
independent of European models, and Georgia O'Keeffe, who studied
with the Asian-inspired art educator Arthur Wesley Dow.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Whitney show neglects to pursue the matter,
American vernacular traditions remained vital and found their way,
as they always had, into high art. The sculptor Elie Nadelman was
an early collector of American folk art, and the charming dancing
couple in his ``Tango'' clearly show its influence.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these ingredients come together in certain vital works.
Joseph Stella's ``Brooklyn Bridge: Variation on an Old Theme'' is
one of them. In this painting, by a working-class Roman Catholic
immigrant steeped in European avant-garde styles, a New World
monument to progress is transformed into a folk altarpiece,
floating between sea and sky and illuminated by what look like
vigil lamp headlights.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
