<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICA-WHITNEY-2NDTA     04-22 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA-WHITNEY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: lamp headlights. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stella painted this theme repeatedly; the version at the
Whitney, dated 1939, is a late one and is installed on the museum's
fourth floor, devoted to ``Jazz Age America 1920-1929.'' The
``machine esthetic'' that marked the era, all wheels and
razor-sharp edges, is symbolically ambivalent, as much about lives
ground down as about energy generated. But while many Americans
still looked to Europe for art, Europeans sought a vision of the
future in the mongrelized American city, where amazing things were
happening.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was the Harlem Renaissance, in which black artists
brought a new content to modernism, including traces of vernacular
art, suggested in works as varied as Meta Warrick Fuller's
``Awakening of Ethiopia'' and Archibald Motley's urbane night life
scenes. And jazz, all-American, became a transatlantic force,
pervasive, in the air, as in the sound of Duke Ellington's band,
heard in the Whitney installation.
</P>
<P>
   In the art of the '20s one might trace an American sense of the
visionary. It's there in nature imagery: O'Keeffe's ``Summer
Days,'' with its deer's skull and flowers rising over the desert in
a secular Ascension, could only have come from this country.
</P>
<P>
   But one also finds it in Stuart Davis' ``Lucky Strike,'' an
apotheosis of commodity culture, and Florine Stettheimer's madcap
temple-of-fashion homage ``Spring Sale at Bendel's.'' Finally
Charles Demuth's ``Figure Five in Gold,'' which shuffles commercial
graphics, folk art, Cubism and poetry like a deck of cards, offers
a spiritual emblem for a nation addicted to counting money and
measuring and dividing space.
</P>
<P>
   Money and nature failed in the 1930s when the Great Depression
and droughts set in. The section of the show titled ``America in
Crisis, 1930-1939'' offers no fresh insights into the period, but
the spirit of a time and place still make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   In large part this comes from the exhibition's wealth of
photography, the medium that time and time again manages to bring
``The American Century'' to life. The fact-oriented pictures of
Margaret Bourke-White, Gordon Parks, Eudora Welty, Walker Evans and
Dorothea Lange are in a sense moving exactly because they are so
familiar, unshocking but painful, like a rubbed wound.
</P>
<P>
   But then so much of the work in this section feels extreme.
Figurative art, which is mostly propaganda of one sort or another,
goes right for the gut. Political work is no-holds-barred furious.
Government-sponsored painting is all ``we can if we believe we
can'' uplift. Good-time pictures like Reginald Marsh's ``Twenty
Cent Movie'' feel slightly frantic. And the paintings of Thomas
Hart Benton and Grant Wood in this context make sense; they have
the half-ironic but heart-tugging populist theatricality of films
like ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Against such voices, abstract art, geometric and biomorphic, has
to struggle to make itself heard. And some of its practitioners _
Willem de Kooning, Arshile Gorky and Ad Reinhardt _ who worked on
the Federal Arts Project in the '30s ended up being heard, loud and
clear, in the decade that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that decade, ``War and Its Aftermath: 1940-1949,'' is
strangely reticent, even dull in this telling. Photography, again,
comes on strong, in the combat images of Robert Capa, Walter
Rosenblum and W. Eugene Smith, and in the heat-crazed nocturnal
shots of New York at its downest and dirtiest by the indefatigable
Weegee (Arthur Fellig).
</P>
<P>
   But the big creative bang usually associated with the advent of
Abstract Expressionism is muted. Pollock, de Kooning and Kline,
circa 1950, look innovative, no question. Yet so many dynamic and
contradictory things have happened in American art and culture
before their arrival, including those barely suggested by this
show, that their accomplishments are brought down to size.
</P>
<P>
   One has the impression that at this point the show has simply
run out of steam, but the effect is an interesting one. Suddenly
the conventional picture of American art _ as a string of minor
impulses building toward a single, unifying art that we could
finally, unblushingly, call our own _ is revealed for what it is:
unnatural, unnecessary, defensively conservative and, in a word,
provincial.
</P>
<P>
   That view of American art certainly makes sense at our own
end-of-the-century moment, a time skeptical of received histories,
mistrustful of the politics of the ``important'' and ``great,''
unthreatened by an American art and culture composed of many, many
equal parts. Perhaps such expansive critical thinking will find a
place in ``The America Century: Part II,'' which opens in
September.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN CENTURY: ART &AMP; CULTURE, 1900-1950'
</P>
<P>
   At the Whitney Museum of American Art, 945 Madison Ave. at 75th
Street, New York, through Aug. 22. Part II of the exhibition, ``Art
&AMP; Culture, 1950-2000,'' opens Sept. 26. The exhibition is sponsored
by Intel Corp. An online version of the show can be found at
http://www.whitney.org
</P>
</TEXT>
