<HEADER>
A9417 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND-IFYOUG     04-22 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND-IFYOUGO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheap fares aside, Iceland will snow budget, big time
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland _ The most important item visitors will need
here is money. It doesn't matter whether it's the folding kind or
plastic, but if it's cash, it had better be a lot, and if it's the
latter, it better have a roomy spending limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let the cheap airfare fool you,'' warns Bostonian Joe
Steen, 25, who traveled here in February via Icelandair's ``Spring
Break in Reykjavik'' package. ``Iceland is definitely the most
expensive country in Europe. There isn't anything inexpensive about
visiting Reykjavik.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spring Break package _ which includes airfare, two nights'
hotel stay and airport taxes for about $500 _ seemed surprisingly
cheap. (It's even cheaper if you depart Sunday or Monday, but we
wanted to be there for the weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   The real surprise is how much Iceland costs once you get here. A
Big Mac will set you back about $9. A casual cafe lunch can easily
top $25 per person. And the food (primarily fish) isn't even
memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go back during the summertime someday, but it's so
expensive,'' says 34-year-old Paul Stokely of Emmitsburg, Md., here
for a week with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Icelandair's best deals run from November to May, the
off-season. Sure, it's cold, but if money is a consideration and
you don't mind putting on a couple (or three or four) extra layers,
take advantage of these deals.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapest packages are billed as four-day trips, but you only
spend three days in Iceland because of flight time. I would have
enjoyed at least a couple of extra days, but that would have
demolished the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Atlanta isn't among Icelandair's gateway cities, which
include New York, Boston, Washington, Minneapolis-St. Paul, Orlando
and Halifax, Nova Scotia. So you have to fly first to one of these
cities and change planes.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you spring for a hotel upgrade (an extra $25-$40 per
night), Icelandair books you into one of its two standard-grade
Reykjavik hotels. These are similar in quality and comfort to
hotels in other European cities, which is to say that the rooms are
tiny by American standards.
</P>
<P>
   My room at the Hotel Esja, a five-minute cab ride ($11) from
downtown Reykjavik, had two twin beds and a shower stall instead of
a bathtub. The beds looked uninvitingly lumpy until I drew back the
covers and realized the lumpiness was a down-filled duvet.
</P>
<P>
   For an extra $21 per day, you have unlimited access to the
hotel's well-outfitted health club and spa, including the services
of a personal trainer and a masseuse. Of course, if you're in
Iceland for only 60 hours, you should be spending much more time
outside the hotel than in it.
</P>
<P>
   There are essentially two ways to see the countryside: take an
organized bus tour or rent a car and strike out on your own. We
tried both, and preferred the latter.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say that the tours, offered by various local
companies, are no good. On the contrary, they're perfect for those
uncomfortable with the idea of driving in an unfamiliar country,
navigating by a sketchy map in a foreign language. Driving in
Iceland in the winter, especially, isn't for the faint of heart or
the ignorant of stick shift.
</P>
<P>
   The farther you get from Reykjavik, the worse the roads become
(the major highway is a two-lane road lacking a median or guard
rails). In addition to being narrow, winter's snow-covered roads
occasionally become indistinguishable from the snow-covered
roadsides.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when I go back, I'll rent a car for the whole trip.
Renting wheels is pricey, to be sure: Our Daihatsu mini-SUV with
four-wheel drive and nail-studded snow tires (a must) ended up
costing a little more than $200 for 24 hours. That included mileage
but not gasoline (another $42). Still, it was worth it for the
pleasure of tooling around unfettered by tour schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Icelandair features several tours and rental car options in its
brochure. But it's best to wait until you arrive, since more
choices _ and possibly better deals _ are available through the
hotels and the tourist information center in downtown Reykjavik.
</P>
<P>
   We signed up for Reykjavik Excursions' popular Blue Lagoon tour
(about $54 per person), which was fine, despite our stuffy guide.
Our biggest complaint was the odd timetable. We felt rushed at the
lagoon, the pinnacle of the six-hour tour, yet we dawdled at a
miserable little aquarium where the fish looked as haggard as we
did after three nights of little sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently, though, the tour dropped us off at Keflavik
Airport in plenty of time for last-minute duty-free shopping before
our flight back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   You might have more fun and flexibility if you hire a private
tour guide for a custom-tailored tour in a SuperJeep (a monster
all-terrain vehicle), as did Steen and his pals.
</P>
<P>
   Travel brochures will try to convince you that Iceland winters
are mild. In truth, the temperature hovers around freezing, but
wind chill makes it seem much colder. If you go in wintertime,
bring long underwear, woolen socks, hiking boots, thick gloves and
a hat that covers your ears.
</P>
<P>
   Pack dressy clothes if you plan to splurge on dinner at a nice
restaurant. Women also should bring something black and skimpy for
the nightclubs. And don't forget a swimsuit for the hot springs and
heated pools, open year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Summer temps are more comfortable, but even in June and July,
the warmest months, the mercury doesn't rise much above 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Icelandair offers a few spring specials, but you'll have to move
fast:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prices for the ``Midweek Spring Fling,'' a four-day trip
offered a few times in May, start at $399 per person, double
occupancy, including two nights' hotel stay and round-trip airfare.
Airport taxes are an additional $64 per person.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Icelandair's four-day Reykjavik Adventure Package, available
though mid-May, is less restrictive in terms of when you travel but
costs from $499 per person, plus applicable taxes. That's still a
great deal; from June through August the price for the same package
soars to $1,061 per person.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Another Icelandair option is to stop in Iceland on your way to
or from Europe, without additional airfare. For instance, through
April, Icelandair offers a New York-Paris round-trip fare of $282
that permits a stay of up to three days in Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   As mentioned, plastic is a great way to handle your Icelandic
spending, especially as you'll avoid the poor exchange rates and
high commissions charged at hotels. But note that while Visa and
MasterCard are almost universally accepted throughout Iceland,
American Express isn't.
</P>
<P>
   For an Icelandair brochure, call 1-800-223-5500 or view the
company's Web page at www.icelandair.com. You can sign up for
regular e-mailings of special fares through the site's ``Lucky
Fares'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
