<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, April 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A front separating record warmth over the South from a very
chilly air mass over southern Canada will be active with showers
and thunderstorms. Several weak disturbances will race eastward
along the boundary from southern New England to the Ohio Valley,
with the passage of each low forcing the chilly air farther south.
</P>
<P>
   It will be dull and damp from Connecticut to Illinois. Behind
the front, temperatures will drop as much as fifteen degrees in a
few hours. Very warm air preceding the front in the Middle Atlantic
region and Ohio Valley will give rise to thundershowers. A few
strong storms are possible with hail and damaging winds.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over the southwest Atlantic will produce bright
and hot weather in the Southeast. The fire danger will remain high
in Florida. A flow of humid air from the western Gulf of Mexico
will sponsor clouds and a few thundershowers in Louisiana and
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Colder air will surge southward into the Texas and Oklahoma
panhandles with drizzle and brisk winds. The snowstorm along the
Front Range will diminish, but heavy snow will persist over the
higher elevations of the central Rockies. A complex storm in
northern Arizona will circulate clouds and mixed showers across
Utah and Nevada. Gusty showers are likely in eastern Arizona and
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Offshore winds will promote sunny and milder weather in the
Northwest and Northern California. High pressure building southward
from Canada will bring bright but cool conditions to sections of
the border states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snow Season
</P>
<P>
   Though it is spring, winter is not over near the Front Range of
the Rockies. Indeed, the two snowiest months at Denver, Colo., for
example, are March and April, with average snowfalls of 12.8 and
9.0 inches. Most of the spring snow falls in a few, big spurts.
With the northward retreat of the jet stream in spring, the
availability of moisture from the Gulf of Mexico increases. When
passing disturbances draw cold air from Canada southward and moist
air from the Gulf of Mexico northward, big snows can result. Over a
foot of wet snow fell Thursday at several locations south and west
of Denver.
</P>
</TEXT>
