<HEADER>
A9421 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND-NIGHTC     04-22 1503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND-NIGHTCLUBS22-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deep into the night, it's a party out of bounds
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland _ I hate to interrupt couples while they're
engaged in mouth-to-mouth saliva exchange, because that's a
delicate moment of intimacy and all.
</P>
<P>
   But these two hadn't come up for air in about five minutes, so I
figured they could use an oxygen break. Intrusive, yes, but I was
performing a public service.
</P>
<P>
   I introduced myself. The girl did likewise. Then she eyed her
apparently very new boyfriend, shrugged and asked him, ``What's
your name?''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much the way it goes at a quarter to three on
Saturday night _ Sunday morning, whatever _ in Reykjavik's
nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department provides a helpful bulletin of travel
warnings, alerting Americans to dangers such as outbreaks of dengue
fever or civil unrest in foreign countries. All it says about
Iceland is that Reykjavik can become ``disorderly'' on weekend
nights.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department is being diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Always quick to ferret out the latest hot spot, the media lately
has developed a tic for painting Reykjavik as an Arctic Bangkok,
seething with the exotic and the erotic. In truth, it's basically a
small town that marries Euro ultra mod and Old World quaintness,
with residents who display both Continental savoir-faire and
British civility.
</P>
<P>
   Reykjavik's nightlife varies little from that of Miami or New
York _ or Atlanta, for that matter. The clubs are all exploding
with people, mostly twentysomethings and those who wish they were
still twentysomething, lavishly drunk and drunkenly lascivious,
partying like it's 1999. (You knew that was coming.)
</P>
<P>
   That said, clubbing in Reykjavik does possess a certain
piquancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found the female Icelander to be tall, blond, blue-eyed and
very beautiful,'' says Joe Steen, 25, a Boston native who spent a
long weekend in Reykjavik with a few friends. ``We did find the
male Icelander to be a little rude. Why? We don't know, but we came
across a few situations that could've gotten ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Um, take a guess, pal.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, maybe it's the sharply honed Icelandic sense of style
that makes the Reykjavik party scene. Icelanders dress up no matter
what the mercury reads. These are not your
schlepping-around-in-jeans kind of people.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's just that these people are descended from Vikings,
not Puritans. They do not lack self-confidence, as I learned from a
20-year-old Adonis I met at the coat check counter at Nelly's Cafe,
a nightclub in the heart of Reykjavik.
</P>
<P>
   Bjarnie Pordarson was wearing a black T-shirt with short, tight
sleeves designed to accentuate his deltoids. The deltoids were from
his day job, which involves lifting large tubs of fish, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing, Iceland's primary industry, must pay decently, because
going out in Reykjavik is very expensive _ a beer costs about $7,
and no one has just one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your favorite thing to do on weekends?'' I inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual activities,'' Bjarnie replied, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   Taken aback, I came back with, ``So you pick up girls?''
</P>
<P>
   The two coat check girls giggled and ogled him. He was
ogle-worthy, if totally full of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they usually pick me up,'' he said in dead earnest before
sliding off into the crowd, presumably to be picked up by some
luscious babe.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Cergol, a 35-year-old filmmaker from New York, found the
Icelandic brand of candor refreshing, if a little disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Icelandic woman was saying how they're very open
sexually,'' Cergol said. ``It's just a matter of going right up to
someone and talking to them and being open and honest. There
doesn't seem to be the layers of games that I think we're used to
in the States.''
</P>
<P>
   His theory proved itself as the dance floor at Nelly's started
to fill, around midnight, the Reykjavikian witching hour. The room,
roughly the size of a healthy kitchen (as they always seem to be in
A-list nightclubs), was packed with an astonishing number of people
doing that bouncy club dance you do when there's no space to move
horizontally. Three disco balls whirled overhead, reflecting
colored lights onto the matte-black walls and everyone's black
clothes. It was like fireworks going off in a cave.
</P>
<P>
   Only the occasional tune by Icelandic singer Bjork interrupted
the steady diet of American and British pop. Everyone knew all the
words. I would have thought I was in an American nightclub, except
that these white kids were dancing way too well.
</P>
<P>
   Apropos, the DJ kept spinning the aggressively annoying
Offspring song ``Pretty Fly for a White Guy'' every 20 minutes.
Each time, he cut the sound for a few seconds and let the frenzied
crowd fill in. ``Give it to me baby! UH-HUH! UH-HUH!'' everyone
screamed on cue. Clearly, the Offspring needs to play Reykjavik on
its next tour.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 a.m. the music was so loud it made my solar plexus ache,
so we decided to roll.
</P>
<P>
   As in Atlanta, the major bars and dance clubs mostly line the
town's main drag, which has three names within eight blocks. Most
of the trendy shops, eateries and bars are on this street, making
it convenient to stagger from one to another.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted to check out Astro, a flavor-of-the-month club, where
clusters of snappily dressed hipsters, too cool to look cold,
waited behind the velvet rope in the 25-degree night air. The men
wore enough hair gel to lubricate the space shuttle; the girls wore
itty-bitty excuses for skirts that left the imagination out of a
job. Their only concession to the climate was thick, flesh-colored
hose, like ice skaters wear.
</P>
<P>
   A bouncer gave us the once-over and decided we weren't fly
enough to make the cut. He didn't trouble to tell us so; he just
looked at us ... then looked away.
</P>
<P>
   Note to self: Next time in Reykjavik, don't wear big green,
down-filled Eddie Bauer parka while clubbing.
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from rejection, we wound up in the classier and calmer
Rex, where we met Margret Baldursdottir, a 25-year-old strawberry
blond femme formidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Iceland! I hope you have a wonderful time,'' said
Margret, and all around us I could see men who were imagining just
how she could help them have a wonderful time.
</P>
<P>
   Rex is the sort of place where the bartenders are as beautiful
and almost as expensively dressed as the clientele, who all look
like the models in the French edition of Vogue, except less surly.
</P>
<P>
   We introduced ourselves to a girl at the next table in
spectacles and a floor-length ballgown.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I have to tell you that I am very tipsy,''
27-year-old Asta Gardarsdottir started, very tipsily.
</P>
<P>
   We learned that she writes and hosts an Icelandic children's TV
show based on ``Sesame Street.'' Earlier in the evening, she had
been at the station's annual party, which explained her condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I'm playing adult, I'm not playing with puppets,'' she
said, punctuating every word with an intoxicated nod. ``I'm getting
drunk with my friends. And it's a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, her friend wasn't getting drunk with her. She
was sipping a Diet Coke. Iceland has stringent drunken driving laws
that locals appear to take seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always try to have somebody sober in the car. There
might be six people in the car: five dead drunk, one sober,'' says
Thorstein Henn, 29, a German-born free-lance photographer who now
lives here.
</P>
<P>
   Rex was nice, but it wasn't suited for easy mingling, since
people mostly sit at tables. At 2:30 a.m. we went back to Nelly's
to resume the process of losing our hearing and witnessed what an
hour of drinking and dancing had wrought upon the madding crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A totally wasted blonde who looked young enough to be a
``Dawson's Creek'' extra fell down the stairs. Two boys hauled her
off. A moment later I heard retching noises.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell it's 3 in the morning in Reykjavik by the sound of
beer bottles smashing on the sidewalks. That's when the bars and
nightclubs close, leaving clubhoppers with the choice of going
home, moving on to a private party or simply taking the party into
the frozen streets.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latter, we met a couple of teen girls who had been at
an '80s party at a club and were dressed like Duran Duran groupies.
Acting like them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing we were Americans visiting Reykjavik for the first
time, Unnur Einarsdottir tugged on my sleeve and implored me to
tell others back home that Reykjavik was a special place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them the nightlife in Reykjavik is really great,'' she
slurred. ``It's really different.''
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to ask this 17-year-old wild child, ``How is it
different? And how would you know?''
</P>
<P>
   But she was already lolloping down the street, shrieking like a
banshee under the Arctic full moon.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
