<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9422 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND-TOPOGR     04-22 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND-TOPOGRAPHY22-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The island's rugged beauty is way beyond the ordinary
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland _ Gazing at this desolate, inhospitable land,
I developed a profound respect for the Vikings who beached their
boats and decided to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they settled here,'' says New Yorker Bryan
Flynn, who arrived in February. ``What were they thinking? That
they could plant something?''
</P>
<P>
   If they were, they were fooling themselves. There are no trees.
Not a one. Not a surprise, since much of Iceland's surface looks
like a gigantic charcoal briquette, thanks to the plentiful
reddish-black volcanic rock. Small wonder Icelanders call their
country ``the Rock.'' The rest of the island features vast plains,
mountains and glaciers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you're on the moon,'' Flynn adds. ``It's really
like being on another planet. All you see are rocks. But cool
rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   In summer, the plains turn verdant, and the midnight sun lights
the sky well after bedtime. In winter, though, the snow-dusted land
is barren and the sun travels a shallow arc, setting by 6 and
staying down until after 10 a.m. That's a lot of dark.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of the dark? I got to see the aurora borealis. Yeah,
you've seen pictures. The pictures are great.
</P>
<P>
   But actually seeing it for real, watching those wisps of green
luminescence undulating across the heavens like colossal cosmic
skywriting _ that's some kind of wonderful we don't have in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   The aurora borealis is but one of Iceland's one-of-a-kind
natural attractions that we experienced during our three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   We soon realized that Icelanders apparently do not feel the
urge, as Americans do, to put up mondo billboards telling tourists
where all the cool stuff is. It's not hidden or anything, but you
have to know where to look. And here are a few things you should
look for:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gullfoss: Only a road sign assures you that you have indeed
arrived at the renowned waterfalls a few hours' drive from
Reykjavik. Simple wooden steps lead down to a natural ledge from
which you can view the two-tiered falls, each hundreds of feet wide
and together more than 100 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   The lower waterfall plunges into a gorge at right angles to the
higher falls. So much spray fills the air, a rainbow has taken up
almost permanent residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have stared at it for hours,'' says Paul Stokely, 34,
of Emmitsburg, Md., visiting with his wife, Sarah. ``It's
incredible, like the Grand Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Geysir: A cluster of hot springs and geysers in a lava field,
Geysir took my breath away _ literally. When the geyser Strokkur
(Icelandic for ``butter churn'') erupted from a gently gurgling
pool into a frothy 60-foot plume of boiling water, I gasped
involuntarily. Strokkur repeats the performance every three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   All around, threads of steam waft from hot pools in the
crumbling volcanic rock, creating a generally postapocalyptic
effect. The pools, some no larger than a manhole, simmer at more
than 250 degrees, as a small sign politely alerts visitors. There
are no fences, just a few cautionary ropes. You fall in and cook
yourself, that's your problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Icelandic ponies: To maintain the purity of the breed, Iceland
hasn't allowed importation of horses in 800 years. Barely as tall
as an average person, these ponies are prized for their size and
unique running gait. The ones I encountered on a horse farm a few
minutes outside Reykjavik were endearingly friendly _ although I
suspect they were angling for some sugar cubes or carrots. Several
farms offer guided pony rides.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blue Lagoon: Fortunately, it has nothing to do with that
Brooke Shields movie. It's not even a true lagoon, but a man-made
pool filled with hot effluent from the adjoining Svartsengi power
plant, less than an hour from Reykjavik.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not radioactive; the plant runs on geothermal heat,
like just about everything else in Iceland. So the water's not only
clean and safe, but said to have therapeutic properties due to its
high mineral content.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds icky, but it's really divine. Think of the best, most
relaxing bath you've ever taken. This is way better. You can swim
(there's a shallow section for people who don't), your skin feels
silky-smooth from the minerals and the water never gets cold.
</P>
<P>
   After paddling around the lagoon for a half-hour, I couldn't say
I felt dramatically healthier, but I didn't want to get out,
despite my tour guide's gesticulations for us to leave. I wanted to
luxuriate in the pale blue, nearly opaque water until I turned into
a giant prune _ or an Icelandic mermaid.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
