A9424 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND22-COX     04-22 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ICELAND22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Obscurely hip Iceland: Land of Fire and Ice
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland _ ``Why Iceland?'' everyone asked when they
heard I was headed to this icy chunk of volcanic rock at the edge
of the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   The best answer came to me at 2 o'clock one morning during my
three-day visit, as I stood, mesmerized and frozen, watching the
aurora borealis perform the world's most fantastic light show.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, I had sacrificed yet more sleep, riveted until
almost 4 a.m. by a very different but equally memorable nocturnal
phenomenon. Reykjavik's nightclubs were swarming with the world's
most gorgeous people, drinking and dancing _ and doing stuff that
goes with that _ in a frenzied revel that would have made Bacchus
blush.
</P>
<P>
   In three nights I managed a total of 11 hours of sleep. And I
didn't care, because it was wonderful, glorious, entrancing, and
I'd go back _ I will go back _ to this remote island of savage,
unearthly beauty populated by savagely beautiful inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Land of Fire and Ice, as it's called, never crossed
your travel radar. It is, after all, way up on top of the globe,
and it doesn't have anything Disney or any towers of Eiffel or any
Roman nude statuary.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's become a hot spot for young Americans, especially
college spring breakers trolling for an experience beyond the
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like an awfully long way to go to party. After all,
you can get drunk anywhere, and beaches come cheap in the States.
</P>
<P>
   But in Iceland the beaches are made of volcanic lava, and they
fringe steamy azure pools of geothermally heated water bubbling
over with swimsuited blondes year-round. At night the same blondes
put on slightly more clothing _ never mind the climate; layers
aren't sexy _ and get jiggy wit' it until breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Never has a place so cold been so heitt (hot).
</P>
<P>
   Icelandair, the country's airline, is doing its part to foster
the travel boomlet by offering discounted airfare-hotel packages to
this costly country. OK, it's still not as cheap as Cancun, but
Cancun is so MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Reykjavik, Iceland's capital and largest city (population:
110,000), is as yet untainted by the likes of Carmen Electra
hosting wet T-shirt karaoke contests _ although American pop music
does rule the Icelandic airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you can drink the water _ and, even better, most
Icelanders speak at least passable English.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt part of the cachet of visiting here is the uniqueness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the whole thought of going to Iceland, this place
you never thought of going,'' says Bryan Flynn, a 35-year-old
advertising director and stand-up comedian from New York. ``The
funny thing is, I'd been in Amsterdam maybe two weeks before, and
no one cared,'' adds Flynn, who visited here in February with two
college friends. ``But as soon as you say Iceland, they say wow. It
has such a mysterious connotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's plenty more to Iceland than its blondes, bars and
beer, enough to tempt those who want more out of a vacation than a
thundering hangover and a heinous Visa bill. The breathtaking
landscapes alone will linger in your dreams long after you leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a wild place,'' Flynn says. ``As soon as I got back
I was looking at prices for flights to go back again.''
</P>
<P>
   So was I.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
