A9425 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKSHOP-DECKS22-COX     04-22 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKSHOP-DECKS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hit the decks _ to waterproof them seal 'em for summer
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Waterproofing your deck should become an annual rite
of spring to protect against wood rot, splintering and warping.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it was waterproofed last year and there aren't any
visible signs of damage, this is a maintenance project you don't
want to put off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waterproofing is a yearly event because all waterproof sealers
eventually wear off. You want to stop moisture from getting into it
and replace the wood's natural oils,'' said Mark Wetzel, vice
president of sales for Behr Process Corp., a Santa Ana, Calif.,
company that does business in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The project takes about a day and a half, largely because of
drying time. The temperature outside should be at least 50 degrees,
which isn't a problem this time of year in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's too cold outside, it takes too long to dry,'' Wetzel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies needed:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bleach or a mildew stain remover
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pump sprayer
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oxalic acid
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stiff push broom or brush
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Linseed oil-based waterproofer
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Natural-bristle paintbrush
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plastic
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garden hose
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Face mask
</P>
<P>
   B E F O R E Y O U B E G I N
</P>
<P>
   Cover surrounding masonry, metal, painted surfaces, grass and
plant life with plastic to prevent staining.
</P>
<P>
   What to do:
</P>
<P>
   1 Kill mold and mildew by pouring bleach or a mildew stain
remover into a pump sprayer. Saturate deck with the chemical and
allow to work for 10-15 minutes. Then rinse deck with fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   2 Using a stiff push broom or brush, clean deck with oxalic acid
to remove dead wood cells and tree and leaf stains. Deck should be
saturated and scrubbed hard to activate the chemical. Allow to sit
for 15-20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3 Rinse deck again with water and allow to dry for at least 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   4 When deck is completely dry, pour waterproofer/sealant into
pump sprayer.
</P>
<P>
   5 Apply sealant until wood is completely saturated, leaving a
wet sheen. The number of passes you make with sealant depends on
the porosity of the wood. Do not allow sealant to dry between
coats.
</P>
<P>
   6 After sealer is applied, back-brush deck to ensure proper
penetration. Allow to penetrate for up to 30 minutes, then remove
excess with clean cloth. Allow deck to dry completely before
walking on it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second installment in our Spring Workshop series, a
step-by-step guide to doing inexpensive weekend projects for the
home or garden. If there's a project you'd like to suggest or you
want more information about this series, call 404-222-8689 or send
an e-mail to dflanders(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
