<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9427 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-ART22-COX     04-22 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-ART22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riveting sculptures a family affair
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Visitors strolling through the Atlanta Botanical
Garden might be ``ribbeted'' by the sight of copper amphibians.
</P>
<P>
   Frogs will do that to you. Especially the life-size sculptured
ones. These fanciful creatures are the creation of the Smiths,
namely father Charles and his two sons, Beau and Alexander. Each
sculpted four that will be on display until May 30. This is the
third year the botanical garden has exhibited them.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Smith of St. John's Island, S.C., has been sculpting
full time since 1980, but he didn't do his first frog until years
later. He and his sons have made frogs their trademark, sculpting
about 300.
</P>
<P>
   But they aren't into frogs, per se. They don't collect them, and
Charles Smith only has two life-size one of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them, but I'm not one of these people who are goofy
about frogs,'' said the senior Smith. ``In the early '80s, one of
my clients kept asking me to make frogs. I just kept putting it off
because I didn't see the relevance of doing frogs.''
</P>
<P>
   His first one was, dare we say, weird looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like something from outer space,'' Charles Smith
recalled. ``It was bigger than the ones nowadays. I consider it the
most valuable one of all.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees frog sculptures as an art medium, sort of like oil
paintings. The amphibians have their own personalities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Beau Smith, 37, likes to write songs. So the Smyrna
sculptor made his frogs musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a natural theme. It's kind of like a muse playing
music, an inspiration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Smith, 33, did one of a parent frog reading to a
child. The botanical garden will place that one in the upcoming
children's garden, scheduled to open in September.
</P>
<P>
   Although sculpting has become a family business for the Smiths,
it wasn't the elder Smith's first profession.
</P>
<P>
   His background is in science and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was an artist. I was always into making things. My
father was an engineer. It's sort of a combination of those
things,'' Charles Smith explained.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of his work _ he also does deer, birds and raccoons _
are for the private gardens of his clients. He also does abstract
sculptures and human forms.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Bellagio, a garden art store on Miami Circle in
Atlanta, were familiar with his work and put Smith in touch with
management at the botanical garden. The first show was held there
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Beau and Alexander Smith started sculpting frogs through
osmosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something my father did, and it really caught on,''
Beau Smith said. ``It's a neat way to build something that is like
a human being, but you're not locked into representing a human
being. It's easier to build a frog and have the personality come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
