<HEADER>
A9428 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-GUTTERS22-CO     04-22 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-GUTTERS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grungy gutters call for clever stopgap ploys
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I try to stay out of gutters whenever I can.
</P>
<P>
   There comes a time, however, when gutters cannot be ignored.
Those without leaf guards need to be cleaned frequently, and even
those with leaf guards eventually will deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Corrosion in gutters occurs from the inside out, so what looks
like a perfectly good gutter from the ground is a horrifying sight
when you climb onto a ladder and see the damage close up. Usually a
rusted gutter calls for replacement of the entire system _ and
several hundred dollars. But there are temporary solutions that
will take care of the problem until you win the lottery or your
rich aunt dies.
</P>
<P>
   Patching leaks
</P>
<P>
   To repair a leaky section of gutter, you'll need a wire brush,
steel wool or an abrasive scouring pad, a bucket of plastic roofing
cement and a putty knife.
</P>
<P>
   Wash away any accumulated silt or leaves with a hose. Then use a
wire brush to scrub the rusty area, let dry and scrub with steel
wool or an abrasive pad. Spread roofing cement over the leak with a
putty knife and smooth out so the patched section is as level as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   For larger leaks, you may have to get some tin snips and cut a
strip of metal flashing to fit over the damaged area. Bend the
flashing to fit inside the gutter and spread enough roofing cement
around the edges to hold it in place. This won't last forever, but
it will stop the annoying drips until you replace the system.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the problem
</P>
<P>
   Another solution is to replace an entire section of gutter.
</P>
<P>
   The experts at Home Depot recommend these steps:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remove the screws and connectors from the damaged area. If you
are removing the spikes, slip a 2-by-4-inch block of wood in the
gutter to protect it while you pull out the spike.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cut a replacement section that is 2 inches longer than the
section you remove. Use a spacer block to keep the gutter from
bending while you cut it with a hacksaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spread roof cement or gutter repair compound on the old
section of gutter and to the edges of the new section and set in
place with the up-slope section on top of the down-slope section.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Drill pilot holes and fasten the two sections with rivets. Now
drill pilot holes for the spike and ferrule fasteners, keeping
spacer blocks in place.
</P>
<P>
   This should take care of the problem until the next monsoon.
Meanwhile, I suggest you set up a fund for new gutters or eliminate
gutters altogether. Yes, it's annoying to get rained on when you
walk up the steps to the front door, but think of how many
door-to-door salesmen will get drenched.
</P>
<P>
   Question of the month
</P>
<P>
   Paul Stokes of Atlanta called to inquire about a footing for a
stone retaining wall he is building. Stokes wanted to know how wide
and how thick the footing should be for a 2 1/2-foot wall about 60
feet long.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, let me say that I admire Stokes' ambition.
Building a stone wall is not a simple task, but it can be done well
with planning and patience.
</P>
<P>
   For the footing, most experts recommend poured concrete as thick
as the width of the wall and twice as wide. Your local building
codes may have other requirements, such as starting the footing
below the frost line (6 inches in Georgia). But for a low wall, the
specifications recommended by most experts should be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   One tip from stonemasons: Begin the wall by building short
sections at each end of the wall. You also should try a dry run
before adding mortar to make sure the stones fit together right.
Or, better yet, just build a dry stone wall. You won't need a
poured concrete footing, and it's a lot easier to correct your
mistakes.Write to us
</P>
<P>
   Send questions or suggestions to Weekend Handyman, in care of
Don O'Briant, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689,
Atlanta, GA, or call 404-526-5465.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes a monthly column on home improvement tips.
E-mail him at dobriant(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
