<HEADER>
A9429 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN22-COX     04-22 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bushy-tailed marauders more brazen than usual
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those of us who have seen more than a few Atlanta springs agree
that this year's is as great as they get. No matter what comes
next, we have seen paradise, gained inspiration from its
loveliness. But like any paradise, this one attracts a devilish
intruder from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   In my garden, the squirrel's the one.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the mild winter that ensured that the banana
shrub wouldn't get zapped but would instead produce a big bunch of
little yellow blooms with fragrance mimicking the yellow fruit was
the same winter that allowed the bushy-tailed rats to frolic all
through December and January, getting a head start in February and
roaring into spring with tails flying. They've not rested for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the middle of January, in fact, that I saw the rodents
move their insults to the highest level ever.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hunkering down in nests at the top of the neighboring
oaks and pecan trees as they usually do in ``normal'' winter
temperatures, the varmints were taking advantage of the balmy times
to play and plague.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I like to see a squirrel or a group of them spiral at high
speed up and down the trunk of a tree as much as anyone. If they'd
stop there, I could begin to tolerate them. But once they hit the
ground, they stop playing and go to destroying; I've had to put
rocks on top of my bonsai soil to prevent squirrels from rooting
the little trees and shrubs out of their trays. Mere okra-seed-size
rocks no longer deter. Still, I've seen a rock about the size of my
fist tossed off the white pine bonsai, indicating the presence of
an exceptionally strong squirrel or a frightening example of rodent
teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   The list of squirrel victims around the garden always is long,
but it grew longer as the weather warmed. In addition to the usual
upheaval of newly planted perennials and shrubs, several rose
cuttings I stuck in a pot of dirt in December got squirrel-trashed,
as did unfurling ferns, tender and apparently tasty.
</P>
<P>
   One happy discovery in the perennial war on squirrels: My
pansies always get decapitated sooner or later, but this year a
half-barrel of them has remained headed. The container sits under a
metal wind chime. Squirrels likely don't like music. It figures.
</P>
<P>
   Wisteria fared not as well. Usually, it twirls along the railing
on the back porch, blooming as it wishes, going from groups of
tight little burgundy buds to large purple droplets. Well, this
year, some of the blossoms got nipped in the bud stage, as the
railing happens to be a squirrel run. The rodents dashed along,
grabbing buds as they went, recalling their stripping of a
beautifully pregnant tomato bush last summer. (One friend, Woody
Oliver, was so undone by a similar tomato-stripping experience last
summer, he says he's taking some time off from growing food, a
great loss to beggars like me.)
</P>
<P>
   After losing my wisteria buds, I decided to press Buuud into
service as a garden cat. I was hoping he might redeem himself after
failing so miserably to adapt to the woods of McCaysville. (He and
Vincent, after demanding to be outdoor cats, cowered in corners and
closets during their only trip to the North Georgia mountains.)
</P>
<P>
   Out into the garden bounded Buuud. Onto the brick wall he
leaped. Alas, as hard as he tried to be fierce and stealthy, as
resolutely as he wore his game face, he still looked like just
another clean, wary house cat out for an uncertain stroll.
</P>
<P>
   And like any creature whose body language signals vulnerability,
Buuud seemed to invite disrespect. He got it from one squirrel
running atop the wall. The little thug stopped and took a bite out
of the piece of French bread clamped between its teeth. After
chewing furiously, it flicked its tail obscenely, then jumped onto
my balcony, heading for the roof, then into the big oak, leaving
the rest of the bread sitting precariously on the wall. Unwilling
to subject Buuud to more indignity, I brought him in and advised
him that his garden-cat duties were over.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a spring plagued by rampaging rodents, there are
gardeners who think squirrels are cute.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Norris is one of them. In her Acworth garden she has
what she calls bird/squirrel feeders, inviting the rodents to eat
as much as they like: ``I enjoy watching them climb in and out of
my feeders,'' she says, acknowledging that she suffers from a
``squirrel fetish.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris, who got acquainted with some of my family through
reading one of my books, has named one of her squirrels ``Uncle
Buddy.'' She speculates that Buddy is ``up there smiling down at
me'' as she gently tells the squirrels to ``save some seeds for the
birds.''
</P>
<P>
   She may be right, but I'd hope my rural Alabama, food-loving
uncle would think, instead, about a nice Brunswick stew recipe that
calls for a ``fine gray squirrel.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay(at)bellsouth
</P>
<P>
   .net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
