<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-DESIGNDUO22-COX     04-22 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-DESIGNDUO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dynamic design duo giving women what they want: Color, ease
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meet Dana Buchman and Karen Harman. After a decade spent
designing the Dana Buchman label together, this duo lends credence
to the notion that two heads sometimes are better than one.
</P>
<P>
   And two creative minds are necessary, once it's considered how
large is the workload Buchman and Harman share. Besides the
signature collection of $350 jackets and $130 pants, they also
co-design Dana Buchman Luxe ($450 jackets, $250 pants), large and
petite collections, sunglasses and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent appearance at Neiman Marcus in Lenox Square, the
pair pointed out that their partnership is not without the
proverbial butting of heads, but the creative tension works to the
benefit of their collections and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Do the two ever disagree?
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out it's OK to disagree,'' says Buchman. ``It's part
of the learning process. And, each of us is allowed to change her
mind!''
</P>
<P>
   After a show for 250 customers, Buchman and Harman _ both in
their 40s, both comfort- and cost-conscious _ chatted about their
design approach.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What are American women looking for when it comes to clothes?
</P>
<P>
   Harman:A: ``Items and outfits that make them look and feel
beautiful, modern and feminine. And they want color. This is
especially true of Atlanta women. The sunlight here is radiant.
Women want to dress themselves in these colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:How has fashion changed in the past five years?
</P>
<P>
   Buchman:A: ``There's a major shift from tailored suitings to
relaxed pieces. At some offices, a rayon shirt and soft
drawstring-waisted trousers make a great outfit. Jackets are more
sweaterlike. We've even taken the interlinings out of jackets to
make them less constructed. Still, the look has to be polished and
not thrown together. However, jackets are still around, just
softer-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are five classic pieces that a woman should have in her
closet?
</P>
<P>
   Buchman and Harman: A: ``A black pantsuit; a twin set in white
or metallic gray; a white Lycra T-shirt; a long, easy-fitting black
skirt; a pop of color, such as a soft jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Anything special you two are designing for the year 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Harman:A: ``Toward the end of '99, we are coming out with
drop-dead, black-tie party clothes in a package. We call it
Packable Glamour. These will consist of black or white ball gown
skirts with matching camisoles or sweaters in rich metallics that
you fold into a bag and be on your way to a party.''
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
