<HEADER>
A9431 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXISTENZ-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      04-22 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXISTENZ-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH FANTASY SUFFERS FROM TOO EARTHLY SETTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If you're already spending too much time playing video
games, watch out for ``eXistenZ,'' a futuristic thriller about
players who get lost in a bio-electronic game that plugs directly
into their spinal columns.
</P>
<P>
   This twisted tale of reality and illusion begins at a
test-marketing session, where the new game, eXistenZ, is being
tried out by avid fans.
</P>
<P>
   Players consider the game designer, Allegra (Jennifer Jason
Leigh), the high priestess of their wired world, but
anti-technology rebels are trying to destroy her.
</P>
<P>
   A would-be player (Jude Law) tries to rescue Allegra from spies
and assassins, who are everywhere. While on the run for their
lives, they also have to save Allegra's game. So they plug into the
game world, where they risk losing the separation between reality
and fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``eXistenZ'' comes from writer/director David Cronenberg, who
frequently has explored the links between science and horror,
reality and illusion in starkly gripping movies like ``The Fly,''
``Scanners'' and ``Videodrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg infuses ``eXistenZ'' with stimulating ideas about how
bio-electronics could become an addictive mind drug or a path of
liberation. But the ideas are more interesting than the movie
itself. It would have made a better book than it does a picture.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's biggest weakness should be its strength: the game
world itself. The fantasy landscape through which Allegra moves
isn't dramatically different from her reality. If that's the most
imaginative world the game designers could come up with, you wonder
why anyone would want to play it _ much less go to war over it.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh's intensity was better demonstrated in ``Rush,'' ``Short
Cuts'' and ``Last Exit to Brooklyn,'' and Law was stronger in
``Gattaca'' and ``Music From Another Room.'' Cronenberg doesn't put
their passions to effective use in ``eXistenZ.'' Their characters
are more like game pieces than real people.
</P>
<P>
   ``eXistenZ'' is the second movie of the season to blur the
borders between reality and illusion. Although ``eXistenZ'' is
better thought out than ``The Matrix,'' it's not nearly as exciting
a movie experience. It plays too flat.
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg once combined provocative thinking about technology's
impact on humanity with a pulsating visual story in the nearly
perfect science-fiction horror story ``The Fly.'' But Cronenberg's
directing energy seems to have flattened out, too.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``The Matrix'' and ``eXistenZ'' left me wondering: If
reality is an illusion, why isn't it a better one?
</P>
<P>
   ``eXistenZ'' is rated R for violence and profanity. 2 stars.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Fenster can be reached at bob.fenster(at)pni.com by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
