<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRONENBERG23-COX     04-22 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRONENBERG23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bizarre finds a cozy berth in this director's work
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting to know David Cronenberg, the Canadian writer-director
of ``eXistenZ,'' his new mind-games-with-computers movie starring
Jennifer Jason Leigh and Jude Law (see review above):
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Yeah, he's the guy who:
</P>
<P>
   1. Gave Marilyn Chambers a bloodsucking armpit (``Rabid'').
</P>
<P>
   2. Had Jeremy Irons play twin gynecologists sharing their
bedside manner with Genevieve Bujold (``Dead Ringers'').
</P>
<P>
   3. Turned Jeff Goldblum into a romantic lead who barfed on his
food before eating it (``The Fly'').
</P>
<P>
   4. Gave cinema its first exploding head in living color
(``Scanners'').
</P>
<P>
   5. Introduced Peter Weller to a bunch of huge insects who talked
out of their butts long before Jim Carrey ever did (``Naked
Lunch'').
</P>
<P>
   6. Cast Conyers (Ga.) native Holly Hunter as a doctor turned on
by car wrecks in a movie that led to a public dissing by Ted Turner
and earned an NC-17 rating (``Crash'').
</P>
<P>
   Consider him the Pedro Almodovar of biological dread.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How he got interested in video games:
</P>
<P>
   His kids (no surprise). He has two sons, 27 and 19, and a
daughter, 14. ``I look over their shoulder when they play,''
Cronenberg says. ``But I don't have the desire to spend eight or 12
hours trying to get to Level 8. But I am fascinated by the process
and the inventiveness. If a new art form emerges from computers, I
think it will arise from that technology.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hey, David, isn't it weird timing that another virtual-reality
sci-fi flick is also in theaters (``The Matrix'')?
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seems that way,'' he says. ``When I did `Dead
Ringers,' there were suddenly five twins movies. When I did `Naked
Lunch,' there were four movies about writers writing.'' For the
record, he hasn't seen ``The Matrix,'' and yes, everybody keeps
asking him if he has.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What about those freaky, fleshy game pods in ``eXistenZ''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold myself responsible for everything in the movie. It's
described in great detail in the script. It's a four-month
collaboration with artists and sculptors and people who can make
silicone skin. They show me models. I say, `It's too thick or too
thin,' or `It's not organic enough.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Why Jennifer Jason Leigh and Jude Law?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer is fearless. You never know what she's going to do,
because she isn't interested in being `a star.' Jude was a real
discovery. I saw him in `Gattaca' and thought he was terrific.
Here's a guy who, for the same reason as Jennifer, the audience
doesn't really know which way he's going to go, what he's capable
of.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Was it this movie Leigh was filming that kept her from going
back to England to reshoot scenes for ``Eyes Wide Shut''?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct. She was very cool about that, and so was
Kubrick. He was very gentlemanly with her and she loved him, and he
tried very hard to make it work. But she knew when she left his set
that he wasn't satisfied with one of the scenes and wanted to
reshoot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Was Stanley Kubrick an influence for you as a filmmaker?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure. By the time I started to see his stuff, my
character as a filmmaker was pretty well formed. But I admired him
as a figure in moviemaking who was renowned for having a mind and
being an intellectual.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What about ``Crash''? Was the controversy a plus or minus?
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely a plus. It was a big success in France and Poland
and Canada. It was really only Ted Turner's problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What's next:
</P>
<P>
   The director will chair the panel of filmmakers and actors at
this year's Cannes International Film Festival. (It was at Cannes
that ``Crash'' received a specially created award ``for
originality, for daring and for audacity,'' so Cronenberg will be
right at home.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
