<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEWS-MOVIES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is it real _ or is it a skewed `eXistenZ'?
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any movie with an opening credit that reads ``And Willem Dafoe
as Gas'' should pique your curiosity. But when that movie is also
directed by the unpredictable and brainy David Cronenberg
(``Crash,'' ``The Fly''), then you know it's fasten-your-seat-belts
time.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a pretty accurate assessment of ``eXistenZ,''
Cronenberg's newest nut-case extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   The territory is virtual reality. Sometime in the near future,
video games have become so technically evolved and manifest
alternative realities so terribly potent that a countermovement of
``realists'' has arisen. These realists are dead set against all
things virtual _ especially the inventors of the games. Their
fanaticism suggests the fatwa declared against novelist Salman
Rushdie, an event that Cronenberg, who has returned to writing his
own material for the first time since 1982's ``Videodrome,'' says
was one of his touchstones for the film.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's realists set their sights on supershy ``game-pod
goddess'' Allegra Geller (Jennifer Jason Leigh), who after a
botched assassination attempt finds herself on the run with a
novice security guard named Ted (Jude Law). Damaged in the attack
was her game _ eXistenZ _ and to see what condition its condition
is in, she's got to play it with Ted.
</P>
<P>
   If you're already a fan of Cronenberg's creep-genius
moviemaking, then you know some of what to expect: strange
mutilations and mutations; yucky, icky-squishy stuff dripping with
gore, pus and primal fears; matter-of-fact grotesqueries; and a
pitch-black sense of humor. For instance, to play a virtual-reality
game, a player has to be fitted with a bio-port at the base of the
spine. Discovering that Ted doesn't have a bio-port because, well,
he's squeamish about body piercing, Allegra scoffs, ``They do it at
malls. It's like getting your ears pierced.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg creates a Chinese box structure that constantly
challenges us with who's- reality-is-it-anyway twists and
surprises. At the same time, ``eXistenZ'' clearly doesn't take
itself altogether seriously. With its self-consciously arcane
jargon (``You neuro-surged and blew my pod!'') and nasty
body-function absurdities, the movie often seems to be mocking the
filmmaker's own trademark over-the-top conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his intentions _ to crack us up or gross us out _
Cronenberg has never been timid about his cinematic visions.
Allegra could be speaking for him when she says, ``People are
programmed to accept so little, but the possibilities are so
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities in ``eXistenZ'' offer state-of-the-art messing
with your mind. Fasten your seat belts and grab hold of your gag
reflex.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and about that ``Willem Dafoe as Gas'' credit. See, if you
can't get to the mall, you can seek out some repulsive backwoods
gas station where they deal in black-market bio-ports and . .
.well, you get the idea. Double yuuuuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``eXistenZ''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jennifer Jason Leigh and Jude Law. Directed by David
Cronenberg. Rated R for violence, sexual themes and general
nastiness. 1 hour, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Welcome to another of David Cronenberg's amazing
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
