<TEXT>
<P>
   (lh) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, April 23. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littelton, Colo.) _ The ledeall. The two
outcasts who massacred their classmates before killing themselves
intended to blow up the school, the authorities said Thursday after
discovering two large propane bombs hidden in the school's kitchen.
By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS (Littleton) _ At a time when the gun industry
is battling lawsuits and other challenges, outrage over the high
school shooting is suddenly altering the debate over guns,
bolstering, at least for the time being, the political power of the
gun control advocates. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-KOSOVO (Washington) _ Lede-all on events in Washington on
the NATO summit, with the Kosovo campaign dominating discussion.
President Clinton and Javier Solana, the NATO secretary-general,
confer and then meet with the press. Tony Blair, the British prime
minister, and others meet congressman at the Capitol. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ A month into NATO's war against
Yugoslavia, U.S. cruise missiles destroyed one of President
Slobodan Milosevic's official residences in Belgrade early Thursday
in a direct strike at the core of Milosevic's power. The Pentagon
warns that more attacks are coming. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-IMMIG (New York) _ The 20,000 Kosovar refugees coming to
the United States will be given green cards that will pave the way
for them to become permanent citizens. But the decision has angered
some Albanians who say it plays into the hands of Milosevic. By
Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SOCSEC (Washington) _ Republican leaders in the House
of Representatives have abandoned the idea of making fundamental
changes in Social Security this year, just as the top Republicans
on the Ways and Means Committee are putting the final touches on a
plan to base the retirement program partly on private investments.
By David Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-FOSSIL (Undated) _ Digging beneath a plain in
Ethiopia, paleontologists have found a skull and other fossils of
what they say is a new prehuman species, possibly the long-sought
connecting link between apelike ancestors and the human family. By
John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU (Jerusalem) _ It is four months since Benjamin
Netanyahu's government was dissolved prematurely, and he was forced
into a tight race for re-election on May 17. Netanyahu, nicknamed
Bibi, is still held in high regard by many admirers. But his circle
of allies has shrunk. And his small clique of advisers, like him,
exudes an air of us against the world. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GAYS-GENE (Undated) _ Researchers report they are unable to
replicate earlier findings that variations in a region of the
X-chromosome are linked to male homosexuality. The report does not
necessarily invalidate the earlier work but scientists say it shows
how difficult it will be to link complex behavioral traits to a
particular gene or genes. By Erica Goode. (800 words).
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ Three months after the largest economy
in Latin America appeared headed for an Asian-style meltdown,
Brazil is bouncing back. While the country remains in recession,
the average Brazilian seems willing to tolerate that so long as
there is no renewal of the hyperinflation of the 1980s and early
1990s. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
