<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     04-22 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wild, Wild Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Barring a cataclysm, the biggest film of the summer,
and probably the year, will be the extravagantly promoted George
Lucas fantasy ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' But
the film that has stirred almost as much talk is ``Wild Wild
West,'' directed by Barry Sonnenfeld and based on the popular
television series.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which stars Will Smith, Kevin Kline, Salma Hayek and
Kenneth Branagh, opens on July 2. It's a big, sprawling comedy
adventure made by a director whose last movie, ``Men in Black,''
was a huge hit. But the Hollywood spin and rumor machine has gone
into high gear about the movie, and its creators are furious. Rival
studio executives began whispering that the expensive movie was not
only in trouble but that its costs had spiraled to $150 million,
even $175 million. Or more. Every year, it seems, the Hollywood
rumor mill focuses on cost overruns, targeting one film. A few
years ago it was ``Last Action Hero,'' which turned out to be a box
office dud. More recently it was ``Titanic,'' which turned out to
be, well, titanic.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers, which is releasing ``Wild West West,'' says the
cost is a little over $105 million. Asked about the higher figures,
Barbara Brogliatti, a spokeswoman, said, ``It's totally
ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio sorely needs ``Wild Wild West'' to succeed. While
Warner Brothers has had a string of recent successes like ``You've
Got Mail,'' ``Analyze This'' and ``The Matrix,'' these films barely
compensate for losses on flops like ``Quest for Camelot,''
``Soldier,'' ``Wrongfully Accused,'' ``Major League 3,'' ``The
Avengers,'' ``The Postman'' and ``Mad City.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenfeld spoke in frustration and anger about the rumors and
articles involving his movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an out-of-control director,'' he said. ``It's a good
movie.'' He added, ``I can now see how easy it was for Joe McCarthy
to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it's Hollywood, there are conspiracy theories about rival
producers' spreading the rumors to damage the film's prospects. All
this sounds bizarre and Machiavellian. But that's life in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Abbie Hoffman's Story
</P>
<P>
   The Yippies are back! Robert Greenwald, a television producer
and director, vividly recalls following the odyssey of Abbie
Hoffman in the 1960's, as just about everyone else did. Greenwald,
who was then a high school student in New York and an undergraduate
at Antioch College in Yellow Springs, Ohio, particularly remembers
when Hoffman and a circle of friends founded ``Yippie,'' the band
of quintessential revolutionaries whose antiwar theatrics turned
them into counterculture heroes and heroines.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years later Greenwald explained the antiwar
movement to his grown daughters and their friends, who were
fascinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them about the Chicago trial, the march on the
Pentagon, the antiwar movement,'' Greenwald said. ``Sure, there
were the externals: the Janis Joplin songs and what hippies wore.
But I realized there was a great hunger in this generation to
capture that sense of excitement when there was a commitment to
issues that you believed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of this experience, and meetings over the years with Hoffman
and his former wife, Anita Hoffman, Greenwald has made ``Abbie,'' a
film about Hoffman's sometimes crazy, sometimes serious life. The
movie, to be seen by distributors over the next few weeks, has a
screenplay by Bruce Graham and Robert Ward based on two books: ``To
America With Love: Letters From the Underground,'' by Anita and
Abbie Hoffman, and ``Abbie Hoffman: American Rebel,'' by Marty
Jezer.
</P>
<P>
   The film stars Vincent D'Onofrio as Abbie, Janeane Garofalo as
Anita, who died of cancer last year at age 56, and Jeanne
Tripplehorn as Johanna Lawrenson, Hoffman's companion in his later
years.
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie is funny, it is also a dark exploration of a
man who shrewdly used a clowning style to provoke and outrage. In
1974 Hoffman went underground for six years while being sought by
the FBI on charges of selling cocaine, leaving behind Anita and a
small son, america, who was deliberately named with a lowercase a.
(His son is now an electrician in North Carolina.) For seven years
Hoffman was on the run, finally meeting Ms. Lawrenson, who
protected him. In 1978 he resurfaced as Barry Freed, an
environmental activist in upstate New York. Two years later he
surrendered and served a short prison term. The Hoffmans were
divorced in 1980 but remained close friends.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's later years were darkened by bouts of manic
depression. He committed suicide with a huge dose of barbiturates
in 1989 at age 52.
</P>
<P>
   Several film projects about Hoffman have foundered, partly
because Mrs. Hoffman refused to sell the rights to her book.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was dubious that anyone could capture the love story, the
times, the passions, the humor,'' Greenwald said.
</P>
<P>
   He had the advantage of having met Mrs. Hoffman in the 1970s; at
one point he was even invited to a dinner to meet Barry Freed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was funny, charismatic and really, really smart,''
Greenwald said. ``We spent a lot of time that evening talking about
music _ Phil Ochs, Country Joe and the Fish, Richie Havens.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald said he wanted to depict not only the importance of
Hoffman in his time but also his relevance today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbie was consistent to the end,'' Greenwald said. ``He
believed you had to commit to something beyond your narrow
self-interest, or as he said, beyond greed. And in that sense your
life becomes meaningful. It's a positive message to pass on.''
</P>
<P>
   The film cost about $10 million, with most of the money raised
from some Wall Street hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbie would have gotten a kick out of that,'' Greenwald said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An Irish Tale
</P>
<P>
   Since childhood Aidan Quinn has been immersed in his Irish
roots. Although he grew up in Chicago and Rockford, Ill., the
40-year-old actor lived off and on in Dublin and other Irish cities
as a boy. His father, Michael, a college teacher and Irish
immigrant, frequently moved the family back to Ireland when he took
academic sabbaticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dominated by both cultures,'' said Quinn, whose film
roles have included ``Legends of the Fall,'' ``Michael Collins,''
``The Playboys'' and ``Blink.'' He added: ``It was a blessing and
curse. Moving back and forth. In one sense, you were always a
stranger in a strange land.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Quinn is seeking to depict the Irish experience through his
role in ``This Is My Father,'' a movie that is very much a Quinn
family experience, too. The film, which opens on May 7, was written
and directed by Paul Quinn, his 39-year-old brother, who is also a
theatrical director. Another brother, Declan, 41, who was the
Oscar-winning cinematographer for ``Leaving Las Vegas'' (1995), is
behind the camera on this movie. A sister, Marian, plays a small
role.
</P>
<P>
   The film chronicles the journey of a bitter Chicago
schoolteacher (played by James Caan) who takes his teen-age nephew
(Jacob Tierney) to Ireland in a quest to unravel a mystery about
his family's past and the tragedy that befell his mother. Quinn
plays a poor farmer, an outsider who was in love with the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is hardly a romantic view of Ireland like `Waking Ned
Devine.''' Quinn said. ``It sort of makes you understand why there
have been 800 years of emigration.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said there were few younger brother-older brother
complications on the film set.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get away from that completely,'' he said.
``Hopefully, you iron all that stuff out by the time you're a
teen-ager.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually we all had tremendous respect for each other, but we
did disagree,'' he said. ``And if Declan and I had one view, and
Paul had another, Paul would say, `I hear what you're saying, but I
disagree.' In other words, he was the director, it was his film and
he made the ultimate decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who lives in New Jersey with his wife and two young
daughters, is popular in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a celebrity there,'' he said, ``much more than I am
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is frequently cast in movies, Quinn said his acting
career had become a bit frustrating as he approached middle age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get offered enough good parts, and this film kind of
spoiled me,'' he said. ``The studio system is difficult and
somewhat disastrous for all actors and actresses unless you're one
of those 10 or 15 stars whose name can green-light a film.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said that friends like Stanley Tucci and Steve Buscemi
were now writing and starring in their own independent films
because of similar frustration with the lack of interesting roles
in studio films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be Zen about the whole thing,'' Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Does living away from Los Angeles and in New Jersey hurt his
career?
</P>
<P>
   ``It may make a little bit of difference,'' Quinn said. ``But
the trade-off in my sanity makes it worthwhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
