<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-ART-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-22 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POP IMPRESSIONS:' THE CONSUMERAMA OF POP ART  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most sought-after trophies of the Pop Art era are
paintings, of course, with their big, catchy images of consumer
products and media scenes. But printmaking, too, by the very fact
of its populist, disseminative nature, was an important Pop
activity. A well-rounded reminder of this is the Modern's bright,
snappy show, ``Pop Impressions Europe/U.S.A.: Prints and Multiples
From the Museum of Modern Art,'' whose 90 objects are drawn
entirely from the museum's collection.
</P>
<P>
   The show has a good deal of material _ cocky, brassy, vulgar,
sexy, sometimes impassioned and occasionally witty _ that may
trigger nostalgia in those who were of art-viewing age in the 1960s
and '70s. But what is most interesting is that the exhibition and
its well-researched catalog cover developments in Europe as well as
the United States, placing works by Americans like Andy Warhol, Roy
Lichtenstein, James Rosenquist, Ed Ruscha and Robert Indiana cheek
by jowl with those of artists from abroad: among them Martial
Raysse (France), Dieter Roth and Gerhard Richter (Germany) and
Richard Hamilton and Eduardo Paolozzi (Britain).
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's organizer, Wendy Weitman, associate curator in
the department of prints and illustrated books at the museum, has
divided the show into five very loose and sometimes overlapping
themes: proto-Pop, mass media, consumer culture, politics and
erotica. As she points out in the catalog, there was ``no one Pop
art''; it developed differently in different countries. Broadly
speaking, in Europe politics was more apt to color the work, while
in the United States, with a milder postwar hangover and an
economic boom that produced a flourishing demand for goods,
artists' imagery was dominated by consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   Black-and-white lithographs by Jasper Johns (``Flag I,'' 1960)
and Robert Rauschenberg (``License,'' 1962) begin the show. Though
pop in portent, they were still influenced by the rough brushwork
of Abstract Expressionism. But working in lithograph ateliers like
June Wayne's Tamarind and Tatyana Grosman's Universal Limited Art
Editions, the two artists furthered the appeal of printmaking as a
medium. Europeans like Daniel Spoerri, Arman and Christo were more
3-D-oriented. Christo's contribution to the show, ``Wrapped Look
Magazine'' (1965), a copy of the popular periodical tightly wrapped
in see-through plastic and cord, was created for a Spoerri project,
a series of multiple objects called MAT (Multiplication d'Art
Transformable). Each of the three MAT series that actually were
released was produced in an edition of 100, the object being to
make artwork affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Spoerri is represented here by a multiple from a different
edition, a wonderful pop-up collage from 1973, mounted on bright
blue board, of the dishes and detritus left after a meal, a
recurring image in his work. The multiple, based on a photograph,
was part of a portfolio made up, long after their disbanding, of
work by New Realists, a French Pop group that included Yves Klein,
Raysse and Arman and whose goal was to bring the real world into
their art.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1960s, mass imagery, already ``discovered'' in the
1950s by Hamilton and Paolozzi, had entrenched itself in American
consciousness. Screen printing, a commercial process, became the
preferred medium for its ease of use and ability to give smooth
registry to multicolor images and photo processes. The mass media
section of the show includes such icons as Warhol's screen print
``Cagney'' (1964), a black-and-white still from a 1930's gangster
movie showing James Cagney menaced by the shadow of a manned rifle
as, gun in each hand, he faces an unseen killer. Unlike Warhol's
later work, this one still has painterly touches, notably the white
streaks left by the squeegee as it pushed ink through the printing
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Sharply contrasting with the Warhol in terms of brilliant color
and elegant finish is Indiana's ``Love'' (1967), a sophisticatedly
geometric logo of that word in saturated hues of red, green and
blue. It is nice to see this old chestnut, originally designed as a
Christmas card for the Modern and redone in more than 20
variations, including one used for an 8-cent United States postage
stamp of 1973 that was produced in a truly mass edition of more
than 300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The universality of Marilyn Monroe's appeal is reaffirmed in
this section by Hamilton's ``My Marilyn'' (1966), an elaborately
worked-over screen print of publicity photographs rejected by
Monroe with ``X'' marks, except for a playfully sexy shot on the
beach. The rejected photos in this poignant montage are meant to
convey the vulnerability of Monroe's life and its final negation,
her suicide in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Warhol and Lichtenstein dominate the liveliest section of the
show, consumer culture. Warhol's ubiquitous Campbell's soup can
adorns a paper shopping bag, the first version of this image to
appear in an edition (of 125-200), sold for $12 at a landmark Pop
show of 1964, ``The American Supermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on display is the shopping bag made by Lichtenstein for
that show, depicting one of his signature cooked turkeys, probably
swiped from a newspaper advertisement. Hitting the spectator right
in the deja vu are Warhol's famous ``S &AMP; H Green Stamps'' (1965),''
Lichtenstein's banal ``Sandwich and Soda'' (1964) printed in color
on clear plastic for a portfolio of work by 10 painters and
Ruscha's big, garish stylization of an auto stop, ``Standard
Station'' (1966), a veritable emblem of the Pop movement.
</P>
<P>
   The imagery seems thinnest in the politics section, maybe
because the complexities of the subject did not lend themselves so
well to Pop stylization. One arresting piece, however, is Jim
Dine's ``Drag _ Johnson and Mao'' (1967), a large etching and
aquatint showing the heads of President Johnson and Mao, the
Chinese leader, wearing makeup and clownish facial adornments,
apparently a comment on Johnson's Vietnam-influenced loss of power
vis-a-vis Mao's iron political grip. A screen print by the British
artist Joe Tilson, ``Is This Che Guevara?'' (1969), impresses with
its striking arrangement of newsprint images of Che's dead face
punctuated by repetitive news clips of him as a Cuban hero.
</P>
<P>
   The erotica section, whose imagery draws from the liberated
sexual climate of the 1960s, concentrates on _ what else? _ women,
from Tom Wesselmann's heavily stylized, hard-edge ``Nude'' (1965),
stressing the nippled white section of a tanned torso, done for the
screen print portfolio ``11 Pop Artists, Volume II,'' to Sigmar
Polke's deliberately fuzzy black-and-white photolithograph,
``Girlfriends'' (1967), based on a provocative newspaper
advertisement for women's clothing and depicting two women, in a
maybe relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Pop may not be every artgoer's dish, but its impact still
resonates. This lively show is valuable for its attempt to explore
how artists connected or collided with the great global consumerama
set in motion during the 60s and their subversive view as a
nonelitist pursuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
