<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-BURTON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON CHALLENGING GORDON FOR CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This could be the year Jeff Burton breaks out. Burton, 31, is in
his fourth year driving for Roush Racing, the high-powered five-car
Ford team owned by Jack Roush.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday at Martinsville, Va., Burton wound up second to John
Andretti, who passed him four laps from the end to take the win.
</P>
<P>
   It was Burton's sixth top-five finish in the first eight races,
enabling him to remain on top in the Winston Cup point standings,
where he leads another Ford driver, Dale Jarrett, 1,239 to 1,154.
</P>
<P>
   With victories at Las Vegas and Darlington, S.C., Burton already
is within one win of his best season in 1997, when he won three
races.
</P>
<P>
   But to win the championship, he must avoid problems like he had
in February when he finished 35th in the Daytona 500. Burton's
Daytona car, though, was much better than that, which is why he is
optimistic heading for the Diehard 500 in Talladega, Ala., on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We qualified 11th and finished third in the 125-mile
qualifier, and then got in a wreck at Daytona,'' Burton said.
``That's why we finished where we did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we felt pretty good about our Daytona effort,'' Burton
said. ``We really didn't get down about it. Daytona is so different
than everything else we do. We just kind of put it behind us and
went to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, when Jeff Gordon won his first Winston Cup title,
anyone who expects to challenge him has to win races and finish in
the top five consistently. Gordon, who is 27, has won three Winston
championships and finished second once. From 1995 through 1998, he
won a remarkable 40 out of 127 races and recorded 86 top fives.
</P>
<P>
   Things may be different this year. Already, Gordon has failed to
finish in two races, equaling the number of his entire 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon's consistency breaks down, it could pave the way for
someone else _ like Burton _ to break through. After finishing
fourth in 1997 and fifth in 1998, Burton has an idea of what it
takes to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a contender the last two years has made us a smarter
race team in ways we probably don't even realize,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a chance to run against Dale Jarrett and Jeff
Gordon and Bobby Labonte and Rusty Wallace _ everybody that runs up
front every week _ those experiences are irreplaceable,'' Burton
said. ``You learn so much by doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult things for young drivers to understand
is that you don't win a race on the first lap and you don't win a
championship in one race. For example, Andretti, who is 36, won
last Sunday in Martinsville, Va., even though he spun out and lost
a lap early in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing that stands out most for me is patience,
understanding that not every race is gonna go the way you want it
to, that every lap is not gonna go the way you want it to,'' Burton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let those negatives mess up your whole year and get
you so mad that you do things out of anger or emotion,'' he said.
``This is a long, long season and there's a lot of time from race
to race. We've learned to take each race for what it is. If we win
a race, we don't think that just because we've won means we're
gonna win next week. At the same time, if you finish 35th, don't
think that means you're gonna go finish 35th next week.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
