<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFETT-REPORT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG PROFITS AND MORALITY MIX ON WALL STREET FOR BUFFETT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WALDO PROFITT   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have been reading the annual report of Berkshire Hathaway
Inc., which I always find an enjoyable way to spend an evening
because a) extensive portions of it are written by Warren Buffett,
and b) it almost always reports a substantial return to
stockholders, of whom I am one of the very smallest.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett, who has been called the most successful investor in
history, has a wry humor, a rare trait among financiers, and an
almost compulsive streak of honesty, which is not necessarily rare
for corporate chieftains, but is something less than universal
amongst the breed.
</P>
<P>
   One of his qualities I find most attractive and amusing is his
unabashed penchant for synergy. For instance, he notes that
Berkshire has the largest net worth of any American corporation,
$57.4 billion, which is not the same as market value but which does
indicate the amount of capital that managers must deploy. To
increase intrinsic value at an average rate of 15 percent a year
will require massive new investment.
</P>
<P>
   So, a few pages ahead in the annual report, Buffett says he
would like to hear from principals of large companies that would
fit comfortably into the Berkshire family. ``We would like to make
an acquisition in the $5 billion to $20 billion range. We will not
engage in unfriendly takeovers. We can promise complete
confidentiality and a very fast answer _ customarily within five
minutes _ as to whether we're interested. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Buffett also uses the annual report and the company's annual
meeting to increase revenues for businesses owned by Berkshire. The
annual meeting will be May 1 to 3 in Omaha, Neb. A coliseum and a
convention center with a combined seating of 19,000 have been
booked.
</P>
<P>
   Stockholders may secure help with plane, hotel and car
reservations from American Express (Berkshire owns 50.5 million
shares).
</P>
<P>
   Chartered buses will make trips to Borsheim's, a purveyor of
fine jewelry, owned by Berkshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``A full line of Berkshire products will be available. ... Last
year we set sales records across-the-board, moving 3,700 pounds of
See's candy, 1,635 pairs of Dexter shoes, 1,150 sets of Quikut
knives and 3,104 Berkshire shirts and hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Dairy Queen, owned by guess who, will be on hand. Last year it
sold about 4,000 frozen delicacies. Borsheim's will be open
especially for shareholders on the Sunday of the meeting. Last
year, the store's volume on that stockholder Sunday ``greatly
exceeded'' volume for any day in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Even in small matters, you can see, Buffett and his partner,
Charles Munger, don't overlook many chances to increase Berkshire's
intrinsic value.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire either paid or will soon pay $2.7 billion in federal
income tax for 1998. Buffett's reaction: ``Writing checks to the
IRS that include strings of zeros does not bother Charlie or me.
Berkshire as a corporation and we as individuals have prospered in
America as we would have in no other country ... we feel
extraordinarily lucky to have been dealt a hand in life that
enables us to write large checks to the government ...''
</P>
<P>
   Another attractive thing about Buffett is that he is not afraid
to say something critical of business. He expresses particular
sorrow this year at companies and managers who manipulate earnings
to satisfy Wall Street's desires. ``These managers start with the
assumption, all too common, that their job at all times is to
encourage the highest stock price possible (a premise with which we
adamantly disagree). ... When operations don't produce the result
hoped for, these CEOs resort to unadmirable accounting stratagems
...
</P>
<P>
   ``The distortion du jour is the `restructuring charge,' an entry
that can, of course, be legitimate but that too often is used as a
device for manipulating earnings. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``In the acquisition arena, restructuring has been raised to an
art form. Managements now frequently use mergers to dishonestly
rearrange the value of assets and liabilities in ways that will
allow them to both smooth and swell future earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry I won't be at the annual meeting. I'd be happy to make
my meager contribution to Berkshire's cash flow by buying company
ice cream and candy and caps for an opportunity to listen to
Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of The New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
