<HEADLINE>
IN COMICS, ANYTHING BUT NORMAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(af) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You don't want your characters to be perfect,'' said Mark
Bode, looking spiky, disheveled and agreeably imperfect himself in
his Felix the Cat T-shirt, black sneakers, earrings and slouchy,
conspiratorial demeanor. ``You want them to have problems, quirks,
personality. Just as long as they're not normal. Normal isn't very
interesting, is it? You want your characters to have something
wrong with them.''
</P>
<P>
   We are at the Words and Pictures Museum in Northampton, Mass.,
one of three museums in the United States (and the only one in the
Northeast) devoted solely to what the museum calls ``fine graphic
narrative and fantasy illustration,'' i.e., cartoon and comic-book
art in all its caricatured, heavy-metal humor and superhero
permutations.
</P>
<P>
   The balance between perfect and imperfect, funky and artful,
casual and purposeful, is the essence of the museum, which was
founded in 1992 by Kevin B. Eastman, one of the creators of the
Teen-Age Mutant Ninja Turtles.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in a four-story building downtown with cartoon
silhouettes in the windows and a giant gargoyle on top, the museum,
whose full name is the Words and Pictures Museum of Fine Sequential
Art, is half art gallery and half fun house. It has both
traditional galleries with fantasy art displayed like Rembrandts
and grotto-like, kid-friendly work spaces.
</P>
<P>
   But the sense of walking both sides of the street applies
equally to Northampton itself, the very symbol of renascent,
refined New England on the one hand and a beehive of grunge style,
buzz cuts, body piercing and alternative everything on the other.
So you can get a bracing course in cultural dichotomy both inside
and outside the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to take our kids, ages 8 and 12 and more attuned to
the South, where they lived until last summer, than to New England,
for a weekend in Northampton and a trip to the museum, which was
featuring a course in cartooning taught by Bode.
</P>
<P>
   Great artistry doesn't necessarily run in our family. But
Garfield, Calvin and Hobbes, Dilbert, the Far Side and various
too-expensive ``Star Wars'' and ``Star Trek'' graphic novels have
been on their bookshelves forever, and taking a crash course in
cartooning seemed too good an idea to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   We wended our way from our home outside Manhattan, arriving at
the old Hotel Northampton, where mummies and daddies of countless
generations of Smith College students have come to knock down gin
and tonics at the Wiggins Tavern Pub and visit the campus. The red
brick hotel, which is in the middle of downtown and opened in 1927,
is like a snapshot of the more traditional Northampton: musty,
genteel and sedate.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, you can make a beeline from the hotel to the Smith
campus _ with its green groves and Paradise Pond; its three-level
Smith College Museum of Art, with an exquisite collection of
Monets, Homers, Cezannes and van Goghs; its Botanic Garden and
Lyman Conservatory _ and feel as if you were in a New England
college movie circa 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, the whole downtown, with its amiable
clutter of low-scale ice cream parlors and craft shops, outdoor
clothes emporiums, bookstores and coffee shops upon coffee shops,
suggests an impossibly idyllic small town life in the pre-mall,
pre-franchise America.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this analysis goes only so far. If Northampton has
the look, scale, foliage and climate of L.L. Bean country, it also
has the populace of Berkeley or Ann Arbor.
</P>
<P>
   These days it is better known for its large and influential
lesbian community than for the fact that Calvin Coolidge was once
mayor or that Jonathan Edwards used to evoke the plight of sinners
in the hand of an angry God from his pulpit there in the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, a comic book museum doesn't entirely fit either
image of Northampton. It is definitely not the Currier &AMP;
Ives/Robert Frost New England. But on the surface, it seems a
little intellectually down market for the hip, engaged, North Face
Northampton of liberal politics and gender-bending.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the museum is something of an institution,
with its own alternative mission. The whole purpose of the museum,
which has 18,000 works in its collection, is to show respect for an
art form and for artists that are often not taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   American comics are usually said to date to 1896, with the
publication of the first newspaper cartoon strip, ``The Yellow
Kid,'' in The New York Journal. Comic books became popular in the
1930s, and many of the superheroes we think of first when we think
of comic books _ Superman, Batman, Captain America, Mandrake the
Magician _ began around that time. Since then comics have waxed and
waned in terms of artistry, popularity and artistic daring, with
the current moment one of the less auspicious ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comic book industry is always a roller coaster,'' Bode
said. ``But it's very scary out there right now. The underground
field is virtually nonexistent; almost all the underground
publishers have gone belly up. And unless you have a movie or toy
figure attached to your comic book, you're not going to get it
published. It's one reason this museum is so important. Even in
good times, it's hard in this country for people to take this kind
of art seriously, and this museum does an unbelievably great job of
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Professional pride is only one reason Bode cares about this so
much. He is the son of Vaughn Bode, a comic artist and
self-proclaimed ``Pop-Mystic Transvestite and One-Man Band'' whose
comic and erotic figures and use of wild lettering, have inspired
graphic arts and graffiti artists since the 1960s. A Web site with
a glimpse of his work is at www.dross.com/cheechwizard.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Bode died in 1975 at the age of 33, when his son was 12.
Mark Bode, who is now 36, sees his role at the museum as a way of
carrying on his father's work, part of a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't look at comic book art as fine art the way they
do in Europe,'' he said. ``I went to a festival in Angouleme,
France, where comic book art takes over the whole city and 100,000
people attend. But we've got this museum here full of incredible
art, and most people don't even know it exists.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``I tell people what I do, and they say: `Wow! You
make a living at being an idiot?' It used to irk me a little bit,
but now I don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He met his 16 students, most 7 to 12 years old, at the museum
shop and led them through what looked like caves full of
hieroglyphics and cave paintings to an elevator that took us to a
second-story atrium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Mark Bode,'' he told them. ``I'm a cartoonist. I've been a
cartoonist all my life. My father was a cartoonist before me.''
</P>
<P>
   He began with a few dos and don'ts. First, he said, you need to
draw a lot and there's nothing wrong with tracing. Then you need to
be enterprising in terms of sources. If you want to draw a
motorcycle, get a book of motorcycles to learn from. Then you want
to start building up your own cast of characters, like a family. He
runs through some of his drawings to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a parody of the Wizard of Oz,'' he said. ``It's the
Lizard of Oz. He's a little more neurotic. He has more problems, I
guess. You can see the poor Lion here. He's a nervous wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Then each student got a pad and pencils; it was time for them to
draw an animal. What kind, he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The first suggestion, a scorpion, seemed a little imposing. The
second idea, a frog, made more sense.
</P>
<P>
   They started with two circles for the eyes and added lines for
eyelids. They added a smile that went to the side of the eye and
lips, and they had a face. Next came the frog's lapel (``He's a
fancy dresser''), a bow tie, a squared-off body, shoulders and
arms, cuffs, hands, legs and feet. They added a hat and a balloon
so he could say ``Redeep!'' Voila! Every kid had come up with a
credible frog.
</P>
<P>
   Next came a very feisty kangaroo with boxing gloves and a
pathetic combination of a duck and turtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This poor guy,'' Bode said sympathetically. ``His mother was a
duck and his father was a turtle. It's unfortunate he came out this
way, but he didn't have a choice. He grew up in a nuclear power
plant swamp, and he's feeling sorry for himself. He's thinking,
`Why did you draw me like this?'''
</P>
<P>
   They added squiggly lines, the universal smelly sign, to make
him more ignominious, then admired their work. Before they were
done, they drew a weird hippie/punk bird with a mohawk, robe and
beer belly; a muscleman with tattoos, a fake arrow through his head
and a Jay Leno chin; a Ninja turtle, and a demented alligator
dentist. My daughter, Emma, came up with his name _ Dr. Decay _ so
she got to keep his original.
</P>
<P>
   The museum itself is a mixed experience. The book shop is kids'
and cartoon maven heaven, with cards, comic books, books on drawing
and the history of cartoons, posters, action figures, magnets,
T-shirts and caps of well-known and obscure comic figures.
</P>
<P>
   It leads to an interesting but modest display of comic books
through the ages, or at least decades, neatly divided by category:
science fiction, underground, alternative, fantasy, western,
funnies, superheroes, suspense. Next is a crash course in world art
from cave paintings to Persian manuscripts to Renaissance
altarpieces, making the case, more or less, that words-and-pictures
art didn't start with comic books.
</P>
<P>
   The main exhibition hall is the formal gallery on the fourth
floor with works by well-known comic and graphic artists' like
Vaughn Bode, Frank Frazetta, Will Eisner, Jack Kirby, Bill
Sienkiewicz and Bernie Wrightson. The work tends more to vivid,
imaginative fantasy or horror art or Vargas pinups than Mickey and
Goofy and is probably more attuned to adults than to children.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those represented are contemporary artists, primarily
from the United States, Britain and Europe. My favorite was the
series of Friendly Dictator trading cards by Sienkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   You can easily see the whole place in an hour and a half, then
return to the greater Northampton street circus, which seems to
have picked up the moniker Noho, though residents mostly prefer the
less pretentious Hamp as a nickname.
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite nuclear turtle-ducks, but the shops, galleries,
bookstores and eateries and the various variations on body piercing
provide an intriguing menagerie of their own.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who haven't had their fill of culture, there is
always the Beer Can Museum with its collection of 5,500 beer cans
at Ye Ol' Watering Hole, 287 Pleasant Street. But that's another
story. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting Northampton, Mass.: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay:
</P>
<P>
   THE HOTEL NORTHAMPTON, 36 King Street, Northampton, (413)
584-3100. Daily room rates are $135 to $145 Sundays to Thursdays
and $150 and $160 Fridays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat:
</P>
<P>
   GREEN STREET CAFE, 62 Green Street, Northampton, (413) 586-5650,
offers American and country French cooking. Dinner entrees with
salad are $16 to $24.
</P>
<P>
   LA VERACRUZANA, 31 Main Street, (413) 586-7181. Popular,
unpretentious San Francisco-style Mexican food. Most dishes $5.45
to $6.95.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions:
</P>
<P>
   WORDS AND PICTURES MUSEUM OF FINE SEQUENTIAL ART, 140 Main
Street, (413) 586-8545. Admission: $3 for adults; $2 for students
and the elderly; $1 for children under 18. The museum store is open
noon to 5 p.m. Tuesdays and Wednesdays; the store and museum
galleries are open noon to 5 p.m. Thursdays, noon to 8 p.m.
Fridays, 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. Saturdays and noon to 5 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   SMITH COLLEGE MUSEUM OF ART, Elm Street at Bedford Terrace,
(413) 585-2760. Open 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. Tuesdays, Wednesdays,
Fridays and Saturdays; 9:30 a.m. to 8 p.m. Thursdays, and noon to 4
p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   BOTANIC GARDEN AND LYMAN CONSERVATORY, 15 College Lane, (413)
585-2740. Open 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There:
</P>
<P>
   BY CAR: Take I-95 North to Exit 47. Take I-91 North to Exit 18.
Turn left onto Route 5 North into town.
</P>
<P>
   BY TRAIN: Amtrak has service from Penn Station in Manhattan to
Springfield, Mass., about 35 miles from Northampton, and to
Amherst, about 9 miles from Northampton. Fares: $33 one way, $66
round trip. Schedules and reservations: (800) 872-7245.
</P>
<P>
   BY BUS: Greyhound has as many as 13 buses daily to Northampton,
but many involve transfers to subsidiary lines like Peter Pan.
Round-trip fare is $53, with companion fares available more cheaply
on certain days. Service also available from the train terminus in
Springfield. Greyhound information and reservations: (800)
231-2222.
</P>
</TEXT>
