<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9465 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV29-     04-22 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV29-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I LOOK GOOD? WHAT DO YOU MEAN BY THAT?
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, April 29)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's becoming almost a standard part of the American greeting.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it goes: Big ``hi.'' Big hug. Step back, do a quic
scan and exclaim, ``You look GOOOOOD.'' This can be said with a
slight hint of amazement.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the response, ``YOU look good.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a compliment, isn't it? A positive exchange between two
people assuring one another that neither has fallen apart since the
last sighting, in fact has held up remarkably well.
</P>
<P>
   And you can't really challenge a compliment and ask, ``Well,
what do you mean by that?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can't help being a little suspect and wondering just
how bad you looked the last time. Or, more to the point, just how
fat you looked the last time.
</P>
<P>
   We know this because, if pressed to elaborate, the greeter will
often follow up by saying, ``YOU'VE lost weight.''
</P>
<P>
   If you protest that no, in fact you haven't, it's just a new
lipstick or maybe taller shoes, they will often tell you that
you're mistaken. You HAVE lost weight. They know.
</P>
<P>
   Then you start wondering if perhaps you went through a large
period and didn't realize it. Maybe it's those dumb black pants
that you know better than to wear with a sweater tucked in. Anyhow,
someone has been noticing and now she's congratulating you for
losing weight you didn't even realize you had gained.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose if we were higher-minded we would be confident enough
to rely on what our mirror tells us and ignore the opinion of
others. But not even a three-way mirror reveals everything. So, we
depend on a regular review from the outside. And then the outer
critic sets off the inner critic.
</P>
<P>
   I recently introduced myself to a stranger who looked me over
and declared that I was a lot thinner than my photograph. Well,
thanks, I said, automatically, and then wondered how a tiny little
mug shot at the top of a newspaper column could imply overweight,
underweight or any weight at all. Is it a thick chin, one big ear?
</P>
<P>
   Still, I was flattered and quietly told myself that had she said
the opposite, ``you look a lot fatter than your picture,'' I would
have walked around hugging friends until I found someone to say,
``You look GOOD.''
</P>
<P>
   Great is different. When someone says, ``You look GREAT,'' it is
getting closer to a true compliment. It means the haircut or the
new suit works or there's been a distinct improvement since last
week when you were down with the flu and your eyes hung off your
chin. Weight-wise, a ``great'' might indicate a whole size drop.
</P>
<P>
   If you are sensitive to these things you will want to know about
a marketing gimmick for a new diet pill. A woman I know was feeling
vulnerable _ probably having what I call a blubby day _ when she
received an envelope addressed to her and inside a newspaper
clipping talking about this great Asian remedy for losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing new there, but at the top of it, written in
ink, was a personal note saying something like, ``Judy. Try it. It
works.''
</P>
<P>
   What would you think if you were Judy, and feeling a bit
sensitive, and got that in the mail? Would you think, oh, just
another diet scheme? Or would you think, which friend out there
thinks I'm porking up and won't even sign her name?
</P>
<P>
   This woman had a couple hard days, stewing over who she knew who
could be so mean. Bravely, this woman confided in another woman,
maybe thinking she might tip her hand, but that woman reported that
she, too, had received the identical clipping in the mail with her
name on the top.
</P>
<P>
   I called the diet pill people and asked if they were sending
these out and a spokeswoman admitted they were and it was a very
successful campaign. She says it's called a ``personalized ad'' and
the names come off a mailing list. It has nothing to do with
anybody's size.
</P>
<P>
   The moral to this is: If your friend thinks you need to lose
weight, she'll infer it to you personally.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
