<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9469 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-WALESA-Q&AMP;A23-COX     04-22 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-WALESA-Q&AMP;A23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WALESA SAYS 'OVERWHELMING' NATO FORCE NEEDED FOR KOSOVO
 &HT;    With PHOTOS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nobel Peace Prize winner Lech Walesa, the legendary
leader of the anti-communist Solidarity movement who later served
as president of Poland, met Thursday with reporters and editors in
the Cox Washington Bureau. In an hour-long interview on the eve of
the NATO summit here, he talked through a translator about the
conflict in Kosovo. Excerpts:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you agree with NATO's air attacks against Yugoslavia, and
is there a diplomatic solution?
</P>
<P>
   A. I've already won a Nobel Peace Prize and I don't want to lose
it. It is obvious that I am against the use of any military force.
But, there are certain situations in which you don't see any other
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The present tactic adopted by NATO has resulted in the reverse
to what it was intended for (because it has resulted in the forced
exodus of ethnic Albanian refugees). This wasn't really what we
were aiming for.
</P>
<P>
   I think we must adopt a new strategy, ... We must disarm the
people participating in the conflict. Pour some cold water on them.
Make them calm down.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How could this be accomplished?
</P>
<P>
   A. By answering with an overwhelming (NATO) force. ... (Give
Yugoslavia's President Slobodan Milosevic) a deadline: ``If you do
not obey the deadline, we will use all the force available to
attack Yugoslavia. You cannot count on any mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   I also had another rough idea. All the (19) NATO members would
divide Yugoslavia into the number of regions that is equal to the
number of NATO members and each NATO member would be given the task
to put order in the particular region that he will have the
responsibility for.
</P>
<P>
   We would cut off all the supplies. And months later, after (Serb
forces) have really become hungry, we will put huge grills outside
the borders so that they will get all the smoke and all the flavor
and the fumes of the grill without giving them the food. And we
will trade: ``If you hand us the weapons, we will hand you the
sausage in return.'' This is a joke, of course. ... They are
serious issues, I know. But they can be dealt with by different
forms of strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you believe Milosevic should be tried as a war criminal?
</P>
<P>
   A. Whoever goes back to the Holocaust, whoever goes back to
genocide, whoever goes back to ethnic cleansing, is a criminal in
the new era. And there is no mercy on such people. ... (He) must be
brought to court because he constitutes a threat to progress and to
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Should NATO have taken military action in Kosovo earlier than
it did?
</P>
<P>
   A. Poland cannot question the decisions of the (NATO)
commanders. We will remain faithful allies until the end. ... We
cannot afford for NATO to lose in this conflict. Defeat of NATO in
this conflict would cause a real problem in the world. We have to
win the victory here.
</P>
<P>
   Q. A Russian parliamentary leader said recently that relations
with the United States are the most dangerous they have been since
the Cuban missile crisis. How would Russia and the Slavic world
react if NATO ground forces go into Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   A. Russia used to be an empire, but is now declining and
becoming a weaker and weaker empire. ... For centuries (it has
been) like this in Russia, that in order to be able to run the
country ... it has always needed a good outside enemy. They have
always had this concept of an outside enemy and that's what has
kept them together.
</P>
<P>
   Now I think they are trying to find an event, an outside enemy,
in order to be able to deal with their domestic problems. So if we
coolly look at things and reflect on them, we can understand their
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
