<P>
   GREATNESS-ARTISTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Consensus and the luxury of retrospect
provide a comfortable platform for calling something ``great.'' But
can ``great'' also be used to describe art and artists of our
times? Is it simply too soon to say? Is any opinion on the topic
little more than speculation? Or is it possible that the present
doesn't deserve description in such terms? Maybe greatness abides
in the past because, to paraphrase Norma Desmond, ``Art is great;
it's the artists that got small.'' By JANET TYSON. Story will move
in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LOST &AMP; FOUND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ At this year's ShoWest in Las Vegas, even David Spade
seemed dumbfounded that he was starring in the lightweight,
canine-centric romantic comedy ``Lost &AMP; Found.'' But don't worry,
the former ``Saturday Night Live'' snarkster hasn't gone to the
dogs just yet. Though you'd never know it from the trailers, ``Lost
&AMP; Found'' actually has a number of funny moments that don't involve
animal-based sight gags. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-METROLAND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The new animated television series ``Family Guy'' is
an object lesson in trying too hard. A recent episode featured
three flashbacks in the first five minutes. Something similar
happens in the movie ``Metroland,'' which stars Christian Bale in a
'70s-style shag haircut that looks so heavy you wonder how he keeps
his head up. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The Information Age is about 30 years old, so why are
we still covered in a sea of paperwork? Because we're not using the
tools in front of our face, says Bill Gates, creator and chief
executive of the dominate leader in computer toolmaking, Microsoft.
By TERESA MCUSIC. Story has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ It is unfortunate that modern, civilized men and women
have become too sophisticated to speak seriously of demon
possession or to describe acts of unspeakable horror as
manifestations of evil incarnated. If that were not so, it would be
so much easier to explain the ethnic cleansing in Kosovo, the
Rwandan genocidal rampage, the hideousness of the killing and
mutilating in Sierra Leone, Saddam Hussein and the massacre of the
innocents at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. By CECIL
JOHNSON. Story has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
