<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, April 23. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN (Littleton, Colo.) - The snow fell all through
Thursday morning, smudging the ink of a thousand scrawled messages,
bending the roses and the carnations beneath its weight. Slush
covered a family of teddy bears. Footprints tracked every which
way. By mid-morning, the park bordering Columbine High School felt
shrouded, even more obscured. As the story of the school does with
each passing day. By DAVID LEIBOWITZ. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BROTHER-SCHOOL (Phoenix) - The brother of an Arizona Cardinals
player is a teacher at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. He
knew and tought since junior high the two kids responsible for the
killings. His classroom is next door to the library so he knows
exactly where things happened when people describle them. The good
news for him is that he is on a monthlong sabbatical. By STEVE
SCHOENFELD. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
OUTCASTS-SCHOOL (Phoenix) - They're the kids whom the athletes, the
popular kids, don't want to deal with and sometimes taunt. Who are
these kids, what do they have to deal with? By JULIE AMPARANO.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KELLY-SCHOOL (Phoenix) - Kelly Fleming was an aspiring songwriter
and author who wrote scores of poems and short stories based on her
life experiences. She was well-liked by teachers and friends at
Desert Sky Middle School in Phoenix before she moved to Littleton
18 months ago. On Thursday she was being eulogized, one of the
vicitims in the Littleton massacre. By LORI BAKER and BRENT
WHITING. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KIDSGUNS-SCHOOL (Phoenix) - After the mayhem, there is always
hand-wringing. People want to know what went wrong in Littleton,
Colo., or Phoenix, Ariz. What could have been done to prevent the
slaughter of 12 students and a teacher by teenage outcasts, or the
killing of a cop by a 17-year-old gangbanger? One of the answers,
invariably, has to do with guns. How do kids get them? Would
tougher gun-control laws make a differnce? Do guns kill people, or
boys? The argument, as bloody rhetorical as a shootout, ricochets
from the NRA to Handgun Control Inc., from barber shops to talk
shows. By DENNIS WAGNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ARM-SCHOOL (Phoenix) - We find out how easy it is for law-abiding
citizens orbad guys to buy high-powered weaponry, explosives, body
armor, etc. inthe Phoenix area. By WILLIAM HERMANN. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUMMER-MUSIC (Phoenix) - In December, singer and sometime actress
Cree Summer opened for Lenny Kravitz on his European tour. In many
ways, she considers it one of the most terrifying experiences in
her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights would go black,'' Summer recalls, on the phone from
her home in the Hollywood Hills. ``Like 15,000 people in the
audience think Lenny is coming out. Then here I come, and everybody
is like, `Who the (expletive) is that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   History probably won't repeat itself in Phoenix next week, when
Summer does the honors again for the recent Grammy winner. By RANDY
CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GENERAL-MOVIE (Phoenix) A small Irish working-class film buried
under all the technical glitz and glamor of a Hollywood epic, John
Boorman's look at famous Dublin criminal Martin Cahill is overlong,
way too pretty and ultimately aimless, despite some excellent
acting by Brendan Gleeson (Braveheart) and Jon Voight. 3 stars. By
RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PUSHING-MOVIE (Phoenix) - John Cusack and Billy Bob Thornton are
rival air traffic controllers in a comic-drama about how the air
traffic control system is out of control because the control freaks
running it are too apt to crack under the stress. Good point, but
the movie plays like a magazine article, neither dramatic nor comic
enough to make a good movie. 2 stars. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved
in the ``E' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EXISTENZ-MOVIE (Phoenix) - An action/adventure thriller in which
Jennifer Jason Leigh stars as a computer programmer who creates a
virtual-reality game that taps into theplayers' minds. 2 stars. By
BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - The Corvette hardtop is a lighter, tighter,
racier and marginally cheaper version of Chevrolet's brawny sports
car. It's a sportier version, compared with the coupe and
convertible, but its power accessories, comfort features and most
of the price tag remain intact. It's tuned in to drivers primarily
interested in performance, and is available only with a six-speed
stick shift, beefier suspension and a limited-slip differential. By
BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category. EMBARGOED FOR
SATURDAY, APRIL 24. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
