<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9483 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT-HNS &LR;      04-22 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO ESCALATE ATTACKS ON SITES FREQUENTED BY MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL and ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana vowed Thursday to escalate allied attacks against sites
frequented by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the western alliance's three-day summit here,
Clinton and Solana underscored NATO's determination to step up the
bombing. They spoke after a meeting that set the stage for the
summit that will include not only leaders of the 19 nations in the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization but also officials from 23 other
countries associated with it.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders, initially planning to celebrate the 50th
anniversary of the alliance that was forged at the start of the
Cold War, are now assessing the effectiveness of NATO's first
military operation against a sovereign country. And they are
weighing a possible invasion of Kosovo by allied ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Thursday that it was ``wise and prudent'' for the
alliance to update its six-month-old plan to invade Yugoslavia. The
original plan foresaw an invasion force of up to 200,000 ground
troops, including 75,000 sent into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Solana ordered the update on Wednesday before leaving Brussels
for the summit. Clinton said the update did not signal a decision
to send allied ground forces into Kosovo but was a way of getting
ready to do so if such a decision is made.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces growing allied pressure from Britain and France _
as well as some in the United States _ to consider using ground
troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The president said allied attacks that began March 24 will
continue until Milosevic orders Yugoslav forces out of Kosovo, the
1.4 million uprooted ethnic Albanian Kosvars are permitted to
return to their homes, an international security force enters
Kosovo and ethnic Albanians are free to pursue self-government in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic can accept this outcome or he can watch as NATO
grinds down his war machine and the Serb people he claims to
represent face mounting hardship,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   The president pointedly noted that allied attacks since Tuesday
night have targeted a home used by Milosevic and his Serbian
Socialist Party headquarters. Clinton insisted that the attacks are
not targeting Milosevic personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this conflict it would be wrong and unfair not to target
the command and control operations,'' Clinton said, including the
home and the party headquarters in that category. He added that
allied attacks are increasingly focusing on Yugoslav ``facilities
used to incite and direct'' ethnic repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Solana, the Spanish diplomat who serves as the chief executive
of the NATO alliance, echoed Clinton's resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance will use the summit to ``signal our determination
to intensify the political and military pressure on Belgrade until
our goals are met,'' Solana said. ``We have the means and we have
the will.''
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said during a meeting with
senators on Capitol Hill that ``we shall remain with this action
and intensify it until we see it through.''
</P>
<P>
   The three leaders spoke as first reports reached the White House
of a possible diplomatic gesture in Belgrade. Former Russian
Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin emerged from a day-long meeting with
Milosevic to report that the Serbian leader had accepted the
concept of a United Nations-controlled ``international presence''
in Kosovo in return for NATO halting the bombing campaign and the
alliance withdrawing troops from Yugoslavia's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed warily receptive to the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an offer for a genuine security force, that's the
first time that Mr. Milosevic has ever done that, and that
represents, I suppose, some step forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has shied away from dubbing Milosevic a war
criminal, reiterated that the United States would accept the
Serbian dictator remaining in power if he agreed to allied
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he meets those conditions, and the Serbian people are
willing to continue him in power, then I could imagine such an
outcome,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the United States nor NATO has insisted that Milosevic
step down in order to reach an agreement, Clinton noted.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger conceded that
the gathering of allied leaders had become a de facto council of
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had planned a summit that focused a bit on the past and a
great deal on the future,'' Berger said, adding that the summit had
become ``a working meeting of a military alliance in the middle of
a conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Wednesday by the Pew Research Center for the
People and the Press found that nearly two thirds of Americans
believe that ground troops will be needed to resolve the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number _ 66 percent _ are worried the fight over
Kosovo will cause U.S. casualties. The figure has risen by 10
percentage points in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the summit would be the largest gathering of
foreign dignitaries ever in the nation's capital _ surpassing even
the number attending President John F. Kennedy's funeral in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO summit was to have been a triumphant weekend of
diplomatic pomp, glass-clinking and banquets of roasted lamb marked
with speeches commemorating NATO successes.
</P>
<P>
   With tulips, dogwoods and azaleas exploding in hues of pink, red
and white across the city, a planned highlight was to have been the
welcoming of Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic, the three new
NATO members that once were aligned with the Soviet Union, the
alliance's vanquished foe.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the gathering takes place in a tense capital blanketed
with heavy security, and the festivities have been recast into more
serious discussions as the alliance confronted the crisis in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Washington braced for limousine gridlock and tight restrictions
in a 100-block downtown security zone, including much of the
National Mall. City schools were to be closed Friday and thousands
of federal workers were given the day off.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders are scheduled to hold a three-hour meeting on
Kosovo Friday morning at the Ronald Reagan International Trade
Center, next to the Andrew Mellon Auditorium, where the original
NATO treaty was signed 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, five blocks east of the White House, is to be
attended by the leaders of the 19 NATO countries and military
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are concerned that strains may develop within the
alliance as the war effort drags into a second month and NATO
presses ahead with plans for a ground war, a naval blockade of
Yugoslavia or increased economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Greece have expressed concern over a U.S. suggestion
to blockade Yugoslavia and step up sanctions to deny Milosevic the
ability to resupply and refuel his military forces.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to decisions on Kosovo, the NATO leaders are
expected to revamp the mission of the military alliance, originally
geared to defend against a Soviet attack.
</P>
<P>
   A new ``strategic concept'' is expected to be adopted, laying
out broad guidelines for dispatching NATO troops around Europe to
areas like Kosovo or Bosnia that threaten stability in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
