<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning three pages of stories, photos
and graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo and the NATO summit
meeting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-KOSOVO (Washington) _ Lede-all on events in Washington on
the NATO meeting, with the Kosovo campaign dominating discussion.
President Clinton and Javier Solana, the NATO secretary-general,
confer and then meet with the press. Tony Blair, the British prime
minister, and others meet congressman at the Capitol. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-CREATION (Washington) _ The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, whose 50th anniversary will be ceremonially
commemorated by the leaders of its 19 member nations here this
weekend, was the brainchild of a portly, rough-hewn former trade
union leader with a grade-school education, the illegitimate son of
a serving-girl. His name was Ernest Bevin, and he was Britain's
foreign secretary. R.W. Apple talks to some of those who were
present at the creation of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ A month into NATO's war against
Yugoslavia, American cruise missiles destroyed one of President
Slobodan Milosevic's official residences in Belgrade early Thursday
in a direct strike at the core of Milosevic's power. The Pentagon
warned that more attacks were coming. Yugoslavia denounced the
strike as an assassination attempt, while American and NATO
officials denied their intent was to kill Milosevic. They defended
the target as a legitimate attack on the military leadership of
Yugoslavia, if not him directly, effectively a distinction without
a difference. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS-ASSESS (Brussels) _ A military analysis: From the
military's point of view, planning for ground troops won't
accomplish much. What's needed to have a force ready by July or
August is putting the force together now: calling people up,
signing basing agreements, starting to move equipment. And if NATO
waits much longer it could miss any chance of having a force able
to go in before winter. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ In the Yugoslav
capital: The scene after Milosevic's home is attacked, with Serbs
saying it was an assassination attempt. The Yugoslav information
minister says 517 civilians have been killed and more than 4,000
seriously hurt since campaign began. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Viktor Cherynomyrdin, the Russian
special envoy, meets with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslavia
president; is expected to return to Russia tonight. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Lisec, Macedonia) _ Some 130,000 ethnic
Albanians have poured into Macedonia from Kosovo during this last
month. While 50,000 of them are temporarily housed in refugee
camps, most of the rest have found shelter in private homes. By
Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ A month of war in Europe has already
brought deep changes to the continent, turning the anti-war
generation of 1968 into some of the firmest advocates of military
force, rekindling tensions over ``American imperialism,'' and
reviving the sagging fortunes of some leaders. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VETS (Washington) _ A generation ago, John Kerry, a
decorated navy lieutenant, came home to lead protests against the
Vietnam war he had served in. Max Cleland, a young Army captain
lost his legs and an arm when he reached for a loose grenade that
exploded. Chuck Hagel, an Army sergeant, fought and was wounded
alongside his brother. John McCain, a navy pilot, was shot down,
imprisoned and tortured in Hanoi. Now as Congress grapples with
Kosovo, and Vietnam-era words and phrases like ''quagmire' and
''fighting with one hand tied behind the back'' resonate once
again, these Vietnam combat veterans in the Senate and two more _
Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Charles S. Robb of Virginia _ speak with
the special authority of experience. But the vexing questions of
this war have pulled them in different directions. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   This story, budgeted earlier, is now scratched:
</P>
<P>
   NATO-CLINTON, which has been rechristened NATO-KOVOSO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA.
