<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CLINTON-0423-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDENTS ADVISE CLINTON ON SCHOOL VIOLENCE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ High school students gave President Clinton an
earful Thursday on what adults should do to avert tragedies like
the one in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting down with 30 students at a Virginia suburban high
school, the president conceded that many of the solutions were
``beyond anything government can do.'' A recent White House
conference on violence in schools plus more federal aid for school
counselors and security has not halted the violence, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rampage that resulted in 15 deaths at Littleton's Columbine
High School on Tuesday was the seventh such incident since a
student killed his mother and then nine schoolmates in Pearl,
Miss., 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In his first extended response to the horror in Colorado,
Clinton visited T.C. Williams High School in Alexandria. A school
of some 2,000 students representing dozens of nationalities and
diverse racial groups, Williams has a large staff of counselors,
plus a hotline for students to report trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Several told Clinton that if violence could erupt at a place
like Littleton, it could anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know, when is the government -- when are you --
going to do something for the other students out there?'' Jonelle
Mitchell, a senior, asked the president.
</P>
<P>
   She praised her school for a system in which students mediate
conflicts among their peers. But she said that other schools
``don't have the resources that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Other students pointed to families as the root of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what we're missing are morals,'' Sindy (cq)
Benavides said. ``Mr. President, I think that one thing that my
parents taught me is that, like a tree, you form it when it's
little, and how you form it when it's little, it comes up right.''
</P>
<P>
   One student, John Chuico, asked how it is that information about
how to build bombs is freely published on the Internet. ``What is
our government doing to prevent this ...dangerous information, you
know, so that they don't make bombs and they don't blow people up
and they don't hurt people?''
</P>
<P>
   Another pointed to the murder and mayhem depicted in movies and
in video games.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who spent much of the hourlong discussion
listening, acknowledged that ``we do have more violence among
younger people in America than other cultures.'' He added that
``everyone has to take a hard look at what all the elements of our
society are that contribute to that and what we can do to diminish
it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he called curbs on the Internet too difficult to
administer and chose not to criticize the entertainment industry.
``I don't want to blame the movies or blame the video games,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who only recently emerged from an impeachment battle
involving his relationship with a former White House intern, ducked
the invitation to discuss morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with that,'' he told the student who called for
parents to stress morals. ``But what happens if all of that still
doesn't work because young people at some point develop a whole
other life? `` the president asked. He said he preferred to stress
the need for ``early warning'' systems, such as school hotlines,
for reporting potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also related the problems of schoolyard taunts and
ridicule to his own experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in what I do and the people I deal with, it's amazing how
much energy is lost and how many things are not done for America
because people in Washington, D.C., at the highest levels of power
and influence, get hurt by what other people say about them --
mean, bad things other people say about them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the president, whose own tirades have been chronicled
by former aides, said he hoped that the students would follow the
T.C. Williams practice of working out their disputes by discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be amazed how many people my age, in very responsible
positions, still can't manage their anger because they never
learned to have a constructive way to talk about it,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
