<HEADER>
A9496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ROCKETS-0423-C     04-22 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ROCKETS-0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMY SOLDIER REFLECTS ON THE COMING BATTLE: ``IT'S NOT A NICE
THING''
 &HT;    EDs: AP Photo of Hoover is available.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ As he prepares to launch the U.S.
Army's most lethal anti-personnel rockets into Kosovo, Staff
Sergeant Robert Hoover sometimes thinks about the Serb soldiers in
his target zone.
</P>
<P>
   And about the ethnic Albanian refugees in Kosovo that the Serbs
might be holding as human shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir, it's not a nice thing,'' said Hoover, 29, of Twin
Falls, Idaho, the fire direction chief for an MLRS (Multiple Rocket
Launch System) mobile launcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have confidence that the right people above me will make
the right decisions,'' said Hoover, who fights his battles from a
computer terminal inside the cab of his launcher.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover belongs to Charley Battery, 1/27 Field Artillery that
flew in about four days ago from Badenhausen, Germany. His launcher
is a big green military truck with what looks like a giant
cigarette pack resting on the flat bed. Inside the box are six
rockets, each about 13 feet long without their warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Charley Battery's job here is to serve as the remote-control
bodyguards for the slow-flying 24 Apache helicopter gunships when
they start attacking Serb tanks and guns -- which could begin
within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Apaches are easy to spot on enemy radar. If the American
commanders get intelligence of a Serb anti-aircraft crew getting
ready to shoot down an Apache, it will be Charley Battery's
responsibility to ``suppress'' those Serbs before they can get off
a fatal shot.
</P>
<P>
   In case anyone needs a translation of the military verb ``to
suppress,'' it means anything from scaring their pants off to
blowing them into little pieces. With an MLRS, it's likely to be
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   To Charley Battery, it really doesn't matter, so long as the
Apache and its two-man crew flies back to this base unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, Charley Battery has been practicing to
help protect the first attacks of the Apaches on Serb tanks,
artillery guns and troops concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rehearse battle drills of what our assigned mission will
be,'' explained Charley Battery's executive officer, 1st Lt.
Cecilio Coleman, 31, of Virginia Beach, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Based on how MLRS mobile launchers functioned during the Gulf
War, the launcher crew moves almost at the last minute to a forward
firing position. That's where Charley Battery will await a radioed
``fire mission'' from an operations officer somewhere at a battle
headquarters in the rear. The crew takes a reading on a Global
Positioning System (GPS) satellite to set its firing position.
</P>
<P>
   It may be only a few minutes before the ``fire mission'' is
ordered. Once this happens, crew members including Hoover will
punch in the coordinates of the target and adjust the altitude of
the desired blast.
</P>
<P>
   But there will also be hours of tedium when the battle is
unfolding and the command center cannot identify any targets for
the MLRS. ``We take every possible precaution to minimize any
collateral damage,'' said Capt. Martin Downie, a U.S. Army
spokesman for ``Task Force Hawk'' commander, Lt. Gen. John Hendrix
.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the shots fired by the 1/27 Field Artillery in the first
few days of Apache attacks are likely to be MLRS rockets. During
the Gulf War, these fired at targets out to about 30 miles.
</P>
<P>
   For targets further out, the MLRS units here are also capable of
firing a longer-range and more accurate weapon called the Army
Tactical Missile System, known by its phonetic acronym
``Attack-Ems.'' The latest version of ``Attack-Ems'' is a guided
missile that carries 950 cluster bomblets and shoots out to a range
of more than 180 miles.
</P>
<P>
   By putting Hoover and Coleman on display for a hoard of media,
the Army was increasing the psychological pressure on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's frontline soldiers and officers.
Army officers said privately that they believe that Milosevic and
many in the top military command are regular followers of CNN, BBC
and other Western news outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Especially since Wednesday's neatly choreographed arrival of the
first Appache helicopters, the U.S. military appears to be stepping
up its psychological warfare campaign to soften up the crews of
Serb air defenses. This parallels what happened before the start of
the ground war in the Gulf, when the U.S. forces dropped leaflets
over front-line troops that helped to encourage mass surrenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some of the best equipment in the world, and the best
people,'' said Hoover, one of a half-dozen soldiers chosen by
senior commanders to present the human face of ``Task Force Hawk''
strike force to journalists. ``We come here to do a mission, and
we're going to do it to the best of our ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are capable of firing any time,'' said Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Foreign correspondent Joseph Albright was a pool
correspondent with an Army MLRS unit during Operation Desert Storm
in Iraq in 1991.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
