<HEADLINE>
UNH'S BOWES RETIRES; MCDONNELL NAMED TO POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ It started with a 16-14 win over Boston
University Sept. 23, 1972, and it ended Nov. 14 with a 9-7 win over
Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   University of New Hampshire football coach Bill Bowes called it
quits Thursday after 27 years at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   At a Whittemore Center press conference announcing his
retirement, athletic director Judy Ray also announced that
offensive coordinator Sean McDonnell was the new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell, 43, played defensive back under Bowes and graduated
in 1978. He has been an assistant at Hamilton College, Boston
University, Boston College and Columbia, and returned to UNH as an
assistant in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Bowes said he long ago set a goal for himself: if he could
afford to do it, he would retire at age 55. Thanks to UNH's
retirement plan, Bowes said, he could afford it and now plans to
spend much more time with his family and pursuing interests such as
golf and fishing than being a football coach allows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked my tail off all my life and I turned 55 and I want to
be able to smell the roses a little bit,'' Bowes said. ``That's
something I always patterned my life around. When I got to that
certain age, I was going to slow down and that's one thing you
can't do in this profession, you can't slow down. It's not fair to
the school or to the program.''
</P>
<P>
   He told Ray and president Joan Leitzel of his plans last summer,
turned 55 in October, and went through the recruiting season and
the start of spring practice to make sure of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   He has no doubt it's the right move, he said Thursday. He told
his team of his decision Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Bowes played tight end at Penn State and graduated in 1965.
After a year as a graduate assistant at Penn State, he spent two
years as an assistant coach under Joe Yukica and then moved with
him to Boston College. Bowes returned to Durham in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats went 4-5 in each of his first two seasons and then
posted a winning record in 21 of the next 23 seasons. Two years
ago, UNH was 5-6 and last year the Wildcats were 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, UNH was 176-106-5 under Bowes. His teams contended, and
contended well, without the financial resources and facilities of
many of its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't bothered that he is going out on a couple of teams with
losing records, Bowes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never considered myself as one who had a huge ego,'' Bowes
said. ``If I had a huge ego, I might have considered that. Last
year our record wasn't the greatest, but I don't think we were a
bad football team. We came within 1 point of UMass and they won the
national championship. In spite of the record, it was an exciting
year with Jerry Azumah and what not. I'm not going to leave the job
with any remorse. I had enough winning seasons over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray called it a ``happy/sad'' day. She was happy for Bowes, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled through the meeting with the students this
morning,'' Ray said. ``It got harder with the coaches. He's just
such a wonderful person. People wouldn't agree all the time, but
like Sean says, he's tough and he's not approachable some times.
But when you look at all his qualities, it makes it real difficult
to have those qualities leave the institution. It's tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
