<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTUGAL THROWS MASTERPIECE, BUT SOX FALL, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Red Sox may not hit, but at least they're quick
about it.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly less time than it took manager Jimy Williams to
concoct a lineup in which the occupants of slots 3 through 9 had no
home runs this season, the Red Sox fell, 1-0, to the Detroit Tigers
and lefthander Justin Thompson, who got last-inning help from
Tigers closer Todd Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of the game _ 1 hour 49 minutes, the shortest Sox game
in at least two decades, according to the Elias Bureau statmen,
whose records on such matters only go back to 1981 _ was tribute,
too, to the exquisite pitching of Sox starter Mark Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal set down 19 straight Tiger batters, only to throw a
first-pitch fastball to Dartmouth's Brad Ausmus that Ausmus drove
over the right-field wall in Tiger Stadium with two outs in the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just try to make sure you don't make a mistake to beat
you,'' said Portugal, a loser for the first time in three starts
despite giving up just three hits and no walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two outs, I thought Ausmus would take a pitch. I tried to
get ahead of him. I was trying to keep him in the big part of the
ballpark, so I threw him a fastball away, but he went out and hit
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this park has a history of being friendly to balls hit
over the right-field fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox initiated little action hostile to Thompson, who had
a no-hitter until Damon Buford beat out a ball that he topped in
front of the plate to start the fifth. Thompson didn't allow
another hit until Donnie Sadler hit a ball off his fists into right
field for a bloop single to open the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Tigers manager Larry Parrish went to the bullpen for Jones.
Williams, whose 13th different lineup in 15 games was an
all-righthanded affair featuring Lou Merloni at first, Sadler in
left, and Creighton Gubanich making his big-league debut behind the
plate, countered with Reggie Jefferson to bat for Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson hit a smash, but right at shortstop Deivi Cruz, who
turned a double play, and Jose Offerman tapped out to second to end
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it hard, but as soon as I looked up, I saw it was right
at him,'' Jefferson said. ``Four feet either way, and he has no
chance for it. But he got to him so quick, I could see I had no
chance. That's what happens when you can't get a break.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox sent only 28 batters to the plate Thursday, one over the
minimum. Mike Stanley, who went hitless in two at-bats and is now 0
for 18, walked to start the second, but the next two batters,
Buford and Merloni, struck out, and Gubanich popped to second.
</P>
<P>
   Gubanich hit into a double play to erase Buford in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   No Red Sox runner advanced as far as second base on a cool, damp
day conducive to pitching, especially with the wind blowing in.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, it seems, it could be 85 degrees with gale-force
winds blowing out from home plate, and the Sox still wouldn't hit.
After opening the season with four straight games of 10 or more
hits, the Sox have reached double digits just once in the last 11
games, and are batting .205 in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has grown progressively worse. They scored three
runs in three games here, winning only by a 1-0 score Tuesday night
behind Pedro Martinez. They've scored two or fewer runs in seven of
their last eight games, a stretch in which they've gone 2-6 and
batted a collective .197. Only three times in those games have they
had as many as two consecutive hits in an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling thunder, they're not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that in the time I've been here, this has never
happened,'' said Jefferson, who has been with the team since 1995
and couldn't recall a time when essentially everyone stopped
hitting at the same time. ``It's odd, too, because we have some
pretty sound hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, we're definitely not going to be the '27 Yankees, but
we shouldn't be scuffling this bad.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a name for such a phenomenon: It's called the no-Mo
effect. Take away Vaughn, the team's only legitimate slugger _
Nomar Garciaparra hits home runs, but he's not your prototypical
basher _ and there's a ripple effect that hasn't taken long to
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra has two singles in his last 13 at-bats. John
Valentin didn't have a hit in 10 at-bats in Detroit, and is 0 for
his last 15 overall. The rookie, Trot Nixon, is buried on the bench
with an 0 for 21 hanging on him. Stanley has two RBIs in his last
11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Nixon, these are all proven hitters. None of them are
seeing much to hit these days. There's no Vaughn in the heart of
the lineup to keep pitchers honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we look at it as though we're in a funk,''
Valentin said. ``I think the way our team is set up, we're going to
be pitched differently. Knowing that, we still are professionals,
we still have to hit the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what these guys feel, but from my
perspective, I think we're going to hit. But this is a different
team this year. We're going to have a lot of battles like this.
We've got more young guys playing. This is a new experience for
them. We're asking them to hit, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Give it time, Portugal said bravely, the hitting will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team can hit,'' he said. ``I don't think anybody in this
room doubts that we can hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season, you can't judge a team on the first three
weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
