<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9500 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-ART-N     04-22 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE MISSILES DESTROY ONE OF MILOSEVIC'S RESIDENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: An expanded version will be filed later this evening.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic of is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A month into NATO's war against Yugoslavia, U.S.
cruise missiles destroyed one of President Slobodan Milosevic's
official residences in Belgrade, and the Pentagon and NATO vowed to
launch more attacks at the core of his power and control.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia denounced the strike as an assassination attempt, but
U.S. and NATO officials denied that the attack was a deliberate
attempt to kill Milosevic. They defended the target as a legitimate
assault on the military leadership of Yugoslavia, though not on him
directly, effectively a distinction without a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the White House with NATO's secretary general,
Javier Solana, on the eve of NATO's 50th anniversary summit,
President Clinton said the alliance had an obligation to pursue the
power structure that Milosevic uses to command the forces that have
driven hundreds of thousands of Albanians from the province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this conflict,'' the president said, ``it would be wrong
and unfair not to target the command and control operations as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and his family were not in the residence, Yugoslav
officials said, when four cruise missiles fired from warships in
the Adriatic Sea struck with thunderous blows about 4 a.m. in
Belgrade. By Thursday afternoon, Milosevic appeared on Yugoslavia's
state-run television at a meeting with Viktor Chernomyrdin,
Russia's newest envoy to the Balkans, at another presidential
residence nearby, called Beli Dvor, or White Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The images from that meeting juxtaposed those of the destruction
at Milosevic's villa on Uzicka Street in Dedinje, an exclusive
section of the Yugoslav capital where many diplomatic compounds are
situated, including the residence of the U.S. ambassador.
Yugoslavia's former leader, Josip Broz Tito, lived in the villa,
and his mausoleum is on the grounds, though evidently far enough
away that it was not damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes on Thursday strikes came just one day after NATO
forces blasted a 23-story office tower in Belgrade that housed the
political parties of Milosevic and his wife, as well as several
radio and television stations, including one owned by their
daughter. These attacks signaled an expansion of NATO's efforts to
undercut the political and economic pillars that Milosevic has
relied on in more than 11 years of rule.
</P>
<P>
   The air assault continued with new ferocity Thursday, the 30th
day of NATO's bombing campaign. The Yugoslav news agency, Tanjug,
reported new missile strikes around Pristina and villages in
southern Serbia. NATO aircraft again attacked a bridge in
Yugoslavia's second largest city, Novi Sad, after discovering
workers trying to repair damage from two previous strikes. [Updates
as warranted)
</P>
<P>
   ``We are targeting the head of this military regime on the one
hand,'' the Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said Thursday.
``We're trying to cut that off and break the central nervous
system, the central command and control system of the regime. And
we're also attacking the feet of the regime on the ground in
Kosovo, the feet that are being used to stamp out, or attempt to
stamp out, the Kosovar Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the United States and its NATO allies agreed to review
contingency plans for the possible use of ground forces to rout
Yugoslav forces from Kosovo, the Pentagon offered one of its most
detailed assessments to date of the damage being inflicted on
Yugoslavia's military and police forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
