<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-DISSIDENTS-B     04-22 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-DISSIDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISTS PROTEST BARRING OF 11 CHINESE DISSIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Democracy activists Thursday slammed Hong Kong for
barring entry to 11 Chinese dissidents, accusing the local
government of political censorship and of undermining Hong Kong's
autonomy from mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   The exiled dissidents, including Harvard University student Wang
Dan, leader of the 1989 student movement in Beijing's Tiananmen
Square, had applied to attend a seminar here next month on reform
movements in China.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 democracy activists and local university students
marched to the office of Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa
Thursday, waving banners and shouting slogans. Ten of the barred
dissidents, including the long-jailed Wei Jingsheng, live in exile
in the United States. One lives in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every reason to be concerned over this erosion of
freedoms of expression and cultural exchange that Hong Kong has
enjoyed over the years,'' declared Albert Ho, a Democratic Party
legislator and one of the organizers of next month's conference.
``Hong Kong's reputation as a free, international city is now
tarnished _ a warning bell has been sounded.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference will mark the 80th anniversary of the May 4th
student movement and the 10th anniversary of the June 4th massacre
in which hundreds, or perhaps thousands, of demonstrators were
killed by Chinese troops.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong officials denied there had been pressure from Beijing
to reject the applicants, and said the decision was based on
established policies.
</P>
<P>
   Ho said if that were true, ``it's even more deplorable that
government is doing something to fetter its own discretion'' and to
avoid irritating Beijing at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   Dissident Wang Dan, whom Beijing branded the ``most-wanted''
student leader after the 1989 Tiananmen crackdown, said in a
telephone interview from his Somerville home that he was ``very
disappointed'' to be barred from Hong Kong. Wang, who was
imprisoned six years, but paroled on medical grounds to the United
States before President Clinton visited Beijing last year, is
subject to reimprisonment if he returns to mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Wang said Hong Kong's refusal to allow him to visit made him
``worried about the future of Hong Kong under `one country, two
systems.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Britain returned Hong Kong to China after 156
years of colonial rule, Beijing's Communist leaders promised to
abide by ``one country, two systems,'' an arrangement allowing Hong
Kong to keep its ``capitalist system and way of life'' for 50
years. Hong Kong was guaranteed autonomy in all matters except
defense and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   China made it clear before the handover, however, that Hong Kong
could not be used as a base for ``subversive activities'' that
promote the overthrow of China's Communist system. The Hong Kong
Alliance in Support of the Patriotic Democratic Movements in China,
which is sponsoring next month's seminar, is considered subversive
by Beijing, but has been allowed to continue operating.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Tam, a spokesman for the Hong Kong Immigration Department,
said visa approvals are based on ``the intention of a visit,
whether the person is coming to Hong Kong as a visitor and not to
work, if such person is an undesirable . . . and also if the person
has any previous record as a criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Many mainland dissidents are considered ``subversives'' and
criminals under Chinese law. But Hong Kong and China have separate
criminal codes, and a convict in China is not necessarily a
criminal here, nor would he or she automatically be denied a
visitor's visa, Tam said. Tam denied that there was a lifetime ban
on any dissident or a blacklist, saying anyone could reapply.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Beijing legislator Tsang Yok-sing defended the government,
saying it had to consider ``stability'' and possible disruptions
caused by visiting activists. Conference organizers said the
dissidents had no intention of causing trouble or staying for June
4th memorial demonstrations in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Ho said the Alliance had been given hope by immigration
officials in three meetings that at least some of the visas would
be granted. Several of the dissidents had been here before the
handover. ``There was no reason other than political
considerations'' to keep them out now, Ho said.
</P>
<P>
   In the months before the 1997 handover, several mainland exiles
left Hong Kong for fear they might not be safe or able to advocate
for democracy here. Prominent labor activist Han Dongfang has
remained, but China revoked his citizenship so he cannot enter the
mainland to organize trade unions.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the handover, Boston-based Chai Ling, another
leader of the 1989 Tiananmen movement, visited Hong Kong, but has
not tried to return since.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of the 11 visa applications is believed to be the
first time since the handover that mainland dissidents have
attempted to visit Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Cheuk-yan, a Frontier party legislator, criticized the
timing of visa rejections; they were announced just after Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji left Canada, saving Zhu embarrassment over the
incident while in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the alliance would invite dissident Wang Dan's mother,
who became a vocal advocate for her son when he was in prison, to
attend the conference on his behalf. It will be up to Hong Kong
immigration officials whether to allow entry to Wang Linyun, a
researcher at Beijing's Revolutionary History Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clear political censorship, and it will tarnish the
image of Hong Kong,'' Lee complained. ``Maybe they don't care about
image anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators Thursday delivered a protest letter to Tung _ plus
two tickets and an invitation to their May conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
