<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAD-WHALE-BOS &LR;      04-22 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-WHALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD WHALE HAD BROKEN JAW, SUGGESTING IMPACT WITH VESSEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dead right whale undergoing an autopsy on a Wellfleet, Mass.
beach had a fractured right jaw, scientists discovered Thursday,
providing the first evidence that the endangered animal could have
been struck by a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Ship strikes are the leading human-induced cause of death among
right whales, the world's most endangered whale species.
</P>
<P>
   However, federal officials in charge of the autopsy stressed
that the broken jaw could have resulted from a collision with
another whale or other causes, and might not have been a fatal
injury. They say it might take weeks to figure out what killed the
animal, nicknamed Staccato.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't rule out ship strike. I can't rule out disease. I
can't rule out anything,'' said Douglas Beach of the National
Marine Fisheries Service after crews spent two days cutting open
Staccato's carcass to look for clues to her demise.
</P>
<P>
   Even a single dead right whale worries biologists because only
about 300 of the animals remain, but Staccato's death was
particularly painful because she had borne six calves over the past
25 years, making her one of the species' most prolific breeders.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the National Marine Fisheries Service was eager to
study Staccato, paying to have her carcass towed ashore from five
miles offshore. But the autopsy has so far produced ambiguous
results, including tongue ulcers that could indicate a virus that
is fatal in some whales.
</P>
<P>
   Staccato's carcass was reported floating off Wellfleet's Great
Island on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
