<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S SO AWFUL ABOUT CELL PHONES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you start to grind your teeth at the sight and sound of a
fellow bus passenger or pedestrian yakking into a cell phone, your
annoyance is not inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   Literary critic  &UR; Sven Birkerts &LR; , a professor at Mount Holyoke
College, shared his analysis of the problem with the New York
Observer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are holding the thing and talking into it,'' Birkerts
told the weekly, ``then the line of intimacy or connection goes to
the person you're talking to, and it kind of eliminates the
physical space that you're in, and it kind of insults the other
people in that space. It's hard to put a finger on, but I'm aware
of it as an insult.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Birkerts, ``The people who use them adopt a body
language of extreme secrecy and intimacy. It gives the impression
to the person on the street that `something really important here
is happening that I'm not a part of, that it's so important that it
can't wait for him to be in a quiet place,' and that makes what I'M
doing seem really trivial.''
</P>
<P>
   When people talk on cell phones, he said, the place with which
they're connected ``is brought into the picture. It's like this
collapsing of all geographies into one place. ... It has,
philosophically at least, the effect of neutering your own
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Los Angeles magazine puts ``parking your own car'' on its
``What's Now'' list.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Zubin Mehta &LR;  forgot his suspenders when he conducted the
Philharmonic Orchestra of Israel at Buckingham Palace, so  &UR; Prince &LR; 
 &UR; Philip &LR;  let him borrow a pair. ``And before he could even return
them with a thank-you note,'' says W, ``one of Philip's assistants
asked for the suspenders back.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Chris English &LR;  forwards a Morning Sydney Herald report citing
a South African newspaper: ``The Kenyan government has set a
deadline of April 2000 for a report on preparations for the
millennium bug.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tina Sinatra &LR;  goes on the Home Shopping Network on A &LR; pril
29 &LR; to sell an $18 ``collector gift set'' that includes a  &UR; Frank &LR; 
 &UR; Sinatra &LR;  CD, an array of photos and a glass cylinder containing a
candle, decorated with a picture of her father. Sales are to
benefit the Frank Sinatra Foundation, reports People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three kissing pointers from All About You! magazine:
``Remember to breathe''; ``No passing gum or candy back and
forth''; ``If you mess up, keep going and it will fix itself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ladies' Home Journal tested a chain hotel room, a luxury hotel
room and a room in a bed and breakfast and found germs, germs and
more germs. Never mind the obvious toilet seats, pillowcases,
telephones _ you may be exposed to germs before you even reach the
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a heavy growth of two kinds of bacteria on this key
card, including yeast _ Rhodotorula rubra,'' said the magazine
about an electronic door opener in a luxury hotel. As for an
old-fashioned key, used in a B&AMP;B, the perils are even worse: ``Home
to an unhealthy dose of three different types of bacteria. ... A
metal key has crevices in which germs can hibernate.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Begley &LR;  saw a VW in the Mission District  &LR; of San
Francisco  &LR; with a dimple in its rear, above which was written, by
hand, ``El Dente.'' In other vehicular news,  &UR; Howard Bennett &LR; , just
back from Hilo, is wondering why gas is only $1.55 a gallon there
when it's $1.75 in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maxim magazine says you'll win more coin tosses by calling
tails, &LR;  because the heads side of a coin ``weighs infinitesimally
more.'' In 10,000 tosses, tails comes up about 50 more times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIVIC CENTER MYSTERY  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Who painted a 20-by-40-foot dollar sign on the roof of the Bill
Graham Civic Auditorium at the Civic Center? A lawyer attending a
meeting high up in the nearby California State Automobile
Association building noticed it early this week.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain the sign, an auditorium administrator said it
was the first he knew of it. He theorized that the tagger
responsible had reached the roof by climbing up a fire escape on
the outside of the building, but he couldn't say how long it had
been there.
</P>
<P>
   Moving with lightning speed _ will someone put this civil
servant, who requested anonymity, in charge of Lotta's Fountain? _
he had it painted over by the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Did a tagger climb the fire escape, or was the sign painted by
aliens leaning out the windows of flying saucers? Who done it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Hopper playing golf is one of the first signs of the
apocalypse. It's true _ he's become a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kris Kristofferson in Esquire magazine
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
