<SLUG> BC-LEONE-ARMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN TO TRAIN NEW ARMY FOR SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Britain's military role in Africa, a relic of
its colonial past, has been revived with London's decision to train
a new army for the tiny West African country of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   After nine years of brutal civil war in the former British
colony, the government of Prime Minister Tony Blair has concluded
that greater foreign intervention is needed to rescue the country's
elected leader, Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, from defeat by one of Africa's
most ruthless rebel groups. Widespread defections to the rebels
have left the government's army in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for sending British officers to help train Sierra
Leoneon troops, Britain has pressed Kabbah to begin negotiations
with the United Revolutionary Front (RUF), whose rebels have earned
a notorious reputation for savagery by mutilating civilians. And
Britain has urged Kabbah to take the difficult step of integrating
the rebels into the new army.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates are slamming Britain for providing a
future role for the rebels. They say it is hypocritical for the
government that jailed the former Chilean president, Augusto
Pinochet, for alleged war crimes is now encouraging an African
government to make peace with some of region's most vicious war
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is neither morally nor politically valid to jettison
justice on the grounds that we have to achieve reconciliation,''
said Ian Levine, the United Nations representative for Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
   But others say Britain, in particular, deserves credit for
taking action at a time when the US and other western powers have
been withdrawing from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brits are stepping forward because they are sensing that
there is not much support or leadership coming out of Washington,''
said Chester Crocker, the former US assistant secretary of state
for African affairs. ``The alternative is you sit on your hands and
let the men with the guns dictate.''
</P>
<P>
   After independence from Britain in 1961, Sierra Leone was
plagued by decades of mismanagement and civil conflict. It plunged
into civil war in 1991 after an insurgency backed by rebel leader
Foday Sankoh. And it has since been plagued by a series of military
coups. The contest has been largely over control of the country's
lucrative diamond trade. On Monday, Kabbah, Sierra Leone's first
democratically elected president, met with Sankoh for peace talks
in Togo. Sankoh is facing a death sentence in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's deputy foreign minister, Tony Lloyd, said that the
only hope for longterm stability in Sierra Leone requires a deal
with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a number of donor nations from Europe, the US and
Asia, agreed at a UN-based conference to back a two-track policy
for Sierra Leone: support a Nigerian-led military offensive against
the rebels while pressing for negotiations on a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of Sierra Leone descending into further chaos leaves
``unpalatable decisions'' for those trying to prevent it, Lloyd
acknowledged. But he added that any attempt to ``rebuild the
shattered country'' will require integrating into the new military
``perpetrators of acts of terror and acts of horror.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's growing role comes amid new reports of atrocities by
the rebels. A spokesman for a West African peacekeeping force
battling the insurgents said that 125 civilians were massacred last
week in the town of Songo, 25 miles east of the capital, Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, a number of attempts at bringing
stability to the country have foundered.
</P>
<P>
   A Nigerian-led West African peacekeeping mission, known as
ECOMOG, failed to defeat the rebels or to shield Kabbah from a May
1997 coup that forced him into temporary exile. Last year, a
British-backed mercenary company, Sandline, drove the coup plotters
from power and restored Kabbah to power.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, meanwhile, rebounded with a major offensive in
January that raised doubts in Washington and London about the
prospects of their defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by dissident army officers, the rebels seized control of
the country's largest diamond mines and marched into Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   A UN investigation reported that between 3,000 and 5,000 people
were killed during the offensive. At least 2,000 of them were
civilians, according to the UN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is shocking that there is a place at the table for Foday
Sankoh,'' said Reed Brody, the director of advocacy for the New
York-based Human Rights Watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
