<HEADER>
A9532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-ASSESS-     04-22 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-ASSESS-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NO TIME TO WASTE IN PREPARING FOR GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ After four weeks of inconclusive airstrikes
against Yugoslavia, talk at NATO has increasingly turned to ground
troops to evict Yugoslav forces from Kosovo and secure autonomy for
the province and its Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   But unless NATO starts assembling ground forces soon, the
alliance may not have a credible threat of a land attack before the
onset of winter.
</P>
<P>
   For now, as the allies gather in Washington for a grand summit
marking NATO's 50th anniversary, there is broad agreement within
the organization that the bombing needs to continue, in the
lingering hope that it will eventually force Slobodan Milosevic,
the Yugoslav president, to meet NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   But what if several more months of bombing raids do not compel
Milosevic to withdraw his forces from Kosovo? While NATO's military
commanders have insisted that airstrikes are delivering a punishing
blow to the Yugoslav military, they have never guaranteed that air
power alone can deliver a victory.
</P>
<P>
   And what if the air campaign produces more cases of ``collateral
damage,'' the military's antiseptic term for the accidental bombing
of civilians, and public support for protracted bombing begins to
wane?
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, allied nations are talking of ground troops as a
way to bring the war to a speedy close. Nobody at NATO is eager to
rush into a land war. But if the alliance decides to turn to ground
troops, military experts say, they should go in before the weather
begins to worsen in September and October. Clear skies and
unhampered air power would be needed to protect the troops. It
would also be best if Western troops did not have to endure a
winter war.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to quiet the criticism in Congress that NATO lacks a
backup plan for using ground troops, the Clinton administration
said Wednesday night that it favors ``updating'' the options allied
military planners developed last summer for sending ground troops
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. would certainly support as a prudent measure any
updating of the assessments of the use of ground troops in a
permissive and non-permissive environment,'' a White House official
said.
</P>
<P>
   But informal planning is at best a small step and one that is
unlikely to seriously worry Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   To make the vague talk of combat troops credible, the alliance
needs to start actual military preparations immediately, like
deciding which NATO members would contribute troops, mobilizing and
training reserves, persuading nations in the region to make their
ports and airfields available and then shipping troops and weapons
to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Although it might seem strange that it would take the allied
nations so long to prepare for conflict in the heart of Europe,
NATO has its own procedures and diplomatic rituals in addition to
the practical and logistical considerations necessary to engage
tens of thousands of troops.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States prepared for the 1991 Persian Gulf war,
it began to send huge numbers of troops and weapons to the region
even before the generals worked out a military plan to evict Iraqi
soldiers from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   While in principle there is no reason that allied nations could
not start preparing troops now for a possible mission in Kosovo,
NATO does not generally work that way.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many military preparations are unlikely to be made
before allied nations formally instruct Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO
commander, to prepare a plan for a ground combat operation, and
then debate the strategy and approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Such a process has not even begun.
</P>
<P>
   The blessing of the entire 19-member alliance would be needed to
approve and implement a plan to engage ground troops in the
conflict. So far, NATO has agreed to send a peacekeeping force of
28,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the political decision to send combat troops into Kosovo
is made, getting forces to the Balkans could take six to eight
weeks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics would not be easy. Albania, which is already being
used a base for Apache helicopters and multiple-rocket launch
systems, is willing to serve as the staging ground for an attack.
But its port, airfields and roads are poor and its terrain
mountainous.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, a non-NATO nation where 12,000 troops for a potential
British peacekeeping force have already been deployed, would be
more suitable. But that would mean aligning political support from
its government and from Greece, whose port at Salonnika would be
crucial. Neither is yet willing to support a land attack.
</P>
<P>
   Though the difficulties are formidable, there are powerful
reasons why NATO might at least want to have an option to use
combat troops.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it would strengthen the allies' negotiating
leverage in trying to work out a settlement. Milosevic's strategy
is to try to ride out NATO's air war in the hope that the alliance
will crack. But that would be harder to do if the allies made clear
that they had other military options.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the option to use ground forces might also be useful
if airstrikes eventually lead Yugoslav forces to retreat.
Paramilitary units operating in Kosovo, some NATO officials worry,
could launch a final spasm of violent reprisals against any ethnic
Albanians remaining in the province as Yugoslav forces withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Without substantial forces on the ground in the Balkans, NATO
could only look on from the sidelines, much as America and its
allies watched from the southern side of the Euphrates as Iraqi
forces attacked Iraqi Shiites immediately after the war in the
Persian Gulf in 1991. The alliance could ultimately win a military
victory through air power but end up suffering a moral defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, using ground troops to impose a peace settlement
against disorganized Yugoslav resistance might be the only way to
bring a decisive end, a point top British officials have
underscored in recent days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Clark has contended that the bombing may succeed in
breaking the will of the Milosevic regime, diplomats say he has
also told allies that there are no guarantees. As an Army officer,
could hardly be expected to believe differently.
</P>
<P>
   Another Army man was also careful to emphasize the limits of air
power in forcing foreign dictators to bend to the will of the
United States. Just before the Persian Gulf war, Gen. Colin Powell,
who at the time was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told
Congress that he was not about to rely exclusively on air power to
evict Iraqi forces from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   And Powell offered that view even though he had far more air
power at his disposal than Clark and the foe he was fighting was
vulnerably situated in the open desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can hunker down, one can dig in, one can disperse to try
to ride out such a single-dimension attack,'' he said. ``Such
strategies are designed to hope to win; they are not designed to
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
