<HEADLINE>
BARRETT TO HEAD LAHEY CLINIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Minn.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Dr. David Barrett has been named chief executive of
the Lahey Clinic in Burlington, succeeding Dr. John A. Libertino,
who will return to his surgical practice full time.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, 57, is chief of urology at the Mayo Clinic in
Rochester, Minn., where he has practiced for 25 years and was part
of the elite medical team that treated Jordan's King Hussein before
his death in February from lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's appointment is effective Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Libertino, a practicing urological surgeon, said he wanted to
focus on his medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work 100 hours a week doing both clinical medicine and
administration,'' said Libertino, who has been chairman and CEO of
the Lahey Clinic for five years. ``I still have the second-busiest
surgical practice at the Lahey Clinic, and 100 hours a week is just
too much to sustain for any more than five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Libertino, 59, will remain as vice chairman of Lahey's board of
trustees and chairman of its department of urology. He said the
management change does not signal any shift in Lahey's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   After the clinic dissolved its merger with Dartmouth Hitchcock
Medical Center in New Hampshire in 1997, Lahey embarked on
expansion of its physician group practice throughout eastern
Massachusetts. The Lahey Clinic has 500 physicians at 40 sites,
including its flagship hospital in Burlington, and has been
recruiting more. It recently succeeded in wooing a team of liver
transplant surgeons from Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lahey has always differentiated itself from its competitors by
being a physician-focused organization,'' said Ellen Lutch Trager,
a health care consultant with Brown Rudnick Freed &AMP; Gesmer, a law
firm in Boston. ``But in a fiercely competitive market like Boston,
Lahey needs to secure its future by developing strategic
alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lahey Clinic last year managed well financially, earning
$2.2 million on operating revenue of $389 million in fiscal year
1998, ended Sept. 31. In the first five months of its 1999 fiscal
year, Lahey earned $400,000 on revenue of $168.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, a urologist, said he would continue to practice
medicine while at the helm of the Lahey Clinic. He received his
medical degree from Wayne State University in Detroit and a
bachelor's degree from Albion College in Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-SUIT-BOS &LR;      04-22 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE FIRM SETTLES Y2K SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In what appears to be the first legal settlement of
its kind in Massachusetts, a software firm agreed to resolve
allegations against it over the computer problem known as the ``Y2K
bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few such suits have been resolved in other states to
date, out of 61 cases tracked by a national litigation group.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of complaints is expected to increase
dramatically as lawyers and companies wrestle with the question of
just who should pay for the billions of dollars that it will
eventually cost to stave off widespread system problems at the
start of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's likely to be substantially more litigation concerning
responsibility for Y2K-type issues,'' said Gary Greenberg, an
attorney at Goldstein &AMP; Manello in Boston, the plaintiff's attorney
in the local suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future you're going to be dealing with losses or
damages, but for now these suits are about ways to minimize those
losses,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   His case, a class-action complaint, was brought by Qual-Craft
Industries Inc., a Stoughton construction tools maker. Filed in
Norfolk Superior Court last June, the suit alleged that software
maker RealWorld Corp. of Manchester, N.H., wrongly failed to
upgrade certain accounting software products to make them
Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the settlement, approved by a judge April 16,
RealWorld agreed to provide certain free upgrades and other
discounts worth an estimated $915 to each of 40,000 business
customers whose software might not have functioned through the date
change to Jan. 1, 2000. Users have until September to claim the
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Like others' software, many of RealWorld's programs used just
the last two digits of each year to keep track of the date. Those
programs might misinterpret Jan. 1, 2000, and cause computer
systems to crash or malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Many corporations are spending large sums to review and fix code
written by their own programmers. But for smaller companies, the
problem often lies with software purchased from outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   In its case, Qual-Craft bought programs from RealWorld in 1995
to keep track of accounting and order-processing functions, then
learned they might crash at the end of December.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at RealWorld said the older programs weren't worth
fixing and instead suggested Qual-Craft buy its latest programs.
Kurt Mueffelmann, RealWorld's chief executive, said in an interview
Thursday that any effective fix to the old programs would have
required users to buy new hardware as well _ in which case they
would be better off buying RealWorld's newer, Y2K-compliant
products.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, it was better for the company to settle the case
rather than spend the time and legal fees needed to dispute it at
trial. ``If we were to go through with the whole litigation, we
would have taken our eye off the business ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the settlement could cost RealWorld as much as $55
million, which Mueffelmann described as several times the
privately-held company's total revenue. It has 97 employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Mueffelmann said the firm would remain in business to sell
new products. ``What can we do except focus on our newer
products?''
</P>
<P>
   RealWorld was represented by Boston firm Bingham, Dana LLP.
Qual-Craft was also represented by New York firm Milberg, Weiss,
Bershad, Hynes &AMP; Lerach, best-known for bringing similar
class-action suits. Nationally, the firm has also brought many of
the 61 cases related to Y2K issues tracked by the Federation of
Insurance &AMP; Corporate Counsel in Walpole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
