<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-DRUNKDRIVE-LAW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia governor signs tougher vehicular homicide law
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes signed ``Heidi's Law'' DUI legislation
Thursday, as the father of the bill's namesake stood at his side.
</P>
<P>
   The law that toughens penalties for drivers convicted of
homicide by vehicle was named for Heidi Flye, the Cumming mother
killed with her two young daughters last summer when her car was
hit by a drunken driver. It takes effect May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Flye described DUI as a crime that often leads to
devastating consequences and ``wrecks the lives of those left
behind.'' He called for expanded use of a car ignition interlock
device that prevents a car from starting when it detects alcohol on
the driver's breath.
</P>
<P>
   Under Heidi's Law, those convicted of a second DUI would have to
have the device on their vehicle if they seek to drive during the
first six months of probation. It also requires a 12-month
probation of anyone convicted of DUI, regardless of jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Flye called the ignition interlock device the ``last and most
effective line of defense'' against drunk drivers and predicted
they eventually could be installed routinely by car manufacturers.
``I probably won't live to see it,'' Flye said. ``But drunk driving
could be virtually eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Heidi's law also:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gives judges compete leeway to set or deny bail in homicide by
vehicle cases.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bars those with a second DUI in five years from obtaining a
limited driving permit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Raises the minimum sentence for first-degree homicide by
vehicle from two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
