<SLUG> BC-NH-GAY-ADOPT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. SENATE VOTES TO REPEAL BAN ON GAY ADOPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ In another sign that New Hampshire's political
culture is changing, the Senate voted Thursday to repeal a law that
bans homosexuals from adopting children or serving as foster
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The repeal passed the more conservative House earlier this year,
and Gov. Jeanne Shaheen has said she will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, whose ban which took effect in 1988 amid what
critics call an ``AIDS hysteria,'' is one of only two states with a
law preventing gays and lesbians from adopting children. Florida is
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Several states, however, including Arkansas and Utah, have
effectively banned gay adoption by administrative rules.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, like many states, does not have enough foster
parents to help all the children in search of homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a shortage of foster parents in this state. We are
denying these children a family,'' said Sen. Katie Wheeler, a
leader in the fight to repeal the ban. ``Due to the ignorance,
prejudice and discrimination of those members of the 1988
legislature the foster children of New Hampshire have suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said that before the ban, there was ``not one single
incident or complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the six Senate proponents of the ban chose to speak. In
debates that led to the ban, however, some lawmakers cited Biblical
prohibitions against homosexuality. Others suggested that gays
sought to adopt children in order to prey upon them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One member of the House, a House which has gay and lesbian
members in it, actually stood up and looked at them and said that
homosexuals are predators, pedophiles and perverts,'' Sen. James
Squires said of the 1988 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the ban would be yet another sign that even a Granite
State can change said Rep. Raymond Buckley of Manchester, House
Minority Whip. Last year the legislature passed civil rights
legislation. Democrats in control of the Senate for the first time
in 86 years. The state's first female governor is in office.
Chances are good that this spring, New Hampshire will finally join
the other 49 states and adopt a Martin Luther King holiday. Talk of
an income tax no longer taboo.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators spoke in very personal terms during the debate
that preceded Thursday's 18-6 vote. One said he and his wife could
not adopt a child without banning a gay sibling from their home.
Another said he would face the same problem if a gay nephew were to
come for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Trombly, a lawyer whose representation of a gay men's
club became a campaign issue last year in his race with a
Republican challenger, said that he too, was a target of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sit down with you as an equal, we can have dinner, but
under the law of the state of New Hampshire, I cannot help those
special children in need,'' Trombly said.
</P>
<P>
   It took 11 years of work for gay rights advocates to erase what
Buckley called called a state symbol of hate by repealing the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, I think, is a quantum leap from the days of old in New
Hampshire when people who were different in some way didn't feel
that they had a home here,'' Buckley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
