<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-GILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAL GILL: AN UNLIKELY SUCCESS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ OK, so it's not the Montreal, Toronto, or
even Chicago of the South. Hockey down here remains a quirky fit, a
bauble in the curiosity shop, all the more so because the 'Canes
will vacate Greensboro Coliseum after this season and move into
their new rink in Raleigh in the fall. It was a franchise forged on
a farewell. How close would any fan want to get?
</P>
<P>
   But success can be spawned in some unlikely places.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Gill is proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, the Bruins' towering second-year defenseman, was the 207th
pick in the '93 draft, giving him about as much chance to make the
NHL as a Chilean nanny has of winning a $197 million lottery. He
spent his formative hockey years playing for Nashoba Regional High
School, one of some 600 students from the towns of Bolton, Stow,
and Lancaster. Just as Greensboro is to the NHL, Nashoba is to the
powers of Massachusetts high school hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at going to schools better known for hockey, like
Acton-Boxboro and St. John's (Shrewsbury),'' recalled Gill, before
suiting up against the Hurricanes in the opening game of the
Bruins' first-round playoff series. ``But my brothers went to
Nashoba, and I wanted to play football _ I just wanted to do what I
wanted to do. And I thought, `Hey, if I'm going to make it, I'll
make it no matter where I go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons why the 24-year-old Gill has gone on to
become such a key component to the Boston defense. It helps to be 6
feet 7 inches and 240 pounds, and it helps even more to be such a
mobile and agile block of granite willing to work at getting
better. But Gill also arrived in the Hub at a perfect time, when a
new coach (Pat Burns) had no preconceptions (read: misgivings)
about what a No. 207 draft pick might bring to the dance, and when
a new assistant coach (Jacques Laperriere) was there to program him
with a few decades of Montreal-honed defensive data. There was also
the general plight of the franchise, the Bruins just having
finished dead last in the Original 26.
</P>
<P>
   Gill was big, young, and willing. The Bruins were down, out, and
wanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing with Jacques is positioning,'' said Gill. ``If
you're in good position to start with, then you don't have to be
catching up the whole time. It's anticipation: read the play and
try to be in the right spot. In other words, you don't want to be
in the corner thinking, `Oh, hey, I need to be in front of the
net.' Jacques's big on that kind of thing, and he's also always
reminding me to keep it simple out there. If the only play is to
bang it off the glass _ and a lot of time that's your only option _
then that's what you do. Just make the simple play.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Gill's transition from playing four years at
Providence College to suiting up nightly for the Bruins has been so
seamless, it is almost taken for granted that he is behind the blue
line almost every time the opposition's top player is on the ice.
When the Bruins play Pittsburgh, he's out there whenever Jaromir
Jagr, arguably the best player in the game, rolls over the boards.
He was back there, captain Ray Bourque at his side, just about
every time the 'Canes Keith Primeau, the 6-5, 220-pound power
pivot, jumped into the play _ a matchup that should last through
this best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a more straight up-and-down player than Jagr is,'' said
Gill. ``You've got to try to keep guys close by him, not let him
use his speed, and he's not someone you can line up and kill. Jagr
is always looking for the play out there. Primeau is more strength
and speed, but in a straight line, more north-south. Maybe he
doesn't have Jagr's moves, but they both like to get down low and
make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does the enemy get down low on Gill's watch. The rare
time he hasn't anticipated the play, he often can cover his mistake
with his valley-of-the-jolly-green-giant reach. With a quick ho,
ho, ho, the puck is usually cleared from harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   From the backwoods of Nashoba Regional to the forefront of the
Boston defense. Even for Gill, there are times that seems like an
incredible reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sometimes it's hard to believe,'' he said. ``But it's
never something where I go, `Wow, this is amazing.' It's more like,
`Wow, this is good stuff.' It's what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The big kid from the little school now laughs to himself when he
attends a hockey clinic and routinely gets quizzed by parents about
how their own Billy, Johnny, or Genevieve isn't progressing in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say to me, `What's wrong? He's playing all season _
he's in this league, that league, going to this camp, that camp . .
. why's he not getting better?' '' said Gill. ``I know, as a kid,
if there was a sport, I played it, whether it was baseball,
football, basketball _ absolutely everything _ I was out there
playing it and having a great time. But these kids who are all
hockey all the time, geez, give 'em a break. If you're playing one
sport your whole life, how do you get excited about it? Maybe when
you're in college, or if you make it to pro, then it's a different
story, because you're more mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a kid, I think the most important thing is to be out
there having fun _ go out and play. If it's not fun, you won't get
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Gill brought his game to Greensboro, an unlikely success
story in an unlikely place. But somehow it all fit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
