<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILESTONE FOR BUSH: CIA COMPLEX TO BE NAMED FOR FORMER PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When George Bush walked into the troubled CIA in
1976, he feared he was kissing his political career goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   The secretive agency was under siege in Congress, and just to
get Bush's nomination to be director of central intelligence
through the Senate, President Ford pledged not to consider him as a
vice-presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every friend I had in politics felt this would be the
dead end, the absolute end of any politics in the future for me,''
Bush said in an interview this week. ``And I kind of thought that
maybe was true ... That happily proved to be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush would become the only CIA director later to be elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the sprawling CIA complex in suburban Virginia will
be named the George Bush Center for Intelligence. He is so admired
there that a CIA official said: ``It will be like Elvis has
returned.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to name CIA headquarters for Bush was approved by
Congress in legislation introduced by Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, who
was director of legislative affairs in Bush's White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, now retired in Houston, recalled his tenure at the CIA _
although it lasted just under a year _ as ``one of the biggest
challenges in my life ... one of the most interesting and rewarding
assignments I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Then as president, Bush became the ultimate consumer of
intelligence material. His White House day usually began with a
briefing by a CIA officer. Some 60 percent of the material covered
issues not in the daily press, said John L. Helgerson, CIA deputy
inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   To protect the confidentiality of the eight- to 10-page report,
typewritten and marked ``Top Secret,'' Bush and a handful of aides
would read the document, ask questions and then give all copies
back to the agency representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very security conscious,'' said Charles Peters, who
gave Bush the early-morning intelligence briefing several times a
week throughout Bush's 12 years as vice president and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I ever missed a day,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always thus. Agency veterans who gathered Thursday at
CIA headquarters to recount the Bush era said President Reagan
rarely received the intelligence briefing personally.
</P>
<P>
   During the Reagan presidency, one former CIA analyst said, the
written briefing was left with an aide, and Reagan ``read it
whenever he wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was disturbed, the analyst said, when he would see a
CIA briefing paper lying unattended on staffer's White House desks
in the Reagan era.
</P>
<P>
   Peters conceded that the ``PDB'' _ or presidential daily brief _
did not correctly foresee every turn in international affairs. He
recalled that early in Bush's presidency, the report ``confidently
predicted'' re-election of leftist Daniel Ortega as president of
Nicaragua a few days before he was defeated by the pro-U.S.
challenger, Violeta Chamoro.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, Peters said, the CIA brief would differ from what
other government agencies were telling Bush. In the Persian Gulf
War, he said, the CIA doubted that as much Iraqi armament had been
destroyed in the opening air attacks as the Defense Department
contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very frank,'' Helgerson said _ whether the agency had
gotten something right or ``blown it.'' Bush was equally frank,
Helgerson said, when his own assessment of an international
development had been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrived at the CIA in January 1976, after serving as U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, chairman of the Republican
National Committee and head of the U.S. mission in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morale was shot,'' Bush said, because of what he once called
``a handful of abuses'' and by House and Senate investigations
ramrodded by ``young, untutored, disrespectful'' congressional
staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had got ourselves really wrapped around the axle,''
Helgerson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, also a former congressman, worked to calm congressional
criticism and to stem any residue of CIA abuse with what Helgerson
called ``controlled, sensible openness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The high regard in which Bush is held in this agency and
around town regarding his handling of intelligence is not just the
way he did it as president,'' Helgerson said. ``It was what he did
for us when he was here.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hedley, who also briefed Bush when he was vice president
and is now a CIA retiree, recalled: ``The morale boost was not
insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   Helgerson said Bush not only ``got things back on track'' in
Ford's final year but for the next four administrations as well. He
said Bush gave detailed briefings to Jimmy Carter, who defeated
Ford in the 1976 election. Over the next three elections, Bush
became vice president and then president and, after his own defeat
in 1992, made certain that President-elect Clinton was made aware
of the importance of intelligence resources.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he retains high admiration for the cloak-and-dagger
side of the agency as well as for ``the very dedicated people who
never get their names in lights, never get to sit at the head
table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all James Bond and Miss Galore, if you will,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
