<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9556 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-LINK-BOS &LR;      04-22 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-LINK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PRE-HUMAN FOSSIL MAY BE EARLIEST TO USE TOOLS, EAT MEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting around a freshly-killed antelope by the edge of a large
lake, some of our earliest ancestors were using sharpened stone
tools to carve meat from the bones and to extract the marrow about
2.5 million years ago _ far earlier than any evidence for such tool
use has ever been seen before.
</P>
<P>
   These earliest-known, small-brained tool users may have been
embarking on an evolutionary journey that led directly to us, their
discoverers say. By learning to use sources of meat that other
primates could not, they may have set the stage for increasing
intelligence and a rapid spreading of their kind around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The new discoveries of animal bones with distinct markings from
the butchery carried out with stone tools, and some bones of the
ancient butchers themselves _ a never-before seen species that may
have been one of our direct ancestors _ were all found in the Awash
basin of Ethiopia and are being reported in the current edition of
the journal Science. The new finds could help to rewrite the tree
of human evolution, the researchers said, although it is still too
soon to say exactly how.
</P>
<P>
   The new finds may represent a kind of ``missing link'' between
early human ancestors of the genus Australopithecus, best know from
the famous ``Lucy'' skeleton found in 1978 by Donald Johansen, and
modern day humans of the genus Homo.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstructing the complex evolutionary process that led to
present day humans ``is all putting the pieces of a puzzle into
place,'' said Tim White, an anthropologist at the University of
California at Berkeley who led the 13-nation team of scientists
that made the discoveries. ``This is a major piece.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest previous widely-accepted evidence of tool use dated
from about 1.8 million years ago. While others had made earlier
claims of possible tools from a similar age, the new finds for the
first time provide unambiguous evidence not only for tools, but for
exactly how they were used and for what purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The fossilized, butchered bones, when examined though a
microscope, provide ``incontrovertible evidence for human
modification of the bones,'' said J. Desmond Clark, another
Berkeley anthropologist who was part of the team. ``It's very
different from the marks left by carnivores such as hyenas.''
</P>
<P>
   With this discovery, the scientists have finally been able ``to
actually find the smoking gun, . . . the signature of those tools
on the bones themselves,'' White said Thursday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, because of the close proximity of the bones of an
early human ancestor, the team has provided strong evidence of
exactly who was using the tools, which consisted of sharp flakes of
stone for carving, and large round stones for crushing bones. The
fragmentary bones of this ancient tool user have been given the
name Australopithecus garhi _ from an Ethiopian word for
``surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The new species fills an important gap in the fossil record of
human ancestry in a region that has produced a longer record of our
forebears than anyplace else on Earth. Fossils found in the rift
valleys of East Africa extend all the way back to about 4.4 million
years ago, and include direct human ancestors less than 2 million
years old, but there had been a major gap in this record in the
critical period between 2 and 3 million years ago _ a period when
large brains and the use of tools were thought to have evolved.
</P>
<P>
   With this find, White said, Ethiopia's Middle Awash region,
where these fossils and may of the others have been found, ``has
become the world's most important single site for studying human
origins and evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the region is a harsh desert, but 2.5 million years ago
it was a grassy plain at the edge of a large lake full of catfish,
crocodiles and hippos. The plains themselves were populated by
herds of grazing antelope, predatory saber-toothed cats and hyenas,
and various now-extinct species. Among these fearsome competitors,
the relatively short, small-brained, large-toothed primate could
successfully compete only by its wits, by finding a new way of
using available resources.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that these 4-foot creatures were actually hunting
the large animals that they butchered, White said. Most likely,
they were scavengers, finding ways to extract meat from carcasses
abandoned by large cats or hyenas. The stone tools that have been
found at the site are suitable for processing a carcass _ cutting
through tough hides to get at the meat, and smashing the bones to
get the marrow _ but not suitable for hunting large game.
</P>
<P>
   But that put these animals into a position of ``competition with
the hyenas. All of a sudden, they're competing with very dangerous
animals,'' White said. With the combination of new food sources
that allowed their growth and spread, and dangers that may have
required great ingenuity to escape, ``perhaps that stands behind a
very rapid process of evolution,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear, the researchers say, whether this new
hominid is really a direct ancestor of modern humans, or perhaps
simply the beginning of another evolutionary line that later went
extinct. Only much more painstaking excavation at this Awash site
and others like it can answer such questions, and the arduous work
will continue this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The fossilized bones at the site were encrusted with minerals
identical to the surrounding stones, making it incredibly difficult
to locate the bones of interest. Just extracting a few fragments of
skull, leg and arm bones from the site required seven weeks of work
by a team that included 40 scientists from 13 nations.
</P>
<P>
   But such labor is well worth it, White said. ``To understand
where we came from, this is the only way to find out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
