<SLUG> BC-AMSTERDAM-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCH GOVERNMENT AND EL AL CRITICIZED FOR RESPONSE AFTER CRASH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ More than six years after an Israeli cargo plane crashed
into an apartment complex near Amsterdam, killing 43 people, an
official investigation sharply criticized the Dutch government and
the Israeli airline El Al Thursday for slow and inadequate
responses after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary commission, which began work six months ago,
published its conclusions Thursday in a 400-page report.
</P>
<P>
   The group said that local and national health authorities
consistently underestimated health complaints from rescue workers
and from residents of the area who were exposed to toxic smoke from
the burning wreck and apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   It also said it was incomprehensible that El Al did not respond
immediately to repeated Dutch requests for all the cargo documents.
It took El Al almost six years to provide satisfactory answers to
concerns about the cargo, and only this year, during the inquiry,
was the full cargo list revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings in the Dutch Parliament, which included six weeks
of public sessions earlier this year, dominated the Dutch news.
Because of the foot-dragging over the cargo and the missing
evidence like the cockpit voice recorder, numerous conspiracy
theories were developed and suspicions were raised of a cover-up.
Investigative journalists, for example, wrote but never proved that
the voice recorder was taken from the wreck by Israeli security
personnel at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry has debunked some of the theories, including the
notion that dangerous explosives and lethal weapons were on board
the Boeing 747 as it took off from Amsterdam's Schiphol airport on
the second leg of its flight from New York to Tel Aviv, Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not comment on the cargo, which burned in its
entirety. But it did say that cargo papers were now complete and
that there were no indications of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash, in October 1992, El Al described the freight as
perfumes, electronics and machine parts. But last year, following
Dutch news reports, the airline admitted that the cargo had
included chemicals used in making sarin nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident, metal fatigue in an engine mounting
which caused two engines to drop off, was established early on. But
the hearings here have pointed to other malfunctions. Airport
employees testified that El Al, while keeping tight security, was
casual and even negligent in the maintenance of its planes.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions also revealed flaws in the Dutch government
bureaucracy. The report said that after the crash, civil servants
failed to pass on crucial information to government ministers,
including the fact that the plane's ballast included carcinogenic
depleted uranium.
</P>
<P>
   Several government ministers did not provide Parliament with
accurate information and were lax in addressing public concerns,
the report said. Some of the report's strongest criticism was
reserved for the minister of health.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that, contrary to the government view, there was
a direct link between health complaints and the crash.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people have reported physical complaints and
sleeping problems, but the government never deemed a full study
necessary. The report, however, linked the ailments to the sulphur
dioxide, metals, dioxins, asbestos and depleted uranium released
during the fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
