<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO TO STEP UP STRIKES ON SERB CONTROL CENTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Allied leaders insisted Thursday that they do not
intend to mount a ground invasion of Kosovo but will press ahead
with an intensified NATO air campaign that targets facilities used
as control centers by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
other Serb military and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The comments followed a NATO missile attack Wednesday on one of
Milosevic's homes in Belgrade, an event that Yugoslav government
officials described as a a criminal attempt to assassinate the Serb
leader.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, however, U.S. and allied officials scoffed at the
claim, calling the strike that damaged one of Milosevic's two
primary residences a legitimate military action designed to take
out Yugoslav ``command-and-control systems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not targeting President Milosevic or the Serb people,''
Defense Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon emphasized in his daily
briefing for reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He said the two-story villa that was destroyed was in effect ``a
command-and-control facility,'' complete with underground military
bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the military and security forces are run out of a
variety of residences, office buildings and other facilities
throughout the country, particularly in the Belgrade area,'' Bacon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all interconnected with the political (Socialists)
party as well. And we have always said ... that the price is going
to be high in terms of degradation and damage to the military and
security structure, and this is one example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a joint appearance at the White House with
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, also stressed that the allies
are not trying to kill Milosevic but would continue to focus
attacks on any ``key facilities used to direct and incite the
campaign of `ethnic cleansing''' of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo by
Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also denied that allied plans to update a blueprint for
a ground invasion of Kosovo put together last fall is a precursor
to committing ground troops to battle against Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Solana has ordered U.S. Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme
commander, to revise the assessment of what size force it would
take to drive Milosevic's army and paramilitary units out of the
Serb province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the secretary general's position to update the
assessment. It's only prudent,'' Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But he emphasized that he believes the air campaign alone will
be enough to accomplish NATO's objectives of driving the Serbs out
and seeing to it that Kosovar refugees are allowed to return to
their homes under the protection of international security force.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton was speaking to reporters, the Russian Itar-Tass news
agency reported that Milosevic had agreed, in talks with Moscow
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, to accept the presence of an
international peacekeeping force in Kosovo. If true, it could
amount to a diplomatic breakthrough in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, sounded skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an offer for a genuine security force, that's the
first Mr. Milosevic has done that, and that represents, I suppose,
a step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Itar-Tass report said Chernomyrdin, on a peace mission to
Belgrade, had drawn up a document with Milosevic that calls for
``an international presence in Kosovo'' with Russian participation
and under United Nations control. But Yugoslav officials said it
also called for the pullback of NATO forces now deployed in
Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, reacting cautiously, said that any security force would
have to have ``the confidence of the people who live there and will
have to operate in a way that protects all the people there,
including the Serb minority.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said later that the allies would not
accept any agreement on a security force that does not include
NATO-led troops as a key element.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
