A9560 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-LEGISLATION-     04-22 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-LEGISLATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SHOOTING PROMPTS FLURRY OF ACTIVITY ON GUN-CONTROL
LEGISLATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
and JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Colorado school shootings prompted a flurry of activity on
gun-control legislation Thursday in Washington and Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and some members of Congress said
they are preparing a package of measures to keep firearms away from
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is far too easy for a disturbed young person to get his
hands on a gun or a bomb and channel their anger into carnage,''
said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. ``Let's not kid ourselves. It's
not possible to confront the epidemic of violence in our schools
without dealing with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, pro-gun legislation now pending in the Texas
Legislature could be shot down in the aftermath of the Colorado
massacre, several lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the legislation was voted out of committee on
Tuesday, the day of the school shooting, the mood is beginning to
shift, said the chairman of the House panel that decides when bills
go to the floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is terribly, terribly important,'' said Rep. Barry
Telford, D-DeKalb, the Calenders Committee chairman. ``I'm
beginning to hear, because of this tragedy, some real concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, some lawmakers urged a deliberate response to the
Littleton, Colo., shooting rather than simply pushing gun-control
measures previously rejected by the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, said he would
expedite House legislation to set up a national panel of experts to
study teen-age gun violence and make recommendations to educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional understanding through a very thorough, systematic
process is the thing that is critically needed here, not a quick
political statement,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, speaking at a Justice
Department briefing, urged quick legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that one of the positive things that would come
out of this very tragic event in Littleton would be the passage of
the legislation that we will be proposing,'' Holder said. ``The
vast majority of the American people support reasonable
restrictions on the possession of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposals that the administration is expected to send to
Congress within two weeks would:
</P>
<P>
   _Require companies selling weapons at gun shows to perform the
same background checks gun shop owners must perform.
</P>
<P>
   _Prohibit juveniles who have committed violent crimes from
possessing handguns.
</P>
<P>
   _Stiffen penalties for adults who sell or give handguns to
juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   _Require gun makers to install trigger locks on the guns they
sell.
</P>
<P>
   _Impose a three-day cooling-off period before a handgun can be
transferred to a purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas, said he was not sure that
tightening gun-control laws would make schools safer. But he said
he would reintroduce legislation _ the Safe Schools Act, killed in
committee last year _ that would provide $175 million to hire law
enforcement officers to patrol schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at the different options,'' said Frost, who
will speak today to students at Arlington High School and Sam
Houston High School, about the Colorado shootings. ``We need to
talk about counseling and police in the schools and a whole range
of issues. You can't just focus on gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Telford, the calendars committee chairman, stressed
that he is a gun-rights supporter.
</P>
<P>
   But he said legislators have expressed concerns about a bill
that would lower the age limit to 18 for concealed weapons
licenses, provided the applicant is a member of the armed forces,
the state militia or National Guard, and another bill allowing
concealed weapons on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you had youngsters involved so heavily in this tragedy
in Colorado, it has a lot of the members very nervous,'' Telford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills are the work of Rep. Suzanna Hupp, R-Lampasas. Hupp,
who ran on a pro-gun agenda after her parents were slain in the
1991 Luby's massacre in Killeen, said lawmakers should be expanding
gun rights, not restricting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This knee-jerk reaction that we are seeing of certain groups
asking for more gun control is ludicrous,'' she said. ``I am
suggesting that perhaps we should consider allowing our teachers
and administrators to carry concealed (weapons) if they so choose.
Our schools are supposed to be gun free zones. Where has that
gotten us?''
</P>
<P>
   Another pending bill would, with certain exceptions, shield the
firearms industry from lawsuits by governmental entities, including
cities, counties and hospital districts. It passed the Senate, but
the bill's fate in the House is unclear. A similar measure in
Florida was postponed in the wake of the Colorado massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We operate on emotions, unfortunately,'' said state Rep. Bill
Carter, R-Fort Worth, a leading force behind the state's
conceal-and-carry law. ``We will see an overreaction, I think, to
the Colorado incidents for the wrong reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, a gun restriction measure _ requiring instant
background checks for weapons sales at guns show _ got the backing
of Gov. George W. Bush the day after the Colorado massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by state Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, was
defeated in committee, but the lawmaker said she would try to
resurrect it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
