<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MEDIAGENERAL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox buys cable TV cluster in Virginia
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Cox Communications has agreed to buy
Media General's cable television division for $1.4 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to close late this year, gives Cox 260,000
customers in Northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The Media General cable customers are in Virginia's Fairfax
County, the city of Fredericksburg and parts of Stafford and
Spotsylvania counties.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is one of the 10 largest cable television
companies, with about 3.8 million subscribers. Cox already has more
than 450,000 cable television customers in Virginia, located in the
Hampton Roads area on Virginia's coast and in the Roanoke area.
</P>
<P>
   The move fits into Cox Communications' strategy of offering a
range of broadband communications products in large metropolitan
areas, said Amy Porter, a Cox Communications spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   This part of Northern Virginia is growing fast and has lots of
upper-income residents who are more likely to subscribe to the
advanced media products Cox offers in its larger markets, Porter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Porter said Cox research showed the Northern Virginia
communities had more home PCs than most communities and a higher
number of people with Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond standard cable television, Cox Communications products
include high-speed Internet access, digital cable television and
digital phone service. Media General offered cable television and
high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises, a privately held media
conglomerate, controls both Cox Communications and The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
