A9564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-SLAIN-HNS &LR;      04-22 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-SLAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES IN TEXAS SEEK MOTHER OF TWO SLAIN TODDLERS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ Investigators Thursday searched for the
mother of a boy and girl whose bodies were found dumped in a rural
creek bed earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Attention turned to the mother, 22-year-old Tina Marie
Cornelius, who is sought for questioning but has not been named as
a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, apparently single, has lived in the Austin-Round
Rock area with the children for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The small children, whose identities eluded authorities until
Wednesday evening, have been identified as Amanda Lee Miller, 3,
and Dominick Logan Cornelius, 2. Autopsies revealed the girl was
suffocated and the boy killed by a blunt blow to his skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unusual for a woman to have two children missing and
not be able to find her,'' said Texas Department of Public Safety
spokesman Mike Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we're trying to find her, to make sure she's OK, to
see if she knows anything about where the children might have been
or anything like that. That's what's critical right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Linda Bunte, head of the Williamson County sheriff's
criminal investigation unit, and Cox said authorities have not
issued any arrest warrants or identified any suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are concerned that the mother ``might be in
danger,'' Bunte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for the mother ... because her children are
dead,'' Cox added. ``We are not calling the mother a suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius was last seen by relatives a week ago and was driving
a 1990 white Pontiac Grand Prix with a Texas license plate of ZPC
70M, Bunte said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was a day-care center in Austin that helped
investigators identify the children and mother, after seeing
sketches of them and descriptions reported in the media. Day-care
workers said the last time they had seen the three was April 14.
</P>
<P>
   It has proved the first big break in the case since the little
bodies were discovered Monday afternoon in Brushy Creek near the
farming town of Hutto.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they have been in contact with several family
members, some of whom live in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first and most important call received was from the
day-care center,'' Cox said. ``Someone at the day-care center
snapped on the type of diapers they had on. That's what led to the
initial information.''
</P>
<P>
   Both children were wearing Mickey Mouse pull-up diapers, his
blue and hers pink.
</P>
<P>
   Bunte said the day-care workers noticed no signs of trouble with
the mother or children last week.
</P>
<P>
   A search of records so far shows no reports of abuse to child
protection workers, said Marla Sheely, spokeswoman for the Texas
Department of Protective and Regulatory Services.
</P>
<P>
   Bunte said authorities are now trying to re-create the last days
before the bodies were found and the mother disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The mother had worked at several occupations, most recently as a
dancer at a south Austin strip club called Expose, according to The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   A dancer, who identified herself only as Joy, and several other
employees of the club told The Associated Press that Cornelius had
worked there for about three weeks. Joy said she had not seen
Cornelius in more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she was going away and was going to leave her kids
with some friends for the weekend,'' Joy said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cornelius had moved from the Austin address on her driver's
license, perhaps several times within the area, said DPS
spokeswoman Tela Mange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for anyone who has seen this woman, who has
seen these children, who has seen these two together,'' Cox said.
``If they can call and tell us that `yes they were at such and such
a convenience store buying a six-pack' or whatever, that's what we
need right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the children had two different fathers who are
thought to live outside the state. Reports conflicted as to whether
the fathers had been located, informed or questioned about the
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the children were positively identified Wednesday by
relatives escorted by a sheriff's deputy to a funeral home in
Taylor where the bodies were sent after undergoing autopsies in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
