<SLUG> BC-NH-EDUCATION-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT TO FUND EDUCATION FOCUSES ON PROPERTY TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N. H. _ In joyless votes taken just minutes apart, New
Hampshire's House and Senate Thursday passed similar tax bills to
pay for public schools. Legislators will now meet in a conference
committee to hammer out their differences, bringing the state a
step closer toward resolving a crisis that has dominated politics
for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today marks a milestone in our efforts to resolve the
school-funding issue,'' said Gov. Jeanne Shaheen. The state supreme
court gave lawmakers until April 1 of this year to replace the old
system of funding schools, which relied heavily on local property
taxes. The deadline passed without a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers cautioned, however, that Thursday's developments
do not represent a major step forward. The bills that passed were
seen by many as at most a temporary fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desperate people in desperate times do desperate things,''
said Sen. Edward Gordon by way of explaining why most of his
colleagues were voting for a plan they neither liked or thought
fair.
</P>
<P>
   Others worried that the Thursday's agreement, if it were the
basis of a final agreement, might not sustain a court challenge
because it does not raise enough money. Still others fear that the
court will frown on provisions in both bills that would soften the
blow for property-rich towns that would otherwise see tax bills
skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be sure when I vote for something, that we are not
going to go down an unconstitutional road again,'' said Sen.
Beverly Hollingworth, an income tax proponent.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills rely heavily on a statewide property tax and
increased taxes on business. The Senate version calls for the state
to pay $841 million of the estimated $1.4 billion cost of public
education. The House bill raises $808 million.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to meet that deadline has led Wall Street to warn that
the state's credit rating is in danger of being downgraded. With
money to operate schools due to run out by July most of the state's
teachers have now received pink slips.
</P>
<P>
   The political environment continues to be chaotic, but most now
expect some kind of legislative agreement, and a vote, within the
next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
