A9566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-CBS23-COX     04-22 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-CBS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charter investigating allegations, questions CBS reporting
methods
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charter Behavioral Health Systems said Thursday it's
conducting an internal investigation of charges made by the CBS
News program ``60 Minutes II'' about practices in the
Alpharetta-based company's psychiatric hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Charter said its inquiry is standard company practice when
patient care allegations are reported. And the company, which
operates 91 psychiatric hospitals in 32 states, repeated earlier
assertions that CBS News may have violated North Carolina and
federal laws in reporting the story.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong segment Wednesday alleged dangerous conditions,
falsification of medical records and lack of employee training in
Charter hospitals. The program also alleged injuries and deaths in
Charter hospitals. Charter officials stood by earlier statements
that patients' safety, privacy and well-being are the company's
primary concerns. The company also said it does not condone
violations of policies, including falsifying records, and would
take disciplinary actions if it found violations.
</P>
<P>
   The program, anchored by Ed Bradley, based much of its reporting
on a hidden camera worn by a social worker, Terrance Johnson, who
worked for eight weeks in a Charter hospital in Charlotte. Johnson
was not paid by the network, CBS News said.
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes II'' went to great lengths to protect patient
confidentiality, obscuring patients' faces, changing their voices
and appearance, Bradley said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Network spokeswoman Kerri Weitzberg added: ``We proceeded very
carefully every step along the way in reporting this story. We are
confident that we operated fully within the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charter attorney Steve Petrovich said that with the use of a
hidden camera and microphone, ``Charter believes that (Johnson)
invaded our patients' confidentiality and intruded on their
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited North Carolina law protecting patient confidentiality
and patient medical records, and protections for psychiatric
patients and their treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Charter, citing confidentiality concerns, filed a motion for a
temporary restraining order in Federal District Court in Charlotte
late Tuesday to keep the program from being aired. Judge Graham
Mullen denied the request.
</P>
<P>
   But Mullen also expressed concern that laws may have been broken
in the gathering of the information for the report. Mullen said he
would refer the matter to the U.S. attorney's office to look into
whether federal mail fraud laws were violated.
</P>
<P>
   The media's use of hidden cameras has not been settled in the
courts, said David Hudson, an attorney with the First Amendment
Center in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a greater amount of (legal) protection for publication
of material than the acquisition of it,'' Hudson said. ``We really
need to have some guidance on how much protection there is.''
</P>
<P>
   A North Carolina jury two years ago ordered ABC to pay $5.5
million for using a hidden camera in an investigation of Food Lion
supermarkets. The award, reduced to $315,000, is under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   News services contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
