<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPACIFIC-EARNINGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific profit rises sharply
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia-Pacific Group beat analysts' expectations and
reported a sharp increase in first-quarter profit Thursday, boosted
by a rise in prices and shipments of building products.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Group, which excludes the Atlanta-based
company's timber business, posted net income of $99 million for the
first quarter, or $1.13 a share, from the year-ago profit of $4
million, or 4 cents a share. The year-ago figure included $12
million in charges for early retirement of debt.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter revenue grew to $3.35 billion, a 5 percent
increase from $3.19 billion one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific was expected to earn $1.02 a share, based on a
survey of analysts by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The company is benefiting from an exceptionally strong housing
market, which is boosting sales of its gypsum wallboard, plywood
and oriented strand board. Meanwhile, the company's pulp, paper and
packaging businesses were mixed but are recovering from slumping
prices last year caused by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Profit more than doubled at Georgia-Pacific's
construction-materials unit, which makes lumber, plywood and other
types of panels. The unit had a profit of $248 million, compared
with $103 million in the year-ago period. Georgia-Pacific also made
money distributing such materials, a business that had a loss a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at the company's packaging unit rose, but profits fell
about 70 percent for pulp and paper operations because of low
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Georgia-Pacific's timber business reported a drop in
first-quarter net income. Timber Co. earned $46 million, or 53
cents a share. A year earlier, Timber Co. posted net income of $50
million, or 54 cents a share, including a $2 million charge for
early retirement of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue declined 4 percent to $139 million, compared with $145
million in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
