<SLUG> BC-NETBANK-EARNINGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net.B(at)nk in black for 4th quarter in row
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Net.B(at)nk on Thursday announced its fourth straight
profitable quarter and met analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpharetta-based, Internet-only bank posted net income of
$691,000, 9 cents per share, compared with a loss of $151,000, or 2
cents per share, for the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Net.B(at)nk shares are up 10 percent the past five days, 540
percent for 1999. The stock hit a 52-week high of $249 April 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Keane, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens, said
earning are not the top priority for Internet banks _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their job right now is to try to market and get out there and
get customers,'' Keane said. ``27,000 accounts _ that's a huge
number. That's up 10,000 in four months. That's huge growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Net.B(at)nk said customer accounts, which grew by 3,000 in March
and are up 2,400 so far in April, now total 27,000. That number is
up from 17,400 at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening in October 1996, Net.B(at)nk (www.netbank.com) has
attracted customers because of a unique business model that lets it
offer traditional banking services more cheaply than most because
it is based solely on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   D.R. Grimes, chief executive officer, attributed the growth to a
sixfold increase in the company's marketing spending. Net.B(at)nk's
$3.6 million marketing budget paid for ads on 60 Web sites and in
national newspapers. The company also started mailing brochures to
people who pay their Internet service provider by credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Customer deposits now exceed $332 million, up from $128.7
million in the year-ago period. Net.B(at)nk has $526.5 million in
total assets, up from $163.5 million at the end of the first
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If Net.B(at)nk grows at its current pace, Grimes said it could
have more than 50,000 accounts by year's end. Grimes said
Net.B(at)nk increased its percentage of checking and money-market
account customers from 50 percent of the bank's total accounts in
September to 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who conduct their checking transactions at the site
tend to be more frequent visitors than those with certificates of
deposit accounts. They also tend to be longer-term customers,
Grimes said.
</P>
<P>
   Net.B(at)nk's per-share numbers do not reflect its previously
announced 3-for-1 stock split, which happens May 14.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
