<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTMAN-DEBT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Portman firm sells asset to pay debt
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AMC Inc., the firm created in John C. Portman Jr.'s
huge debt restructuring in 1995, has paid off $8 million in debt
through the sale of its stake in a San Francisco mixed-use office
complex and is seeking an extension of a $93.1 million mortgage due
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The financial actions of AMC, which owns the large downtown
Atlanta trade mart complex developed by Portman, were disclosed in
a recent filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. While
AMC's stock is not publicly traded, it is required to file with the
SEC because some of its debt is traded in the public market.
</P>
<P>
   Architect-developer Portman had acquired a minority interest in
Embarcadero Center through his participation in creation of the
landmark San Francisco complex in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   That interest was among the assets Portman transferred to AMC
when the firm was formed to allow Portman creditors to exchange
debt for ownership interests in AMC. Portman is chairman and chief
executive officer of AMC.
</P>
<P>
   The $8 million debt _ which had the highest repayment priority
of AMC's debt _ was incurred to obtain working capital to keep the
complex operating during Portman's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Funds for the payoff came in late 1998 when Boston Properties, a
real estate investment trust, acquired Embarcadero Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the sale, AMC received an unspecified amount of cash plus
partnership units, valued at $22.2 million, in a Boston Properties
affiliate. AMC then sold a portion of the units to FBCC, a
Dallas-based firm that is part of the Hunt family business
organization and is AMC's largest shareholder. From that firm, AMC
received $7.4 million _ $4.5 million in cash and $2.9 million in
exchange for debt.
</P>
<P>
   AMC's remaining debt totals $281.7 million. The company said it
has requested, but not received, a one-year extension of the $93.1
million mortgage on the Atlanta Gift Mart due July 31. The lender
is Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   The company owes $181.6 million in mart bonds due July 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year ago, AMC hired Victor Capital Group of New York
to pursue a capital restructuring, refinancing or sale of the
company or some of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   A mart refinancing package, consisting mainly of bonds and bank
debt, was circulated on Wall Street this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
