<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SLAYINGS23-COX     04-22 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SLAYINGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How can you tell when your kid is headed for real trouble?
 &HT;    By By Christine Evans and Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was everywhere this week _ the sound
of parents worrying about their kids. The clothes they wear. The
music they worship. The games they play. Alienation and isolation.
Cliques. Outcasts. Peer pressure. And, of course, guns.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Tuesday's school shootings, an unimaginable
rampage by two black-clad students that left 15 dead and many more
wounded at an entirely normal public high school tucked into the
suburbs in Littleton, Colo., parents whispered with furrowed brows
around breakfast tables and water coolers. How do you know, they
asked one another, if your kid is in trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Not stay-out-late, graffiti-on-the-wall,
talk-back-and-dress-funny trouble. Real trouble.
</P>
<P>
   How far is too far? Where is the line between fun and frenzy?
When is a trenchcoat a portent of doom?
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you tell?'' asked Randy Stafford, a psychologist at the
alternative Gold Coast Community School in West Palm Beach. ``You
have to listen very, very carefully. You have to take every
opportunity you have to talk to your child. Sure, people are busy.
But the car is a very good place. Make good use of the car. Let
your kids listen to their music in the car, and then ask questions
about it. `What are you listening to? Why do you like it?' But
don't interrogate them. Don't judge them. Use it as a springboard,
a sort of communication trampoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start talking, and keep talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Details about the two suspected shooters in the Littleton
tragedy are still spilling out, amid the tears and the sudden snow
and the hundreds of police interviews that have turned the town
into a chilly, confusing place with too many questions and precious
few answers. They were 17 and 18. They wore black trench coats,
black lipstick, black trousers. At the bowling alley, they were
seen flashing the Nazi salute. And after they killed 12 students
and one teacher, they turned their guns and killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There were, it seems, so many warning signs; there usually are
in cases like this _ children rarely suddenly ``snap,'' turning
from good to bad in a single breath overnight. But here and across
the country this week, people who teach and counsel and study
children had two pieces of advice for parents worried about some
aspect of their children's behavior: Don't panic. And don't clam
up.
</P>
<P>
   Find out more. Calmly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Stafford says, ``When you talk to some kids who
identify themselves as Satan worshippers, some of them have only a
very general, superficial knowledge. They may have five books at
home on this stuff, but they haven't read any of them. So when
parents say their child makes devil signs, this kind of thing, I
say, `Tell me more. Is it really a significant part of their
lives?'''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Tonya Aultman-Bettridge of the Center for the Study and
Prevention of Violence: ``Parents should know how the child is
doing in school and pay attention to complaints about their
behavior. They shouldn't panic and call a psychologist the minute
they see him wearing a Marilyn Manson T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between listening to a type of music
and building pipe bombs in the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   The center is affiliated with the University of Colorado at
Boulder, just 32 miles from the site of the shooting spree at
Columbine High School in Littleton. Center researchers studying
youth violence have identified a number of ``risk factors'' that
might contribute to over-the-edge behavior.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a child might be at risk if he or she keeps
constant company with friends who provide a negative influence _
the notorious ``bad crowd'' _ or if their parents cannot properly
supervise them. Doing poorly in school can be another factor
(parents should watch for a sudden and deep decline in grades), and
so can living in a neighborhood where firearms are readily
available.
</P>
<P>
   Research also shows that in children, remarkable acts of
violence _ such as Tuesday's mass shootings _ often are preceded by
smaller, less remarkable violent acts. Killing animals, for
instance. Often, an at-risk youth is significantly depressed and
angry as well; perhaps he has threatened suicide; perhaps he
bullies others; maybe he drinks and abuses drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this is common sense. But there's no formula, cautions
Aultman-Bettridge, ``no easy way, no one thing you can look at and
say, this child is going to be violent.'' And parents should take
care not to grow overly alarmed by the usual signs of teen-age
rebellion or discontent, or, certainly, styles of dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most kids who have tattoos on their arms and bandanas on their
heads and wear a certain type of clothes are just kids,'' says Eric
Gorovitz, legal director for the Pacific Center for Violence
Prevention in California. ``There are some kids who are violent who
wear these clothes as well, but it's terrifying to say if somebody
has a tattoo, you'd better worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are clues.
</P>
<P>
   And parents, and anybody else on hand, should watch for them.
</P>
<P>
   At Boca Middle School, for instance, teachers, parents and even
the principal can glean clues from the organizers that students
keep to set goals and chart progress in school. In the normal
course of a school week, parents and teachers take a look at the
organizers to see how a child is doing, and the principal, Dick
Reed, regularly looks them over to check reading logs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a look at what he or she is writing, and the doodlings
and drawings,'' Reed says, keeping an eye out for violent lyrics,
gang symbols, drug-related sketches, or ``the portrayal of a lot of
death.'' If there is something really wrong, ``there ought to be
some signs in there.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, says Janet Hibel, president-elect of the Palm Beach
County chapter of the Florida Psychological Association, parents
should pay particular attention to electronic leisure time, such as
video games. If your child is in the bedroom, with the door closed,
the lights off, whooping it up at the action on screen, this might
be simply a normal display of enthusiasm for a game that is fun.
Or, it might be something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should not have a benign acceptance of these games as
just entertainment,'' Hibel says. ``They really need to sit down
and talk about what is being gratified in their child as they play
these games ... Are they getting gratification out of harming or
killing somebody? Are they deriving a sense of superiority by
identifying with the aggressor or violent hero? Are the games
giving them a sense of identity they're not getting in a healthy
way on the outside?''
</P>
<P>
   But again, she says, don't panic. Be observant, not alarmist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the parent is looking for is a balance in the child's
life. So, yeah, they have these games but they have other things in
their lives, too, some other way of obtaining healthy
gratification. And the other point is, can they talk about what
they're getting? Can they say it's fun? Can they understand it's a
fantasy world?''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Do they live in the real one?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the whole child,'' says psychologist
Stafford. ``Are they doing well in school? Are they connected to
family members? Do they have a job? Are they part of a social
activity, sports, clubs? Are they isolated or are they connected?
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, that's pretty good information.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
