<HEADER>
A9573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      04-22 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ATTEMPTS TO CALM STUDENTS IN WAKE OF SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ T.C. Williams High is not Columbine High, and
Alexandria, Va., is not Littleton, Colo. But the deadliest school
shooting spree in US history has left a trail of fear among
students coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, President Clinton tried to restore a certain degree of
calm during a visit that was beamed to 12,000 schools across the
country by Channel 1, a national classroom cable network, and on
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in orange plastic chairs arranged in a circle in the
school library, Clinton told the 30 T.C. Williams students who
joined him for the discussion, ``On balance, our schools are still
the safest place our kids can be in most communities under most or
all circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Clinton and and the students struggled to understand
why Tuesday's school shooting, which ended with 15 dead and dozens
injured at Columbine High, happened, and what could be done to make
sure it never happens again.
</P>
<P>
   Because the students presumed to be the killers, both of whom
died of self-inflicted wounds, learned how to make explosives via
the Internet and may have targeted athletes and minorities, some
students wondered aloud whether easy access to such material on the
Internet was the culprit, or whether it was racism, or violent
movies and videos, or the accessibility of guns, or lapses in
guidance at school or home that would turn a good child bad.
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton: ``We don't know all the facts about what happened
in Littleton, but one of the things that's come out of this that's
really made an impression on me is that the young men who were
involved in this horrible act apparently felt that they were
subject to ridicule and ostracism, and they were kind of social
outcasts at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``But their reaction to it was to find someone else to look down
on. And, apparently, they were very prejudiced against
African-Americans and Hispanics, and observed Adolf Hitler's
birthday, and otherwise reacted to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added, ``They had the wrong reaction to the fact that
they were dissed. Hey, look, everybody gets dissed sometime in
life. Even the president; sometimes especially the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The students meeting with the president were all conflict
mediators at the school, or enrolled in an advanced placement
government class. Their school district has placed a high priority
on school safety, including establishing a zero-tolerance policy on
weapons and drugs, instituting anger-management programs, promoting
peer-conflict mediation, and offering a hotline that students can
call anonymously to report potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   But such efforts to reduce the chances of school violence campus
have not completely erased their anxiety, especially since
Littleton has become only the latest in a series of school
shootings that occurred in places like Paducah, Ken., Jonesboro,
Ark., and Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is there going to be a change?'' Jonelle Mitchell, a
senior, asked Clinton. ``I mean, there's been a lot of acts of
violence in the schools recently...As a student, I need to have
that guarantee of safety, and truthfully, I really don't feel safe
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mitchell said she feels safer in her school than she would
in some others, she asked: ``I want to know when is the government,
when are you going to do something for the other students out
there'' who attend schools with fewer resources to combat school
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the government published a booklet on school safety
last June, after the Springfield shoting, to help adults detect
early warning signals to head off school violence. He also said his
administration hosted the first-ever White House conference on
school violence last year, and he plans to send a new crime bill to
Congress next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times we forget that a small crack can cause a big
problem'' said student Luisa Soaterna. ``There are things which
occur in life, or things that you hear when you're walking down the
hallway and we just think nothing of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students said a lack of diversity at the Littleton high
school may have triggered the violence or, at the very least,
negative racial attitudes. ``The racism should stop, because the
racism leads to bad things, like what happened in Colorado,'' said
student Sindy Benavides. ``Racism cannot produce anything good.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Tyler Cotrone told Clinton tougher gun-control
laws also are needed. ``I know we already have a waiting period on
how long you can get guns or whatever, but I think we need to take
some other action to make regulations on weapons and other guns, so
that they don't fall into the hands of the wrong people, and this
sort of thing doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was planning legislation to try to ``strike a
better, proper balance between making it harder for people who are
violent to get guns and misuse them, without interfering with the
constructive role'' of guns for recreational use.
</P>
<P>
   One student warned Clinton not to seek ``the easy answer,'' such
as restricting the rights of students by requiring them to wear
school uniforms or carry clear backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be careful that we ensure people's security without
running high school like a prison system,'' said the student,
Patrick Egan. ``I'm really worried that in the wake of a disaster
like this, then the first thing people are going to say is, `Oh,
they're kids, their rights don't matter. You can just take them
away, take away their freedom of speech, take away their freedom to
be a person.' And I just hope that that doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded Clinton, ``I think that's a point well taken.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
