<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREATNESS-ARTISTS-100     04-22 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREATNESS-ARTISTS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS GREAT ART? DEPENDS ON WHOM YOU ASK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ ``Great'' is a word we easily apply to
athletic performance, bargain prices, a new hairstyle or piece of
clothing. Occasionally, we even use it to describe art.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this year, the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth has been
showing works by two men almost universally acknowledged as the
greatest artists of the first half of the 20th century: Henri
Matisse and Pablo Picasso. Even those who don't care for their art
concede their innovation, influence, prodigious output and
technical mastery _ or, at least, concede that a lot of people who
know a lot about art consider Matisse and Picasso great.
</P>
<P>
   Consensus and the luxury of retrospect provide a comfortable
platform for calling something ``great.'' But can ``great'' also be
used to describe art and artists of our times? Is it simply too
soon to say? Is any opinion on the topic little more than
speculation?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it possible that the present doesn't deserve description
in such terms? Maybe greatness abides in the past because, to
paraphrase Norma Desmond, ``Art is great; it's the artists that got
small.''
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, not every era in every part of the Western world has
borne witness to greatness: The Dutch, for example, are recognized
for their artists of the baroque period, for one in the late 19th
century (van Gogh) and for one in the early 20th century
(Mondrian). And that's about all.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Western world, plenty of people resent terms
such as ``great'' and ``important,'' particularly in their
superlative forms, because they represent Western chauvinism and
ranking and the imposing of a hierarchy they perceive as unfair or
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, a number of observers simply look around at the
multiplicity of what is happening _ the endless variety of media
and techniques, ranging from painting to video to performance art _
and helplessly throw up their hands. They say there's no basis for
comparison: It's not as if you're judging which artist in
16th-century Florence painted the sweetest Madonna and Child.
</P>
<P>
   They'll nit-pick over exactly what constitutes greatness or
importance: Influence on other artists? The number of museum shows?
Inclusion in Janson's latest ``History of Art?'' The price
someone's work fetches at auction?
</P>
<P>
   They'll complain, too, about the hype: Is greatness connected to
how often an artist is mentioned in glossy magazines? Or the
politics: Is someone being touted because a cadre of curators and
dealers has a stake in their career?
</P>
<P>
   Generally, those willing to name names do so after they've
defined the terminology to their satisfaction. And then they talk
in subjective terms of whom they most admire _ not in objective
terms of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, though, they supply us with some names of
artists who are of consequence in our time. It's a mixed bag, with
only a few distinguishing features.
</P>
<P>
   One is that none is what you might call a whippersnapper.
</P>
<P>
   The other is that they've demonstrated a commitment to their own
visions and a well-informed disregard for trends. Regardless of
what you think of their art, there's a word for that, too:
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   GERHARD RICHTER (German, born in 1932)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Painting in at least two distinct veins _
photorealism and abstraction _ and compiling a vast archive of
images Richter calls his ``atlas.''
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by: Michael Auping, chief curator, Modern Art Museum of
Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   An artist's influence is one way of evaluating greatness, Auping
says, and based on influence, he chooses Richter.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other artist living today, Richter seems to
encapsulate in his work a lot of the contradictions inherent in
late-20th-century art,'' Auping says. ``He paints abstractly and,
simultaneously, realistically and maintains a certain integrity in
both. He is a formalist, but he also engages political content.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his own way, he would be a kind of postmodern Picasso.''
</P>
<P>
   JACOB LAWRENCE (American, born in 1917)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Series of small paintings on cardboard of events and
individuals in African-American history.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by Janet Tyson, art critic, Fort Worth Star-Telegram
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Lawrence's greatness _ what I would call his heroism _
lies in his humility and integrity. Here is an artist who came to
renown for small pictures, in marked contrast to what art
historians have come to view as important American art of the
mid-20th century. Also, much 20th-century art is about art and the
artist, but Lawrence turns his focus outward toward humanity.
</P>
<P>
   That's not saying Lawrence isn't aware of art issues and art
history: I thoroughly enjoy his ``After Vesalius'' group of
drawings, based on anatomical studies by the Renaissance scientist.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not as fond of Lawrence's more recent paintings. They're
larger and more brightly colored than his well-known early series.
But they testify to the artist's commitment to interpreting human
experience _ and I have to respect that.
</P>
<P>
   FRANK GEHRY (American, born in 1929)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: The Guggenheim Mseum in Bilbao, Spain, and other
innovative structures
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by Aaron Betsky, architecture curator, San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art
</P>
<P>
   Without hesitation, Betsky names Gehry, whose shimmering,
undulating titanium-clad museum in Bilbao has been called the
greatest building of our era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire him because he does what artists do best,'' Betsky
says. ``He makes objects that make us look at our world in a whole
new way. He crystallizes and clarifies an urban environment we
otherwise might not notice or understand because it is so chaotic
and complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he does so in beautiful and voluptuous forms.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
<P>
   BALTHUS (Polish-French, born in 1908 as Balthasar Klossowski de
Rola)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Uncanny images of figures.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by: Hilton Kramer, publisher and editor in chief, ``The
New Criterion''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer picks Balthus with some reluctance because, as he says,
``We don't have any really great artists at the moment _ unless
they've managed to conceal themselves from public attention. So the
choices are limited to people who are less than great.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer concedes that the sometimes macabre sexual undercurrents
in Balthus' work are not every viewer's cup of tea. But he is ``a
marvelous draftsman,'' Kramer says. ``He also is a very
deliberately traditional artist who has been totally independent of
trends and fashion and gone entirely his own way _ which one has to
admire, whether they admire the results or not.''
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD SERRA (American, born in 1939)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Taking huge slabs of steel and propping them against
one another.
</P>
<P>
   CLAES OLDENBURG (American, born in 1929)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Public artworks in the form of binoculars, lipstick
and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by Marianne Stockebrand, director of the Chinati
Foundation, Marfa
</P>
<P>
   Stockebrand chooses Richard Serra and Claes Oldenburg because
``each in his own way is absolutely of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Serra's sculptures have gone through many powerful stages of
development, she says, noting his early torn rubber pieces, his
works made of lead (splattered in its molten form and allowed to
harden where it landed) and his massive slabs of steel.
</P>
<P>
   Serra was also chosen by Ken Baker, art critic of the San
Francisco Chronicle. Baker notes that Serra's immense, dark slabs
of steel, precariously balanced or standing in people's way,
provoke as much hostility as they do admiration.
</P>
<P>
   But ``his work reminds us that life is lived through the body,''
Baker says. ``When you're in the presence of his work, you
comprehend things in the most immediate physical way. It's not a
theoretical experience at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Serra's starkly beautiful abstract forms,
Oldenburg and his wife, Coosje van Bruggen, re-create objects from
everyday life on a monumental scale, endowing them with elements of
engaging bombast: There is something about encountering a gigantic
horseshoe _ like the one in Marfa, which Oldenburg made to honor an
old military horse _ that makes life seem sweeter and a bit less
serious.
</P>
<P>
   SIGMAR POLKE (German, born in 1941)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Radically crude images executed in a wide range of
media
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT RAUSCHENBERG (American, born in 1925)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Pioneering a number of major art forms, including
photo-transfer, a process of transferring photos onto metal,
plaster, cloth, canvas, and other materials.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by: Gabriella Fanning, publisher of ``Art on Paper'' and
``Art Byte''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one deeply involved in the contemporary art world can
adequately make such a judgment,'' Fanning says. ``However, if I
change your question to `Which living artist would you most like to
have in your collection?' I could answer.''
</P>
<P>
   She cites Polke, whose pictures incorporate kitschy materials
and are loaded with irony, as an artist who captures her
imagination. A picture might be painted on fabric usually reserved
for a cheap tablecloth. It could be marked with abstract gestures
and human body parts, often crudely rendered, all floating and
overlapping in a seemingly random way that suggests narrative
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always has demonstrated a continuity with the past while
constantly innovating _ recently even working with computer
imaging,'' Fanning says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Rauschenberg has been so influential and has meant so much
to artists from the '60s through today. His early works,
especially, are innovative and have great expressive depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rauschenberg was also picked by Fort Worth artist Vernon Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you define importance in terms of influence, then I'd pick
Robert Rauschenberg,'' Fisher says. ``He still is underrated. But
there's a whole list of artists, like Joseph Beuys, you wouldn't
hear about if it weren't for him. There's a whole list of
movements, too _ pop, process art, performance, installation.''
</P>
<P>
   BRUCE NAUMAN (American, born in 1941)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Installations mixing lights, sound and strange
objects.
</P>
<P>
   BETYE SAAR (American, born in 1926)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Intricate assemblages made of found objects
</P>
<P>
   ANN HAMILTON (American, born in 1956)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Installations made of materials that change and decay
</P>
<P>
   SAM GILLIAM (American, born in 1933)
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Pioneering painting on unstretched canvas
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by Kenshasha Conwill, director, Studio Museum in Harlem
</P>
<P>
   Conwill names four and refuses to narrow her selection. One
reason is that she doesn't consider art a competition. Another is
that, to the extent that she believes in greatness, she believes
it's best determined in retrospect, after an artist is dead. But
her diverse group has some common threads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of these artists has some degree of international
recognition, which gives their work force and influence,'' she
says. ``But their work also has an emotional dimension that I
respond to.
</P>
<P>
   ``And each follows their own muse. Their work is honest and
authentic. They've steadily worked on ideas that engage them, and
pursue them with an integrity that has a sort of moral dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
