<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY REALITY BIT THE TOY DEPARTMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the newspaper business, they don't call us the toy department
for nothing. To locate our workplace, first take the escalator to
the top of the building, bypassing electronics, household goods,
cosmetics, jewelry, furniture, and also Dennis Rodman's favorite,
women's lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   And then, once you've escaped the real world, there we are,
totally isolated from reality.
</P>
<P>
   Could I possibly interest you in the Nine-Toed Deion,
battery-operated, complete with fake limp, mechanical doll?
</P>
<P>
   The real world is forced to deal with a Slobodan Milosevic.
About as bad as it gets for us is George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, there does come an occasional time when
not even the toy department can sequester itself from tragedy, from
violence, or from natural disasters. Even the normal isolation the
jock kingdom enjoys, including the media who report on that
kingdom, can be instantly shattered, so great is the emotional
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Such, of course, was the case in Denver this week, when the
city's major-league baseball team, the NBA team, and the hockey
club all immediately postponed games. In the case of hockey, an
entire playoff series was rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Colorado didn't make this request of the teams,
nor the Denver mayor. This involved owners, and mainly jocks,
acting on their own feelings. Even players from those visiting
teams in Denver requested not to play, saying they were in shock
and grief over what happened at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Sports does serve as a reality escape, but none of us can run
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the most trying of times, professional sports has almost
always provided the one constant hideout. President Roosevelt asked
major-league baseball to continue to play with makeshift rosters
during World War II, citing a national morale boost.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, the games go on, as long as a stadium or an
arena is still standing.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, what happened this week near Denver caused a
nagging personal question to resurface. For nearly four decades, I
have wondered how in the name of decency could the late Pete
Rozelle have ordered NFL teams to take the field on Sunday, Nov.
24, 1963?
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier in Dallas, President John F. Kennedy had been
shot and killed. When NFL games kicked off around the country that
weekend, it touched off an obvious controversy. Commissioner
Rozelle made a decision he would later admit haunted him forever.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to creating positive public relations for the NFL,
Rozelle was known as a master. But this?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete would say many times after that how much he considered it
a mistake,'' said Tex Schramm, a close friend of Rozelle's, and the
Cowboys' longtime president and general manager. ``But truthfully,
I thought he had made the right decision because it was an
alternative for a nation in grief. Jack Ruby, however, erased any
positive that could have come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Schramm, Rozelle contacted John Kennedy's confidant
and friend, Pierre Salinger, to ask for advice on playing the
Sunday games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salinger had been on a State Department trip to the Far East
and was returning when he called Pete on an air phone,'' said
Rozelle. ``He told Pete in his opinion Jack would want the games
played that Sunday. Salinger recommended Pete go ahead and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were at Cleveland. ``We flew in there and more than
one player was worried what might happen since we were representing
the city of Dallas,'' said Schramm. ``But then when we got the news
on what Ruby had done \Rshooting and killing Lee Harvey Oswald\S,
the whole stadium was in a mental fog anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rozelle, of course, was wishing NFL teams had not been on
the field. The toy department received a national black eye that
day. Reality bit us.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, however, no praise is necessary, or really deserved,
for decisions made by that chapter of the jock kingdom. Those
postponements were from the heart. Even the toy department has one.
/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
