<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE TRUST'S DEBTORS MUST SETTLE FOR 20 CENTS ON THE DOLLAR,
COURT SAYS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In another blow to foreign banks, a Chinese court
said Thursday that it expected to salvage only $783 million in
assets from one of China's largest and most troubled state
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Guangdong International Trust and Investment, or
GITIC, has been in bankruptcy since October, when it capsized under
$4.3 billion in debt. At a meeting of creditors Thursday in
Guangzhou, the provincial capital of Guangdong, the bankruptcy
court said that foreign and Chinese banks had lodged $5.66 billion
in claims against GITIC and three subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Although GITIC's creditors have been steeling themselves for
heavy losses since the bankruptcy, the banks now face the
likelihood of recovering less than one-fifth of their original
loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said T.K. Chang, a lawyer at Coudert
Brothers in Hong Kong, who attended the meeting as a representative
of South Korean banks. ``Previously, we would have gotten about 60
cents on the dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang based that estimate on an earlier assessment of GITIC's
finances, in which the company was reported to have $2.6 billion in
assets and $4.7 billion in liabilities. Since then, however,
GITIC's liabilities have edged up while the quality of its assets
has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors are watching GITIC's bankruptcy proceedings as
a test case of how China will deal with its financially troubled
corporate sector. Although GITIC is so far the only investment
trust company to be forced into bankruptcy, several others have
defaulted on loan payments.
</P>
<P>
   Another major state-owned company, Guangdong Enterprises
Holdings, has suspended payments on $2.9 billion in debt while it
overhauls its operations with the help of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
Executives who represent the creditors said Goldman would complete
its proposal within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's attitude toward foreign lenders has hardened over
time,'' said Gordon C. Chang, a bankruptcy lawyer in the Beijing
office of Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison. ``I think China
is seeing how hard it can push.''
</P>
<P>
   The court gave several reasons for its inability to extract more
money from GITIC, most stemming from its disastrous real estate
ventures. Several of GITIC's hotels and office buildings are losing
money, while the company is fighting lawsuits over numerous
unfinished development projects.
</P>
<P>
   After delivering its bad news, the Guangzhou Provincial People's
High Court appointed a nine-member steering committee to sort
through claims from 540 creditors, 175 foreign and 365 from
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   The steering committee includes Citibank, a unit of Citigroup;
UBS of Switzerland; two Japanese banks, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank and
Sakura Bank; Hong Kong's Hang Seng Bank, a unit of HSBC Holdings,
and two Chinese banks, the Bank of China and the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese court promised to give equal treatment to foreign
and domestic creditors. ``All debts, whether on the mainland or
outside the country, will be equally compensated,'' said Li Qi, the
deputy judge.
</P>
<P>
   But that failed to quell fears about equal treatment among
foreign banks. Chang of Coudert Brothers noted that all the banks
on the steering committee had registered their loans to GITIC with
the government. But other creditors did not seek approval, and
Chang fears they may be left empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only depend on the steering committee,'' he said.
``We're focusing, out of a lack of choice, on the fairness of the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest bad news from GITIC comes at a time when fears about
a debt crisis in China have subsided a bit. China's prime minister,
Zhu Rongji, said recently that he did not foresee a rash of
bankruptcies among state-owned companies. Beijing seems determined
to save other failing companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be further liquidations,'' said Ted
Osborn, a partner at PricewaterhouseCoopers in Hong Kong, which
represents creditors of Guangdong Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts warned that foreign bankers should not make
any assumptions. Like GITIC, the finances of Guangdong Enterprises
have become shakier as more information has seeped out. Chang of
Paul Weiss predicted that even if the company was not liquidated,
the banks could wind up taking heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is doing something good,'' he said. ``They're putting
their financial sector on a commercial footing. But predicting the
future is inherently difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
