u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-MCCARTHY-BOS &LR;      04-22 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-MCCARTHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. MCCARTHY SEES `MORAL OBLIGATION' TO CURTAIL GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A nurse turned congresswoman, whose bid for
Congress was ignited by the crackle of gunfire, Thursday said the
Capitol Hill forces that have consigned gun-control bills to
legislative limbo have been changed by the Colorado school
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by Senators Edward M. Kennedy, whose two brothers were
slain by gunmen, and Dianne Feinstein, who became mayor of San
Francisco after a 1978 City Hall assassination, Representative
Carolyn McCarthy vowed to press a floor fight to defy the powerful
gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not willing to wait another year,'' said the New York
Democrat, whose husband was killed and son wounded by a gunman in
the 1993 Long Island Railroad shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not willing to wait any longer until there's another
shooting,'' McCarthy said. ``I happen to believe Congress has a
moral obligation to stop this. I happen to think that we can do
something about this. I'm tired of people saying, `What can you do?
We can't do anything.' I don't believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   As the National Rifle Association announced plans to scale back
its annual meeting in Denver next week, lawmakers in two states
abandoned pro-gun bills, legislators in a third state sought to
hasten a measure designed to restrict access to guns, and
gun-control forces said their fortunes on Capitol Hill may be
brightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday, there was a shift in the gun debate that in my 15
years fighting for gun control I have never seen,'' Senator Charles
Schumer, a New York Democrat, said at a Capitol news conference.
``When the NRA and pro-gun state lawmakers are retreating on their
long-held views, it proves conclusively that there has to be
additional laws to protect innocent people from gun violence.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to its members this week, NRA President
Charlton Heston and Wayne LaPierre, the group's executive vice
president, said it was scuttling plans for expositions, seminars,
and other ``festive ceremonies'' out of respect for the families of
victims and the community in Littleton, Colo., just miles away from
the NRA convention site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our spirits must endure this terrible suffering together, and
so must the freedoms that bring us together,'' Heston and LaPierre
wrote. ``We must stand in somber but unshakable unity, even in this
time of anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some gun control measures have been advanced by
high-profile tragedies. The Gun Control Act of 1968, barring the
imports of certain weapons, followed the assassinations of the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. and Senator Robert F. Kennedy. And President
Bush banned imports of assault-style weapons in 1989, the year
after a gunman killed five children in a Stockton, Calif.,
schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   But the current GOP-led Congress has been less receptive to
gun-control measures, and no substantial gun legislation passed
last year in the wake of several school shootings, including the
highly publicized killings in Jonesboro, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said she met this week with House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, an Illinois Republican, and urged him to allow a floor
debate on her bill that would require handgun trigger locks, hold
adults criminally liable if a child uses their gun to commit
violence, and help trace guns used in juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Hastert said Thursday that the speaker has yet
to review the legislation and has not taken a position on it. But
McCarthy said she will petition the bill onto the floor, if she is
thwarted in efforts to move it through House committees.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, in Colorado to speak with victims'
families and school officials, said there should be a reasoned and
nonpolitical approach to curb a culture of violence. ``We have more
youth violence in these last 10 years than at any time in our
history,'' Reno said. ``We must renew our efforts, not just in
connection with this terrible tragedy, but with what we do about
guns in the hands of young people _ young people who do not know
how to safely and lawfully use them.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said the legislative efforts by
gun-control lawmakers mirror some proposals embraced by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said the Colorado slayings
should spur passage of a packet of gun-control measures the
administration will send to Congress in several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the environment is there,'' Holder said. ``I think all
the public polls always show that the American people _ the vast
majority of the American people _ support reasonable restrictions
placed on the possession of guns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
