u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-TRADE-NYT &LR;      04-22 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD TRADE STUDY SAYS EXPORT GROWTH MAY SLOW FURTHER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The rate of growth in world merchandise exports fell to
3.5 percent last year, only one-third of its 1997 growth rate of
10.5 percent, mainly because of the Asian economic crisis, the
World Trade Organization said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The organization said in an annual appraisal of global trade
trends that export growth could slow further in 1999, depending
largely on what happens in the United States, the strongest
industrial nation. Many expect American growth to slow later this
year, which could reduce exports to U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that part of 1998s decline in export growth
reflected lower commodity prices, including a 30 percent drop in
the price of oil. Other commodity prices fell 20 percent in 1998,
said Patrick Low, the World Trade Organization's chief economist.
</P>
<P>
   The report said 1998 was the first time since World War II that
commodity exports represented less than 20 percent of all exports.
Many developing countries are still highly dependent on the exports
of commodities, particularly food, and a continuing decline in
world prices on such raw products has widened the disparity between
rich and poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   Trade performance in 1998 varied widely among regions. Exports
increased 3 percent from North America, while imports there rose
10.5 percent. Increases up to 10 percent in exports and imports
were recorded in Latin America and some Eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Western Europe was the only region where the growth rate in
imports did not fall from a year earlier. It remained at 7.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Imports into Asian countries fell over all by 8.5 percent last
year, and by double that in the once-booming economies of Hong
Kong, Malaysia, South Korea, Singapore, Taiwan and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Low said at a news conference that signs of improvement in Asian
economies could mean that exports to Asia increase in 1999. ``But
if we see too sharp a slowdown in the United States and Western
Europe,'' he said, ``then this will definitely threaten to swamp
whatever happens in Asia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
