u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NABISCO-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      04-22 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO LITIGATION CONTRIBUTES TO 54 PERCENT DROP EARNINGS BY RJR
NABISCO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its final quarter as an international tobacco and food
company, the RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. reported Thursday that its
first-quarter earnings fell 54 percent because of costs to settle
tobacco litigation and declining cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   Profit from operations fell to $83 million, or 24 cents a
diluted share, compared with $179 million, or 52 cents a share, in
the quarter a year earlier. Analysts expected RJR to earn 28 cents
a share, according to the First Call Corp., which tracks company
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 6.9 percent, to $4.22 billion, aided by higher
cigarette prices.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in first-quarter profit reflected costs of RJR's share
of the $206 billion settlement the tobacco industry reached with 46
states in November, as well as falling demand for cigarettes
related to a price increase that began last fall. Still, the profit
was far better than the company recorded in the fourth quarter of
last year, one analyst noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry went through the most troublesome quarter in
history, both as a result of planned changes to the dynamics of the
U.S. tobacco industry because of the settlement and a difficult
international environment,'' said Martin Feldman, an analyst at
Salomon Smith Barney. ``But RJR more than doubled what it made in
the fourth quarter of 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, RJR's chairman and chief executive, Steven F.
Goldstone, said that the company would sell its international
tobacco division to a Japanese buyer for $8 billion and spin off
its domestic tobacco division. That would leave only its Nabisco
shares under the company's control, and RJR would be renamed
Nabisco Holdings Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The company's largest shareholder, Carl Icahn, has challenged
the plan, saying the food business should be spun off instead and
nominated an alternate board of directors. Shareholders are to vote
on the competing plans at the company's annual meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic tobacco sales were $1.65 billion in the quarter, up
40.3 percent from $1.18 billion in the first quarter of 1998.
Volume was lower, though, falling 14 percent, which management
attributed to the higher prices. The entire cigarette industry's
sales declined 10 percent in the quarter, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   RJR's market share slipped as well, by nearly one full
percentage point, to 24.57 percent. Its higher-priced brands had
varying results, with Camel increasing its share slightly, to 5.23
percent, but Winston falling to 5.32 percent, from 5.65 percent in
the corresponding period in 1998. The company blamed ``heavy
competitive discounting and promotion'' for the decline.
</P>
<P>
   International tobacco sales continued to suffer, falling 31
percent compared with sales in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its Nabisco Foods division showed improvement,
even though worldwide sales rose just 1 percent, to $1.85 billion.
Cookie and cracker sales increased 4 percent, with the company
crediting promotions for cookies like Oreos, Teddy Grahams and
cheese-flavored snacks like Cheese Nips for the growth.
</P>
<P>
   Profit, however, fell 15 percent, to $121 million, which the
company attributed to brand promotions and the cost of improving
its sales force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
