<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TALKS WITH HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS ABOUT COLORADO ATTACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER DAY 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton met with a group of suburban high
school students Thursday to discuss the Colorado shooting and what
can be done to prevent such incidents, including possible
gun-control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling the availability of guns was the administration's
focus a day after two students opened fire with semiautomatic
weapons on a rampage through Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., on Tuesday, killing 13 and wounding 23 before killing
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Attorney General Eric Holder told reporters
Wednesday the most positive thing that could come from the massacre
would be momentum to pass ``reasonable restrictions placed on the
possession of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a culture of having a right to own weapons and a right
to use them, and a big hunting culture. I grew up in it,
participated in it and enjoyed it very much,'' the president told
students at T.C. Williams High School in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little thing I have tried to do, from passing the Brady
bill to passing the assault weapons ban, all these things were met
with violent opposition as if I was trying to destroy the American
way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all I was trying to do is keep more people alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Manown, a spokesman for the National Rifle Association,
which has lobbied strongly against gun-control legislation, said it
was not ``appropriate for us to engage in a political debate at
this time'' and declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho and an NRA board
member, said the Colorado gunmen broke several existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking at it in a deeper sense as to what drives kids to
do something so horrible,'' spokesman Will Hart said. ``There's
quite possibly a bigger issue at stake than legislation or gun
control could ever mend.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control legislation the Clinton administration would like to
see passed includes:
</P>
<P>
   Prohibitions on youths who have been convicted of serious crimes
from ever being allowed to possess a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Requirements for gun manufacturers to equip every gun with
trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Reauthorization of the Brady Law that would require a three-day
wait before purchasing a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Instant background checks for those who make purchases at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties for adults who allow minors easy access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for expansion of a program that allows law enforcement
officers to track and shut down sources where youths illegally
obtain guns.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., whose husband was killed and her
son injured by a gunman who opened fire on a commuter train, pushed
legislation she introduced last year to make it more difficult for
children to get guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's meeting with the students, which was broadcast live
to 12,000 schools nationwide, he reassured the youths that schools
are still safe, touted the benefits of peer mediation and pushed
for funding for more after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   The president also drew a comparison between Serbian aggression
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and the aggression the two
gunmen in Colorado took against fellow classmates who had ridiculed
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the wrong reaction to the fact that they were
dissed,'' Clinton said. ``Look, everybody gets dissed sometimes in
life _ even the president _ sometimes especially the president.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
