<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US NINTH IN FUNDING   TO COMBAT AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a percentage of national wealth, the United States ranks
ninth in the amount it donates to combat AIDS worldwide, the United
Nations' AIDS agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   US contributions toward AIDS control amount to only $17 for
every $1 million of the nation's gross national product, an overall
measure of national wealth. By contrast, Norway spends $93 per $1
million of GNP and the Netherlands $92.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the annual US contribution fell by $2.5 million
between 1996 and 1997, the most recent data available.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers come from the most comprehensive financial
accounting done in the 20-year history of the global AIDS epidemic,
done in collaboration between UNAIDS, a UN agency, and researchers
at the Harvard School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The project identified $549 million in AIDS donations from all
sources in 1996, half of it from governments.
</P>
<P>
   Overall funding for AIDS control has fallen far behind the pace
of the global epidemic, which is ``expanding three times faster
than the funding to control it,'' said Dr. Peter Piot, executive
director of UNAIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people infected with the AIDS virus more than
tripled between 1990 and 1997, said the UNAIDS analysis. But money
to fight AIDS in developing nations, where 95 percent of infected
individuals live, rose only 66 percent between 1990 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donor nations must realize that their substantial investments
toward improving conditions in developing countries will be
effectively obliterated unless more is invested in fighting AIDS _
the single greatest threat to global development today,'' Piot
said.
</P>
<P>
   The amount allocated to fighting AIDS amounts to less than one
percent of donor countries' budgets for fostering economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   But that amount actually fell by $2.5 million from the previous
year, the UNAIDS report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the number of dollars, the US looks really
good, but when you put it in terms of economic capacity, it's a
pretty paltry showing,'' said Mary Pat Kieffer of the
Francois-Xavier Bagnoud Center for Health and Human Rights at
Harvard, an analyst involved in the two-year effort to compile
global AIDS funding data.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on AIDS prevention is not always concentrated on areas
where the epidemic is spreading fastest. Only one-quarter of global
spending is devoted to sub-Saharan Africa, the most severely
affected region.
</P>
<P>
   Within Africa there are enormous disparities, ranging from a
high of $37 million on AIDS prevention in Uganda _ where strong
government support has turned the tide of new infections _ to a low
of less than $4 million in Nigeria, which has one of the region's
highest rate of AIDS virus infections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9589 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT &LR;      04-22 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE PAYS A CALL ON MILOSEVIC, BUT HE WAS NOT AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ NATO sent a missile into the bedroom of
Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic, early Thursday morning,
but insisted it was nothing personal.
</P>
<P>
   Three missiles devastated the elegant 1936 villa in the wealthy
Dedinje district at 15 Uzicka Street, the most famous address in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   An eclectic two-story building of white stucco, with columns and
rounded windows that its original owner described as a little
Hollywood in inspiration, the villa was built as a private house
and finished in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Tito appropriated the house for himself in 1944, after taking
power in Belgrade, and Yugoslav leaders have lived there since
then, making it an official residence.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is a charred ruin. One entire side wall of the structure
is blown away, all the windows are broken, and many trees in the
surrounding parkland have been uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   There are gaping holes where the missiles pierced the walls,
flares of soot shoot from the arches of the empty window frames,
and chunks of concrete and broken glass are scattered over the
lavish grounds.
</P>
<P>
   NATO may have intended its missiles as a message to Milosevic,
who has not been sleeping at the house in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tito, who is associated with the house more than any of his
successors, is buried in a sort of mausoleum 200 yards away in what
is known as the House of Flowers, a glassed-in structure where he
used to run the government in the summertime. Serbian television
gave no indication of any damage to the House of Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Yugoslav officials were livid in Milosevic's name.
They accused NATO of trying to assassinate the leader of a
sovereign state, and said the other missiles, which hit at about
3:15 a.m., had struck the living and dining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been avoiding the house ever since a
little-reported missile attack on a nearby building housing his
presidential guard, in which as many as 30 people are said to have
been killed, Serbian officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, for its part, claimed that the building was a vital link
in the military command system of Yugoslavia and that the strike
had nothing to do with Milosevic or its symbolic importance to the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   But this building was no radar station, and some Serbs reacted
with anger and incredulity.
</P>
<P>
   A Serbian photographer said: ``This is simply demagoguery.
Whether one likes Milosevic or not, this is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Serbian journalist with the magazine Vreme said: ``This
building is part of our cultural heritage. Yesterday Tito lived
there, and today Milosevic does, but tomorrow it will be Pera
Pric.'' That is the Serbian form of John Doe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO wants to pretend now that it's hit at the heart of the
repressive regime and not the Serbian nation, it's not true,
because they've only done this after a month of hitting civilian
targets,'' the journalist said.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist, who asked for anonymity, bemoaned the regular
trashing of Belgrade's cultural history, saying, ``When people come
to visit Belgrade, I can't show them a building more than 200 years
old, because every 50 years somebody bombs and blows them away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
