<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T ups ante for MediaOne
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell and Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AT&AMP;T has thrown a $62 billion bid on the table for
MediaOne _ $8.6 billion higher than the offer made weeks ago by
Comcast.
</P>
<P>
   With MediaOne, AT&AMP;T would become America's leading cable
provider with access to one-third of the nation's homes _ including
540,000 served by MediaOne in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning move is aimed at giving AT&AMP;T direct connections to
homes, detouring around lines owned by regional phone companies
such as BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the deal would allow the New York-based giant to
offer all manner of communications _ including local phone service,
long-distance, television and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding war for MediaOne is yet another dramatic sign of
consolidation in communications and media businesses. AT&AMP;T is the
nation's largest phone company, with one-half of the $90
billion-a-year long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T last month completed purchase of Tele-Communications Inc.,
which had been the nation's second-largest cable company. TCI had
virtually no presence in northern Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, MediaOne is the largest cable provider and has
spent hundreds of millions of dollars upgrading its system to
handle high-speed Net access, as well as television and phone
service.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne in metro Atlanta is offering a local phone service
competing with BellSouth. But the service is limited to places
where the costly upgrade has been made.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday, Comcast had not responded to the AT&AMP;T bid.
Officials at MediaOne, who had agreed to Comcast's proposal, would
say only that they were reviewing the AT&AMP;T bid.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever buys MediaOne will be part of a trend that is global:
consolidation. The AT&AMP;T offer came on the heels of an $80 billion
deal between the national phone companies of Germany and Italy.
Earlier this week, BellSouth announced it was buying 10 percent of
Qwest Communications, a company that specializes in high-speed
data.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
