<HEADER>
A9592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-BUSINESS23-COX     04-22 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-BUSINESS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slower profits won't sidetrack Intel, execs say
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Intel Corp. has used its mastery of microprocessor
technology to build the world's largest, richest and most powerful
computer chip company.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Santa Clara, Calif., company's senior
management told Wall Street analysts that it retains its old magic
despite the seismic changes that are undermining profits in its
main market, the personal computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   The old magic has a new Internet theme to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be the building block supplier to the Internet
economy,'' said Chief Executive Craig Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   That means developing faster and more powerful processor chips
for desktop computers that use the Internet and for server
computers than run Internet Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel's Internet strategy also is reaching into new areas.
The company revealed that it has formed the Intel Data Services
Division, which will create a global network of 10 or more service
centers located in the United States, Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Each center will have 2,000 or more server computers and cost
between $50 million and $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The centers will essentially become information processing
centers for electronic commerce and will speed up smooth and global
Internet electronic commerce around the globe, Intel promises.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett stressed that his company doesn't expect its core
market, the personal computer business, will dwindle, however.
Intel, he said, is simply building on its core business and
expanding into related markets with high growth opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent is to make sure that networked bits (information)
will be shaped and shipped primarily by Intel silicon and Intel
services,'' said Intel Chairman Andrew Grove.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's new strategy probably means more competition for
companies like Motorola Inc. and Lucent Technologies Inc., among
others, that traditionally have devoted more of their businesses to
designing and selling chips to the communications business.
</P>
<P>
   As they spelled out new business opportunities at a meeting with
analysts in New York, Intel officials minimized concerns that
falling prices for personal computers will hurt the average prices
they can get for its processor chips.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is pushing hard at developing high-end chips for
engineering workstations, network server computers and high-end
notebook computers. Its most expensive chips sell for more than
$3,600 each. That helps balance the effects of its low-end Celeron
chips, some of which cost less than $70 each, on the company's
average product prices.
</P>
<P>
   What that means, analysts said, is that the trend toward
low-cost consumer computers probably isn't a sizable business
threat to Intel in the near-term future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going in the right direction,'' said Venu Reddy, an
analyst with Waddell &AMP; Reed Investment Management Co. in Kansas
City. ``It looks like they are going to be the dominant platform
for computing for the next decade.'' But Intel doesn't intend to
stick with just computer chips. It intends to dominate a whole new
market, communications chips, where it has not been a player in the
past. Intel officials said the pending acquisition of Level One
Communications will give them a leg up to become leaders in selling
new kinds of communications processors that will be used to build
new kinds of networks that seamlessly tie voice and data
communications together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC was bound to evolve into a communications device,''
said George Balaschak, president of Boston Capital Advisors Inc.
``This is a natural extension of Intel's involvement with the PC. I
think Intel will do extremely well in making communications chips.
I think they can dominate.'' Barrett said he expects to see both
the communications chip business and the data services business
becoming multibillion-dollar industries within the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   He also hinted that two of the company's design centers in
Austin _ a joint venture design project with Analog Devices Inc.
and its StrongARM embedded processor project _ could lead to Intel
chips being sold to makers of next-generation cellular phones and
other hand-held communications devices.
</P>
<P>
   Intel officials said they expect their Austin design center will
grow to several hundred workers over time.
</P>
<P>
   Intel recorded $6.07 billion in profits on record revenue of
$26.3 billion in 1998 as the chipmaker pushed production of
high-performance, and high-price, chips that power engineering
workstations and network server computers. At the same time, Intel
engaged in a cost-cutting campaign that slashed its manufacturing
expenses on its low-end Celeron processors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
