<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-HNS &LR;      04-22 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ CHAIRMAN FACES THE STOCKHOLDERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Benjamin Rosen, the Compaq Computer Corp. chairman who
has taken the company's reins after ousting its chief executive,
faced stockholders who were alternately pleased and angry in a
spirited annual meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer session after the meeting's formalities
were concluded, Rosen listened patiently to everything from
accusations of illegal insider trading to suggestions that the
company merge with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   A request that the Houston-based computer maker sell shares of
its pending AltaVista Co. spinoff to current Compaq stockholders at
the offering's initial price drew enthusiastic applause but no
commitments from Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very complicated to do,'' Rosen said. ``Present plans
are to have a public offering of a minority stake reflecting the
value of the company, but the details of how that offering is (to
be) done have not been defined yet. But we certainly hear what you
are requesting.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Rosen's first appearance before stockholders since
Eckhard Pfeiffer, Compaq's chief executive since late 1991, and
Chief Financial Officer Earl Mason resigned on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen, along with board members Robert Ted Enloe and Frank
Doyle, have formed a three-member ``office of the chief executive''
to run the company.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq reported profits of 16 cents a share on Wednesday, a
penny over the estimate given in the April 9 earnings warning that
presaged Pfeiffer's departure. Before the warning, analysts had
expected Compaq to have profits of about twice that figure.
</P>
<P>
   Several shareholders complimented Rosen on ``cleaning house,''
but one asked, ``What took the board so long?''
</P>
<P>
   ``From what you have said, this was going on for five
quarters,'' the shareholder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This board has a serious responsibility, and the board cannot
act capriciously, or act on a single data point,'' Rosen said. ``On
the other hand, a board can't do as they did at IBM and Digital,
where red flags were flying after five and six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen repeated the declarations given to analysts and the press
over the last several days that he, Enloe and Doyle are studying
all facets of the company and will take ``whatever action is
necessary to address the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said again that his goal is to ``re-energize'' Compaq.
Rosen told reporters after the meeting that Compaq has become too
bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bureaucracy gets in the way of making decisions quickly,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen also heard from several shareholders _ including one who
flew in from Tokyo _ who were upset over sales of large amounts of
stock by board members and senior executives in February. Shortly
afterward, Compaq's stock began a tumble that has reduced its price
by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   The sales have inspired several shareholder lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said the sales were approved by the company's lawyers, and
were made in a narrow window during which the company's officers
may sell shares. He told reporters after the meeting that the sales
were related to stock options and were considered part of the
executives' compensation package.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one shareholder called on members of the board and
senior executives to say whether they would express their
confidence in the stock by doing some ``insider buying.'' Only one
executive raised his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The standing-room crowd _ which spilled into two overflow rooms
on Compaq's northwest Harris County campus _ was most enthusiastic
about the idea of getting AltaVista shares at a cut-rate price.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders at the meeting proposed being allowed to buy stock
in AltaVista's spinoff at the initial price, before it hits the
market _ which could happen as early as this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Initial public offerings of Internet stocks have hit the market
at many times their opening prices. Under the proposal, current
Compaq shareholders would be able to buy shares at the opening
price, before market forces took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said the option was being looked at, but that it may be
legally complicated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard S. Chu, an analyst with SG Cowen &AMP; Co. in San Francisco,
said structuring the spinoff in that way would be unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Selling shares of a hot stock to existing Compaq shareholders
would drive up the price of Compaq's stock, but only temporarily,
Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be transient, like announcing a special dividend,''
he said. ``But once it was paid out, the value would dissipate.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
