u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-IMMIG-NYT &LR;      04-22 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION PLAN WILL OFFER KOSOVO REFUGEES PERMANENT RESIDENCE
IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A White House plan to bring 20,000 refugees from
Kosovo to the United States will make all of them eligible for
permanent legal residence, a senior administration official said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the administration expects that many of the refugees
will choose, after the war in Yugoslavia ends, not to go back to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian-American groups and some private refugee organizations
reacted angrily on Thursday to the relocation plan, arguing that
while it is a humane offer, it sends a signal that the United
States does not expect the refugees will be able to return to
Kosovo any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The relocation plan, announced Wednesday by Vice President Al
Gore in a speech at Ellis Island in New York harbour , would screen
Kosovo Albanians who have fled to refugee camps in Macedonia to
find 20,000 who have family in the United States or who are at risk
because of illness. Gore said the refugees would not be granted
political asylum. ``We anticipate their return to Kosovo,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But an administration official involved in planning the
relocation program said on Thursday that the refugees would be
accepted into the United States under a law that each year provides
about 75,000 refugees from around the world with federal housing,
health and job-assistance benefits. After 12 months, they would
have the option, under the law, of accepting a green card, which
confers permanent resident status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the refugee program is used when it is clear
that the situation at home isn't resolvable,'' said the
administration official, who spoke on the condition that his name
not be used. ``We are going to try to create conditions in Kosovo
for these people to return, but the choice will ultimately be
theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The relocation plan, a repackaging of another much-criticized
White House proposal to fly tens of thousands of Kosovo refugees to
the naval base at Guantanamo Bay in Cuba, grew out of President
Clinton's decision that the Albanian refugees under U.S. care
should not be confined in a prison-like camp, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president himself realized that it just isn't right for
these people to be so isolated from their loved ones and others
that they might need,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also grew out of a desire in the White House to relieve
pressure on the Macedonian government, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonians have been alarmed by a flood of about 130,000
ethnic Albanian refugees who have been pushed out of Kosovo by the
security forces of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Slav majority in Macedonia has frequently come into conflict
with the ethnic Albanian minority, which makes up about one-third
of the population. Fearing that the ethnic Albanian refugees from
Kosovo will join forces with their ethnic Albanians, the Macedonian
government has alternately closed its borders, harassed the
refugees and cooperated with international groups building refugee
camps.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, it has complained bitterly to the United States
and Western Europe, demanding that the refugees be flown away to
third countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some basis to the Macedonians' concern,'' said the
administration official. ``It is a very new government. The last
thing we want to do is create another Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, about 17,000 refugees from Macedonia have been sent
to 11 countries, with about 10,000 going to Germany. The White
House did not know on Thursday if those countries are offering the
same permanent resident status to Kosovars as planned by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee groups have criticized the relocation of Kosovo refugees
to third countries, saying that it split up families and that some
refugees did not want to leave the region. Television pictures two
weeks ago showed weeping refugees boarding a plane for Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said its new program will be voluntary,
carefully coordinated with refugee groups and that it is not
intended to change the basic goals of NATO's war against the
Milosevic government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a small part of a larger strategy to get people back
to their homes and that is the point of the military operation,''
said David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council.
``This is designed to give the Kosovars a number of options. No one
will come that doesn't want to. All will have their return flights
paid, so they can go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanian-Americans who are raising money to help the refugees
said on Thursday, however, that they do not think the White House
has thought through the consequences and symbolism of the
relocation program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed because this stuff all supports
Milosevic's plan for ethnic cleansing,'' said Avni Mustafaj,
director of the Kosovo Relief Fund, a New York group that raises
money for the refugees. ``It gives some people relief, and for that
we are glad. But once you start sending people out of the region,
the odds of them returning become smaller and smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Some human-rights groups were critical of the program because,
they said, it appeased the Macedonian government's mistreatment of
refugees and because it sends a signal that Washington accepts
ethnic cleansing as an accomplished fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signal we are sending to Milosevic is a disaster,'' said
Holly Burkholter, advocacy director for Physicians for Human
Rights, a Boston group that has eight monitors in the Balkans.
``This program is minuscule in comparison to the problem, and its
humanitarian usefulness is eclipsed by the political signal it
sends _ that we don't expect these people to be able to come home
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States Committee for Refugees, a group that defends
the rights of refugees worldwide, was less critical on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration deserves credit for showing flexibility,''
said Bill Frelick, senior policy analyst for the group. ``It
switched from the Guantanamo plan for immediate evacuation and is
putting together a voluntary plan that will look for family
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Frelick said that it is unlikely that many of the refugees who
do enter the United States under the administration plan will want
to go back to burned and looted homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A team of officials from Washington will fly to Macedonia this
weekend to begin setting up the selection process for refugees,
according to the White House. There are about 500,000 people of
Albanian descent in the United States, about half of them in the
New York metropolitan area. A large percentage of the Kosovo
refugees are expected to settle there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
