<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reno urges Americans to address violence
 &HT;    By C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. _ U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno Thursday used
the killing rampage at Columbine High School to urge the nation to
deal with the culture of violence crippling America's youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had more youth violence in the last 10 years than in
previous history,'' Reno told a battery of television cameras at
the Jefferson County Courthouse on Thursday. ``We must not be
complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno steered clear of talking about the mass killings or any
details of the help the U.S. Justice Department is providing to the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she talked about the inspiration she has witnessed
since coming to Denver on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Reno suggested Americans stop youth violence through initiatives
that deal with the way guns get into the hands of youth, and the
values parents instill in their children.
</P>
<P>
   Reno warned the nation not to politicize the tragedy. Instead,
she encouraged those locally and nationally to work together to
solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
   The events of this week will not be remembered by the students
of Columbine as only a tragedy, said Reno, who met with some
students on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students and the community don't want to be known for
tragedy,'' she said. ``They want to be known as the school that
overcame adversity and tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a message self-described high school ``stoner'' Josh
Neilson said he and the athletes he used to not get along with have
come to an understanding about the last couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to talk about our differences,'' he said. ``But that
has changed now. We need to be together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
