<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-MONTENEGRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLY BACKS MONTENEGRO-SERB LINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ Feeding a growing tension between local
police and the national Yugoslav Army, 10,000 people filled the
heavily-guarded central square of Montenegro's capital Thursday to
demand the republic show solidarity with its sister republic of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, one of a series of anti-NATO demonstrations, was as
much a denunciation of the fragile government of Montenegrin
President Milo Djukanovic as a call to end the bombing. Djukanovic
has striven to maintain his authority over Montenegro through the
republic's police force, despite moves by the army to take control
away from the police. Many here fear the dispute could result in
civil war in the republic, which with Serbia makes up what is left
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be allowed that the police in Montenegro are
equipped and trained for conflict with the Yugoslav Army,'' Momir
Bulatovic, a close ally of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
said at the rally. Bulatovic lost to Djukanovic in last year's
presidential election in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way is to take the police under control of our army.
They've got to obey or they won't exist,'' he told the cheering
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrins have held anti-NATO rallies since the bombing began
last month. Thursday's protest was significant because of the
presence of Bulatovic, who is prime minister of Yugoslavia under
Milosevic and traveled from Belgrade for the event. The
pro-Milosevic camp is growing in Montenegro, threatening the
stability of the republic, whose government leans toward the West
and has declared neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Djukanovic is in real trouble now,'' said a middle-aged man at
the rally, who would not give his name. ``We gathered here in large
numbers. It's just a matter of time before he loses his position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic called the Montenegrin leader a ``puppet of the United
States,'' and the crowd screamed ``Traitor! Traitor!'' every time
Djukanovic's name was mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of supporting the Army, Djukanovic is creating his own
defense force,'' said Zoran Zizic, deputy chairman of Milosevic's
Socialist Party. ``There is no way to have two armies in
Montenegro. When this is all finished, we shall know who was right,
who was wrong, who was faithful, and who was not.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was heavily guarded by both army soldiers in
riot gear and local police, and both forces lined the streets
leading to the rally, weapons at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators carried posters that said ``Target,'' and others
displayed images of the cross-shaped NATO symbol twisted into a
Nazi swastika.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man approached by an Italian journalist leaped from
his perch at the base of a statue when asked his opinion of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are spies! You are bombing us!'' he said, shaking his
finger in the reporter's face.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Army has demanded that the Montenegrin police
surrender authority to them, but the police have refused. The most
recent confrontation was at the Croatia border, where several
hundred soldiers closed the border pass this week.
</P>
<P>
   The crossing reopened Thursday after negotiations between the
Montenegrin government and the police, but both the army and the
police are still watching over it in an uneasy standoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
