<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER ITCHING TO BE IN ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The white towel is usually a dead giveaway.
If the towel is draping his bald dome like a bonnet, Derek Harper
is preparing to sit 48 minutes on the Los Angeles Lakers bench.
</P>
<P>
   After four straight games of that hooded posture, all part of
coach Kurt Rambis' campaign to rest him for the playoffs, Harper is
getting antsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' he said, ``but you can't do it without
being put out there. . . . It's his decision, he says I need rest,
and all I can do is rest.''
</P>
<P>
   This is new territory for the 16th-year veteran, who has been
healthy and ready to play for most of the last week, despite the
official explanation that he had a sore right foot. He played just
seven minutes off the bench last week at Portland and has played
zero minutes in the four games since.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rambis is starting Derek Fisher at point guard and
giving big minutes to rookie Tyronn Lue, trying to determine which
two-man combination the Lakers will use in the playoffs. So Harper,
who went to the bench after shooting 27 percent in his previous 10
games, sits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm more tired than anybody else,'' he said. ``I
guess the concern is me being 37 and having 15 years under my belt.
I think they're supposedly looking out for me, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced of it (needing to rest), but I'm not going
to question what he wants to do as a coach,'' he added. ``And
obviously he wants to experiment and do some other things and try
some other people and all those things. If that's the case, then so
be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet one concern, health, begets another _ rust. Harper worries
he'll lose his rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you turn water on and off during the playoffs,''
Harper said. ``I'm not superhuman. I can't just turn it on when the
playoffs start. . . . I don't think you can be sharp just sitting
through games. So whatever (Rambis') thinking is, hopefully it'll
work.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The results: Rambis appears to be leaning toward a
combination of Harper and either Lue or Fisher for the playoffs,
but neither has distinguished himself.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher has started the past five games, shooting 28 percent,
averaging 3.6 points and 3.2 assists in 24.8 minutes. He has just
three assists in his past three games after combining for 17
against Portland and Utah last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the same span, Lue has averaged 7.4 points and 2.4 assists in
22.8 minutes and is shooting 39 percent. He played most of the
fourth quarter and all of overtime in the Lakers' comeback win at
Golden State on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hold the Rice: Since returning from a bout with tonsillitis
four games ago, Glen Rice is shooting 31 percent (18 for 58) and
averaging just 13.3 points. In the past two games, he's 8 for 33
(24.2 percent), including 3 for 14 from 3-point range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
