</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DURANGO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DURANGO' IS WARM AND FUZZY BUT NOT GREAT THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hallmark Hall of Fame presentations go well with pancakes. The
syrup flows freely and sweetly, and, unlike Saturday mornings in a
large household, it never seems to run out.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 201st installment in the H.H. of F. body of work is a
worthy representative of this sticky genre. ``Durango'' takes us
back to 1939 in County Kerry, Ireland, where fields are dewy,
cheeks are rosy and accents are lilty. Mark Doran, a young man with
destiny writ large on his forehead, wants to get the best of a
greedy merchant named Vestor McCarthy, who has managed to keep
cattle prices _ and the local population _ depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Doran's bold idea is a 40-mile cattle drive to another town
where the
</P>
<P>
   market isn't monopolized by one individual. The route is
arduous, but Doran believes the trip will be worth it to get a fair
price _ and to get McCarthy's goat.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, McCarthy (Ian McElhinney) won't take the prospect of
financial ruin lying down. And so the stage is set: good vs. evil,
right vs. wrong, honor vs. treachery. We know the drill.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and what would a heroic Irish tale be without a love story?
Doran wants to marry Annie (Nancy St. Alban), the beautiful
daughter of the curmudgeonly Fergus Mullaney (Patrick Bergin), who
supports Doran's cattle drive but doesn't fancy losing his daughter
to the lad.
</P>
<P>
   The story is based on an experience that Irish author John Keane
remembers from his boyhood in the town of Listowel. He wrote a
novel about it seven years ago to remind himself of the event, and
of its importance to a small town of poor, courageous people.
</P>
<P>
   But Keane's story, or at least its translation to the small
screen, is so knowable that it's actually a little surprising when
all of the trite plot developments unfold as expected. Indeed, the
only surprise in ``Durango'' is that it's not a western. (The name
comes from the western-themed tavern that waits at the end of the
cattle drive.)
</P>
<P>
   When a story is this familiar, the writing and the performances
had better be off the charts. But not so. Walter Bernstein's script
sparkles here and there, but it ultimately fails to bring any depth
to the characters, many of whom are supposed to be just that _
colorful characters _ yet don't get enough time to establish
themselves. Thus, even the wonderful Brenda Fricker, as Doran's
feisty Aunt Maeve, is left trying to pour her considerable talent
into a shallow vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Shallow is the best summation of ``Durango.'' Matt Keeslar
gamely holds the story together as the principled and determined
Mark Doran. And George Hearn is amusing as an unconventional
Protestant clergyman. But the ``Durango'' story is the same
young-leader-coming-of-age saga that the A&AMP;E Network has been
telling all this month in its ``Horatio Hornblower'' series.
Frankly, ``Hornblower'' does it much better, with more engaging
stories and more thoughtful performances.
</P>
<P>
   Still, viewers who like lush scenery, uncomplicated stories and
swelling musical scores will find plenty to like in this
warm-and-fuzzy Hallmark Hall of Fame presentation. What they won't
find is great theater or intellectual stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   Durango. Two-hour Hallmark Hall of Fame movie about a young
Irishman who undertakes a 40-mile cattle drive in order to get a
fair price for his town's livestock. Starring Matt Keeslar, Brenda
Fricker, Nancy St. Alban, George Hearn and Patrick Bergin. Sunday.
Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
