<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9608 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-22 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO EXPECTED TO REJECT MILOSEVECH PEACE OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and NATO allies were
poised to reject an offer Thursday by Yugoslavia's embattled
president, Slobodan Milosevic, to permit the United Nations to keep
peace in Kosovo if NATO forces stop pummeling his country.
</P>
<P>
   Former Russian prime minister Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, who met
throughout the day with Milosevic in Belgrade, told reporters the
Yugoslav leader had agreed in principle to ``the possibility of an
international presence led by the UN'' if NATO calls off its
five-week air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The talks came the morning after the NATO airstrikes hit home
for Milosevic, as cruise missiles ripped into one of his
presidential mansions in Belgrade, blowing apart his living room,
dining room and bedroom. Milosevic and his family were not in the
house when the missiles struck.
</P>
<P>
   Early this morning, air strikes hit the Serbian state television
(RTS) building, taking all channels off the air, residents said.
``The RTS building has been hit,'' said one witness. ``There is
smoke everywhere and there are people inside the building.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as NATO agreed to formally reassess
the prospect of deploying ground troops to drive Serb forces out of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But US and NATO officials saw little more in Milosevic's
apparent agreement with Chernomyrdin, Russia's envoy to the
Balkans, than the first signs of hope that the Yugoslav president's
defiance may be dissolving amid the NATO assault.
</P>
<P>
   Barring major changes to the Milosevic offer, administration
officials said privately, the 19-nation NATO alliance is expected
to reject the plan because it contains two highly unacceptable
elements: barring armed troops from serving on a security force in
Kosovo and granting control of the peacekeepers to the UN rather
than NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the offer also raised suspicion in the White House
that Milosevic, who often feigned peace overtures before the NATO
bombing raids began, was engaging in a diplomatic ploy to score
public relations points and divide NATO on the eve of the
alliance's 50th-anniversary summit, which opens Friday in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, in a statement issued by his office after the
Chernomyrdin meeting, said: ``Yugoslavia and Russia are firmly
determined to jointly work for a peaceful resolution of the
problems in Kosovo, and that can be achieved only through political
means.''
</P>
<P>
   But the statement made no reference to permitting an
``international presence'' in Kosovo. And the statement reflected a
continuation of Milosevic's provocative rhetoric, as he ``condemned
the aggression of NATO ...and stressed that it must be stopped
without further delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking to reporters in the Rose Garden Thursday
afternoon, said he had just learned of Chernomyrdin's comments and
had no additional information. ``If there is an offer for a genuine
security force, that's the first time that Mr. Milosevic has ever
done that,'' Clinton said. ``That represents, I suppose, some step
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, Clinton had assailed Milosevic's ``reckless
tyranny'' and warned him to accept peace on NATO's terms or ``watch
as NATO grinds down his war machine.''
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments on the 30th day of NATO air
raids aimed at halting the alleged genocide, rape and forced
expulsions by Serb forces that have driven 1.4 million ethnic
Albanians from their homes in Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   --American and British officials reiterated their opposition to
invading Kosovo with ground troops, although they endorsed the NATO
move to assess the possibility of mounting such an attack.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said a study last year
determined that NATO would need as many as 75,000 troops to invade
Kosovo and at least 200,000 to fight all the way to the Yugoslav
capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not favor the deployment of ground troops into a hostile
environment in Kosovo,'' said Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   --The Pentagon said NATO has damaged all four major routes from
Serbia into Kosovo, cutting the ability of Milosevic's forces to
supply ammunition, fuel and other supplies to the troops that are
carrying out the campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Though the supply flow has been cut in half, the Pentagon said,
Serb troops are ``still responding to political guidance and still
conducting operations.''
</P>
<P>
   --The European Union agreed to ban the shipment of oil to
Yugoslavia, beginning next week. NATO warplanes already have
destroyed most of Yugoslavia's oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO is considering air drops of food and other supplies to an
estimated 850,000 Kosovars who are homeless in Kosovo and unable to
reach refugees camps in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   --A senior commander of the Kosovo Liberation Army was killed
and four rebel soldiers were wounded in battles with Serb forces
along the border between Yugoslavia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Chernomyrdin said he and Milosevic did not discuss
many details of ``the international presence'' in their proposed
peace pact for Kosovo. ``What kind of international forces they
will be or from which countries, this is yet to be discussed,''
Chernomyrdin said. ``The main thing is that Russia take part.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he supports Russia's inclusion in a NATO-led
peacekeeping mission involving armed troops. Of the NATO demands
for a ceasefire, Clinton said Thursday, ``We want all the people of
Kosovo restored to their homes, free of the hostile presence of Mr.
Milosevic's forces, protected by an international security force,
enjoying liberty and self-government.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, appearing with Clinton at
the White House, said NATO ``will not be divided'' and will
demonstrate its unity during the three-day summit. ``Let there be
no doubt NATO will see this through to the end,'' Solana said. ``We
have the means, and we have the will.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a senior Yugoslav government official assailed the
NATO attack on one of Milosevic's homes as ``a criminal act without
precedence _ an assassination attempt against the president of a
sovereign state.''
</P>
<P>
   US and NATO officials denied they were specifically targeting
Milosevic, the mastermind of alleged war crimes against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, who represented 90 percent of the province's
population of 2 million before the siege began.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon described the raid as a part
of NATO's effort ``to cut off the head'' of the Serb military by
destroying ``the central nervous system, the central command and
control system, of the regime.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
