<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVINE DREAMS UP SUCCESS STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The perfect Hollywood climax to Ken Levine's
career would be sharing a seat in the Dodger Stadium press box next
to his idol, Vin Scully.
</P>
<P>
   Levine seems to be the kind of person who could make it happen.
He's not only written his own ticket around these parts but
directed them as well. That's his OTHER job.
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old Woodland Hills native and Taft High and UCLA
grad has been hired by KXTA-AM (1150) to co-host the weekend
Dodgers ``Game Day'' shows when the team is on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Which might not seem like much. But with Levine's career
successes, it will be. Levine fell in love with baseball by
listening to Scully's calls as a kid and parlayed that into a
major-league play-by-play career of his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the TV world, Levine is better known for his scriptwriting,
directing and creative consultant work on award-winning shows like
``MASH,'' ``Cheers,'' ``Frasier,'' ``Wings'' and ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   But fans of the Baltimore Orioles, Seattle Mariners and San
Diego Padres will also recognize his voice. For the last eight
years, he did play-by-play for those teams.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Dodgers, who have more than doubled their TV games
this year while allowing Scully to ease off on his schedule, be
Levine's next radio and/or TV broadcasting stop?
</P>
<P>
   It makes too much sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's such an unbelievable dream, I almost try not to think
about it,'' Levine admitted. ``I not only got interested in
announcing but in writing from listening to Vin Scully. To announce
the Los Angeles Dodgers is almost beyond my thinking. It's like
wanting to date Cindy Crawford.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially now that she's married and expecting a kid. And
Levine is happily married as well.
</P>
<P>
   Levine has made himself known to Dodgers personnel since 1988,
when he took a break from his sitcom writing to pursue a dream of
becoming a baseball play-by-play man. The Dodgers would allow him
to come down into the press box to pick up game information and
he'd take it up to the general-admission level and call the game
into a tape recorder to practice.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of years in the minor leagues, Levine caught on
with the Orioles for the '91 season. They wanted him back full
time, but it would mean having to move his family back East when a
lot of his writing work continued out here.
</P>
<P>
   That provided the basis of a book called ``It's Gone . . . No,
Wait a Minute . . .: Talking My Way Into the Big Leagues at 40.''
Astute fans of ``The Simpsons'' might also remember when he wrote
himself _ or his voice _ into an episode as the play-by-play man
for the Springfield Isotopes and got to scream: ``Topes win . . .
Topes win!''
</P>
<P>
   Levine worked full time with the Mariners in '92 and then part
time for them the next two seasons. In '95, Padres president Larry
Lucchino, who knew him from the Orioles, hired him to do a handful
of weekend games when Jerry Coleman had assignments for CBS Radio.
</P>
<P>
   But when CBS Radio lost the game rights to ESPN Radio this
season, Coleman went back to a full schedule with the Padres. And
Levine, in essence, was written out of their sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he's done a screenplay called ``Satisfaction'' that
he's trying to get produced. It's a romantic comedy set against the
backdrop of a Bakersfield radio station _ a place he's also worked
in his radio DJ career that started at KMPC in the late '60s and
included stops at KABC and KFI. Angelenos might also remember him
when he went by the name ``Beaver Cleaver'' from his FM days.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Levine has been directing shows like ``Lateline'' with
Al Franken, ``Just Shoot Me,'' ``Dharma and Greg,'' ``Becker,''
``Brother's Keeper,'' ``Encore, Encore'' and ``Conrad Bloom.'' His
real baby was the Nancy Travis sitcom ``Almost Perfect,'' which he
and writing partner David Isaacs created.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Levine's TV projects obviously made it big. Others have
had marginal success. Still others didn't make it out of the first
season. That's TV.
</P>
<P>
   But in baseball broadcasting, Levine's career has been almost
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   And, if truth be told, he's already had one chance to sit with
Scully in the press box. When Levine wrote for the KMPC sports desk
in 1969, the station's sports director, Steve Bailey, arranged for
Levine to meet Scully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I introduced myself and asked if I could watch him work,''
Levine said. ``He said, `Sure, come in the fourth inning after
Jerry (Doggett) finishes the third.' So I go in at the half inning,
and Vin waves me in and I sit in the chair next to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'M sitting in the booth next to Vin Scully. And there was
a great play where he makes the call, `He's out at the plate!' . .
. and I just had chicken skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, Levine is still pinching himself. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
Bryant Gumbel's closing remarks on the current installment of HBO's
``Real Sports,'' a series that picked up three national Emmy awards
at Wednesday night's ceremony: ``When two well-known athletes left
the stage last week it forced a lot of us media folks to do
something heretofore unthinkable and totally unwarranted, and that
was to put Wayne Gretzky and Dennis Rodman in the same thought. For
Rodman, that's social climbing. Because while one man defined
professionalism, the other not only lacked it entirely, but took
perverse pride in it. As much as one went out of his way for the
sake of the team to fit in, the other took the same pains to stand
out. That Gretzky was so conspicuously good, brought out the best
in those who covered him. That Rodman got so much coverage for just
being conspicuous doesn't speak highly of any of us. Predictably,
while one exited with honor, the other left in the kind of dishonor
he long courted. And therein lies some modern lessons for young
athletes looking to cultivate one of our divergent definitions of
character. As Dennis Rodman and Wayne Gretzky clearly proved, you
can be a character and enrich only yourself or you can show some
character and enrich us all.'' &QL; 
__ Fred Wallin and Peter Vent start venting on their new
sports-talk show weeknights from 6 to 7 p.m. on KVTA-AM (1520)
starting Tuesday.!dlim!WHAT CHOKES!dlim!__ Ted Turner's latest
verbal scud at Rupert Murdoch was at the National Association of
Broadcasters annual meeting in Las Vegas. Responding to the fact
Murdoch's Fox network has been pulling back advertising time from
its affiliates, Turner said: ``We will not do that at Time Warner.
We will not screw you and lie to you. . . He's getting you because
he's losing on his regional sports networks and he's got to pay
Kevin Brown's salary from somewhere.'' &QL; 
__ Deeply infected with Lupica Syndrome, Sports Illustrated
back-page sellout Rick Reilly-Stamos appeared on ``The Late Late
Show with Craig Kilborn'' Tuesday. Booked as a guest with nothing
really to promote except himself, Reilly had that talk-show banter
down and really acted sheepish when the equally swishy Kilborn
sprung some outtakes of Reilly's latest beer commercial _ a spot
which then actually ran in full during the commercial break in the
interview. &QL; 
__ The Angels should be kicking themselves for allowing Orange
County based KIK-FM (94.3) to take games bounced by KRLA-AM (570)
when the Lakers take precedent. Valley folk have a better chance of
picking up affiliate KSJB-AM (600) out of North Dakota. &QL;
</P>
