<HEADLINE>
SECOND DRAGGING DEATH TRIAL WILL REMAIN IN JASPER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The trial of a second white man accused of
dragging a black man to death will remain in Jasper, a state judge
ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection for the capital murder trial of Russell Brewer
Jr., 32, will begin May 17, state District Judge Monte Lawlis
ruled. Testimony will probably start on June 7, the first
anniversary of the brutal murder of James Byrd Jr., 49, who was
dragged almost three miles behind a pickup truck along back country
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's attorney, Doug Barlow of Beaumont, gave Lawlis 11 hours
of videotaped news reports and stacks of newspaper articles about
the crime and the trial earlier this year of Bill King, 24, who was
sentenced to death. Trial for a third defendant, Shawn Berry, 24,
has not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's girlfriend, Tammy Perritt, and brother, John Brewer,
were visibly upset about the ruling. John Brewer rushed from the
courtroom. Perritt sat with tears in her eyes, waiting for a chance
to spend a few moments with Brewer in a courthouse jury room before
he was taken to the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   John Brewer, 27, later issued a short statement he had written
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brewer family is totally devastated over the death of Mr.
James Byrd Jr. Our deepest sympathies and all of our prayers go out
to his family and his loved ones, as well as the King and Berry
families each and every night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly do not understand why a change of venue was not
granted,'' he said as he began to sob.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind I am his brother _ to be honest with the whole
world, I myself do not care where it is at. As far as I am
concerned this is my brother, Lawrence Russell Brewer, (and he) is
still an innocent man until proven guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
