<HEADER>
A9614 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS-2TAK     04-22 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO SCHOOL MASSACRE ALTERS COURSE OF DEBATE OVER GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Fla., Ill., Kan., Mo., Neb., N.M., Okla.,
Ore., Va.)   (rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With gun manufacturers already on the defensive over
lawsuits, outrage over the nation's worst high school shooting in
modern history is altering the gun debate, bolstering the political
power of the gun-control advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Colorado, where three bills long advocated by the gun
lobby were expected to become law within days, Colorado state
legislators hastily withdrew two of them on Thursday and Gov. Bill
Owens unexpectedly promised to veto the third.
</P>
<P>
   And Mayor Wellington Webb of Denver has asked the National Rifle
Association to cancel its national meeting here, scheduled to start
April 30. Spurning a forecast $18 million in spending by the
conventioneers, the mayor said on Thursday, ``We don't want you
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In California on Thursday, the Assembly unexpectedly voted to
approve a bill intended to curb handgun trafficking, limiting sales
to one handgun per person each month.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida on Wednesday, the House unexpectedly tabled a bill
designed to prevent localities from suing gun manufacturers. In
Arizona on Wednesday, Gov. Jane Hull vetoed similar legislation.
And in Illinois, Gov. George Ryan urged state legislators to pass a
bill that would require adults to store guns at home with trigger
locks or in locked cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   The gun industry remains a powerful lobby in state governments
around the country. And it is likely that at least some of these
measures will be resurrected when the publicity surrounding the
shootings here subsides down.
</P>
<P>
   But the reaction marks a break in the momentum that the rifle
association and similar groups, which in recent months have sought
the passage of laws that would allow citizens in some states to
carry concealed weapons. The horror and revulsion brought on by
Tuesday's tragedy has also derailed efforts by the gun lobby in
some state legislatures to stop cities from passing tougher gun
laws. Moreover, it may give new vigor to proponents of lawsuits
against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing out of this tragedy is that legislators are
listening to their constituents, and not the NRA,'' said Joe
Sudbay, state legislative director for Handgun Control Inc., a
Washington-based group.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that his office has deployed eight people to help its
lone receptionist field a deluge of calls after the Littleton
shootings, Sudbay said, ``Around the country, the same thing is
happening _ people are just fed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago _ well before the massacre at Columbine High
School _ Missouri voters defeated in a referendum intended to lift
the state's constitutional ban on concealed weapons. Even though
the rifle association outspent its opponents by nearly a 5-to-1,
voters rejected the idea, 52 percent to 48 percent. Political
analysts attributed the defeat to a large turnout of middle-class
Republicans from the suburbs of St. Louis, a constituency that in
the past the rifle association could rely on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun lobby has been losing influence over the past number
of years, so they have focused their energies on state
legislatures,'' said Sudbay, adding that no state has liberalized
concealed permit laws since 1996. ``Since January, concealed
weapons bills have been defeated in Nebraska, Kansas and New
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is now sharpest in Colorado, where grieving
residents are driving by a large billboard in which Charlton
Heston, the president of the rifle association urges passersby,
``Join me.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Rep. Diana DeGette wrote one of the convention's
featured speakers, Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, asking him to
cancel his appearance in Denver. Referring to the shootings in
Littleton, she wrote, ``Your appearance and the controversy
surround the NRA would throw salt into those wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasting angry demonstrations, state Sen. Pat Pascoe of
Denver urged the rifle association to ``cancel it totally, go
somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not welcome,'' Pascoe said. ``This shouldn't add to
the torture of the families.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the rifle association has announced that it will
scale back the three-day event to one day, and will cancel all
seminars, luncheons and exhibitions by vendors and gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   Heston and Wayne LaPierre, the organization's executive vice
president, sent a letter out to members explaining that the steps
were taken, ``to show our profound sympathy and respect for the
families and communities in the Denver area in their time of great
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dietrick, a member of the rifle association from Colorado
who lobbied hard for the three bills this season, said, ``This was
supposed to be a happy event, now it can't be.
</P>
<P>
   Dietrick said the organization's bylaws required holding an
annual meeting, adding, ``We have got members from all over the
country who have purchased non-refundable tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   John Velleco, a spokesman for Gun Owners of America, a
Virginia-based group allied with the NRA, said on Thursday,
``Unfortunately, there are going to be politicians who are going to
climb over the bodies of the victims and pursue an agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, Colorado has also witnessed sharp debate
over the bills, which would have loosened restrictions on permits
for concealed weapons, would have banned local lawsuits against
weapon manufacturers and would have pre-empted local ordinances on
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concealed guns may go anywhere,'' was the page one headline on
an article in the Denver Post last month after the House approved a
bill intended to loosen restrictions on permits for concealed
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9615 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS-2TAK     04-22 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DENVER: concealed weapons. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After public protests, another front-page article appeared three
days later with a headline that said, ``Protests knock schools off
weapons bill.''
</P>
<P>
   And days later, the sponsor of the bill, Rep. Doug Dean, was
challenged to a debate on the steps of the state capitol here by
Dennis Murphy, the fire chief in Springfield, Ore., who responded
to high school shooting last spring in which a student killed two
classmates and wounded 23.
</P>
<P>
   In unincorporated Jefferson County, which embraces Littleton and
where the two youths lived and went to school, there are no local
ordinances restricting the use of guns. Federal law bars most
firearms sales to minors. State law bars carrying firearms into
schools, unless for educational purposes.
</P>
<P>
   While many Coloradans have reacted to the Littleton massacre by
calling for tighter gun controls, some say the shootings bolster
their arguments for concealed weapons permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make places like school off limits to the honest
carrying people, those who have gone through the background checks,
the training, you create a killing ground for those who are
inclined to do so, they know there is no resistance,'' said
Dietrick. A solution, he said, would be to allow a few trained
adults _ the principal and some teachers _ carry handguns at
school.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's climate, some politicians are finding they must
back off that position.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for instance, Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota said
that the shootings in Littleton illustrated the need for ``conceal
and carry'' laws, or more gun permits for law-abiding citizens.
``Had there been someone armed in this particular situation, in my
opinion, it may have stabilized,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, responding to a large outcry, he issued of
statement saying, ``I believe that, except for uniformed police
officers, a school is no place for weapons, and that the carrying
of concealed weapons in schools is not the answer to this terrible
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
