<HEADER>
A9618 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-EXISTENZ-SPI &LR;      04-22 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EXISTENZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXISTENZ IS CONSISTENTLY ENGAGING AND FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the the more obvious movie trends to take shape thus far
in 1999 are films that, in one way or another, play with the idea
of computer-generated, alternate realities.
</P>
<P>
   Already in the multiplexes is ``The Matrix,'' which supposes
that our current late-20th-century reality is actually only the
computer animation of some future race of malevolent machines.
</P>
<P>
   And coming in late May is ``The 13th Floor,'' about a pair of
visionaries who create ``a living, breathing simulation of 1937 Los
Angeles in a computer chip.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's David Cronenberg's latest offering,
``eXistenZ,'' which is the name of a role-playing computer game of
the future that can be downloaded directly into the human body.
</P>
<P>
   More precisely, the game is fed into a ``bioport'' _ a small,
permanent spinal jack embedded in the back _ so that the body's
nervous system, metabolism and energy provide the game's power
source.
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg's story _ which he says was inspired by the plight of
Salman Rushdie _ is about the designer of the game (Jennifer Jason
Leigh), who goes on the lam to escape a band of
assassination-minded, anti-technology extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by a worshipful devotee (Jude Law), she moves from one
tight situation and double-cross to another, at the same time she
and her companion move in and out of the eXistenZ game.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, they (and we) have no idea what is
computer-generated and what is real, and the story steadily works
to a climax of criss-crossed, illusion-and-reality scenes that
ultimately leaves the entire movie open to reinterpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone expecting ``The Matrix'' here is likely to be
disappointed. ``eXistenZ'' has an imaginative effect or two, but
the movie is not carried by its visuals in quite so spectacular a
way. It's basically a low-tech rendering of a high-tech subject.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the premise is solid, the script is clever and
well-thought-out, and the movie is consistently engaging and fun.
At exactly 90 minutes, it doesn't wear out its welcome, and it
never gets bogged down in pretension like the other Cronenberg
epics of the '90s _ ``Naked Lunch,'' ``M. Butterfly'' and
``Crash.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast strikes just the right note of alienated weirdness,
with some inspired cameos from Ian Holm, Willem Dafoe and
Christopher Eccleston. Law provides a sympathetic audience
point-of-view, and Leigh has never carried off a lead role with
more command and assurance, or with less reliance on her usual
mannerisms.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the film is fueled by that distinctive blend of
horror, eroticism and technology-run-amok that we've come to expect
from the Canadian master of macabre. Love him or hate him,
Cronenberg is one of the cinema's true originals, and a trip to his
spooky world is always a harrowing, thought-provoking experience.
</P>
<P>
   eXistenZ. Directed and written by David Cronenberg. Cast:
Jennifer Jason Leigh, Jude Law, Ian Holm, Willem Dafoe. Dimension
Films. 90 minutes. Rated R for sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9619 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS &LR;      04-22 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL VIP LENDS WEIGHT TO MOVE TO `SAVE THE PATS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- National Football League commissioner Paul Tagliabue
will blitz Boston Friday as part of a campaign to keep the New
England Patriots in Massachusetts. But it appears the team will
stick with its stadium deal in Hartford, backed by $374 million in
taxpayers' money, unless the Bay State can top it _ quickly.
</P>
<P>
   That will be difficult, people familiar with the situation say.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran stood firm in his
stance against the state buying land around the team's current
stadium in Foxborough and leasing it back to owner Robert Kraft. He
also remains opposed to using using taxpayer money to finance any
part of a new facility other than public infrastructure, such as
roads and lighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no change in position,'' Finneran said. ``It's the
exact position we've had for three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Both provisions were part of a bill agreed to last year by Kraft
and Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham under which Kraft would
have spent $250 million to build a new stadium in Foxborough.
Finneran effectively killed that bill, opening the door for
Connecticut to lure the Patriots with what has been called the
sweetest stadium deal ever in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Finneran said Thursday he would not scramble
against a deadline to get the House to consider a local stadium
plan to rival Connecticut's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a budget ahead of us . . . education, the economy, and
health care and taxes, all of which have a higher priority in the
eyes of ordinary citizens, ordinary taxpayers,'' Finneran said.
``We'll move but at a pace that's appropriate. There won't be undue
delay, but there won't be undue haste.''
</P>
<P>
   Timing could be a significant stumbling block to any efforts put
forth by the NFL and a civic group headed by former Democratic
National Committee chairman Paul Kirk to secure the team's future
in Massachusetts before the league votes on the Patriots move at
the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of his preliminary accord with Connecticut, Kraft
has until May 2 to decide whether to commit to the Hartford
proposal. Despite environmental and logistical problems with the
site there, he is expected to go forward, people familiar with the
situation say.
</P>
<P>
   Then the move must be approved by NFL owners, who are set to
vote during their next conference in Atlanta, from May 24-26. Eight
out of 31 owners must vote against the move to derail the project.
League sources say there do not appear to be enough votes at this
point to stop Kraft from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change if the league comes up with a solid plan
to keep the Patriots in Masschusetts, the country's sixth-largest
TV market. That is the opening that local business leaders and
Tagliabue hope to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue is scheduled to meet with the Greater Boston Chamber
of Commerce executive committee at BankBoston headquarters and
later will head to the State House to speak with Finneran and
Governor Paul Cellucci, who addressed about 200 people rallying
outside the Bulfinch building to keep the team from moving.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci joined the crowd in chanting ``Save the Pats'' but
added a dose of reality to the last-minute hopefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have an uphill battle,'' Cellucci said. ``But we do
have a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Spread out before him, Patriots fans held signs that read
``Don't be Conn-ed'', ``The Boston TEAm Pahty'' and ``Send Finneran
to Connecticut and keep the Pats.'' Some in the crowd wore suits
and ties. Others painted their faces and wore football jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriot Peter Brock took to the podium to urge those
inside the State House to ``leave their personal agendas and their
games behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A rally with a couple hundred people singing on or off key is
not new information upon which to commit taxpayers funds to
private, profitable businesses,'' Finneran said, adding, ``I would
think there would probably be 20,000 citizens on the steps of the
State House to articulate a different point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the NFL passed a new financing rule under which it
could offer a loan to help build a Massachusetts stadium and the
business community could offer support to bridge small funding
gaps.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that would pale in comparison to the Connecticut
deal, under which the state would build a stadium and
infrastructure like roads. Kraft would build a hotel and health
complex, reaping profits from all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has remained silent in the face of this intense wave of
NFL involvement and media attention. But those close to the
situation say that while he may want the team to stay in
Massachusetts, he would be hard pressed to pass up the Hartford
deal.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he may be willing to move in 2003, a year later than
currently contemplated, rather attempt a stadium deal in Foxborough
or Boston to which he would have to contributed hundreds of
millions of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Said one person close to the team, ``Their $374 million one year
later is still better than $250 million one year earlier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9621 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SOSEC-NYT &LR;      04-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SOSEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS GIVE UP EFFORT TO MAKE FUNDAMENTAL CHANGES IN
SOCIAL SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House have abandoned the
idea of making fundamental changes in Social Security before the
next election, just as the top Republicans on the House Ways and
Means Committee are putting the final touches on a plan to base the
retirement program partly on private investments.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican House members said they had been told by
their party's leaders in meetings and private conversations this
week that trying to overhaul the Social Security system would
create a serious political risk for Republicans without any
likelihood of reward.
</P>
<P>
   The chances were already remote that Congress and President
Clinton could agree on comprehensive Social Security legislation
before next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who have met with the party leaders said they had
been told that polls commissioned by the party indicated that among
people who felt very strongly about Social Security one way or the
other, many more were skeptical about the Republicans' plan than
felt favorably toward the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said they were also told that there was little
point in taking the political risk of voting for changes in the
most popular program created by the government when there was
little likelihood that the Senate would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief sponsors of the private investment plan, Rep.
E. Clay Shaw Jr., chairman of the Ways and Means Committee's Social
Security subcommittee, said on Thursday that he and his cosponsor,
Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, chairman of the full committee,
recognized the obstacles and would not try to advance legislation
without the support of their party's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to dive into an empty swimming pool and neither
is Bill Archer,'' said Shaw, R-Fla. ``We're not going to move a
bill that the House is not going to embrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he understood why the party leaders, including Speaker
Dennis Hastert, Rep. Dick Armey, the majority leader, and Rep. Tom
DeLay, the whip, were wary. ``The Democrats have used this is a
club against us for decades, and they have been damn good at it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Shaw said, he and Archer believe they have developed a
good plan and will announce the details anyway in the hope that the
leaders' minds will be changed by an outpouring of public support.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview, Archer said he felt compelled to offer
a plan because, ``I don't see any movement on Social Security, and
I feel this debate needs a shot in the arm.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no urgent reason to overhaul Social Security now. By
current estimates, it will remain solvent without changes until
2034.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, when Republicans began talking about using the
budget surplus to finance tax cuts, Clinton replied with the
assertion that the issue was whether to use the surplus to give tax
breaks to the wealthy or to shore up Social Security. This stance
played well in last November's election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union Message this year, the president
outlined a proposal to strengthen Social Security by using most of
the budget surplus over 15 years to pay down the national debt and
by having the government invest part of Social Security tax
revenues in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who have been burned time and again when they have
tried to tinker with the popular Social Security program, then
began to search for proposals that would fit their ideological
predilictions. They countered with two plans.
</P>
<P>
   For the short term, they offered legislation that would allow
Social Security taxes to be used only to reduce the national debt
or to finance an overhaul of the retirement system. It was blocked
on Thursday when Senate Republicans could not get the 60 votes
necessary to clear the parliamentary hurdle of cutting off debate.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the Republicans began working on a measure to
allow people to divert some of their Social Security taxes into
private retirement accounts that they could invest in the financial
markets. Such a measure has long been a dream of Republicans who
want to keep the government out of people's lives as much as
possible and who believe many retirees get a bad deal from the
public retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, Archer and Shaw developed a plan that would
include a tax cut to give workers money they could invest. The
plan, which has been certified by Social Security actuaries as
sufficient to keep the system solvent for at least 75 years, would
guarantee workers retirement benefits no smaller than what they
could expect under the current Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan has come under fire from the left and right. The
White House and liberal Democrats object to making the retirement
program partly private. They believe it would be the first step
toward breaking the longstanding social compact under which each
generation pays taxes to support retirement benefits for the
previous generation.
</P>
<P>
   Many conservative Republicans object to parts of the plan that
would require retirees to turn their investment accounts into
annuities, mandate a portfolio of 60 percent stocks and 40 percent
bonds and leave little or nothing in most retirement accounts to be
bequeathed to heirs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of
the Finance Committee, has told colleagues that he has no intention
of moving Social Security legislation this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
