<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-LEDE23-COX     04-22 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-LEDE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police uncover propane-tank bombs in aftermath of shootings
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ This shell-shocked town had fresh snow and
fresh worries Thursday, as police found two powerful propane-tank
bombs in the Columbine High School kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery renewed suspicions that Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold, the two boys who gunned down 12 students and a teacher on
Tuesday, may not have acted alone in planning and preparing their
deadly melee. Police also said the newly found bombs showed the
boys may have wanted to burn their school down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong suspicion because of the amount of ordinance
that they had some assistance,'' Jefferson County Sheriff John
Stone said. ``The evidence supports that these individuals not only
were on a shooting spree, but also were intent on destroying the
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 70 investigators split into several teams scoured the
sprawling school building about midday when they came upon the
devices in the kitchen. The two, 20-pound propane tanks _ similar
to those used on barbecue grills _ would have made a massive
explosion, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, police believe the two boys, who wore black trench coats
and laughed as they fired upon their victims, were the only
shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no evidence that anyone else was involved,'' said
sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis. ``But we're not ruling out
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   As the officers worked on what may turn into a weeklong
investigation inside the building, Columbine students and others
continued gathering in Clement Park, near the school campus.
</P>
<P>
   An overnight blanket of snow seemed to add a new layer of
solemnity to the site, where makeshift memorials of flowers,
stuffed animals and hand-written posters and cards grew into
massive piles. Tents were erected to cover the memorials, which
drew hundreds of students and other onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them simply stood silently, heads bowed, some sobbing as
drops of melting snow spattered hand-scribbled notes, pink and blue
ink running down poster board and pages torn from school notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   At one of the tents, someone pounded 13 small crosses into the
ground, four painted pink for the female victims, nine painted blue
for the males. To the side, lying on the ground, were two black
crosses, apparently for the shooters.
</P>
<P>
   The pile of flowers, balloons and heartbroken notes atop a red
Acura Legend belonging to 17-year-old Rachel Scott, one of the
victims, also grew dramatically, literally covering the vehicle. A
small teddy-bear was attached to the driver's side mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine's students called a private meeting with their
teachers late Thursday, one more sign of their need to talk, hug,
and simply share their emotions as they struggled to make sense of
the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   School officials were scrambling to find a building where they
could move the 2,000 students for the remaining three weeks of the
term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students are saying they want to be back together with
their teachers,'' said Jefferson County Superintendent Jane
Hammond. ``We are committed to keeping them together.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno visited Denver on
Thursday, meeting with top officials and pledging federal support
for their investigation. She also spoke to students upset by the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, which had an annual meeting
scheduled in Denver in the near future, announced it would scale
back its meeting from three days to one, although some Denver
groups called on the group to cancel the meeting completely.
</P>
<P>
   All over Denver, the main question was why the suspected
shooters chose to vent their anger in such a terrible fashion.
</P>
<P>
   After releasing statements of condolence Wednesday, their
families remained in seclusion, their neighbors saying little.
</P>
<P>
   Media reports said Harris' father was retired from the military.
Klebold's father was a geophysicist who worked for oil exploration
companies for years, but lately had run a mortgage management
business from his home, a sprawling, $500,000 property on five
acres outside of town.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold's mother once worked with deaf, blind and disabled
children, while friends said his father favored gun control and
likely wouldn't have owned any weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Several students gave more details about videos the pair made in
a class at school. In at least one of the videos, they apparently
wore trench coats and carried guns, an eerie foreshadowing of their
tragic rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Cory Hardison, 18, a Columbine senior who knew the suspected
shooters, said the videos were tongue-in-cheek, not taken seriously
by other students or faculty. The boys got in trouble once for
using profanity in a video, but the guns were apparently never an
issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also confirmed that a note was found at Harris' home, but
would not reveal the contents or even the general tone.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' Web page, taken off the Internet by his provider in the
wake of the killings, reportedly contained seething anger, dark
images, demonic drawings and references to death.
</P>
<P>
   Students also said Harris wrote poems with disturbing themes in
his creative writing class.
</P>
<P>
   Police continued to defend their handling of the rampage,
insisting that a small SWAT team was in the building within 20
minutes, while the school's assigned resource officer fired on the
suspects within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the family of slain teacher Dave Sanders wondered whether he
might have been saved by faster police action. Sanders reportedly
shouted the first warnings in the school cafeteria that likely
saved dozens of lives, then stayed in the school warning more
students when he had the chance to escape.
</P>
<P>
   He was eventually shot in the chest, collapsing in a science lab
where a group of terrified students ripped off their shirts to
staunch his wounds. He remained in the room for some three hours,
despite frantic calls placed to police operators via cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that my dad was left there, was still alive and
wasn't helped,'' said Sanders' adult daughter, Angie.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, Sanders asked the students with him to pull his
wallet from his pocket so he could look at pictures of his wife and
children, Angie Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Such images are likely to stay etched in the minds of the
students and the victims' families for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Even veteran authorities have been shaken by the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most devastating things I've ever seen,'' said
Jefferson County District Attorney David Thomas, who toured the
school before the bodies were removed. ``One of the kids still had
a pencil in his hand. It's just something I wish I could erase from
my mind, but I don't think I can.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
