<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KINKY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HIDEOUS KINKY' MIGHT HAVE BEEN BETTER WITH A NARROWER FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming off both a best actress Oscar nomination and the biggest
movie hit of modern times, one would think ``Titanic'' star Kate
Winslet would be taking advantage of her fame with one A-level
movie project after another. Yet, like co-star Leonardo DiCaprio,
she's been lying low.
</P>
<P>
   And now here she is in ``Hideous Kinky,'' a low-budget, art
house adaptation of an obscure novel by Esther Freud in which she
plays a not-especially sympathetic English hippie hanging out in
'70s Morocco with her two young daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the modest budget aside, it's an interesting project,
and an often fascinating and scary movie. Indeed, with a somewhat
more probing script than the one provided by director Gillies
MacKinnon's brother Billy, this might have been something truly
special.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1972, it's the story of Julia (Winslet), the estranged
mistress of a noted poet, who has somehow ended up in the hippie
mecca of Marrakech with her two daughters, 6-year-old Lucy (Carrie
Mullan) and more dissatisfied 8-year-old Bea (Bella Rea).
</P>
<P>
   When we join them, the family has been in Morocco for about a
year. They live in near poverty on the backstreets of the city, but
are reasonably well-adjusted to their environment and constantly
expect a support check from the children's father.
</P>
<P>
   The script follows Julia's episodic adventures over several
months as the family becomes attached to a Moroccan street
performer (Said Taghmaoui), make several hitchhiking journeys
around Morocco and to Algeria, and find themselves in one
vulnerable _ even dangerous _ situation after another.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the movie is filled with wonderful little moments
of revelation, and the exotic visual splendor of North Africa _ all
which is exquisitely reflected in the wide eyes of the children,
who are perfectly cast and completely natural.
</P>
<P>
   Winslet brings off a delicate, detailed character study of a
naive and courageous young woman in pursuit of spiritual
enlightenment, and trying to embrace the esthetic of the
counterculture even as it battles with her own maternal instincts.
The performance speaks whole volumes about the hard core of the
'60s generation.
</P>
<P>
   Director MacKinnon (``The Playboys,'' ``Small Faces'') also
projects just the right ambivalent attitude toward Julia and her
quest. He seems to admire her, even while he realizes her hippie
naivete is doomed to frustration, perhaps disaster, and the risks
she's taking with her children are insane.
</P>
<P>
   His soundtrack is littered with American rock songs _ the
Jefferson Airplane, Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash, America _ but the
juxtaposition of images makes them come off less as cheerful
nostalgia than as a sad, wistful ode to an impractical lost dream
of limitless freedom and possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is so powerful in so many ways that it's painful that
it doesn't go all the way. But it's also filled with holes (an
explanation of the title, for instance) and the kind of gaps in
character development that are usually evidence of script problems
and a massive, last-minute re-editing job.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a movie that might have been better served by
narrowing its point of view to that of the two children _ as Jean
Renoir did in ``The River,'' a curiously similar film about the
coming-of-age of two British girls in India.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the perspective is scattered, confusing and finally
tiring. But had we experienced this world _ Morocco, the hippie
'70s, Julia's quest _ entirely through the innocent eyes of Bea and
Lucy, this might have been considerably more than another good-try
art film.
</P>
<P>
   Hideous Kinky. Directed by Gllies MacKinnon. Screenplay by
Billy MacKinnon, from the novel by Esther Freud. Cast: Kate
Winslet, Said Taghmaoui, Bella Riza, Carrie Mullan. 99 minutes.
Rated R for brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
