<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PETTY-ANDRETTI23-     04-22 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETTY-ANDRETTI23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Team Petty on fast track
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Halfway through the 1994 Winston Cup season,
John Andretti was losing his ride in the sponsorless No. 14 car
when he heard that Richard Petty might be looking for a driver. So
he went up to Petty in a track garage area and applied for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the King for about 15 minutes and he said, `Well,
just come on down to Level Cross, and we'll talk some more.' And I
looked at him and asked, `Well, where's Level Cross?' And the guy
next to me hit me. He said, `Be quiet; I'll tell you where it's at
later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti laughs about his naivete now. ``Level Cross is about
the smallest little town you could ever know,'' he said, ``but
anybody in racing should know where Level Cross is because it's
where the King is from.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the smallest little town just south of Greensboro, N.C.,
is where Petty, modern stock-car racing's King, hung his crown.
It's been a decade since there was reason to remember the address.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Andretti is helping put Level Cross back on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti snapped a personal 57-race winless streak last weekend
at Martinsville Speedway. He put Petty Enterprises in victory lane
for the first time since October 1997, snapping a string of 42
races.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Hensley drove the team's Dodge to victory in the
truck-series race on Saturday, making Petty Enterprises the first
team to win a Winston Cup and truck event at the same speedway with
different drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The team's timing has been incredible: Two weeks ago, Petty
Enterprises cut the ribbon on its 20,000-square-foot addition and
kicked off a 50th anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   What's happened since: Petty has had seven NASCAR entries _ four
Winston Cup, two Truck Series, one Busch Grand National _ in five
different races and has recorded two wins, four top-fives and six
top-10s.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti won last weekend in the No. 43 Pontiac. Kyle Petty, who
did not have a top-10 finish all last season, already has three
this year in the No. 44 Pontiac. Adam Petty, Kyle's son, has been
impressive in his Busch series debut.
</P>
<P>
   Small steps but solid ones. Kyle understands better than any of
the Pettys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time Petty Enterprises was the yardstick for
Winston Cup racing,'' Kyle said. ``We were the Hendricks and the
Roushes of the day. To be honest, we kind of fell off that in the
'80s. Now, we're trying to get caught back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty Enterprises was once at that top level because Richard was
the most successful driver of his era. Seven years after his
retirement, he still holds records for career wins (200), career
poles (126), wins in a season (27), consecutive wins (10), most
years leading the circuit in wins (seven) and a bunch of others.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Petty stayed in his car too long and did not
groom a replacement driver. His last pole was 1978. Between 1984
and his last year, 1992, he went 199 races without a win. He even
left Petty Enterprises in the mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anytime you have anybody who's had as much success in
a sport as Richard had, it's a hard, hard thing to give up,'' said
Robbie Loomis, Andretti's team manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Allison went through it, and now Darrell Waltrip. They
love the sport so much. As we get older, our reactions are not the
same, we can't physically do the things we used to do, our mind's
not quite mentally as sharp. We have more wisdom and knowledge, but
a lot of times the other things outweigh it. I think Richard would
tell you he probably drove three or four years longer than he
needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Loomis joined Petty Enterprises in November 1988, missing the
King's best days and experiencing the downslide. He realizes that
the climb back to respectability is going to take more than a good
weekend at Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I told the guys in the shop, the win was great for us; it
shows what we can do,'' Loomis said. ``I want to get to feel like
(Jeff Gordon's crew chief) Ray Evernham on Mondays, and it's just
no big deal because you've done it so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti is quick not to put too much weight on one victory. He
isn't even optimistic about this weekend's DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway, given the team's problems with restrictor-plate
racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you win, it's such a great feeling,'' Andretti, who
has won twice in slightly more than five Cup seasons. ``I don't
know that it's a relief, because it all starts back at zero the
next week. But your zero's a lot closer (to success) because it
just happened for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti is a big part of the Petty equation. This is his second
time with Petty. He left in 1995, joining a new Kranefuss-Haas
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I got a better opportunity,'' he said. ``I was very
new to NASCAR, I didn't know the names of the people and the
personalities that well, it was a new team that felt like they had
the funding and the personnel to really do it right. They kept
raising the money.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a bad fit. His next job, with Cale Yarborough, ended
with sponsor problems. He finally asked Petty for his old job back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would have stuck around, we would be that much further
down the road,'' Andretti said. ``They would have been working with
the same guy for this whole duration. You can change people within
the team, but changing drivers is such a big change, it just
doesn't happen overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they could have fooled NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
