u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD     04-22 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE PAYS A CALL ON MILOSEVIC, BUT HE WAS NOT AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for addition; section after option trim is new.)  
(lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ NATO sent a missile into the bedroom of
Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic, early Thursday morning,
but insisted it was nothing personal.
</P>
<P>
   Three missiles devastated the elegant 1936 villa in the wealthy
Dedinje district at 15 Uzicka Street, the most famous address in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   An eclectic two-story building of white stucco, with columns and
rounded windows that its original owner described as a little
Hollywood in inspiration, the villa was built as a private house
and finished in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Tito appropriated the house for himself in 1944, after taking
power in Belgrade, and Yugoslav leaders have lived there since
then, making it an official residence.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is a charred ruin. One entire side wall of the structure
is blown away, all the windows are broken, and many trees in the
surrounding parkland have been uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   There are gaping holes where the missiles pierced the walls,
flares of soot shoot from the arches of the empty window frames,
and chunks of concrete and broken glass are scattered over the
lavish grounds.
</P>
<P>
   NATO may have intended its missiles as a message to Milosevic,
who has not been sleeping at the house in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tito, who is associated with the house more than any of his
successors, is buried in a sort of mausoleum 200 yards away in what
is known as the House of Flowers, a glassed-in structure where he
used to run the government in the summertime. Serbian television
gave no indication of any damage to the House of Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Yugoslav officials were livid in Milosevic's name.
They accused NATO of trying to assassinate the leader of a
sovereign state, and said the other missiles, which hit at about
3:15 a.m., had struck the living and dining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been avoiding the house ever since a
little-reported missile attack on a nearby building housing his
presidential guard, in which as many as 30 people are said to have
been killed, Serbian officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, for its part, claimed that the building was a vital link
in the military command system of Yugoslavia and that the strike
had nothing to do with Milosevic or its symbolic importance to the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   But this building was no radar station, and some Serbs reacted
with anger and incredulity.
</P>
<P>
   A Serbian photographer said: ``This is simply demagoguery.
Whether one likes Milosevic or not, this is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Serbian journalist with the magazine Vreme said: ``This
building is part of our cultural heritage. Yesterday Tito lived
there, and today Milosevic does, but tomorrow it will be Pera
Pric.'' That is the Serbian form of John Doe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO wants to pretend now that it's hit at the heart of the
repressive regime and not the Serbian nation, it's not true,
because they've only done this after a month of hitting civilian
targets,'' the journalist said.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist, who asked for anonymity, bemoaned the regular
trashing of Belgrade's cultural history, saying, ``When people come
to visit Belgrade, I can't show them a building more than 200 years
old, because every 50 years somebody bombs and blows them away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nearby, the old royal palace, the Beli Dvor, or White Palace, is
a ceremonial residence, where Milosevic and others before him
normally meet guests, but do not live.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has put the Beli Dvor off-limits as a target, in part
because a Rembrandt borrowed from the National Museum is on the
first floor. But the residence destroyed on Thursday is also listed
on the Yugoslav register of protected cultural sites.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Matic, a Serbian government minister of the Yugoslav
United Left Party of Milosevic's wife, Mira Markovic, did not try
to contain his anger at a news conference. ``NATO committed a
criminal act without precedence _ an assassination attempt against
the president of a sovereign state,'' Matic said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and other Western officials called the building a
presidential command post and legitimate military target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic himself is not a target,'' said the White House
spokesman, Joe Lockhart. ``The command and control center is.''
</P>
<P>
   But the spokesman for the Yugoslav Foreign Ministry, Nebojsa
Vujovic, said the building had no military utility and challenged
NATO to find ``one wire or one button.''
</P>
<P>
   Vujovic asked, ``Are their next targets child-care centers?''
</P>
<P>
   About 24 hours earlier, NATO had destroyed an office building
housing the offices of Milosevic's party as well as the radio and
television studios and transmitters of stations belonging to their
daughter, Marija, and their friends. That attack was seen as the
beginning of a targeting of the regime itself and its most notable
associates.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern Serb town of Krusevac on Thursday, about 125
miles from Belgrade, Zivadinka Damjanovic, the director of a home
for the elderly, was furious about the attack on the residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO showed its real position when they destroyed the
president's house,'' she said to a group of reporters visiting the
town. ``This was not his house, but an official one, and it was
built long before him.''
</P>
<P>
   Damjanovic said the attack only proved that NATO is being
disingenuous about the stated war aims. ``The point is destruction,
and not any kind of humanitarian protection or intervention,'' she
said. ``It's very obvious they want to occupy us and destroy us as
a people.''
</P>
<P>
   The villa, built by a wealthy engineer named Alexander Acovic,
was completed in 1936. His nephew, Dragomir Acovic, is currently
the president of the Serbian Heraldic Society and something of a
monarchist.
</P>
<P>
   According to Acovic, the Nazis seized the house in 1941 when
they occupied the country. Tito confiscated half of it in 1944 when
he came to Belgrade, forcing Acovic's uncle to sell the rest to the
state in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   The building is said to have one of the best air raid shelters
in Belgrade, which was apparently part of the original design.
Dragomir Acovic has said that on April 6, 1941, when the city was
bombed, the government held a cabinet meeting in the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Serb state television led its evening news with the building's
destruction. A commentator called the attack ``the drop that spills
the glass of condemnation by the largest part of justice-loving
humanity.'' It also cited the disapproval of Viktor Chernomyrdin,
the former Russian prime minister who is now serving as President
Boris Yeltsin's special Balkan envoy.
</P>
<P>
   With more fervor than realism, perhaps, the commentator asserted
that the destruction of the villa ``will no doubt start the
momentum of the resistance of the world to NATO's criminal
machinery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
