<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-22 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 When Age Bias Rears Its Head
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I've been working as a software quality assurance
engineer on a contract basis. I do a good job and have a good
reputation. However, I am middle-aged and wear hearing aids and
sometimes experience subtle discrimination because of this.
</P>
<P>
   I recently had one interview where the manager asked me
point-blank how old I was _ and then, seeing the look on my face,
said ``Oh, never mind.'' Then he looked at my hearing aids and
started to question whether I could work in an environment where I
had to communicate with other people. I handled his questions with
grace and dignity, but inside I was seething. Should I lodge a
formal complaint? And how should I handle such situations in the
future?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It's illegal for employers to ask about age or
disabilities in a job interview. But face it: Many of us walk
through life carrying blatant or subtle prejudices. And sometimes
these prejudices surface in the hiring process.
</P>
<P>
   Your best strategy is to anticipate such issues and defuse them
in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a visible difference like a hearing aid, people are going
to notice it,'' said Kitty Wilson, director of ProMatch, a
Sunnyvale organization that helps unemployed professionals find
work. ``They may never ask about it, but you can be sure it's on
their mind. So you should be prepared with whatever you need to
defuse it.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you could point to your hearing aids during the
interview and say, ``I imagine you may be wondering about these.''
Then explain how the aids allow you to function perfectly normally,
and note that you got high marks for communication and teamwork
from your former employers.
</P>
<P>
   On the age issue, many high-tech employers fear that older
workers will lack energy or cutting-edge skills. So make sure you
address these underlying stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly in Silicon Valley, one of the big issues is
always energy,'' said Susan Gould, a Palo Alto career consultant
and author of the book ``Free Agents.'' ``It's important to
demonstrate energy and to acknowledge that you understand that's
what is demanded of you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all looking to the future. Now for the past: What should
you do about those illegal, offensive questions in your recent
interview?
</P>
<P>
   Legally, you have the right to file an age or disability
discrimination complaint with the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission or a similar state agency. But that would consume huge
chunks of time and energy that might be better spent on your job
search. And in a small community like Silicon Valley, it could tar
you as a ``troublemaker'' in the eyes of other potential employers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I'd try a polite call or letter to someone at this
company _ perhaps the human resources director or a recruiter with
whom you had a positive connection.
</P>
<P>
   Mention the offensive remarks, and say you were concerned that
the hiring manager might not have been seeing a full picture of
your abilities. If you still want to work for this company, ask
them to keep you in mind for future positions.
</P>
<P>
   If the HR folks are any good, they'll realize that this hiring
manager is a big fat lawsuit waiting to happen. They may call him
on the carpet. They may initiate some companywide training on how
to conduct effective (and legal) job interviews.
</P>
<P>
   And they may even call you back when other jobs open up _
hopefully, jobs that would report to a different manager.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Deposits
</P>
<P>
   Q: &LR;   &LR; My company has a 401(k) retirement plan. The company seems
to deposit my money at very random dates that don't correspond with
my paycheck deductions. Is this legal?
</P>
<P>
   A: Federal pension law requires employers to transfer 401(k)
money into workers' retirement account within 15 business days
after the end of the month that the money was withheld from their
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had money withheld from your paycheck on March 15, they
would have until April 15 to put that money in trust,'' said
Constance Hiatt, a pension law expert with Hanson Bridgett Marcus
Vlahos &AMP; Rudy in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The law encourages employers to transfer 401(k) money more
quickly, if feasible. But many companies take several weeks to make
the transfer. Yours is probably one of them _ which would be why
your 401(k) deposit dates don't correspond with the dates of your
paycheck deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Single-Paycheck System
</P>
<P>
   Q: My employer owns two medical practices, one as a sole
proprietor and the other as a corporation. They're both in the same
office. Some employees treat patients for both practices but only
get paid by one of the practices. Does this break any labor laws?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no law against one company handling payroll for
another company, or issuing one paycheck that covers work done for
several firms.
</P>
<P>
   And the risks here are mostly on the employer's side _ not the
employees.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, an employer could run into legal trouble if
payroll taxes or workers' comp premiums aren't being correctly paid
by both companies, according to Jamie Johnson, an employment lawyer
with Brobeck Phleger &AMP; Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   For employees, the question is whether they're getting paid for
the total number of hours they put in. If so, this single-paycheck
system isn't hurting them.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to Johnson, it may actually be working to their
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an example: California state disability insurance must be
withheld from the first $31,767 of employees' paychecks. If workers
earn a single paycheck of $40,000, SDI is withheld from only the
first $31,767 of that money. But if a worker earns two separate
paychecks of $20,000 each, SDI would be withheld on $40,000 worth
of income _ more than is necessary. The state would refund the
extra payments at the end of the year, but in the meantime the
worker would receive smaller paychecks than he or she is entitled
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually may be benefiting the employees if they're being
paid through one employer,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
