<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-BANK-MARKETPLACE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK EXECUTIVES CHARTING THE INTERNET STRATOSPHERE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Pa., Texas)  (rk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The quickest way for a chief executive to bolster his company's
stock price, it appears, is to announce a connection to the
Internet. In recent weeks, the banking industry has become
accustomed to such announcements _ and with the associated
stock-trading frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of little-known regional financial companies like
Florida Banks Inc. of Jacksonville, First Sierra Financial Inc. of
Houston and the Patriot Bank of Pottstown, Pa., have jumped as much
as 300 percent in a single day after the companies publicized their
intentions to provide banking services over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who bought in before the announcements are mostly
sitting on paper profits. Among the buyers have been executives and
directors of Florida Banks, First Sierra and Patriot Bank who
purchased shares in the four to six weeks before each company
announced its Internet plans.
</P>
<P>
   The executives say that while they are enthusiastic about the
Internet plans, their recent stock purchases were not timed to take
advantage of an Internet premium. And few, if any, of the insiders
have cashed in so far by selling stock.
</P>
<P>
   In buying shares shortly before announcing their Internet
ventures, however, the executives raise questions that are relevant
to a large number of companies today. At a time when any corporate
press release with the the word ``Internet'' in it seems to move
stock prices, corporate America might need to take a broader view
of what is considered material information to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission defines materiality as
anything a typical investor would need to know to make an informed
decision. Securities laws prohibit people who are in a position of
fiduciary responsibility and who have access to material, nonpublic
information from trading on that knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not at all clear whether the executives in these
instances ran afoul of those rules. In a legal sense, materiality
cannot be judged solely by whether an announcement causes a stock
price to move.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, it seems, have quite another view.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm for Internet banking can be linked directly to
the stock performance of Net.Bank Inc. and the Telebanc Financial
Corp. These two companies, which say they do all their business in
cyberspace without the burden of brick-and-mortar branches, have
captured the fancy of investors in large part because they have
already demonstrated the ability to generate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Telebanc, for example, is expected this year to earn $2.6
million, or 15 cents a share, double its profit last year. Those
earnings would be even higher without a huge advertising budget by
Telebanc intended to attract customers, said Henry Blodget, who
tracks the company for Merrill Lynch and is recommending its
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Blodget says the attraction of Internet-based banks is that they
are not limited to serving customers in areas where the bank has
branches. Like other Internet service businesses, the banks aim to
pass the savings along in the form of higher interest rates on
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The public has enthusiastically responded to the stocks, if not
the online bank accounts, pushing Telebanc shares up to $104.50
from $34 at the beginning of the year and less than $8 last
October. Similarly, Net.Bank shares closed Thursday at $182.4375,
up more than 500 percent since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising, then, that investors seem to have jumped
on any bank's decision to reach out over the Internet. On April 13,
when Florida Banks announced that it would begin offering Internet
banking services in the third quarter, its shares soared from about
$8, where they had been trading for most of the previous year, to
as high as $37.75, closing at $31.25. They have since declined,
closing Thursday at $11.8125, 47 percent higher than before the
Internet announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks before the announcement, four insiders bought
9,000 shares of Florida Banks at about $7 each. The purchases,
totaling $63,500, increased each person's holdings by 1 percent to
20 percent. Though the purchases were relatively small in terms of
the company's $63 million market value, they accounted for as much
as half of the trading in the stock March 22-24.
</P>
<P>
   Should the insiders have been allowed to buy stock when an
announcement about their companies' Internet plans was looming?
</P>
<P>
   T. Edwin Stinson, the chief financial officer of Florida Banks,
who was one of four officials who bought shares, said the news was
important but not entirely new. Florida Banks' plan for Internet
banking was outlined in the company's prospectus for its initial
public offering last July, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were extremely surprised by the reaction'' of the stock,
Stinson said. The main reason the company issued the press release,
he said, was because it had signed a final agreement with a service
provider that would allow the formal startup of the Internet
service, and it wanted to get the news out before discussing it at
an investment conference that week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Florida Banks also draws a strong distinction between its
strategy and Telebanc's. ``We don't want to service commercial
customers that are not in the geographic markets that we are in,''
Stinson said. ``We didn't imply that we are trying to be an
Internet bank.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock purchases were made ``because the stock was trading
below book value,'' Stinson said, referring to the net value of the
company's assets and liabilities. Some of the company's directors
had been lamenting that the shares seemed appreciably cheap, and
``none of us benefited at all'' since none of the shares have been
sold, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks before First Sierra Financial, an
equipment-leasing company, announced that it would establish ``the
first Internet-based business-to-business bank,'' its chief
executive and a director bought 50,000 and 29,600 shares,
respectively, at about $9 each.
</P>
<P>
   The purchases each represented about a day's average volume in
the shares, which trade on Nasdaq. After the announcement on April
14, First Sierra's shares jumped as high as $30 and have since
settled at $14.50.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Depping, the chief executive, points out that the
company's share price had started to move up after First Sierra
reported strong first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been consistently buying shares since November,'' shortly
after their price fell to $9 from $33 amid a downdraft in
speciality finance shares, Depping said. A large block of stock
became available in mid-March, prompting his decision to buy more,
he said. The decision ``really had very little to do with the fact
that we were working on an Internet bank,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Joni S. Naugle, chief operating officer of Patriot Bank, said
she, too, was surprised at the market reaction to Patriot's April
12 introduction of ``Virtual Access Internet Banking'' service.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares, which had traded around $9.50 for two
weeks, jumped as high as $18.75 on the news. Roughly a month before
the announcement, Ms. Naugle and another company executive bought
1,000 shares each, while a director bought 7,400. Each paid about
$10 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purchases were not related at all'' to the anouncement,
Ms. Naugle said. ``Insiders have been buying because the stock is
on sale,'' trading roughly at book value, and they did not sell
shares when the price jumped. Since then, the price has returned to
its previous level, closing Thursday at $10.
</P>
<P>
   That is probably because, once investors read Patriot's press
release closely, they might have noticed that while Patriot was
adding Internet banking services _ including the ability to
transfer funds and pay bills online _ it was not becoming an
Internet bank.
</P>
<P>
   Similar services have been offered by big financial institutions
like Citibank for more than a decade. But to date, only a small
portion of Citibank's customers use the service regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for investors, of course, is that not all Internet
connections are equal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
