<HEADER>
A9660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-FEATURE23-     04-22 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-FEATURE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The gang's not here
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Sunday's DieHard 500 will kick off the 30th
anniversary of Talladega Superspeedway. For the first time in three
decades, however, the Winston Cup race will contain one glaring
omission _ a driver from Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and '80s, Alabama left an indelible mark on the
world of stock car racing. NASCAR legend Bobby Allison of Hueytown,
Ala., tied with Darrell Waltrip for third with 84 career Winston
Cup victories, founded the Alabama Gang nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The founding members were Allison, his brother Donnie, Red
Farmer and Neil Bonnett. Bobby Allison was the only one to win a
Winston Cup championship, in 1983, edging Waltrip in the final race
of the season. Yet, Allison and the Alabama Gang combined to win
112 Winston Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than a half-decade after the deaths of Bonnett and
Davey Allison, Bobby's son, who was considered a second-generation
driver of the Alabama Gang, Sunday's race will be run without an
in-state driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very good feeling,'' Donnie Allison said. ``We
prided ourselves on being pretty good race-car drivers from
Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Allison isn't the only one concerned about the absence.
John Andretti, who was born in Bethlehem, Pa., but who usually
lists Indianapolis as his hometown, tried to persuade Talladega
officials to let him represent Alabama in this weekend's race.
Andretti wanted to list Talladega as his hometown, and he would
have been an honorary citizen of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Alabama Gang was a big deal when I was growing up,''
Andretti said. ``They've been a big part of NASCAR and what got the
sport here. It was more to say thanks for all that they did to help
me enjoy such a great sport. I believe in tradition. I wanted to do
it out of respect. I even talked to Bobby Allison, and he said it
sounded like a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   But Talladega officials turned down the request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were certainly thrilled that he would consider doing
that,'' track spokesman Rick Humphrey said. ``But when the idea was
proposed to us two weeks ago, we had three guys still trying to get
rides for the race. We didn't want to do something that could be
perceived as a lack of loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Winston Cup season opened at Daytona in February, three
Alabama natives were still behind the wheel. Steve Grissom, a
native of Gadsden, started the season in the No. 91 Chevrolet of
owner Joe Falk. Gary Bradberry of Chelsea opened his second Cup
season in the No. 78 Ford of owner Jim Wilson, and Mike Harmon, a
short-track specialist from Birmingport, was supposed to drive for
longtime owner Junie Donlavey.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon's sponsor fell through during Daytona's Speed Weeks.
Donlavey elected to use a variety of more experienced drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom, a former Busch Grand National champion, failed to
qualify for two of the first four races, including the Daytona 500.
He didn't finish higher than 36th in the others and was fired March
13 by Falk after failing to qualify at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom, 36, was a relief driver for injured Jimmy Spencer at
Bristol two weeks ago and helped lead the No. 23 Ford to a
17th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Grissom isn't happy about not driving at Talladega, where
Alabama drivers have won 10 of 59 Winston Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to go to any Winston Cup race without Alabama being
entered,'' Grissom said. ``Here, there's a little extra to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradberry, a former ARCA standout, failed to qualify at Daytona
for Triad Motorsports, a team being helped by Hut Stricklin, a
former Winston Cup driver from Calera, Ala., who is still looking
for a ride this year. Triad Motorsports hasn't entered a race since
Daytona and seems close to folding.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Allison, who co-owns the Busch car driven by Hueytown's
Jimmy Kitchens, doesn't know what the future holds for Alabama's
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope, somewhere down the road, somebody can come back and
put a smile on the faces of everybody in Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
