</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ITEMS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's hot in NASCAR racing? Dale Jarrett
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dale Jarrett hasn't gone this long into a season
without a victory since 1995, when he didn't get his first win
until the 17th event at Pocono. Although he's winless in his first
eight starts this year, Jarrett has been one of Winston Cup's most
consistent drivers, finishing in the top 10 in all but two events.
Going into Sunday's DieHard 500 at Talladega Superspeedway, Jarrett
has six top 10s in a row, including an eighth-place finish last
week at Martinsville, after starting 31st. Jarrett trails Winston
Cup leader Jeff Burton by only 85 points.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S NOT?
</P>
<P>
   After an eighth-place finish at North Carolina Speedway in
February, veteran Geoffrey Bodine said the outing wasn't a
``fluke.'' Sorry, Geoffrey, but it seems to have been. Bodine, who
turned 50 on April 18, is 32nd in points, 640 behind Burton. Only
Jerry Nadeau, Ricky Rudd, Ricky Craven and rookie Elliott Sadler
have fewer points among drivers with at least eight starts. Since
North Carolina, Bodine's average finish in six starts is 31st,
including 38th at Martinsville last week.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To veteran Darrell Waltrip, who returned to the lead lap at
Martinsville for the first time since he finished 25th in the
road-course race at Watkins Glen, N.Y., last season. Waltrip
avoided all the wrecks that caused 10 cautions at Martinsville, but
he did fall a lap down to the leaders during the race. He was able
to regain that lap, however, after making an air-pressure
adjustment and finished 12th, his best effort in 25 races. Waltrip
climbed to 28th in points, only 43 out of the top 25, where he
needs to be to earn a non-chargeable provisional start. ``We've got
enough on us without people saying things about us, so if they'll
just give us a chance, we'll get it there,'' Waltrip said. ``We
can't do it overnight. We're racing a first-year team against guys
that have been doing this for several years now, and I'm proud.''
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To NASCAR, which has done little about addressing the escalating
costs of racing. Only eight events into the Winston Cup season,
Bill Elliott and Ricky Rudd already are hinting that the days of
owning their own cars are numbered. It's no coincidence that the
four remaining independent teams _ Elliott, Rudd, Brett Bodine and
Dave Marcis _ are struggling. At 21st, Elliott's the highest-ranked
owner/driver in the points standings, while Bodine (25th), Rudd
(35th) and Marcis (43rd) are falling behind. None of those teams
has been a factor in a race this season.
</P>
<P>
   TIP SHEET
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup rookie Ken Bouchard will debut in the No. 84 Chevy
and attempt to qualify for Sunday's race. Rookie Stanton Barrett
failed to qualify in the Beau Petty-owned car at the Daytona 500. .
. . Burton, who finished last in the season's first IROC event at
Daytona, will start from the pole in the series' second race
Saturday (1 p.m., ESPN) at Talladega. Dale Earnhardt, who won the
Daytona race, will start last. According to IROC rules, the
finishing order from the previous race is reversed at the next
event. Earnhardt leads the IROC standings with 21 points, while
Bobby Labonte and Mark Martin are tied for second with 19. . . .
Ernie Irvan and Rich Bickle had the fastest laps at 125.815 mph _
an official track record _ at this week's Pontiac testing at
Richmond. Rookie Buckshot Jones was third at 121.45
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Loomis, crew chief for the No. 43 Pontiac of John
Andretti owned by Richard Petty, is one of five active crew chiefs
who have won a Winston Cup event with at least two different
drivers in the 1990s. Andretti won last week's Goody's Body Pain
500 at Martinsville, Va., and Loomis won one race each in 1996 and
1997 with driver Bobby Hamilton. Other crew chiefs (and their
current drivers) with wins in the 1990s with two or more drivers
are Paul Andrews (Jeremy Mayfield), Jimmy Makar (Bobby Labonte),
Larry McReynolds (Mike Skinner) and Robin Pemberton (Rusty
Wallace).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
