<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eyler joins team
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Skip Eyler, a former crew chief for Mark Martin and
Chad Little, has rejoined Roush Racing as crew chief for Kevin
Lepage.
</P>
<P>
   Eyler, who started the season with Dick Trickle, will join the
struggling No. 16 Ford team after Sunday's DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway. Eyler, 35, was the crew chief for Little in 1997 and
Martin in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to work with Kevin and the (No. 16) team,'' Eyler
said. ``They're heading in the right direction now, and I'm just
excited that Jack Roush would give me the opportunity to be a part
of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyler replaces James Ince, who resigned after a 28th-place
finish at Bristol on April 11. Lepage had only one top-10 finish _
seventh at Darlington _ in his second season with Roush.
</P>
<P>
   The team already stands to lose its sponsor, Primestar, after
this season. The satellite communications company was recently
acquired by a competitor. TV Guide has signed on as an associate
sponsor and could become the primary one if the team shows
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR levies fines
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Morgan, Lepage's interim crew chief last week at
Martinsville, was one of three crew chiefs fined by NASCAR for
rules violations.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Leslie, crew chief of Johnny Benson's No. 26 Ford, and
Jimmy Elledge, crew chief for Kenny Wallace's No. 55 Chevrolet,
also were fined $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   All three crew chiefs were penalized for illegal parts and/or
equipment and for drilling holes in frames, frame supports and
cross members with the intent of making the metal lighter. The
violations were found before last week's Goody's Body Pain 500.
</P>
<P>
   Casey is back
</P>
<P>
   It was only two months ago that Casey Atwood's No. 27 Chevrolet
got rear-ended by Mike McLaughlin, flipped several times on the
front stretch and then sat destroyed in the infield grass at
Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, 18, says the wreck won't affect his driving when the
Busch Series hits Talladega Superspeedway on Saturday for its
second and last restrictor-plate race of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you race long enough, then you will be involved in that one
bad crash,'' said Atwood, ninth in the points standings. ``I feel
that I'm lucky in two ways. I was not hurt in the crash, and since
I was not hurt, it has not affected my will to go fast. I'm ready
for the fast speeds and close racing of Talladega.''
</P>
<P>
   Two's not a crowd
</P>
<P>
   Progressive Motorsports' decision to add driver Jeff Green and
the No. 32 Chevy to its stable is paying immediate dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Green and teammate Jason Keller, in his second season with
Progressive, each has one win in the first eight races. Keller is
third in points, only 47 behind leader Elton Sawyer, and Green is
sixth going into Saturday's Touchstone Energy 300.
</P>
<P>
   Green won at Nashville Speedway on April 3, and then Keller
followed with a victory at Bristol a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
