<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schrader wins Busch pole
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Ken Schrader won the pole for Saturday's
Touchstone Energy 300 Busch series race Thursday at Talladega
Superspeedway, and then said his 192.455 mph lap was nothing to get
excited about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car either runs or it don't,'' Schrader said. ``It's very
uneventful riding around here by yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought he'd accomplished something significant by
knocking Joe Nemechek (192.366) from the top starting position,
Schrader said, ``I was just the monkey that sat in the car while it
went around.''
</P>
<P>
   His point was that his engine builder and body people had more
to do with the efficiency of his No. 15 Chevrolet than an
experienced driver tooling around a superspeedway with no traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver here for qualifying is not that big a deal,'' said
Schrader, who also took the Busch pole in the season's first event
at Daytona. ``I feel that the guys in the chassis shop really did a
lot of work.'' Schrader's day went a lot smoother than Nemechek's,
who had to go to a backup engine after he blew his primary
qualifying engine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
