<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOST-FOUND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOST AND FOUND' IS SNARLY, ABUSIVE IN ITS PURSUIT OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Warhol once said every person would be famous for 15
minutes. Well, ``Lost &AMP; Found'' is funny for 15 minutes and then
fades into mean-spirited cruelty and stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   It seems every new comedy wants to be the next ``There's
Something About Mary.'' As a result, the jokes aimed at innocent
people or animals just get more perverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost &AMP; Found'' is a nasty story about smug restaurateur Dylan
Ramsey (David Spade), who falls in love with his luscious French
musician neighbor, Lila Dubois (Sophie Marceau). Lila has come to
America to find work in a symphony and to fulfill her dream of
playing the cello at the Hollywood Bowl. Her ex-fiance, Rene
(Patrick Bruel), has followed her to Los Angeles in order to win
her back.
</P>
<P>
   He's everything Dylan isn't: rich, handsome, buff, clever - and
a philanderer. His very presence rankles Dylan, who is puny and
struggling to expand his short-menu coffee house into a
full-fledged bistro.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan ultimately launches the perfect plan: Lila has a dog named
Jack who continually runs away. He'll kidnap Jack and, when Lila is
frantic with worry, he'll return the terrier and look like a hero
to his dream girl.
</P>
<P>
   But Dylan underestimates Rene's perserverance and canniness.
Soon the two men are at each other's throat for Lila's affections.
And Jack just keeps getting lost in the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Movies have gone a long way down in presenting behavior that
might easily be called ``borderline'' as normal, appealing and
romantic. ``Lost &AMP; Found'' is snarly and abusive in its pursuit of
true love.
</P>
<P>
   Star David Spade co-wrote the script, and the cynical/abusive
attitude he generally displays so well is glaringly in evidence. He
acts so superior that he barely registers enough interest in
another person to make us believe he might fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, ``Lost &AMP; Found'' turns into a woefully contrived, unfunny
mess. Lila, who must be smarter than the film portrays, is stuck
between picking the loser behind door No. 1 or a worse loser behind
door No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   We're ultimately left wondering why Marceau, a French movie
star, ever picked such an unlikely project. By the end, when Lila
is reconciled with her beloved dog, it's clear he's the best of all
her sorry options.
</P>
<P>
   Lost &AMP; Found. Directed by Jeff Pollack. Written by J.B. Cook,
Marc Meeks, David Spade. Cast: David Spade, Sophie Marceau, Patrick
Bruel. Warner Bros. 98 minutes. Rated PG-13 for language, sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
