u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY-N     04-22 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY STILL STANDING, BUT ON UNSTABLE GROUND
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also BKN-CHARLOTTE-SILAS)  
(DW) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeff Van Gundy was working a roll of ankle tape in
his hand. He had walked down a gray hallway inside Madison Square
Garden, flipping the roll against the wall and catching it as he
made his way to an interview room.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat down, he appeared weary and unshaven. Although on
practice days Van Gundy has always looked as if he has been pulled
from the bottom of a hamper, Thursday he was a little more
disheveled than usual, a little more loaded with the nervous energy
he was taking out on the roll of tape.
</P>
<P>
   He did not seem like a relieved man, nor the winner of a power
struggle with Ernie Grunfeld, the team's former president and
general manager. Van Gundy looked like a survivor who had escaped
the ax that had fallen on Grunfeld a day earlier. Grunfeld was
dismissed for assembling a team with a league-high $68-million
payroll that has been skimpy on results, and for allowing acrimony
and miscommunication to divide the organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Grunfeld was held accountable for a team in danger
of missing the playoffs for the first time in 12 years. But the
decision made by the Garden's president, Dave Checketts, did not
absolve Van Gundy from his role in guiding a team that has
struggled to a 21-21 record. With eight games left, beating
Charlotte Friday night at the Garden is the only way to start
making things right again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you work with someone for a long time, you're going
to have disagreements,'' Van Gundy said after Thursday's practice.
``The unfortunate part is, losing caused this. If we win some of
those close games, everybody has their job. What was reported as a
feud, that's way overstated. I even read where Dave said there was
a division. If there was, losing caused the division, not a
division causing losing. That's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm responsible for the results on the floor. Whatever blame
people want to assign, I have to take a great portion of that
because of what happens on the floor. Ernie's thing, because of the
results, certainly that had an impact. I don't know everything
about why Dave decided to do it because I'm not in on those
decisions. But I think everything is triggered by losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's survival will depend on the same quotient. That's
why he had to chuckle when he was asked if he would seek more power
over personnel moves in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, when you're coaching a 21-21 team and thinking
about getting more, I think that's a little hasty,'' Van Gundy said
with a smile. ``I've always been consulted. That doesn't mean
agreement is always there.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, you want to have your voice heard, certainly, but
this isn't about that. This is about losing. There can be a million
conspiracy theories, but it comes down to losing more than people
think you should.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks fail to land a playoff spot or fail to make it
past the first round, there is no guarantee Van Gundy will return
even though he has the unwavering support of Patrick Ewing, the
franchise's centerpiece player. That relationship likely insulated
Van Gundy from being the first one held accountable for this
season, but even Ewing understands that the bond will not save him
if the slide continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's job is on the line,'' Ewing said. ``When you don't
perform to the level you're expected to, everybody's job is on the
line. We definitely have to play for ourselves and for Jeff. The
bottom line is, we have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Win with the talent Grunfeld collected. Marcus Camby was one of
those hand-picked by Grunfeld. Often, Camby was an innocent
middleman in the rift between Grunfeld and Van Gundy over how much
of a role he should play. Now, without Grunfeld as an advocate, he
is not sure if he fits into the Knicks' plans for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be here, but anything can happen now,'' Camby
said. ``Ernie has left and everything's up in the air. We just have
to turn this thing around. If we don't turn it around, I think
there are going to be a lot of changes here.''
</P>
<P>
   Another new addition to the team, Latrell Sprewell, has failed
to blend in well and already has management thinking of trading him
in the off season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't personally feel like I've been put on notice,''
Sprewell said. ``But we're definitely aware there could be other
changes if we continue to play the way we have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one saw Grunfeld's dismissal from his position as
anything but a warning, the change is unlikely to affect how the
team plays on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   As Van Gundy worked the tape Thursday, he acknowledged that.
``I've learned a couple of things by being here,'' he said, ``and
one is, when you lose, it's ugly. That's how it is. Yeah, if we'd
won more, there wouldn't be a need to blame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
