<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HORNETS-SILAS-NYT     04-22 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HORNETS-SILAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILAS TURNS HORNET'S DISARRAY TO DELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C., Ohio, Wis., Ind.)  (Eds: See also BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY) 
(DW) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest team in the National Basketball Association is a
crew full of castoffs, a coach and players who have been
disregarded or underappreciated for a significant stretch of their
careers. But after winning their last nine games and turning a
once-pathetic season into a potential joy ride, Paul Silas and his
Charlotte Hornets can no longer be discounted.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets, who lost eight of their first nine games and at one
point were 4-11, are playing the best basketball in the Eastern
Conference and, incredibly, have their sights set on the playoffs.
With nine regular-season games remaining, Charlotte (21-20) holds
the eighth and final playoff spot, one-half game ahead of the
Knicks, who they visit Friday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   A short time ago, the Hornets seemed to be in disarray. Injuries
to Glen Rice (right elbow) and Anthony Mason (torn biceps) had
sidelined their two best players, and the disgruntled head coach,
Dave Cowens, was venting his frustrations with management to the
news media. Circumstances were as precarious with the owner, George
Shinn, who was being chastised for his financial frugality and
problems in his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even if the Hornets fail to qualify for post-season play,
the future is bright. First, Michael Jordan is reportedly near an
agreement with Shinn that would make him a half owner of the team,
a move that would bring untold benefits to the franchise. Second,
the Hornets seem to have the personnel and chemistry necessary to
become a member of the conference elite.
</P>
<P>
   It all begins with Silas, who took over on an interim basis
after Cowens resigned on March 8. Silas, who coached the hapless
San Diego Clippers from 1980 to 1983 and has been an assistant with
both the Knicks and the Nets, had to wait 16 years for another shot
at a lead job. The delay is somewhat regrettable, since the
longtime assistant has had the respect of players for years. But
under Silas the Hornets have a 17-9 record and the ``interim'' will
almost certainly be removed from his title, especially if the
players have any say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Silas is the man,'' said Bobby Phills, the guard-forward
who has led the Hornets on their nine-game winning streak.
``There's no question that he should get the head-coaching job.
What more could you want in a coach? He's turned this organization
around. He believed in everybody from the get-go and that gave
everyone a lot of confidence. We respect him, and he respects us.
We couldn't ask for anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Phills is one of the many Hornets who, like Silas, has risen
above past slights. A second-round draft pick of the Milwaukee
Bucks, who cut him almost immediately, Phills spent a year in the
Continental Basketball Association, before sticking for six seasons
with Cleveland. Though he built a reputation as a defensive stopper
with the Cavaliers, they thought the seven-year, $33 million
contract Charlotte offered him before last season was too long and
steep.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a mediocre season, Phills has emerged as the team
leader. When Rice and J.R. Reid went to the Los Angeles Lakers for
the shooting guard Eddie Jones and center Elden Campbell, Phills
seemed to be the odd man out. But Silas moved the muscular,
6-foot-5-inch Phills to small forward and the player and team took
off.
</P>
<P>
   Phills, 10th in the league in 3-point accuracy (.415), has led
the Hornets to a 16-4 record since the switch. When he missed six
games from March 28 to April 5 with a pulled left groin, Charlotte
went 1-5. Since his return, the Hornets have not lost, as he has
averaged 19.4 points, 5.6 rebounds and 4.9 assists. He hit
game-winning jump shots against Washington and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby has been the glue to our team since early on,'' Silas
said. ``And now his confidence is unbelievable. He's taking people
off the dribble. He's developed a medium range game. I'm even
seeing him take a couple of dribbles, step back behind the 3-point
line and let it fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Phills, David Wesley, Charlotte's starting point guard,
spent a season in the CBA, and when the Hornets signed him last
season he was viewed as a big stat man on weak teams. Now, he is
proving his critics wrong by helping Charlotte win. As are Campbell
and Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, Shaquille O'Neal's talented backup for the past few
seasons, has been widely regarded as an inconsistent malcontent who
would never deliver on a nightly basis. But in 22 starts for the
Hornets, the 7-footer has been exceptional. He grabbed a
career-high 19 rebounds in his first game in Charlotte and has been
a solid ever since, averaging 15.6 points and 9.5 rebounds, and
shooting 50 percent from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   While Jones, a two-time All-Star, always has been recognized for
his skills, his solid contributions to the Lakers were taken for
granted because of Kobe Bryant's acrobatics. Since the trade,
however, the Lakers have floundered without Jones' defense. (Jones
is doubtful for Friday night's game with a lacerated finger on his
right hand.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
