<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PUSHINGTIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stress, sex and video screens fill up-and-down tale of air
controllers `Pushing Tin'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like ``Donnie Brasco,'' his last movie, director Mike Newell's
``Pushing Tin'' takes us into a high-stress, high-testosterone
demimonde. It's a parallel universe where men make life-and-death
decisions and their women are accustomed to being treated as steam
valves.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Brasco'' was a fact-based slice of mafia life, ``Pushing
Tin'' (also fact-based) introduces us to another kind of family:
the sweaty fraternity of air traffic controllers who keep 747s from
colliding every few seconds in the super-crowded sky above
Manhattan. (``Pushing tin'' is controllers' slang for routing
planes.)
</P>
<P>
   Nick Falzone (John Cusack) is known for keeping his cool,
choreographing the trajectory of all the blips (representing
planes) on his radar screen. It's like a very hip video game, but
``game over'' could translate into hundreds of charred bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're gonna have to build planes faster to keep me
interested,'' he boasts, but the stress shows up in the way Nick
drives maniacally through traffic and can turn anything into a bet.
</P>
<P>
   His sense of competition kicks into high gear with the arrival
of his polar opposite, the brooding, Harley-riding Russell (Billy
Bob Thornton).
</P>
<P>
   Russell's rep as a Zen master of the control room is made even
more impressive by the appearance of Angelina Jolie as his luscious
19-year-old wife, Mary. (``What number are you?'' a woman asks her
at a backyard barbecue full of second and third wives of
controllers.)
</P>
<P>
   For its first third, ``Pushing Tin'' is a fascinating look at
this obsessive-compulsive world. But it turns into something much
more routine, a comedy of discomfort as Nick and Russell's
competitive streak starts to have repercussions in their bedrooms.
The movie becomes a domestic melodrama that could be unfolding in
just about any high-stress situation; it sheds the specifics that
make the film so interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the actors keep the movie in the air even while its
script is steadily losing altitude. Cusack is ideally cast as a
grown-up kid, a family man who can't quite keep the lid down on
temptation. He makes the film's middle section a memorable study in
muted agony as he tries to keep his jealousies and mistakes from
destroying his life. He's beautifully matched by Cate Blanchett as
his wife (a ``first''). Sporting a dead-on Long Island accent, she
exudes an almost palpable sense of decency as a woman trying to
expand her suburban horizons by taking night classes.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, in denim and leather, brings to the movie a sense of
sinuous menace mixed with a sly sense of humor. Jolie (who was the
best thing in the ensemble comedy ``Playing by Heart'') proves that
her physical assets are secondary to her emotional clarity as an
actor. She's one to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble includes Jake Weber as Cusack's pal and Vicki Lewis
as the sole female controller, who works her stress out by lifting
weights when she's not pushing tin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack, Billy Bob Thornton, Cate Blanchett and
Angelina Jolie. Rated R for language and a scene of sexuality. 2
hours, 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A juiced-up ensemble comedy-drama that loses its
bearings halfway through its flight.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
