<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-GARDENS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tour showcases garden retreats perfect for living large and
relaxing outdoors
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lavender wisteria shrouds the deck with wafts of
morning sweetness, inviting homeowners to bring their mug of coffee
outdoors for a look.
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon, canopies of green envelope the porch, attracting
neighbors for a glass of iced tea, while by evening, the cool,
crisp air lures families into the garden for a quiet moonlit meal,
away from the chatter of television.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about this time of year that makes us want to stay
outdoors, long after completing a day of gardening? For the nine
homeowners who will open their private retreats for this year's
Gardens for Connoisseurs Tour on May 8 and 9, it's having a spot
that blends the indoors with the out.
</P>
<P>
   From quaint cottage gardens to sprawling, gracious estates,
``Each garden is truly an extension of the owner's home and a place
where they live,'' said Mary Stanley, co-chairwoman of the event.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, a Mother's Day tradition benefiting the Atlanta
Botanical Garden, illustrates what's become a major design trend _
gardens that are more than just pretty places to pass through. They
are sanctuaries where people relax, share meals and give parties.
Homeowners are using their yards for everything from quiet
breakfast nooks to jazz-filled banquet halls for entertaining
hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   So you say you have a nice garden but need some ideas for making
it more livable. If so, the tour, with stops from Buckhead to
Decatur, offers an array of options.
</P>
<P>
   Creating intimate spaces
</P>
<P>
   When husband and wife are both landscape architects, it's a safe
bet their garden is quite a showplace. Hugh and Mary Palmer Dargan
have designed gardens from grand estates in Atlanta to tiny
courtyards in Charleston, S.C., where they lived until moving to
Atlanta four years ago. Like most new homeowners, they faced their
share of unromantic gardening projects, such as correcting
drainage, when they bought their Peachtree Heights bungalow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised the entire lawn 4 feet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The front yard is anchored on one side by a pair of towering
oaks, while a weeping corkscrew willow creates a focal point on the
other. A wide curving border encircles the lawn, forming what the
couple calls their ``perennial sweep,'' filled with color and
texture at all seasons. In spring, a Japanese maple, snowball
viburnum and a variety of old roses take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Look for practical details in this garden. The beds are lined
with an 8-inch mow strip of Pennsylvania bluestone that keeps the
lawn safe from gardeners, visitors and dogs. The driveway blends
with the garden because the Dargans planted its median with
low-growing ground covers, including sedums and strawberry
begonias. A 20-inch-tall wooden rail fence, backed with wire,
allows their two small dogs to enjoy the yard without needing a
solid enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   In the small L-shaped back yard, the Dargans extended their
cottagelike home into two classically designed garden ``rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The first is accessible through a pair of French doors that open
onto an arbored stone patio, set with table and chairs for enjoying
summer dinners. The patio extends to a quatrefoil-shaped lawn that
gives guests plenty of standing room for taking in the views. At
the rear is a gurgling fountain that draws them to a backdrop of
handpainted ceramic tiles in deep blues, accented by large blue
pots and ornamental spheres.
</P>
<P>
   To the side, a stone path leads to an herb garden with a raised
bed at its center and rosemary topiaries at each corner. This
garden extends to a red ``dining tent'' covering a wooden platform,
open only on the garden side to create privacy. It's ideal for
small dinner parties.
</P>
<P>
   The tent is one of several props the Dargans inherited from
gardens they designed for decorator houses and managed to work into
their tiny retreat. ``We call them `homeless show garden pieces,'
'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms that divide and conquer
</P>
<P>
   Space wasn't a problem two years ago when Doug Candler and Craig
Dick developed their Atlanta garden; the challenge was creating
intimate areas within their expansive back and side yard. Landscape
architect William Smith designed a multiterraced garden large
enough for entertaining hundreds but with cozy spots for suppers
with a few friends.
</P>
<P>
   Six birches were removed to build a long swimming pool extending
from a two-story sun deck to a rear woodland garden, where a
bridge-covered stream flows into a goldfish pond. The pool's
terrace, covered in warm crab orchard stone with umbrella-covered
tables, descends to a second terrace, where a serpentine pathway
winds through a wide border filled with pansies and snapdragons.
Finally, granite steps lead to a lush fescue lawn, where the view
of the Midtown skyline reminds visitors they're not touring a
country estate after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all just a shady lawn before we put in the pool,''
Candler said. ``Now, the extra light allows us to grow a lot
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Using fences, hedges and borders to divide a lawn into ``rooms''
allows homeowners to conquer large open spaces, making them more
functional.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest gardens on tour lies behind a Georgian manor
house in Atlanta. Three years ago, Hugh Dargan Associates updated
the hilltop site, designed by landscape architect Ed Daugherty,
with new plantings and, most recently, a kitchen garden.
</P>
<P>
   One unique feature is that the estate is maintained exclusively
with organic methods and materials. ``It's a new mind-set to do
something of this scope organically,'' Dargan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeping curved borders snake their way through the garden,
creating intrigue as to what's around the bend. White tulips,
Gourmet Popcorn roses and Japanese anemone form the ``white
garden,'' while pastel tulips and blue pansies line a
crescent-shaped garden at the edge of the circular lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen garden's stone walls already were in place. ``We
just jazzed it up a little,'' Dargan said, with a variety of herbs,
including parsley, rosemary and chives. A weather vane creates a
focal point in a center raised bed, while four other beds are
anchored by Regency-inspired tomato baskets, which support Golden
Orb cherries in summer.
</P>
<P>
   From the garden, a path extends to a tulip-blanketed border that
once served as a refuse area. Earlier this month, it dazzled crowds
gathered for a garden party marking a family wedding. ``We now call
it the wedding garden,'' Dargan said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's making a garden space livable.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Gardens for Connoisseurs Tour
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: 11 a.m.-5 p.m. May 8; noon-6 p.m. May 9 (rain or shine).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: Nine private metro gardens and the Atlanta Botanical
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tickets: $20, or $5 per garden, available at the botanical
garden and selected retailers. Maps available with tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 404-876-5859.
</P>
<P>
   CREATING OUTDOOR LIVING SPACES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think garden ``rooms,'' using hedges, fences and borders as
partitions for creating intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use benches, tables and chairs to make areas inviting.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Design sitting areas as focal points in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Direct visitors to these spots with steppingstones or
pathways.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Consider views from the sitting area when selecting a site.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Decorate'' sitting areas with garden ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
