<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-OFF-DAY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz picking up pace of '98
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It's early, but not too early to notice what John Smoltz
is doing.
</P>
<P>
   He is 2-0 with a 2.37 ERA this season. Before that, he waltzed
through spring training _ 2-1, 2.63 ERA. Backing that up was last
year's 17-3 record, and the distinction as baseball's winningest
pitcher over the past three years with 58 victories.
</P>
<P>
   He will go into his next start _ Sunday against the Marlins in
Miami _ having won 20 of 23 decisions dating to Sept. 19, 1997.
That run coincides with Smoltz's last elbow surgery, in the
offseason in 1997, and the ensuing decision to change his pitching
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I step on the mound now, I feel like there's many ways I
can get you out, where I never felt that way before,'' Smoltz said.
``Sure, it was great when I was so-called `dominating.' People saw
the stuff and said, `Why can't he do that 27 times a year?' But
inside, you know every fifth day you're not going to feel great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched too many guys like (Greg) Maddux and (Tom)
Glavine go out there and pitch when they haven't been their best
and win. That's what puts you in a different class. I feel like I'm
approaching that now.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing has been different for Smoltz this year, particularly
so after Monday night's 11-3 win over the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had fun,'' said Smoltz, who unlike last year is pitching
relatively pain-free. ``I haven't had too many games where you say
you had fun and accomplished things at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not too early for catcher Javy Lopez to give Smoltz the
first Cy Young mention of the season. ``That year he won the Cy
Young (in 1996), he did the same thing,'' Lopez said. ``The way
he's throwing, there's no doubt he could be the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Smoltz, he just wants to keep on keeping on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get to the feeling, `Hey, Smoltz is pitching _
game over,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
