r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKNOTES23-COX     04-22 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hornby's slacker portraits lure filmdom's eye
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you wear Doc Martens and listen to Radiohead, you've probably
heard of Nick Hornby. If you haven't, you soon will. The balding,
41-year-old former British high school teacher has struck a chord
with young men _ and women _ with his best-selling books about
soccer, slackers and singles on the prowl.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his novels, ``High Fidelity'' (Riverhead, $12.95
paperback) and ``About a Boy'' (Riverhead, $12.95 paperback) are
headed for the big screen. John Cusack is set to star in ``High
Fidelity,'' the story of the misadventures of a group of record
store employees, and Robert DeNiro has paid $3 million for rights
to ``About a Boy,'' Hornby's tale of a superficial, 36-year-old
bachelor who joins a single parents' club just to meet women.
</P>
<P>
   All this is pretty heady stuff for a middle-aged family man
whose literary inspiration is Anne Tyler. ``I think she's cool,''
Hornby says from his home in London. ``She probably wouldn't think
so. When I read `The Accidental Tourist,' I found it completely
liberating. I realized you could write literary books that were
simple and had jokes in them. I always thought jokes weren't
permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornby was a regular contributor to Esquire and other magazines
before he wrote ``Fever Pitch'' (1992), a memoir about his
obsession with soccer. He followed that in 1995 with ``High
Fidelity,'' which chronicles a breakup from a guy's point of view.
``The kind of fiction I enjoyed reading was domestic, but it tended
to be mostly women who wrote those books,'' Hornby says. ``There
didn't seem to be any reason why a guy couldn't write that kind of
stuff. And, of course, there was the music as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the music. Rob, the protagonist in ``High Fidelity,'' is a
record shop owner who makes music lists such as the Best Five Pop
Songs About Death and has nothing but disdain for fans of Billy
Joel. Will, the self-absorbed bachelor in ``About a Boy,'' cannot
stand it when a woman he meets sings Judy Collins' ``Both Sides
Now'' with her eyes closed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his references to musical trends, Hornby admits that he
really doesn't feel hip. His first music idol was Rod Stewart,
because he also likes soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep up with what's in and out,'' Hornby says of
music. ``I do buy a lot of new stuff. I'm listening to Lauryn Hill
now and I like that a lot. But if anyone tells you something's
cool, it probably isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornby will sign books at 7 p.m. Friday at Chapter 11 at Ansley
Mall, 1544 Piedmont Ave., 404-872-7986.
</P>
<P>
   SASSY OPERA: It's hard to imagine Will Tweedy, Grandpa Rucker,
Miss Love and other characters from ``Cold Sassy Tree'' strutting
across the stage and singing opera, but that's what's planned next
year at the Houston Grand Opera company. Composer Carlisle Floyd,
whose ``Susannah'' is being performed this week at the Metropolitan
Opera House, has been commissioned to write an opera based on late
Atlanta author Olive Ann Burns' classic Southern tale. The story of
Grandpa Rucker's scandalous marriage to Miss Love barely two weeks
after his wife's death is told by 14-year-old Will Tweedy. It's set
around the turn of the century in a Georgia town called Cold Sassy,
which was renamed Commerce by its citizens to make it sound more
modern. ``The first thing that attracted me to `Cold Sassy Tree'
were the characters,'' Floyd says from his home in Houston. ``They
were wonderfully rich and colorful, and the story is a curious mix
of the comic and the serious. It was the hardest libretto I've ever
had to do.'' The opera is scheduled to debut in Houston next
spring, with Australian film director Bruce Beresford (``Driving
Miss Daisy'') helming the production.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
