<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9684 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-BONE25-COX     04-22 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BONE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enigmatic anti-hero characterizes best, worst of capitalist
spirit
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the appropriately named novel ``Bone by Bone,'' Peter
Matthiessen completes his brilliant trilogy about a back-country
South Carolina farmer who became a legend on the lawless frontier
of turn-of-the-century Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about the real Edgar J. Watson. He was born in
Edgefield, S.C., in 1855, fled under suspicious circumstances and
ended up in Florida after adventures out West.
</P>
<P>
   When Matthiessen introduced his character in his 1990 novel,
``Killing Mr. Watson,'' the man is murdered by 20 neighbors in the
first chapter. The rest of the book is an account of the victim's
life as seen through the eyes of the witnesses. It becomes clear
that Watson is a man of contradictions. Was he a decent family man
and prosperous sugar cane grower? Or a coldblooded killer who shot
the outlaw queen Belle Starr in the back and murdered dozens?
</P>
<P>
   We never hear from Watson in the first book _ or the second. In
``Lost Man's River'' (1997), Lucius Watson tries unsuccessfully to
solve the mystery of a father whose moods were as unpredictable as
the South Florida weather.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in ``Bone by Bone,'' Matthiessen, a founder of the
Paris Review and winner of the National Book Award for ``The Snow
Leopard,'' lets his enigmatic character tell his story, from his
traumatic childhood as the son of an abusive, alcoholic father to
his brutal demise in the Everglades. Yes, he did kill Starr, but
there were extenuating circumstances; and yes, he did kill a number
of people, but most were justified.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on local lore and legend, Matthiessen reconstructs
Watson as meticulously as a scientist reassembles the skeleton of a
prehistoric creature. The result is a portrait of a troubled man
determined to let nothing derail his dreams of an empire. Always in
a black frock coat that concealed his ever-present pistol, Watson
was an intimidating figure who loomed over his neighbors,
physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   In a sprawling tale reminiscent of Larry McMurtry's ``Lonesome
Dove,'' Matthiessen eloquently re-creates the last years of the
American frontier, when railroad barons such as Henry Flagler used
any legal means to carve out his empire and men like Edgar Watson
ignored the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``No decent American is going to believe that a man who pays his
bills is a common criminal, no matter what,'' Watson says.
</P>
<P>
   But believe they did. Everywhere Watson went, his reputation as
a killer preceded him and thwarted his dreams of becoming a
respectable businessman. Bankers and developers refused to lend him
money, scoffed at his ideas, then adopted them as their own.
Frustrated by lack of acceptance, Watson resorted to violence to
achieve his ends.
</P>
<P>
   How myths are created _ particularly in frontier regions _ is
one of the novel's central themes. But the author, an ardent
environmentalist, is more interested in a tragedy greater than the
self-destruction of an anti-hero. This is an account of the
plundering of paradise by Watson, Flagler and others.
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen describes in poetic but horrifying detail how
multitudes of egrets and flamingos were killed for their valuable
plumage, how Indian mounds were ravaged by relic hunters and how
thousands of alligators were slain for their hides.
</P>
<P>
   On one alligator hunt, Watson tells of ``stripping the soft
flats off the bellies and rolling them up by firelight. It was
exciting for a while, because stacking flats at such a rate was
like heaping up cash money. . . . It soon turned to a stink of
putrefaction, as if the Everglades had rolled over and died.''
</P>
<P>
   That odor clings to Watson as he sinks deeper into debt and
desperation. By novel's end, Matthiessen has fit the bones together
to show a man who represents the capitalist spirit of America at
its best _ and worst. In Watson's view, his actions were no
different from those of an imperialistic nation that seized Spanish
colonies in the Caribbean and Pacific. In the words of one of
Matthiessen's fictional historians, ``Say what you like about
Mister Watson, he looked and acted like our idea of a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Bone by Bone. By Peter Matthiessen. Random House. $23. 288
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A searing portrait of frontier Florida and an
empire builder created and destroyed by his own myth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
