<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9689 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE25-C0X     04-22 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE25-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Behind-scenes Clinton tale feels like old news
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The house wine would do, and the second glass would be
pushed aside at the end. No one thought to order a bottle for the
table. The tone of the evening was less celebratory than warily
businesslike. Michael Isikoff, the author of ``Uncovering Clinton:
A Reporter's Story'' (Crown, $25), had finished a book signing at
Chapter 11 bookstore in the Peachtree Battle Shopping Center and
now, sitting on the patio of Anis, a Provencal restaurant in
Buckhead, he fidgeted in his seat continually while conversations
around him went on without reference to Bill Clinton or Monica
Lewinsky or, for that matter, Michael Isikoff.
</P>
<P>
   A first-time author on tour is anxious about reviews, anxious
about sales, anxious about making a good impression. In Isikoff's
case, there was anxiety of another kind as well. At Chapter 11,
while he was signing copies of ``Uncovering Clinton,'' a display
case promoting George Stephanopoulos' ``All Too Human'' flanked
him, and one could hardly notice Isikoff's book without noticing
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff is the Newsweek reporter credited with uncovering (while
working for The Washington Post) the undisclosed extent of
President Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky, and with it the
supporting cast of a soap opera whose run has just about played
out. He was to have appeared on Geraldo Rivera's CNBC program that
evening, but gamely settled for dinner with a reporter and his
media escort when the show's producers decided Kosovo was of
greater urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Tenacious reporting
</P>
<P>
   Before the entrees were served, Isikoff groused about reviews
his book has received and about ``the scandal,'' as he put it, of
book reviewing in general. The only reviewers who had actually read
``Uncovering Clinton,'' apparently, were the ones who had good
things to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's right there,'' Isikoff said, and indeed it is. As
a piece of reporting, no one can begrudge Isikoff his tenacity and
keen intuition. You admire it all the more if you were once a
political reporter yourself, and know the gray area that separates
public appearance from private reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great story, a compelling story,'' Isikoff was saying.
But is it really? Its principals by now are tediously familiar. Is
it worth knowing still more? This is the curse of current events,
of course. They are evanescent as snowflakes, if never quite so
pure. A sense of proportion takes hold and the Linda Tripps and
Lucianne Goldbergs seem even smaller than we imagined.
</P>
<P>
   This is not entirely Isikoff's fault. He only wanted to tell a
story that first was pirated out from under him by Matt Drudge, the
guttersnipe of the Internet, and then made community property.
Robbed of a story that was, in a sense, ``his,'' he sets out to
tell it in the first person, with his own tribulations and shouting
matches with editors never far from center stage.
</P>
<P>
   An ear for journalese
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff would not be the first journalist to find that the
narrative techniques of news reporting are not those of nonfiction.
A news story, written in a tight prose that allows no breathing
room, assumes the shape of an inverted pyramid, with the most
important information presented first. A book requires a different
contour altogether. It doesn't look like a pyramid and it shouldn't
look like a sack of potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Neither should its language sound like a gab on the phone.
Journalism lives by immediacy, serious nonfiction by a more
measured consideration of what one wants to say. Isikoff, needing
to finish his book before Monica was yesterday's news, is given to
the journalese of reporters whose nose is better than their ear.
Thus, Kenneth Starr is described as a ``conservative legal titan,''
lawyer Joseph Cammarata is ``slated'' to appear on TV talk shows, a
Post colleague is ``a pro'' (but, one paragraph earlier, a Clinton
adviser an ``eminence grise.'' An article in a legal magazine
exploring Paula Jones' complaint is not long but ``massive.'' And
when one editor wants to talk to another, he ``marches'' into his
office. Isikoff himself, within the space of half a page, is
``stunned to learn,'' ``amazed to discover'' and ``chagrined to
discover.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the misspellings. The first I noticed was
that of my old Raleigh colleague James Bennet, who covered the
White House for The New York Times. It would be easy for the
unawares to give him the extra ``t'' of most Bennetts, including
Clinton lawyer Robert Bennett. But ``Arkansas senator William
Fullbright'' is inexcusable, and former Clinton press secretary Dee
Dee Myers will wonder who this ``DeDe Meyers'' might be.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, these are small and inconsequential; cumulatively
they add up to sloppiness in a book whose story does not become
more compelling with each day. The morning after Isikoff finished
his dinner in Buckhead and flew to Chicago for another signing, the
headlines read, ``Scores of refugees killed in disputed convoy
attack.'' Monica didn't matter much to Bill, and now the world's
losing interest, too.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
