<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9692 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-ELLISON23-COX     04-22 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-ELLISON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ellison's second act
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writing a first novel that becomes a classic can be a blessing
and a curse. There's instant acclaim, of course, but with the fame
comes intense pressure to write an even better second book.
Margaret Mitchell and Harper Lee didn't even attempt to top their
spectacular debuts. Ralph Ellison died trying.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two years after his landmark book ``Invisible Man'' was
published, Ellison was still reshaping and rewriting his sprawling
manuscript when he died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had become a saga,'' says Ellison's literary executor, John
F. Callahan, ``and within the saga were several possible novels.''
</P>
<P>
   One of these novels will be published this summer as
``Juneteenth'' (Random House, $25), thanks to Callahan's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The professor of humanities at Lewis and Clark College in
Portland, Ore., was asked by Ellison's widow to edit the manuscript
into one volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seemed to betray his work,'' Callahan says. ``Then, in
the midst of this manuscript, I found there was an
all-but-finished, compelling novel. One of the sections of the
novel he called `Juneteenth,' and it hit me one day, that's the
title.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 1950s, ``Juneteenth'' is the story of Hickman, a
black jazz musician. Hickman eventually becomes a minister and
raises a young boy, Bliss, as a black child even though he looks
white. Bliss runs away from home, becomes a race-baiting senator in
New England, and is shot on the floor of the Senate by a young
black man. As he lies dying, he summons Hickman to his bedside to
talk of their shared pasts and buried secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to June 19, 1865, the day that Union troops
landed at Galveston, Texas, and brought news of Lincoln's
Emancipation Proclamation. Ever since, that date has been a day of
celebration among blacks in Texas and Ellison's home state of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has been moved by `Invisible Man' is going to want
to read this book,'' says Callahan, who spent 2 1/2 years preparing
the manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   ``Invisible Man'' chronicles the life of a black man who grows
up in the segregated South, moves to New York and struggles to
escape racial stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Invisible Man,'' ``Juneteenth'' is about what it means to
be an American, Callahan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the novel says you can't deny your kinships, and
kinship is not fundamentally a matter of bloodlines. It has to do
with the relationships in your life. The book is about liberation
and rebirth. You never fully gain liberation. You have to achieve
it over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   I N E L L I S O N ' S W O R D S
</P>
<P>
   The following are among copious notes Ralph Ellison made during
the four decades that ``Juneteenth'' was a work in progress:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A great religious leader is a `master of ecstasy.' He evokes
emotions that move beyond the rational onto the mystical. A jazz
musician does something of the same. By his manipulation of sound
and rhythm, he releases movements and emotions which allow for the
transcendence of everyday reality. As an ex-jazzman, Hickman
combines the two roles, and this is the source of his leadership.
He possesses a power which is not directly active _ or at least not
recognized for what it is in the south's political arena, but it is
there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Negroes appear to whites to enjoy themselves more because
they have so little of that which is material. They appear to
whites to suffer grief, heartbreak, and sadness more because they
have, apparently, so much to be unhappy about. And the source of
that unhappiness is seen as based in their color and social status
rather than in their humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
