<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9694 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-FICTION25-COX     04-22 1917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-FICTION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    List of new fiction books
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  FIRST FICTION
</P>
<P>
   The Coldest Winter Ever. By Sister Souljah. Pocket Books. $23.
The renowned hip-hop artist and political activist paints a
street-smart portrait of the daughter of a Brooklyn drug lord.
</P>
<P>
   The Drowning People. By Richard Mason. Warner Books. $24.
``Yesterday afternoon, my wife of more than 30 years shot herself.
. . . It was I who killed her.'' So begins this story of passion,
revenge and murder among Britain's upper class from a 20-year-old
student at Oxford University. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise Engaged. By Suzanne Finnamore. Knopf. $22. Eve has 12
months and 27 Valium (``Only twenty-seven more bad things can
happen to me'') before the big day. It's an enlightening glimpse
into the time-honored transformation from rational woman to
bride-to-be. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Hadrian's Walls. By Robert Draper. Knopf. $23. The lifelong
friendship between a prison director and a notorious convict
creates a conflict between obligation and loyalty. The author, who
lives in Austin, Texas, has ``a good ear for the tones of the
region,'' according to Larry McMurtry, wo should know. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing. By Melissa Bank.
Viking. $23.95. In seven connected stories, witty and wise Jane
navigates her way through love, sex, relationships and career. Bank
was paid $275,000 in advance, a huge sum for a debut collection of
stories, and she's already working on the screenplay, which is in
development with Francis Ford Coppola and American Zoetrope
Studios. (June)
</P>
<P>
   A Stranger in the Earth. By Marcel Theroux. Harcourt Brace. $23.
Horace Littlefair, an innocent from a small English village, goes
to London to make his fortune in this debut effort from the son of
Paul Theroux. (Aug.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GENERAL FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Tough, Tough Toys for Tough, Tough Boys. By Will Self. Grove
Press. $23. A collection of warped tales of drug-dealing and
hitchhiking from the British author of last year's ``Great Apes.''
The Guardian of London describes Self as ``a wayward genius.''
(May)
</P>
<P>
   England, England. By Julian Barnes. Knopf. $23. From the British
writer who wrote the uproarious ``Flaubert's Parrot'' and ``A
History of the World in 10 1/2 Chapters,'' a funny and serious
novel that was short-listed for the Booker Prize. Sir Jack Pitman
creates a ``destination'' on the Isle of Wight where tourists can
find replicas of Big Ben, Wembley Stadium, Princess Diana's grave
and even Harrods, conveniently located inside the Tower of London.
(May)
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Faith. By Jodi Picoult. Morrow. $24. When her parents
divorce, 7-year-old Faith finds a friend who supports her _ a
friend who may be imaginary. Is Faith a prophet or just a troubled
little girl? (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Ground Beneath Her Feet. By Salman Rushdie. Henry Holt. $26.
The author's sixth novel remakes the myth of Orpheus and Eurydice
in the world of rock 'n' roll. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Another World. By Pat Barker. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $17.50. A
study of memory and the way the violent past distorts the present
by the winner of the 1995 Booker Prize for ``The Ghost Road.''
(May)
</P>
<P>
   A Dangerous Friend. By Ward Just. Houghton Mifflin. $23. The
former journalist, following last year's ``Echo House'' (a National
Book Award finalist), returns to Vietnam, the subject of such
earlier fiction as ``A Soldier of the Revolution'' (1970 ) and
``Stringer'' (1974). Just portrays American innocents undertaking
``nation building'' in a land they don't understand. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Nanny and the Iceberg. By Ariel Dorfman. Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux. $25. This is billed as ``an ebullient comedy about sex,
Antarctica and Che Guevara'' by the Chilean expatriate who teaches
at Duke University and lives near Durham, N.C. He wrote last year's
``Heading South, Looking North: A Bilingual Journey.'' (May)
</P>
<P>
   Brief Interviews With Hideous Men: Stories. By David Foster
Wallace. Little, Brown. $24. The first new fiction in four years
from the author of ``A Supposedly Fun Thing I'll Never Do Again''
and ``Infinite Jest.'' All the stories in this new collection first
appeared in Harper's Bazaar, Esquire and elsewhere. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Night Inspector. By Frederick Busch. Harmony Books. $23. In
1867 New York City, a Civil War veteran finds himself drawn into a
steamy underworld of murderers, whores and sewer and slum dwellers.
Twenty-two years ago Busch tried the same sort of ``historical
reconstruction'' in ``The Mutual Friend,'' which reimagined the
Victorian world of Charles Dickens. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Elementals: Fire and Ice. By A.S. Byatt. Random House. $21.95. A
collection of stories about opposites _ passion and loneliness, art
and life, betrayal and loyalty _ from the Booker Prize-winning
author of ``Possession'' and ``Angels &AMP; Insects.'' (May)
</P>
<P>
   A Corner of the Veil. By Laurence Cosse. Scribner. $23. Already
a best seller in France, this theological thriller asks: What if
God's existence was proven, undeniably and irrefutably? (May)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Great Snow Mountains: Stories. By Louis L'Amour.
Bantam Books. $16.95. This is the first of four posthumous
collections of L'Amour material, edited by his daughter Angelique,
featuring an eclectic mix of early adventure stories set in China,
on the high seas and in the boxing ring. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Snow Man. By Carolyn Chute. Harcourt Brace. $23. From the author
of ``The Beans of Egypt, Maine,'' comes the drama of two women who
shelter a militia member wanted for murder. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Fencing Master. By Arturo Perez-Reverte. Harcourt Brace.
$24. The Spanish-born author of ``The Club Dumas'' and ``The
Seville Communion'' sets this elaborate historical mystery in
19th-century Madrid. (June)
</P>
<P>
   A God in Ruins. By Leon Uris. HarperCollins. $27.50. The
literary lion (``Exodus,'' ``QB VII,'' ``Trinity'') jumps ahead to
2008, when a presidential candidate raised Catholic discovers he
was born Jewish. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Timbuktu. By Paul Auster. Henry Holt. $23. Mr. Bones, the canine
confidant of Willy G. Christmas, a poet-saint from Brooklyn, cannot
speak, but he can think, and out of his thoughts the endlessly
inventive Auster (the screenplay for ``Smoke'' and a memoir, ``Hand
to Mouth'') has spun a tragic and comic tale. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Someone to Watch Over Me: Stories. By Richard Bausch.
HarperFlamingo. $24. A new collection. In ``Riches,'' one couple's
lives are changed in an unexpected way after they win the lottery;
in ``Not Quite Final,'' an older couple going through a divorce
re-evaluate their decision when their daughter and her husband and
new baby move back into town; and in ``Two Altercations,'' a newly
married couple assess their marriage when violence tests each
person's true character. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Local Girls. By Alice Hoffman. Putnam. $22.95. A collection of
stories about the Samuelsons of Long Island, a family torn apart by
tragedy and divorce, from the author of ``Here on Earth'' and
``Practical Magic.'' (June)
</P>
<P>
   The Redhunter: A Novel Based on the Life of Sen. Joe McCarthy.
By William F. Buckley Jr. Little, Brown. $25. By the National
Review founder who, as a young man, endorsed McCarthy's crusade.
(June)
</P>
<P>
   Until the Real Thing Comes Along. By Elizabeth Berg. Random
House. $23. A woman in love with the wrong man finds an original
solution, by the author of ``Durable Goods,'' ``The Joy School''
and ``What We Keep.'' (July)
</P>
<P>
   Broke Heart Blues. By Joyce Carol Oates. Dutton. $24.95. John
Reddy Heart, a handsome young heartthrob in Willowsville, N.Y., is
implicated in his mother's murder and quickly becomes a celebrity
on the lam. (July)
</P>
<P>
   The Anniversary and Other Stories. By Louis Auchincloss.
Houghton Mifflin. $25. Nine previously unpublished stories from the
master storyteller of American high society. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Bagombo Snuff Box. By Kurt Vonnegut. Putnam. $23.95. Vonnegut
first began writing short fiction half a century ago, during the
golden age of magazines. Soon he was selling enough stories to The
Saturday Evening Post, Collier's, Argosy and others to quit his job
as public relations man at General Electric and devote himself full
time to a writing career that has included 14 novels, a collection
of stories and three books of nonfiction. This collection features
24 of the author's favorite stories. (August)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  PAGE TURNERS
</P>
<P>
   Fortune. By Belva Plain. Delacorte. $25.95. Two women love the
same man, who loses his idealism to ambition. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The White House Connection. By Jack Higgins. Putnam. $25.95. A
secret White House aide and a former terrorist pursue an assassin.
(May)
</P>
<P>
   Granny Dan. By Danielle Steel. Delacorte. $19.95. A simple box
is filled with a grandmother's mementos. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Havana Bay. By Martin Cruz Smith. Random House. $25.95. Arkady
Renko travels to Cuba to solve the murder of an old friend. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Prayers for Rain. By Dennis Lehane. Morrow. $24. Boston private
investigators Patrick Kenzie and Angela Gennaro _ a Nick and Nora
Charles for the '90s _ track a vicious predator. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Shell Game. By Carol O'Connell. Putnam. $24.95. New York cop
Kathleen Mallory probes the death of a magician on live television.
(July)
</P>
<P>
   Black Notice. By Patricia Cornwell. Putnam. $25.95. A cargo ship
arriving at Richmond's Deep Water Terminal from Belgium is
discovered to be transporting a locked container holding the
decomposed remains of a stowaway. Medical examiner Kay Scarpetta's
autopsy reveals neither a cause of death nor an identification, but
the victim's personal effects and an odd tattoo take her on a case
that careens across international borders. (July 5)
</P>
<P>
   Loose Lips. By Rita Mae Brown. Bantam. $24.95. World War II
home-front life is the backdrop for the continued antics of the
Hunsenmeir sisters, Juts and Wheezie. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Lake News. By Barbara Delinsky. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $24. Lily
Blake is wrongly accused of having an affair with a newly appointed
cardinal. (July)
</P>
<P>
   The Burglar in the Rye. By Lawrence Block. Dutton. $23.95.
Bookseller by day, burglar by night, Bernie Rhodenbarr is back.
(July)
</P>
<P>
   The First Victim. By Ridley Pearson. Hyperion. $23.95. Seattle
policeman Lou Boldt's investigation involves illegal aliens and a
mysterious disappearance. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Double Reverse. By Tim Green. Warner Books. $24. The author of
``The Red Zone'' and ``The Dark Side of the Game'' sets another
thriller in the world of professional football. Green, an Atlanta
Falcon for eight seasons, lives in New York. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Devil's Teardrop. By Jeffery Deaver. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25. In
Washington in the last hours of 1999, the police are called in to
solve a mass murder and prevent another massacre. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter's Bones. By Faye Kellerman. Morrow. $25.50. A brilliant
astrophysicist disappears for 25 years, re-emerges as guru Father
Jupiter, and then is found dead. This is the 11th in Kellerman's
series of blockbusters featuring Peter Decker and Rina Lazarus.
(August)
</P>
<P>
   Mr. X. By Peter Straub. Random House. $25.95. The son of a
diabolical father must discover his own supernatural powers to end
a legacy of evil. (August)
</P>
<P>
   The Edge. By Catherine Coulter. Putnam. $21.95. An FBI agent
suddenly develops ESP. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Hearts in Atlantis: Stories. By Stephen King. Scribner. $27.
Four disturbing tales of an America shadowed by Vietnam, our
national nightmare. (September)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
