<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-PROULX25-COX     04-22 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-PROULX25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proulx takes edge off her harsh tales
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Annie Proulx isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Little she writes about smacks of the familiar. Where so many
successful authors strive to create worlds that are instantly, even
comfortably, recognizable to readers, Proulx goes where few others
would. Not if they had many other options, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in 1993's Pulitzer Prize-winning ``The Shipping News,''
the distraught main character relocates to a Newfoundland that is
more day-to-day details about codfishing than dreamy seascapes.
And, in making a musical instrument the central motif of 1996's
``Accordion Crimes,'' Proulx settled not on the piano or violin,
but rather on the unfamiliar
</P>
<P>
   squeezebox.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it's not surprising that Proulx chose America's least
populated state, Wyoming, as the setting for the stories in her new
collection, ``Close Range.'' Or that in some ways, the people and
places she writes about seem more foreign than if the book had been
set in Wiesbaden, Germany, or Wales.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Mud Below,'' Diamond Felts is a rodeo bull rider
constantly bucked about by life and increasingly looking for
reasons to keep hanging on. In ``People in Hell Just Want a Drink
of Water,'' the eight Dunmire brothers are ``brass-nutted boys''
who ride their horses hard on their ranch outside Laramie _ and are
even harder in their treatment of an addled neighbor who
``displays'' himself to the local women.
</P>
<P>
   There are 11 stories in all, each one featuring characters
seemingly as unrelenting as the land they work or as desperate as
the furtive couplings they engage in with near-strangers in drab
motel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it all might be too hard for readers to take were it not
for Proulx's unerring eye for detail and her unfailing use of
language. Diamond is ``playing the bull night after night,''
experiencing the short-lived rush of sex, but making sure ``there
was nobody in his life to slow him down with love.'' We may not
know many people like Diamond, the Dunmires or any of Proulx's
other characters, but we can't help wanting to know these
characters in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they can even break our hearts without warning. In
the final story, ``Brokeback Mountain,'' Ennis Del Mar and Jack
Twist are at once Proulx's most unbelievable creations and her most
poignantly believable. Hard-driven and hard-drinking cowboys, they
meet in their late teens and embark on an intense sexual
relationship that lasts for nearly 20 years despite both their
marriages and long periods of separation.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like an affair (and an affair that must be kept secret
in unforgiving Wyoming), but really it's love. And then it's too
late to do anything about it. Or as Ennis tells himself at the end
of a story that should have even the most hardhearted reader
blinking back tears, ``If you can't fix it, you've got to stand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy. But Proulx's ``Close Range'' is definitely worth
it.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska covers pop culture for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
