<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9697 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-SOUTH25-COX     04-22 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-SOUTH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Focus
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   The Seventh Child: A Lucky Life. By Freddie Mae Baxter. Knopf.
$21. Part personal history, part social history, this story spans
three generations of an African-American family. Baxter grew up in
South Carolina and moved to New York in the 1940s as a teenager in
search of a better life. Eventually, she brought all seven siblings
up North to be with her. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Southerners in NYC. Edited by Judy Long and Patrick Allen. Hill
Street Press. $24. A collection of fiction, nonfiction, memoir and
poetry by writers ranging from Truman Capote and Langston Hughes to
Willie Morris and William Styron, all writing on the New York City
experience, whether they were passing through or there to stay.
(May)
</P>
<P>
   My Grandfather's Finger. By Edward Swift. University of Georgia
Press. $24.95. An affectionate portrait of Big Thicket in east
Texas. The author _ a New York novelist and visual artist who says
growing up in this colorful, singularly Southern community
virtually sealed his fate as a writer _ takes a sentimental journey
through this ``mystical world of carnivals, talking fiddles, houses
on wheels, atomic bombs and total-immersion baptisms.'' (May)
</P>
<P>
   Southern Hospitality: Tourism and the Growth of Atlanta. By
Harvey K. Newman. University of Alabama Press. $44.95. Newman, an
associate professor of public administration and urban studies at
Georgia State University, studies the burgeoning hospitality
industry in the city, paying particular attention to how race,
gender, ethnicity and class have affected growth. (June)
</P>
<P>
   We Were the Land's: The Biography of a Homeplace. By John Head.
Longstreet. $22. Head, a member of The Atlanta Constitution's
editorial board, brings his grandfather's house back to life
despite naysaying appraisers. His tale of the experience touches on
the meaning of family, community and our connection to the past.
(June)
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Like a River: The Black Church and Social Reform. By
Andrew Billingsley. Oxford. $25. African-American churches have
long been the focal point of social change in their communities.
Billingsley, a professor at the University of South Carolina,
surveys 1,000 black churches across the country, including the
oldest, the First African Baptist Church in Savannah. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Due South: Dispatches From Down Home. By R. Scott Brunner.
Villard. $19.95. A collection of essays on daily life from a
National Public Radio commentator who grew up in Bessemer, Ala.,
and lives in Brandon, Miss. Topics range from the all-purpose
Southern disclaimer ``Bless her heart'' to the exoticism of
Southern town and county names _ like Eastaboga, Opp and Slapout _
to universal questions such as ``Why can't I enjoy fishing the way
my father does?'' (July)
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   The Oxygen Man. By Steve Yarbrough. MacMurray &AMP; Beck. $20. A
gritty first novel of retribution and reconciliation set in
Indianola, Miss. Yarbrough, whose short fiction has appeared in The
Oxford American, The Hudson Review and The Southern Review and in
three collections, ``Family Men,'' ``Mississippi History'' and
``Veneer,'' is a professor of English and creative writing at
California State University in Fresno. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Rushing. By Patty Friedman. Counterpoint. $23. In this
second novel from Friedman, a charming but delusional woman wanders
through glorious, gaudy New Orleans, where the author lives. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Poachers. By Tom Franklin. Morrow. $22. Stories set in Alabama
evoke a world of hunting, trailer parks, poor white trash and
boozers. The author, who has worked in a sandblasting plant, at a
hazardous waste cleanup site and in a hospital morgue, teaches
writing in Mobile. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Back to the Moon. By Homer H. Hickam Jr. Delacorte. $23.95.
Before becoming a permanent display at the Smithsonian, the space
shuttle Columbia is hijacked by a renegade group of former NASA
insiders and headed for the moon. Hickam, a former NASA engineer
and author of the acclaimed memoir ``Rocket Boys'' (renamed
``October Sky'' for the big screen), tries his hand at fiction for
the first time. He lives in Huntsville, Ala. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Miss Julia Speaks Her Mind. By Ann B. Ross. Morrow. $23. When
Wesley Lloyd Springer passed away, he left his proper Southern wife
two legacies: a sizable estate and an out-of-wedlock son. The
author lives in Hendersonville, N.C. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Cup of Love. By Franklin White. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $22.50. In his
follow-up to ``Fed Up With Fanny,'' Atlanta author White introduces
Vance, a young man who reforms his doglike ways only to find out
that true love doesn't always run smoothly. (July)
</P>
<P>
   O Careless Love: Stories and a Novella. By Susan Dodd. Morrow.
$22. The settings for these 10 stories range from a desolate island
in winter to a broken-down bus in rush-hour traffic. Dodd, who
lives in Ocracoke, N.C., wrote last year's well-received novel
``The Mourner's Bench.'' (August)
</P>
<P>
   Florida Roadkill. By Tim Dorsey. Morrow. $25. In South Florida,
$5 million is left in the trunk of the wrong car and a convoy of
homicidal wackos takes off in pursuit. This black comedy is the
first novel for Dorsey, a native of Florida who works at the Tampa
Tribune. (August)
</P>
<P>
   A Long Way From Home. By Connie Briscoe. HarperCollins. $25.
Briscoe (``Big Girls Don't Cry,'' ``Sisters and Lovers'') tells the
story of Civil War Virginia through the eyes of three generations
of house slaves. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
