<HEADER>
A9698 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-HEMINGWAY25-C     04-22 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-HEMINGWAY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ernest Hemingway: Everyone Remembers Papa
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway once said he wanted no biography of himself
written while he was alive and preferably not for 100 years after
he died. He was granted the first wish, but shortly after his death
in 1961 the scholars and critics descended on his literary carcass
like so many vultures circling a dead leopard on Mount Kilimanjaro.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,100 scholarly articles, numerous biographies and
four posthumous books have been published since he blew his brains
out with a 12-gauge shotgun from Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch. Literary
festivals and bars have been named after him, T-shirts are marketed
bearing his likeness, and hundreds of aspiring young writers have
made near-religious pilgrimages to Paris and Pamplona in hopes of
absorbing some essence of Papa.
</P>
<P>
   Larger than life when alive, Hemingway became a giant when dead.
</P>
<P>
   On the 100th anniversary of his birth this summer _ June 21 _
Hemingway fans can enjoy a feeding frenzy on new books about the
man whose goal in life was to write one true sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to several biographies and photo books, ``True at
First Light,'' the final posthumous work of Hemingway's, will be
published. Edited by his son, Patrick Hemingway, the ``fictional
memoir'' chronicles Hemingway's final safari in Africa and his love
affair with a young African woman.
</P>
<P>
   Four other unfinished Hemingway works have been published
posthumously: ``A Moveable Feast,'' ``Islands in the Stream,''
``The Dangerous Summer'' and ``The Garden of Eden.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hemingway were alive, the sight of the upcoming literary
spectacle would drive him to suicide _ or murder, says his friend,
author A.E. Hotchner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hated this kind of thing. Years ago, a young professor of
English decided he would be an interpreter of Hemingway and wrote
to him,'' says Hotchner, whose memoir, ``Papa Hemingway'' (Carroll
&AMP; Graf, $13.95 paperback), recently was reissued. ``Hemingway said,
`Whatever your publishers will pay you, I'll pay you double not to
write it. You'll get it wrong.' They're still getting it wrong. The
man's been written about enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic problem, Hotchner says, is that every professor has to
find a new way to write about Hemingway. ``What on earth can you
write that's new? They're all just scratching for more stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the man who supposedly hated publicity probably did
more than any other writer to cultivate his reputation. ``He was a
genius at creating and maintaining an image,'' says Matthew
Bruccoli, a Hemingway scholar and Jeffries professor of English at
the University of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bruccoli says, Hemingway's reputation has never
faltered. ``Almost with every other writer after his death, there
is an assessment or an evaluation. Hemingway remains the most
recognized American writer in the world. No writer has ever been
imitated to the extent that Hemingway has been imitated, both on
paper, in style and technique.''
</P>
<P>
   To some critics, Hemingway's enduring fame is more a result of
his adventurous lifestyle than his literary style. Actually, says
Hotchner, it's a combination of his personality, plus the fact that
his books are vivid records of times and places.
</P>
<P>
   ``That book about Paris in the '20s, `The Sun Also Rises,' it's
a portrait of the mores and attitudes of that period. `For Whom the
Bell Tolls' is the only vibrant history we have of the Spanish
Civil War. `A Farewell to Arms' gave an insight into the first
World War that nothing else did. He was avant-garde in his
personality and everything he did. That's what endured. So, like
Babe Ruth and a few other icons, Hemingway represents the
writer/adventurer that's disappeared. He's become a symbol of
something that's past.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruccoli did not realize how important a figure Hemingway was
until one night in New York when he had gotten off work as a copy
boy at the New York Herald Tribune. Waiting for his train in the
subway station, he noticed a crowd of people around a newsstand
that got magazines a day early.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was 1 o'clock in the morning, and they were lined up to
get an issue of Life magazine that had `A Moveable Feast' in it. Is
there any other 20th-century American writer for whom people would
line up to get the first possible copy of his work? You'd have to
go back to Dickens. That's when I realized that Hemingway had an
attraction for readers such as no other writer, with the possible
exception of Mark Twain. Yes, it's hero worship. But if people have
to worship heroes, why can't they worship writers instead of some
Hollywood pretty boy?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9700 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-KIDDER25-COX     04-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-KIDDER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kidder celebrates life of community
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northampton, Mass., a town of 30,000 souls, is old by American
standards (Jonathan Edwards preached there before the Revolutionary
War), home to prestigious Smith College and a sizable gay and
lesbian community, as safe and community-spirited as any place you
can find in America these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``As places go, it seemed so orderly,'' Tracy Kidder writes in
``HomeTown,'' his evocative new book about the people who live
there. ``And yet what an appalling abundance it contained. If all
of the town were transparent, if the roofs came off all the
buildings and the houses and the cars, and you were forced to look
down and see in one broad sweep everything that had happened here
and was happening . . . To apprehend it all at once _ who could
stand it?''
</P>
<P>
   In literary terms, that's exactly what Kidder does, although the
``appalling abundance'' and ``who could stand it?'' of that passage
may make you think this is one of those seamy
underbelly-of-the-American-dream books, which it emphatically is
not. Kidder is a gentle and respectful reporter and writer, and he
obviously loves the people of Northampton, even the misfits.
Especially the misfits.
</P>
<P>
   Kidder celebrates, without being sappy, communities, whether the
fifth-grade classroom in 1989's ``Among Schoolchildren'' (set in
nearby Holyoke) or those ``Hardy Boys'' building a computer in
``The Soul of a New Machine,'' which won a Pulitzer Prize for
nonfiction in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   His, and our, entree to Northampton is Tommy O'Connor, a
hometown boy who always wanted to be a policeman and became one: a
big, brusque, my-way-or-the-highway cop with a shaved head and an
intimidating presence. Tommy is both nicely settled (loving wife,
dad who's a character) and frequently conflicted between his code
of ethics and what he encounters as a Northampton cop.
</P>
<P>
   There's Frankie, an addict and goofy loser who does undercover
drug buys for the cops, and whom Tommy wants to rescue from street
life, but can't. And Rick, his childhood friend, also a cop, who's
accused of molesting his young daughter. Rather than turn
``HomeTown'' into an ugly incest whodunit, though, Kidder focuses
on the effect the devastating charge has on Tommy.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Tommy's orbit, but within Northampton's, live others,
like Alan Scheinman, an attorney who made piles of money in real
estate deals and then developed an obsessive-compulsive disorder so
severe it cut him off from humanity. He struggles to overcome his
mental problems, and when he begins dating a flighty stripper half
his age, what for most men would be unseemly feels like a sweet
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   And Laura Baumeister, a young woman on scholarship at Smith. A
victim of bad luck and bad choices, she's forced to apply for food
stamps to support her young son even as she's memorizing her T.S.
Eliot. The dowdy but hard-working mayor, the old-timer who reads
the news every morning on the AM radio station, the ER nurse, the
market owner, the guy who plays the bongos outside City Hall. ``To
apprehend it all at once _ who could stand it?''
</P>
<P>
   But to apprehend all is to understand all, with Kidder as a
guide. He burrows to the core of many of these people, telling us
their secrets, their fears, what they think when they lie awake at
3 a.m. This is not exactly new territory for Kidder, neither the
approach to presenting people nor the geography (all five of his
books are set in Massachusetts, where he lives in Williamsburg,
near Northampton). But it is exceedingly hard to do at the level he
does it, both the intensive reporting and the smoothly unobtrusive
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Kidder does not draw larger lessons in his books: They are rich
with specifics, and it is up to the reader to search for any
universality. Some people may want to do that, but it isn't
necessary. ``HomeTown'' is a book that lingers like the best
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HomeTown. By Tracy Kidder. Random House. $25.95. 344 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: To know all is to understand all.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer covers television for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
