<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-MASON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author ties threads of life together in memoir
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobbie Ann Mason spent her young adulthood trying to get away
from western Kentucky. Now, at 58, she is back in her home state,
re-creating in a memoir the rural setting and lifestyle that have
unwittingly shaped her writing from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   In the same unembellished, unpretentious prose that has
propelled her fiction _ from her acclaimed collection ``Shiloh and
Other Stories'' to the novels ``In Country'' and ``Feather Crowns''
_ Mason's ``Clear Springs: A Memoir'' (Random House, June) recounts
her odyssey as a writer, her escape from the family's 54-acre dairy
farm to the wider world and her eventual return to country life.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more of us are rummaging in the attic, trying to
retrieve our history,'' Mason writes in the introduction. ``We draw
genealogical charts and hang old quilts on the wall. We seem to
hope that if we can find out our family stories and trace our roots
and save the old cookie jars and coal scuttles, we just might
rescue ourselves and be made whole.''
</P>
<P>
   From her home in central Kentucky, where she lives with her
husband of 30 years, Roger Rawlings, and their seven cats and two
dogs, Mason talked about her first foray into nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What prompted you to write a memoir?
</P>
<P>
   A: I had spent a good part of the decade doing genealogical
research, studying family history and Kentucky history. And I had
written a historical novel, ``Feather Crowns'' (about the birth of
quintuplets to a Kentucky couple in the 1890s). So this memoir
clearly grew from some of that. It started in fact when I wrote
Chapter 1, which was an independent piece for The New Yorker. But
the inspiration for that was just standing at the pond (on the
family farm). It was a tone I felt. It radiated outward like the
ripples in the pond. I was standing there looking around at the
fields and the highway, and it felt like the whole world revolved
around that pond. It was a moment of self-awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How difficult was it to change gears from fiction to fact?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, it was a lot like writing fiction, except the
material I had to work with was very troublesome. I was forced to
make sense of facts, rather than just closing my eyes and making it
all up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How involved was your research?
</P>
<P>
   A: I did a lot of genealogical research, but that didn't really
amount to anything in the book. It did, though, get me into the
whole feeling of trying to tie the threads together. That was part
of it, feeling like everything should fit together. The other part
was talking to my mother, trying to learn everything I could about
her early life. Mainly it was a matter of making sense of what I
had before me. I had a lot of facts and trivia and memories and
little stories that I had been told, and I had to kind of
understand it all. I had to put it in a coherent form that I could
make something out of. This is the fiction writer talking: as if
you could make a literary structure out of your life.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have a sensational story to tell right off the bat, but
it was more about the texture of experience, the comprehension of
where am I right now, what did I come from? Those are the kinds of
questions we all ask.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was there any resistance from the family to your telling this
story?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. My mother read it, and all she said was, ``Well, I know
that. Tell me something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since you moved back to Kentucky, what has the adjustment
been like?
</P>
<P>
   A: Very difficult. I had moved back to be closer to the family
and it turned out I was still too far away. And my father died as
soon as I moved back. So I've spent the rest of the decade trying
to be with my mother. I haven't really developed a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you read any memoirs to prepare for this project? Were
there models that you followed?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I didn't re-read Nabokov's ``Speak, Memory,'' but it
was certainly whispering in my ear.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
