<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-MAYES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A further journey into beauty of Italy
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 15.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I walk from window to window, taking in the view.''
</P>
<P>
   When Frances Mayes wrote that final line about her new part-time
home near Cortona, Italy, in her best-selling book ``Under the
Tuscan Sun,'' she says, she was also writing the first line for her
second, even more substantial obeisance to Italian life, this time
dubbed ``Bella Tuscany: The Sweet Life in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes do take it all in: the tall, tall cypress trees (``tips
pointed like sable paintbrushes'') planted in remembrance of
Italy's World War I veterans; stars that shoot over the valley,
``stars that fell even before the Etruscans watched from this
hillside.'' Her nostrils and ears are on full alert as she travels
through small towns: ``As I walk by open windows, I'm transfixed by
the aroma of ragu and the cascades of concurrent voices.'' And the
food she tastes. The magnificent food. Cannellini simply dressed
with oil, sage, salt and a healthy dose of pepper. Pasta al limone.
Carp paired with herbs and bits of roast pork. Truffles and
mushrooms and sausages. And green Sicilian tangerines, ``exactly,''
as she so precisely points out, ``the color of a parrot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Tuscan Sun,'' published in 1996, was at its core a
captivating combination of PBS' ``This Old House,'' ``Victory
Garden'' and ``Cooking Secrets of the CIA.'' Book clubs ate it up.
</P>
<P>
   This follow-up memoir continues Mayes' sweet-life sojourns to
Bramasole, the old Tuscan house with the Etruscan stone wall that
she and her second husband, Ed, bought and began loving and
restoring (with a seemingly bottomless bank account) nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bella Tuscany'' echoes plenty from the first book _ part of a
stone wall falls and needs repairing; a lingering evening is spent
enjoying lasagna and Vino Nobile outdoors with lanterns perched
atop the stone wall; each summer day brings ``a heaping basket of
perfect, absolutely perfect, red, red tomatoes'' _ but it is also
where Mayes spends more pages stretching her soul.
</P>
<P>
   She has sent out her taproot to run deep into Italy. Well beyond
Tuscany, her visits take her to Sicily, partly to see and taste the
island's 2-foot-tall Easter-time chocolate eggs and marzipan
creations (Noah's Ark complete with animals, for example), and to
watery Venice, where beauty is so stunning that tourists ``step out
of the gondolas like new beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayes' quest for a spiritual connection to Italy is a sometimes
poignant melding of her new life with her second home in San
Francisco and her early roots in Fitzgerald, Ga. It's also a way
for her to deepen her sense about life (including a surprise
marriage in San Francisco), death (in both America and her newfound
country), and what pulses far within her own psyche (a
preoccupation with monogrammed linen, for example, or inner musings
about the curing comfort of sticking tired feet into the temperate,
healing Italian waters of Bango Vignoni).
</P>
<P>
   To some, her connections may seem strained. (In an early
chapter, while gazing at a church's stained glass, she wonders
whether fetuses perceive the same kind of filtered light.) But near
the book's end, her mind is so exquisitely in tune with Italy that
she can evoke three vivid metaphors for the land's dry autumn
grasses. And that makes for, undoubtedly, sweet reading.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bella Tuscany: The Sweet Life in Italy. By Frances Mayes.
Broadway Books. $25. 286 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A deeper, often more eloquent, ode to Italy from
the author of ``Under the Tuscan Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino is movie editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
and occasionally writes about food.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
