</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-NABOKOV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nabokov remains utterly resistant
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In October of 1958, a seemingly lurid novel about a 12-year-old
nymphet assumed the No. 1 position on The New York Times Bestseller
List. Its author, largely unknown to the reading public, was a
Russian expatriate named Vladimir Nabokov, then teaching literature
at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had ``Lolita'' risen to No. 1 than another Russian
novel, ``Dr. Zhivago,'' made its first appearance on the list. The
author was as little known as Nabokov, but within six weeks Boris
Pasternak's epic about the Russian Revolution had passed
``Lolita.'' By coincidence, both authors had begun their books 11
years earlier, Pasternak while imprisoned in the Soviet Union,
Nabokov while enjoying the freedom of American academic life and
the leisure of netting butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   On the centenary of his birth, Nabokov has never thrown off the
criticism that his novels and stories were those of a dilettante _
intricate, interesting in the way chess puzzles are interesting,
but things to be admired from an emotional distance. Critics
expected an emigre from the Soviet Union to write tracts about
tyranny in the form of fiction. Nabokov was utterly resistant. ``I
write for the sake of the pleasure, for the sake of the
difficulty,'' he told an interviewer. ``I have no social purpose,
no moral message. . . . I just like composing riddles with elegant
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Born into the aristocracy of czarist Russia, Nabokov claimed to
have been bilingual from birth and judged his English to be better
than his Russian. Whatever the fluency of his Russian, he was
renowned as a master of English prose (a matter of keen interest,
no doubt, to the prurient who flocked to the 1962 movie version of
``Lolita''). Someone asked him once which language he thought in.
He answered:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in any language. I think in images. I don't
believe that people think in languages. They don't move their lips
when they think. It is only a certain type of illiterate person who
moves his lips when he reads or ruminates.''
</P>
<P>
   His opinions were strong and his grudges permanent. Certain of
the great names of Literature were, he thought, overrated
(Faulkner) and others outright hacks (Dostoyevsky). James Joyce he
admired extravagantly. But when the public embraced ``Dr.
Zhivago''_ and just at the time his own novel was making him known
_ he felt only disgust and nausea (``dreary, conventional stuff'').
</P>
<P>
   It may have been sour grapes, writes Stacy Schiff in a biography
of Vera Nabokov, his wife of 52 years and intimate collaborator,
but no one could convince Nabokov otherwise. ``He restrained
himself as much as possible,'' Schiff writes, ``but still could not
resist snorting when told that the waiting list for `Zhivago' in
the Ithaca library was longer than that for `Lolita.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to be the only Russian novelist in existence,''
complained Edmund Wilson, a friend until Nabokov dismissed Wilson's
grasp of Russian grammar and style at great length in the pages of
The New York Review of Books.
</P>
<P>
   It is a minor irony that Nabokov's first published work was not
in a literary magazine but a journal called The Entomologist. All
his life he considered himself a professional lepidopterist, and he
contributed articles on butterflies to numerous scientific
journals.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he was as much an artist in English as Flaubert was in
French, and it is little wonder that his diamond-perfect prose is
enjoying renewed appreciation. Besides Schiff's elegantly written
biography of Vera Nabokov, the Everyman's Library has brought out a
new edition of ``Speak, Memory'' and Beacon Press later this year
will publish ``Nabokov's Butterflies.'' And last fall a new edition
of ``Lolita,'' which Nabokov ranked one of his two favorite works
(along with his translation of Pushkin's ``Eugene Onegin''), was
reissued.
</P>
<P>
   All of this comes almost 22 years after Nabokov died in
Montreux, Switzerland, where he and Vera _ to whom he dedicated
every one of his 27 books _ lived in a hotel, took Alpine walks and
lived apolitical lives. ``The larger the issue the less it
interests me,'' he said. ``Some of my best concerns are microscopic
patches of color.''
</P>
<P>
   He was hardly oblivious of the social and political issues of
the day. But he had only contempt for writers who believed that
artists have a moral duty to something other than their
imagination. The Russia he had known was one he was content to
leave forever: ``All the Russia I need is always with me _
literature, language and my own Russian childhood. . . . Anyway,
the grotesque shadow of a police state will not be dispelled in my
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   He would have thought it a fine irony: The Soviet Union he hated
lies dead and buried. Russia is gravely ill, as usual. But the art
of Vladimir Nabokov is alive and well, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
