<HEADER>
A9704 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-NONFICTION25-     04-22 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-NONFICTION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    List of new nonfiction books
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Jerk on One End: Reflections of a Mediocre Fisherman. By
Robert Hughes. Ballantine. $16.95. The erudite Hughes (``American
Visions'') casts his considerable intellectual gaze on the sport of
fishing. As he so accurately observes, fishing ``largely consists
of not catching fish. ...'' (May)
</P>
<P>
   High Exposure: An Enduring Passion for Everest and Unforgiving
Places. By David Breashears. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $26. Add IMAX
cameraman Breashears to the list of authors from the cast of
characters in Jon Krakauer's best-selling ``Into Thin Air.'' (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Other Side of Everest. By Matt Dickinson. Times Books. $23.
While Krakauer and the other protagonists of ``Into Thin Air'' were
struggling up Everest from Nepal, British adventure filmmaker
Dickinson was filming actor Brian Blessed's summit attempt on the
mountain's Tibetan side. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Miracle of Castel Di Sangro. By Joe McGinnis. Little, Brown.
$25. The author of ``Fatal Vision'' gets caught up in the
remarkable true story of an Italian town turned upside down during
an against-all-odds shot at a soccer championship. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Party Crasher. By Rich Tafel. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25.
Demonstrating that ``gay Republican'' is not an oxymoron, the
executive director of the Log Cabin Republicans presents his
political philosophy. (June)
</P>
<P>
   God, Dr. Buzzard and the Bolito Man. By Cornelia Walker Bailey
and Christena Bledsoe. Doubleday. $21.95. A cultural memoir
celebrates the dwindling Geechee culture on Georgia's Sapelo Island
and mourns the loss of the younger generation to the lure of a more
modern lifestyle. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Wake Up, I'm Fat. By Camryn Manheim. Broadway. $23. The Emmy
Award-winning actress reflects with humor on her struggles with
weight loss and eventual self-acceptance. (May)
</P>
<P>
   I'm a Stranger Here Myself. By Bill Bryson. Broadway. $25. After
living in England for 20 years, Bryson muses on returning to his
native United States with his customary mirth. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Hungry Ocean. By Linda Greenlaw. Hyperion. $22.95. Greenlaw,
a sea captain and a primary source for Sebastian Junger's ``The
Perfect Storm,'' recounts her adventures on a 30-day swordfishing
voyage. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Why We Buy: The Science of Shopping. Paco Underhill. Simon &AMP;
Schuster. $25. Research shows that 60 percent to 70 percent of what
we buy in the supermarket is entirely unplanned. Underhill's
anthropology of retail also tells us why the Internet will not
replace the shopping mall and how working women have altered the
way grocery stores are designed. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Old Neighborhood: What We've Lost in the Great Suburban
Migration, 1966-1999. By Ray Suarez. Free Press. $25. The host of
National Public Radio's ``Talk of the Nation'' tackles a subject
that will hit close to home for many Atlantans. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Encore Provence: New Adventures in the South of France. By Peter
Mayle. Knopf. $23. More Francophile frolics from the author of ``A
Year in Provence'' and ``Toujours Provence.'' (June)
</P>
<P>
   The Other Side and Back: A Psychic's Guide to Our World and
Beyond. By Sylvia Browne with Lindsay Harrison. Dutton. $23.95. The
author of the best-selling ``Adventure of a Psychic'' takes readers
on a tour of the spirit realm. (June)
</P>
<P>
   The Embrace: A True Vampire Story. By Aphrodite Jones. Pocket
Books. $23. Jones looks at black magic and Satanism among bored,
disenfranchised teenagers, including 16-year-old Rod Farrell, the
self-proclaimed leader of a vampire cult, who is on death row for
the bludgeoning death of a Florida couple. (June)
</P>
<P>
   On the Border: A Murder in the Family. By Marie Brenner. Crown.
$22. Culture clashes, a contract killing and the role of
journalists are all part of this tale of the death of 18-year-old
Texan Joey Fischer, the author's cousin. (June)
</P>
<P>
   In the Spirit: Conversations With the Spirit of Jerry Garcia. By
Wendy Weir. Harmony. $24. The sister of Garcia's Grateful Dead band
mate Bob Weir relates telepathically received pearls of wisdom from
the late guitarist's spirit. Uh huh. (June)
</P>
<P>
   The Velveteen Father: A Gay Man's Unexpected Journey to
Fatherhood. By Jesse Green. Villard. $23.95. Green finds himself in
a parental role after he becomes involved with a man who has
adopted a child. An affecting, amusing and often poignant look at
the joys and perils of gay parenting. (June)
</P>
<P>
   God's Funeral: The Decline of Faith in Western Civilization. By
A.N. Wilson. Norton. $29.59. The 19th century saw many
intellectuals, writers and artists abandon Christianity, partly as
a result of scientific discovery. But, as formidable critic Wilson
demonstrates, doubts about the existence of God had many sources.
(June)
</P>
<P>
   A Short History of Rudeness: Manners, Morals and Misbehavior in
Modern America. By Mark Caldwell. Picador USA. $22. Caldwell charts
the demise of manners, concluding that the phenomenon is not as
recent as we might think. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Homelands and Waterways: The American Journey of the Bond
Family, 1846-1926. By Adele Logan Alexander. Pantheon. $30. The
author traces the rise of her African-American family through three
generations. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Virus. By Luc Montagnier. Norton. $24.95. A professor at the
Pasteur Institute in Paris and the co-discoverer of the HIV virus
brings an insider's perspective to the history and science of AIDS.
(July)
</P>
<P>
   The Last Survivor: In Search of Martin Zaidenstadt. By Timothy
Ryback. Pantheon. $21. Ryback draws a portrait of the town and
townspeople of Dachau, Germany, and their daily struggle with a
troubling past. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Proper Mark Twain. By Leland Krauth. University of Georgia.
$29.95. Though Twain is often seen as irreverent and skeptical with
little use for propriety, Krauth explores a side of Twain that is
often ignored: a man who honored the conventions and moralities of
his time. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Disco Bloodbath. By James St. James. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
Party promoter and club kid extraordinaire Michael Alig was
convicted of murdering suspected drug dealer Angel Melendez in
1996, after a confession to fellow clubland denizen St. James.
(August)
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
