<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTAB-PAPERBACKS25-     04-22 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTAB-PAPERBACKS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    List of new paperbacks
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   The Last Full Measure. By Jeff Shaara. Ballantine. $14. Picks up
where the author's father, Michael Shaara (``The Killer Angels''
and ``Gods and Generals''), left off, after the Battle of
Gettysburg, as the Confederate Army begins its long, tortuous
retreat. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Quite a Year for Plums. By Bailey White. Random House $12.
Vignettes of small-town life from the popular author and NPR
commentator. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Damascus Gate. By Robert Stone. Scribner. $14. This finalist for
the National Book Award is a political thriller and an extended
philosophical inquiry, set in the ever-turbulent Holy Land. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Lost in Translation. By Nicole Mones. Delta. $12.95. A first
novel set in China, where interpreter Alice Mannegan searches for
love and the long-lost missing bones of Peking man. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Cavedweller. By Dorothy Allison. Penguin. $13.95. In this novel
by the best-selling author of ``Bastard Out of Carolina,'' Delia
Byrd packs up her old Datsun and her daughter Cissy and hits the
road for Cayro, Ga., to reclaim her life _ and the two daughters
she left behind. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Mammy. By Brendan O'Carroll. Plume. $10.95. Irish comedian
O'Carroll chronicles the comic misadventures of a large North
Dublin family in the 1960s. A film version, directed by and
starring Anjelica Huston, is scheduled for release this fall. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Dog Days. By Daniel Lyons. Plume. $12.95. In this comic debut
novel, a young software developer and his roommate dognap a
champion greyhound named Coco from the Boston mafioso. (May)
</P>
<P>
   On the Occasion of My Last Afternoon. By Kaye Gibbons. Avon.
$12.50. The fictional reminiscences of Emma Garnet Tate Lowell,
child of Virginia's Seven Oaks plantation, set mostly in the Civil
War South, by the popular North Carolina writer of ``Ellen Foster''
and ``A Virtuous Woman.'' (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Last Resort. By Alison Lurie. Holt. $13. A depressed writer
plans his ``accidental'' death in Key West while trying to avoid a
young female fan. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Marchlands. By Karla Kuban. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $12. Set on a
1,000-acre Wyoming sheep ranch, this debut novel tells of one
pivotal year in the life of 15-year-old Sophie Behr. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Jones's Diary. By Helen Fielding. Penguin. $12.95. The
surprise best seller about a 30-something who's on a quest for
self-improvement. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil. By John Berendt.
Vintage. $13. At long, long last, this blockbuster nonfiction novel
makes the transition from hardback to paperback. Berendt's
Savannah-set tale of murder, money and Southern eccentricities has
sold more than 2 million copies since it was published in 1994.
(July 6)
</P>
<P>
   Cities of the Plain. By Cormac McCarthy. Vintage. $13. The
setting for this epic quest, by the National Book Award-winning
author of ``All the Pretty Horses'' and ``The Crossing,'' is New
Mexico in 1952. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Park City. By Ann Beattie. Vintage. $14. The author's fifth
collection of short stories, most of which have been published
before. (July)
</P>
<P>
   My Heart Laid Bare. By Joyce Carol Oates. Plume. $13.95. A New
England con man teaches his children the tricks of his trade and
sends them out into the world. This novel traces the Licht family's
fortunes through the first three decades of the 20th century.
(July)
</P>
<P>
   The Mourner's Bench. By Susan Dodd. Morrow. Price TBA. Ten years
after the death of his wife, Pammy, 50-something academic Wim
travels to the North Carolina backwoods to die in her sister
Leandra's arms. (August)
</P>
<P>
   The Half-Life of Happiness. By John Casey. Vintage. $14. A
marriage breaks up against the backdrop of a fascinating
congressional election. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Kaaterskill Falls. By Allegra Goodman. Delta. $12.95. In a
remarkably graceful first novel _ a finalist for the National Book
Award _ Goodman intertwines the stories of three Orthodox Jewish
families who summer together in upstate New York. (August)
</P>
<P>
   My Sister From the Black Lagoon. By Laurie Fox. Scribner. $13.
This immensely readable ``semiautobiographical novel'' by Fox, a
California poet and literary agent, tells the story of a
dysfunctional family torn apart by one child's mental illness.
(August)
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   Angela's Ashes. By Frank McCourt. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $12. This
haunting, hilarious memoir of growing up in abject poverty in
Ireland spent more than two years on The New York Times Bestseller
List, won a Pulitzer Prize and helped spark the autobiographical
fire that still burns bright in publishing. First published in the
fall of 1996, it's finally making a paperback appearance. (May 25)
</P>
<P>
   Be Sweet. By Roy Blount. Harcourt Brace. $13. Josephine
Humphries described this as ``both literary and down-home, a
thinking man's thigh slapper.'' It's a hilarious and heartbreaking
memoir. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Philistines at the Hedgerow: Passion and Property in the
Hamptons. By Steven Gaines. Little, Brown. $14. A voyeuristic
account of secrets and scandals among the moneyed. (May)
</P>
<P>
   A Walk in the Woods. By Bill Bryson. Broadway Books. $13.
Restless writer Bryson tackles a new topic: the American
wilderness. Accompanied by an old college pal, Bryson starts out
one March morning in North Georgia, intending to walk the entire
2,100 miles to the end of the Appalachian Trail. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Pack of Two: The Intricate Bond Between People and Dogs. By
Caroline Knapp. Delta. $12.95. An affectionate exploration of the
relationship between a writer and an intelligent, pointy-eared
mutt. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Cold New World: Growing Up in a Harder Country. By William
Finnegan. Modern Library. $14.95. In her review for The New York
Review of Books, Joyce Carol Oates wrote that this is ``a sustained
and unflinching look into the lives of young Americans who live in
poverty of varying kinds.'' (June)
</P>
<P>
   Ship of Gold in the Deep Blue Sea. By Gary Kinder. Vintage. $14.
In 1857, the Central America, a sidewheel steamer, sank off the
Carolina coast, carrying more than 400 passengers and all her cargo
with her. She then sat for 132 years, 200 miles off-shore and
almost two miles below the ocean's surface _ until 1989. This is a
fascinating true story. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Meditations From a Moveable Chair. By Andre Dubus. Vintage. $12.
In 25 intensely personal essays, the late writer ponders the people
who meant the most to him, from his family to Norman Mailer. (June)
</P>
<P>
   A Monk Swimming. By Malachy McCourt. Hyperion. $14. The less
literary of the McCourt brothers' memoirs (his brother Frank wrote
the Pulitzer-winning ``Angela's Ashes''), this is a collection of
freewheeling anecdotes from a self-styled rascal. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Family Man. By Calvin Trillin. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $11.
Meditations on parenthood from a writer at The New Yorker. (June)
</P>
<P>
   A Beautiful Mind. By Sylvia Nasar. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $16. This
compassionate account of schizophrenic math genius John Forbes
Nash's life won this year's National Book Critics Circle Award for
biography. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Tale of a Sky-Blue Dress. By Thylias Moss. Avon. $13.50.
Acclaimed poet Moss remembers a childhood shattered by her
baby-sitter's cruelty. (July)
</P>
<P>
   The Murder of Helen Jewett. By Patricia Cline Cohen. Vintage.
$14. The true story of the 1836 murder of a young New York
prostitute and the ensuing trial of her lover that captivated the
nation. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Ecology of Fear. By Mike Davis. Vintage. $14. By relating the
story of Los Angeles, Davis draws larger lessons about the
relationship between urban growth and natural ecosystems. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Summer of Deliverance: A Memoir of Father and Son. By
Christopher Dickey. Touchstone. $14. The journalist's unflinching,
unrelenting recollections of his father, the author
(``Deliverance'') and poet James Dickey. (August)
</P>
<P>
   The Gifts of the Jews. By Thomas Cahill. Anchor Books. $14. The
author of the best-selling ``How the Irish Saved Civilization''
continues his ``Hinges of History'' series with this immensely
readable account of ancient Jewish culture. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
