<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9707 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-SPI &LR;      04-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY OUTLINES VISION FOR A 21ST-CENTURY PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Although hard to draw out on details, former Sen. Bill
Bradley on Thursday mapped broad outlines of a 21st-century
presidency he said would have greater vision, more authority
delegated and fewer daily sound bites than life under Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The former New Jersey senator skewered the Clinton
administration on its Yugoslavia bombing campaign, committed
himself to expanded trade with China, and said America's top
spending priority should be its neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley came to Seattle to raise $250,000 for his presidential
campaign, and to draw out differences between himself and Vice
President Al Gore, the leading Democratic presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time New York Knicks forward argued that the
administration had no game plan last month when NATO launched its
aerial war against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said from the beginning that objectives of this
operation were not clear. You do not have success without clear
objectives,'' Bradley said at a meeting with Seattle
Post-Intelligencer editors.
</P>
<P>
   If the goal of the United States and its allies was to avert
ethnic cleansing, Bradley said, ``It's already happened.'' If NATO
wanted to stop the conflict from spreading to unstable states
bordering Serbia and Kosovo, ``It has already spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Although offering support for U.S. troops in the field, Bradley
offered a biting analysis of proposed commitment of ground forces
to Kosovo. ``I've always believed you do not commit military force
into some place without figuring out how you get out of that
place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley traced what he called U.S. policy blunders over
Yugoslavia back to the Bush administration. He noted that U.S.
peacekeepers have been in Bosnia more than three years, not the
promised three to four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said in a (1996) speech in the Senate that we had just
created the next Berlin,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was campaigning in Washington state at the same time
President Clinton was traveling to a Washington, D.C.-area high
school for a televised talk with students in the wake of killings
at a Colorado high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what he (Clinton) does, he is comfortable with it, and
it is reassuring.... But it is not my way of doing things,''
Bradley said of Clinton's public empathizing.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the presidency offers America's premier bully
pulpit, but is not meant for non-stop preaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea, since Ronald Reagan, has been that the essence of
public policy is you dominate the daily news cycle,'' he said.
``(It seems that) the president has to be on the evening news each
night.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bradley's view, constant exposure gives the White House small
tactical victories but deprives it of the ability to convincingly
offer a larger vision and goals to the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franklin D. Roosevelt used to go on boat trips for three
weeks,'' he said. ``When he spoke, people wanted to hear what he
had to say. He spoke with an authority you do not have by competing
for airtime with TV anchormen.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of China, Bradley is an unabashed supporter of
China trade and strongly opposes any restrictions on commerce tied
to China's human rights policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more China opens up, the more it ultimately liberalizes,''
he said. ``You now see a higher level of political freedom in China
than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said China should be allowed to join the World Trade
Organization ``with no special favors'' and should be welcomed into
the international financial system.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century after he played with the Knicks' winning
teams, Bradley, 55, can still display an off-court elusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   He is eloquent on such objectives as helping children achieve
and bringing about racial reconciliation in America. But he gives
few details of of how he would achieve such goals.
</P>
<P>
   He would ``do something'' about teen pregnancies and ``deal
with'' the fact that one in every five children grows up in
poverty. He said he strongly feels the need for strong families
teaching children ``that there is a meaning to life deeper than the
material.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a vision, after which comes the policies and
then the actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has shown signs of catching on in polls. A recent
Reuters-Zogby survey showed him trailing Gore by 54 percent to 35
percent in New Hampshire, site of a crucial early primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the Clinton impeachment saga may have broken the
personal ``invasiveness'' of presidential campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fever is broken,'' he said. ``We can get back to talking
about things that are substantive and relevant.... The people have
a right to know whether I am a crook.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a right to know whether I am a sinner. We're
all sinners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
