<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SIDE-SHOELS23-     04-22 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SIDE-SHOELS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father's agony: African-American son slain for race
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Michael Shoels moved his family to this
middle-class suburban community because he wanted a better
environment for his family.
</P>
<P>
   But the violence and racial antagonism that afflict so many
African-American families in this country followed the Shoels even
to placid Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Shoels, 18, was the only black victim of the Columbine
High School tragedy, and witnesses say his killers targeted him
specifically because of the color of his skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid said to the other, `There's an n-word over here,'''
said Craig Scott, who huddled under a table in the school library
with Isaiah when the two killers entered the room. ``The other kid
came over and saw him. Isaiah tried to back up and he didn't say
anything, and they shot Isaiah.''
</P>
<P>
   After battling through a sleepless night Tuesday not knowing his
son's fate, Michael Shoels finally got official confirmation of his
son's death Wednesday. That racism was part of the reason his son
died made the tragedy that much harder to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been agonizing,'' Shoels told reporters. ``I'm
really hurting inside. No child, whether they are black, white,
red, yellow, should die for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shoels has two other children, both of whom attend
Columbine High and survived the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Isaiah Shoels was a bright, outgoing youth who
liked other people and did his best to fit in, even though at
Columbine, he was one of only about two dozen African-Americans in
an overwhelmingly white student body of 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Short in stature but powerfully built, Shoels had played
football at a previous school and wrestled when he transferred to
Columbine. He was in top condition, and once lifted twice his
weight in the work-out room, amazing some of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   When Larry Mingo, another African-American student, transferred
to Columbine last month, Shoels went out of his way to make him
feel at home, Mingo told the Rocky Mountain News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was new, and he did what no one else volunteered to do, he
showed me around,'' Mingo said.
</P>
<P>
   But being black in a mostly white school wasn't without its
tensions. Isaiah told his father that some students who dressed in
black trench coats and hung out together made him feel
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always used to tell me they would pick on him, and I would
always say, `Son, you will have to overcome that,''' he said. ``I
trained my children to get along with everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shoels now cringes when he recalls his reaction to his
son's complaints. But, perhaps like many African-American parents,
he may have felt torn, wanting his son to rise above the taunts,
but also not wanting to see him hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should've listened to my son more,'' he told NBC. ``I should
have gone to the authorities, but I felt he was strong enough to
overcome it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
