<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METHODIST-BAN:COLBERT     04-22 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODIST-BAN:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED METHODISTS IN CRISIS OVER SAME-SEX HOLY UNION SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By CHUCK COLBERT 
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Ceremonies that celebrate homosexual unions shall not be
conducted by our ministers and shall not be conducted in our
church. _ Social Principles of the United Methodists' Book of
Discipline.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The top policy-making body of the 8.5 million-member United
Methodist Church, the General Conference, passed this principle in
1996 specifically banning same-sex unions in the nation's second
largest Protestant denomination (the Southern Baptist Convention is
the largest). But some ministers and lay persons considered the
principle to be advisory and not binding.
 &HT;    Then on Aug. 8, 1998, the Methodists' Judicial Council, the
denomination's top governing body, ruled that this principle had
the force of church law, declaring the principle to be binding
rather than advisory on all United Methodist clergy. Pastors who
perform same-sex unions may be tried before church courts and
reprimanded and defrocked.
 &HT;    On Sept. 19, 1998, the Rev. Gregory Dell, 53, of the Broadway
United Methodist Church in Chicago, performed a ``service of holy
union'' for two gay men. Two weeks ago a 13-member jury of
Methodist ministers, by a 10-3 vote, found Dell guilty of
disobedience to Methodism's ``order and discipline'' for
officiating at the same-sex commitment ceremony. The jury suspended
Dell from his ordained ministerial duties, effective on July 5 _
unless Dell signs a written pledge to his bishop not to officiate
at another holy union ceremony as long as the ban is in place.
 &HT;    Dell is not willing to do that: ``I will never sign such a
pledge,'' Dell said. ``That would be a violation of what I believe
the spirit of God and all these people signify,'' he told The
Chicago Tribune.
 &HT;    The trial cost the church $100,000.
 &HT;    During his 30 years of pastoral service, Dell, who is a married
heterosexual and the father of a son, has conducted 33 services of
holy union for gay and lesbian couples. He estimates that 30
percent of his congregation is gay.
 &HT;    ``I took a vow to be in ministry with all persons _ not
regardless of their identity but in celebration of their
identity,'' Dell said in a press statement. ``I'm expected to
Baptize, teach, counsel, visit, bury and learn from all of the
persons to whom I've been appointed to pastor. I'm also charged to
bless and celebrate relationships of love between persons when
those relationships uphold standards of fairness and ministry. It
is a privilege _ not a duty _ to do so. To withhold such blessing
from some because of their identity and regardless of the quality
of their relationships would be the true violation of my
ordination,'' he said.
 &HT;    Dell's conviction of breaking church law comes in the wake of
another high-profile trial in March 1998 of the Rev. Jimmy Creech
of Omaha, Nebraska. Creech had performed a holy union ceremony for
a lesbian couple in September of 1997 _ before the Judicial
Council's decision to make the ban on same-sex ceremonies binding.
In his case, a church jury narrowly acquitted Creech, accused of
disobedience; but he was not reappointed to the Omaha church.
 &HT;    Still another act of Methodist ecclesiastical disobedience
occurred on Jan. 15, 1999 in Sacramento, Calif. In the Convention
Center there before 1,000 invited guests, a group of 84 United
Methodist ministers performed a service of union to bless a lesbian
couple. According to an Associated Press news account it was billed
the ```wedding' of the year for U.S. Protestantism.''
 &HT;    Two weeks ago the Methodist bishop of Northern California filed
a complaint against the ministers who participated in the holy
union ceremony and the presider, the Rev. Don Fado. The bishop's
action is the first step toward a possible church trial of the
clergy members, who if convicted, could be defrocked like Dell.
 &HT;    The United Methodist Church has a potential crisis on its hands.
There are approximately 350 United Methodist ministers who have
signed a public statement of their intention to perform same-sex
commitment ceremonies. If these ministers follow through on their
pledges and church officials choose to put them on trial, the
United Methodist Church will incur enormous costs and cause
serious, perhaps irreparable, divisions between its conservative
and liberal wings. Such developments may ripple throughout
Protestant Christianity where the battle over gays and religion so
far has been largely fought out over the ordination of openly gay
and lesbian clergy.
 &HT;    Fado described the problem in simpler terms: ``In our church,
unfortunately, I'm allowed to come into their (a gay or lesbian
couple) home and bless their house, bless their car, bless their
tractor and even bless their dog, but I am not allowed to bless
them,'' he said.
 &HT;    But for United Methodists _ and for that matter all Christians _
there is an even more serious theological crisis when rigid
adherence to church law takes precedence over the Gospel teachings
and compassion of Jesus Christ.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Chuck Colbert 
<TEXT>
