<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-HILLS:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAY TO REPAIR THE GREAT INJUSTICE TO THE GREAT SIOUX NATION
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Nineteen years ago the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in the case of
the Black Hills Claims suit brought by the united tribes of the
Great Sioux Nation that these lands, sacred to several Indian
tribes, were taken illegally.
 &HT;    At the time, Supreme Court Justice Harry Blackmun, who died last
month, wrote for the court, ``A more ripe and rank case of
dishonorable dealing will never, in all probability, be found in
our history.''
 &HT;    The tribes of the Great Sioux Nation were awarded a judgement of
$17.1 million as value of the 7.3 million acres taken by the 1877
Congressional Act, $3,484 for the right of way, $450,000 for
damages resulting from gold removed prior to the Act, plus 5
percent simple interest from the date of the theft totaling
$105,994,430.52. This brought the total monetary award to the
tribes to $123,447,914.52.
 &HT;    On July 18, 2000, 20 years will have passed since Congress
appropriated this monetary award. The tribes of the Great Sioux
Nation have refused to accept it and thus far, not one penny has
changed hands. The lawsuit over the Black Hills was first filed by
the Sioux Nation in 1921. After 59 years of litigation, the tribes
finally had their day in court. I realize justice often moves
slowly, but 59 years?
 &HT;    The monetary award has been held in trust by the Bureau of
Indian Affairs since 1980. It has been accumulating interest since
it was awarded and has grown to nearly $600 million. And still the
tribes of the Sioux Nation, the absolute poorest of the poor,
refuse to accept it.
 &HT;    In 1985 former Sen. Bill Bradley (D-N.J.), introduced the
Bradley Bill to address the claims of the Sioux Tribes. The
mainstream media immediately reported erroneously that the tribes
were attempting to regain all of the Black Hills. This was never
the case. In the Bradley Bill the tribes asked to be awarded 1.3
million acres of the total 7.3 million acres, to be used as a Great
Sioux Nation National Park. And they asked only for U.S. National
Forest lands. They did not ask for private, state, national parks
or municipality lands.
 &HT;    The U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the 7.3 million acres of land
taken in 1877 were taken illegally. By awarding money only, the
court was saying, ``All right, we stole your land and we admit it.
Therefore we will award you the money we believe it was worth in
1877, but forget the billions of dollars in timber and mineral
wealth since extracted from your stolen land.''
 &HT;    The tribes of the Great Sioux Nation didn't see it this way.
They simply refused to take the money and run. They asked that a
small portion of the land be returned to them since the land was
always regarded as sacred.
 &HT;    Whenever I read in newspapers that the Sioux are trying to get
back the Black Hills or whenever I hear it on the radio or see it
on a TV newscast I cringe. It is bad enough this erroneous
information is being used as propaganda against the tribes, but to
reinforce this error by repeating it as news has really damaged the
ability of the tribes to communicate their real desires. For
responsible news reporters to lend credence to a lie, I believe, is
almost unforgivable.
 &HT;    The tribes will soon meet to discuss the future of their claim
and of the monetary award they have thus far refused to accept. In
all probability, a new sponsor in the House and the Senate will be
found to introduce another bill seeking the return of a very small
portion of the Black Hills. The Bradley Bill never got off the
ground so the tribes are ready to try again.
 &HT;    When this happens, the tribes will make copies of the new Bill
available to all of the media, both national and local. News
directors should become familiar with the language in the Bill so
that unfounded rumors generated by opponents do not cloud the facts
and inflame the issue.
 &HT;    The summer of 1999 will be the season when many decisions will
be reached by the tribal leaders and members of the tribes who have
waited patiently for justice for more than 100 years.
 &HT;    Just remember that the tribes are not trying to remove or
displace any present occupants residing in the Black Hills. They
are only asking for a small portion of the land stolen from them
112 years ago, land which is unoccupied Forest Service land.
 &HT;    History judges great nations by how they treat their indigenous
people. How will history judge South Dakota and America?
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
