<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE:RACIAL-PROFILI     04-22 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE:RACIAL-PROFILING:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE IS AN ISSUE IN POLICING
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa, African American, is a freelance writer living
in Oakland, Calif., and a contributor to the forthcoming book
``Seductions of Justice: Lesbian Legal Theories and Practices.''
(1999) Routledge Press.)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Race is an issue in policing.'' This is no surprise to lots of
people of color. It is usually denied by white people, though,
especially police officials. But at a recent forum some police
chiefs publicly acknowledged that people of color have been
unfairly singled out in traffic stops.
 &HT;    The Police Executive Research Forum (PERF) early this month
organized a day of closed-door meetings in Washington, D.C. between
police executives and community leaders to address the topic
``Balancing Crime Strategies and Democratic Principles.''
 &HT;    Philadelphia Police Commissioner John Timoney, president of
PERF, declared: ``If we are to deal with it, we must stipulate that
race is an issue in policing.'' Timoney went on to say, ``There are
an awful lot of people in denial, but so be it. We must move
forward.''
 &HT;    The PERF meeting consisted of 35 police chiefs and activists.
Racial profiling is currently being investigated by the U.S.
Justice Department which is looking at the practices by the New
Jersey State Police as well as police agencies in Eastpointe,
Michigan and Orange County, Florida.
 &HT;    Many of the studies on racial profiling focus on traffic stops.
But recently New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman fired State Police
Superintendent Carl Williams for remarks he made that people of
color are responsible for most of the cocaine and marijuana
dealing. And African American men are eight times more likely to be
convicted than white men.
 &HT;    PERF participants discussed solutions to racial profiling
practices. One solution discussed was to adopt a program used in
San Diego, Calif.: to keep records of the race of the people
routinely stopped by police officers. This way actual statistical
tracking data will indicate whether racial profiling is being used
in traffic stops.
 &HT;    Of course racial profiling is not limited to traffic stops.
People of color are subject to racial profiling in every aspect of
criminal law. When a police report is released stating that a black
man is suspected of a crime, just about all black men are stopped
regardless of height, weight, hair texture or color, or whether
they fit the description at all.
 &HT;    Williams is not the only person to suggest that people of color
are more likely to engage in criminal activities. Many people think
that is the case even if they don't acknowledge it publically. And
therein lies the rub. People holding these beliefs become police
officers who are in the position to (consciously or unconsciously)
engage in racial profiling.
 &HT;    Although it is painful, I am glad when officials admit the
truth. But the discussion should go much further. There needs to be
a complete examination of all aspects of the so-called justice
system, beginning with the initial contacts police have with people
of color. It is only in this way that racism in criminal law can be
prevented.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Akilah Monifa 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
