<HEADER>
A9732 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIZABETH-PENA-NEWAME     04-22 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIZABETH-PENA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTRESS ELIZABETH PENA: ``REVOLUTIONS HAPPEN ONE PERSON AT TIME.''
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``e''
entertainment and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By CHRISTINE GRANADOS 
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Talk to any Latino actor and invariably the conversation turns
to typecasting. There isn't a working Hispanic actress in
Tinseltown, for instance, who hasn't been offered a role as a
prostitute, a maid, or a welfare mother.
 &HT;    Elizabeth Pena is no exception. The difference lies in how she
approaches such roles. ``We're showing more self-respect in the way
we handle roles and offers,'' Pena said in an interview with the
Los Angeles Times. ``I've seen actors fight to put flesh on roles,
refusing to play a cartoon character.''
 &HT;    For example, Pena, in her late 30s, beefed up her role as
Carmen, the Salvadoran maid in the 1986 comedy ``Down and Out in
Beverly Hills,'' with humor. She managed not to make a caricature
of the young Salvadoran illegal alien. She also gave an
unforgettable performance as Rosie, the abused wife of Richie
Valens' elder brother, in the 1987 crossover hit ``La Bamba.''
 &HT;    Since 1986, she has continued to win meatier roles. In 1990 she
played Jezebel, the alienated girlfriend of Tim Robbins in
``Jacob's Ladder.'' She appeared in ``The Waterdance,'' ``Across
the Moon,'' ``Dead Funny,'' and ``Vibes'' on the big screen.
 &HT;    Among her TV appearances, Pena portrayed Jinx on NBC's ``L.A.
Law'' and Mika Camarena in the Emmy-Award-winning NBC miniseries
``Drug Wars: The Camarena Story.''
 &HT;    In 1996 she landed the lead in the John Sayles film ``Lone
Star,'' a movie about the Texas border town of Frontera, where
Pena's character, Pilar Cruz, a high school history teacher,
rekindles an old flame with sheriff Sam Deeds, played by Chris
Cooper. Pena's and Cooper's characters embody the film's central
ideas about crossing borders, escaping the burden of history, and
challenging the past. Her portrayal of the strong, widowed, single
mother of two children won accolades and awards.
 &HT;    The Cuban American actress understood the Mexican American
character she would play in that movie and spent countless hours
listening to, recording and absorbing Mexican American and Mexican
culture for her role as Pilar.
 &HT;    ``I recorded people's voices to get the proper inflection. I
crossed the border to collect history,'' she told the Dallas
Morning News about her work in Eagle Pass, Texas, during the
filming of ``Lone Star.''
 &HT;    ``I would sit for hours looking at women, how they dressed. I
talked to people. I hung out. I shopped at stores to see what kind
of clothing was there and what food was eaten.'' That attention to
detail allows Pena to capture nuances of Hispanic roles that take
her far beyond stereotypes.
 &HT;    ``Honoring ourselves as human beings and becoming the best
actors is the way to succeed. Hollywood's notion of what roles we
can play will have to change,'' she told the Los Angeles Times last
year.
 &HT;    Today, Hispanic actresses are getting starring roles in
comedies, action adventure films, and dramas. Cameron Diaz starred
in ``There's Something About Mary,'' a mainstream box office hit
earning more than $130 million, while Jennifer Lopez played the
lead character in the action thriller ``Anaconda,'' which grossed
$16.1 million when it opened in 1997. Pena's starring role in the
popular independent film ``Lone Star'' won her the 1997 Independent
Spirit Award and the Bravo Award for Best Actress in a Film.
 &HT;    ``For a young actress, she has a rare maturity on screen,'' said
``Lone Star'' director Sayles about Pena. ``Perhaps it's a
confidence that comes from having been raised in the theater,'' he
added.
 &HT;    She comes by her talent for stage and screen naturally. Her
parents, Margarita and Mario Pena, founded and still run the
bilingual Latin American Theater Ensemble in New York. Her father
is an actor/writer/director and a three-time Fulbright Scholarship
recipient who travels the world helping start-up theater companies
similar to the one he and his wife founded.
 &HT;    Despite the fact that there were actors and directors in the
family, Pena still had a hard time convincing her mother that she
wanted to be an actress. When she was accepted to the New York High
School of Performing Arts, her mother said, ``If you become an
actress, you'll kill me.'' Pena was so determined that she replied,
according to People magazine, ``Well, you better start arranging
your funeral.''
 &HT;    The experience she gained watching her parents and performing on
stage at such a young age (she was 10 years old when she got her
first lead role) did not prepare her for the attitudes she would
face at the performing arts school. It wasn't until after she was
enrolled there that she felt the tinge of discrimination.
 &HT;    ``I was never, ever taught that there was a difference between a
black person, Jewish person, a Hispanic or Asian person. My parents
were not typical Cuban traditionalist parents, they were people in
the theater, people who traveled,'' she told People magazine in
1991.
 &HT;    She learned the difficult lesson of discrimination at the school
when ``all of a sudden I couldn't play Madge in `Picnic.' I'm going
`Why'?''' When she found out that it was because she wasn't from
Kansas, her first thought was, ``But that's why we're actors!''
 &HT;    Things have gotten better since then. In 1995 she played Kate
Haley, a marine mammal veterinarian, in ``Free Willy II,'' and more
recently she played a bomb squad expert in New Line Cinema's ``Rush
Hour,'' starring Jackie Chan and Chris Tucker. The movie shows
Hollywood executives that an action/buddy movie without an Anglo
costar can cross over and be a box office success.
 &HT;    Pena has completed production on independent feature films
``Strangeland'' and ``The Pass'' and the Showtime movie ``Aldrich
Ames: America Betrayed,'' with Timothy Hutton. In the Showtime
original feature, Pena plays Rosario Ames, the wife of the CIA
agent who sold secrets to the Soviets.
 &HT;    Pena has had some experience with politics and secrecy. Although
she was born in Elizabeth, N.J. (for which she is named), she spent
eight years in her parents' native Cuba before immigrating to New
York. Her father was imprisoned for writing antigovernment poetry.
After talking his way out of prison, he fled back to the United
States, followed shortly afterward by then nine-year-old Elizabeth,
her sister, Tania, and her mother.
 &HT;    The five-foot-three actress has lived in the United States since
1968. She currently resides in Seattle with her husband, Hans
Rolla, a carpenter- contractor, and their daughter, Fiona, born in
1997.
 &HT;    Latinas are gaining ground in Hollywood, but the progress has by
no means been steady enough to keep up with the dramatic shift in
the Hispanic population of the United States. Pena says she gets
tired of hearing Latinos whine about typecasting.
 &HT;    ``The question of typecasting and lack of access is a big
yawn,'' she says. ``Every time we project ourselves as a victim,
the subliminal `them' keeps us stuck in that place.''
 &HT;    She admits that improvements for Hispanic actors are slight, but
she is optimistic, insisting, ``Revolutions happen one person at
time.''
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
<TEXT>
