 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHURCH FINDS ITS CALLING IN CHILDREN. Christ United Methodist
Church in Gainesville, Fla., was surrounded in the 1960s by a
blue-collar white community. ``Today, it is mostly black and
poor,'' reports columnist Bill Maxwell. The average age of the
congregation _ white, except for two black members _ is 65,
compared to 30 for area residents. So, what should their role be,
church members wondered. The answer: Prime Time, the church's
unique after-school program. Offering music, art, academic tutoring
and field trips, it is free of charge to the neighborhood's
kindergarten and elementary school children _ ``who love
attending,'' adds Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-HELPING-KIDS:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   A WAY TO REPAIR THE GREAT INJUSTICE TO THE GREAT SIOUX NATION.
The U.S. Supreme Court ruled 19 years ago in the case of the Black
Hills Claims suit that these lands were taken from the Great Sioux
Nation illegally. The awarded money, held in trust since then, has
grown to nearly $600 million, but the impoverished Sioux refuse to
accept it, writes columnist Tim Giago. They simply ask that a small
portion of the land _ 1.3 million acres (unoccupied U.S. Forest
land) of the total 7.3 million _ be returned to them to be used as
a Great Sioux Nation National Park. ``History judges great nations
by how they treat their indigenous people. How will history judge
America?'' Giago wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-BLACK-HILLS:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED METHODISTS IN CRISIS OVER SAME-SEX HOLY UNION SERVICES.
Some 350 United Methodist ministers have pledged to continue to
perform same-sex commitment ceremonies _ defying church law banning
homosexual unions, reports columnist Chuck Colbert. If church
officials choose to put them on trial, the United Methodist Church
will incur enormous costs and cause serious, perhaps irreparable,
divisions between its conservative and liberal wings. ``For United
Methodists _ and for that matter all Christians,'' he writes,
``there is an even more serious theological crisis when rigid
adherence to church law takes precedence over the Gospel teachings
and compassion of Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-METHODIST-BAN:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   RACE IS AN ISSUE IN POLICING. At a recent Washington D.C.
meeting of police executives and community leaders to address the
topic ``Balancing Crime Strategies and Democratic Principles,''
organized by the Police Executive Research Forum, police officials
admitted that people of color have been unfairly singled out in
traffic stops. ``Although it was painful to hear,'' it was
commendable that officials told the truth, concedes columnist
Akilah Monifa. ``But a complete examination of racial profiling in
all aspects of the justice system is needed, beginning with the
initial contacts police have with people of color. Only this way
can racism in criminal law be prevented,'' she writes.
</P>
