<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9748 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TONY-AYALA-TEX     04-22 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TONY-AYALA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 16 YEARS IN PRISON, TONY AYALA EYES RING AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conversation, naturally enough, gravitates toward boxing.
Tony Ayala Jr., after all, is a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Or he was a boxer, before that horrible night 16 years ago in
Paterson, N.J., when, high on heroin and alcohol, he went to the
home of a female neighbor and raped her.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio native was a skilled boxer with powerful,
lightning-quick hands. Even as a 19-year-old, he was the top-ranked
junior middleweight of the day, with a sparkling 22-0 record and 19
knockouts. He looked powerful in such fights as the battering of
Curtis Ramsey on June 26, 1982, at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum in
Fort Worth. He was headed for a title bout, and stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing skills and fame couldn't help him in the courtroom,
though. Ayala, already on probation for beating a woman at a San
Antonio drive-in theater in 1980 and for breaking into a San
Antonio home, was sentenced to 35 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ayala wants to be a boxer again.
</P>
<P>
   He was released from a New Jersey prison on Tuesday after 16
years behind bars, out early because of good behavior. Even though
he is 36, and even though he hasn't fought as a professional since
he was 19, he is talking about a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, boxing was the first topic he discussed yesterday during a
news conference that Fort Worth promoter Lester Bedford put
together in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't, however, the most important thing on Ayala's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep talking about comebacks and we keep talking about
boxing, but the crime itself and the fact that out there, there is
still a victim, that's not forgotten,'' Ayala said. ``It will never
be forgotten by me. While others may judge me as a fighter and
judge my life depending on what I do in the ring, my view of it is
totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Ayala Jr. who went to prison was young, reckless and
out of control, tormented, he said, by demons caused by being
sexually abused as a youngster by a male friend of the family, and
exacerbated by drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a wreck,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, I victimized an
innocent person. That is never lost on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Ayala Jr. who was released on Tuesday, knows that he is
not the victim in this sorry saga. He sounds like a changed man.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are measuring the success of my life on
whether or not my comeback in boxing is a success,'' he said. ``The
fact is, I feel personally that I've already reached a level of
success in that I'm not out of control, that I've gained insights
about how I was, that I don't have the desire to go out and drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quote, unquote normal. I feel good and happy and fulfilled
without the need of chemicals in my system.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala began to change when he started visiting prison
psychologist Brian Raditz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the conclusion that I had to resolve the issues that
were tearing me apart, that had gotten me in prison,'' Ayala said.
``I had to find out why I had committed such a horrible crime, and
I had to find out whether or not I was just an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Raditz, who now is Ayala's manager and adviser, saw a man who
wanted to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 21 years I've treated thousands of patients, and never have
I seen anyone work as hard on himself as Tony did,'' Raditz said.
``He unmasked a lot of his fears, his hurts. He got a great handle
on himself and developed significant insights.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala became a peer counselor in the prison system. In the past
couple of years, he gave seminars to groups that were brought into
the jail, including students from nearby schools.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to continue that kind of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much interested in sharing my experiences with kids,
how I got to that point in my life, in the hopes that it could
change a few lives around,'' he said. ``Do I believe that I'm a
savior? No, I do not. Do I believe that every person who hears my
story will decide to settle down and make the right choices? No, I
do not. But if I can help one, there's one life that won't have to
experience the sadness and the shame and the remorse that I've had
to. In doing so, maybe something positive will have turned out of
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, Ayala is a boxer again.
</P>
<P>
   The man-child was in line to fight the best of his day, to take
on Roberto Duran, Thomas Hearns, Sugar Ray Leonard and Marvin
Hagler.
</P>
<P>
   The man wants to see if that talent is still there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personal thing,'' he said. ``I ruined my career. I have
been compared to some great, great fighters. I don't know if I
belong with that category, and this is an opportunity I will never
get again in life. The window of this opportunity is very small.
I'm 36 years old. If I do make a comeback, and if it is in any way,
shape or form successful, it has to be done quickly. Time is not on
my side.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Sr. will, as before, be his trainer, primarily at his San
Antonio gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will come into the gym, work six rounds at a time, work on
the little things that he missed while he was incarcerated, and
mostly mentally get focused on fighting again,'' Ayala Sr. said.
``Four to six weeks after he's been in the gym, he'll start
sparring again and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala Jr. is ready to take on ``every top dog out there.'' But
even if he's no longer good enough to climb into the ring with the
likes of Oscar de la Hoya, there's money to be made fighting
what-might-have-been bouts against Duran and Hearns.
</P>
<P>
   But, he insists, this really isn't about fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's much more than boxing,'' he said. ``I'm recognizing
things. The most important thing is my adjustment back into the
real world.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
