<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SENATE23-COX     04-22 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SENATE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vets' views shaped by Vietnam experience
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Then a young ROTC recruit enthusiastic about the
war in Vietnam, Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) recalls the moment in 1965
when Marines were deployed to provide defensive ``support'' for
U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Marines were frontline soldiers. Two years
after that, Cleland, then a young Army captain, helicoptered into
Vietnam to help break a siege of 5,000 Marines trapped by enemy
forces. A grenade explosion on that mission almost killed Cleland,
blowing off both legs and an arm.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cleland looks at the 2,200 Marines on a ship in the
Adriatic Sea off the Balkans, sent to provide ``support'' to
helicopter units in Albania, and is reminded of those first Marines
sent to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're slipping into a ground war,'' Cleland warns.
</P>
<P>
   As a Navy pilot stationed on an aircraft carrier off Vietnam,
Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) watched Soviet ships unload missiles and
transport them to Vietnamese planes. Then he would shake his head
in disgust. U.S. pilots were under orders from Washington not to
hit the Soviet ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the strategy that's being employed has some parallels
to Vietnam: graduated escalation, reliance on air power,
politicians choosing targets,'' says McCain, a Republican
presidential candidate. ``Those things have some haunting
reminiscences.''
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict in Kosovo wears on, both Cleland and McCain have
emerged as some of the toughest critics of the administration's
military policy in the Balkans. Cleland advocates an end to the air
war and a cease-fire. McCain wants a massive ground force to
overwhelm Serbia and win the war quickly.
</P>
<P>
   To varying degrees, both have shaped their views of the Kosovo
crisis based on their experiences in Vietnam 30 years ago. For the
Senate's three other wounded Vietnam veterans, the war's lessons
have also served as warning markers for U.S. involvement in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel (R-Neb.) echoes McCain in calling for a ground
war option in Kosovo. Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.) supports the air
strikes and believes the United States should at least prepare for
the possibility of a ground war. Sen. Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.), like
Cleland, firmly opposes ground troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For each of these men, Vietnam was a defining moment. They lived
a ground war. They saw the costs of war. And, through luck and
grit, they lived to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, shot down over Vietnam in 1967, survived 5 1/2 years of
torture at the hands of his captors, enduring repeated beatings,
isolation and inhuman living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Hagel, a highly decorated Army sergeant, was wounded twice,
first when a booby-trap mine ripped a hole in his chest and later
when his vehicle was incinerated, nearly burning him and his
brother alive.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, a recipient of the Congressional Medal of Honor and a
former Navy Seal, lost his leg to a grenade in an assault on a
Vietnamese camp in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, a Navy gunboat commander, was wounded three times in
ambushes in and around Vietnam's Mekong Delta.
</P>
<P>
   They differ about what to do in Kosovo. But they share a deep
distrust of politicians conducting wars and a powerful skepticism
about the ability of bombing alone to defeat an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   They also all subscribe to the military doctrine articulated by
another Vietnam veteran, Gen. Colin Powell, that wars are won with
a massive deployment of force in the shortest possible amount of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Hagel refers repeatedly to the so-called Powell doctrine in
explaining his demand for a ground war option in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't engage your military for whatever objective unless
you are prepared to do what it takes to win,'' says Hagel, a member
of the Foreign Relations Committee. ``We're not doing that in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cleland, American policy in Vietnam never had a clear
objective and never had an exit strategy. He finds neither in
American policy in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two things a Vietnam veteran fears the most in terms of
military engagement anywhere in the world is, number one, no win,
and, number two, no exit,'' Cleland says. ``When you combine both
of them, a Vietnam guy like me goes nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, who became an anti-Vietnam war protester when he returned
from combat duty, says he sees some of the same ``political
committee management'' of the war in Kosovo that he saw as a
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry says he wants a better defined mission that holds out the
threat of a ground war to bring maximum pressure on Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to send every clear message possible to
someone like Milosevic,'' says Kerry, a member of the Foreign
Relations Committee. ``Some of the messages, frankly, have been
less than clear.''
</P>
<P>
   After Vietnam, Kerrey said he made a promise to himself never to
allow personal politics to influence decisions about war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politicians were afraid to change their views because they
didn't want to lose credibility,'' he says. ``And while they were
satisfying that desire not to lose credibility, we were losing our
lives and our health.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, the ranking member of the Select Committee on
Intelligence, says the Kosovo conflict is less vital to U.S.
interests than threats from North Korea and Iraq. He is opposed to
U.S. ground troops in Kosovo and, like Cleland, says the
effectiveness of the air strikes may be coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vietnamese defeated us with truncheon tools,'' he says. If
the Serbs ``have the will to fight, they will survive as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
