<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9756 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-WNBA-LABOR-HNS &LR;      04-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The collective-bargaining agreement reached last week between the
Women's National Basketball Association and its players' union has
fallen apart, postponing Tuesday's draft and making the 1999 season
an ``all-or-nothing'' proposition, league president Val Ackerman
said Thursday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We had hoped to announce the signing of the WNBA's first
collective-bargaining agreement,'' she said. ``There is no deal,
and we have no choice but to postpone the draft indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Further talks between the two sides have not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   When Ackerman announced last week's accord, she called it a
landmark proposition for women's professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was established as the deadline for obtaining the
majority vote from the union's 122 players needed for ratification.
Although that was thought to have been a formality, talks broke
down Wednesday night when several new issues were brought to the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said the union is trying to renegotiate minimum
salaries for rookies, the sliding rookie pay scale, and player
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's National Basketball Players Association, she said,
also seeks to limit the number of public player appearances, a move
that could damage the community-friendly image the league has
fostered during its two years of existence.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the WNBPA were unavailable for comment Thursday.
But in a prepared statement released by union director Pam Wheeler,
blame for the 11th-hour breakdown was placed on the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, the league officials are trying to intimidate the women
into signing a document that contains terms far more onerous than
anything we shook hands on last week,'' Wheeler's statement said.
``Among other things, we are being asked to sign away virtually any
meaningful right a woman may have to market her own personal image,
and accept a wage freeze for the next four classes of rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, those veteran players who are joining our
bargaining unit from the ABL (the defunct American Basketball
League) are being asked to come in the league as `rookies,' hereby
giving up any right they may have to engage in individual salary
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share in the disappointment of the college players and
former ABL players who have been affected by this capricious action
by the WNBA, and hope to get things back on track as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 14, the league and the union, which has been in place
only since last fall, reached agreement in principle on a four-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   It included increases in the minimum salary from $15,000 to
$30,000 for veterans and $25,000 for rookies. Those figures would
rise to $40,000 and $30,000, respectively, by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the benefits package were a year-round health and
dental plan, a 401(k) retirement plan, maternity leave and life
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the groundwork was laid for four expansion teams to begin
competition in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Every day the ratification and signing process is delayed,
Ackerman said, increases the amount of work that must be completed
in a given time frame to facilitate the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision, our hope, always was that we would have a deal
before the season,'' Ackerman said. ``We accept that this is a
funny year with everything that's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nonetheless, and in the course of bargaining, we had tried
very hard to make the point (to the union) that we didn't have a
lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the same sort of luxury that a league such as
the NBA has to postpone things. For us, it's really all or nothing.
There won't be a delay to the start of our season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It either happens, or it doesn't happen. We're not in a
position where we can start three weeks late. That won't happen. We
either start on time or it won't start at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said when, or if, the draft takes place is contingent
upon reaching a new accord.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 season is scheduled to begin June 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
