r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SOCCOL-COLUMN-LAD     04-22 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T WIN REVOLUTION WITH SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans in New England last Saturday chanted, ``No more
shootouts,'' as the Revolution lost to Columbus. It was its third
shootout loss in four games.
</P>
<P>
   The first four Galaxy games also ended in shootouts. And all
four of San Jose's wins this season have come in shootouts.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the shootout becomes an issue every year. Fifteen MLS
games have been decided in such fashion this season _ and something
has to give, if you listen to the coaches and players.
</P>
<P>
   The shootout, adopted by the now defunct North American Soccer
League in the 1970s, is a corny method of deciding draws. There's
nothing traditional about it. And it's no big deal during the
regular season for a league that takes excitement where it can be
found.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the shootout isn't hurting teams in the standings.
Teams get a victory, but the win is worth only a point.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose and Chicago are both 4-1. But all of Chicago's wins
have come in regulation while all of San Jose's have come under the
shootout clock. The Fire leads the Clash 12-4 in points, which is
the only thing that really matters.
</P>
<P>
   Fans might boo the shootout once in a while, but I've never seen
a fan get up and leave before the shootout decided a game. Most of
the time it's a delight for fans who have been bored by a scoreless
draw.
</P>
<P>
   Still, under pressure from coaches and management, MLS
commissioner Doug Logan was asked this week whether the shootout
will remain in the league's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the day coming where our competition committee goes a
different way in determining the outcome of the games,'' said
Logan. ``I maintain that (the shootout) is exciting for our fans
and discourages the number of draws. If we did not have the
shootout, the subject matter today would be, `Why are we having so
many draws?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Most casual fans and general sports fans favor games in which
there is an outcome. That's a fact of life. There is a balance to
weigh, but this is a wasted exercise unless MLS becomes a good
business. We have to do things that would not be detrimental to us
as a business.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with the shootout system is during the
playoffs, when the points system is thrown out the window. Only
wins (shootouts included) count in the three-game playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   This means less-talented visiting teams play more defensive
soccer, hoping to steal a victory via shootout on the road. It's
unfair to decide a playoff game in this manner. If anything, MLS
has two alternatives. It could learn from hockey and continue to
play in a sudden-death format until a team scores. There is nothing
as exciting as sudden-death playoff hockey.
</P>
<P>
   It could also use the aggregate system used by many other soccer
leagues. Under this system, draws count and the team with the best
record and goal differential at the end of a series advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion to improve the soccer is that we need to learn from
Europe,'' said New England player-coach Walter Zenga. ``If I want
to learn about basketball, I go to the United States. If I want to
learn about soccer, I go to Italy or Germany or Europe or Argentina
or Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Wild and wacky: It has been a crazy week around the MLS.
Kansas City coach Ron Newman, the winningest coach in U.S. soccer
history, resigned after the Wizards' 0-4 start. He was under heavy
criticism from goalkeeper Tony Meola.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian Carlos Valderrama, one of the best playmakers in the
league, was benched by Miami coach Ivo Wortman and is rumored to be
on the trading block.
</P>
<P>
   And in Chicago, the reigning MLS champions played their season
opener on a spray-painted Soldier Field against Dallas. The field
was in such horrible shape, Logan almost tripped during the pregame
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed. I almost sprained my ankle during the ring
ceremony,'' Logan said. ``. . . I was very disturbed. (Soldier
Field is) not holding up (its) end of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To call that a soccer field, that's pretty embarrassing,''
Dallas coach Dave Dir told the Chicago Tribune. ``It's the worst
thing I've ever played on _ worse than any high school field, worse
than any club field. It's an embarrassment to Chicago that the
champions of the league have to play on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
