<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BIAS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT ALLEGES COCA-COLA DISCRIMINATED AGAINST BLACK EMPLOYEES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of black employees filed a class-action
lawsuit Thursday accusing the Coca-Cola Co. of discriminating
against African-Americans in pay, promotions and performance
evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in U.S. District Court in Atlanta by four
past and current employees ranging from a security guard to a
former executive who earned nearly $100,000 a year. But the
complaint said the four brought the action on behalf of as many as
1,500 black employees who work or have had salaried positions at
Coca-Cola throughout the United States since April 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs contend that Coca-Cola pays its average black
employee nearly $27,000 a year less than its average white
employee. For two years, the suit says, at least one of the
plaintiffs, Kimberly Gray Orton, a supervisor in Atlanta, was paid
less than white employees who worked for her.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint contends that Coca-Cola limits black workers'
chances for promotion and that those who are promoted are shunted
into management positions in areas like human resources, public
relations and community affairs that have little power and offer
little chance of further advancement.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also contends that though Coca-Cola goes to great
lengths to market its products to black consumers _ about 25
percent of its brands are bought by African-Americans _ the company
``has failed to place the same importance on its African-American
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baskin, a spokesman for Coca-Cola, said the company's
lawyers had not seen the suit and therefore he could not comment on
any details about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not yet seen the lawsuit,'' Baskin said in a telephone
interview. ``But based on what we have heard, we believe it without
merit. The Coca-Cola Company does not tolerate discrimination, and
if discrimination is found we take action to stop it and prevent it
from occurring.''
</P>
<P>
   A crucial accusation in the suit is that black employees
consistently received poor evaluations of their work from their
supervisors. According to figures compiled by the plaintiffs'
lawyers on white-collar employees at Coca-Cola's corporate
headquarters, 55.8 percent of whites received one of the top three
of six performance grades last year while 46.1 percent of blacks
got such evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no defense for this,'' said Cyrus Mehri, a lawyer who
is representing the plaintiffs. ``There is no reason why
African-Americans should be consistently getting poor performance
evaluations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
