<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-WALKOUT-ART-N     04-22 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-WALKOUT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S TEACHERS WALK OUT IN A PAY PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle's 4,000 teachers and classroom assistants shut
down the school system Thursday by staying away from work in a
one-day protest against what they called inadequate pay increases
during the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and staff in six smaller Washington districts also
walked out, joining those in more than 30 other districts around
the state, who, in a series of rolling single-day protests over the
last week, have left the job to lobby state legislators for sizable
raises.
</P>
<P>
   In four of the last six years, Washington's public-school
teachers, whose pay is financed by the state budget, have received
no raises from the Legislature. Only in 1995-96 and 1997-98 did
they get increases, of 4 percent and 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the same six-year period, the cost of living in the state has
risen 15 percent, and the average price of a Seattle home has grown
to $198,000 from $151,000. Many Seattle teachers say they can no
longer afford to live here.
</P>
<P>
   Washington teachers, whose average pay ranges from about $25,000
a year, for beginners, to some $50,000, for those with at least 15
years' experience and a doctorate, are demanding across-the-board
raises of 15 percent over the next two years, more than is
envisioned under even the most generous plan contemplated in
Olympia, at either the State Capitol or the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Some 1,000 teachers, parents and students rallied Thursday
morning at the construction site of the Safeco baseball stadium,
the Seattle Mariners' future home, which is being financed in part
with state dollars. State officials were able to win approval of
that state financing with talk of ``creative funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers carried signs that said, ``If you can `creatively' fund
a stadium, you can `creatively' fund educators,'' and, ``They took
the cream from my coffee and left me with 2 percent,'' a reference
to the offer made to the teachers by the governor, Gary Locke, a
Democrat. One woman held a sign saying, ``I don't have a husband to
support my teaching habit.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisa Warden, 16, attended the rally in support of her mother,
a teacher. ``They're a national resource,'' she said of educators.
``It's disrespectful not only to teachers but to students when they
treat people like this.''
</P>
<P>
   After the rally, the teachers and their supporters rode about 50
buses south to Olympia, where legislators, their session scheduled
to end on Sunday, were engaged in negotiations on the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Democratic-controlled Senate passed the most
generous pay offer to emerge from the capital. It would provide a
15 percent raise over two years to only newer teachers, limiting
mid-level teachers to 8 percent and the most experienced to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, whose membership is divided evenly between the two
parties, Democrats were working Thursday on a two-year raise of
about 6 percent, plus $12 million set aside for additional pay for
beginning teachers, but the Republicans were talking about a less
expensive package.
</P>
<P>
   Locke's plan calls for a two-year increase of about 4 percent.
The governor said Thursday that the teachers' demands would cost
the state hundreds of millions of dollars that it could not afford
and, because of a spending cap that limits annual increases in the
budget, would result in large cuts for nursing homes, mental health
programs and the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting on the Capitol grounds, one new teacher showed
House leaders his letter of resignation as well as his pay stubs
($1,500 a month take-home) and monthly student loan bills ($600).
The 30-year-old teacher, Joshua Proudfoot, who has been working for
two years at the New Options Middle School in Seattle, said he was
accepting a teaching job in Eugene, Ore., where he will get a 15
percent raise and be able to buy a house that costs about half of
what one in Seattle would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Devin Gruver, a special-education teacher in the Highline School
District south of Seattle, told legislators that he had taught for
26 years, in a specialty with a serious staffing shortage. ``The
abuse,'' he said, ``has been such that financially, the only wise
thing to do is retire'' and move to Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford to have a computer, the Internet or a newspaper
anymore,'' Gruver said later. ``Every year I have to figure out
what would be a luxury, what is the next luxury I can give up.
There's nothing left to pare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
