<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-7     04-22 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS FIND ROOM TO HARBOR REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISEC, Macedonia _ Fetie Rreci, at age 50, was hoping to be
adopted by a nice family, but she knew she was not at her best. Her
clothes were crusted with mud. She was not smelling so good. She
stood in a public building with her husband, son and daughter. They
had also been sleeping on the ground. They also stank.
</P>
<P>
   Then Harum Mustafa, a farmer from the tiny village of Lisec, saw
them and smiled. The unwashed were exactly what he was looking for.
``We're willing to take in some refugees,'' he said to them in
familiar Albanian. ``If you want, you can come with me.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last three weeks, the four Rrecis have been living with
the six Mustafas. It is a story repeating itself a thousand times
over in this Balkan nation. Some 130,000 ethnic Albanians have
poured into Macedonia from Kosovo during this last month. While
50,000 of them are temporarily housed in refugee camps, most of the
rest have found shelter in private homes.
</P>
<P>
   In cities like Skopje or Tetovo, it is common to find some
connection between the helpers and the helped: a cousin is given
sanctuary and he brings in some friends who also bring in some
cousins. In the villages, though, most often it is strangers in a
strange house.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are our brothers and sisters,'' said Shehadije
Mustafa, 49, Harum's wife. ``If we don't help them, who will? When
you see your own kind being beaten and tortured, you must do
something. We do not have much, but what we have we will share.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisec is a farming village in the mountains just outside of
Tetovo. It has 120 homes, dozens of bean patches, a single mud
road. Dwellings have roofs of tin and walls of stone and cement.
Animal sheds are made of remnant lumber and thin branches.
</P>
<P>
   Every family in Lisec is of Albanian stock, and every one has
taken in refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make a big problem for you, I'm afraid,'' Fetie Rreci
said when she met Shehadije Mustafa.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is mine is yours,'' Mrs. Mustafa replied.
</P>
<P>
   For most refugees, a room in someone's home _ no matter how
cramped _ is preferable to the tents in the camps. The Rrecis spent
six days in the camp at Blace near the border. They considered it
hell and abandoned it when they could.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees are arriving faster than the tents are going up. On
Thursday, 1,500 to 2,000 more people came in by train, and U.N.
relief officials have declared that the nation is simply
overwhelmed. They asked those countries that had agreed to accept
refugees, including the United States, to step up efforts to
transport the dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees are a varied lot; some of them young and healthy,
wearing Nike sneakers and nylon sweat pants. Others are old,
walking bent over like rows of apostrophes.
</P>
<P>
   They do have one thing in common, the story of being uprooted.
They talk of nasty soldiers with guns, days of hiding and awful
questions: Where have they taken those women? Why are they
separating out the young men? How will I ever find my loved ones?
</P>
<P>
   The Rrecis are from the town of Lausa. When the Serbian
paramilitary chased them from their home, they made their way to
Pristina, Kosovo's capital. There, they were told they had to leave
the country. ``Give our regards to President Clinton,'' they recall
one soldier taunting them. They were herded toward a train like
cattle, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded you of those movies about the Jews and Hitler,''
Mrs. Rreci said.
</P>
<P>
   As they neared the train, they found themselves in one of two
thick columns of people. A vehicle with tank treads came speeding
between these rows. A soldier pushed a little girl in front of the
huge rig, the Rrecis said. A thousand people screamed.
</P>
<P>
   The girl was crushed, Ms. Rreci said. She saw the girl's mother
collapse to the ground in sorrow. The father ran toward the body,
and, for a time, tried to press the head back together. ``Leave the
mess for the dogs,'' soldiers said, pulling him away.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Rreci told the story, she began to weep. Mrs. Mustafa
took her hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is fragile, isn't it?'' Mrs. Mustafa said.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that Mrs. Rreci show some photos. As the family
hid in the woods near Lausa, they once came back to see what had
happened to their house. They took pictures that showed charred
cement, a mangled tricycle, an oven with its door torn off. Beside
the front door, the words, ``This is Serbia,'' were spray-painted
on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the only pictures we have now,'' Mrs. Rreci said.
``Our family photographs are gone. Burned. Destroyed. Our family's
past is destroyed, too.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After three weeks in Lisec, the Rrecis are practically
old-timers. Across the lumpy mud road, a family of 16 had just
arrived the night before. They slept in a single room _ and were
glad to do it. They had earlier been at that horrible camp in
Blace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blace can never be forgiven,'' said Qamil Murati, 46, an
electrician from the village of Shakovice.
</P>
<P>
   At Blace, the family lived in the mud. As it rained, Salerie
Murati, 26, lay on her back and tried to remain still as she slept.
Her 5-week-old son rested on her chest, swathed in damp blankets.
She was afraid she would roll over and the baby would slide into
the muck.
</P>
<P>
   The Muratis, like the Rrecis, had a personal tale of
unfathomable evil. They had seen it at Blace. The Macedonian police
are no better than the Serbs, they said. They had seen them
separate an infant from its mother, leaving the women in
inconsolable grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray to God that he sees all this happening and makes
careful notice,'' said Mrs. Murati, who was nursing her baby.
Another of her children was holding a stuffed animal, a little
yellow caterpillar with yarn strands serving as the feelers. A wood
stove provided heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that God rewards the people of this village who have
shown us a kindness that is beyond words. And I hope God punishes
the Serbs and Macedonians for the bad things they do. Such hate
they have. They hate us and it makes us hate them.''
</P>
<P>
   This is surely so.
</P>
<P>
   Far along the mud road, where Lisec begins to run out of bean
patches and potato fields, is the village's small school house.
Refugee children have come to study, and their classmates have
given them spare notebooks and pencils. Teachers try to encourage
the transplanted students who, they say, are prone to outbursts of
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Gezim Feka, a 10-year-old from the village of Vushtria, is a
favorite among the newcomers. He has written a poem about hate that
his teachers are quite proud of. It speaks of Slobodan Milosevic,
the Serb who is Yugoslavia's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will cut Slobodan into pieces, into pieces, into pieces,''
the poem reads. ``Then we will bury him in separate holes, separate
holes, separate holes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
