<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISING PROFITS SEND MARKETS SOARING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ IBM's strong profit report helped propel the stock
market to another big advance Thursday as large growth stocks,
which had fallen out of favor as perhaps too expensive just a
couple of weeks ago, continued to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, which brought another record for the Dow Jones
industrial average, came despite a slump in the bond market that
raised interest rates along a broad front.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was the star performer after reporting a 42 percent rise in
first-quarter earnings on Wednesday, climbing 22|, to 194{. It
accounted for 105 of the 145.76-point gain in the Dow, which
finished up 1.4 percent, to 10,727.18. Even lacking IBM, the Nasdaq
composite index did twice as well, advancing 72.53 points, or 2.91
percent, to 2,561.61. The index is now just 37 points shy of its
all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 22.7 points, or 1.7
percent, to 1,358.82 also a record.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pointed to several more reports of surprisingly good
earnings besides IBM's as the main impetus for the market's third
consecutive advance after Monday's swoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a continuation of some really impressive earnings,
definitely better than the Street was expecting,'' said Warren
Epstein, head trader at Richard Rosenblatt &AMP; Co. ``There's a
tremendous amount of buying momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined volume on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq was
more than 2 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   According to IBES, which tracks analysts' profit estimates, the
quarter ended in March appears to have been the best for positive
earnings surprises in 11 years. Many analysts cut projections last
autumn on spreading economic turmoil overseas.
</P>
<P>
   And more companies reported Thursday, bringing the season's
total to about 50 percent of the S&AMP;P 500. Among them were Lucent,
up 2|, to 61}; American Express, up 2 5/16, to 137 3/16; Chevron,
up 2[, to 98{; Nokia, up 2 9/16, to 81 3/16, and Quaker Oats, up
4\, to 67 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, slumped after disclosing results. Procter &AMP;
Gamble declined 4 13/16, to 94[; Black &AMP; Decker dropped 4 7/16, to
54 1/16, and McDonald's fell 11/16, to 44 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, which rose 2 13/16, to 120 13/16, announced a
2-for-1 stock split, its seventh since the brokerage firm went
public in 1987. The previous split, which was 3-for-1, was in
December. Sara Lee, which warned analysts to expect lower profit
growth and was downgraded by Merrill Lynch, fell 1[, to 24. After
the market closed, the company said it was bidding $10.50 a share
for Chock Full o' Nuts, which had risen ], to 6]. Chock Full
responded by calling the offer ``inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer and other technology issues, benefiting from IBM
fallout, turned in another strong performance, with Amazon.com
climbing 10 13/16, to 190 1/16, America Online up 5 15/16, to 148
11/16, Microsoft rising 2 15/16, to 84 15/16, and Yahoo up 9[, to
184.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Ghriskey, a value-oriented portfolio manager at the
Dreyfus Corp., expressed hope that the market's sudden mid-April
lurch toward cyclical and smaller stocks would resume, but he was
unwilling to predict this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is so dominated by megacap growth stocks, and I
don't think they'll be abandoned so quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 928 million shares changed hands on the New York
Stock Exchange as 1,705 stocks advanced and 1,307 declined and new
52-week highs outnumbered new lows by 65 to 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
