<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE-ART-1ST     04-22 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T BIDS TO BECOME BIGGEST CABLE PROVIDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 5th, 7th, 8th and 10th grafs, and to attach 9
new grafs to end of original text, beginning: Some major
independent ...) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT and SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bidding to become the largest cable television provider in the
United States, AT&AMP;T Corp. made an unsolicited offer Thursday to
acquire MediaOne Group Inc. for about $58 billion in cash and
stock.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is trying to break up a deal announced last month in which
MediaOne agreed to be acquired by Comcast Corp. for $53 billion in
stock. AT&AMP;T has already won the support of Amos Hostetter, whose
family is MediaOne's biggest shareholder with about 13 percent of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T, already the nation's biggest long-distance telephone
carrier, succeeds in its bid for MediaOne, it will have grown from
no presence in the cable television market to the nation's largest
cable company in less than a year. Last June, AT&AMP;T agreed to
acquire Tele-Communications Inc., the No. 2 cable company, for
$31.8 billion; that deal was completed last month.
</P>
<P>
   With TCI, AT&AMP;T now offers cable service in 10 of the 20 biggest
U.S. markets. If AT&AMP;T acquires MediaOne, almost three-quarters of
the combined company's subscribers will be in 15 of the top 20
markets.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's offer, which came after the market closed Thursday,
represented a 17 percent premium over the current value of
Comcast's offer and a 26 percent premium to MediaOne's current
trading price. On Thursday, AT&AMP;T closed at $56.75 a share, down 25
cents; Comcast closed at $66.1875, up $2.5625, and MediaOne closed
at $69.50, up $2.5625. In after-hours trading, Mediaone traded as
high as $82.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, a combined AT&AMP;T-MediaOne would serve about 16 million
cable television subscribers and would be in markets covering about
27 percent of the nation's roughly 100 million homes. The company
would also be poised to serve millions of additional homes through
affiliates and partners. That raised concerns among some consumer
advocates Thursday that such a behemoth could stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the Washington office of
Consumers Union, a consumer advocacy group, said his organization
would challenge the deal as a violation of both antitrust laws and
rules that are meant to limit concentration in the cable industry _
rules that have been stayed temporarily by the Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amasses massive power in the hands of one cable
company,'' Kimmelman said. ``This would create an enormous obstacle
to the development of competition in the cable industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Since C. Michael Armstrong, a former IBM executive, took over as
AT&AMP;T's chairman in 1997, he has been trying to build a
comprehensive portfolio of voice, video and Internet communications
services that AT&AMP;T can offer to consumers in a single bundle. Just
as important, he has been looking for ways for AT&AMP;T to reestablish
the direct links into the homes of U.S. consumers that the company
lost when it was forced to shed its local telephone business in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   To help pay for its offer, AT&AMP;T plans to have $30 billion in
financing in place by the end of the month _ the largest short-term
financing deal yet, an AT&AMP;T spokeswoman said. Goldman Sachs Credit
Partners LP and Chase Manhattan Corp. have each committed $5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   With its move into the cable television industry, which also
includes a troubled partnership with Time Warner Inc., AT&AMP;T is
getting set for a showdown with the Baby Bell local phone giants
for the ears and eyeballs of U.S. consumers. At least one of the
Bells could win regulatory approval to compete in AT&AMP;T's core
long-distance market this year, and AT&AMP;T plans to counter that by
offering consumers integrated packages of local, long-distance,
wireless, Internet and television service.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T acquires MediaOne, the remaining independent cable
companies, like Cox Communications, would be faced with a titan in
their midst, even though cable companies do not generally compete
directly against one another.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne did not return a phone call from a reporter Thursday
night. Comcast declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T believes it can have a dominant role in the consumer
market,'' said Brian Adamik, an analyst for Yankee Group, a
technology consulting firm in Boston. ``We are moving to a duopoly
in the consumer market between AT&AMP;T and the Baby Bells.''
</P>
<P>
   Salvatore Muoio, who runs an investment firm that bears his
name, called the bid ``a terrific move for AT&AMP;T because by owning
systems outright, they control their own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is buying cable companies so they can offer local phone
and Internet service,'' Muoio said. ``Otherwise the local phone
companies could begin offering long distance while AT&AMP;T did not
have the ability to offer local phone and Internet service.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you can't do everything, you are going to lose
market share in your core business, without taking it in new
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T's bid for MediaOne succeeds, it would be a setback for
Comcast, the Philadelphia-based cable company that has been
competing with the telephone companies to offer high-speed access
to the Internet. As the only two industries that have
communications cables passing almost every house and business in
the United States, cable and telephone companies have been
positioning themselves to grab a share of each other's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some major independent cable companies remain, including
Cablevision Systems Corp., but a Comcast merger with Cablevision
might be more complicated since both are controlled by families.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said Thursday that AT&AMP;T was prepared to pay more than
Comcast to acquire MediaOne because AT&AMP;T could make better use of
MediaOne's cable assets. He added that an acquisition was
preferable to a joint venture with MediaOne because making
partnerships like the one with Time Warner work has proved
difficult. In that venture, AT&AMP;T is to provide telephone services
over Time Warner's cables.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joint ventures are running into difficulties in defining
the scope,'' Armstrong said in a conference call with reporters.
``We are having problems separating the voice and data
applications, because technology and time are converging them.''
</P>
<P>
   A potential problem in AT&AMP;T's current venture with Time Warner
is that MediaOne owns 25.5 percent of the Time Warner subsidiary
that owns most of Time Warner's cable systems. But by acquiring
MediaOne, AT&AMP;T would be removing a potential obstacle in its
relationship with Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, AT&AMP;T would exchange $30.85 in cash
and 0.95 shares of AT&AMP;T stock, valued at $59.50 a share, for a
total of $87.375 for each of MediaOne's roughly 660 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The deal may be particularly attractive to MediaOne shareholders
because AT&AMP;T has guaranteed a floor price. AT&AMP;T said it would add
more cash to offset up to 10 percent of any decline in its stock
from its $57 closing price on Wednesday. Making good on that
promise, AT&AMP;T said, could cost an additional $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T would also assume MediaOne's debt of about $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $30 billion in financing, about $23 billion would go to
finance the cash part of the purchase. Another $1.5 billion would
go to Comcast, since MediaOne has already agreed to pay Comcast
$1.5 billion in breakup fees if it terminates their deal. AT&AMP;T
would use the balance for more general needs.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T also said it planned to sell some of MediaOne's noncable
operations _ such as its overseas wireless phone unit _ which AT&AMP;T
said had a value of $18 billion to $20 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
