<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INQUIRES WHY SUSPECT AT ATOM LAB KEPT ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson is investigating
how a computer scientist at Los Alamos National Laboratory kept his
access to U.S. nuclear secrets long after he was suspected of being
a Chinese spy, officials said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson may soon take disciplinary action against officials
who allowed the scientist, Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born computer
expert at Los Alamos, to retain his access to a classified
information about America's nuclear-weapons designs for nearly
three years after he emerged as a leading suspect in China's theft
of design data related to America's most advanced nuclear warhead.
</P>
<P>
   Lee continued to have access to U.S. nuclear secrets at Los
Alamos for more than a year after the director of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation, Louis Freeh, told Energy Department
officials in 1997 that there was no longer any investigative reason
to keep Lee in a sensitive position.
</P>
<P>
   When the FBI investigates spy cases, it often asks employers not
to move suspects out of their jobs in order to avoid tipping them
off.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known which officials might face punishment. Los
Alamos and the nation's other nuclear-weapons laboratories are
owned by the Energy Department. Richardson's internal inquiry came
just as congressional leaders presented President Clinton with
evidence that Chinese nuclear spying has continued during his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican chairman and the ranking Democrat on a select
House committee that has investigated illicit transfers of American
high technology to China briefed Clinton Thursday on their
findings, including evidence of ``current and ongoing'' Chinese
espionage during the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting that lasted for more than an hour, Rep. Christopher
Cox, R-Calif., and Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., told Clinton that
Chinese efforts to steal American atomic secrets is ``not ancient
history.''
</P>
<P>
   The president did not dispute their findings, the two lawmakers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether Beijing's espionage has continued during
the Clinton presidency is politically significant because of the
furor over the administration's handling of evidence in the Los
Alamos spy case.
</P>
<P>
   In response to criticism that the White House sought to play
down the evidence in that case for fear of damaging
American-Chinese relations, Clinton and his advisers have stressed
that the loss of design data related to the W-88 warhead from Los
Alamos occurred in the 1980s, long before Clinton took office.
</P>
<P>
   While The New York Times has reported on evidence of Chinese
atomic espionage during the Clinton administration, the president
has never publicly acknowledged that such spying occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stated last month that he had never been told about
evidence of Chinese nuclear espionage during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   During a March 19 news conference, Clinton even stated that he
was not certain that the loss of the W-88 design data had been the
result of Chinese espionage. ``It is my understanding that the
investigation has not yet determined for sure that espionage
occurred,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   After the session with the congressional leaders, a spokesman
for the National Security Council, David C. Leavy, said that the
``president and the administration are under no illusions about the
fact that China and other countries are trying to acquire sensitive
technologies from the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   An administration official did not dispute the fact that the
briefing with the leaders of the Cox panel included a discussion of
possible Chinese atomic espionage during the Clinton presidency.
But the official emphasized that the information did not deal with
assertions of further espionage at one of America's nuclear-weapons
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We covered in great detail a number of incidents of
espionage,'' Cox said after the meeting with the president. ``There
is no disagreement between Congress and the Executive Branch that
this is a current, ongoing problem that needs immediate and
aggressive attention.''
</P>
<P>
   An administration official noted that Clinton had already been
briefed by his staff on all of the incidents of possible espionage
raised during the congressional session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
