<HEADLINE>
DODGERS GET READY FOR HOLLANDSWORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a week of Dodgers decisions, another one looms
as the Dodgers brain trust decides which day to activate Todd
Hollandsworth and how they want to make room for him.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, on the disabled list since opening day, spent the
past three days on a rehab assignment and he could be activated
before the Dodgers and St. Louis Cardinals begin a three-game
series today at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   If Hollandsworth is activated _ manager Davey Johnson said
earlier in the week that was the plan _ then a roster spot must be
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone said the possibility exists the
Dodgers could continue to go with 12 pitchers and four outfielders
or they could return to the conventional 11 pitchers and five
outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have options,'' Malone said. ``It's something we're going
to have to talk about. We can do a couple of different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Dodgers' bullpen is beaten-up (Alan Mills has a
tender shoulder and Antonio Osuna is on the disabled list) and
lacks experience (Jeff Arnold, Jeff Kubenka, Onan Masaoka and
Robinson Checo have 24 games of experience), 12 pitchers might not
be needed because the Dodgers had Thursday off and will have Monday
off. They've bumped Carlos Perez from his next start, but pitching
coach Charlie Hough said Perez could be used in relief.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers could send down a pitcher. Checo, who came to the
Dodgers in the Mel Rojas and Dave Mlicki deal last week, has been
awful in his two outings. He's given up seven earned runs in 32/3
innings and Johnson said reports he received were Checo's fastball
and sinker had more movement than he saw.
</P>
<P>
   As he was with Rojas, Johnson is leery about pitching Checo in
crucial spots.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers elect to remain with four outfielders, Jacob
Brumfield could be the odd man out. Brumfield, a favorite of
Johnson's from their Cincinnati days, has two hits in 11 at-bats.
Hollandsworth has been on the disabled list with a pulled
hamstring, which he injured April 1 in an exhibition game against
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   __ McGwire day-to-day: A year ago Mark McGwire missed a series
in Los Angeles because of injury, and as the Cardinals make their
first trip to Dodger Stadium this season, his status is in question
again.
</P>
<P>
   The home run king strained his left hamstring Tuesday in
Milwaukee, didn't play Wednesday and a Cardinals spokesman said
Thursday his status for the three-game series against the Dodgers
is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, coming off his 70-homer season, was experiencing
tightness in his hamstring, a Cardinals spokesman said. St. Louis
had Thursday off.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hitting woes: Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley's early-season
problems at the plate were somewhat expected considering he missed
most of spring training, but production from the Dodgers' catchers
has been abysmal through the first 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley is 8 for 44 (.182), backup Paul LoDuca is hitless in 16
at-bats and Rick Wilkins, recently designated for assignment, was 0
for 4. The three catchers have hit a combined .125 (8 for 64).
Hundley owns both homers and all three RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting's something I've always been able to do, so I'm not
worried about it,'' said LoDuca, who hit .309 in six minor-league
seasons. ``I'm a little too anxious. I've been working on it the
last few days, hitting the ball up the middle and the other way.
I'm happy with the way I'm catching and my defense. I'm just
swinging at bad pitches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
