<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS TO CONSOLE STUDENTS BUT FALTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ With two dozen students as his sounding board,
President Clinton puzzled Thursday over the causes of school
violence and mulled how to prevent it. But in the end, he could not
guarantee the students the protection they sought from the kind of
fatal chaos that erupted on Tuesday in Littleton, Colo., where 14
high school students and a teacher lay dead amid bombs and guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't feel safe anymore,'' Jonelle Mitchell, a
student here in the Washington suburbs, said to Clinton, who
presided over an hour-long discussion on lessons to be drawn from
Littleton. ``When is the government, when are you, going to do
something for the other students out there?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had little to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government doesn't run this high school,'' he
replied. ``You know, you have a local school board, and most of the
money comes from the state.''
</P>
<P>
   He referred to the ``big hunting culture'' in America and said
that his efforts to control access to weapons had met with
hostility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little thing I've tried to do, from the passing of the
Brady Bill to the passing of the assault weapons ban _ all these
things have met with violent opposition, as if I were trying to
destroy the American way of life,'' Clinton said. ``And all I'm
trying to do is keep more people alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He did note that after earlier school killings, the federal
government had sent to all school districts a booklet describing
early warning signs of antisocial behavior.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would send new legislation to Capitol Hill but was
vague about what it would entail. Deputy Attorney General Eric
Holder said the administration would push for legislation to make
it harder for youths to get guns and to crack down on sales by
unlicensed dealers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this could do anything to prevent the killings in
Littleton, and Clinton Thursday could do little more than lay out
the scope of the problem, empathize with teen-agers about high
school cliques and highlight some of the techniques that officials
at the T.C. Williams High School here have used to try to minimize
violence.
</P>
<P>
   T.C. Williams is one of the most diverse high schools in the
country. Its students come from more than 84 countries and speak
more than 56 languages. The school requires students to take an
``anger management'' program in ninth grade and offers a conflict
resolution and peer mediation program starting in seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the mediation group intervened in student conflicts
about 100 times. The school also has a confidential hot line on
which students can discuss problems and report incidents that
trouble them.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's discussion provided Clinton another chance to espouse
one of his central concerns: that hatred is driven by a need for
some people to look down on people who are different. He said the
student-killers in Littleton had been ``dissed'' by their peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the wrong reaction to the fact that they were
dissed,'' Clinton said. ``Everybody gets dissed sometime in life,
even the president.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the students that the adage ``sticks and stones will
break my bones but words will never hurt me'' was not true and
suddenly seemed to personalize the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how much energy is lost and how many things are
not done for America because people in Washington, D.C., at the
highest levels of power and influence get hurt by what other people
say about them _ mean, bad things other people say about them,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
