u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-500&AMP;ADD     04-22 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ENVOY ENDS PEACE VISIT; SLIGHT SIGNS OF PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ President Slobodan Milosevic spent nine
hours Thursday with a Russian peace envoy but appeared to give very
little ground.
</P>
<P>
   The envoy, former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, left
Belgrade late Thursday saying that Milosevic had agreed to an
``international presence in Kosovo under United Nations auspices''
to implement any political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic has agreed to such a U.N. presence before, and
details were scarce, including the key point of whether
international participants would be armed, and if so, under whose
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of international forces they will be, or from which
countries _ this is yet to be discussed,'' Chernomyrdin said at the
Belgrade airport. ``But the main thing is that Russia will take
part in them.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO insists on an armed ``international security force'' with
NATO troops as its core, so it is highly unlikely that Chernomyrdin
has made enough progress to change NATO's plans, which call for
continued bombing. Milosevic continues to insist that NATO stop
bombing first, before any talks proceed on a Kosovo settlement, and
he has refused to withdraw all Serbian security forces from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin described his long session with Milosevic as
important progress, but initial Western reactions were dubious.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, responding at a Washington news conference on
the eve of NATO's 50th anniversary summit meeting, said: ``If there
is an offer for a genuine security force, that's the first time
Milosevic has done that, and that represents, I suppose, some step
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   British officials said it was too early to judge the outcome,
but emphasized that NATO's demands included issues such as the safe
return of all ethnic Albanian refugees and the ability for
international investigators to pursue allegations of Serbian war
crimes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is hoping that the Russians can mediate this
conflict, but they have limited influence over the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   While Milosevic spent hours with Chernomyrdin, it was not clear
he liked what he heard. State television gave the Chernomyrdin
visit very little airtime late in the broadcast, a sharp contrast
to the lavish treatment given the visit April 14 of the Belarussian
leader, Aleksandr Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Lukashenko said at a joint appearance with Milosevic that
Belgrade would accept unarmed civilian monitors from non-NATO
countries in Kosovo under a U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Chernomyrdin and Milosevic signed a joint declaration
calling for an end to the airstrikes, the safe return of refugees
to Kosovo, a possible reduction of Yugoslav troops and police but
also for a withdrawal of NATO troops from the borders of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said relief agencies should be allowed to carry out
work in Kosovo, economic aid should be offered to Yugoslavia and
talks on broad autonomy should continue.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, appointed Russia's special Balkan envoy last week
by President Boris Yeltsin, came with specific proposals that
included some form of armed international presence in Kosovo, but
one that would be agreeable to all sides.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His trip came one month after a mission led by Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeni Primakov ended in failure. Unlike the visit to
Belgrade by Primakov and a delegation of military and intelligence
officials days after the bombing began, Chernomyrdin's visit was
designed to elicit some concessions from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of Primakov's mission was to show an effort, but he
was fully aware of the impossibility of achieving any results,''
said a Western diplomat based in Moscow. ``Chernomyrdin has no need
to repeat that effort. He needs to bring home something.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has already moved away from a one-sided
condemnation of NATO's bombing campaign, calling Wednesday for an
end as well to ``ethnic cleansing and separatism'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin spent two days this week consulting with the
leaders of Georgia, Azerbaijan and Ukraine, seeking support close
to home.
</P>
<P>
   The war is growing increasingly costly for Yugoslavia.
Information Minister Milan Komnenic said Thursday that 517
civilians, including 13 children, had been killed in the bombing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He said that more than 4,000 civilians had been seriously
injured since the start of the strikes on March 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
