<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SURVIVORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS MUST TRY TO LIVE WITH MASSACRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ It took five minutes for Katie Trojan to make
her escape from Columbine High School as two classmates unleashed a
storm of gunfire and bomb blasts. She remembers every second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see every step I took,'' said Trojan, a junior who was among
the first students able to flee the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still see the places where I put my feet on the fence to
jump over it.''
</P>
<P>
   She and others who lived through the massacre are now living
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Police SWAT team member Donn Kraemer, 49, relied on his training
to keep focused during the daring rescue of a trapped student. But
when asked if he has shed tears since, he admitted to a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cops aren't supposed to cry,'' he said. ``We do that on our
own time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraemer was training recruits at a gun range when he was
dispatched to the far more deadly shooting scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard on the radio shots were being fired and there were
explosions,'' Kraemer said. ``But until I got here I didn't believe
it. I knew it wasn't Hollywood, I knew it wasn't a prank. It was
just disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   He arrived to a chaotic scene of students rushing from the
school and others signaling for help from windows.
</P>
<P>
   A sign in a second-floor window read ``1 bleeding to death.'' A
student was trying to leap from another window.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get to the window with the sign,'' Kraemer said.
``But we knew we had one victim we could help. He was ready to jump
head first to get out of that room. At the time we didn't know
where he was but he was in the library, the main killing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraemer and six other SWAT officers were about 40 yards from the
window in an armored vehicle that a courier service had provided
for rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   One officer rode in the cab with the driver and his supervisor,
while the others walked behind the vehicle, using it as mobile
cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept our weapons pointed at the window because we didn't
know if he was alone,'' Kraemer said.
</P>
<P>
   When the vehicle was positioned under the window, Kraemer put
down his weapon, climbed on the roof of the armored car with
another officer and pulled the boy to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who he was. I don't even know his name,'' Kraemer
said. ``He was in deep shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraemer said he heard no other sounds coming from the room where
several victims and the two gunmen later were found dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was any bright spot in our mission, it was rescuing
him,'' Kraemer said.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath left Kraemer and other hardened police officers
emotionally drained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers by nature sometimes use black humor to relieve
stress,'' Kraemer said. ``I saw none of that. Everyone was numb.
There were no high-fives, no `You did a good job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Trojan, 16, was in a counseling office when a teacher came in to
tell them someone was shooting a gun in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   She and several teachers and students took cover in a copy room
closet for a few minutes, then decided to make their break when
explosions set off fire alarms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were running just trying to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, she heard teachers yelling at other fleeing students,
telling them to jump a nearby fence and ``Run for your lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time I was thinking `What about this person? What
about that person?' '' she recalled Thursday. ``One of the first
people that came to my mind didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trojan returned to a park near the school Wednesday and
Thursday, placing flowers and seeking comfort from other survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I find a lot of my friends and we need each
other right now,'' Trojan said. ``We feel so fortunate that we're
here and that we survived. But then you realize your friend didn't
make it, and you just have to tell yourself she's in a better
place.''
</P>
<P>
   And matters difficult to fathom just two days ago have come into
focus with terrible clarity. ``Last year I never understood what it
was like for the kids in Jonesboro (the site of a deadly school
shooting in Arkansas),'' Trojan said. ``Now I do. And it's a
horrible feeling to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
