<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SIMILAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING ANSWERS TO UNSETTLING QUESTION OF SCHOOL SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERS, N.Y. _ They are two days and 1,650 miles removed from
the death and disbelief consuming Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., but in the minds of students at Somers High
School in northern Westchester County, visions of the carnage
linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an awkward feeling when I came to first period this
morning,'' said Noah Stebbins, 18, a burly senior with blond hair
as short as razor stubble. ``Just like the first time you step on a
plane after a major plane crash.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an apt description of how most of the 50 students at
Somers High, where wooded acres give an air of seclusion and wild
geese peck at the school's manicured baseball field, are feeling
since the murder of 15 people at Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   Though they had followed the news of other shootings at other
schools in recent years _ memories of Jonesboro, Ark., and West
Paducah, Ky, have not faded entirely _ the latest killings shook
students here as none of the others had. In Columbine High,
students at Somers see a simulacrum of themselves: an affluent
suburban hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that feeling has been dashed, students said. Before they
opened fire on their classmates and then, the police say, killed
themselves, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold had not seemed very
different from some students at Somers High.
</P>
<P>
   Like Columbine and, indeed, most high schools, Somers High has
its contingents of jocks, brains, burnouts and goths, the
black-clad demimonde to which Harris and Dylan apparently belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have to worry even more, who you can and can't be
friends with,'' said Jenn Sgroi, a 16-year-old junior. ``There used
to be basically, like, the preps and the geeks. Now it's like
there's so many different groups. Like, there is the goths, and
there is the jocks and there is the preps and there is the nerds.
Now I have to worry about all these different groups.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, school officials, in an appeal piped into
classrooms, asked students for a moment of silence for the 15 dead.
Thursday, the school tried to regain its normally ingrained sense
of security.
</P>
<P>
   But television images broadcast in the aftermath of the murders
have left Somers students more cautious. ``It made me conscience of
what I say,'' said Cindy Boniello, a junior who recalled a chilling
interview with a Columbine student who said she had begged one of
the gun-wielding classmates for her life, only to watch the gun
turned on a friend nearby. ``You just can't joke with some people.
You just have to be aware of that.''
</P>
<P>
   As have their peers around the nation, a wave of students at
Somers High visited school counselors to discuss their feelings
about the violence in Littleton, said the principal, Linda Horisk.
So, too, have a few teachers, faced with the double burden of
dealing with their own reactions and those of their students.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Zeinoun, an English teacher, confronted her first-period
class with the massacre, asking students to write out their
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of try to bring it home, to make it more personal,''
said Ms. Zeinoun.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the essays betrayed feelings of anger toward the news
media. But many Somers students said they had spent hours
transfixed by the live broadcasts immediately after the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stuff that I saw is stuff I never want to see
again,'' Stebbins said, shaking his head. ``Kids aren't supposed to
go into buildings and shoot everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet students here predicted the grisly events would happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   School killings are starting to feel like an annual ritual, said
Christopher Sales, a Somers High senior. ``I wouldn't be surprised
if it happens again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the chances of it happening at Somers High School,
parents have been invited to meet with psychiatrists from the Four
Winds Psychiatric Hospital in Katonah on May 4 to talk about
identifying the signs of a child in need of help, Ms. Horisk said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zeinoun, the English teacher, said the Columbine killings
have created a renewed sense of community and inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more aware of wanting to make everybody feel, not
loved, but cared for,'' she said. ``So that if they need to turn to
somebody, they're not going to turn to violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
