<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-KOSOVO-ART-2TAKE     04-22 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-KOSOVO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTH OF LAND-ASSAULT PLAN DARKENS ALREADY GRIM EVE OF SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of the opening of the NATO summit here,
President Clinton and NATO leaders vowed to intensify the military
and economic punishment of Serbia even as they reserved judgment on
a possible peace proposal from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   American and NATO war planners in Washington and Brussels began
drawing up options for a land assault to drive the forces of
President Slobodan Milosevic from the Yugoslav province of Kosovo
as alliance leaders gathered in Washington for a suddenly grim
commemoration of NATO's 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, standing in the Rose Garden with Javier Solana, NATO's
secretary general, said that Milosevic must withdraw his troops
from Kosovo ``or he can watch as NATO grinds down his war machine,
and the Serb people he claims to represent face mounting
hardship.''
</P>
<P>
   As the summit opens, some difference are clear within an
alliance that has struggled to present a unified face. Prime
Minister Tony Blair and other British officials, the first
arrivals, aggressively pushed a hard line on Kosovo in a series of
meetings with Clinton, members of Congress and business leaders.
Blair has been the most outspoken of the NATO leaders in urging the
deployment of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Sketchy reports that Milosevic was willing to accept some form
of international monitoring force in Kosovo were called a possible
``step forward'' by Clinton at the news conference Thursday.
However, those reports left it unclear whether Milosevic would
accept an armed international presence.
</P>
<P>
   As the president spoke Thursday afternoon, NATO warplanes and
missiles began a third night of attacks on leadership targets in
Serbia. NATO bombs hit Milosevic's presidential residence and the
government television station in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia denounced the strike as an assassination attempt,
which American and NATO officials denied. They portrayed it as a
legitimate assault on the military leadership of Yugoslavia, though
not on Milosevic directly, effectively drawing a distinction
without making a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that removing Milosevic from power was not one of
the aims of the conflict, and that if Milosevic withdrew his troops
from Kosovo and allowed the peaceful return of the refugees, NATO
would wreak no further damage and would not seek to unseat the
Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we set forth certain conditions, and if he meets those
conditions, and the Serbian people are willing to continue him in
power, then I could imagine such an outcome,'' Clinton said. ``Now
that begs the question of what the War Crimes Tribunal will do or
what other action might be taken. But we _ NATO has never taken a
position on that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin, the former Russian prime minister, said
Thursday after meeting with Milosevic in Belgrade that Milosevic
would be willing to accept an unspecified international
``presence'' in Kosovo to monitor the return of refugees. The
United States and NATO have tried to suggest to the Russians that
Russian troops be part of some type of land force there.
</P>
<P>
   Administration and allied officials said Thursday night that
they were skeptical about the Russian-Serbian initiative and that
few details were available.
</P>
<P>
   A European official said he thought Belgrade and Moscow might be
trying to undercut the summit by offering a vague peace plan just
as NATO leaders sat down to map a military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One senior American official said he suspected the initiative
was a propaganda ploy designed to appeal to the Russian people; an
American aide said that the proposal had gaps on issues like the
size and composition of a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did not dismiss the offer out of hand, as he did an
earlier cease-fire initiative brokered by Yevgeny Primakov, the
current Russian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an offer for a genuine security force,'' the
president said, ``that's the first time that Milosevic has ever
done that, and that represents, I suppose, some step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then repeated that such a force could include not only
American and NATO troops, but also Russians, Ukrainians and
soldiers from other Slavic and Orthodox Christian countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is true,'' Clinton said of the Milosevic offer, ``then
it is at least the first acknowledgment by Milosevic that there
will have to be a security force there. But for the security force
to work, it will have to have the confidence of the people who live
there, and it will have to operate in a way that protects all the
people there, including the Serb minority.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO summit was intended to be a celebration of the
alliance's victory over communism and a seminar on its future.
Instead, it has become a war council on Kosovo, with all its
reminders of the grisly ethnic conflicts that grew into the
century's bloodiest wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This NATO summit in Washington will be one of the most
important meetings the alliance has ever held,'' Solana said. ``Our
focus will be on the immediate, and particularly on Kosovo. It is,
no doubt, the gravest crisis that Europe and NATO have faced for
many years.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior European official said that Milosevic's apparent
willingness to consider an international presence in Kosovo was a
sign that he was beginning to crack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting,'' the official said, who insisted on
anonymity. ``We're getting these signals from Milosevic, that
here's a guy sitting there in front of his TV screens trying to
read signals from NATO, and he's hearing that we're not going away,
and the air strikes are getting harder and getting close to home,
and he's getting worried.''
</P>
<P>
   But a NATO diplomat said that Milosevic would only accept a
small and unarmed force, and pointed to language calling for a
``reduction'' in Yugoslav forces in Kosovo rather than complete
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Blair staked out a hard line as he moved from
speech to speech in his first full day here. Addressing about 30
United States senators, he laid out what one congressional aide
called a ``compelling case'' for the allied attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Alistair Campbell, chief spokesman for the prime minister's
office, said that Blair was trying, in his public and private
comments, to assure allied unity.
</P>
<P>
   His language has been more forceful than Clinton's, in part
because the president fears alienating an American public that lags
behind the British people in support for the Balkan conflict,
Campbell said. But he denied that the British were serving as the
stalking horse for the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   And he insisted that the two countries are on the same track on
Kosovo. He said that Blair was determined to use the NATO summit
``to send powerful signals to Serbia and rest of world about NATO
determination and confidence the air campaign is working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
