<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SAXTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 CONGRESSMAN SAYS NATO IS WORSENING REFUGEE CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just back from a stealthy three-day mission of
personal diplomacy to Belgrade, Yugoslavia, Rep. Jim Saxton,
R-N.J., said Thursday that the NATO bombing had succeeded mainly in
hurting Yugoslav civilians and worsening the refugee crisis in
Kosovo, but not in weakening the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton, in an hourlong interview with reporters in his Capitol
Hill office, went so far as to contend that the United States and
its NATO allies deserved some blame for the mass expulsion of
Albanians from Kosovo by Yugoslav forces, and suggested that it
might not have happened if NATO had not started the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when the ethnic cleansing started, I know when the
refugees started to move,'' he said. ``It was when we started
bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Saxton, an eight-term representative from Mount Holly in
southern New Jersey, is relatively shy of the media and usually
keeps a low profile, and his colleagues considered him an unlikely
candidate to slip into a war zone on a mysterious mission. The only
official in Washington he told of his plans was House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, who counseled him not to go for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Saxton said the trip was arranged through contacts
he had developed as chairman of the House Task Force on Terrorism
and Unconventional Warfare. They put him in touch with a Yugoslav
organization called the Institute for Geopolitical Studies, which
persuaded the Yugoslav government to extend him an official
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton said he flew from Washington to Paris last Sunday, and
then to Budapest, Hungary, where Yugoslav officials drove him
across the border to Belgrade, a five-hour trip. Over two days, he
said, he met with the Yugoslav foreign minister, the deputy prime
minister for international relations, and the chairman of the
Parliament's foreign relations committee.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton said he also toured a nearby city, Pancevo, where he said
NATO bombs had damaged an oil refinery, a chemical plant and
hundreds of homes. He did not meet with the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic. He left on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton was accompanied on the trip by an aide, Yossef Bodansky,
whose writings on Middle Eastern terrorism have been acclaimed in
Serbia. Bodansky says that Muslim leaders in Bosnia and Kosovo have
been heavily supported by fundamentalist Islamic terrorists and
Osama bin Laden, a suspect in the bombings of U.S. embassies in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton made similar assertions Thursday, saying NATO had
inserted itself into a dirty civil war in which both sides were
guilty of atrocities. The Clinton administration contends that
Yugoslav forces have been far more brutal than the Kosovar rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got people who are supported by bin Laden, and you've
got people supported by Milosevic,'' he said. ``We have chosen bin
Laden?''
</P>
<P>
   Saxton said his goal had been to learn more about the conflict
before voting on whether to send in ground troops. He also said he
had hoped to bring home the three American soldiers in Yugoslav
custody. Yugoslav officials had told him he might be able to visit
the soldiers, but withdrew the offer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton said the trip had confirmed his opposition to American
involvement in the conflict and to the use of American ground
troops. He said he had come away convinced that the Yugoslavs were
prepared to negotiate in good faith, and he said he expressed this
conviction to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright over the
telephone Thursday morning. A State Department spokeswoman said
Albright would not comment on Saxton's trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
