<HEADLINE>
BOMB DISCOVERY RAISES CONCERNS SCHOOL KILLERS HAD HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN AND MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The largest of 30 homemade bombs was
discovered Thursday in the kitchen of Columbine High School,
heightening suspicions that the presumed killers had help in their
conspiracy and planned an apolycptic ending to the massacre that
killed 15 and shocked the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These subjects were not only on a killing rampage, but they
were going to destroy the school. They were going to burn the
school up,'' said Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb, hidden in a duffel bag and fashioned from a 20-pound
propane tank attached to a container of gasoline, was overlooked in
the initial sweep by SWAT teams, and investigators said it was
possible there were still more bombs hidden in the school.
</P>
<P>
   Police are investigating whether presumed killers Eric Harris
and Dylan Klebold, who attended a Saturday night after-hours prom
party at Columbine High School, used that access to the school to
prowl the hallways placing explosives. But another possibility was
that the killers had as-yet unidentified co-conspirators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have been difficult, maybe not impossible,
but very difficult, for two people to have gotten all these
explosives into the school, in addition to the weapons,'' said
Jefferson County District Attorney David Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that investigators have no physical evidence
to indicate a third person was directly involved in the attack.
Thomas reiterated, however, that investigators suspect others at
least knew of Klebold and Harris's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, investigators reported finding a note at Harris's
home that could provide clues to the motive. Police would not
reveal the contents of the note.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, school property remained a community shrine,
attracting hundreds of people who braved a spring snowstorm to draw
as close to the school, and each other, as they could.
</P>
<P>
   A makeshift shrine to the 12 slain students and one dead teacher
continued to grow Thursday, organized loosely aroung the theme,
``In The Arms of Angels.'' Several tents were erected to protect
mourners and their offerings from the falling snow. Hundreds of
bouquets of flowers and scores of sympathetic notes littered the
ground. Under one, a football jersey belonging to slain high school
senior Isaiah Shoels was hung. On his No. 80, someone had written,
``We love you, Isaiah.''
</P>
<P>
   A wooden cross festooneed with blue-and-white ribbons,
representing the school colors stood tall. On the cold ground
nearby were 13 small crosses, 9 blue and 4 pink, representing the
nine boys and four girls killed, not including the shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends of sophomore John Tomlin, crawled into the
back of his beloved Chevrolet pick-up truck, which was covered in
flowers and cards. They huddled inside, drawing close for warmth
and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said Columbine would remain closed
indefinitely. They hope to relocate the 1,965 students to another
location sometime next week. They said their priority in
determining the location is keeping students and faculty together.
</P>
<P>
   The crime scene investigation has been painstakingly slow,
police say, because of the scores of knapsacks, lunch sacks, gym
bags _ all possible hiding spots for bombs _ that were left behind
in the chaos and must be searched. All the bodies were removed by
early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Officals who have seen the shattered classroom windows and
blood-stained hallways said they are haunted by the images.
``Everything seemed frozen in time. Some of the victims seemed to
have stopped almost in mid-action. One victim had a pencil in his
hand. In the cafeteria, there were sandwiches with one bite out of
them. Glass and debris were everywhere,'' Thomas said. ``It was a
devastating scene. I can only describe it as a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hours following the shooting spree, three teen-agers,
wearing jackets inscribed with a symbol the presumed killers also
sometimes wore _ a crucifix with a slash through it _ were
arrested. The teenage boys, police say, were spotted standing on a
nearby hill watching the bloodshed, but they were released
following initial interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday police said they had not identified other suspects,
though they continued to question friends of Harris and Klebold,
other members of the so-called ``Trench Coat Mafia,'' a loose
affiliation of outcasts.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation searches its collective conscience for solutions
or at least explanations for the schoolhouse killings, the quest to
understand Harris and Klebold continues. They shared a passion for
computers, spending hours in the Harris family garage navigating
Internet Web pages for instructions on building bombs, friends say.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have retrieved a computer from the Harris home, and
several web sites visited frequently by the boys, who favored two
of the country's best selling video games, ``Quest' and ``Doom.''
Aside from video games whose winners have the highest body count,
just about everything the ``Trench Coat Mafia'' stood for has been
examined by a confused public.
</P>
<P>
   Questions persist: Was it the Gothic movement, attracting teens
who paint their faces death-white and their fingernails blood-black
that drew Harris and Klebold to killing? Or were Harris and Klebold
fueled by the racist song lyrics they favored, the modern-day
Internet they revered, or the age-old clash of high school cliques
some say plauged them?
</P>
<P>
   Looking for ways to help school communities across the country
feel safe, President Clinton Thursday hosted a roundtable with
students in a suburban Washington, D.C., school, hearing their need
for school psychiatric care and peer efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno Thursday arrived in this traumatized
city to meet with the victims and their families, school officials,
and investigators in an attempt to ``erase this kind of violence
once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, due to host its annual
conference in Denver this weekend, will scale back the event from
three days to one in response to the killings, and the public
outcry over access to handguns.
</P>
<P>
   But the Denver Mayor Wellington Webb called on the NRA to canel
the event completely. Denver District Schools, and two other
suburban school districts, took the unusual step of banning black
trench coats worn in schools, a response to the Trench Coat Mafia
uniform of long black dusters worn by Harris, Klebold, and their
friends.
</P>
<P>
   The parent of the two boys have hired attorneys, after providing
short statements saying they were stunned by the actions of their
sons, and sympathized with other grief-stricken parents.
Prosecutors say it is too early to determine whether the boys'
parents will be charged in conn
</P>
</TEXT>
