<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAZARD-SETTLE-NYT &LR;      04-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZARD-SETTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZARD TO PAY $11 MILLION TO SETTLE FEDERAL CHARGES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.J., Fla., Ark., Pa., Wash. Ind.)   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lazard Freres &AMP; Co., the Wall Street investment bank, agreed
Thursday to pay $11 million to settle federal charges for its role
in an industrywide scandal of overcharging in the sale of billions
of dollars worth of bonds in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the closing chapter of Lazard's disastrous foray into
the municipal finance business, the firm agreed to pay about $7.45
million to the federal government and the remainder to local
government agencies in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Indiana and
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Lazard centered on a practice known as ``yield
burning,'' in which financial firms profited heavily by inflating
the prices of U. S. government securities they sold to
municipalities seeking to lower their borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
   While negotiating with Lazard Freres, federal investigators also
have been in talks to settle similar charges against more than a
dozen other Wall Street firms, lawyers close to the case said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement with Lazard ``represents a framework for similar
resolutions with other investment banks,'' said William R. Baker,
an associate director of enforcement at the Securities and Exchange
Commission in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers close to the case say the settlements with the
other firms could easily exceed $100 million in total. As with the
settlement with Lazard, some of the money would be to repay losses
suffered by the Treasury Department and some would compensate local
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   For Lazard, the settlement brings to an end a
reputation-damaging affair that began more than a decade ago when
Lazard decided to break into the trillion-dollar municipal finance
market. Using political power as entree to municipal deals, it set
about hiring political figures around the country. One was Mark S.
Ferber, a former aide to a state Senate leader in Massachusetts.
Others were Richard P. Poirier Jr., who had been close to Gov. Jim
Florio of New Jersey, and James E. Eaton, a one-time aide to Gov.
Bob Graham of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992, Lazard had broken into the top ranks in municipal
underwriting, winning big contracts in Boston, New Jersey and New
York. But three years later, Lazard closed its municipal department
after a series of federal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   With the settlement Thursday, Lazard has agreed to pay $44
million to settle a number of cases involving its municipal bond
sales. Ferber, who had represented himself as an independent
adviser at Lazard, but had taken kickbacks to steer clients to
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., was sentenced to jail for 33 months in late
1996. Poirier and Eaton were indicted on charges of conspiring with
an Arkansas brokerage firm to steer municipal bond business in
Georgia to Lazard in 1992. Eaton pleaded guilty; Poirier is
awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement after the latest settlement was announced,
Lazard said it was ``especially pleased to have finally resolved
this matter.'' Through its lawyers, it declined to discuss the case
further.
</P>
<P>
   Yield burning was a technique that bond dealers devised to
secure better rates as municipalities refinanced debt. When
interest rates fall, municipalities often issue new bonds to
refinance the debt and lower their interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   But there are usually restrictions on when the old bonds can be
retired. So a municipal bond issuer has to wait before using the
new proceeds to retire the old debt. During that time, the money
from the new municipal bonds is invested in Treasury bonds and held
in escrow.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the escrow account cannot earn a higher return than the
interest rate paid by the new bonds. If it does, the excess is
supposed to go to the Treasury. To reduce, or burn down, the yield,
Wall Street firms sometimes sold the Treasury bonds to the
municipalities at artificially high prices. In this way, the
Treasury was maneuvered out of millions that went into pockets of
the bankers. It was not supposed to cost the municipalities
anything. But sometimes, federal officials say, the bankers also
gave the municipalities less than they were entitled to.
</P>
<P>
   The first widely publicized complaints about the practice came
in early 1995. They were made by Michael R. Lissack, an investment
banker who was dismissed by Smith Barney, now Salomon Smith Barney,
in a dispute over several issues. Lissack filed a suit under the
federal whistle-blower statute and the federal agencies joined in.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Phillips, a lawyer for Lissack, said that under a
provision in the whistle-blower statute, his client is eligible to
receive 15 to 25 percent of settlements that go to the Treasury.
Lissack has had to deal with his own legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, for example, he agreed to pay $30,000 and accept
a ban of at least five years from the securities business to settle
federal charges that he misrepresented how much money would be
saved for Dade County, Fla., in a municipal bond transaction in
1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
