<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9811 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TALLADEGA-BURTON-     04-22 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TALLADEGA-BURTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Many NASCAR followers have thought Jeff Burton
was on the verge of greatness since he won his first Winston Cup
race two years ago in the inaugural event at Texas Motor Speedway.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burton finished fourth in the points race in 1997 and fifth last
year, but he still wasn't a serious contender for the championship.
He had the talent, and he had the equipment in the Exide Batteries
Ford, but something was holding him back.
</P>
<P>
   Burton was angry that he couldn't get over the hump, and that
anger, coupled with a fiery temper, might have been the reason for
his problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``My emotions have gotten me where I am, but they also have held
me back at times,'' Burton said. ``I think the best thing about me
is the passion I have for what I do, but I haven't always been the
easiest guy in the world to work with. So this year is a kinder and
gentler Jeff Burton, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, it's working, because the 31-year-old Virginian
is on top of the Winston Cup point standings after eight races.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, Dale Jarrett and Mark Martin are lurking near the
top, just as they have in each of the last three seasons. But all
three are looking up at Burton entering Sunday's DieHard 500 at the
Talladega Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early, so I really don't like talking about points
much,'' Burton said. ``We're not going to get overexcited about
being the leader. Obviously, we feel good about what we've done so
far, but I'm trying to focus on what we need to do to keep
improving. You can't win a championship this early, but you can
lose one.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton probably had Talladega in mind when he made that
statement. The restrictor-plate superspeedways of Daytona and
Talladega have been the nemesis for Roush Racing teammates Burton
and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In his last five restrictor-plate races, Burton's average finish
is 24.2, including a 35th and 40th at Daytona, and a 43rd at
Talladega one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff can't walk out of here with a 30th- or 40th-place
finish,'' said Buddy Parrott, the general manager of Roush Racing.
``That would be disastrous. We've got to get better on the
superspeedways.''
</P>
<P>
   Talladega has been better for Burton than Daytona. He has three
top-10 finishes at NASCAR's fastest track, but he never has
finished higher than seventh on the 2.6-mile tri-oval. And
qualifying has been a problem. Burton has started 34th or lower in
five of his 10 starts at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some decent finishes, but I want to win here,''
Burton said. ``You have to be patient. I think that's the biggest
difference that stands out for me this year _ patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every race is going to go the way you want. It's a long
season. If we win a race, we don't think that means we're going to
go win the next one. And if we have a problem and finish 35th or
whatever, we don't think that means we will have problems in the
next race.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton hasn't had many problems since his 35th-place finish in
the Daytona 500 to start the 1999 season. He has finished seventh
or better in each of the last seven races, including victories at
Las Vegas and Darlington, and a second-place finish to John
Andretti last weekend at Martinsville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Burton held off his older brother, Ward, to win at Las Vegas,
and he won at Darlington when rain stopped the race one lap after
he was involved in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we can feel a difference in this year's
team,'' Burton said. ``We are better by a long shot than we were at
this point last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've had some breaks and we've won two races because of
circumstances. We caught a caution at the right time at Las Vegas,
and the rain won it for us at Darlington.''
</P>
<P>
   Being fortunate helps, but a lot more than luck has placed
Burton ahead of the pack this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is a hard worker who understands the car, which makes him
a big asset to the crew,'' Parrott said. ``Jeff is in the shop as
much as he can be. He is involved in building the cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Roush first noticed Burton a decade ago when he was a
youngster on the Busch Grand National circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built the engines Jeff was using on the Busch circuit, and
he often would outrun Mark (Martin) and the (Busch) car we were
fielding,'' Roush said. ``Jeff seemed to have the same maturity,
knowledge and instincts I had seen in Mark years earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin finished second to Gordon in the championship chase last
season, the third time Martin has ended up No. 2. He could end up
No. 2 to his teammate this year, but Burton knows he wouldn't be
the driver he is today without Martin's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark brings a lot of things to the table that have helped
me,'' Burton said. ``He is as honest a guy as you will find, and I
believe he is the best race-car driver in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gained a mutual respect for each other, and I think
we've made each other better. Mark and I work together on a daily
basis. We make decisions together. That's the strength of what
we're doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the big break of his career came when he joined
Roush Racing, which is the only five-car team in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best decision I've made in my career was to become
associated with Jack Roush,'' Burton said. ``When you drive a car
that isn't capable of running up front, you don't learn much. But
Jack has given me a competitive car, and that's when I really
started learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton was the Winston Cup Rookie of the Year in 1994, one year
after Gordon did the same. Gordon has won three championships since
then, but many NASCAR fans are hoping Burton has reached the point
where he can give Gordon stiff competition for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started this season with a goal to improve three things:
our pit stops, our qualifying and our consistency,'' Burton said.
``You have to be consistent. We felt if we improved in those areas,
we would have a successful season.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton and his crew have improved in all three areas, but they
still must prove they can improve at a restrictor-plate track like
Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a championship requires excellence in every aspect of
the sport,'' Burton said. ``We have to get better. We haven't run a
complete race and done everything right yet by any means. We can be
better than we've been.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 24 car (Gordon), the 6 (Martin) and the 88 (Jarrett) are
going to be there at the end, so we have to continue to race
aggressively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
