<HEADER>
A9813 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-OFFENSE-HN     04-22 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-OFFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ Seemingly out of options on their own pitching staff, the
Chicago Cubs were bailed out when Mother Nature took the mound to
water down the Astros' smoking bats Thursday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A persistent storm stopped long enough for the Astros and Cubs
to play the first two games of their series, but Thursday's finale
was washed out. It couldn't have come at a better time for the
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of blistering Cubs pitchers, the Astros take
their traveling assault show to Cincinnati, where they begin a
three-game series against the Reds tonight at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long ago that there was so much concern over the
Astros' offense that it seemed manager Larry Dierker would issue an
all-points bulletin to locate his wayward sluggers. Rest easy; they
have been found and are again the most feared assortment of hitters
in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros rank first in the NL in batting average (.306) and
on-base percentage (.378) and second in slugging percentage (.485)
and hits (145). For good measure, they are second in stolen bases
(19).
</P>
<P>
   Normally, when the offense is rolling it's a good bet Jeff
Bagwell and Craig Biggio are leading the charge. And while Bagwell
is on fire, the two most consistent Astros hitters are an unlikely
pair.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Carl Everett is the only Astro who has reached
base in every game. He has hit safely in 13 of the Astros' 14
games, and his .400 average is second on the team to Ricky
Gutierrez, who is hitting .424 and would be second in the league in
batting if he had enough at-bats to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky gets overlooked a little bit because we have so many
great hitters in our lineup, but he's been going great,'' Dierker
said of his eighth-place hitter. ``Opposing pitchers make a big
mistake when they overlook Ricky; that's when they end up paying
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez, who collected the 500th hit of his career Tuesday
against the Cubs, is riding a six-game hitting streak and is
batting .500 over his last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys the challenge of hitting in front of the pitcher, even
though eighth-place hitters seldom see good pitches. Opposing
pitchers often view the ninth spot as an automatic out and rarely
challenge the No. 8 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're hitting eighth you have to be patient, and I don't
mind that at all,'' said Gutierrez, who has hit .261 in each of the
past two seasons. ``A lot of guys don't like to hit eighth, but
it's not a pride thing with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm seeing the ball well, and I've been able to get
some hits. Hopefully, I'll be able to keep it going because the
strength of our lineup is getting hits up and down the order.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the season, there were questions about the middle of
the order _ specifically the fifth spot, which was occupied by
Moises Alou in 1998. Alou had arthroscopic knee surgery in February
and is out at least until August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moises is gone,'' Astros hitting instructor Tom McCraw said.
``We have to fight with the guys we have. It's like in war; if your
buddy goes down, you can't go back and get him. You have to keep
fighting, and that's what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And Everett hasn't been a bad replacement as the No. 5 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old switch hitter, whom the Astros acquired from the
Mets for John Hudek in December 1997, has produced multiple hits in
seven of the Astros' 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   He and Bagwell are tied for the team lead with 33 total bases,
and his 10 RBIs rank second to Bagwell's 12 on the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the least bit surprised,'' said McCraw, who coached
Everett when both were with the Mets. ``(General manager) Gerry
(Hunsicker) asked me about him before we made the trade, and I told
him Carl was ready to explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent has always been there. Now he's maturing as a
hitter, and he's getting an opportunity. I think he could have a
big year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett hit .333 before the 1998 All-Star break and .257 after
it, which may be why Dierker describes him as a streak hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on a hot streak right now, and it would be great if he
could keep it going for an extended period of time,'' Dierker said.
``He proved that he could drive in runs last season. So even when
he's not on a hot streak, I'm going to keep on playing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett downplays talk about his being streaky, choosing instead
to call his production consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is streaky?'' he said. ``To me, that's basically saying
it's going to end. That's what people said last year (when he
finished with a .296 batting average).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay any attention to that. I'm just going to try to
keep doing what I've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
