<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: NATO Summit Draws the Keen Interest of Defense
Stock  Investors 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
After initial belief that defense stocks would not benefit from the
Kosovo conflict, investors in aerospace and defense firms are now
keeping a close eye on the NATO summit that begins today in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   As the possibility of a ground attack grows, investor focus is
expected to shift from stocks that benefit from an air war to those
companies whose products would be used in a ground war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability of a NATO ground attack against Yugoslav
forces in Kosovo is increasing. (And) Congress seems likely to add
billions of dollars more to the Department of Defense budget,''
says defense firm analyst Byron Callan of Merrill Lynch in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   While the prospects of a pending ground war is nothing to
celebrate, it is doubly painful for American taxpayers who probably
will see their slim chances of a tax cut destroyed like a Belgrade
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   In short, a ground war would probably cost more than the $6
billion the Clinton administration is prepared to spend. However,
since it isn't clear how much more Congress might allocate to the
war, Callan isn't changing his defense stock recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, one stock that Callan thinks might eventually get a
lift from the additional spending tied to a ground attack is
Alliant Techsystems, a maker of medium-caliber cannon ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Callan surmises that defense stocks might
psychologically benefit from Russia's ``vehement opposition to a
ground attack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Russian) threats may sharpen investor concerns about the
deterioration (of) international security, (which in turn) bolsters
the attractiveness of defense stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LUCKY ACE: &LR;  Successful investing takes intelligence, sound
strategy, execution and sometimes a little bit of luck. Take San
Francisco's Parkside Group, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Parkside is a relatively young buyout partnership founded by
managing partner Barry Schneider, who deftly transformed his
family's $4 million (sales) floor covering business, MSA
Industries, into the nation's largest distributor of commercial
floor coverings.
</P>
<P>
   Under his direction, the company expanded to 46 branches in 31
states and racked up more than $300 million in sales. Eventually,
Schneider sold MSA Industries to DuPont in August 1996 for an
undisclosed amount. He rolled much of his proceeds from the sale
into Parkside, where he is joined by partners Gil Amelio, former
chief executive of Apple Computer and National Semiconductor, and
Chuck Frank, former president of Il Fornaio.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was more than luck that spurred the growth and
sale of the Schneider family business, which largely resulted from
hard work and vision. Where luck came into play was with Parkside's
first investment: MacGregor Golf Co.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout group bought then-struggling MacGregor of Georgia
last August. Considering the relatively flat demand for golf clubs
and the stiff competition with other major manufacturers, Schneider
knew turning around MacGregor wasn't going to be a ``gimme.''
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks ago, at the storied Master's golf tournament in
Augusta, Ga., the turnaround task suddenly got a little easier.
Spanish touring pro Jose Maria Olazabal won the grand slam event
using MacGregor clubs.
</P>
<P>
   For Schneider, who along with his son followed Olazabal for
three rounds of the tournament, it was like sponsoring the winner
of the Indianapolis 500 on his first try.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost indescribable to watch a person who represents
your brand, play the way he played,'' Schneider beamed. ``(And) the
resulting feedback from consumers has been phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOND FAREWELL: &LR;  I just wanted to say goodbye to our colleague
Mark Martinez, who has been an editorial assistant in The Chronicle
business section for more than two years. Mark is leaving the paper
to work for his mentor, financial columnist Herb Greenberg, at
TheStreet.com. While Mark's job description here didn't call for
doing research and checking the facts of columnists, he routinely
did just that on his own initiative. He has been an invaluable
asset to Street Smarts and the business section.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Herb occupied this space for about 10 years and was
largely responsible for recruiting Mark to The Chronicle. Our loss
is TSC's gain. Good luck, Mark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
