<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLERS PLANNED TO DESTROY THE SCHOOL WITH LARGE BOMB 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Two students who massacred classmates at
Columbine High School left a large bomb in the kitchen, indicating
they planned to destroy the school and may have had help from
others, investigators said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These subjects were not only on a killing rampage, but they
were going to destroy the school. They were going to burn the
school up,'' said Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, used sawed-off shotguns,
a semiautomatic rifle, a pistol and homemade bombs to kill 12
students and one teacher Tuesday before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As the 11:30 a.m. attack inside the two-story building dragged
on, SWAT teams worked to free students caught inside the school and
frantic parents gathered outside, some waiting hours for word that
their children were safe.
</P>
<P>
   No motive has been established, although the two collected guns,
professed to like Adolf Hitler and disliked minorities and athletes
and belonged to a costumed social group called the ``Trenchcoat
Mafia.'' Most of the members, numbered to be about 15, graduated
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said a note had been found at the home of one of the
gunmen but did not release details. CNN reported that it was a
suicide note and indicated the two teen-agers acted alone. ``This
is the way we want to go out,'' the note said, according to CNN,
which cited unidentified sources.
</P>
<P>
   But sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said police were looking
into the possibility of additional suspects because of the amount
of ammunition and explosives strewn around the school and the
uncertainty about how the two gunmen, masked and dressed in long
black coats, carried it all inside.
</P>
<P>
   There is a ``very good chance there were more people involved,''
Davis said. &UR;  &LR; At least 30 bombs, some on timers and others hidden as
booby traps, were found after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb discovered in the kitchen was in a duffel bag and
included wiring, a two-gallon can of gasoline and an explosive
device fashioned from a 20-pound propane tank, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume that the gas, if the bottle was full, it would have
been devastating,'' said Sgt. Jim Parr, a Jefferson County
Sheriff's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty pounds of propane can create quite an extensive amount
of damage,'' Davis said. The bomb went undetected in the first
police sweep of the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how it got there. No one has identified them
carrying the tank into the kitchen,'' said District Attorney David
Thomas of the First Judicial District in Golden, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Police have questioned ``associates'' of the gunmen, interviewed
parents and are talking to dozens of the school's 1,900 students.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said investigators are questioning eight to 10 former
members of the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' who are no longer students at
Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said a third gunmen has not been ruled out, although
physical evidence of another shooter has yet to surface during the
search of the school. Some students who fled the school said they
saw a third gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they would collect damaged tiles and
furniture and take hundreds of photographs to conserve evidence in
case of future charges.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Marianos, of the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms, said the weapons used would be traced to determine how
the teens obtained them.
</P>
<P>
   At the Harris home, investigators found pipe bomb parts, the
personal diary of Harris and a video the teen-agers filmed at the
school last fall, in which they staged a mock attack on the school,
the Denver Post said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In Harris' school yearbook, the words ``dead, dying'' or
``save'' had been written over some of the pictures, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said Columbine will be closed indefinitely as
the investigation continues and the damage is assessed. Other
schools in the district reopened Thursday although heavy snow
delayed some openings. Security was tightened in the district.
</P>
<P>
   A plan was being formulated to have Columbine students finish
the school year at other schools, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23 people wounded in the attack, 14 people remained
hospitalized Thursday, three in critical condition and five in
serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   Families began making funeral arrangements as the 15 bodies _
most of them had lain in the school for 24 hours while police
searched the building _ were released by the coroner. About half
the bodies had been released by late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first to be buried will be Rachel Scott, 17, whose
service is set for Saturday. Scott's automobile, left in the school
parking lot, has become a gathering site for mourning teens.
</P>
<P>
   Another teen will be buried out of state on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The community has held several services and vigils since the
massacre. Hundreds of people, mostly teens, continued to stream
through a media staging area by the parking lot to leave flowers,
butterfly balloons, banners and notes for the victims' families and
the school.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-foot lattice wall was erected to hold bunches of flowers.
Teen-agers huddled to sing hymns, cry and pray.
</P>
<P>
   As the Denver suburb of 35,000 tried to make sense of the
tragedy, President Clinton traveled to a Virginia high school to
address the nation's students. In a meeting with students at T.C.
Williams High School in Alexandria, broadcast to schools elsewhere,
he said U.S. schools ``are still the safest place our kids can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the wrong reaction to the fact they were `dissed,' ''
he said of the gunmen. ``Look, everybody gets `dissed' some time in
life _ even the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of the two gunmen have described their families as
respectable, middle class and generally friendly. The boys, while
described as bright and typical teens by many who knew them, had
for some time shown a dark side to others. Students said they had
been belligerent, obsessed with violent computer games and had
threatened school athletes and others who teased them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
