u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DREAMLIFE-SPI &LR;      04-22 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DREAMLIFE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUTED TALENTS OF BOUCHEZ HARD TO FIND IN `THE DREAMLIFE OF
ANGELS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a few seasons since a newcomer has taken the European
critical establishment by the storm of Elodie Bouchez, the young
French star of ``The Dreamlife of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   She won the best actress prize at Cannes, the European Film
Awards' best actress and best newcomer awards, and the best actress
nod of Les Prix Lumieres - a near clean sweep of the major European
awards for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, exactly why her performance has captured the European
critics on such a grand and unanimous scale is not completely
obvious to me on the evidence of this film.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchez does have a melancholy charm, and the movie is
reasonably engrossing, with the look and feel of gritty
authenticity. But why it has been singled out for such lavish
praise is hard to figure.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchez plays Isa, a 20-year-old free spirit who, after some
time on the road, arrives in the northern city of Lille with
nothing but a backpack of possessions and an optimistic attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, she picks up a job as a seamstress in a sweatshop,
where she makes friends with another rebellious 20-year-old girl
named Marie (Natacha Regnier). Soon, they become friends and
roommates.
</P>
<P>
   Isa soon loses her job, and while vegging around Marie's
apartment one day, she finds the journal of its past occupant, a
young woman who is now in a brain-dead coma after a car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, Isa becomes obsessed with the accident victim,
reading her journal over and over again, and visiting her bedside
so often that the hospital staff assumes she's a relative.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she becomes increasingly drawn into the plight
of her best friend, Marie, who has fallen into her own obsessive
relationship: a masochistic backstreet affair with a wealthy young
man about town (Gregoire Colin).
</P>
<P>
   However, Isa is utterly helpless on both fronts. The comatose
woman doesn't even know of her existence and sinks further into
oblivion with every passing hour; and Marie's low self-esteem has
put her on a collision course with disaster.
</P>
<P>
   So Isa is more a passive observer of the action of the movie _
the voyeur, the audience point-of-view. Bouchez's acting task is to
communicate the character's growing concern and helplessness in the
face of two situations she can't possibly affect.
</P>
<P>
   As this plays out, Regnier has by far the showier part; the
script mostly requires Bouchez to just stand around looking worried
and sympathetic. And since she doesn't have a particularly
expressive face or demonstrative acting style, she doesn't make a
huge first impression.
</P>
<P>
   But she does somehow linger in the mind long after everything
else in this movie is forgotten. And she has that waiflike,
enigmatic quality that the French tend to find absolutely
irresistible. Whatever she's got, it's made this modest little
Gen-X drama a big hit in Europe and made Bouchez the hottest new
thing in French films.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamlife of Angels. Directed by Erick Zonca. Screenplay by
Zonca and Roger Bohbot. Cast: Elodie Bouchez, Natacha Regnier,
Gregoire Colin, Jo Prestia, Patrick Mercado. Sony Classics. 113
minutes. In French with English subtitles. Rated R for nudity and
sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
