<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM LIFTS DOW TO RECORD AS NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P SOAR
</P>
<P>
   IBM's strong profit report helped propel the stock market to
another big advance as large growth stocks, which had fallen out of
favor as perhaps too expensive just a couple of weeks ago,
continued to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The rally brought another record for the Dow Jones industrial
average, which rose 145.76 points, or 1.38 percent, to 10,727.18.
The Nasdaq composite index did even better, gaining 72.53 points,
or 2.91 percent, to 2,561.61, just 37 points shy of its all-time
high. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 22.7 points, or
1.7 percent, to 1,358.82, also a record.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN BACKS WIDER DOLLAR USE
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before a congressional committee, Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve chairman, and Lawrence H. Summers, the deputy
treasury secretary, presented a united openness to other countries
seeking to adopt the dollar as their national currency, but warned
that such a move should not replace sound monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL TO EXPAND TO THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it was planning a big move into the Internet services
business. The strategy is a striking departure for the maker of
Pentium chips that serve as the electronic brains of most personal
computers and reflects how far Intel is willing to go to grow.
</P>
<P>
   LAZARD SETTLES MUNICIPAL BOND CASE
</P>
<P>
   Lazard Freres &AMP; Co., the Wall Street investment bank, agreed to
pay $11 million to settle federal charges for inflating the prices
of government securities it sold to municipalities. The settlement
ends the firm's disastrous foray into municipal finance.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSICO EARNINGS BEAT FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico reported better-than-expected first-quarter earnings,
but the company's shares fell after its chief financial officer
said future earnings might be a little lower than analysts had been
led to believe by the company's chairman and chief executive, Roger
A. Enrico. Pepsico will spend $75 million to upgrade its computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Profits at Lucent Technologies, the phone-equipment maker,
Airtouch Communications, Bell Atlantic and GTE met or surpassed
Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said first-quarter earnings rose 14 percent, mostly
through cost cuts, but its shares fell because revenue did not
increase.
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA ACCUSED OF RACIAL BIAS
</P>
<P>
   A group of black employees filed a class-action lawsuit accusing
Coca-Cola of discriminating against African-Americans in pay,
promotions and performance evaluations. The suit contends that the
company pays its average black employee nearly $27,000 a year less
than its average white employee and limits black workers' chances
for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   CRACKDOWN ON WEB INVESTIGATORS
</P>
<P>
   The federal government began cracking down on the deceptive
practices of a proliferating number of private investigators who
advertise on the Internet that they can inexpensively provide
confidential details about bank accounts and telephone records.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT DECLINES 54 PERCENT AT RJR NABISCO
</P>
<P>
   In its final quarter as an international tobacco and food
company, RJR Nabisco Holdings reported that its first-quarter
earnings fell 54 percent because of costs to settle tobacco
litigation and declining cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   EXPORT GROWTH PLUNGES TO 3.5 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization said the rate of growth in world
merchandise exports fell to 3.5 percent last year _ only one-third
of its 1997 growth rate _ mainly because of the Asian economic
crisis. It warned that growth could slow further this year.
</P>
<P>
   GITIC CASE WORSE THAN EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   In another blow to foreign banks, a Chinese court said that it
expected to salvage only $783 million in assets from one of China's
largest and most troubled companies, Guangdong International Trust
and Investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
