<HEADER>
A9822 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOL-SCATES-LADN-(SLAN     04-22 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-SCATES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S SCATES SYNONYMOUS WITH VOLLEYBALL SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The phone rings in Al Scates' Tarzana home. He
picks up the receiver and answers, ``Volleyball.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs at his gaffe, but it's totally in character to anyone
who knows Scates.
</P>
<P>
   His teams have won 17 national titles and more than 900 matches
in his 37 years as UCLA's men's coach. Since men's volleyball
became an official NCAA sport in 1970, Scates has had 34 players
earn All-America honors, coached seven Olympic medalists, seven
Players of the Year and the biggest name in the game: Karch Kiraly.
</P>
<P>
   His success has been so unusual in the sport that Scates was
inducted into the Volleyball Hall of Fame in Holyoke, Mass., even
though inductees usually have to have been retired for five years
to be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's dominance of the men's college game has been so
consistent that there hasn't been a player who spent four years in
the Bruins program who hasn't won at least one
national-championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   But this season has tested even Scates' mettle. The 20-6 Bruins
have suffered through more injuries and illnesses than any in
recent memory. This season, UCLA lost four straight matches _
including one to UC Irvine, which had never beaten UCLA _ for the
first time ever. Brigham Young beat it 15-0 in a game, the first
time in six years that the Bruins had been skunked.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mountain Pacific Sports Federation tournament begins
Saturday, UCLA will be on the road. Scates was so sure the Bruins
would play at home, he listed the Wooden Center as the match site
on the team schedule. Instead, they're at Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   And to top it off, Scates was reprimanded by the conference for
comments he made about the officiating on the Bruins' trip to
Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the 59-year-old coach, who impressed John Wooden with
his meticulous practices, isn't changing his tune. Always
optimistic, Scates maintains his team is on track to win another
national championship when the Final Four comes to Pauley Pavilion
on May 6 and 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``He envisions success and so do his teams,'' said Denny Cline,
who played for Scates from 1974-76 and won NCAA titles each year,
then assisted Scates from 1977-84 and won five more titles. ``It's
a mind-set. You have to win the last games. You're used to doing
things that way . . . and he has a very good plan.''
</P>
<P>
   One his players always believe in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in his mind,'' junior opposite hitter Ed
Ratledge said. ``He doesn't give us a lot of lame pep talks. He
knows confident athletes play better. By not cutting us down, he
instills confidence in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Scates knows who and what he seeks, so much so that when it
comes to choosing players, he doesn't have to recruit. He hasn't
seen a future Bruin play since Tom Stillwell arrived six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he never personally scouted Kiraly, who went on to win
three Olympic gold medals. Kiraly wrote in his autobiography, ``The
Sand Man,'' he drove 60 miles from Santa Barbara to meet Scates
supposedly halfway, while the coach rode his bicycle two miles
(Scates said it was 10 miles, and he had to get on the freeway.)
</P>
<P>
   Cline once received a letter from Scates. It began, ``Dear
Dan.''
</P>
<P>
   Scates' assistant coaches _ all of whom have played for him _
know the kind of player he wants: one who comes from a winning
program, is self-motivated and knows how to win, will work hard in
practice and hates losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're used to winning,'' Scates said. ``They know what it
takes to win. I don't want to retrain someone. It's an advantage to
get competitive players who are used to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   A winning attitude also means someone who plays 100 percent all
the time, which is why Scates makes practices tougher than matches.
If you don't practice well, you don't play. And if you continue to
fare poorly, you'll drop from the main practice court to the
secondary court behind the infamous Blue Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   The need for toughness began in Scates' childhood. His father,
Ed, never wanted his son to run from a fight, so he paid kids to
come to his garage and box little Allen. When Al beat one kid, a
bigger one awaited next time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong survive in our program,'' Scates said. ``A weaker
competitor will come and say, `If you tell me I'm a starter, I'll
play better.' The real competitor never asks. He just gets
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Every drill, pitting the first team against the second team, has
a winner and loser. Scates and his assistants often rig the match
with a bad call so the second team wins, thus infuriating the
starters but preparing them for match-like conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Ratledge transferred from Long Beach State and immediately
became impressed that Scates never scheduled three-hour practices
the day before a match. Nor does he ever insult or speak
condescendingly to his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people will tell you it's hard work that wins,''
Ratledge said. ``Al Scates is a man who knows how hard to work and
when.''
</P>
<P>
   Even John Wooden was impressed. Then again, Wooden always liked
volleyball and sometimes stopped his practices when they weren't
going well and let his teams play volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at Al's ability and his teaching,'' Wooden said.
``He was one of the premier teachers. He ran a clean practice, well
organized and covered all the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect,'' Wooden said. ``His record speaks for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   In matches, the object is to win, but it's OK to lose as long as
you beat a team the last time you play.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Last season, UCLA lost the MPSF championship to
Pepperdine but beat the Waves in the NCAA final.
</P>
<P>
   Scates knew UCLA would make the Final Four regardless of the
outcome. So he tried various lineups and plays, all the while
keeping his detailed statistics. To the untrained eye, the stats
resemble hieroglyphics. To Scates, they are a system that shows
what a UCLA player or what an opposing player did in a particular
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   He also videotapes every match and carefully breaks down every
play. The tape and stats showed Scates that during one rotation,
Pepperdine never set the middle, so he instructed his middles to
slide outside and block.
</P>
<P>
   Result: Pepperdine never scored a point on that rotation and
UCLA won its 17th national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``What coach Scates has is a system of analysis that helps train
the players for the next time,'' Cline said. ``He is a master of
coming up with ways to minimize his (team's) weaknesses and
maximizing ways to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratledge said his Long Beach coaches told their teams they're
every bit as good as UCLA, but Ratledge couldn't understand how
UCLA always won.
</P>
<P>
   He knows now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew our tendencies better than we knew theirs,'' he
said. ``They scouted us better. He's a master of scouting.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of how Scates has won so much _ 966 matches, more
than any other men's or women's volleyball coach; why he has been
named the sport's coach of the year five times.
</P>
<P>
   And why he continues to believe that in spite of this season's
hardships, a national championship is possible in spite of having
to play at Hawaii and then at BYU.
</P>
<P>
   Scates' former players understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 30 years of coaching, you believe it,'' said Charlie
Jackson, who finished his career in 1998. ``You think, `He knows so
much more than I do.' If he says it with confidence, you don't
challenge it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-AMY-FISHER-NYT &LR;      04-22 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AMY-FISHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEARFUL AMY FISHER FACES VICTIM IN COURT AND APOLOGIZES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ With tears in her eyes, Amy Fisher apologized
Thursday to Mary Jo Buttafuoco for shooting her in the face seven
years ago when she was having an affair with Mrs. Buttafuoco's
husband, Joey.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Buttafuoco, who still has the bullet lodged in her neck and
suffers from lingering nerve damage, said she accepted the apology
and urged the judge to release Ms. Fisher from prison so she could
start a new life. The judge accepted her request and reduced Ms.
Fisher's sentence, making her eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has shown true remorse and sorrow for what she did to
me,'' Mrs. Buttafuoco, 44, told the court. She then turned to Amy
and said, ``You are being given a second chance in life, and I pray
you will take it and make something positive out of all this
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher was 17 when she shot Buttafuoco on May 16, 1992. She
initially claimed that Buttafuoco had urged her to kill his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom proceeding Thursday paved the way for Ms. Fisher
to be released on parole soon.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the courtroom Thursday morning was Buttafuoco, 43,
an auto body repairman. He and his wife have since moved their
family to California, where Buttafuoco has worked as an actor and
radio talk shot host. Although Buttafuoco had denied having a
sexual relationship with Ms. Fisher, he did plead guilty to
statutory rape in October 1993 and served six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Also absent Thursday morning was Eric W. Naiburg, the lawyer who
first represented Ms. Fisher and urged her to plead guilty in
October 1992. Ms. Fisher has charged that Naiburg lied to her about
the consequences of her plea, promising her that she would be
released from prison in in three and a half years. Ms. Fisher also
has charged him with having a sexual relationship with her when he
was representing her.
</P>
<P>
   Naiburg again Thursday denied the charges and limited his
comments to Thursday morning's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy for Ms. Fisher,'' he said. ``Obviously the work
I did on her behalf has borne fruit. If Mary Jo can forgive Amy for
shooting her, and Joey for inspiring the shooting, I too can be
forgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   The somber mood of Thursday morning's court proceedings was
broken only briefly after Fred Klein, an assistant Suffolk County
district attorney, attempted to explain to the court why he was
recommending a shorter sentence for Ms. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said several factors were taken into consideration,
including the fact that `` Buttafuoco raped Amy when she was 16
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Buttafuoco jumped to her feet and shouted: ``Stop it, Fred.
Look at me when you say that Fred, you son of a bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Buttafuoco was restrained by her lawyer, Dominick A.
Barbara, who told Nassau County Court Judge Ira H. Wexner,
``Obviously there are a number of very heated and unreconciled
issues here today.''
</P>
<P>
   The parole board is scheduled to meet on May 3 at the Albion
Correctional Facility in upstate New York, where Ms. Fisher has
spent most of her time in prison. If they hear her case at that
meeting, she could be released later that week, said a board
spokesman, Thomas Grant. Barket said he hoped that Ms. Fisher, who
was still in the Nassau County jail, would be returned to Albion in
time for the hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
