<SLUG> BC-FILM-TIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PUSHING TIN' FAILS AS A COMEDY AND A THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   English director Mike Newell has an uncanny knack for producing
art house films with a wide audience appeal _ a list that includes
``Dance With a Stranger,'' ``Enchanted April,'' ``Into the West,''
and ``Four Weddings and a Funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   And his only Hollywood film of the '90s, the mafia drama
``Donnie Brasco,'' was a near slam-dunk that worked as a breathless
gangster saga, a funny slice of lower-middle-class life and a
perfect star vehicle for Johnny Depp and Al Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   But he definitely has his off days. His follow-up to that
critical success, a clumsy comedy-drama called ``Pushing Tin,'' is
a dismal misfire _ almost as excruciating in its own way as
Newell's career nadir, ``An Awfully Big Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Billed as a thriller about overstressed air traffic controllers,
it's almost devoid of aeronautical excitement, and its concerns are
so juvenile it often seems to have the macho sensibility of a '60s
biker movie.
</P>
<P>
   The hero is Nick Falzone (John Cusack), a hotshot controller who
works with an Animal House of misfits who ``push tin'' around the
overcrowded, unfriendly skies above Newark, N.J., in a single
viewless, claustrophobic room.
</P>
<P>
   One day, a new maverick controller, Russell (Billy Bob Thornton,
looking as scruffy and antisocial as he did in ``Chopper Chicks in
Zombietown''), arrives on the scene riding a big motorcycle. He and
Nick take an instant dislike for one another.
</P>
<P>
   When Nick beds Russell's alcoholic wife (Angelina Jolie),
Russell makes overtures toward Nick's wife (Cate Blanchett), and
pretty soon the guys are in such a war of one-upmanship that _ like
kids playing a computer game _ they're competing to see who can
squeeze the most planes in the narrowest air space.
</P>
<P>
   The point, of course, is that the pressure of the air traffic
controllers' jobs is so heavy that it tends to drive them nuts, and
endangers all our lives. That point is made well in one or two
chilling scenes. But most of the rest of the movie is a bore. The
testosterone battle between these two geeks _ racing each other on
the freeway, seducing each other's wives, slugging it out in the
control room _ makes them seem so repulsively adolescent you just
want to get away from them.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it fail as a compelling character study, it's
never funny enough to work as a comedy, or gripping enough to work
as a thriller. Is there anything less exciting than watching a
character watch a video screen for endless amounts of screen time?
Does anyone really want to see a disaster epic without a disaster
in it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin'' does have one saving grace, however. As Nick's
long-suffering wife, Blanchett gives the movie some badly needed
charisma, and its one point of sympathy _ even nobility. If there
were any lingering doubt after ``Elizabeth,'' her big
change-of-pace role as a cheated-upon Jersey housewife in this
otherwise empty vessel is proof positive. The woman is a movie
star.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing Tin. Directed by Mike Newell. Screenplay by Glen Charles
and Les Charles, from an article by Darcy Frey. Cast: John Cusack,
Billy Bob Thornton, Cate Blanchett, Angelina Jolie, Jake Weber. 124
minutes. Rated R for language and brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
