<SLUG> BC-BBC-BIG-12-BASEBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONS HEAT UP AS RACE FOR BIG 12 TITLE ESCALATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Baylor's darkest hour in ... oh, a couple of months. But
Bears coach Steve Smith was sitting tall in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the first-base line reviewing for the media the
sequences that led to Baylor's first back-to-back losses since the
season's opening week, Smith was being loudly heckled by a Texas
A&AMP;M fan, who had an appreciation for a personally abusive phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Smith _ a former A&AMP;M assistant _ turned toward his
admirer and said, ``Suppose you just try to /act'' like you've got
some class and sit down and shut up?''
</P>
<P>
   End of heckling.
</P>
<P>
   But with four nationally ranked Texas teams rolling down the
stretch in the Big 12's final weeks, emotions are beginning to heat
up.
</P>
<P>
   At Disch-Falk Field in Austin, Texas Tech shortstop Lance
Woodcock had to be restrained from climbing into the stands after a
Texas fan, who was involved in an altercation with Woodcock's
father.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Woodcock had unknowingly seated himself amid ``The
Wild Bunch,'' a charming knot of Texas fanatics whose heckling
techniques _ aimed at Woodcock in this case _ are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, order was restored, one individual was ejected and
the 10th-ranked Red Raiders (35-10, 15-5) won two of three in a
hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the battle between A&AMP;M (35-10, 16-4) and Baylor
(37-9, 16-5) was carried out in the style of a Super Regional.
</P>
<P>
   For the series opener in Waco, each team put an All-American on
the mound _ Jason Jennings (9-0) for the Bears against Casey Fossom
(7-4) for the Aggies. Jennings threw a tough, 147-pitch complete
game while Fossom struggled as the Bears won, 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   The series then moved to College Station, where nearly 20,000
fans perched in and around Olsen Field for the final two games. The
Aggies captured two dramatic one-run victories, as catcher Shawn
Schumacher hit a two-run homer in the eighth to win the first and a
two-run single in the ninth to win the second.
</P>
<P>
   But the soft-spoken Schumacher also rankled Smith with a remark
that the first win had ``broken Baylor's bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   After the series final, Smith retorted: ``Our bubble isn't burst
by any stretch of the imagination. We came in here against a
nationally ranked team in a tough environment and lost two games in
the last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the way this team battled, and I still like our
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   So does A&AMP;M's Mark Johnson, whose first-place Aggies are the
third-ranked team in the nation, with Baylor sitting at seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great team,'' Johnson said, ``and they've got a
better-looking schedule from here on out than the rest of us. This
isn't over.''
</P>
<P>
   So this weekend, the Bears will try to regroup with three at
home against struggling Oklahoma (21-21, 6-12); A&AMP;M will play host
to Kansas (10-30, 4-20). Tech will be on the road at Kansas State
(16-21, 5-13); No. 24 Texas (29-17, 13-8) will visit Iowa State
(14-25, 1-17).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Western Athletic Conference leader Rice became the
first Texas team to reach 40 victories (40-8, 18-3) and is ranked
second in the nation. The Owls hold a half-game lead over TCU
(26-17, 17-3), which lost to Texas with more than 14,000 in
attendance at The Ballpark in Arlington on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both are on the road this weekend, with the Owls in Hawaii and
TCU visiting Nevada-Las Vegas.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
