<HEADLINE>
TROJANS LOSING NUMBERS GAME AT RECEIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's never hard to notice USC wide receiver R. Jay
Soward, but it's become almost impossible to ignore the senior in
spring practices this week after injuries and academic problems
have decimated the Trojans' receiving corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken most of the snaps,'' Soward said. ``Really, I like
it. It's more of an opportunity to get involved in the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward and senior Windrell Hayes are the only receivers of note
remaining in spring practice after junior Troy Garner tore knee
ligaments and senior Quincy Woods became academically ineligible.
Junior Stan Guyness has also missed spring practice after tearing
knee ligaments in November.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries and lack of depth mean three incoming freshmen _
Marcell Allmond of St. Paul, Kareem Kelly of Long Beach Poly and
Steve Stevenson of Charter Oak _ will probably play prominent roles
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, you'd like to redshirt one or two of them, but you
can't think that at the start,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``We're going to find ways to use them. We're going to tell them,
`Go play. Get in there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One thing to remember with Kelly: He needs to get a qualifying
score on his Scholastic Assessment Test.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is evaluating how USC should award its 85 scholarships
to avoid future shortages at certain positions. One problem was the
Trojans had five kickers on scholarship when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not well distributed,'' Hackett said. ``We'll have
18 linemen on scholarship next year. That's what we should have.
We'll only have (three) kickers on scholarship next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also are trying to add walk-ons. About eight players
have decided to walk on next season, and Hackett would like to get
about 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   __ One more scrimmage: With only one day of spring practice
remaining, USC will hold its final scrimmage today, the Trojans'
third game simulation in the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a contrast from last spring, when USC held only one
official scrimmage, but Hackett has warmed to the idea of extra
scrimmages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go full blast,'' Hackett said. ``I'm going to
scrimmage as many young guys as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Free safety Darnell Lacy, defensive lineman Jason Steen and
fullback Chad Pierson are expected to participate in the scrimmage
after sitting out Thursday's practice to concentrate on classe.
Tight end Antoine Harris, who missed Tuesday's practice to study,
returned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking for time: Hackett said senior Donta Kendrick has
emerged as the most improved lineman of spring practice. His
presence could shake up the look of the line. Already, right guard
Travis Claridge has spent considerable time at right tackle, but
Hackett said it is due to junior tackle Matt Welch being out with
shoulder injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Kendrick can play guard or tackle.
</P>
<P>
   __ Big recruit: Among the recruits at Thursday's practice was
highly regarded offensive lineman Paul Mociler of St. John Bosco.
Mociler is considering USC and Notre Dame, among other schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
