<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DEVILS MUST DOUSE THE TORCH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Just call him the Torch now.
</P>
<P>
   After Jaromir Jagr scored the overtime goal that momentarily
silenced Wayne Gretzky's going-away party last Sunday at Madison
Square Garden, the Great One talked about how ``maybe it was
fitting that the best young player in the game'' scored that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always talks about passing torches and all that
stuff; Jaromir caught it,'' Gretzky said. ``That's what I told him
after the game. I said, `You caught it.'''
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday night the Pittsburgh Penguins' right wing, who led
the NHL in scoring for the third time during the recent season,
carried that torch into the opening round of the Stanley Cup
playoffs against the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very nice Wayne said that,'' Jagr was saying before the
game. ``But you've got to prove it in the playoffs. And I want to
prove he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Devils are to survive the first round for the first time
in three years, they must find a way to douse the Torch. Out of
Kladno in the Czech Republic, he is 27, a rugged 6 feet 2 inches
and 230 pounds, his mane of wavy black hair flying from under the
back of his Penguins helmet.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to be voted the Hart Trophy as the NHL's most
valuable player. He has already scored a career total of 345 goals
during his nine seasons and 50 more in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he plays within the team concept,'' said Robbie
Ftorek, the Devils' coach, ``that's what makes him the player he
is. You try to keep him on the outside and you don't want your
players in the penalty box.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagr scored 44 goals this season, but he led the NHL with 83
assists. He also led the NHL with 34 power-play assists. When
opponents swarmed to stop him during a power play, he wisely was
content to set up others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of anyone in hockey that can dominate an offense
like he does,'' said Scott Stevens, the Devils' defenseman and
captain. ``His teammates feed off him. You want to make him pass
the puck. You just want to control him.''
</P>
<P>
   During the season, the Devils controlled him. Of the Penguins'
13 goals against the Devils during the season, Jagr was involved in
eight (three goals, five assists), but the Devils won four of those
five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be in his face,'' Stevens said, ``but you've got
to be smart. He loves you to come at him. When you do, he braces,
then he rolls off and spins away. So you've got to play between him
and the goal. And you want to try to make him pass the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to hit him, do it off the boards, not in the
open. You want to keep him on his backhand. You would rather have
him go wide than have him cut to the middle because he's really
fast. But he'll always try to beat you to the middle and get you
one-on-one.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Devils won the Stanley Cup in 1995, Stevens' primary
assignment in the Eastern Conference finals was to control the
Flyers' Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jagr is different,'' Stevens said. ``Lindros was more dump the
puck and chase it. Jagr likes to control the puck more than Lindros
does.''
</P>
<P>
   During the season Jagr, with his 127 points, was involved in a
remarkable 53 percent of the Penguins' 242 goals. But of their 13
goals against the Devils, his involvement in eight was an even
higher ratio, 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has so many tools in his bag,'' Devils goaltender Martin
Brodeur said. ``Speed. Good shot. The way he sees the ice. You've
got to know where he is all the time. If not, he'll bury you.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Devils, center Petr Sykora, their leading scorer this
season, has been aware of Jagr the longest.
</P>
<P>
   When Jagr was named to the Czech national team at age 16, Sykora
was an 11-year-old in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew Jaromir was going to be great,'' Sykora said.
``And now he's the most popular player in the Czech Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more popular than Dominik Hasek, the Buffalo Sabres'
goaltender whose acrobatics sparked the Czech Republic to the
Olympic gold medal in Nagano, Japan, early last year?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Jagr is more popular there than Hasek,'' Sykora said.
``Because of Jagr's scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Even better, Jaromir Jagr is now carrying the torch that he
caught from Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
