<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE'S NUMBERS POINT TO ANOTHER RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCONNELL  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For baseball fans, the question is: Can he do it
again?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the real question should be: When will he do it again?
</P>
<P>
   When you crunch Mark McGwire's numbers like he's been crunching
the baseball, you realize his 70-home run season last year was no
fluke. And when you talk to those in baseball who know him best,
there's little question McGwire can equal or break his own record.
It depends on one thing _ his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stays healthy, there's no reason why he can't continue
to hit 60-70 home runs a year for the next three or four years,''
said Rod Dedeaux, who coached McGwire at USC. ``He's always had the
ability to do it. What he has now is the maturity to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Scolinos and Art Mazmanian, who along with Dedeaux coached
McGwire on the 1984 USA Olympic team, agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always had the power, but now he's really learned the
strike zone,'' said Scolinos, the former coach at Cal Poly Pomona.
``When we had him on the Olympic team, he had a tendency to be a
wild swinger, to go into slumps, to try to pull everything and hit
every ball 500 feet. When you see him today, he's very disciplined
at the plate. He's learned that all he has to do is hit the ball
and the home runs will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark has always had the same amazing ability to hit the ball a
long, long way,'' said Mt. San Antonio College coach Mazmanian.
``He made a believer out of me when he was on the Olympic team. One
night in Memphis, he switched from an aluminum bat to a wooden one
and still hit three balls up against the fence in left-center
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got tremendous bat speed, which is the key to being a
great hitter. He generates tremendous energy with his swing, which
you know if you have ever stood around the batting cage and watched
him hit. When you put those things together, you understand why he
hits so many home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's career statistics leave little doubt he can match _
and surpass _ the 70-home run barrier.
</P>
<P>
   He's the only hitter in major-league history with three
consecutive 50-plus home run seasons. The 128 home runs he hit in
1997 and 1998 combined are the best two-season total in history
(Babe Ruth is next, at 114). McGwire's home run per-at bat ratio is
the best in history.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most amazingly, he figures to become the only man in
history to surpass the 400 career home run record in one season and
the 500 barrier the next. He needs 38 more homers this year to
reach 500.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, McGwire has benefited from playing in an era when
pitching is diluted, primarily because of expansion. As a rookie
with the Oakland Athletics in 1987, he was on a 70-home run pace
before winding up with 49 (which is itself a record for rookies).
This was accomplished while playing in the spacious Oakland
Coliseum and at a time when there were only 26 major-league teams.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he had almost exactly the same number of plate
appearances as in 1998, and he walked 71 times. Last year, he
walked 162 times. As his walk totals have increased, so have the
frequency of his home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 to 1998, he played in 545 games and hit 219 home runs,
which means he homered in 40 percent of his games. That's a
60-homer-per-season pace.
</P>
<P>
   Which means if you have tickets to all three Cardinals-Dodgers
games this weekend, odds are you will see McGwire hit at least one
home run. That is, if the hamstring injury that has plagued him the
last couple of games doesn't keep him out of the
lineup. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
