<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGNESS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: A TRUCE IN TURF WARS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)   (jw) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMELIA ISLAND , Fla. _ The advertising industry has long been
enamored of hyperbole in the service of size. So it was appropriate
that the opening general session here Thursday of the 81st annual
meeting of the American Association of Advertising Agencies was all
about bigness: a big client, a big agency company and big news
about a big contentious issue.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a dispute between the agency association, known as
the Four A's, and its counterpart representing big marketer
clients, the Association of National Advertisers. A surprise
decision by the advertiser association last fall to invite agencies
to join its group has roiled relations between the two trade
organizations, particularly because the move was made after little
or no consultation with officials of the Four A's.
</P>
<P>
   But during a break in the general session Thursday, John Sarsen
Jr., president and chief executive of the advertiser association,
disclosed that he had suspended the invitations pending a study,
``jointly funded and managed'' by both organizations, of ways that
advertisers and agencies could cooperate ``to help marketers build
their brands and build their businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The move seems to be a big retreat by the advertiser
association, whose decision last fall was attacked by several
prominent agency executives who used inflammatory terms like
``sabotage'' and ``power grab.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarsen, of course, does not agree.
</P>
<P>
   Many agency executives considered the invitations ``an
affirmation of their importance to advertisers,'' Sarsen said, and
``we had a whole bunch of agencies say they wanted to be members.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did it,'' he said, ``we assumed that as most
advertisers are members of multiple associations,'' belonging to
more than one organization ``would not have a negative impact'' on
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in some cases, other agencies said it was an either-or
situation,'' Sarsen added. ``We don't want to do anything that
would negatively impact agencies, so on reflection we said why
don't we jointly look at ways the two organizations can work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The two associations will hire a consultant who will study the
issues and make recommendations. Consultants are being interviewed,
Sarsen said, and the advertiser association hopes the study can be
completed before its next annual meeting, which is scheduled for
Oct. 9 to 13.
</P>
<P>
   O. Burtch Drake, president and chief executive of the Four A's,
who was especially vociferous in his opposition to the invitations,
declared his satisfaction at this turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's not to like about it?'' he asked. ``Having a neutral
party take a look at the two organizations is very worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll still say I don't think they had really thought it
through,'' Drake said, referring to the officials of the advertiser
association. ``To use a marketing analogy, it was like announcing a
new product and not being ready to ship it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another outspoken opponent of the invitations also pronounced
himself pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sensible approach to have someone from outside
both organizations looking at both organizations,'' said Patrick
McGrath, president and chief executive at Jordan McGrath Case &AMP;
Partners/Euro RSCG in New York, part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide
unit of Havas Advertising, ``to see how to help the ANA accomplish
what it set out to do _ enhance our skills at branding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be ways for the two organizations to bring more
efficiency and creativity to solving problems we have together,''
he added, such as difficulties with the federal government or
unions.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, the 1998-99 chairman of the Four A's, which continues
to meet Saturday, declined to characterize the shift by the
advertiser association as a victory for his association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken off our boxing gloves,'' he said, ``and now we're
going to try to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath's successor for 1999-2000 at the helm of the Four A's,
Shelly Lazarus, termed the hiring of the consultants as ``the exact
right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's valuable to have a third party with an objective view
come in and give us suggestions,'' said Ms. Lazarus, who is
chairwoman and chief executive at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide in New
York, part of WPP Group PLC Last fall, Ms. Lazarus said she
believed that agency membership in the advertiser association was
worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Geier Jr., chairman and chief executive of the
Interpublic Group of Cos. in New York, which owns agencies like
Lowe Group and McCann-Erickson World Group, said, ``Maybe we'll
find ways to work together and maybe not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, having a consultant helping figure it out is by
far the best way to go,'' he added. ``It's a victory for both of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Geier, whose agency company is the world's biggest, with
estimated billings of $37.7 billion, addressed the general session
in a rare public speaking appearance. He focused his speech on the
new media, urging Madison Avenue to go beyond using the new
technology and ``help define its potential and give it a purpose
and a place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk personally, tell stories, spin dreams,'' he added.
``Inform and entertain. Create unique new forms of communication.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Geier said, agencies must remember what he
called Geier's Law: ``People don't change anything like as fast as
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The theorists may like revolutions,'' he added. ``Consumers
prefer evolutions. And guess who's making the final call?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the big client at the general session was John Pepper
Jr., chairman of the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., the world's biggest
advertiser. He drew the biggest applause of the day with
exhortations to strengthen the relationships between agencies and
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies must ``create the kind of great advertising campaigns
that create great global leadership brands'' and ``serve consumers
extraordinarily well,'' Pepper declared.
</P>
<P>
   And clients must help agencies create ``more great
advertising,'' by helping them ``to overcome fear,'' he added,
``the greatest inhibitor to relationships that nurture great
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be a mind-set of great expectations,'' Pepper said.
``Shoot for the moon or reach for the stars, whatever your galactic
preference happens to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
