<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIANS RAISE $2 BILLION IN SALE OF NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With strong demand from investors, Brazil sold $2 billion of
five-year notes Thursday, finishing the first leg of a bond sale
that could hit $3 billion, three times the original size.
</P>
<P>
   The second leg of the sale comes Friday, when Brazil decides how
many more notes to sell in exchange for existing Brazilian Brady
bonds, which were created as part of the debt reduction deals done
when bankers restructured their bank loans with Latin American
countries in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Some corporate bond traders said Thursday afternoon that the
swap was rumored to total $1 billion. The rumor was based, in part,
on a report from Brazil by Bloomberg News Thursday morning, quoting
an executive for one of the underwriters, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, that the sale, originally set at $1 billion, could be
increased to $3 billion. The other underwriter is Salomon Smith
Barney, a unit of Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil made no comment on the size of the exchange in two news
releases Thursday. It remained unclear how attractive a swap of
Brady bonds would be because the securities eligible for the swap
had a higher yield than the new notes.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady bonds, however, are more complicated and harder to
trade. The swap would be based on the yield of the $2 billion of
notes sold Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing just a $1 billion sale last week was probably the
best way for Brazil to test its ability to return to the capital
markets without setting itself up for an embarrassment. And
increasing the size of a deal always looks good.
</P>
<P>
   The sale has been closely watched because it comes just three
months after Brazil devalued its currency, the real, and was faced
with the prospect of rising interest rates, rising inflation and a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Its success could open the door to global bond markets for
Brazilian corporate borrowers while giving another boost to
emerging markets in general. Already this year, stock and bond
markets in emerging economies have been among the best performers.
This deal follows the return to the market of the Korean
Development Bank last week.
</P>
<P>
   The quick turnaround in Brazil has surprised many investors. It
also left many of them without what they may normally have thought
was the right amount of exposure to Brazil. This fact helped
heighten demand.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors wanted a premium for buying Brazil again.
Brazil apparently was willing to give one.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year notes, maturing in 2004, were priced to yield
11.88 percent, 6.75 percentage points over the yield on the
five-year United States Treasury note. That is just above the yield
of about 11.82 percent now on Brazil's outstanding note that
matures in 2008. A shorter maturity would normally yield less. The
coupon on the note is 11.625 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving a little extra is a smart way to bring investors
back,'' said Barbara Kenworthy, portfolio manager at Prudential
Mutual Funds. She said that she bought a ``small position'' for her
bond funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
