<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JUDGE-3TAKES-NYT &LR;      04-22 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDGE-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SYSTEM WITH FEW STANDARDS PUT THE HOLYFIELD JUDGE AT RINGSIDE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Dec. 12, Eugenia Williams was at ringside in Atlantic City,
N.J., to judge a lightweight rematch bout between Arturo Gatti and
Ivan Robinson. The first fight between the highly regarded boxers
had gone 10 bruising rounds, with Robinson gaining a split
decision, and the rematch was just as brutal. Williams scored it
97-92 for Robinson in what was a unanimous decision for the
promising Philadelphian.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' verdict, on its face, struck most observers as
perfectly acceptable, and Gatti himself did not object to it. Now,
however, Gatti's handlers and others have come to question whether
Williams should ever have been in position to judge the fight in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, it turns out, was a friend of Williams and her
daughter. Williams said in a recent interview that she had come to
know and befriend Robinson during his amateur boxing career. Her
daughter went to high school with Robinson, and the daughter and
Robinson were regularly in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, though, did not inform anyone involved in the fight _
not the New Jersey State Athletic Commission or the promoter or the
fighters _ that she and her daughter were friends of Robinson. She
did not have to, and, as she notes, nobody ever asked her to
declare any possible conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known that, I would have definitely asked her to be
changed,'' Pat Lynch, Gatti's manager, said of the Williams family
friendship with Robinson. ``As a professional, she should have
stepped aside anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' involvement in the Gatti-Robinson fight is not the
only time her professionalism has come under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Her most publicly debated performance as a boxing judge came
March 13 in the Evander Holyfield bout with Lennox Lewis at Madison
Square Garden. Williams scored the fight for Holyfield, making
possible the much-disputed draw. Her scoring, as well as that of
the judge who ruled the fight even, drew howls of outrage and cries
of ``fix'' from fans. It also prompted a criminal investigation by
New York State prosecutors in Manhattan and a pledge of reform by
officials in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   How Williams, a 48-year-old municipal accounts clerk in Atlantic
City, came to be at ringside in the biggest heavyweight fight in
New York in decades represents for many followers of boxing yet one
more example of how flawed the sport is, and how badly it needs
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks before Williams earned the biggest payday of her
career as a judge _ $5,150 for the Holyfield fight _ she had filed
for bankruptcy, declaring herself overwhelmed by debts on more than
a dozen credit cards. Investigators looking into the circumstances
of the Holyfield fight believe her financial distress should have
barred her from serving as a judge. But the bankruptcy was never
disclosed, nor was it required to be disclosed by state officials.
Indeed, in New York and New Jersey, the only thing preventing a
judge from participating in a major prizefight is a pending felony
charge or a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Williams did not earn the right to work the fight because of
stellar credentials. No organization or sanctioning body in the
United States ranks judges. Williams, whose New Jersey license to
judge is honored by most states, was at ringside at the Garden
because she had been selected by Bob Lee, the president of the
International Boxing Federation, one of the organizations that was
behind the fight and whose heavyweight crown is held by Holyfield.
Lee is a former deputy commissioner of boxing in New Jersey, having
left that office in 1984 after investigators determined that the
commission was rife with conflicts of interest among its officials.
The IBF is currently under investigation by a federal grand jury in
Newark into possible improprieties in its ranking of boxers.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was paid for her work in the Holyfield bout by the
fight's promoters on a check that was issued by Don King
Productions. Many of those who advocate boxing reform have long
considered the paying of judges by promoters as potentially
dangerous. The concern is that judges might feel pressure to score
a fight in a way that serves the promoter's long-term financial
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to a baseball game and the umpire makes a bad
call, people never presume that the game is fixed,'' said Eliot L.
Spitzer, the New York State attorney general who has ordered an
investigation into how the New York State Athletic Commission deals
with boxing judges. ``But in boxing, whenever there is a
questionable decision, we presume, reflexively, a fix. That says
something about the lack of integrity in the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Of judges working prizefights, Spitzer said, ``We know virtually
nothing about these judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the sport say that state boxing commissions have
been reluctant to enforce tough standards for fear of losing
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promoters live in a different ethical world and they're not
going to acquiesce to strict regulatory rules,'' said James J.
Morley, executive director of the New Jersey Commission of
Investigation, who led an examination of boxing in the state in
1984. ``They'll just take the fights somewhere else where they can
do what they like.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment of her controversial decision, Williams has
emphatically denied that the decision was influenced in any way by
her relationship with members in the IBF, the fight's promoters or
anybody else. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
