<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAMS-ELWHA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEITHER SIDE BUDGES ON REMOVAL OF WASHINGTON'S ELWHA DAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The likelihood of a dam being removed on the Elwha
River seemed to diminish significantly Thursday when Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt and Sen. Slade Gorton made it clear there
is no room for compromise between them.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have long pushed to remove the two dams on the
Olympic Peninsula's Elwha River in an effort to restore salmon
runs. Last year, all interests, including the city of Port Angeles,
elected officials from both parties and the dams' private owner
agreed to removal.
</P>
<P>
   But funding fell through when Gorton, R-Wash., insisted that a
provision be included stating that no dam on the Columbia or Snake
rivers could be removed without congressional permission.
Environmentalists are pushing to breach four federal dams on the
lower Snake River in an effort to restore salmon runs, but they
have won no support from elected officials of either political
party.
</P>
<P>
   Current law requires congressional approval for the removal of
federal dams, and after a testy hearing before Gorton's
subcommittee, Babbitt told reporters that he would never agree to
also grant Congress veto power over the removal of privately owned
dams. That is the price Gorton is demanding before he will agree to
grant federal money for the acquisition and removal of the Elwha
River dams.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt and Gorton have dug in their heels as each nears the end
of his term. Babbitt is expected to leave office by January 2001,
when President Clinton's second term ends, and Gorton must win
re-election if he is to avoid leaving at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The two have conflicting desires in their remaining months.
Babbitt has made the restoration of free-flowing rivers a goal of
his tenure, while Gorton has made defending the dams on the Snake
and Columbia a central element of his re-election campaign
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to be able to reach any agreement that will allow
us to go forward on the Elwha... and provide a degree of protection
and public consent with respect to major decisions on the Columbia
and Snake rivers?'' Gorton asked Babbitt Thursday, during a hearing
before the Senate Interior Appropriations Subcommittee which Gorton
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator, I've given this a lot of thought since... last year,
and I'm not prepared to support or advocate a linkage,'' Babbitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt has argued that Congress already has the right to
approve or reject the removal of federal dams, but that private
parties should be able to negotiate with regulators the removal of
non-federal dams. As an example, he cited the Condit Dam on the
White Salmon River, which is expected to be breached as a result of
an agreement now being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it is inappropriate to freeze a (dam licensing)
system that is working over apprehensions that I think are entirely
unjustified,'' Babbitt said. ``History and reality argue for using
the existing system. It has never led to an inappropriate result
and I don't think it's going to.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews after the hearing, Babbitt and Gorton each
expressed hope that the Elwha dams might yet be removed, but
offered no suggestion as to how that might be accomplished given
their rift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll continue to advocate and try to persuade the Congress to
give us the funding necessary to get the dams down, provide a water
supply for Port Angeles, and restore the fish, but I cannot
acquiesce in having it held hostage to a whole range of other
issues,'' Babbitt said. ``This dam and the town of Port Angeles can
not be held hostage to a back door rewrite of federal hydro(power)
policy that would apply nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said he was ``gravely disappointed'' by Babbitt's
comments, but that he will continue to try to find a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't jump to any conclusions,'' he said. ``If one road
turns out to be a dead end, you just try another road. But one road
did seem to turn out to be a dead end. There's no question about
that with his response.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and environmentalists are upset at Gorton's insistence
on linking the Elwha and Columbia/Snake river dams, which they view
as a politically driven attempt to position Gorton as the lone
champion of eastern Washington interests against a threatening
federal government. They point to statements such as one Gorton
included in a news release Thursday, in which the senator said
``the Pacific Northwest's economic foundation is still at risk of
being destroyed by the Clinton-Gore administration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no intent in Congress to take down the Columbia or
Snake River dams, and we should not... try to make this into some
hot-button event,'' said Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash. ``There is no
reason to do that, and I really hope Sen. Gorton backs down and we
can move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash, said he will use his position as
ranking Democrat on the House Interior Appropriations Subcommittee
to push for funds to remove the Elwha dams, and then attempt to
persuade Gorton to back down in conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we can break this impasse,'' he said. ``As (former
Secretary of State) George Shultz used to say, nothing in this town
is ever over. We'll just keep working on this thing and see if
hopefully we can't find a way to go forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0536 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JUDGE-2NDTAKE-NYT     04-22 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDGE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: anybody else.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eugenia Williams was 13 when she went to a neighborhood gym in
Atlantic City to learn how to box so she could defend herself from
the teasing of her older brother. Discouraged by the lack of
opportunity for female fighters, though, she later turned to
judging boxing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, she was certified by the U. S. amateur boxing
organization to judge amateur fights. All she had to do to gain the
work was read a 200-page book, pass a written test on the rules of
the sport and informally judge several bouts where her scores did
not officially count. She judged amateur bouts for five years until
becoming a professional judge in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' fortunes in the ranks of professional boxing judges,
she said in a recent interview, owed much to her relationship with
Lee, the IBF president. She said Lee identified her early on as a
promising prospect and that he became a kind of mentor. As a
professional judge, in fact, she became almost exclusively
associated with IBF fights.
</P>
<P>
   But the work was never highly lucrative. According to Williams'
financial records, she earned roughly $3,500 a year as a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who makes $36,000 a year as a city clerk, lives with
her daughter and granddaughter in a modest white, vinyl-sided row
house a few blocks from the opulent casinos on the Atlantic City
boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' bankruptcy filing, submitted to the court on Jan. 25,
listed two checking accounts with balances of $20 and $19
respectively, and she listed 18 individual credit card debts among
the $35,500 she owed creditors. Other than her house, with its
outstanding mortgage, she listed very few assets: a 1994 Pontiac
Grand Am, household goods and furniture worth $1,000, and jewelry
worth $250.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams was not required to declare her financial
difficulty to officials with the New Jersey Athletic Commission,
she did not volunteer the information, and no one ever asked. When
applicants apply for licenses with the boxing commissions in New
York and New Jersey, they are checked only for past criminal
records or current felony warrants. There is no inquiry into credit
status or questions about pending civil lawsuits against the
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, officials with the New Jersey commission even today say
they would not be interested in whether a judge, including one
about to decide a major prizefight, was financially vulnerable.
They say the question of a judge's being prone to criminality has
little to do with his or her financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't check for that,'' Rhonda Utley-Herring, a
spokeswoman for the commission, said. ``Nobody does. If a person is
of that mind-set, they're going to be corrupt anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL CUT BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   To law enforcement officials, as well as local and national
legislators looking into boxing reform, a judge in serious
financial straits should not be allowed to sit at ringside for a
multimillion-dollar prizefight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a judge who is presumed to be financially vulnerable
shows the slightest hint of being beholden to the promoter or the
sanctioning organization in a fight they are judging, then that is
going to raise suspicions about that judge,'' Spitzer, the New York
attorney general, said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL CUT ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   To have been at ringside for a fight of the magnitude of
Holyfield-Lewis, Williams' resume was not outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that she has judged more than 500 bouts, including
numerous title bouts for the IBF Others, though, have doubts about
her expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have never put Eugenia Williams in such a high-profile
fight,'' said Jon Robinson, president of the World Boxing Union, a
London-based organization that oversees many European title fights.
``It's one of the best fights of the year, and I would look for one
of the best officials that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he had essentially dismissed Williams last May
after her five years of work for the WBU Robinson said he had too
many other, superior judges to use. Williams said she left the WBU
because Robinson wanted her to pay $1,100 a year to remain a judge
with the organization and not work for any other sanctioning body.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Sulaiman, president of the World Boxing Council, another
sanctioning group, also said he was uncomfortable at the time with
Williams' judging the Holyfield fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the judge from the IBF wasn't well known,''
Sulaiman said of Williams. ``We would prefer someone with more
experience or more recognition. We never said we didn't want her to
judge the fight with regards to any dishonesty. We only said it was
based on experience and competency.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, there is almost no mechanism to measure the
competency of judges in professional boxing. Judges licensed in New
York and New Jersey are required to attend annual seminars to
refresh themselves and sharpen their skills. But there are no
formal evaluations, no systematic ranking of judges by levels of
ability or accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, for instance, Larry Hazzard, the state athletic
commissioner, checks scorecards of judges during the year for
inconsistencies and handles formal complaints made against judges.
But Utley-Herring, the commission spokeswoman, said she could not
remember a judge's ever being reprimanded or dismissed for
incompetence or wrongdoing in the 15 years Hazzard has been
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' decision to judge the Robinson-Gatti fight last
December never came to the attention of the New Jersey commission.
Williams said she had come to know Robinson during his amateur
career when she judged several of his fights. She acknowledged that
her daughter called Robinson in the days after the fight from
Williams' home in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she did nothing wrong in failing to disclose her
relationship with Robinson before the fight, which ultimately
established him as a top contender. She said she had often judged
fights involving boxers with whom she was friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I was judging amateur fights when there
would be boxers I knew from Atlantic City,'' Williams said. ``They
all knew that they weren't going to get anything from Jean
Williams. The fact that I knew them didn't get in my way of giving
a fair decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are far from convinced this is an acceptable approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the biggest no-no's in amateur boxing,'' Ray
Silvas, chairman of the referees and judges committee for USA
Boxing, said of Williams' judging a friend's fight. ``If we find
out we will immediately disqualify a judge from doing any more of
that fighter's bouts.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials, having been made aware of Williams'
potential conflict, said they would explore ways of preventing it
from occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of information should have been disclosed,''
Utley-Herring said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0537 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JUDGE-3RDTAKE-NYT     04-22 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDGE-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Utley-Herring said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Williams was at ringside for the Holyfield fight because of the
IBF's Lee. All three main sanctioning organizations got to select a
judge for the fight, which was intended to unify the heavyweight
titles, and Lee said he chose Williams because he wanted a judge
who had not worked a Lewis or a Holyfield fight in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact sanctioning organizations were selecting a fight's
judges disturbed people who have believed such a practice is
fraught with problems. In the 1984 investigation of boxing in New
Jersey, for example, investigators recommended that this practice
be abolished. They feared that a judge's loyalty to a sanctioning
body might make him or her apt to score the fight favorably for
that organization's champion.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation, however, was ignored by state legislators.
Frustrated investigators believe that was because officials feared
that promoters would take their fights elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter, if the sanctioning bodies aren't going
to have a role in selecting the judges, they're not going to
sanction championship fights and they're not going to come to New
Jersey,'' said Morley, who headed the investigation in New Jersey
in 1984. ``At the time we were looking at this, the people higher
up in the bureaucracy realized that. I think they caved in and said
we don't want to make it impossible to bring championship fights to
New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL CUT BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he would never give up the right to select judges for a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appoint these officials with the approval of the local
commissions,'' Lee said. ``Now someone wants to come in and take
over that right from the sanctioning organizations. I'm not willing
to relinquish that to some of these commissions that only deal in
boxing on a part-time basis. Not when I'm providing training and
seminars to judges and I'm working with them all year around. I
know the officials. I train them and I license them. But I can't
tell you how they're going to score a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL CUT ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Gregory P. Sirb, president of the Association of Boxing
Commissions, a national umbrella group, has proposed some measures
that would begin to reform the monitoring and selecting of judges.
One proposal would be to create a championship pool made up of the
best three judges and best two referees from each state who would
be paid a standard fee for title bouts. Sirb's proposal will have
to be voted on by the state commissions that belong to the national
association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't rocket science,'' Sirb said. ``We should be able to
fix this problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
