<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS AND REVENUE RISE AND STOCK PRICE STILL FALLS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pepsico reported better-than-expected first-quarter earnings
Thursday, beating analysts' estimates by one cent.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, shares of the maker of Frito-Lay, Pepsi-Cola and
Tropicana fell after the company's chief financial officer, Michael
D. White, said Pepsico would spend $75 million to upgrade its
computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings from continuing operations were $373 million, or 25
cents a share, beating analysts' expectations of 24 cents a share,
according to the First Call Corp.. A year ago, Pepsi earned $377
million, or 24 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi took a charge of $40 million, or 3 cents a share, from
closing plants at its Frito-Lay North America operation.
First-quarter earnings per share also benefited from fewer shares
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 17 percent, to $5.11 billion from $4.35 billion.
Shares of Pepsi, which is based in Purchase, N.Y., fell $1.9375, to
$37.
</P>
<P>
   White said that future earnings might be a little lower than
analysts had been led to believe by the company's chairman and
chief executive, Roger A. Enrico.
</P>
<P>
   Enrico has moved to make Pepsi a large player in the packaged
foods business by spinning off the restaurant business, acquiring
Tropicana and divesting the company's soft drink bottling unit.
</P>
<P>
   During a question-and-answer session, he added, ``Let's show you
we can do 12 percent, or 13 percent, and then we can talk about
more,'' when asked whether earnings would be below the 15 percent
or so estimates made by Enrico over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The spending on new technology, intended to put all of Pepsico's
divisions on compatible systems, struck some analysts as a
necessity, even though Pepsico said it planned to list the expense
separately on its earnings statement for this year. ``The irony
here is, they are doing the right thing,'' said Jennifer Solomon,
an analyst for Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil remained a trouble spot for the company's Frito-Lay
International division, although profits for the division still
managed to rise 3 percent, the company reported. White said in the
conference call that he expected to see ``a gradual improvement''
in the country's economic situation.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for Pepsi-Cola products in North America rose 4 percent,
to $613 million from $589 million. Profits also rose 4 percent, the
company said, from $165 million to $172 million.
</P>
<P>
   White said sales of diet products, including the company's
recently introduced Pepsi One, rose 10 percent in the quarter.
Pepsi-Cola, the flagship brand, declined 1 percent, he said. Prices
for concentrate rose in the quarter but were offset by increased
marketing support for the company's retail customers, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
