<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NAZI-DEPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIARY CITED IN CASE AGAINST SUSPECTED NAZI
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The crumbling pages of a German soldier's wartime
diary are at the center of a new dispute in the government's case
against Jack Reimer, a retired Brooklyn businessman accused of
hiding his Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Reimer contends that two pages from the diary,
which had been kept for more than half a century by a former SS
officer who lives in Germany, may support Reimer's position that he
was not involved in Nazi atrocities during World War II, and should
not be deported.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. government lawyers say the diary proves nothing, and
they told a federal judge in Manhattan in papers submitted last
week that when they asked German authorities to search the former
SS officer's house last month to obtain the entire diary, the man
said he had destroyed it.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the diary comes as U.S. District Judge Lawrence
M. McKenna is preparing to rule on the government's request that he
revoke Reimer's citizenship, the first step in deporting him.
</P>
<P>
   The government has asked McKenna to rule that the two diary
pages are inadmissible, arguing that their contents are
inconclusive, and that without the rest of the diary, mean nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan and the
Justice Department's Office of Special Investigation in Washington
refused to comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Reimer's lawyer, former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark,
said McKenna should admit any defense evidence that would bear ``on
helping you find the truth about the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that for the government ``to make so much of so
insignificant a part of the case implies a lack of confidence in
their case.''
</P>
<P>
   During a trial before McKenna in August, the government offered
evidence that Reimer, now 80, had been a commander at an SS
training camp in Trawniki, Poland, and participated in the
liquidation of Jewish ghettos in Warsaw, Lublin and Czestochowa.
Later, he lied about his past to gain entry into the United States,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer, a former Soviet army officer, denied any role in the
atrocities and testified that he had been taken captive by the
Nazis and forced to work as a bookkeeper in the Trawniki SS camp.
</P>
<P>
   After testimony ended, the judge put off issuing a decision to
allow Clark to go to Germany to interview an additional witness,
Rudolph Reiss, who was an SS man at Trawniki.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying in October before a German magistrate, Reiss
disclosed that he had kept a diary that mentioned Reimer's name.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Justice Department lawyer, Edward Stutman, who was
present, asked to see the diary, Reiss refused, the government has
said in documents submitted to the court.
</P>
<P>
   After the deposition ended, Reiss contacted Clark, he later
wrote to the judge, and they walked to a nearby restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He unwrapped a small decomposing date book which was in an old
creased piece of plastic,'' Clark wrote. ``He turned through a
number of pages. They appeared to contain very few entries.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that Reiss showed him two pages, dated June 23, 1942,
that included Reimer's name. Reiss seemed to say that Reimer had
been sent from Trawniki to Lublin ``for some office purpose,'' and
had returned the same day, Clark wrote to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Clark appeared to be suggesting that the entry confirmed
Reimer's testimony that he worked in the office at the SS camp.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors contend that the selectively disclosed pages do
nothing to prove Reimer's defense. The liquidation of the Lublin
ghetto, for example, occurred in March 1942, they said, for which
they have evidence of his presence.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted that Reiss had described Reimer ``as one of the
founders'' of the SS camp.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief summarizing their case, the government said there was
``uncontroverted documentary evidence'' of Reimer's role as an SS
officer who had ``exercised command authority in the Nazis brutal
liquidations of the Jewish ghettos'' in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has yet to respond to the brief. McKenna has not said when
he will rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
