<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9971 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-COLUMBINE23-CO     04-22 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-COLUMBINE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Propane bombs, note new discoveries in shootings
 &HT;    By Chris Barker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Investigators scouring the abandoned
Columbine High School building found a large unexploded bomb on
Thursday, bolstering their theory that two suspected killers had
help carrying out their deadly rampage.
</P>
<P>
   However, no additional suspects have been identified, said Steve
Davis, a spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb found Thursday was one of 31 unexploded devices found
since the shootings, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb consisted of a 20-pound propane tank and gasoline can
in a duffle bag connected with wiring, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   If it had exploded, even more could have died.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bottle was full, it would have been devastating,'' said
Sgt. Jim Parr of the Jefferson County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, residents of the Denver area visited a nearby park to
remember the 15 who died.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Revas and her daughter planted 13 crosses before a mound of
flowers _ nine painted blue for the boys and one teacher who died
and four painted pink for the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Two black crosses signifying Harris and Klebold were placed flat
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pound them in, I laid them down,'' Revas said. ``I
don't think they deserved to be with the others.''
</P>
<P>
   As authorities poured over interviews in an attempt to build
profiles of the two suspects, about 60 to 75 crime scene
investigators collected and catalogued evidence within the high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Although authorities were mum for a possible motive for the
crime, Davis on Thursday for the first time revealed a note had
been discovered at Harris's house.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to characterize it as a suicide note but said it had
been seized as evidence Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County School District officials announced that 1,965
Columbine students will finish the academic year together and
graduate May 22 at an as-yet undisclosed location within the
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want them separated,'' said Jane Hammond,
superintendent of the district.
</P>
<P>
   Although school officials had not toured the damage inside the
high school, Hammond said the district ``absolutely'' plans to have
students back in the building for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Some Columbine students who visited several growing memorials to
the victims in Clement Park said they felt a need to return to the
scene of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Others felt the building has been violated by the killings and
should be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they need to close it and leave it as a standing
memorial,'' said Joe Dreaden, a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Others accused school officials of ignoring red flags that
Harris and Klebold had been sending up for months.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Oakley, a 16-year-old Columbine student, said the two
suspects made a video in school that watched like a prologue to the
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's those guys in the school with play guns shooting jocks on
video,'' Oakley said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the suspects used video animation to add blood to the
production.
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors told authorities that Harris and Klebold targeted
athletes during Tuesday's shootings.
</P>
<P>
   A district spokeswoman refused to discuss the video but School
Board President Jon DeStefano said similar warnings are evident in
any U.S. high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe the schools have enough resources to address
the problems that exist,'' DeStefano said.
</P>
<P>
   Those warnings became ``our worse nightmare,'' at Columbine, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   DeStefano paid his respects to the families of the dead, and
praised Columbine staff for the way they handled the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saved the lives of hundreds of children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Harris and Klebold used an impressive arsenal
to carry out their killing spree. Besides the bombs _ which were
found in the school, suspects' vehicles and their homes _ they
carried two shotguns, a semi-automatic rifle and a semi-automatic
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators refused to confirm or deny a report that two of
the guns had been traced to a Denver dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities evacuated Columbine when the propane bomb was found
Thursday, a discovery Davis termed, ``disturbing,'' because the
building had already been swept for explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating the crime scene has been painstaking for federal,
state and local authorities who must navigate an eerie sea of
abandoned possessions inside Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are literally thousands of backpacks in that school,''
Davis said. ``I think every kid must have been carrying a
backpack.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
