<SLUG> BC-RAC-DUBAI-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBAI COLTS TEST CHURCHILL'S STRIP  
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ There was no nameplate on Barn 45 and no
chatter from the 10 stable hands who were flown here from Dubai to
tend to the Kentucky Derby's most mysterious horses. Instead, Sheik
Mohammed bin Rashid al-Maktoum let Worldly Manner announce his
Godolphin stables arrival at Churchill Downs and the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Lean but corded with muscle, the big bay galloped on American
soil for the first time since September, floating through a lap
along with his stablemate and Derby entry, Aljabr. He is an
imposing physical specimen and looked well rested despite the
arduous flight and 48 hours in quarantine.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller Aljabr did not seem to enjoy his first trip around
the Churchill Downs oval, returning to the barn sweaty and lathered
around his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always like that,'' said Tom Albertrani, the Brooklyn,
N.Y.-born assistant trainer for Godolphin. ``He's an edgier colt.
It's going to take him a few days to get accustomed to the new
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bob Baffert-trained duo of Prime Timber and General
Challenge had swift six-furlong workouts here Thursday morning and
showed why they were likely to be the morning-line favorites. Prime
Timber ripped the distance in 1:12 3/5, then General Challenge
bettered the time at 1:12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome _ a Real Quiet type move,'' Baffert said,
referring to last year's Derby winner. ``This is as hard as we'll
push him before the race.'' Baffert is seeking an unprecedented
third straight Derby victory.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge, however, appeared to work more effortlessly.
He clipped off the first quarter in 23 4/5 seconds, three furlongs
in 36 and a half in 48 3/5. Then Baffert asked the exercise rider
Dana Barnes through a radio headset to push him. General Challenge
finished the six furlongs in 1:12 and then galloped out a mile.
``Let him gallop out strong; keep going,'' Baffert told her through
the radio. It was satisfying enough for him to joke, of course.
``Well, I don't need the filly,'' he said, referring to Excellent
Meeting, whom he still may enter in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Patin May Be Replaced
</P>
<P>
   The owner of Valhol said Thursday that he was moving closer to
replacing the jockey Billy Patin, who is under investigation for
allegedly using an illegal electrical device in winning the
Arkansas Derby on April 10. James Jackson, who has yet to collect
the $300,000 in purse money, said he reviewed the tape of the race
and agreed that it looked as if his jockey indeed dropped something
after crossing the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Arkansas Racing Commission releases the $300,000,
Valhol will not be eligible for the Derby because of the large
field. Entries are granted in order of graded stakes purses won,
and without the Arkansas Derby money, the horse has just $34,000 in
earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
