A9974 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX     04-22 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILERS LIKE ODDS IN GAME 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hollowness of an opening-night playoff loss lingered in the
Edmonton Oilers locker room ... and center Doug Weight just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we'd like to win Game 1,'' Weight said. ``But we're
comfortable with where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Brash? Cocky? Nah, just experienced. The underdog Oilers have
had a way with Game 2s in the past two seasons, so the chance of
going down two games to none tonight in the second game of a
best-of-seven Western Conference quarterfinals series at Reunion
Arena hasn't entered their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I'd say? One thing: The first game has always
brought us belief,'' Weight said. ``We make some mistakes and we
realize we can play with this team. Forty points better, 30 points
better, they aren't tougher. We believe in ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers rode that philosophy to a seven-game upset of the
Stars two seasons ago _ an upset that began with a stunning 4-0
Game 2 victory at Reunion Arena. Last season, in round two, the
Oilers put another scare into the Stars by taking Game 2, 2-0, on
the strength of a first period in which they held the Stars without
a shot on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Oilers have proved they are far from the eighth
seed that finished 36 points behind the top-seeded Stars during the
regular season. With a hard-fought Game 1 loss, the Oilers opened
the eyes of the Stars and sent a message that Game 2 will be a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the players think, but \RGame 1\S would have
scared me,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, scared might not be the word, but the Stars definitely
were awakened by the performance of the Oilers, who laid out 64
hits, despite getting only 13 shots. That the Stars had more than
twice as many shots (31) on goal only underscored just how much
they need to improve their offense in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our track record in Game 2 against these guys hasn't been the
greatest in the world,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``The
energy level may trail off, but I think we'll definitely have to
get back up to where Game 1 was if we want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Intensity was key in the opening game of the series, a 2-1
victory by the Stars. The Stars matched the physical force of the
Oilers and even did a good job of keeping up with a team Hitchcock
calls ``the fastest in hockey.'' But the Stars fell short in one
department: finishing scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took 31 shots on goal and fired another 21 high or
wide. That's 52 pucks that were flying somewhere near Oilers goalie
Tommy Salo, and yet only two found their way into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you'd say we were nervous, but there's more
pressure on us to win any game at home to keep the home ice
advantage,'' Modano said. ``Because of that, you try to be
cautious, probably overcautious. You start worrying too much and
you start thinking too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars say their tendency to outshoot teams and not always
outscore them isn't a trend toward destruction. But in nine of
their 19 losses this season, the Stars followed a formula of
frustration; they outshot opponents and simply could not get enough
goals. The ultimate frustration came Nov. 4 against the San Jose
Sharks, when the Stars outshot the Sharks, 21-9, and lost, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   It set an NHL record at the time for a loss with the fewest
shots against.
</P>
<P>
   So, do the Stars start worrying about possible frustration?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't try to shoot, you're not going to score,'' Stars
winger Benoit Hogue said. ``So, a lot of times we might be taking
shots from different angles that really aren't good scoring
chances, but sometimes the strangest shot is the one that scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the Stars should continue the hard skating that
results in possession of the puck that results in a lot of shots on
goals. But he said the Stars have plenty of room for improvement in
the goal-scoring department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have more bang-bang plays around the net,''
Hitchcock said. ``We have to create more opportunities at critical
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Hitchcock said the Stars have to improve every facet
of their game, and he wasn't at all upset with how the team played
in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the home team in Game 2, you can create a comfortable
gap or you can go back to the visitor's barn with everything being
revved up,'' Hitchcock said. ``No matter what happens in Game 1,
Game 2 has all the pressure on the home team. We have to accept
that and we have to be better.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
