<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HEARINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLS FOR CHANGE RECEIVE A HEARING IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Muhammad Ali's muted presence packed a Senate
Commerce Committee hearing into federal boxing reform Thursday, and
through his friend, Howard Bingham, he said he could not remain
silent ``while the sport he gave his life to has become a
travesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, Bingham asked on Ali's behalf, are the National Football
League, National Basketball Association and Major League Baseball
regulated and run by commissioners, but boxing has been ``singled
out for total neglect and thrown to the wolves?''
</P>
<P>
   The desire for legislation to alter the sport's business
practices has accelerated since disputed scoring in the Lennox
Lewis-Evander Holyfield heavyweight bout last month produced a draw
rather than the clear victory for Lewis that most observers thought
they had witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   During the bout, Eugenia Williams, a judge selected by the
International Boxing Federation, scored the fight 115-113 for
Holyfield, the IBF champion. Since then, her skills, motivation,
financial need and eyesight have been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the main point of the Lewis-Holyfield controversy,''
said Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who is a co-sponsor
of the Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform Act, ``is that the shadowy
relationships between promoters and sanctioning organizations often
result in injustice and scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, if passed, would force sanctioning bodies to
establish objective criteria for ranking boxers rather than use the
mystifying systems that often defy explanation; prohibit the
sanctioning organizations from receiving payments from promoters
for other than previously established expenses; limit option
contracts with promoters, and require promoters to file complete
contracts with boxers with state commissions and the fees they
assess on the boxers.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot L. Spitzer, the New York state attorney general, added two
more measures, both of which would most likely remain under state
jurisdiction. He suggested the creation of an independent boxing
poll, like those for college football, to replace the sanctioning
bodies' rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer also recommended that the mode of scoring a fight be
changed, to eliminate an aberrant judge's score from each round.
Thus, if two judges score a round 10-9 for one fighter, and the
third scores it 10-9 for the second fighter, the score of the third
is tossed out.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of McCain and Spitzer, who heads a boxing task force
for the National Association of Attorneys General, are designed to
eventually replace sanctioning bodies with a system backed by civil
and criminal penalties prescribed by federal law. Spitzer and Greg
Sirb, president of the Association of Boxing Commissioners, said
the states needed the foundation of federal law to keep promoters
from shopping fights to states with the weakest regulations.
</P>
<P>
   One dissenting voice in the hearing was Walter Stone, the IBF's
counsel. His testimony tried to divert the committee from the
rankings to the ``media's controlling influence over boxing,'' how
to define a fighter, and the failure of rival promoters to make the
best fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to say sanctioning bodies are always the
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain challenged Stone on how Vincent Pettway climbed the IBF's
welterweight ranking to became Felix Trinidad's mandatory
challenger in a May 29 title fight. Pettway has not fought anyone
with a winning record since 1995, and the bout is expected to be a
gross mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had every reason to think he was a good fighter,'' Stone
said about Pettway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you judge a fighter by the quality of his fighters?''
McCain asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I examined his record,'' Stone said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
