<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0547 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS23-COX     04-22 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors, HMOs at odds over collective bargaining
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For doctors and health insurers, this was
supposed to be a quiet year at the statehouse, a time for both
sides to keep their powder dry after some ugly battles over HMO
laws in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But two bills that would give competing physicians the right to
band together to negotiate with health plans have revived the
politicking just as the session is entering its final weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor groups are lobbying hard for the bills, which passed
committees in both chambers, as a check on the power of large
health plans to dictate fees and contractual terms. Insurers and
employer groups are complaining loudly that the pro-business
Republicans favoring the bills, including Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, are
opening the door for doctors to form labor unions in Texas and
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans carrying a collective bargaining bill . . . go
figure,'' said former Sen. Jerry Patterson, executive director of
the state's HMO trade association.
</P>
<P>
   Perry has asked the two sides to try and negotiate a compromise
and says that process is ongoing. But so far, they have found
little room for discussion and have been told that the Senate
version of the legislation, sponsored by Sen. Chris Harris
(R-Arlington), will go to the floor next week if no agreement is
reached, sources familiar with the negotiations said. The House
bill, sponsored by John Smithee (R-Amarillo), is expected to hit
the floor later.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has made me understand why it's not in the patient's
best interest that doctors can't talk to each other,'' Perry said.
``I want to make sure that physicians are able to exchange
information for the best interests of the patients, and I think
this moves us in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The bills would prohibit groups of independent doctors from
boycotting or striking as unions do, but would shelter them from
federal antitrust laws, which make any discussions about contracts
among competing entities a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians would have to hire a third party to negotiate for
them, follow strict guidelines and agree to close supervision by
the state. Under the Senate bill, they could then work together on
a range of terms in their contracts including patient referral
procedures, dispute resolutions, timing of reimbursements, and, in
negotiations with the biggest health plans, the size of those
reimbursements. The attorney general would have to approve all
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The bills are based on model legislation drawn up by the
American Medical Association, which would like to see the right of
doctors to collectively bargain eventually established in federal
law. Washington state has passed a similar statute, but that
measure does not allow doctors to negotiate fees.
</P>
<P>
   Texas would be the first state to give doctors the right to
collectively negotiate fees.
</P>
<P>
   In analyzing the legislation, the Senate Economic Development
Committee acknowledged that allowing doctors to collectively
negotiate could create barriers to competition in health care.
Health plans say increases in doctors' fees would force them to
raise premiums.
</P>
<P>
   But physicians see the ongoing consolidation in the health
insurance industry reducing their leverage when it comes time to
draw up terms of contracts, including those terms that address the
way they care for patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``An independent physician negotiating with a
multibillion-dollar corporation is a bit like Bambi negotiating
with Godzilla. It doesn't happen,'' said James Eskew, an Austin
physician. ``The way they negotiate is they hand you a contract . .
. and say, `Tough. Sign it or get out of here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew said his physician group had recently tried to negotiate
with a major health plan that wanted to drop reimbursements 20
percent, but the plan wouldn't return its phone calls. Yet he
conceded that doctors in Texas are also concerned that their
incomes could eventually decline as a result of cost-cutting in
health care, as he said they have in other states. ``I think it's a
coming problem in Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One expert in health law and antitrust agreed that the impetus
for doctors to collectively negotiate ultimately has more to do
with money than caring for patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always a little skeptical when I hear either insurers or
doctors say they have the patients' best interests at heart,'' said
Seth Chandler, professor at the University of Houston Law Center.
``Actually their interests lie closer to home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
