<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      04-22 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ Scottie Pippen smiled and waved and kept driving,
seeming amused that media had gathered at the airport before the
Rockets' chartered flight Thursday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teammates feigned anger and hurled insults, assuming correctly
the crowd had not gathered to offer good wishes before tonight's
game against the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets seemed repaired, with bravado and banter back
aboard, as if leaving one terrible night behind them as they headed
for a brief road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will not be quite that easy. Seeking a stretch run
before the playoffs, they were embarrassed by the Dallas Mavericks
on Wednesday night. Hours later, Pippen was arrested for suspicion
of driving while intoxicated, a charge he denied in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was released on $500 bond at about 6:30 a.m. Thursday,
and though he did not attend Thursday's practice, he rejoined the
team in time for the flight to Los Angeles. And with that, the
Rockets hoped they could leave behind a terrible performance and
Pippen's legal troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 100 percent behind Scottie,'' Rockets forward Charles
Barkley said. ``He's my teammate. He's my friend. I'm 100 percent
behind him. I think he's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie's going to be fine. Obviously, you're down a bit. You
keep going. It's something that happened. It's a distraction for a
second. He'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're famous or in the limelight and you make a mistake
or do something wrong, everybody throws gasoline on the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, 33, had no comment other than issuing a brief statement
Thursday maintaining his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not intoxicated when arrested after the game last
night,'' Pippen's statement said. ``And I'm confident the evidence
will support me in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Pippen, the arrest can only make a trying season more
difficult. Signed to a five-year, $67 million contract, excluding
incentive bonuses, Pippen has struggled offensively throughout the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 14.1 points per game, he has scored in double figures
only four times in the past 10 games. Thursday, he made just two of
eight shots to score four points in the 109-95 loss to the
Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   But his arrest, though another bump in a rocky season for Pippen
personally, will not affect his status on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make an assumption,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``These things happen. I think it's unfair to make comments
when nothing has been established. You let the legal system do what
it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of used to unexpected things happening, injuries. I
try not to lose composure. You can see a lot of things. Until you
find out all the details, you can overreact and get into a whole
situation that's not fair. It's not the right way to do things.
People love to make assumptions way before the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personal, legal matter. It happens to a lot of people.
Nothing has been decided about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's teammates had a similar reaction, arguing his arrest
would be filed as a personal matter to be left far from the courts
and locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he would talk with Pippen about the issue.
Teammates said they would follow Pippen's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things happen,'' Rockets center Antoine Carr said.
``It's a personal thing he has to deal with. We know what we have
to do. We have to go down there and play ball. It's part of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to tell him, like always, we love every player on
our team. If he needs us in any way, we've got his back. If he
wants us to stay clear, we'll stay clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had spoken to Pippen on Thursday morning, and though he
said Pippen was down, Barkley expected Pippen would not let the
incident become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in that little cell several times myself,'' Barkley
said. ``It's one of those things you get over with. You don't think
too much about it, unless you're in a cell with a guy named Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something unfortunate happened. A mistake was made. It's over
with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets would like to take the same approach with their
arrested performance Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chasing a valuable third playoff seed, they lost to a Mavericks
team with just two previous road victories all season to fall 2{
games behind the San Antonio Spurs. They remain just a game ahead
of the Lakers for the fourth seed and the first-round home-court
advantage that comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich called the performance a nightmare, the tape painful
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to read too much into it,'' he said. ``I'm always
concerned. Your mind is always working. But I've learned you can't
obsess on things. You've got to address them. Try to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it wouldn't have happened. I wish we would have been
more focused. I wish we would have run back and talked. We
addressed those things. We'll see where we're at.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I said is I thought the team needed to refocus like they
did 10 days ago. They got together (in a players-only meeting in
Minnesota) and talked about doing this thing together.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockets players decided that night to treat the remaining
regular-season games as playoff games, believing they could have a
profound effect on the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As a third seed, they would face Phoenix or Minnesota in the
first round. A fourth or fifth seed would mean a first-round
meeting with the Lakers, Monday's opponent at Compaq Center in the
second of back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Spurs have swept the regular-season series with the
Rockets, they would hold a tiebreaker advantage should the Rockets
catch them. And if a third seed is unlikely at best, the Rockets
will have to come up with some other motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I'd say chances are
(third is out of reach), but I'm not going to assume it. Sometimes
the way we play, I think we can climb the ladder. On other nights,
I'm not sure we'll stay in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   One more win, or a Seattle or Sacramento loss, would clinch a
playoff spot and take care of that question. But the Rockets do
have something to achieve down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game matters,'' Barkley said. ``It's going to go down to
the last day of the season whether we're three, four or five. Last
night maybe cost us three. We have to hang on to the four spot.
It's kind of exciting because every game means something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stunk up the joint last night. That's all I can see. We all
played terrible. A wise man told me one time, there's only three
inches from where somebody pats you on the back and kicks you in
the (butt).
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have highs and lows. It's over with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets hope the same will be said for Pippen and his
toughest night as a Rocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
