<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYC-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHALLENGE FOR A GOOD-TIMES BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, April 23: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, before Mayor Rudolph Giuliani detailed his spending
plan for the next fiscal year, he and City Council Speaker Peter
Vallone reminisced companionably about the dark days when they had
been forced to slash the work force and worried about whether New
York City could maintain the balanced budget necessary to preserve
its financial autonomy. Now the city has a $2.1 billion surplus.
Both the mayor and Vallone deserve credit for their ongoing efforts
to keep the budget under control and bring down taxes.
</P>
<P>
   What they have not been able to do, however, is fix the
structural imbalance that shows up in projections for new budget
gaps in the future. Giuliani has not been fully successful in
creating the smaller, more efficient work force he envisioned, one
that would not automatically grow back to its old size as soon as
austerity ended. The head count of city workers has already inched
up near its former level, and productivity improvements have been
scattered. Giuliani has another chance to tackle that problem in
the upcoming labor contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   His job will be harder now, since new leaders have taken over
many unions and are eager to show what they can achieve. Giuliani
wisely ignored their demands that he set aside a large amount of
the surplus to cover wage increases. We hope he is successful in
his plans to pay for raises with new productivity initiatives. The
municipal work force must be both better paid and smaller if the
city is to reach real financial health.
</P>
<P>
   The council and mayor are proposing competing tax cuts, and they
will be able to argue the advantages of their respective stances
over the next few weeks. Their other major differences are over
popular areas like libraries and services for the elderly that
mayors cut every year, just to divert the council with the task of
restoring them. One other difference is Giuliani's proposal for a
school voucher program, which Vallone opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Even if diverting money from the public schools to pay for
vouchers were not a bad idea on its face, the legal and political
obstacles make it a dubious venture. Giuliani says he is willing to
talk about alternatives that would make it easier to improve the
public school system, like eliminating tenure for principals and
getting rid of the present board of education. Vallone, too,
expressed a desire to see the school system reformed. We suggest
that they focus on that issue rather than a fruitless fight over
vouchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
