<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-BONDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO LAWYERS LOOK AT BONDS TO SPEED FEES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add byline and to change `issue' to `underwrite'
throughout.)   (jw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of plaintiffs' lawyers, including some who have already
been awarded billions of dollars in fees for representing states in
tobacco lawsuits, are exploring the possibility of having bonds
issued so they can collect the money faster.
</P>
<P>
   The bond issue, should it go forward, would apparently be the
first used for speeding payment of lawyers fees, several of the
lawyers involved in the discussions said Thursday. The lawyers said
they had already contacted more than 10 major investment-banking
houses about their interest in issuing underwriting bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of recent settlements between states and the
tobacco industry to resolve lawsuits seeking to recover
smoking-related health care costs, cigarette makers are required to
pay the fees of the lawyers hired by the states.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry is not required to pay all the money at once.
The agreement calls for the companies to pay $500 million in fees
annually until the awards are paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Under those terms, the $8.2 billion in fees awarded by
arbitrators last year to lawyers representing three states _
Florida, Mississippi and Texas _ will take about 16 years before
they are paid out.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of dollars in additional fees that are expected to be
awarded by arbitrators over the next year or two will substantially
lengthen the payout period.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lieff, a lawyer from San Francisco whose firm represented
several states, said issuing having bonds issued would allow the
lawyers to get their money faster and with more favorable tax
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Lieff said the bonds would also insulate the lawyers from risks
if any of the cigarette makers participating in the settlement went
bankrupt. The cost of the bonds to investors could be discounted to
reflect that risk.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawyers involved in the group exploring the bond issue
include Richard Scruggs of Pascagoula, Miss., and Ronald Motley and
Joe Rice, members of the same law firm in Charleston, S.C. Along
with participating in the Texas, Florida and Mississippi cases, the
men represented more than 30 other states in cases against the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Borod, whose Boston firm represented Massachusetts and
other states, said the lawyers decided at a meeting in Washington
several weeks ago to approach investment banking houses about
issuing underwriting bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Borod said that the investment houses had until Tuesday to
submit proposals outlining how they would issue underwrite the
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a lot of firms are working on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that based on the response from Wall Street, the group
of lawyers would decide whether to go forward with the bond issue.
Some of the firms involved, like Borod's, have not been awarded
fees yet but expect to get such awards in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   A number of states are also exploring the possibility of issuing
bonds. New York City is likely to become the first government in
the country to raise money based on future payments it will receive
from the tobacco settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
