<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT BETWEEN WNBA AND PLAYERS FALLS APART 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Women's National Basketball Association announced
Thursday that the agreement in principle it reached last week with
the players union had fallen apart and, as a result, it was
postponing next Tuesday's draft.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown came only nine days after both sides hailed what
appeared to be an historic first contract for a women's
professional basketball league in the United States. In doing so,
the WNBA and its newly formed players union, which is represented
by the National Basketball Players Association, had managed to
avoid a labor dispute similar to last year's NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason,'' said Valerie B. Ackerman, president of
the WNBA, ``that was not possible. Instead, there is no deal and we
have no choice but to postpone the draft indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft was for teams to select former American Basketball
League players and players coming out of college.
</P>
<P>
   In talks late Wednesday night, both sides said, there were
disagreements over certain provisions that they had not anticipated
during more than two months of bargaining and the final
negotiations that led to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The union said it was under the impression that players from the
defunct ABL would not be classified as rookies by the league, but
considered as veterans and allowed to negotiate their salaries
based on the veterans' scale.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA has said that for league purposes, the ABL players,
like veterans who have played overseas and joined the league, are
considered rookies.
</P>
<P>
   The union also took issue with the number of appearances players
would be required to make during the season. Union officials
claimed the two sides settled on a total of 12, but that the league
now says the figure applies only to appearances for league
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our mind,'' said Pamela Wheeler, director of operations for
the Women's Basketball Association and one of the union's chief
negotiators, ``this is an attempt to scare and intimidate the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bruce Levy, an agent who represents players in both
the WNBA and the former ABL, the players thought their preliminary
agreement with the league gave them the right to hold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they learned that players who had not signed a contract
with the league by the beginning of training camp would not be
allowed to play for the season,'' Levy said. ``That means that on
May 7, the league's lawyers could give us 70 veteran contracts and
say, `if in one week these aren't signed by your clients, your
clients are out of the league.' With that kind of threat, how much
negotiating can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler insisted that a deal could be made with no more than a
few hours at the bargaining table, but no new talks are scheduled. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
