<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA CONSIDERS OPTIONS INSIDE THE RING AND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGDON, Pa. - The afternoon sun glinted off the water in the
swimming pool as Tony Ayala Jr. basked in his second full day of
freedom. After being released from the Bayside State Prison in
Leesburg, N.J., on Tuesday following 16 years behind bars for a
rape he committed on New Year's Day 1983, Ayala, a former No. 1
junior middleweight contender, can now turn his attention to the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala was sitting poolside at the Philadelphia-area home of his
adviser, Dr. Brian Raditz, conducting interviews, soaking up sun
and trying to deal with the swirl of activity that has engulfed him
since his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is up in the air,'' Ayala said. ``I hope to be in
the ring by the summer. But first I have to get in the gym and see
where I'm at. I have a lot of hard work ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala was 19 when he was a No. 1 contender. His contemporaries
were Sugar Ray Leonard, Roberto Duran and Thomas Hearns, and his
record was 22-0 with 19 knockouts. He is now 36, his black hair
thinning on top, and he has not had a professional fight since he
knocked out Carlos Herrera in the third round on Nov. 20, 1982. He
appears to be physically fit. If he returns as a junior
middleweight contender, some of his opponents will have been first
graders when he went to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said he didn't follow boxing that closely when he was in
prison and he didn't really miss the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not like my dad, who has a real passion for the sport,''
he said. ``I don't love the sport. To me it's just a job. It's a
machismo thing. I love the challenge. I like knocking people out,
seeing their eyes roll back.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as returning, Ayala said he drew inspiration from George
Foreman, who took a 10-year hiatus from boxing before returning at
age 38 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Foreman pushed the clock way back,'' Ayala said. ``He
made it possible to fight in your late 30s and 40s. If it wasn't
for George Foreman, I probably wouldn't even be standing here
talking about boxing. The fact that he did it makes me know that
it's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several questions surrounding Ayala's return. What
effect has the lengthy prison sentence had on his marvelous boxing
skills? Can he still muster the same ferocity that he fought with
now that he says he has conquered the demons that drove him to
commit violent crimes and led him to alcohol abuse and heroin use?
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically he's been right for a long time,'' said
Raditz, who was Ayala's psychologist when he was at Rahway State
Prison, now East Jersey State Prison, at the start of his sentence.
``His attitude is very good. It's a timing thing. If he feels good,
we'll pursue it. If he doesn't, then we'll look at other career
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Raditz said there had already been offers for Ayala, who was a
peer counselor in prison, to do some counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said that he would make all the final decisions about his
career, but that he had put his father, Tony Sr., who has trained
him since he was 5, in charge of setting up his training camp and
helping him select opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Sr. said he was not going to push Ayala at the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll work six rounds at a time,'' the elder Ayala said.
``We'll work on the little things that he missed when he was
incarcerated. Four to six weeks after he's been in the gym, he'll
start sparring.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala has not hired a promoter, but Lester Bedford, a boxing
promoter from Fort Worth, coordinated the media interviews for
Ayala Thursday and said he had made a formal offer to be Ayala's
promoter.
</P>
<P>
   There was a festive mood at Raditz's house Thursday. And Ayala
seemed to be enjoying his freedom. But he said he could not forget
about what he did.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not talk much about his remorse or wanting to
make an apology to his victim, because he said he believed it would
sound insincere. However, he said he wanted to apologize to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she came to me or if she had a representative come to me, I
would go talk to her,'' Ayala said. ``I would leave training camp.
If I was fighting De La Hoya, I'd cancel the fight. Forget De La
Hoya. She would be more important than him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
