<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-CHINA-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NARROW VICTORY LEAVES QUESTIONS FOR U.S. WOMEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERSHEY, Pa. _ With the women's World Cup approaching in June,
the United States appeared to have lost its scoring touch and any
certainty that it was still head and shoulders above every other
team in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But after missing numerous opportunities Thursday night, the
Americans rescued a 2-1 exhibition victory over China two minutes
into extra time on a rebound shot by Tisha Venturini.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm fired a low cross from the right side that Han Wenxia,
the Chinese goalkeeper, poked away. Venturini, who had entered in
the 90th minute as a substitute, pounced on the ricochet and
punched the ball into the net from seven yards out, awakening a
quiet crowd of 15,257 at Hersheypark Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it as hard as I could across the goal and Tisha made
this unbelievable run from midfield,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Venturini said: ``You know Mia is going to get there, so I just
kept running.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's play was seen by many as a potential preview of
the World Cup final, scheduled for July 10 at the Rose Bowl in
Pasadena, Calif. The teams will meet again Sunday in an exhibition
at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who lost by 2-1 to China in Portugal's Algarve
Cup last month, dominated play in the first half but continued to
struggle with putting the ball into the net. Cindy Parlow pounded a
shot off the post in the seventh minute, then failed to lift a chip
shot over Han.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12th minute, Hamm made a brilliant feint to her left,
moved to her right around a Chinese defender but shot the ball just
wide left from 17 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm is considered the world's best player, and with 104 career
goals, she is only 3 shy of the women's career record. But it has
now been six games since she has scored a goal. But she set up both
American goals Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th minute, the American defender Brandi Chastain won a
tackle near midfield and caught the Chinese defense too far forward
as she put the ball through to Hamm, who sprinted free down the
left flank. Wen Lirong had no choice but to drag Hamm down in the
penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Akers took the penalty kick and drilled the ball low
and to the left. Han, a substitute Chinese goalie who was playing
in only her seventh international match, guessed correctly and got
her hands on the ball, but she could not keep it out of the net.
</P>
<P>
   China, which failed to get a shot on goal until the 24th minute,
tied the game in the 59th minute when forward Sun Wen hooked a free
kick into the net from about 25 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans seemed headed for a draw as Hamm then missed twice
on free kicks, but her late blast left Venturini open for the game
winner. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0556 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-PERK-NYT &LR;      04-22 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PERK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALPH J. PERK, A REPUBLICAN WHO LED CLEVELAND IN THE 1970S, DIES AT
85  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ralph J. Perk, a hard-luck mayor of Cleveland whose misfortunes
included accidentally setting his own hair on fire at a ceremonial
appearance, died on Wednesday at the Cleveland Clinic Hospice unit
of the Corinthian Skilled Nursing Center in Westlake, Ohio. He was
85.
</P>
<P>
   Perk, a Republican, was mayor from 1972 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Cleveland, he was also self-made. He dropped out of
high school, managed to get some college education and peddled ice
in the Depression. He benefited from enthusiastic backing of
blue-collar voters in being elected a Cleveland Councilman and,
later, mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But even The Cleveland Plain Dealer acknowledged that he was
``probably best remembered nationally as the mayor with the flaming
hair, whose wife preferred bowling to dining at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1972 that, as R.W. Apple Jr. has written in The New
York Times, Perk, ``at a ceremony designed to demonstrate his
solidarity with the city's working men, somehow managed to set his
hair alight with a blowtorch.'' He was wielding it to sever a steel
ribbon and thereby formally open a convention of the American
Society of Metals.
</P>
<P>
   Some months later, President Richard M. Nixon invited Perk and
his wife, the former Lucille Gagliardi, to a dinner at the White
House. But Mrs. Perk sent word that she could not attend because it
was her night to go bowling.
</P>
<P>
   Perk campaigned for election as mayor on an anti-tax platform.
After taking office, he oversaw the borrowing of nearly $130
million to pay the bills of the city, whose manufacturing
industries were battered by recession in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   He also reduced the work hours and pay of the city's employees
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, not long after Perk left office, Cleveland, with Mayor
Dennis J. Kucinich in charge, defaulted on its financial
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Perk lost to John Glenn, a Democrat, in a Senate race in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Lucille, whom he married 59 years
ago; a daughter, Virginia Bowers of Cleveland; six sons, Ralph Jr.,
a municipal court judge in Cleveland; Thomas, a councilman in
Valley View, a suburb of Cleveland; Kenneth, a member of the Valley
View school board; Michael, of Cleveland, an employee of the
Cuyahoga County Board of Elections; Richard, of Rocky River, west
of Cleveland, an employee of the Ohio Lottery Commission, and
Allen, of Gahanna, near Columbus; 16 grandchildren; five
great-grandchildren, and two brothers, Albert and George, both of
Cleveland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2345EDT &QL; 
