<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MOSS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITTINGHAM WAS GOOD-NATURED OFF TRACK, LEGEND ON IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now it is official: We all have to go sometime.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Whittingham had recently turned 86 when he passed
peacefully on Tuesday after a battle with leukemia. It was
uncharacteristic of him. He didn't lose many battles, on or off the
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   The record shows Whittingham, nicknamed the Bald Eagle for his
trademark shaved head, was the sport's best big-race trainer. He
won the Santa Anita Handicap nine times. Most trainers don't get to
``run'' in the race nine times, let alone win that many. He also
won the San Juan Capistrano 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie started training during the Great Depression and didn't
get Derby fever until his later years. But when he got a taste of
Churchill Downs with Ferdinand in 1986, he came back to win it
again three years later with Sunday Silence and just missed with
Strodes Creek five years after that.
</P>
<P>
   What the record doesn't show is Whittingham's charisma and
kindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can be nice when they feel like it or when they're in a
good mood,'' trainer Bob Baffert reflected this week. ``Charlie was
always the same. He was nice every single day.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Marine, Whittingham also could be a good-natured
roughhouser. He played hard as a young man, and even in his 70s
enjoyed a vodka or two. If he had too many, he might boast about
his fitness and literally beg to be punched in the gut. He might
also be the donor of a head butt, minus the football helmet.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what hours Charlie kept away from the track, his
horses were never neglected.
</P>
<P>
   Once, after repeatedly trying to reach Whittingham by telephone
at Santa Anita, a frustrated reporter asked a stable hand for
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do what everybody else does,'' the assistant offered. ``Call
him at the barn at 4 in the morning. That's when he reads the
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Whittingham was unfailingly gracious to reporters, when he could
be cornered. When his stable was at its peak, he didn't have much
time to talk because he was trying to pay close attention to every
detail about each of his horses. Training racehorses is part
intuition. Trying to get inside the head of a horse is far from an
exact science, after all, and Whittingham was often called half
horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine with me,'' he said, ``as long as it isn't the back
half.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie didn't throw around one-liners like Baffert does, but
his sense of humor was wry and folksy, as you would expect from an
old-school legend. His best-known saying was used whenever a big
race approached and uncertainty hung in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big race tomorrow,'' he would say. ``I guess we'll find out
where Molly put the peaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he would grin, and his piercing blue eyes would sparkle.
</P>
<P>
   When he became ill, Whittingham wasn't able to spend as much
time with his horses, and his stable shrunk, eventually to be taken
over by his son, Michael. He didn't travel much, and when I saw him
a year ago, he no longer looked invincible. He was tired and
feeble, blind in his right eye and his left eye dull and watery. He
looked as if he was coming to the end of the race, but part of you
refused to believe he could ever be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie commented in Jay Hovdey's outstanding 1993 book,
``Whittingham,'' that he would leave this world with his boots on.
He would stop training, he told Hovdey, ``when they put the pennies
on my eyes and plant me 6 feet deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Whittingham was at the races Sunday afternoon, died Tuesday
morning and will be planted 6 feet deep today.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps now he can finally solve that old mystery. Maybe he'll
find out where Molly put the peaches.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2351EDT &QL; 
