r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-PIANIST-TURNED-JO     04-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PIANIST-TURNED-JOCKEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
21-YEAR-OLD APPRENTICE JOCKEY FORSAKES MUSIC CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY RAMPELLINI 
c.1999 Special to the Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Euki Binns has always found herself torn
between two loves: music and horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the latter has been winning the battle for her
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Binns, an accomplished pianist, is pursuing her dream of
becoming a jockey at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Following her dream comes at the expense of her music career, an
endeavor her parents had expected her to follow. Binns even turned
down their offer to send her to the famed Juilliard School in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Binns' interest in racing wasn't a complete surprise to her
family. Her mother, Michi, was a jockey in Japan during her college
days.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Michi was one of Japan's leading riders until she was
forced to give up the sport after male jockeys at the track where
she rode went on strike in protest of her participation. She later
returned to college and earned a law degree.
</P>
<P>
   Euki Binns was playing the piano by age 5, and has since
mastered a number of instruments and won several music competitions
in her native Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play the piano,'' said Binns, 21. ``For me, it's a
form of stress release. But I also love being outside with
horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Her music background has helped in her efforts to become a
jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing the piano helps me have good hands on a horse,'' Binns
said. ``It's good training. I feel like I'm sensitive to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Binns began looking for work at racetracks after graduating from
high school. She found entry-level work at River Downs in
Cincinnati, then moved on to Turfway Park in Florence, Ky. Four
years ago, she ventured to one of racing's biggest tracks,
Churchill Downs in Louisville, Ky., and secured a job as an
exercise rider with one of the track's leading trainers, Frankie
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was looking for riders and he would try me out
for a couple of days,'' Binns said.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days turned into four years. Binns was given the
opportunity to exercise top horses such as Pulpit, a favorite for
the 1997 Kentucky Derby until he was injured, and Arch, winner of
last year's Grade I Super Derby at Louisiana Downs in Bossier City,
La.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Binns left Brothers to travel to Lone Star Park in
an attempt to launch a career as a jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason I came here was because there are so many big
shots who go to Churchill that I wouldn't have a shot to ride many
horses,'' she said. ``When you're learning, you want to get on a
lot of horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she left Brothers, the trainer helped her land her first
mount _ in January at the Fair Grounds in New Orleans. She rode
five more horses during the meeting, including her first winner.
</P>
<P>
   Business has been a little slower at Lone Star Park, where Binns
is seeking an agent to represent her and is getting to know the
local horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, she got her first Lone Star mount aboard Icee Hawk,
for Elliott Walden, one of the nation's leading trainers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a special race for the apprentice jockey because Julie
Krone, who was at Lone Star Park that day to close out her
illustrious riding career, won the same race aboard Dance to Fit.
As a result, Binns had an opportunity to spend time with Krone in
the women's locker room between races.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's another one of my mentors,'' said Binns, who placed
fifth in the race. ``She's so full of knowledge and is so willing
to pass it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Binns said her goal is to have a career like Krone, who won more
than 3,500 races and $81 million in purses during 18 years as a
jockey. While that might be far-fetched, one horseman at Lone Star
Park already believes Binns has the qualities necessary to someday
soar to those heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has everything it takes, all she needs is a chance,'' said
Jerry Quinn, an assistant trainer to Walden based at Lone Star
Park. ``She has a natural ability, and she's a hard worker. All she
needs is the horses.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
