<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL PAYS FOR SELIG'S DEAL WITH THE DEVIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shameless sordid story can now be told only after an
extensive undercover investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig took the Dr. Faustus route and sold baseball's soul to
the devil.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is irrefutable.
</P>
<P>
   Faustus did business with Beezelbub in order to obtain one
moment of perfect contentment, but Selig's motives were much less
altruistic.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted a couple of sluggers to come along and break the
single-season home run record, which would allow baseball to reap
much in the way of public goodwill, marketing position and cold
hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   Selig definitely got what he wanted in Mark McGwire and Sammy
Sosa. But now the devil is extracting his due and it's doubtful
even Daniel Webster, the only lawyer ever to beat Old Scratch in a
court of law, can extract baseball from this mess.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence was right there in front of us if only we were
paying attention. The first clue came when George Steinbrenner's
team walked through the playoffs with hardly any opposition. That
right there is proof enough the devil had taken over.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the National League playoffs, completely ruined
by the underdog Padres. Instead of an exhilirating Braves-Astros
championship series, we got Kevin Brown and Trevor Hoffman instead.
No wonder the Padres play Hell's Bells when their ace reliever
enters the game.
</P>
<P>
   When spring training arrived, it became even more clear baseball
was possessed, particularly when Roger Clemens ended up playing for
Steinbrenner instead of his beloved home state.
</P>
<P>
   But it got worse. Andres Galarraga and Joe Torre were stricken
with cancer. Kerry Wood and Moises Alou were lost for the season.
Rafael Palmeiro had knee surgery twice.
</P>
<P>
   It was the spring training from you know where. But the regular
season hasn't been much better. Just look at the pile of bodies
heaped onto the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   From that rubble we pull out the final two pieces of evidence:
Barry Bonds and Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds hurt? No way. He's never played less than 140 games in a
non-strike season in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows Dodgers owner Rupert Murdoch struck a pact with
the devil long ago and there was no way his team was going to win
the division unless the Giants lost their best player. That also
explains the Padres firesale and the Rockies interia. Randy Johnson
better be careful.
</P>
<P>
   How about Ripken? First his magnificent streak comes to an end,
then he goes on the disabled list for the first time in his career.
Pretty suspicious huh? Now consider who benefits the most from all
this.
</P>
<P>
   Who now has the longest consecutive games played streak in
baseball? Who is the center of attention in Baltimore now that
Ripken is and Will Clark are on the disabled list?
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution rests.
</P>
<P>
   All evidence points back to Selig. He was the one who brought
baseball to the brink of disaster with his leadership during the
1994-95 players strike. He's the one who has desperately tried
everything to get baseball back including realignment, interleague
play and expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he came to the conclusion there were no earthly
solutions so he entered into an unholy conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Now we just need to figure out what Don Fehr's role in all this
is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
