A0015 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-OILERS-HITS-TEX     04-22 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-OILERS-HITS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Oilers bring rugged style to the playoff party (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Defenseman Janne Niinimaa sounded very much like a
``SportsCenter'' anchor, save for his Finnish accent.
</P>
<P>
   He animatedly described hit after hit he and his Oilers
teammates delivered in Game 1 against the Stars on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``... Georges \RLaraque\S leveled \RJere\S Lehtinen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... when \RMike Grier\S gets you in his bull's eye, bye,
bye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... \RJason Smith\S got his licks in.''
</P>
<P>
   He skipped analysis of all 64 hits, instead being content to
predict that number to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it has to be that way. We're underdogs. We're coming
from behind, so we have to be desperate,'' Niinimaa said. ``So you
can look for the number of hits to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Oilers center Todd Marchant: ``We'd like to take it as far
as it can go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'' includes him, although, his Oilers have a couple of
designated hammers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is the hard checks and constant banging that were so
prevalent in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as it can go'' is likely to be pushed to the limit
starting at 7:30 tonight at Reunion Arena when Game 2 begins. The
Oilers realize with only three skaters under 6 feet compared to
nine for the Stars, physical play is the best way to close the
36-point, regular-season gap between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hammer, meet Mr. Nail.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers' designated hammers include defensemen Christian
LaFlamme, Smith and Niinimaa along with forwards Laraque and Grier.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' Smith said, ``we all like to bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two Oilers players were without hits on Wednesday and one
was goalie Tommy Salo. Smith had a game-high 13 hits, with Niinimaa
adding another eight.
</P>
<P>
   If the Oilers have designated hammers, they also have designated
certain Stars players as nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to hit everybody,'' LaFlamme said, ``but
especially their best players, like \RMike\S Modano, \RJoe\S
Nieuwendyk, \RBrett\S Hull, Lehtinen and \RSergei\S Zubov.''
</P>
<P>
   His selections have a common theme. They are players perceived
as not necessarily physical.
</P>
<P>
   So much for perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding me?'' Oilers coach Ron Low asked. ``I thought
that Joe Nieuwendyk played his best game against us in a long, long
time. He played physical. Modano, too. Lehtinen got hit 15 times
and never showed a sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Said LaFlamme: ``If it's true, I didn't see it last game.''
</P>
<P>
   He instead watched Nieuwendyk punch back when tangling with him
in a second-period fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's where the challenge comes,'' Nieuwendyk said.
``Teams will be physical on us, and I think it sends a message back
to them that if you hold your ground and you get physical back;
then they know you're not going away and it's going to be a long,
hard series.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumping and grinding dissolved into boarding and bleeding in the
final moments of Game 1, prompting Stars coach Ken Hitchcock to
send enforcer Grant Marshall in for a faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall isn't a center, he usually doesn't take faceoffs and
Low wasn't amused. He said that if the Stars weren't careful he'd
send in Laraque for a faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we could've had a real faceoff,'' Low said. ``If that's
the way you want to go, I have no problem with that. There is
nobody over there that matches up with Georges, so if you want to
get into that we can definitely go there. I have no problem with
that at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I think Georges may invite him sometime before the
series is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like 64 may just have been a beginning, after all.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0561 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NATO-NYT &LR;      04-22 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AND A NEW EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, April 23: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The caterers and champagne producers may be disappointed that
NATO has scaled back its 50th anniversary gathering in Washington
this week because of the conflict in Kosovo, but the alliance need
not mourn the change. After unsuccessfully seeking a new purpose
since the end of the Cold War, NATO has found a difficult but
worthy challenge in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Abstract debates about NATO's role in Europe have suddenly given
way to tangible decisions about combating Slobodan Milosevic. A
month of warfare in the Balkans has exposed the strengths and
weaknesses of the alliance. This weekend is a fine moment for NATO
to consider how it intends to prosecute the war and to ponder how
to deal with eruptions of ethnic violence in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The threats and military doctrines that once defined NATO are
obsolete, and the alliance must recognize that its role now may be
as much offensive as defensive. Europe no longer faces a monolithic
threat from the East. Today the greatest danger comes from ethnic
conflict and regional satraps like Slobodan Milosevic. Threatening
the use of nuclear weapons, once the backbone of NATO plans to stop
a Soviet invasion, makes no sense in a place like Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO can play a critical role, as Kosovo shows. Even though
the air war lacks the approval of the United Nations Security
Council, it has the endorsement of NATO's 19 members _ 17 European
nations, Canada and America. That unity may come with some
hesitation about when and how intensely to attack, but Kosovo has
demonstrated that Washington and its allies can act collectively
against aggression, and act compassionately to assist hundreds of
thousands of refugees. The immediate issue before the alliance is
whether to open the invasion option by drafting plans for a land
campaign and sending ground forces to the Balkans. The answer
should be affirmative. Air strikes may yet compel Milosevic to seek
peace. NATO, in the end, may decide that the use of ground troops
is not justified, or may employ them as peacekeepers rather than
invaders if a political settlement is reached. But the alliance
should not preclude the option Friday. If nothing else, the
movement of troops, tanks and artillery, which is likely to take
two or three months, may cause Milosevic to reconsider his
position.
</P>
<P>
   The extended time required to assemble an army of at least
100,000 soldiers in the Balkans suggests that NATO needs a more
agile fighting force. Milosevic might have acted with greater
restraint had he feared the presence of more mobile ground forces
in Europe, even if NATO initially said it had no plan to use them.
Size and firepower may be less important than speed and
maneuverability in an era of regional and local conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his NATO counterparts should also discuss
the sensitive issue of when it is appropriate for NATO to intervene
in a nation like Yugoslavia. When an aggressor strikes across
borders, especially those of a NATO member, the case for a military
response is usually clear.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo suggests that intervention may also be justified when a
tyrant orders a genocidal assault against his own people or drives
hundreds of thousands of citizens from their homeland. It would be
preferable for NATO to act with the approval of the security
council in such circumstances, and the alliance should move only
after diplomatic efforts fail. But there will probably be other
cases where action is required and security council support is
unattainable because Russia or China object.
</P>
<P>
   President Harry Truman and the leaders of a war-battered Europe
gathered in Washington at midcentury to meet the rising threat of
the Soviet Union. The alliance they formed helped preserve the
peace for five decades. At the close of the century, Clinton and
his allies must determine how to wage a small but dangerous war in
the Balkans and how to reshape NATO to serve a Europe that is
largely free but not yet immune to conflict. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0562 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NATO-NYT &LR;      04-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NATO AND A NEW EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, April 23: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
