<DOCNO> NYT19990422.0563 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     04-22 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MickeyHerskowitz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN the Rockets returned to the court to start the second half
against Dallas on Wednesday, they looked as if they had turned out
for a graveside service. And when the fans began fleeing the
building with five or six minutes to go, you could almost read
their minds:
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez, maybe we should leave now, in case anybody tries to
slash our tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, among the sad-sack Mavericks, who led by 26 points in
the fourth quarter, you have never seen such gaiety, such
hand-slapping, such teeth. The Mavs, the comic, inept,
bottom-feeding Mavs, played the fourth quarter pretty much on
cruise control because they knew _ everyone knew _ that the Rockets
didn't have a meaningful run in them.
</P>
<P>
   You could build a circumstantial case that this was the kind of
game with the potential to drive a strong man to drink. But that
would be too easy, too cheap and perhaps too close to traffic
court.
</P>
<P>
   On what may well have been the sickest game of Houston's season,
it qualifies as theatrical overkill for Scottie Pippen to be
arrested some three hours later on suspicion of driving while
intoxicated. The recorded facts are these: Pippen was stopped for
running a red light, refused to take a Breathalyzer test, was
booked and released after posting a $500 bond.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that Pippen vigorously denied that he was
drunk, and by all accounts he cooperated with the police. Under the
minimum standards of public discourse, he is presumed innocent.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from the legal distinctions, one can't escape the
irony of the former Chicago Bulls player being singled out. If the
cops had reacted earlier, and checked out the scene at Compaq
Center, they might have busted the entire team on suspicion of
impersonating a championship contender.
</P>
<P>
   As the score mounted, as the game turned from a contest to a
rout to a party, the young Mavericks could not contain themselves.
It might have been sad, watching a sometimes great team catch a pie
in the face, if it hadn't felt so good. If the Mavericks appeared
to laugh out loud, it was not in derision, but in the pure joy of
self-discovery. Well, maybe a little bit in derision. This was
their first victory over the Rockets in 11 encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are eight games left in this Reader's Digest condensed
season, and the Rockets did not protect their home court, did not
gain ground on the Spurs or the Lakers in the race to the playoffs,
and did not pass go. It may be too late to wonder how much the
Rockets are second-guessing their decision to beam up Scottie. It
is certainly not too early. Pippen has been questioning himself
ever since he blew into town on a wave of headlines, hailed as the
team's latest transplanted superhero.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen could do everything that the retired Clyde Drexler could
do, has six rings and hair and is three years younger. But he has
spent a troublesome amount of time trying to fit into the Rockets'
system and asking such questions as, Why am I here? What is my
role? Whose team is this?
</P>
<P>
   Against Dallas, Pippen scored four points and, like his
teammates, was defenseless against the Mavericks, who have no star.
In a league that loves exotic names, what the Mavs do have is a
20-year-old German Wunderkind named Dirk Nowitzki, a 7-foot-6
Mormon named Shawn Bradley and a future franchise player in Michael
Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rockets are 12 games over .500 and feeling
depressed. The Mavericks are 12 games under, going nowhere and
loving their underdog status, their chance to be the spoilers.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only a week ago that Pippen was taking charge,
exploding for 31 points against Portland, and announcing that he
had decided it was time to get aggressive, to fit himself into the
offense. By gosh, it was only a week ago. Time flies when you are
getting blown out by the dregs of the league.
</P>
<P>
   If an unfair portion of the blame for the Rockets' inconsistency
seems to fall on Pippen, we can only belabor the obvious: Life in
the NBA wasn't meant to be fair. The Rockets may be asking if they
are getting their money's worth from a contract that pays Pippen $8
million a season. Having lost in their bid to sign Antonio McDyess,
they could not believe their good fortune when they wound up with
the guy they said they really wanted, the guy who had been Michael
Jordan's sidekick and Air Apparent in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose Scottie ever regrets leaving the Windy City? He
would have been The Man on a lesser team but perhaps the savior for
keeping the Bulls out of the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen clearly misses the triangle offense that was as familiar
to him as the ring in his ear. He has whined about the
predictability of the Rockets' offense, the old inside-outside
game, but no one complains about it when the gunners are hitting
the 3s and the team wins.
</P>
<P>
   And, no, we won't drink to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
