<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-22 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-POLL23-COX     04-22 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poll suggests voters know Bush by name, not recordBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two new polls show that Gov. George W. Bush's
popularity may be based more on name and image than substance and
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas Poll released today shows Bush winning favorable ratings
from 78 percent of the respondents, down a bit from the 81 percent
favorable rating in a February poll.
</P>
<P>
   But in an indication that he is not closely identified with any
initiative or accomplishment, 45 percent of the respondents
answered ``don't know'' or ``not sure'' when asked to name Bush's
top accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``While nearly half of all Texans can think of nothing to credit
as Bush's accomplishments while governor, for those who can,
education efforts top the list, with 19 percent citing Bush's
educational accomplishments,'' said Texas Poll Director Beverly
Barnum.
</P>
<P>
   Barnum also noted that the question about Bush's top
accomplishment was an open-ended one that required respondents to
come up with an answer, not choose from among suggested answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising,'' she said of the 45 percent who couldn't
identify Bush with a particular issue. ``About half the people at
any time don't know much about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush presidential exploratory committee spokeswoman Mindy Tucker
said the governor's high favorable ratings show that Texans
``appreciate the tone that he has set as a leader on a variety of
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And they do recognize that education has been his number one
priority,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication that Bush's popularity might be fragile,
an independent poll of New Hampshire Republicans shows that his
lead evaporates when a short biography is substituted for his name.
</P>
<P>
   The Reuters/Zogby Poll in New Hampshire was conducted two ways,
once with names and once without. When candidate names were used,
Bush piled up a huge lead, picking up 38.4 percent of the support
among the 309 likely Republican voters contacted this month.
Elizabeth Dole was second at 14.9 percent. Arizona Sen. John McCain
was third at 8.9 percent and former Vice President Dan Quayle was
fourth at 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture changed dramatically when names were removed and
short biographies were used. Bush dropped to 24.1 percent. McCain
shot up to second at 19.2 percent which, because of the 5.7
percentage point margin of error, puts McCain and Bush in a
statistical dead heat. Dole dropped to fifth place at 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky said the results show that the
Arizona senator ``is a very compelling figure and has a fantastic
story and personal background.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As more people get to know more about him they will find him
very appealing,'' Opinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential contender Gary Bauer picked up the most ground when
names were omitted. With names, Bauer finished 11th, last, with
support from 0.5 percent. Without names, Bauer moved up to fourth
with 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``blind'' version of the poll, Bush was described as a
recently re-elected governor of a ``large Southern state'' who has
a ``strong record on taxes and education and calls himself a
compassionate conservative'' and has ``strong appeal among
Hispanics and women.''
</P>
<P>
   Poll director John Zogby, whose firm conducted the survey for
the Reuters news organization, said the results should serve as a
warning to Bush, who will not hit the campaign trail until the
legislative session ends on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has to get out of the rose garden,'' Zogby said.
``That's a clear message. A lot of his support at this point in
time appears to be name recognition support, and there are other
people with biographies that can be very appealing to the public.
There could be some surprises here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said Bush's strong showing in the version of the poll
with names should not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, if he decides to run, his name will be on the
ballot, and people will know his name and his record,'' she said.
``Governor Bush recognizes he still has a lot of work to do. He has
not visited New Hampshire yet, and he looks forward to traveling up
there soon to tell them what he believes and hear what they have to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's first trip to New Hampshire won't come until June at the
earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby also noted that Bush's impressive team of New Hampshire
supporters, as well as a money-raising machine unmatched by foes,
leaves the governor well-positioned to shore up support when he
begins campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The brief biographies used to describe the candidates in the
blind poll are intended to be ``fair and balanced and bland and
accurate,'' Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore's lead over
former Sen. Bill Bradley is virtually the same in both versions of
the poll. With names, Gore leads 52 percent to 35 percent. Without
names, Gore's edge is 53 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Poll's early test of Bush's presidential candidacy
showed him with a huge lead in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In a head-to-head primary matchup with Dole, Bush led 68 percent
to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also indicates Bush would easily carry the state in a
general election matchup with Gore, 69 percent to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Poll was conducted March 30 through April 17. The
margin of error for the poll, which includes responses from 1,003
adults, is 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
